var P_HTM = [];
P_HTM[1]="*Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa* **";
P_HTM[2]="*Dīghanikāyo* **";
P_HTM[3]="*Pāthikavaggapāḷi* **";
P_HTM[4]="*24. Pāthikasutta  - About Pāṭikaputta * **";
P_HTM[5]="*1. Sunakkhattavatthu**1. On Sunakkhatta*";
P_HTM[6]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[7]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā mallesu viharati anupiyaṃ nāma mallānaṃ nigamo.**At one time the Buddha was staying in the land of the Mallas, near the Mallian town named Anupiya.*";
P_HTM[8]="*Atha kho bhagavā pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya anupiyaṃ piṇḍāya pāvisi.**Then the Buddha robed up in the morning and, taking his bowl and robe, entered Anupiya for alms.*";
P_HTM[9]="*Atha kho bhagavato etadahosi:**Then it occurred to him,*";
P_HTM[10]="*“atippago kho tāva anupiyāyaṃ piṇḍāya carituṃ.**“It’s too early to wander for alms in Anupiya.*";
P_HTM[11]="*Yannūnāhaṃ yena bhaggavagottassa paribbājakassa ārāmo, yena bhaggavagotto paribbājako tenupasaṅkameyyan”ti.**Why don’t I go to the wanderer Bhaggavagotta’s monastery to visit him?”*";
P_HTM[12]="*Atha kho bhagavā yena bhaggavagottassa paribbājakassa ārāmo, yena bhaggavagotto paribbājako tenupasaṅkami.**So that’s what he did.*";
P_HTM[13]="*Atha kho bhaggavagotto paribbājako bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then the wanderer Bhaggavagotta said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[14]="*“etu kho, bhante, bhagavā.**“Come, Blessed One!*";
P_HTM[15]="*Svāgataṃ, bhante, bhagavato.**Welcome, Blessed One!*";
P_HTM[16]="*Cirassaṃ kho, bhante, bhagavā imaṃ pariyāyamakāsi yadidaṃ idhāgamanāya.**It’s been a long time since you took the opportunity to come here.*";
P_HTM[17]="*Nisīdatu, bhante, bhagavā, idamāsanaṃ paññattan”ti.**Please, sir, sit down, this seat is ready.”*";
P_HTM[18]="*Nisīdi bhagavā paññatte āsane.**The Buddha sat on the seat spread out,*";
P_HTM[19]="*Bhaggavagottopi kho paribbājako aññataraṃ nīcaṃ āsanaṃ gahetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi.**while Bhaggavagotta took a low seat, sat to one side,*";
P_HTM[20]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho bhaggavagotto paribbājako bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**and said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[21]="*“purimāni, bhante, divasāni purimatarāni sunakkhatto licchaviputto yenāhaṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā maṃ etadavoca:**“Sir, a few days ago Sunakkhatta the Licchavi came to me and said:*";
P_HTM[22]="*‘paccakkhāto dāni mayā, bhaggava, bhagavā.**‘Now, Bhaggava, I have rejected the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[23]="*Na dānāhaṃ bhagavantaṃ uddissa viharāmī’ti.**Now I no longer live dedicated to him.’*";
P_HTM[24]="*Kaccetaṃ, bhante, tatheva, yathā sunakkhatto licchaviputto avacā”ti?**Sir, is what Sunakkhatta said true?”*";
P_HTM[25]="*“Tatheva kho etaṃ, bhaggava, yathā sunakkhatto licchaviputto avaca.**“Indeed it is, Bhaggava.*";
P_HTM[26]="*Purimāni, bhaggava, divasāni purimatarāni sunakkhatto licchaviputto yenāhaṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā maṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho, bhaggava, sunakkhatto licchaviputto maṃ etadavoca:**A few days ago Sunakkhatta the Licchavi came to me, bowed, sat down to one side, and said:*";
P_HTM[27]="*‘paccakkhāmi dānāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavantaṃ.**‘Now I reject the Buddha!*";
P_HTM[28]="*Na dānāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavantaṃ uddissa viharissāmī’ti.**Now I shall no longer live dedicated to you.’*";
P_HTM[29]="*Evaṃ vutte, ahaṃ, bhaggava, sunakkhattaṃ licchaviputtaṃ etadavocaṃ:**When Sunakkhatta said this, I said to him,*";
P_HTM[30]="*‘api nu tāhaṃ, sunakkhatta, evaṃ avacaṃ,**‘But Sunakkhatta, did I ever say to you:*";
P_HTM[31]="*ehi tvaṃ, sunakkhatta, mamaṃ uddissa viharāhī’ti?**“Come, live dedicated to me”?’*";
P_HTM[32]="*‘No hetaṃ, bhante’.**‘No, sir.’*";
P_HTM[33]="*‘Tvaṃ vā pana maṃ evaṃ avaca—**‘Or did you ever say to me:*";
P_HTM[34]="*ahaṃ, bhante, bhagavantaṃ uddissa viharissāmī’ti?**“Sir, I shall live dedicated to the Buddha”?’*";
P_HTM[35]="*‘No hetaṃ, bhante’.**‘No, sir.’*";
P_HTM[36]="*‘Iti kira, sunakkhatta, nevāhaṃ taṃ vadāmi—**‘So it seems that I did not ask you to*";
P_HTM[37]="*ehi tvaṃ, sunakkhatta, mamaṃ uddissa viharāhīti.**live dedicated to me,*";
P_HTM[38]="*Napi kira maṃ tvaṃ vadesi—**nor did you say you would*";
P_HTM[39]="*ahaṃ, bhante, bhagavantaṃ uddissa viharissāmīti.**live dedicated to me.*";
P_HTM[40]="*Evaṃ sante, moghapurisa, ko santo kaṃ paccācikkhasi?**In that case, you silly man, are you really in a position to be rejecting anything?*";
P_HTM[41]="*Passa, moghapurisa, yāvañca te idaṃ aparaddhan’ti.**See how far you have strayed!’*";
P_HTM[42]="*‘Na hi pana me, bhante, bhagavā uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ karotī’ti.**‘But sir, the Buddha never performs any superhuman demonstrations of psychic power for me.’*";
P_HTM[43]="*‘Api nu tāhaṃ, sunakkhatta, evaṃ avacaṃ—**‘But Sunakkhatta, did I ever say to you:*";
P_HTM[44]="*ehi tvaṃ, sunakkhatta, mamaṃ uddissa viharāhi, ahaṃ te uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ karissāmī’ti?**“Come, live dedicated to me and I will perform a superhuman demonstration of psychic power for you”?’*";
P_HTM[45]="*‘No hetaṃ, bhante’.**‘No, sir.’*";
P_HTM[46]="*‘Tvaṃ vā pana maṃ evaṃ avaca—**‘Or did you ever say to me:*";
P_HTM[47]="*ahaṃ, bhante, bhagavantaṃ uddissa viharissāmi, bhagavā me uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ karissatī’ti?**“Sir, I shall live dedicated to the Buddha, and the Buddha will perform a superhuman demonstration of psychic power for me”?’*";
P_HTM[48]="*‘No hetaṃ, bhante’.**‘No, sir.’*";
P_HTM[49]="*‘Iti kira, sunakkhatta, nevāhaṃ taṃ vadāmi—**‘So it seems that I did not ask this of you, and you did not require it of me.*";
P_HTM[50]="*ehi tvaṃ, sunakkhatta, mamaṃ uddissa viharāhi, ahaṃ te uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ karissāmīti;* **";
P_HTM[51]="*napi kira maṃ tvaṃ vadesi—* **";
P_HTM[52]="*ahaṃ, bhante, bhagavantaṃ uddissa viharissāmi, bhagavā me uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ karissatīti.* **";
P_HTM[53]="*Evaṃ sante, moghapurisa, ko santo kaṃ paccācikkhasi?**In that case, you silly man, are you really in a position to be rejecting anything?*";
P_HTM[54]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, sunakkhatta,**What do you think, Sunakkhatta?*";
P_HTM[55]="*kate vā uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriye akate vā uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriye yassatthāya mayā dhammo desito so niyyāti takkarassa sammā dukkhakkhayāyā’ti?**Whether or not there is a demonstration of psychic power, does my teaching lead someone who practices it to the goal of the complete ending of suffering?’*";
P_HTM[56]="*‘Kate vā, bhante, uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriye akate vā uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriye yassatthāya bhagavatā dhammo desito so niyyāti takkarassa sammā dukkhakkhayāyā’ti.**‘It does, sir.’*";
P_HTM[57]="*‘Iti kira, sunakkhatta, kate vā uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriye, akate vā uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriye, yassatthāya mayā dhammo desito, so niyyāti takkarassa sammā dukkhakkhayāya.**‘So it seems that whether or not there is a demonstration of psychic power, my teaching leads someone who practices it to the goal of the complete ending of suffering.*";
P_HTM[58]="*Tatra, sunakkhatta, kiṃ uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ kataṃ karissati?**In that case, what is the point of superhuman demonstrations of psychic power?*";
P_HTM[59]="*Passa, moghapurisa, yāvañca te idaṃ aparaddhan’ti.**See how far you have strayed, you silly man!’*";
P_HTM[60]="*‘Na hi pana me, bhante, bhagavā aggaññaṃ paññapetī’ti?**‘But sir, the Buddha never describes the origin of the world to me.’*";
P_HTM[61]="*‘Api nu tāhaṃ, sunakkhatta, evaṃ avacaṃ—**‘But Sunakkhatta, did I ever say to you:*";
P_HTM[62]="*ehi tvaṃ, sunakkhatta, mamaṃ uddissa viharāhi, ahaṃ te aggaññaṃ paññapessāmī’ti?**“Come, live dedicated to me and I will describe the origin of the world to you”?’*";
P_HTM[63]="*‘No hetaṃ, bhante’.**‘No, sir.’*";
P_HTM[64]="*‘Tvaṃ vā pana maṃ evaṃ avaca—**‘Or did you ever say to me:*";
P_HTM[65]="*ahaṃ, bhante, bhagavantaṃ uddissa viharissāmi, bhagavā me aggaññaṃ paññapessatī’ti?**“Sir, I shall live dedicated to the Buddha, and the Buddha will describe the origin of the world to me”?’*";
P_HTM[66]="*‘No hetaṃ, bhante’.**‘No, sir.’*";
P_HTM[67]="*‘Iti kira, sunakkhatta, nevāhaṃ taṃ vadāmi—**‘So it seems that I did not ask this of you, and you did not require it of me.*";
P_HTM[68]="*ehi tvaṃ, sunakkhatta, mamaṃ uddissa viharāhi, ahaṃ te aggaññaṃ paññapessāmīti.* **";
P_HTM[69]="*Napi kira maṃ tvaṃ vadesi—* **";
P_HTM[70]="*ahaṃ, bhante, bhagavantaṃ uddissa viharissāmi, bhagavā me aggaññaṃ paññapessatīti.* **";
P_HTM[71]="*Evaṃ sante, moghapurisa, ko santo kaṃ paccācikkhasi?**In that case, you silly man, are you really in a position to be rejecting anything?*";
P_HTM[72]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, sunakkhatta,**What do you think, Sunakkhatta?*";
P_HTM[73]="*paññatte vā aggaññe, apaññatte vā aggaññe, yassatthāya mayā dhammo desito, so niyyāti takkarassa sammā dukkhakkhayāyā’ti?**Whether or not the origin of the world is described, does my teaching lead someone who practices it to the goal of the complete ending of suffering?’*";
P_HTM[74]="*‘Paññatte vā, bhante, aggaññe, apaññatte vā aggaññe, yassatthāya bhagavatā dhammo desito, so niyyāti takkarassa sammā dukkhakkhayāyā’ti.**‘It does, sir.’*";
P_HTM[75]="*‘Iti kira, sunakkhatta, paññatte vā aggaññe, apaññatte vā aggaññe, yassatthāya mayā dhammo desito, so niyyāti takkarassa sammā dukkhakkhayāya.**‘So it seems that whether or not the origin of the world is described, my teaching leads someone who practices it to the goal of the complete ending of suffering.*";
P_HTM[76]="*Tatra, sunakkhatta, kiṃ aggaññaṃ paññattaṃ karissati?**In that case, what is the point of describing the origin of the world?*";
P_HTM[77]="*Passa, moghapurisa, yāvañca te idaṃ aparaddhaṃ.**See how far you have strayed, you silly man!*";
P_HTM[78]="*Anekapariyāyena kho te, sunakkhatta, mama vaṇṇo bhāsito vajjigāme—**In many ways, Sunakkhatta, you have praised me like this in the Vajjian capital:*";
P_HTM[79]="*itipi so bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavāti.**“That Blessed One is perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.”*";
P_HTM[80]="*Iti kho te, sunakkhatta, anekapariyāyena mama vaṇṇo bhāsito vajjigāme.* **";
P_HTM[81]="*Anekapariyāyena kho te, sunakkhatta, dhammassa vaṇṇo bhāsito vajjigāme—**In many ways you have praised the teaching like this in the Vajjian capital:*";
P_HTM[82]="*svākkhāto bhagavatā dhammo sandiṭṭhiko akāliko ehipassiko opaneyyiko paccattaṃ veditabbo viññūhīti.**“The teaching is well explained by the Buddha—visible in this very life, immediately effective, inviting inspection, relevant, so that sensible people can know it for themselves.”*";
P_HTM[83]="*Iti kho te, sunakkhatta, anekapariyāyena dhammassa vaṇṇo bhāsito vajjigāme.* **";
P_HTM[84]="*Anekapariyāyena kho te, sunakkhatta, saṅghassa vaṇṇo bhāsito vajjigāme—**In many ways you have praised the Saṅgha like this in the Vajjian capital:*";
P_HTM[85]="*suppaṭipanno bhagavato sāvakasaṅgho, ujuppaṭipanno bhagavato sāvakasaṅgho, ñāyappaṭipanno bhagavato sāvakasaṅgho, sāmīcippaṭipanno bhagavato sāvakasaṅgho, yadidaṃ cattāri purisayugāni aṭṭha purisapuggalā, esa bhagavato sāvakasaṅgho, āhuneyyo pāhuneyyo dakkhiṇeyyo añjalikaraṇīyo anuttaraṃ puññakkhettaṃ lokassāti.**“The Saṅgha of the Buddha’s disciples is practicing the way that’s good, straightforward, methodical, and proper. It consists of the four pairs, the eight individuals. This is the Saṅgha of the Buddha’s disciples that is worthy of offerings dedicated to the gods, worthy of hospitality, worthy of a religious donation, worthy of greeting with joined palms, and is the supreme field of merit for the world.”*";
P_HTM[86]="*Iti kho te, sunakkhatta, anekapariyāyena saṅghassa vaṇṇo bhāsito vajjigāme.* **";
P_HTM[87]="*Ārocayāmi kho te, sunakkhatta, paṭivedayāmi kho te, sunakkhatta.**I declare this to you, Sunakkhatta, I announce this to you!*";
P_HTM[88]="*Bhavissanti kho te, sunakkhatta, vattāro, no visahi sunakkhatto licchaviputto samaṇe gotame brahmacariyaṃ carituṃ, so avisahanto sikkhaṃ paccakkhāya hīnāyāvattoti.**There will be those who say that Sunakkhatta was unable to lead the spiritual life under the ascetic Gotama. That’s why he rejected the training and returned to a lesser life.*";
P_HTM[89]="*Iti kho te, sunakkhatta, bhavissanti vattāro’ti.**That’s what they’ll say.’*";
P_HTM[90]="*Evaṃ kho, bhaggava, sunakkhatto licchaviputto mayā vuccamāno apakkameva imasmā dhammavinayā, yathā taṃ āpāyiko nerayiko.**Though I spoke to Sunakkhatta like this, he still left this teaching and training, like someone on the highway to hell.*";
P_HTM[91]="*2. Korakkhattiyavatthu**2. On Korakkhattiya*";
P_HTM[92]="*Ekamidāhaṃ, bhaggava, samayaṃ thūlūsu viharāmi uttarakā nāma thūlūnaṃ nigamo.**Bhaggava, this one time I was staying in the land of the Thūlus where they have a town named Uttarakā.*";
P_HTM[93]="*Atha khvāhaṃ, bhaggava, pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya sunakkhattena licchaviputtena pacchāsamaṇena uttarakaṃ piṇḍāya pāvisiṃ.**Then I robed up in the morning and, taking my bowl and robe, entered Uttarakā for alms with Sunakkhatta the Licchavi as my second monk.*";
P_HTM[94]="*Tena kho pana samayena acelo korakkhattiyo kukkuravatiko catukkuṇḍiko chamānikiṇṇaṃ bhakkhasaṃ mukheneva khādati, mukheneva bhuñjati.**Now at that time the naked ascetic Korakkhattiya had taken a vow to behave like a dog. When food is tossed on the ground, he gets down on all fours, eating and devouring it just with his mouth.*";
P_HTM[95]="*Addasā kho, bhaggava, sunakkhatto licchaviputto acelaṃ korakkhattiyaṃ kukkuravatikaṃ catukkuṇḍikaṃ chamānikiṇṇaṃ bhakkhasaṃ mukheneva khādantaṃ mukheneva bhuñjantaṃ.**Sunakkhatta saw him doing this*";
P_HTM[96]="*Disvānassa etadahosi:**and thought,*";
P_HTM[97]="*‘sādhurūpo vata bho ayaṃ samaṇo catukkuṇḍiko chamānikiṇṇaṃ bhakkhasaṃ mukheneva khādati, mukheneva bhuñjatī’ti.**‘That ascetic is a true holy man!’*";
P_HTM[98]="*Atha khvāhaṃ, bhaggava, sunakkhattassa licchaviputtassa cetasā cetoparivitakkamaññāya sunakkhattaṃ licchaviputtaṃ etadavocaṃ:**Then, knowing what Sunakkhatta was thinking, I said to him,*";
P_HTM[99]="*‘tvampi nāma, moghapurisa, samaṇo sakyaputtiyo paṭijānissasī’ti.**‘Don’t you claim to be an ascetic, a follower of the Sakyan, you silly man?’*";
P_HTM[100]="*‘Kiṃ pana maṃ, bhante, bhagavā evamāha:**‘But why does the Buddha say this to me?’*";
P_HTM[101]="*“tvampi nāma, moghapurisa, samaṇo sakyaputtiyo paṭijānissasī”’ti?* **";
P_HTM[102]="*‘Nanu te, sunakkhatta, imaṃ acelaṃ korakkhattiyaṃ kukkuravatikaṃ catukkuṇḍikaṃ chamānikiṇṇaṃ bhakkhasaṃ mukheneva khādantaṃ mukheneva bhuñjantaṃ disvāna etadahosi—**‘When you saw that naked ascetic Korakkhattiya, didn’t you think,*";
P_HTM[103]="*sādhurūpo vata bho ayaṃ samaṇo catukkuṇḍiko chamānikiṇṇaṃ bhakkhasaṃ mukheneva khādati, mukheneva bhuñjatī’ti?**“That ascetic is a true holy man!”?’*";
P_HTM[104]="*‘Evaṃ, bhante.**‘Yes, sir.*";
P_HTM[105]="*Kiṃ pana, bhante, bhagavā arahattassa maccharāyatī’ti?**But sir, are you jealous of the perfected ones?’*";
P_HTM[106]="*‘Na kho ahaṃ, moghapurisa, arahattassa maccharāyāmi.**‘I’m not jealous of the perfected ones, you silly man.*";
P_HTM[107]="*Api ca tuyhevetaṃ pāpakaṃ diṭṭhigataṃ uppannaṃ, taṃ pajaha.**Rather, you should give up this harmful misconception that has arisen in you.*";
P_HTM[108]="*Mā te ahosi dīgharattaṃ ahitāya dukkhāya.**Don’t create lasting harm and suffering for yourself!*";
P_HTM[109]="*Yaṃ kho panetaṃ, sunakkhatta, maññasi acelaṃ korakkhattiyaṃ—sādhurūpo ayaṃ samaṇoti. So sattamaṃ divasaṃ alasakena kālaṃ karissati.**That naked ascetic Korakkhattiya, who you imagine to be a true holy man, will die of flatulence in seven days.*";
P_HTM[110]="*Kālaṅkato ca kālakañcikā nāma asurā sabbanihīno asurakāyo, tatra upapajjissati.**And when he dies, he’ll be reborn in the very lowest rank of demons, named the Kālakañjas.*";
P_HTM[111]="*Kālaṅkatañca naṃ bīraṇatthambake susāne chaḍḍessanti.**And they’ll throw him in the charnel ground on a clump of vetiver.*";
P_HTM[112]="*Ākaṅkhamāno ca tvaṃ, sunakkhatta, acelaṃ korakkhattiyaṃ upasaṅkamitvā puccheyyāsi—**If you wish, Sunakkhatta, go to Korakkhattiya and ask him*";
P_HTM[113]="*jānāsi, āvuso korakkhattiya, attano gatinti?**whether he knows his own destiny.*";
P_HTM[114]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, sunakkhatta, vijjati yaṃ te acelo korakkhattiyo byākarissati—**It’s possible that he will answer:*";
P_HTM[115]="*jānāmi, āvuso sunakkhatta, attano gatiṃ;**“Reverend Sunakkhatta, I know my own destiny.*";
P_HTM[116]="*kālakañcikā nāma asurā sabbanihīno asurakāyo, tatrāmhi upapanno’ti.**I’ll be reborn in the very lowest rank of demons, named the Kālakañjas.”’*";
P_HTM[117]="*Atha kho, bhaggava, sunakkhatto licchaviputto yena acelo korakkhattiyo tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā acelaṃ korakkhattiyaṃ etadavoca:**So, Bhaggava, Sunakkhatta went to see Korakkhattiya and said to him,*";
P_HTM[118]="*‘byākato khosi, āvuso korakkhattiya, samaṇena gotamena—**‘Reverend Korakkhattiya, the ascetic Gotama has declared*";
P_HTM[119]="*acelo korakkhattiyo sattamaṃ divasaṃ alasakena kālaṃ karissati.**that you will die of flatulence in seven days.*";
P_HTM[120]="*Kālaṅkato ca kālakañcikā nāma asurā sabbanihīno asurakāyo, tatra upapajjissati.**And when you die, you’ll be reborn in the very lowest rank of demons, named the Kālakañjas.*";
P_HTM[121]="*Kālaṅkatañca naṃ bīraṇatthambake susāne chaḍḍessantīti.**And when you die, they’ll throw you in the charnel ground on a clump of vetiver.*";
P_HTM[122]="*Yena tvaṃ, āvuso korakkhattiya, mattaṃ mattañca bhattaṃ bhuñjeyyāsi, mattaṃ mattañca pānīyaṃ piveyyāsi.**But by eating just a little food and drinking just a little water,*";
P_HTM[123]="*Yathā samaṇassa gotamassa micchā assa vacanan’ti.**you’ll prove what the ascetic Gotama says to be false.’*";
P_HTM[124]="*Atha kho, bhaggava, sunakkhatto licchaviputto ekadvīhikāya sattarattindivāni gaṇesi, yathā taṃ tathāgatassa asaddahamāno.**Then Sunakkhatta counted up the days until the seventh day, as happens when you have no faith in the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[125]="*Atha kho, bhaggava, acelo korakkhattiyo sattamaṃ divasaṃ alasakena kālamakāsi.**But on the seventh day, the naked ascetic Korakkhattiya died of flatulence.*";
P_HTM[126]="*kālaṅkato ca kālakañcikā nāma asurā sabbanihīno asurakāyo, tatra upapajji.**And when he passed away, he was reborn in the very lowest rank of demons, named the Kālakañjas.*";
P_HTM[127]="*kālaṅkatañca naṃ bīraṇatthambake susāne chaḍḍesuṃ.**And when he passed away, they threw him in the charnel ground on a clump of vetiver.*";
P_HTM[128]="*Assosi kho, bhaggava, sunakkhatto licchaviputto:**Sunakkhatta the Licchavi heard about this.*";
P_HTM[129]="*‘acelo kira korakkhattiyo alasakena kālaṅkato bīraṇatthambake susāne chaḍḍito’ti.* **";
P_HTM[130]="*Atha kho, bhaggava, sunakkhatto licchaviputto yena bīraṇatthambakaṃ susānaṃ, yena acelo korakkhattiyo tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā acelaṃ korakkhattiyaṃ tikkhattuṃ pāṇinā ākoṭesi:**So he went to see Korakkhattiya in the charnel ground on the clump of vetiver. There he struck Korakkhattiya with his fist three times,*";
P_HTM[131]="*‘jānāsi, āvuso korakkhattiya, attano gatin’ti?**‘Reverend Korakkhattiya, do you know your destiny?’*";
P_HTM[132]="*Atha kho, bhaggava, acelo korakkhattiyo pāṇinā piṭṭhiṃ paripuñchanto vuṭṭhāsi.**Then Korakkhattiya got up, rubbing his back with his hands, and said,*";
P_HTM[133]="*‘Jānāmi, āvuso sunakkhatta, attano gatiṃ.**‘Reverend Sunakkhatta, I know my own destiny.*";
P_HTM[134]="*Kālakañcikā nāma asurā sabbanihīno asurakāyo, tatrāmhi upapanno’ti vatvā tattheva uttāno papati.**I’ve been reborn in the very lowest rank of demons, named the Kālakañjas.’ After speaking, he fell flat right there.*";
P_HTM[135]="*Atha kho, bhaggava, sunakkhatto licchaviputto yenāhaṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā maṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho ahaṃ, bhaggava, sunakkhattaṃ licchaviputtaṃ etadavocaṃ:**Then Sunakkhatta came to me, bowed, and sat down to one side. I said to him,*";
P_HTM[136]="*‘Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, sunakkhatta,**‘What do you think, Sunakkhatta?*";
P_HTM[137]="*yatheva te ahaṃ acelaṃ korakkhattiyaṃ ārabbha byākāsiṃ, tatheva taṃ vipākaṃ, aññathā vā’ti?**Did the declaration I made about Korakkhattiya turn out to be correct, or not?’*";
P_HTM[138]="*‘Yatheva me, bhante, bhagavā acelaṃ korakkhattiyaṃ ārabbha byākāsi, tatheva taṃ vipākaṃ, no aññathā’ti.**‘It turned out to be correct.’*";
P_HTM[139]="*‘Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, sunakkhatta,**‘What do you think, Sunakkhatta?*";
P_HTM[140]="*yadi evaṃ sante kataṃ vā hoti uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ, akataṃ vā’ti?**If that is so, has a superhuman demonstration of psychic power been performed or not?’*";
P_HTM[141]="*‘Addhā kho, bhante, evaṃ sante kataṃ hoti uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ, no akatan’ti.**‘Clearly, sir, a superhuman demonstration of psychic power has been performed.’*";
P_HTM[142]="*‘Evampi kho maṃ tvaṃ, moghapurisa, uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ karontaṃ evaṃ vadesi—**‘Though I performed such a superhuman demonstration of psychic power you say this:*";
P_HTM[143]="*na hi pana me, bhante, bhagavā uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ karotīti.**“But sir, the Buddha never performs any superhuman demonstrations of psychic power for me.”*";
P_HTM[144]="*Passa, moghapurisa, yāvañca te idaṃ aparaddhan’ti.**See how far you have strayed!’*";
P_HTM[145]="*Evampi kho, bhaggava, sunakkhatto licchaviputto mayā vuccamāno apakkameva imasmā dhammavinayā, yathā taṃ āpāyiko nerayiko.**Though I spoke to Sunakkhatta like this, he still left this teaching and training, like someone on the highway to hell.*";
P_HTM[146]="*3. Acelakaḷāramaṭṭakavatthu**3. On the Naked Ascetic Kaḷāramaṭṭaka*";
P_HTM[147]="*Ekamidāhaṃ, bhaggava, samayaṃ vesāliyaṃ viharāmi mahāvane kūṭāgārasālāyaṃ.**This one time, Bhaggava, I was staying near Vesālī, at the Great Wood, in the hall with the peaked roof.*";
P_HTM[148]="*Tena kho pana samayena acelo kaḷāramaṭṭako vesāliyaṃ paṭivasati lābhaggappatto ceva yasaggappatto ca vajjigāme.**Now at that time the naked ascetic Kaḷāramaṭṭaka was residing in Vesālī. And in the Vajjian capital he had reached the peak of material possessions and fame.*";
P_HTM[149]="*Tassa sattavatapadāni samattāni samādinnāni honti:**He had undertaken these seven vows.*";
P_HTM[150]="*‘yāvajīvaṃ acelako assaṃ, na vatthaṃ paridaheyyaṃ, yāvajīvaṃ brahmacārī assaṃ, na methunaṃ dhammaṃ paṭiseveyyaṃ, yāvajīvaṃ surāmaṃseneva yāpeyyaṃ, na odanakummāsaṃ bhuñjeyyaṃ.**‘As long as I live, I will be a naked ascetic, not wearing clothes. As long as I live, I will be celibate, not having sex. As long as I live, I will consume only meat and alcohol, not eating rice and porridge.*";
P_HTM[151]="*Puratthimena vesāliṃ udenaṃ nāma cetiyaṃ, taṃ nātikkameyyaṃ, dakkhiṇena vesāliṃ gotamakaṃ nāma cetiyaṃ, taṃ nātikkameyyaṃ, pacchimena vesāliṃ sattambaṃ nāma cetiyaṃ, taṃ nātikkameyyaṃ, uttarena vesāliṃ bahuputtaṃ nāma cetiyaṃ taṃ nātikkameyyan’ti.**And I will not go past the following tree shrines near Vesālī: the Udena shrine to the east, the Gotamaka to the south, the Sattamba to the west, and the Bahuputta to the north.’*";
P_HTM[152]="*So imesaṃ sattannaṃ vatapadānaṃ samādānahetu lābhaggappatto ceva yasaggappatto ca vajjigāme.**And it was due to undertaking these seven vows that he had reached the peak of material possessions and fame.*";
P_HTM[153]="*Atha kho, bhaggava, sunakkhatto licchaviputto yena acelo kaḷāramaṭṭako tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā acelaṃ kaḷāramaṭṭakaṃ pañhaṃ apucchi.**So, Bhaggava, Sunakkhatta went to see Kaḷāramaṭṭaka and asked him a question.*";
P_HTM[154]="*Tassa acelo kaḷāramaṭṭako pañhaṃ puṭṭho na sampāyāsi.**But when he couldn’t answer it,*";
P_HTM[155]="*Asampāyanto kopañca dosañca appaccayañca pātvākāsi.**he displayed irritation, hate, and bitterness.*";
P_HTM[156]="*Atha kho, bhaggava, sunakkhattassa licchaviputtassa etadahosi:**So Sunakkhatta thought,*";
P_HTM[157]="*‘sādhurūpaṃ vata bho arahantaṃ samaṇaṃ āsādimhase.**‘I’ve offended the holy man, the perfected one, the ascetic.*";
P_HTM[158]="*Mā vata no ahosi dīgharattaṃ ahitāya dukkhāyā’ti.**I mustn’t create lasting harm and suffering for myself!’*";
P_HTM[159]="*Atha kho, bhaggava, sunakkhatto licchaviputto yenāhaṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā maṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho ahaṃ, bhaggava, sunakkhattaṃ licchaviputtaṃ etadavocaṃ:**Then Sunakkhatta came to me, bowed, and sat down to one side. I said to him,*";
P_HTM[160]="*‘tvampi nāma, moghapurisa, samaṇo sakyaputtiyo paṭijānissasī’ti.**‘Don’t you claim to be an ascetic, a follower of the Sakyan, you silly man?’*";
P_HTM[161]="*‘Kiṃ pana maṃ, bhante, bhagavā evamāha—**‘But why does the Buddha say this to me?’*";
P_HTM[162]="*tvampi nāma, moghapurisa, samaṇo sakyaputtiyo paṭijānissasī’ti?* **";
P_HTM[163]="*‘Nanu tvaṃ, sunakkhatta, acelaṃ kaḷāramaṭṭakaṃ upasaṅkamitvā pañhaṃ apucchi.**‘Didn’t you go to see the naked ascetic Kaḷāramaṭṭaka and ask him a question?*";
P_HTM[164]="*Tassa te acelo kaḷāramaṭṭako pañhaṃ puṭṭho na sampāyāsi.**But when he couldn’t answer it,*";
P_HTM[165]="*Asampāyanto kopañca dosañca appaccayañca pātvākāsi.**he displayed irritation, hate, and bitterness.*";
P_HTM[166]="*Tassa te etadahosi:**Then you thought,*";
P_HTM[167]="*“sādhurūpaṃ vata bho arahantaṃ samaṇaṃ āsādimhase.**“I’ve offended the holy man, the perfected one, the ascetic.*";
P_HTM[168]="*Mā vata no ahosi dīgharattaṃ ahitāya dukkhāyā”’ti.**I mustn’t create lasting harm and suffering for myself!”’*";
P_HTM[169]="*‘Evaṃ, bhante.**‘Yes, sir.*";
P_HTM[170]="*Kiṃ pana, bhante, bhagavā arahattassa maccharāyatī’ti?**But sir, are you jealous of perfected ones?’*";
P_HTM[171]="*‘Na kho ahaṃ, moghapurisa, arahattassa maccharāyāmi,**‘I’m not jealous of the perfected ones, you silly man.*";
P_HTM[172]="*api ca tuyhevetaṃ pāpakaṃ diṭṭhigataṃ uppannaṃ, taṃ pajaha.**Rather, you should give up this harmful misconception that has arisen in you.*";
P_HTM[173]="*Mā te ahosi dīgharattaṃ ahitāya dukkhāya.**Don’t create lasting harm and suffering for yourself!*";
P_HTM[174]="*Yaṃ kho panetaṃ, sunakkhatta, maññasi acelaṃ kaḷāramaṭṭakaṃ—**That naked ascetic Kaḷāramaṭṭaka, who you imagine to be a true holy man,*";
P_HTM[175]="*sādhurūpo ayaṃ samaṇoti, so nacirasseva parihito sānucāriko vicaranto odanakummāsaṃ bhuñjamāno sabbāneva vesāliyāni cetiyāni samatikkamitvā yasā nihīno kālaṃ karissatī’ti.**will shortly be clothed, living with a partner, eating rice and porridge, having gone past all the shrines near Vesālī. And he will die after losing all his fame.’*";
P_HTM[176]="*Atha kho, bhaggava, acelo kaḷāramaṭṭako nacirasseva parihito sānucāriko vicaranto odanakummāsaṃ bhuñjamāno sabbāneva vesāliyāni cetiyāni samatikkamitvā yasā nihīno kālamakāsi.**And that’s exactly what happened.*";
P_HTM[177]="*Assosi kho, bhaggava, sunakkhatto licchaviputto:**Sunakkhatta heard about this.*";
P_HTM[178]="*‘acelo kira kaḷāramaṭṭako parihito sānucāriko vicaranto odanakummāsaṃ bhuñjamāno sabbāneva vesāliyāni cetiyāni samatikkamitvā yasā nihīno kālaṅkato’ti.* **";
P_HTM[179]="*Atha kho, bhaggava, sunakkhatto licchaviputto yenāhaṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā maṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho ahaṃ, bhaggava, sunakkhattaṃ licchaviputtaṃ etadavocaṃ:**He came to me, bowed, and sat down to one side. I said to him,*";
P_HTM[180]="*‘Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, sunakkhatta,**‘What do you think, Sunakkhatta?*";
P_HTM[181]="*yatheva te ahaṃ acelaṃ kaḷāramaṭṭakaṃ ārabbha byākāsiṃ, tatheva taṃ vipākaṃ, aññathā vā’ti?**Did the declaration I made about Kaḷāramaṭṭaka turn out to be correct, or not?’*";
P_HTM[182]="*‘Yatheva me, bhante, bhagavā acelaṃ kaḷāramaṭṭakaṃ ārabbha byākāsi, tatheva taṃ vipākaṃ, no aññathā’ti.**‘It turned out to be correct.’*";
P_HTM[183]="*‘Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, sunakkhatta,**‘What do you think, Sunakkhatta?*";
P_HTM[184]="*yadi evaṃ sante kataṃ vā hoti uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ akataṃ vā’ti?**If that is so, has a superhuman demonstration of psychic power been performed or not?’*";
P_HTM[185]="*‘Addhā kho, bhante, evaṃ sante kataṃ hoti uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ, no akatan’ti.**‘Clearly, sir, a superhuman demonstration of psychic power has been performed.’*";
P_HTM[186]="*‘Evampi kho maṃ tvaṃ, moghapurisa, uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ karontaṃ evaṃ vadesi:**‘Though I perform such a superhuman demonstration of psychic power you say this:*";
P_HTM[187]="*“na hi pana me, bhante, bhagavā uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ karotī”ti.**“But sir, the Buddha never performs any superhuman demonstrations of psychic power for me.”*";
P_HTM[188]="*Passa, moghapurisa, yāvañca te idaṃ aparaddhan’ti.**See how far you have strayed!’*";
P_HTM[189]="*Evampi kho, bhaggava, sunakkhatto licchaviputto mayā vuccamāno apakkameva imasmā dhammavinayā, yathā taṃ āpāyiko nerayiko.**Though I spoke to Sunakkhatta like this, he still left this teaching and training, like someone on the highway to hell.*";
P_HTM[190]="*4. Acelapāthikaputtavatthu**4. On the Naked Ascetic Pāṭikaputta*";
P_HTM[191]="*Ekamidāhaṃ, bhaggava, samayaṃ tattheva vesāliyaṃ viharāmi mahāvane kūṭāgārasālāyaṃ.**This one time, Bhaggava, I was staying right there near Vesālī, at the Great Wood, in the hall with the peaked roof.*";
P_HTM[192]="*Tena kho pana samayena acelo pāthikaputto vesāliyaṃ paṭivasati lābhaggappatto ceva yasaggappatto ca vajjigāme.**Now at that time the naked ascetic Pāṭikaputta was residing in Vesālī. And in the Vajjian capital he had reached the peak of material possessions and fame.*";
P_HTM[193]="*So vesāliyaṃ parisati evaṃ vācaṃ bhāsati:**He was telling a crowd in Vesālī:*";
P_HTM[194]="*‘samaṇopi gotamo ñāṇavādo, ahampi ñāṇavādo.**‘Both the ascetic Gotama and I speak from knowledge.*";
P_HTM[195]="*Ñāṇavādo kho pana ñāṇavādena arahati uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ dassetuṃ.**One who speaks from knowledge ought to display a superhuman demonstration of psychic power to another who speaks from knowledge.*";
P_HTM[196]="*Samaṇo gotamo upaḍḍhapathaṃ āgaccheyya, ahampi upaḍḍhapathaṃ gaccheyyaṃ.**If the ascetic Gotama meets me half-way,*";
P_HTM[197]="*Te tattha ubhopi uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ kareyyāma.**there we should both perform a superhuman demonstration of psychic power.*";
P_HTM[198]="*Ekañce samaṇo gotamo uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ karissati, dvāhaṃ karissāmi.**If he performs one demonstration of psychic power, I’ll perform two.*";
P_HTM[199]="*Dve ce samaṇo gotamo uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyāni karissati, cattārāhaṃ karissāmi.**If he performs two, I’ll perform four.*";
P_HTM[200]="*Cattāri ce samaṇo gotamo uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyāni karissati, aṭṭhāhaṃ karissāmi.**If he performs four, I’ll perform eight.*";
P_HTM[201]="*Iti yāvatakaṃ yāvatakaṃ samaṇo gotamo uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ karissati, taddiguṇaṃ taddiguṇāhaṃ karissāmī’ti.**However many demonstrations of psychic power the ascetic Gotama performs, I’ll perform double.’*";
P_HTM[202]="*Atha kho, bhaggava, sunakkhatto licchaviputto yenāhaṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā maṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho, bhaggava, sunakkhatto licchaviputto maṃ etadavoca:**Then Sunakkhatta came to me, bowed, sat down to one side, and told me of all this.*";
P_HTM[203]="*‘acelo, bhante, pāthikaputto vesāliyaṃ paṭivasati lābhaggappatto ceva yasaggappatto ca vajjigāme.* **";
P_HTM[204]="*So vesāliyaṃ parisati evaṃ vācaṃ bhāsati:* **";
P_HTM[205]="*“samaṇopi gotamo ñāṇavādo, ahampi ñāṇavādo.* **";
P_HTM[206]="*Ñāṇavādo kho pana ñāṇavādena arahati uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ dassetuṃ.* **";
P_HTM[207]="*Samaṇo gotamo upaḍḍhapathaṃ āgaccheyya, ahampi upaḍḍhapathaṃ gaccheyyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[208]="*Te tattha ubhopi uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ kareyyāma.* **";
P_HTM[209]="*Ekañce samaṇo gotamo uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ karissati, dvāhaṃ karissāmi.* **";
P_HTM[210]="*Dve ce samaṇo gotamo uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyāni karissati, cattārāhaṃ karissāmi.* **";
P_HTM[211]="*Cattāri ce samaṇo gotamo uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyāni karissati, aṭṭhāhaṃ karissāmi.* **";
P_HTM[212]="*Iti yāvatakaṃ yāvatakaṃ samaṇo gotamo uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ karissati, taddiguṇaṃ taddiguṇāhaṃ karissāmī”’ti.* **";
P_HTM[213]="*Evaṃ vutte, ahaṃ, bhaggava, sunakkhattaṃ licchaviputtaṃ etadavocaṃ:**I said to him,*";
P_HTM[214]="*‘abhabbo kho, sunakkhatta, acelo pāthikaputto taṃ vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā mama sammukhībhāvaṃ āgantuṃ.**‘Sunakkhatta, the naked ascetic Pāṭikaputta is not capable of coming into my presence, unless he gives up that statement and that intention, and lets go of that view.*";
P_HTM[215]="*Sacepissa evamassa—**If he thinks he can*";
P_HTM[216]="*ahaṃ taṃ vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā samaṇassa gotamassa sammukhībhāvaṃ gaccheyyanti, muddhāpi tassa vipateyyā’ti.**come into my presence without giving up those things, his head may explode.’*";
P_HTM[217]="*‘Rakkhatetaṃ, bhante, bhagavā vācaṃ, rakkhatetaṃ sugato vācan’ti.**‘Careful what you say, Blessed One! Careful what you say, Holy One!’*";
P_HTM[218]="*‘Kiṃ pana maṃ tvaṃ, sunakkhatta, evaṃ vadesi—**‘But why do you say this to me, Sunakkhatta?’*";
P_HTM[219]="*rakkhatetaṃ, bhante, bhagavā vācaṃ, rakkhatetaṃ sugato vācan’ti?* **";
P_HTM[220]="*‘Bhagavatā cassa, bhante, esā vācā ekaṃsena odhāritā—**‘Sir, the Buddha has definitively asserted that*";
P_HTM[221]="*abhabbo acelo pāthikaputto taṃ vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā mama sammukhībhāvaṃ āgantuṃ.**Pāṭikaputta is not capable of coming into the Buddha’s presence, otherwise*";
P_HTM[222]="*Sacepissa evamassa—* **";
P_HTM[223]="*ahaṃ taṃ vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā samaṇassa gotamassa sammukhībhāvaṃ gaccheyyanti, muddhāpi tassa vipateyyāti.**his head may explode.*";
P_HTM[224]="*Acelo ca, bhante, pāthikaputto virūparūpena bhagavato sammukhībhāvaṃ āgaccheyya, tadassa bhagavato musā’ti.**But Pāṭikaputta might come into the Buddha’s presence in disguise, proving the Buddha wrong.’*";
P_HTM[225]="*‘Api nu, sunakkhatta, tathāgato taṃ vācaṃ bhāseyya yā sā vācā dvayagāminī’ti?**‘Sunakkhatta, would the Realized One make an ambiguous statement?’*";
P_HTM[226]="*‘Kiṃ pana, bhante, bhagavatā acelo pāthikaputto cetasā ceto paricca vidito—**‘But sir, did you make that statement after comprehending Pāṭikaputta’s mind with your mind?*";
P_HTM[227]="*abhabbo acelo pāthikaputto taṃ vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā mama sammukhībhāvaṃ āgantuṃ.* **";
P_HTM[228]="*Sacepissa evamassa—* **";
P_HTM[229]="*ahaṃ taṃ vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā samaṇassa gotamassa sammukhībhāvaṃ gaccheyyanti, muddhāpi tassa vipateyyāti?* **";
P_HTM[230]="*Udāhu, devatā bhagavato etamatthaṃ ārocesuṃ—**Or did deities tell you about it?’*";
P_HTM[231]="*abhabbo, bhante, acelo pāthikaputto taṃ vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā bhagavato sammukhībhāvaṃ āgantuṃ.* **";
P_HTM[232]="*Sacepissa evamassa—* **";
P_HTM[233]="*ahaṃ taṃ vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā samaṇassa gotamassa sammukhībhāvaṃ gaccheyyanti, muddhāpi tassa vipateyyā’ti?* **";
P_HTM[234]="*‘Cetasā ceto paricca vidito ceva me, sunakkhatta, acelo pāthikaputto—**‘Both, Sunakkhatta.*";
P_HTM[235]="*abhabbo acelo pāthikaputto taṃ vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā mama sammukhībhāvaṃ āgantuṃ.* **";
P_HTM[236]="*Sacepissa evamassa—* **";
P_HTM[237]="*ahaṃ taṃ vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā samaṇassa gotamassa sammukhībhāvaṃ gaccheyyanti, muddhāpi tassa vipateyyāti.* **";
P_HTM[238]="*Devatāpi me etamatthaṃ ārocesuṃ—* **";
P_HTM[239]="*abhabbo, bhante, acelo pāthikaputto taṃ vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā bhagavato sammukhībhāvaṃ āgantuṃ.* **";
P_HTM[240]="*Sacepissa evamassa—* **";
P_HTM[241]="*ahaṃ taṃ vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā samaṇassa gotamassa sammukhībhāvaṃ gaccheyyanti, muddhāpi tassa vipateyyāti.* **";
P_HTM[242]="*Ajitopi nāma licchavīnaṃ senāpati adhunā kālaṅkato tāvatiṃsakāyaṃ upapanno.**For Ajita the Licchavi general has recently passed away and been reborn in the host of the Thirty-Three.*";
P_HTM[243]="*Sopi maṃ upasaṅkamitvā evamārocesi—**He came and told me this,*";
P_HTM[244]="*alajjī, bhante, acelo pāthikaputto;**“The naked ascetic Pāṭikaputta is shameless, sir,*";
P_HTM[245]="*musāvādī, bhante, acelo pāthikaputto.**he is a liar.*";
P_HTM[246]="*Mampi, bhante, acelo pāthikaputto byākāsi vajjigāme—**For he has declared of me in the Vajjian capital:*";
P_HTM[247]="*ajito licchavīnaṃ senāpati mahānirayaṃ upapannoti.**‘Ajita the Licchavi general has been reborn in the Great Hell.’*";
P_HTM[248]="*Na kho panāhaṃ, bhante, mahānirayaṃ upapanno;**But that is not true—*";
P_HTM[249]="*tāvatiṃsakāyamhi upapanno.**I have been reborn in the host of the Thirty-Three.*";
P_HTM[250]="*Alajjī, bhante, acelo pāthikaputto;**The naked ascetic Pāṭikaputta is shameless, sir,*";
P_HTM[251]="*musāvādī, bhante, acelo pāthikaputto;**he is a liar.*";
P_HTM[252]="*abhabbo ca, bhante, acelo pāthikaputto taṃ vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā bhagavato sammukhībhāvaṃ āgantuṃ.**Pāṭikaputta is not capable of coming into the Buddha’s presence, otherwise*";
P_HTM[253]="*Sacepissa evamassa—* **";
P_HTM[254]="*ahaṃ taṃ vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā samaṇassa gotamassa sammukhībhāvaṃ gaccheyyanti, muddhāpi tassa vipateyyāti.**his head may explode.”*";
P_HTM[255]="*Iti kho, sunakkhatta, cetasā ceto paricca vidito ceva me acelo pāthikaputto abhabbo acelo pāthikaputto taṃ vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā mama sammukhībhāvaṃ āgantuṃ.**Thus I both made that statement after comprehending Pāṭikaputta’s mind with my mind,*";
P_HTM[256]="*Sacepissa evamassa—* **";
P_HTM[257]="*ahaṃ taṃ vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā samaṇassa gotamassa sammukhībhāvaṃ gaccheyyanti, muddhāpi tassa vipateyyāti.* **";
P_HTM[258]="*Devatāpi me etamatthaṃ ārocesuṃ—**and deities told me about it.*";
P_HTM[259]="*abhabbo, bhante, acelo pāthikaputto taṃ vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā bhagavato sammukhībhāvaṃ āgantuṃ.* **";
P_HTM[260]="*Sacepissa evamassa—* **";
P_HTM[261]="*ahaṃ taṃ vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā samaṇassa gotamassa sammukhībhāvaṃ gaccheyyanti, muddhāpi tassa vipateyyāti.* **";
P_HTM[262]="*So kho panāhaṃ, sunakkhatta, vesāliyaṃ piṇḍāya caritvā pacchābhattaṃ piṇḍapātapaṭikkanto yena acelassa pāthikaputtassa ārāmo tenupasaṅkamissāmi divāvihārāya.**So Sunakkhatta, I’ll wander for alms in Vesālī. After the meal, on my return from alms-round, I’ll go to Pāṭikaputta’s monastery for the day’s meditation.*";
P_HTM[263]="*Yassadāni tvaṃ, sunakkhatta, icchasi, tassa ārocehī’ti.**Now you may tell him, if you so wish.’*";
P_HTM[264]="*5. Iddhipāṭihāriyakathā**5. On Demonstrations of Psychic Power*";
P_HTM[265]="*Atha khvāhaṃ, bhaggava, pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya vesāliṃ piṇḍāya pāvisiṃ.**Then, Bhaggava, I robed up in the morning and, taking my bowl and robe, entered Vesālī for alms.*";
P_HTM[266]="*Vesāliyaṃ piṇḍāya caritvā pacchābhattaṃ piṇḍapātapaṭikkanto yena acelassa pāthikaputtassa ārāmo tenupasaṅkamiṃ divāvihārāya.**After the meal, on my return from alms-round, I went to Pāṭikaputta’s monastery for the day’s meditation.*";
P_HTM[267]="*Atha kho, bhaggava, sunakkhatto licchaviputto taramānarūpo vesāliṃ pavisitvā yena abhiññātā abhiññātā licchavī tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā abhiññāte abhiññāte licchavī etadavoca:**Then Sunakkhatta rushed into Vesālī to see the very well-known Licchavis and said to them,*";
P_HTM[268]="*‘esāvuso, bhagavā vesāliyaṃ piṇḍāya caritvā pacchābhattaṃ piṇḍapātapaṭikkanto yena acelassa pāthikaputtassa ārāmo tenupasaṅkami divāvihārāya.**‘Sirs, after his alms-round, the Buddha has gone to Pāṭikaputta’s monastery for the day’s meditation.*";
P_HTM[269]="*Abhikkamathāyasmanto abhikkamathāyasmanto, sādhurūpānaṃ samaṇānaṃ uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ bhavissatī’ti.**Come forth, sirs, come forth! There will be a superhuman demonstration of psychic power by the holy ascetics!’*";
P_HTM[270]="*Atha kho, bhaggava, abhiññātānaṃ abhiññātānaṃ licchavīnaṃ etadahosi:**So the very well-known Licchavis thought,*";
P_HTM[271]="*‘sādhurūpānaṃ kira, bho, samaṇānaṃ uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ bhavissati;**‘It seems there will be a superhuman demonstration of psychic power by the holy ascetics!*";
P_HTM[272]="*handa vata, bho, gacchāmā’ti.**Let’s go!’*";
P_HTM[273]="*Yena ca abhiññātā abhiññātā brāhmaṇamahāsālā gahapatinecayikā nānātitthiyā samaṇabrāhmaṇā tenupasaṅkami. upasaṅkamitvā abhiññāte abhiññāte nānātitthiye samaṇabrāhmaṇe etadavoca:**Then he went to see the very well-known well-to-do brahmins, rich householders, and ascetics and brahmins who follow various other paths, and said the same thing.*";
P_HTM[274]="*‘esāvuso, bhagavā vesāliyaṃ piṇḍāya caritvā pacchābhattaṃ piṇḍapātapaṭikkanto yena acelassa pāthikaputtassa ārāmo tenupasaṅkami divāvihārāya.* **";
P_HTM[275]="*Abhikkamathāyasmanto abhikkamathāyasmanto, sādhurūpānaṃ samaṇānaṃ uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ bhavissatī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[276]="*Atha kho, bhaggava, abhiññātānaṃ abhiññātānaṃ nānātitthiyānaṃ samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ etadahosi:**They all said,*";
P_HTM[277]="*‘sādhurūpānaṃ kira, bho, samaṇānaṃ uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ bhavissati;**‘It seems there will be a superhuman demonstration of psychic power by the holy ascetics!*";
P_HTM[278]="*handa vata, bho, gacchāmā’ti.**Let’s go!’*";
P_HTM[279]="*Atha kho, bhaggava, abhiññātā abhiññātā licchavī, abhiññātā abhiññātā ca brāhmaṇamahāsālā gahapatinecayikā nānātitthiyā samaṇabrāhmaṇā yena acelassa pāthikaputtassa ārāmo tenupasaṅkamiṃsu.**Then all those very well-known people went to Pāṭikaputta’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[280]="*Sā esā, bhaggava, parisā mahā hoti anekasatā anekasahassā.**That assembly was large, Bhaggava; there were many hundreds, many thousands of them.*";
P_HTM[281]="*Assosi kho, bhaggava, acelo pāthikaputto:**Pāṭikaputta heard,*";
P_HTM[282]="*‘abhikkantā kira abhiññātā abhiññātā licchavī, abhikkantā abhiññātā abhiññātā ca brāhmaṇamahāsālā gahapatinecayikā nānātitthiyā samaṇabrāhmaṇā.**‘It seems that very well-known Licchavis, well-to-do brahmins, rich householders, and ascetics and brahmins who follow various other paths have come forth.*";
P_HTM[283]="*Samaṇopi gotamo mayhaṃ ārāme divāvihāraṃ nisinno’ti.**And the ascetic Gotama is sitting in my monastery for the day’s meditation.’*";
P_HTM[284]="*Sutvānassa bhayaṃ chambhitattaṃ lomahaṃso udapādi.**When he heard that, he became frightened, scared, his hair standing on end.*";
P_HTM[285]="*Atha kho, bhaggava, acelo pāthikaputto bhīto saṃviggo lomahaṭṭhajāto yena tindukakhāṇuparibbājakārāmo tenupasaṅkami.**In fear he went to the Pale-Moon Ebony Trunk Monastery of the wanderers.*";
P_HTM[286]="*Assosi kho, bhaggava, sā parisā:**The assembly heard of this,*";
P_HTM[287]="*‘acelo kira pāthikaputto bhīto saṃviggo lomahaṭṭhajāto yena tindukakhāṇuparibbājakārāmo tenupasaṅkanto’ti.* **";
P_HTM[288]="*Atha kho, bhaggava, sā parisā aññataraṃ purisaṃ āmantesi:**and instructed a man,*";
P_HTM[289]="*‘Ehi tvaṃ, bho purisa, yena tindukakhāṇuparibbājakārāmo, yena acelo pāthikaputto tenupasaṅkama. upasaṅkamitvā acelaṃ pāthikaputtaṃ evaṃ vadehi:**‘Come, my man, go to see Pāṭikaputta at the Pale-Moon Ebony Trunk Monastery and say to him,*";
P_HTM[290]="*“abhikkamāvuso, pāthikaputta, abhikkantā abhiññātā abhiññātā licchavī, abhikkantā abhiññātā abhiññātā ca brāhmaṇamahāsālā gahapatinecayikā nānātitthiyā samaṇabrāhmaṇā, samaṇopi gotamo āyasmato ārāme divāvihāraṃ nisinno;**“Come forth, Reverend Pāṭikaputta! All these very well-known people have come forth, and the ascetic Gotama is sitting in your monastery for the day’s meditation.*";
P_HTM[291]="*bhāsitā kho pana te esā, āvuso pāthikaputta, vesāliyaṃ parisati vācā**For you stated this in the assembly at Vesālī:*";
P_HTM[292]="*samaṇopi gotamo ñāṇavādo, ahampi ñāṇavādo.**‘Both the ascetic Gotama and I speak from knowledge.*";
P_HTM[293]="*Ñāṇavādo kho pana ñāṇavādena arahati uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ dassetuṃ.**One who speaks from knowledge ought to display a superhuman demonstration of psychic power to another who speaks from knowledge.*";
P_HTM[294]="*Samaṇo gotamo upaḍḍhapathaṃ āgaccheyya ahampi upaḍḍhapathaṃ gaccheyyaṃ.**If the ascetic Gotama meets me half-way,*";
P_HTM[295]="*Te tattha ubhopi uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ kareyyāma.**there we should both perform a superhuman demonstration of psychic power.*";
P_HTM[296]="*Ekañce samaṇo gotamo uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ karissati, dvāhaṃ karissāmi.**If he performs one demonstration of psychic power, I’ll perform two.*";
P_HTM[297]="*Dve ce samaṇo gotamo uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyāni karissati, cattārāhaṃ karissāmi.**If he performs two, I’ll perform four.*";
P_HTM[298]="*Cattāri ce samaṇo gotamo uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyāni karissati, aṭṭhāhaṃ karissāmi.**If he performs four, I’ll perform eight.*";
P_HTM[299]="*Iti yāvatakaṃ yāvatakaṃ samaṇo gotamo uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ karissati, taddiguṇaṃ taddiguṇāhaṃ karissāmī”ti**However many demonstrations of psychic power the ascetic Gotama performs, I’ll perform double.’*";
P_HTM[300]="*abhikkamasseva kho āvuso pāthikaputta, upaḍḍhapathaṃ.**Come forth, Reverend Pāṭikaputta, half-way.*";
P_HTM[301]="*Sabbapaṭhamaṃyeva āgantvā samaṇo gotamo āyasmato ārāme divāvihāraṃ nisinno’ti.**The ascetic Gotama has come the first half, and is sitting in your monastery.”’*";
P_HTM[302]="*Evaṃ, bhoti kho, bhaggava, so puriso tassā parisāya paṭissutvā yena tindukakhāṇuparibbājakārāmo, yena acelo pāthikaputto tenupasaṅkami. upasaṅkamitvā acelaṃ pāthikaputtaṃ etadavoca:**‘Yes, sir,’ replied that man, and delivered the message.*";
P_HTM[303]="*‘abhikkamāvuso pāthikaputta, abhikkantā abhiññātā abhiññātā licchavī, abhikkantā abhiññātā abhiññātā ca brāhmaṇamahāsālā gahapatinecayikā nānātitthiyā samaṇabrāhmaṇā.* **";
P_HTM[304]="*Samaṇopi gotamo āyasmato ārāme divāvihāraṃ nisinno.* **";
P_HTM[305]="*Bhāsitā kho pana te esā, āvuso pāthikaputta, vesāliyaṃ parisati vācā—* **";
P_HTM[306]="*samaṇopi gotamo ñāṇavādo; ahampi ñāṇavādo.* **";
P_HTM[307]="*Ñāṇavādo kho pana ñāṇavādena arahati uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ dassetuṃ … pe …* **";
P_HTM[308]="*taddiguṇaṃ taddiguṇāhaṃ karissāmīti.* **";
P_HTM[309]="*Abhikkamasseva kho, āvuso pāthikaputta, upaḍḍhapathaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[310]="*Sabbapaṭhamaṃyeva āgantvā samaṇo gotamo āyasmato ārāme divāvihāraṃ nisinno’ti.* **";
P_HTM[311]="*Evaṃ vutte, bhaggava, acelo pāthikaputto ‘āyāmi, āvuso, āyāmi, āvuso’ti vatvā tattheva saṃsappati, na sakkoti āsanāpi vuṭṭhātuṃ.**When he had spoken, Pāṭika said: ‘I’m coming, sir, I’m coming!’ But wriggle as he might, he couldn’t get up from his seat.*";
P_HTM[312]="*Atha kho so, bhaggava, puriso acelaṃ pāthikaputtaṃ etadavoca:**Then that man said to Pāṭikaputta,*";
P_HTM[313]="*‘kiṃ su nāma te, āvuso pāthikaputta, pāvaḷā su nāma te pīṭhakasmiṃ allīnā, pīṭhakaṃ su nāma te pāvaḷāsu allīnaṃ?**‘What’s up, Reverend Pāṭikaputta? Is your bottom stuck to the bench, or is the bench stuck to your bottom?*";
P_HTM[314]="*Āyāmi āvuso, āyāmi āvusoti vatvā tattheva saṃsappasi, na sakkosi āsanāpi vuṭṭhātun’ti.**You say “I’m coming, sir, I’m coming!” But wriggle as you might, you can’t get up from your seat.’*";
P_HTM[315]="*Evampi kho, bhaggava, vuccamāno acelo pāthikaputto ‘āyāmi, āvuso, āyāmi, āvuso’ti vatvā tattheva saṃsappati, na sakkoti āsanāpi vuṭṭhātuṃ.**And as he was speaking, Pāṭika said: ‘I’m coming, sir, I’m coming!’ But wriggle as he might, he couldn’t get up from his seat.*";
P_HTM[316]="*Yadā kho so, bhaggava, puriso aññāsi:**When that man knew*";
P_HTM[317]="*‘parābhūtarūpo ayaṃ acelo pāthikaputto.**that Pāṭikaputta had lost,*";
P_HTM[318]="*Āyāmi, āvuso, āyāmi, āvusoti vatvā tattheva saṃsappati, na sakkoti āsanāpi vuṭṭhātun’ti.* **";
P_HTM[319]="*Atha taṃ parisaṃ āgantvā evamārocesi:**he returned to the assembly and said,*";
P_HTM[320]="*‘parābhūtarūpo, bho, acelo pāthikaputto.**‘Pāṭikaputta has lost, sirs.*";
P_HTM[321]="*Āyāmi, āvuso, āyāmi, āvusoti vatvā tattheva saṃsappati, na sakkoti āsanāpi vuṭṭhātun’ti.**He says “I’m coming, sir, I’m coming!” But wriggle as he might, he can’t get up from his seat.’*";
P_HTM[322]="*Evaṃ vutte, ahaṃ, bhaggava, taṃ parisaṃ etadavocaṃ:**When he said this, I said to the assembly,*";
P_HTM[323]="*‘abhabbo kho, āvuso, acelo pāthikaputto taṃ vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā mama sammukhībhāvaṃ āgantuṃ.**‘The naked ascetic Pāṭikaputta is not capable of coming into my presence, unless he gives up that statement and that intention, and lets go of that view.*";
P_HTM[324]="*Sacepissa evamassa—**If he thinks he can*";
P_HTM[325]="*ahaṃ taṃ vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā samaṇassa gotamassa sammukhībhāvaṃ gaccheyyanti, muddhāpi tassa vipateyyā’ti.**come into my presence without giving up those things, his head may explode.’*";
P_HTM[326]="*Paṭhamabhāṇavāro niṭṭhito.**The first recitation section is finished.*";
P_HTM[327]="*Atha kho, bhaggava, aññataro licchavimahāmatto uṭṭhāyāsanā taṃ parisaṃ etadavoca:**Then, Bhaggava, a certain Licchavi minister stood up and said to the assembly,*";
P_HTM[328]="*‘tena hi, bho, muhuttaṃ tāva āgametha, yāvāhaṃ gacchāmi.**‘Well then, sirs, wait a moment, I’ll go.*";
P_HTM[329]="*Appeva nāma ahampi sakkuṇeyyaṃ acelaṃ pāthikaputtaṃ imaṃ parisaṃ ānetun’ti.**Hopefully I’ll be able to lead Pāṭikaputta back to the assembly.’*";
P_HTM[330]="*Atha kho so, bhaggava, licchavimahāmatto yena tindukakhāṇuparibbājakārāmo, yena acelo pāthikaputto tenupasaṅkami. upasaṅkamitvā acelaṃ pāthikaputtaṃ etadavoca:**So that minister went to see Pāṭikaputta and said,*";
P_HTM[331]="*‘abhikkamāvuso pāthikaputta, abhikkantaṃ te seyyo, abhikkantā abhiññātā abhiññātā licchavī, abhikkantā abhiññātā abhiññātā ca brāhmaṇamahāsālā gahapatinecayikā nānātitthiyā samaṇabrāhmaṇā. Samaṇopi gotamo āyasmato ārāme divāvihāraṃ nisinno.**‘Come forth, Reverend Pāṭikaputta! It’s best for you to come forth. All these very well-known people have come forth, and the ascetic Gotama is sitting in your monastery for the day’s meditation.*";
P_HTM[332]="*Bhāsitā kho pana te esā, āvuso pāthikaputta, vesāliyaṃ parisati vācā—**You said you’d meet the ascetic Gotama half-way.*";
P_HTM[333]="*samaṇopi gotamo ñāṇavādo … pe …* **";
P_HTM[334]="*taddiguṇaṃ taddiguṇāhaṃ karissāmīti.* **";
P_HTM[335]="*Abhikkamasseva kho, āvuso pāthikaputta, upaḍḍhapathaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[336]="*Sabbapaṭhamaṃyeva āgantvā samaṇo gotamo āyasmato ārāme divāvihāraṃ nisinno.**The ascetic Gotama has come the first half, and is sitting in your monastery.*";
P_HTM[337]="*Bhāsitā kho panesā, āvuso pāthikaputta, samaṇena gotamena parisati vācā—**The ascetic Gotama has told the assembly*";
P_HTM[338]="*abhabbo kho acelo pāthikaputto taṃ vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā mama sammukhībhāvaṃ āgantuṃ.**that you’re not capable of coming into his presence.*";
P_HTM[339]="*Sacepissa evamassa—* **";
P_HTM[340]="*ahaṃ taṃ vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā samaṇassa gotamassa sammukhībhāvaṃ gaccheyyanti, muddhāpi tassa vipateyyāti.* **";
P_HTM[341]="*Abhikkamāvuso pāthikaputta, abhikkamaneneva te jayaṃ karissāma, samaṇassa gotamassa parājayan’ti.**Come forth, Pāṭikaputta! When you come forth we’ll make you win and the ascetic Gotama lose.’*";
P_HTM[342]="*Evaṃ vutte, bhaggava, acelo pāthikaputto ‘āyāmi, āvuso, āyāmi, āvuso’ti vatvā tattheva saṃsappati, na sakkoti āsanāpi vuṭṭhātuṃ.**When he had spoken, Pāṭikaputta said: ‘I’m coming, sir, I’m coming!’ But wriggle as he might, he couldn’t get up from his seat.*";
P_HTM[343]="*Atha kho so, bhaggava, licchavimahāmatto acelaṃ pāthikaputtaṃ etadavoca:**Then the minister said to Pāṭikaputta,*";
P_HTM[344]="*‘kiṃ su nāma te, āvuso pāthikaputta, pāvaḷā su nāma te pīṭhakasmiṃ allīnā, pīṭhakaṃ su nāma te pāvaḷāsu allīnaṃ?**‘What’s up, Reverend Pāṭikaputta? Is your bottom stuck to the bench, or is the bench stuck to your bottom?*";
P_HTM[345]="*Āyāmi, āvuso, āyāmi, āvusoti vatvā tattheva saṃsappasi, na sakkosi āsanāpi vuṭṭhātun’ti.**You say “I’m coming, sir, I’m coming!” But wriggle as you might, you can’t get up from your seat.’*";
P_HTM[346]="*Evampi kho, bhaggava, vuccamāno acelo pāthikaputto ‘āyāmi, āvuso, āyāmi, āvuso’ti vatvā tattheva saṃsappati, na sakkoti āsanāpi vuṭṭhātuṃ.**And as he was speaking, Pāṭikaputta said: ‘I’m coming, sir, I’m coming!’ But wriggle as he might, he couldn’t get up from his seat.*";
P_HTM[347]="*Yadā kho so, bhaggava, licchavimahāmatto aññāsi:**When the Licchavi minister knew*";
P_HTM[348]="*‘parābhūtarūpo ayaṃ acelo pāthikaputto āyāmi, āvuso, āyāmi, āvusoti vatvā tattheva saṃsappati, na sakkoti āsanāpi vuṭṭhātun’ti.**that Pāṭikaputta had lost,*";
P_HTM[349]="*Atha taṃ parisaṃ āgantvā evamārocesi:**he returned to the assembly and said,*";
P_HTM[350]="*‘parābhūtarūpo, bho, acelo pāthikaputto āyāmi, āvuso, āyāmi, āvusoti vatvā tattheva saṃsappati, na sakkoti āsanāpi vuṭṭhātun’ti.**‘Pāṭikaputta has lost, sirs.’*";
P_HTM[351]="*Evaṃ vutte, ahaṃ, bhaggava, taṃ parisaṃ etadavocaṃ:**When he said this, I said to the assembly,*";
P_HTM[352]="*‘abhabbo kho, āvuso, acelo pāthikaputto taṃ vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā mama sammukhībhāvaṃ āgantuṃ.**‘Pāṭikaputta is not capable of coming into my presence, otherwise*";
P_HTM[353]="*Sacepissa evamassa—* **";
P_HTM[354]="*ahaṃ taṃ vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā samaṇassa gotamassa sammukhībhāvaṃ gaccheyyanti, muddhāpi tassa vipateyya.**his head may explode.*";
P_HTM[355]="*Sace pāyasmantānaṃ licchavīnaṃ evamassa—**Even if the good Licchavis were to think,*";
P_HTM[356]="*mayaṃ acelaṃ pāthikaputtaṃ varattāhi bandhitvā goyugehi āviñcheyyāmāti, tā varattā chijjeyyuṃ pāthikaputto vā.**“Let’s bind Pāṭikaputta with straps and drag him with a pair of oxen!” But either the straps will break or Pāṭikaputta will.’*";
P_HTM[357]="*Abhabbo pana acelo pāthikaputto taṃ vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā mama sammukhībhāvaṃ āgantuṃ.* **";
P_HTM[358]="*Sacepissa evamassa—* **";
P_HTM[359]="*ahaṃ taṃ vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā samaṇassa gotamassa sammukhībhāvaṃ gaccheyyanti, muddhāpi tassa vipateyyā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[360]="*Atha kho, bhaggava, jāliyo dārupattikantevāsī uṭṭhāyāsanā taṃ parisaṃ etadavoca:**Then, Bhaggava, Jāliya, the pupil of the wood-bowl ascetic, stood up and said to the assembly,*";
P_HTM[361]="*‘tena hi, bho, muhuttaṃ tāva āgametha, yāvāhaṃ gacchāmi;**‘Well then, sirs, wait a moment, I’ll go.*";
P_HTM[362]="*appeva nāma ahampi sakkuṇeyyaṃ acelaṃ pāthikaputtaṃ imaṃ parisaṃ ānetun’ti.**Hopefully I’ll be able to lead Pāṭikaputta back to the assembly.’*";
P_HTM[363]="*Atha kho, bhaggava, jāliyo dārupattikantevāsī yena tindukakhāṇuparibbājakārāmo, yena acelo pāthikaputto tenupasaṅkami. upasaṅkamitvā acelaṃ pāthikaputtaṃ etadavoca:**So Jāliya went to see Pāṭikaputta and said,*";
P_HTM[364]="*‘abhikkamāvuso pāthikaputta, abhikkantaṃ te seyyo. Abhikkantā abhiññātā abhiññātā licchavī, abhikkantā abhiññātā abhiññātā ca brāhmaṇamahāsālā gahapatinecayikā nānātitthiyā samaṇabrāhmaṇā. Samaṇopi gotamo āyasmato ārāme divāvihāraṃ nisinno.**‘Come forth, Reverend Pāṭikaputta! It’s best for you to come forth. All these very well-known people have come forth, and the ascetic Gotama is sitting in your monastery for the day’s meditation.*";
P_HTM[365]="*Bhāsitā kho pana te esā, āvuso pāthikaputta, vesāliyaṃ parisati vācā—**You said you’d meet the ascetic Gotama half-way.*";
P_HTM[366]="*samaṇopi gotamo ñāṇavādo … pe …* **";
P_HTM[367]="*taddiguṇaṃ taddiguṇāhaṃ karissāmīti.* **";
P_HTM[368]="*Abhikkamasseva, kho āvuso pāthikaputta, upaḍḍhapathaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[369]="*Sabbapaṭhamaṃyeva āgantvā samaṇo gotamo āyasmato ārāme divāvihāraṃ nisinno.**The ascetic Gotama has come the first half, and is sitting in your monastery.*";
P_HTM[370]="*Bhāsitā kho panesā, āvuso pāthikaputta, samaṇena gotamena parisati vācā—**The ascetic Gotama has told the assembly*";
P_HTM[371]="*abhabbo acelo pāthikaputto taṃ vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā mama sammukhībhāvaṃ āgantuṃ.**that you’re not capable of coming into his presence.*";
P_HTM[372]="*Sacepissa evamassa—* **";
P_HTM[373]="*ahaṃ taṃ vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā samaṇassa gotamassa sammukhībhāvaṃ gaccheyyanti, muddhāpi tassa vipateyya.* **";
P_HTM[374]="*Sace pāyasmantānaṃ licchavīnaṃ evamassa—**And he said that even if the Licchavis*";
P_HTM[375]="*mayaṃ acelaṃ pāthikaputtaṃ varattāhi bandhitvā goyugehi āviñcheyyāmāti. Tā varattā chijjeyyuṃ pāthikaputto vā.**try to bind you with straps and drag you with a pair of oxen, either the straps will break or you will.*";
P_HTM[376]="*Abhabbo pana acelo pāthikaputto taṃ vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā mama sammukhībhāvaṃ āgantuṃ.* **";
P_HTM[377]="*Sacepissa evamassa—* **";
P_HTM[378]="*ahaṃ taṃ vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā samaṇassa gotamassa sammukhībhāvaṃ āgaccheyyanti, muddhāpi tassa vipateyyāti.* **";
P_HTM[379]="*Abhikkamāvuso pāthikaputta, abhikkamaneneva te jayaṃ karissāma, samaṇassa gotamassa parājayan’ti.**Come forth, Pāṭikaputta! When you come forth we’ll make you win and the ascetic Gotama lose.’*";
P_HTM[380]="*Evaṃ vutte, bhaggava, acelo pāthikaputto ‘āyāmi, āvuso, āyāmi, āvuso’ti vatvā tattheva saṃsappati, na sakkoti āsanāpi vuṭṭhātuṃ.**When he had spoken, Pāṭikaputta said: ‘I’m coming, sir, I’m coming!’ But wriggle as he might, he couldn’t get up from his seat.*";
P_HTM[381]="*Atha kho, bhaggava, jāliyo dārupattikantevāsī acelaṃ pāthikaputtaṃ etadavoca:**Then Jāliya said to Pāṭikaputta,*";
P_HTM[382]="*‘kiṃ su nāma te, āvuso pāthikaputta, pāvaḷā su nāma te pīṭhakasmiṃ allīnā, pīṭhakaṃ su nāma te pāvaḷāsu allīnaṃ?**‘What’s up, Reverend Pāṭikaputta? Is your bottom stuck to the bench, or is the bench stuck to your bottom?*";
P_HTM[383]="*Āyāmi, āvuso, āyāmi, āvusoti vatvā tattheva saṃsappasi, na sakkosi āsanāpi vuṭṭhātun’ti.**You say “I’m coming, sir, I’m coming!” But wriggle as you might, you can’t get up from your seat.’*";
P_HTM[384]="*Evampi kho, bhaggava, vuccamāno acelo pāthikaputto ‘āyāmi, āvuso, āyāmi, āvuso’ti vatvā tattheva saṃsappati, na sakkoti āsanāpi vuṭṭhātunti.**And as he was speaking, Pāṭikaputta said: ‘I’m coming, sir, I’m coming!’ But wriggle as he might, he couldn’t get up from his seat.*";
P_HTM[385]="*Yadā kho, bhaggava, jāliyo dārupattikantevāsī aññāsi:**When Jāliya knew*";
P_HTM[386]="*‘parābhūtarūpo ayaṃ acelo pāthikaputto āyāmi, āvuso, āyāmi, āvusoti vatvā tattheva saṃsappati, na sakkoti āsanāpi vuṭṭhātun’ti, atha naṃ etadavoca—**that Pāṭikaputta had lost, he said to him,*";
P_HTM[387]="*Bhūtapubbaṃ, āvuso pāthikaputta, sīhassa migarañño etadahosi:**‘Once upon a time, Reverend Pāṭikaputta, it occurred to a lion, king of beasts,*";
P_HTM[388]="*‘yannūnāhaṃ aññataraṃ vanasaṇḍaṃ nissāya āsayaṃ kappeyyaṃ.**“Why don’t I make my lair near a certain forest?*";
P_HTM[389]="*Tatrāsayaṃ kappetvā sāyanhasamayaṃ āsayā nikkhameyyaṃ, āsayā nikkhamitvā vijambheyyaṃ, vijambhitvā samantā catuddisā anuvilokeyyaṃ, samantā catuddisā anuviloketvā tikkhattuṃ sīhanādaṃ nadeyyaṃ, tikkhattuṃ sīhanādaṃ naditvā gocarāya pakkameyyaṃ.**Towards evening I can emerge from my den, yawn, look all around the four directions, roar my lion’s roar three times, and set out on the hunt.*";
P_HTM[390]="*So varaṃ varaṃ migasaṅghe vadhitvā mudumaṃsāni mudumaṃsāni bhakkhayitvā tameva āsayaṃ ajjhupeyyan’ti.**Having slain the very best of the deer herd, and eaten the most tender flesh, I could return to my den.”*";
P_HTM[391]="*Atha kho, āvuso, so sīho migarājā aññataraṃ vanasaṇḍaṃ nissāya āsayaṃ kappesi.**And so that’s what he did.*";
P_HTM[392]="*Tatrāsayaṃ kappetvā sāyanhasamayaṃ āsayā nikkhami, āsayā nikkhamitvā vijambhi, vijambhitvā samantā catuddisā anuvilokesi, samantā catuddisā anuviloketvā tikkhattuṃ sīhanādaṃ nadi, tikkhattuṃ sīhanādaṃ naditvā gocarāya pakkāmi.* **";
P_HTM[393]="*So varaṃ varaṃ migasaṅghe vadhitvā mudumaṃsāni mudumaṃsāni bhakkhayitvā tameva āsayaṃ ajjhupesi.* **";
P_HTM[394]="*Tasseva kho, āvuso pāthikaputta, sīhassa migarañño vighāsasaṃvaḍḍho jarasiṅgālo ditto ceva balavā ca.**Now, there was an old jackal who had grown fat on the lion’s leavings, becoming arrogant and strong.*";
P_HTM[395]="*Atha kho, āvuso, tassa jarasiṅgālassa etadahosi:**He thought,*";
P_HTM[396]="*‘ko cāhaṃ, ko sīho migarājā.**“What does the lion, king of beasts, have that I don’t?*";
P_HTM[397]="*Yannūnāhampi aññataraṃ vanasaṇḍaṃ nissāya āsayaṃ kappeyyaṃ.**Why don’t I make my lair near a certain forest?*";
P_HTM[398]="*Tatrāsayaṃ kappetvā sāyanhasamayaṃ āsayā nikkhameyyaṃ, āsayā nikkhamitvā vijambheyyaṃ, vijambhitvā samantā catuddisā anuvilokeyyaṃ, samantā catuddisā anuviloketvā tikkhattuṃ sīhanādaṃ nadeyyaṃ, tikkhattuṃ sīhanādaṃ naditvā gocarāya pakkameyyaṃ.**Towards evening I can emerge from my den, yawn, look all around the four directions, roar my lion’s roar three times, and set out on the hunt.*";
P_HTM[399]="*So varaṃ varaṃ migasaṅghe vadhitvā mudumaṃsāni mudumaṃsāni bhakkhayitvā tameva āsayaṃ ajjhupeyyan’ti.**Having slain the very best of the deer herd, and eaten the most tender flesh, I could return to my den.”*";
P_HTM[400]="*Atha kho so, āvuso, jarasiṅgālo aññataraṃ vanasaṇḍaṃ nissāya āsayaṃ kappesi.**And so that’s what he did.*";
P_HTM[401]="*Tatrāsayaṃ kappetvā sāyanhasamayaṃ āsayā nikkhami, āsayā nikkhamitvā vijambhi, vijambhitvā samantā catuddisā anuvilokesi, samantā catuddisā anuviloketvā tikkhattuṃ sīhanādaṃ nadissāmīti siṅgālakaṃyeva anadi bheraṇḍakaṃyeva anadi, ke ca chave siṅgāle, ke pana sīhanādeti.**But when he tried to roar a lion’s roar, he only managed to squeal and yelp like a jackal. And what is a pathetic jackal’s squeal next to the roar of a lion?*";
P_HTM[402]="*Evameva kho tvaṃ, āvuso pāthikaputta, sugatāpadānesu jīvamāno sugatātirittāni bhuñjamāno tathāgate arahante sammāsambuddhe āsādetabbaṃ maññasi.**In the same way, reverend, while living on the harvest of the Holy One, enjoying the leftovers of the Holy One, you presume to attack the Realized One, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha!*";
P_HTM[403]="*Ke ca chave pāthikaputte, kā ca tathāgatānaṃ arahantānaṃ sammāsambuddhānaṃ āsādanāti.**Who are the pathetic Pāṭikaputtas to attack the Realized Ones, the perfected ones, the fully awakened Buddhas?’*";
P_HTM[404]="*Yato kho, bhaggava, jāliyo dārupattikantevāsī iminā opammena neva asakkhi acelaṃ pāthikaputtaṃ tamhā āsanā cāvetuṃ.**When Jāliya couldn’t get Pāṭikaputta to shift from his seat even with this simile,*";
P_HTM[405]="*Atha naṃ etadavoca:**he said to him:*";
P_HTM[406]="*‘Sīhoti attānaṃ samekkhiyāna,**‘Seeing himself as equal to the lion,*";
P_HTM[407]="*Amaññi kotthu migarājāhamasmi;**the jackal presumed “I’m the king of the beasts!”*";
P_HTM[408]="*Tatheva so siṅgālakaṃ anadi,**But in reality he only managed to yelp,*";
P_HTM[409]="*Ke ca chave siṅgāle ke pana sīhanādeti.**and what’s a sad jackal’s squeal to the roar of a lion?*";
P_HTM[410]="*Evameva kho tvaṃ, āvuso pāthikaputta, sugatāpadānesu jīvamāno sugatātirittāni bhuñjamāno tathāgate arahante sammāsambuddhe āsādetabbaṃ maññasi.**In the same way, reverend, while living on the harvest of the Holy One, you presume to attack him!’*";
P_HTM[411]="*Ke ca chave pāthikaputte, kā ca tathāgatānaṃ arahantānaṃ sammāsambuddhānaṃ āsādanā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[412]="*Yato kho, bhaggava, jāliyo dārupattikantevāsī imināpi opammena neva asakkhi acelaṃ pāthikaputtaṃ tamhā āsanā cāvetuṃ.**When Jāliya couldn’t get Pāṭikaputta to shift from his seat even with this simile,*";
P_HTM[413]="*Atha naṃ etadavoca:**he said to him:*";
P_HTM[414]="*‘Aññaṃ anucaṅkamanaṃ,**‘Following in the steps of another,*";
P_HTM[415]="*Attānaṃ vighāse samekkhiya;**seeing himself grown fat on scraps,*";
P_HTM[416]="*Yāva attānaṃ na passati,**until he doesn’t even see himself,*";
P_HTM[417]="*Kotthu tāva byagghoti maññati.**the jackal presumes he’s a tiger.*";
P_HTM[418]="*Tatheva so siṅgālakaṃ anadi,**But in reality he only managed to yelp,*";
P_HTM[419]="*Ke ca chave siṅgāle ke pana sīhanādeti.**and what’s a sad jackal’s squeal to the roar of a lion?*";
P_HTM[420]="*Evameva kho tvaṃ, āvuso pāthikaputta, sugatāpadānesu jīvamāno sugatātirittāni bhuñjamāno tathāgate arahante sammāsambuddhe āsādetabbaṃ maññasi.**In the same way, reverend, while living on the harvest of the Holy One, you presume to attack him!’*";
P_HTM[421]="*Ke ca chave pāthikaputte, kā ca tathāgatānaṃ arahantānaṃ sammāsambuddhānaṃ āsādanā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[422]="*Yato kho, bhaggava, jāliyo dārupattikantevāsī imināpi opammena neva asakkhi acelaṃ pāthikaputtaṃ tamhā āsanā cāvetuṃ.**When Jāliya couldn’t get Pāṭikaputta to shift from his seat even with this simile,*";
P_HTM[423]="*Atha naṃ etadavoca:**he said to him:*";
P_HTM[424]="*‘Bhutvāna bheke khalamūsikāyo,**‘Gorged on frogs, and mice from the barn,*";
P_HTM[425]="*Kaṭasīsu khittāni ca koṇapāni;**and carcasses tossed in the cemetery,*";
P_HTM[426]="*Mahāvane suññavane vivaḍḍho,**thriving in the great, empty wood,*";
P_HTM[427]="*Amaññi kotthu migarājāhamasmi;**the jackal presumed “I’m the king of the beasts!”*";
P_HTM[428]="*Tatheva so siṅgālakaṃ anadi,**But in reality he only managed to yelp,*";
P_HTM[429]="*Ke ca chave siṅgāle ke pana sīhanādeti.**and what’s a sad jackal’s squeal to the roar of a lion?*";
P_HTM[430]="*Evameva kho tvaṃ, āvuso pāthikaputta, sugatāpadānesu jīvamāno sugatātirittāni bhuñjamāno tathāgate arahante sammāsambuddhe āsādetabbaṃ maññasi.**In the same way, reverend, while living on the harvest of the Holy One, enjoying the leftovers of the Holy One, you presume to attack the Realized One, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha!*";
P_HTM[431]="*Ke ca chave pāthikaputte, kā ca tathāgatānaṃ arahantānaṃ sammāsambuddhānaṃ āsādanā’ti.**Who are the pathetic Pāṭikaputtas to attack the Realized Ones, the perfected ones, the fully awakened Buddhas?’*";
P_HTM[432]="*Yato kho, bhaggava, jāliyo dārupattikantevāsī imināpi opammena neva asakkhi acelaṃ pāthikaputtaṃ tamhā āsanā cāvetuṃ.**When Jāliya couldn’t get Pāṭikaputta to shift from his seat even with this simile,*";
P_HTM[433]="*Atha taṃ parisaṃ āgantvā evamārocesi:**he returned to the assembly and said,*";
P_HTM[434]="*‘parābhūtarūpo, bho, acelo pāthikaputto āyāmi āvuso, āyāmi, āvusoti vatvā tattheva saṃsappati, na sakkoti āsanāpi vuṭṭhātun’ti.**‘Pāṭikaputta has lost, sirs. He says “I’m coming, sir, I’m coming!” But wriggle as he might, he can’t get up from his seat.’*";
P_HTM[435]="*Evaṃ vutte, ahaṃ, bhaggava, taṃ parisaṃ etadavocaṃ:**When he said this, I said to the assembly,*";
P_HTM[436]="*‘abhabbo kho, āvuso, acelo pāthikaputto taṃ vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā mama sammukhībhāvaṃ āgantuṃ.**‘The naked ascetic Pāṭikaputta is not capable of coming into my presence, unless he gives up that statement and that intention, and lets go of that view.*";
P_HTM[437]="*Sacepissa evamassa—**If he thinks he can*";
P_HTM[438]="*ahaṃ taṃ vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā samaṇassa gotamassa sammukhībhāvaṃ gaccheyyanti, muddhāpi tassa vipateyya.**come into my presence without giving up those things, his head may explode.*";
P_HTM[439]="*Sacepāyasmantānaṃ licchavīnaṃ evamassa—**The good Licchavis might even think,*";
P_HTM[440]="*mayaṃ acelaṃ pāthikaputtaṃ varattāhi bandhitvā nāgehi āviñcheyyāmāti. Tā varattā chijjeyyuṃ pāthikaputto vā.**“Let’s bind Pāṭikaputta with straps and drag him with a pair of oxen!” But either the straps will break or Pāṭikaputta will.*";
P_HTM[441]="*Abhabbo pana acelo pāthikaputto taṃ vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā mama sammukhībhāvaṃ āgantuṃ.**Pāṭikaputta is not capable of coming into my presence, otherwise*";
P_HTM[442]="*Sacepissa evamassa—ahaṃ taṃ vācaṃ appahāya taṃ cittaṃ appahāya taṃ diṭṭhiṃ appaṭinissajjitvā samaṇassa gotamassa sammukhībhāvaṃ gaccheyyanti, muddhāpi tassa vipateyyā’ti.**his head may explode.’*";
P_HTM[443]="*Atha khvāhaṃ, bhaggava, taṃ parisaṃ dhammiyā kathāya sandassesiṃ samādapesiṃ samuttejesiṃ sampahaṃsesiṃ, taṃ parisaṃ dhammiyā kathāya sandassetvā samādapetvā samuttejetvā sampahaṃsetvā mahābandhanā mokkhaṃ karitvā caturāsītipāṇasahassāni mahāviduggā uddharitvā tejodhātuṃ samāpajjitvā sattatālaṃ vehāsaṃ abbhuggantvā aññaṃ sattatālampi acciṃ abhinimminitvā pajjalitvā dhūmāyitvā mahāvane kūṭāgārasālāyaṃ paccuṭṭhāsiṃ.**Then, Bhaggava, I educated, encouraged, fired up, and inspired that assembly with a Dhamma talk. I released that assembly from the great bondage, and lifted 84,000 beings from the great swamp. Next I entered upon the fire element, rose into the sky to the height of seven palm trees, and created a flame another seven palm trees high, blazing and smoking. Finally I landed at the Great Wood, in the hall with the peaked roof.*";
P_HTM[444]="*Atha kho, bhaggava, sunakkhatto licchaviputto yenāhaṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā maṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho ahaṃ, bhaggava, sunakkhattaṃ licchaviputtaṃ etadavocaṃ:**Then Sunakkhatta came to me, bowed, and sat down to one side. I said to him,*";
P_HTM[445]="*‘Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, sunakkhatta,**‘What do you think, Sunakkhatta?*";
P_HTM[446]="*yatheva te ahaṃ acelaṃ pāthikaputtaṃ ārabbha byākāsiṃ, tatheva taṃ vipākaṃ aññathā vā’ti?**Did the declaration I made about Pāṭikaputta turn out to be correct, or not?’*";
P_HTM[447]="*‘Yatheva me, bhante, bhagavā acelaṃ pāthikaputtaṃ ārabbha byākāsi, tatheva taṃ vipākaṃ, no aññathā’ti.**‘It turned out to be correct.’*";
P_HTM[448]="*‘Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, sunakkhatta,**‘What do you think, Sunakkhatta?*";
P_HTM[449]="*yadi evaṃ sante kataṃ vā hoti uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ, akataṃ vā’ti?**If that is so, has a superhuman demonstration of psychic power been performed or not?’*";
P_HTM[450]="*‘Addhā kho, bhante, evaṃ sante kataṃ hoti uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ, no akatan’ti.**‘Clearly, sir, a superhuman demonstration of psychic power has been performed.’*";
P_HTM[451]="*‘Evampi kho maṃ tvaṃ, moghapurisa, uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ karontaṃ evaṃ vadesi—**‘Though I perform such a superhuman demonstration of psychic power you say this:*";
P_HTM[452]="*na hi pana me, bhante, bhagavā uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ karotīti.**“But sir, the Buddha never performs any superhuman demonstrations of psychic power for me.”*";
P_HTM[453]="*Passa, moghapurisa, yāvañca te idaṃ aparaddhan’ti.**See how far you have strayed!’*";
P_HTM[454]="*Evampi kho, bhaggava, sunakkhatto licchaviputto mayā vuccamāno apakkameva imasmā dhammavinayā, yathā taṃ āpāyiko nerayiko.**Though I spoke to Sunakkhatta like this, he still left this teaching and training, like someone on the highway to hell.*";
P_HTM[455]="*6. Aggaññapaññattikathā**6. On Describing the Origin of the World*";
P_HTM[456]="*Aggaññañcāhaṃ, bhaggava, pajānāmi.**Bhaggava, I understand the origin of the world.*";
P_HTM[457]="*Tañca pajānāmi, tato ca uttaritaraṃ pajānāmi, tañca pajānaṃ na parāmasāmi, aparāmasato ca me paccattaññeva nibbuti viditā, yadabhijānaṃ tathāgato no anayaṃ āpajjati.**I understand this, and what goes beyond it. Yet since I do not misapprehend that understanding, I have realized extinguishment within myself. Directly knowing this, the Realized One does not come to ruin.*";
P_HTM[458]="*Santi, bhaggava, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā issarakuttaṃ brahmakuttaṃ ācariyakaṃ aggaññaṃ paññapenti.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who describe the origin of the world in their tradition as created by the Lord God, by Brahmā.*";
P_HTM[459]="*Tyāhaṃ upasaṅkamitvā evaṃ vadāmi:**I go up to them and say,*";
P_HTM[460]="*‘saccaṃ kira tumhe āyasmanto issarakuttaṃ brahmakuttaṃ ācariyakaṃ aggaññaṃ paññapethā’ti?**‘Is it really true that this is the venerables’ view?’*";
P_HTM[461]="*Te ca me evaṃ puṭṭhā, ‘āmo’ti paṭijānanti.**And they answer, ‘Yes’.*";
P_HTM[462]="*Tyāhaṃ evaṃ vadāmi:**I say to them,*";
P_HTM[463]="*‘kathaṃvihitakaṃ pana tumhe āyasmanto issarakuttaṃ brahmakuttaṃ ācariyakaṃ aggaññaṃ paññapethā’ti?**‘But how do you describe in your tradition that the origin of the world came about as created by the Lord God, by Brahmā?’*";
P_HTM[464]="*Te mayā puṭṭhā na sampāyanti, asampāyantā mamaññeva paṭipucchanti.**But they cannot answer, and they even question me in return.*";
P_HTM[465]="*Tesāhaṃ puṭṭho byākaromi:**So I answer them,*";
P_HTM[466]="*‘Hoti kho so, āvuso, samayo yaṃ kadāci karahaci dīghassa addhuno accayena ayaṃ loko saṃvaṭṭati.**‘There comes a time when, reverends, after a very long period has passed, this cosmos contracts.*";
P_HTM[467]="*Saṃvaṭṭamāne loke yebhuyyena sattā ābhassarasaṃvattanikā honti.**As the cosmos contracts, sentient beings are mostly headed for the realm of streaming radiance.*";
P_HTM[468]="*Te tattha honti manomayā pītibhakkhā sayaṃpabhā antalikkhacarā subhaṭṭhāyino ciraṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ tiṭṭhanti.**There they are mind-made, feeding on rapture, self-luminous, moving through the sky, steadily glorious, and they remain like that for a very long time.*";
P_HTM[469]="*Hoti kho so, āvuso, samayo yaṃ kadāci karahaci dīghassa addhuno accayena ayaṃ loko vivaṭṭati.**There comes a time when, after a very long period has passed, this cosmos expands.*";
P_HTM[470]="*Vivaṭṭamāne loke suññaṃ brahmavimānaṃ pātubhavati.**As it expands an empty mansion of Brahmā appears.*";
P_HTM[471]="*Atha kho aññataro satto āyukkhayā vā puññakkhayā vā ābhassarakāyā cavitvā suññaṃ brahmavimānaṃ upapajjati.**Then a certain sentient being—due to the running out of their life-span or merit—passes away from that host of radiant deities and is reborn in that empty mansion of Brahmā.*";
P_HTM[472]="*So tattha hoti manomayo pītibhakkho sayampabho antalikkhacaro subhaṭṭhāyī, ciraṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ tiṭṭhati.**There they are mind-made, feeding on rapture, self-luminous, moving through the sky, steadily glorious, and they remain like that for a very long time.*";
P_HTM[473]="*Tassa tattha ekakassa dīgharattaṃ nivusitattā anabhirati paritassanā uppajjati—**But after staying there all alone for a long time, they become dissatisfied and anxious,*";
P_HTM[474]="*aho vata aññepi sattā itthattaṃ āgaccheyyunti.**“Oh, if only another being would come to this state of existence.”*";
P_HTM[475]="*Atha aññepi sattā āyukkhayā vā puññakkhayā vā ābhassarakāyā cavitvā suññaṃ brahmavimānaṃ upapajjanti tassa sattassa sahabyataṃ.**Then other sentient beings—due to the running out of their life-span or merit—pass away from that host of radiant deities and are reborn in that empty mansion of Brahmā in company with that being.*";
P_HTM[476]="*Tepi tattha honti manomayā pītibhakkhā sayaṃpabhā antalikkhacarā subhaṭṭhāyino, ciraṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ tiṭṭhanti.**There they too are mind-made, feeding on rapture, self-luminous, moving through the sky, steadily glorious, and they remain like that for a very long time.*";
P_HTM[477]="*Tatrāvuso, yo so satto paṭhamaṃ upapanno, tassa evaṃ hoti—**Now, the being who was reborn there first thinks,*";
P_HTM[478]="*ahamasmi brahmā mahābrahmā abhibhū anabhibhūto aññadatthudaso vasavattī issaro kattā nimmātā seṭṭho sajitā vasī pitā bhūtabhabyānaṃ, mayā ime sattā nimmitā.**“I am Brahmā, the Great Brahmā, the Undefeated, the Champion, the Universal Seer, the Wielder of Power, the Lord God, the Maker, the Author, the Best, the Begetter, the Controller, the Father of those who have been born and those yet to be born.*";
P_HTM[479]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[480]="*Mamañhi pubbe etadahosi—**Because first I thought,*";
P_HTM[481]="*aho vata aññepi sattā itthattaṃ āgaccheyyunti;**‘Oh, if only another being would come to this state of existence.’*";
P_HTM[482]="*iti mama ca manopaṇidhi. Ime ca sattā itthattaṃ āgatāti.**Such was my heart’s wish, and then these creatures came to this state of existence.”*";
P_HTM[483]="*Yepi te sattā pacchā upapannā, tesampi evaṃ hoti—**And the beings who were reborn there later also think,*";
P_HTM[484]="*ayaṃ kho bhavaṃ brahmā mahābrahmā abhibhū anabhibhūto aññadatthudaso vasavattī issaro kattā nimmātā seṭṭho sajitā vasī pitā bhūtabhabyānaṃ;**“This must be Brahmā, the Great Brahmā, the Undefeated, the Champion, the Universal Seer, the Wielder of Power, the Lord God, the Maker, the Author, the Best, the Begetter, the Controller, the Father of those who have been born and those yet to be born.*";
P_HTM[485]="*iminā mayaṃ bhotā brahmunā nimmitā.**And we have been created by him.*";
P_HTM[486]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[487]="*Imañhi mayaṃ addasāma idha paṭhamaṃ upapannaṃ; mayaṃ panāmha pacchā upapannāti.**Because we see that he was reborn here first, and we arrived later.”*";
P_HTM[488]="*Tatrāvuso, yo so satto paṭhamaṃ upapanno, so dīghāyukataro ca hoti vaṇṇavantataro ca mahesakkhataro ca.**And the being who was reborn first is more long-lived, beautiful, and illustrious than those who arrived later.*";
P_HTM[489]="*Ye pana te sattā pacchā upapannā, te appāyukatarā ca honti dubbaṇṇatarā ca appesakkhatarā ca.* **";
P_HTM[490]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, āvuso, vijjati, yaṃ aññataro satto tamhā kāyā cavitvā itthattaṃ āgacchati.**It’s possible that one of those beings passes away from that host and is reborn in this state of existence.*";
P_HTM[491]="*Itthattaṃ āgato samāno agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajati.**Having done so, they go forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[492]="*Agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajito samāno ātappamanvāya padhānamanvāya anuyogamanvāya appamādamanvāya sammāmanasikāramanvāya tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusati, yathāsamāhite citte taṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati; tato paraṃ nānussarati.**By dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus, they experience an immersion of the heart of such a kind that they recollect that past life, but no further.*";
P_HTM[493]="*So evamāha:**They say:*";
P_HTM[494]="*“yo kho so bhavaṃ brahmā mahābrahmā abhibhū anabhibhūto aññadatthudaso vasavattī issaro kattā nimmātā seṭṭho sajitā vasī pitā bhūtabhabyānaṃ, yena mayaṃ bhotā brahmunā nimmitā. So nicco dhuvo sassato avipariṇāmadhammo sassatisamaṃ tatheva ṭhassati.**“He who is Brahmā—the Great Brahmā, the Undefeated, the Champion, the Universal Seer, the Wielder of Power, the Lord God, the Maker, the Author, the Best, the Begetter, the Controller, the Father of those who have been born and those yet to be born—is permanent, everlasting, eternal, imperishable, remaining the same for all eternity.*";
P_HTM[495]="*Ye pana mayaṃ ahumhā tena bhotā brahmunā nimmitā, te mayaṃ aniccā addhuvā appāyukā cavanadhammā itthattaṃ āgatā”ti.**We who were created by that Brahmā are impermanent, not lasting, short-lived, perishable, and have come to this state of existence.”*";
P_HTM[496]="*Evaṃvihitakaṃ no tumhe āyasmanto issarakuttaṃ brahmakuttaṃ ācariyakaṃ aggaññaṃ paññapethā’ti.**This is how you describe in your tradition that the origin of the world came about as created by the Lord God, by Brahmā.’*";
P_HTM[497]="*Te evamāhaṃsu:**They say,*";
P_HTM[498]="*‘evaṃ kho no, āvuso gotama, sutaṃ, yathevāyasmā gotamo āhā’ti.**‘That is what we have heard, Reverend Gotama, just as you say.’*";
P_HTM[499]="*Aggaññañcāhaṃ, bhaggava, pajānāmi.**Bhaggava, I understand the origin of the world.*";
P_HTM[500]="*Tañca pajānāmi, tato ca uttaritaraṃ pajānāmi, tañca pajānaṃ na parāmasāmi, aparāmasato ca me paccattaññeva nibbuti viditā. Yadabhijānaṃ tathāgato no anayaṃ āpajjati.**I understand this, and what goes beyond it. Yet since I do not misapprehend that understanding, I have realized extinguishment within myself. Directly knowing this, the Realized One does not come to ruin.*";
P_HTM[501]="*Santi, bhaggava, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā khiḍḍāpadosikaṃ ācariyakaṃ aggaññaṃ paññapenti.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who describe the origin of the world in their tradition as due to those depraved by play.*";
P_HTM[502]="*Tyāhaṃ upasaṅkamitvā evaṃ vadāmi:**I go up to them and say,*";
P_HTM[503]="*‘saccaṃ kira tumhe āyasmanto khiḍḍāpadosikaṃ ācariyakaṃ aggaññaṃ paññapethā’ti?**‘Is it really true that this is the venerables’ view?’*";
P_HTM[504]="*Te ca me evaṃ puṭṭhā ‘āmo’ti paṭijānanti.**And they answer, ‘Yes’.*";
P_HTM[505]="*Tyāhaṃ evaṃ vadāmi:**I say to them,*";
P_HTM[506]="*‘kathaṃvihitakaṃ pana tumhe āyasmanto khiḍḍāpadosikaṃ ācariyakaṃ aggaññaṃ paññapethā’ti?**‘But how do you describe in your tradition that the origin of the world came about due to those depraved by play?’*";
P_HTM[507]="*Te mayā puṭṭhā na sampāyanti, asampāyantā mamaññeva paṭipucchanti,**But they cannot answer, and they even question me in return.*";
P_HTM[508]="*tesāhaṃ puṭṭho byākaromi:**So I answer them,*";
P_HTM[509]="*‘Santāvuso, khiḍḍāpadosikā nāma devā. Te ativelaṃ hassakhiḍḍāratidhammasamāpannā viharanti. Tesaṃ ativelaṃ hassakhiḍḍāratidhammasamāpannānaṃ viharataṃ sati sammussati, satiyā sammosā te devā tamhā kāyā cavanti.**‘Reverends, there are gods named “depraved by play”. They spend too much time laughing, playing, and making merry. And in doing so, they lose their mindfulness, and they pass away from that host of gods.*";
P_HTM[510]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, āvuso, vijjati, yaṃ aññataro satto tamhā kāyā cavitvā itthattaṃ āgacchati,**It’s possible that one of those beings passes away from that host and is reborn in this state of existence.*";
P_HTM[511]="*itthattaṃ āgato samāno agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajati,**Having done so, they go forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[512]="*agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajito samāno ātappamanvāya padhānamanvāya anuyogamanvāya appamādamanvāya sammāmanasikāramanvāya tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusati, yathāsamāhite citte taṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati; tato paraṃ nānussarati.**By dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus, they experience an immersion of the heart of such a kind that they recollect that past life, but no further.*";
P_HTM[513]="*So evamāha:**They say,*";
P_HTM[514]="*“ye kho te bhonto devā na khiḍḍāpadosikā te na ativelaṃ hassakhiḍḍāratidhammasamāpannā viharanti. Tesaṃ nātivelaṃ hassakhiḍḍāratidhammasamāpannānaṃ viharataṃ sati na sammussati, satiyā asammosā te devā tamhā kāyā na cavanti,**“The gods not depraved by play don’t spend too much time laughing, playing, and making merry. So they don’t lose their mindfulness, and don’t pass away from that host of gods.*";
P_HTM[515]="*niccā dhuvā sassatā avipariṇāmadhammā sassatisamaṃ tatheva ṭhassanti.**They are permanent, everlasting, eternal, imperishable, remaining the same for all eternity.*";
P_HTM[516]="*Ye pana mayaṃ ahumhā khiḍḍāpadosikā te mayaṃ ativelaṃ hassakhiḍḍāratidhammasamāpannā viharimhā, tesaṃ no ativelaṃ hassakhiḍḍāratidhammasamāpannānaṃ viharataṃ sati sammussati, satiyā sammosā evaṃ mayaṃ tamhā kāyā cutā,**But we who were depraved by play spent too much time laughing, playing, and making merry. In doing so, we lost our mindfulness, and passed away from that host of gods.*";
P_HTM[517]="*aniccā addhuvā appāyukā cavanadhammā itthattaṃ āgatā”ti.**We are impermanent, not lasting, short-lived, perishable, and have come to this state of existence.”*";
P_HTM[518]="*Evaṃvihitakaṃ no tumhe āyasmanto khiḍḍāpadosikaṃ ācariyakaṃ aggaññaṃ paññapethā’ti.**This is how you describe in your tradition that the origin of the world came about due to those depraved by play.’*";
P_HTM[519]="*Te evamāhaṃsu:**They say,*";
P_HTM[520]="*‘evaṃ kho no, āvuso gotama, sutaṃ, yathevāyasmā gotamo āhā’ti.**‘That is what we have heard, Reverend Gotama, just as you say.’*";
P_HTM[521]="*Aggaññañcāhaṃ, bhaggava, pajānāmi … pe …**Bhaggava, I understand the origin of the world.*";
P_HTM[522]="*yadabhijānaṃ tathāgato no anayaṃ āpajjati.**Directly knowing this, the Realized One does not come to ruin.*";
P_HTM[523]="*Santi, bhaggava, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā manopadosikaṃ ācariyakaṃ aggaññaṃ paññapenti.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who describe the origin of the world in their tradition as due to those who are malevolent.*";
P_HTM[524]="*Tyāhaṃ upasaṅkamitvā evaṃ vadāmi:**I go up to them and say,*";
P_HTM[525]="*‘saccaṃ kira tumhe āyasmanto manopadosikaṃ ācariyakaṃ aggaññaṃ paññapethā’ti?**‘Is it really true that this is the venerables’ view?’*";
P_HTM[526]="*Te ca me evaṃ puṭṭhā ‘āmo’ti paṭijānanti.**And they answer, ‘Yes’.*";
P_HTM[527]="*Tyāhaṃ evaṃ vadāmi:**I say to them,*";
P_HTM[528]="*‘kathaṃvihitakaṃ pana tumhe āyasmanto manopadosikaṃ ācariyakaṃ aggaññaṃ paññapethā’ti?**‘But how do you describe in your tradition that the origin of the world came about due to those who are malevolent?’*";
P_HTM[529]="*Te mayā puṭṭhā na sampāyanti, asampāyantā mamaññeva paṭipucchanti.**But they cannot answer, and they even question me in return.*";
P_HTM[530]="*Tesāhaṃ puṭṭho byākaromi:**So I answer them,*";
P_HTM[531]="*‘Santāvuso, manopadosikā nāma devā. Te ativelaṃ aññamaññaṃ upanijjhāyanti. Te ativelaṃ aññamaññaṃ upanijjhāyantā aññamaññamhi cittāni padūsenti. Te aññamaññaṃ paduṭṭhacittā kilantakāyā kilantacittā. Te devā tamhā kāyā cavanti.**‘Reverends, there are gods named “malevolent”. They spend too much time gazing at each other, so they grow angry with each other, and their bodies and minds get tired. They pass away from that host of gods.*";
P_HTM[532]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, āvuso, vijjati, yaṃ aññataro satto tamhā kāyā cavitvā itthattaṃ āgacchati.**It’s possible that one of those beings passes away from that host and is reborn in this state of existence.*";
P_HTM[533]="*Itthattaṃ āgato samāno agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajati.**Having done so, they go forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[534]="*Agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajito samāno ātappamanvāya padhānamanvāya anuyogamanvāya appamādamanvāya sammāmanasikāramanvāya tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusati, yathāsamāhite citte taṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati, tato paraṃ nānussarati.**By dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus, they experience an immersion of the heart of such a kind that they recollect that past life, but no further.*";
P_HTM[535]="*So evamāha:**They say,*";
P_HTM[536]="*“ye kho te bhonto devā na manopadosikā te nātivelaṃ aññamaññaṃ upanijjhāyanti. Te nātivelaṃ aññamaññaṃ upanijjhāyantā aññamaññamhi cittāni nappadūsenti. Te aññamaññaṃ appaduṭṭhacittā akilantakāyā akilantacittā. Te devā tamhā kāyā na cavanti,**“The gods who are not malevolent don’t spend too much time gazing at each other, so they don’t grow angry with each other, their bodies and minds don’t get tired, and they don’t pass away from that host of gods.*";
P_HTM[537]="*niccā dhuvā sassatā avipariṇāmadhammā sassatisamaṃ tatheva ṭhassanti.**They are permanent, everlasting, eternal, imperishable, remaining the same for all eternity.*";
P_HTM[538]="*Ye pana mayaṃ ahumhā manopadosikā, te mayaṃ ativelaṃ aññamaññaṃ upanijjhāyimhā. Te mayaṃ ativelaṃ aññamaññaṃ upanijjhāyantā aññamaññamhi cittāni padūsimhā. Te mayaṃ aññamaññaṃ paduṭṭhacittā kilantakāyā kilantacittā. Evaṃ mayaṃ tamhā kāyā cutā,**But we who were malevolent spent too much time gazing at each other, so our minds grew angry with each other, our bodies and minds got tired, and we passed away from that host of gods.*";
P_HTM[539]="*aniccā addhuvā appāyukā cavanadhammā itthattaṃ āgatā”ti.**We are impermanent, not lasting, short-lived, perishable, and have come to this state of existence.”*";
P_HTM[540]="*Evaṃvihitakaṃ no tumhe āyasmanto manopadosikaṃ ācariyakaṃ aggaññaṃ paññapethā’ti.**This is how you describe in your tradition that the origin of the world came about due to those who are malevolent.’*";
P_HTM[541]="*Te evamāhaṃsu:**They say,*";
P_HTM[542]="*‘evaṃ kho no, āvuso gotama, sutaṃ, yathevāyasmā gotamo āhā’ti.**‘That is what we have heard, Reverend Gotama, just as you say.’*";
P_HTM[543]="*Aggaññañcāhaṃ, bhaggava, pajānāmi … pe …**Bhaggava, I understand the origin of the world.*";
P_HTM[544]="*yadabhijānaṃ tathāgato no anayaṃ āpajjati.**Directly knowing this, the Realized One does not come to ruin.*";
P_HTM[545]="*Santi, bhaggava, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā adhiccasamuppannaṃ ācariyakaṃ aggaññaṃ paññapenti.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who describe the origin of the world in their tradition as having arisen by chance.*";
P_HTM[546]="*Tyāhaṃ upasaṅkamitvā evaṃ vadāmi:**I go up to them and say,*";
P_HTM[547]="*‘saccaṃ kira tumhe āyasmanto adhiccasamuppannaṃ ācariyakaṃ aggaññaṃ paññapethā’ti?**‘Is it really true that this is the venerables’ view?’*";
P_HTM[548]="*Te ca me evaṃ puṭṭhā ‘āmo’ti paṭijānanti.**And they answer, ‘Yes’.*";
P_HTM[549]="*Tyāhaṃ evaṃ vadāmi:**I say to them,*";
P_HTM[550]="*‘kathaṃvihitakaṃ pana tumhe āyasmanto adhiccasamuppannaṃ ācariyakaṃ aggaññaṃ paññapethā’ti?**‘But how do you describe in your tradition that the origin of the world came about by chance?’*";
P_HTM[551]="*Te mayā puṭṭhā na sampāyanti, asampāyantā mamaññeva paṭipucchanti.**But they cannot answer, and they even question me in return.*";
P_HTM[552]="*Tesāhaṃ puṭṭho byākaromi:**So I answer them,*";
P_HTM[553]="*‘Santāvuso, asaññasattā nāma devā.**‘Reverends, there are gods named “non-percipient beings”.*";
P_HTM[554]="*Saññuppādā ca pana te devā tamhā kāyā cavanti.**When perception arises they pass away from that host of gods.*";
P_HTM[555]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, āvuso, vijjati yaṃ aññataro satto tamhā kāyā cavitvā itthattaṃ āgacchati.**It’s possible that one of those beings passes away from that host and is reborn in this state of existence.*";
P_HTM[556]="*Itthattaṃ āgato samāno agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajati.**Having done so, they go forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[557]="*Agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajito samāno ātappamanvāya padhānamanvāya anuyogamanvāya appamādamanvāya sammāmanasikāramanvāya tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusati, yathāsamāhite citte taṃ saññuppādaṃ anussarati, tato paraṃ nānussarati’.**By dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus, they experience an immersion of the heart of such a kind that they recollect the arising of perception, but no further.*";
P_HTM[558]="*So evamāha:**They say,*";
P_HTM[559]="*‘adhiccasamuppanno attā ca loko ca.**“The self and the cosmos arose by chance.*";
P_HTM[560]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[561]="*Ahañhi pubbe nāhosiṃ, somhi etarahi ahutvā santatāya pariṇato’ti.**Because formerly I didn’t exist. Now from not being I’ve changed into being.”*";
P_HTM[562]="*‘Evaṃvihitakaṃ no tumhe āyasmanto adhiccasamuppannaṃ ācariyakaṃ aggaññaṃ paññapethā’ti?**This is how you describe in your tradition that the origin of the world came about by chance.’*";
P_HTM[563]="*Te evamāhaṃsu:**They say,*";
P_HTM[564]="*‘evaṃ kho no, āvuso gotama, sutaṃ yathevāyasmā gotamo āhā’ti.**‘That is what we have heard, Reverend Gotama, just as you say.’*";
P_HTM[565]="*Aggaññañcāhaṃ, bhaggava, pajānāmi tañca pajānāmi, tato ca uttaritaraṃ pajānāmi, tañca pajānaṃ na parāmasāmi, aparāmasato ca me paccattaññeva nibbuti viditā.**I understand this, and what goes beyond it. Yet since I do not misapprehend that understanding, I have realized extinguishment within myself. Directly knowing this, the Realized One does not come to ruin.*";
P_HTM[566]="*Yadabhijānaṃ tathāgato no anayaṃ āpajjati.* **";
P_HTM[567]="*Evaṃvādiṃ kho maṃ, bhaggava, evamakkhāyiṃ eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā asatā tucchā musā abhūtena abbhācikkhanti:**Though I speak and explain like this, certain ascetics and brahmins misrepresent me with the false, hollow, lying, untruthful claim:*";
P_HTM[568]="*‘viparīto samaṇo gotamo bhikkhavo ca.**‘The ascetic Gotama has a distorted perspective, and so have his monks.*";
P_HTM[569]="*Samaṇo gotamo evamāha—**He says,*";
P_HTM[570]="*yasmiṃ samaye subhaṃ vimokkhaṃ upasampajja viharati, sabbaṃ tasmiṃ samaye asubhantveva pajānātī’ti.**“When one enters and remains in the liberation of the beautiful, at that time one only perceives what is ugly.”*";
P_HTM[571]="*Na kho panāhaṃ, bhaggava, evaṃ vadāmi:**But I don’t say that.*";
P_HTM[572]="*‘yasmiṃ samaye subhaṃ vimokkhaṃ upasampajja viharati, sabbaṃ tasmiṃ samaye asubhantveva pajānātī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[573]="*Evañca khvāhaṃ, bhaggava, vadāmi:**I say this:*";
P_HTM[574]="*‘yasmiṃ samaye subhaṃ vimokkhaṃ upasampajja viharati, subhantveva tasmiṃ samaye pajānātī’”ti.**“When one enters and remains in the liberation of the beautiful, at that time one only perceives what is beautiful.”’”*";
P_HTM[575]="*“Te ca, bhante, viparītā, ye bhagavantaṃ viparītato dahanti bhikkhavo ca.**“They are the ones with a distorted perspective, sir, who regard the Buddha and the mendicants in this way.*";
P_HTM[576]="*Evaṃpasanno ahaṃ, bhante, bhagavati. Pahoti me bhagavā tathā dhammaṃ desetuṃ, yathā ahaṃ subhaṃ vimokkhaṃ upasampajja vihareyyan”ti.**Sir, I am quite confident that the Buddha is capable of teaching me so that I can enter and remain in the liberation on the beautiful.”*";
P_HTM[577]="*“Dukkaraṃ kho etaṃ, bhaggava, tayā aññadiṭṭhikena aññakhantikena aññarucikena aññatrāyogena aññatrācariyakena subhaṃ vimokkhaṃ upasampajja viharituṃ.**“It’s hard for you to enter and remain in the liberation on the beautiful, since you have a different view, creed, preference, practice, and tradition.*";
P_HTM[578]="*Iṅgha tvaṃ, bhaggava, yo ca te ayaṃ mayi pasādo, tameva tvaṃ sādhukamanurakkhā”ti.**Come now, Bhaggava, carefully preserve the confidence that you have in me.”*";
P_HTM[579]="*“Sace taṃ, bhante, mayā dukkaraṃ aññadiṭṭhikena aññakhantikena aññarucikena aññatrāyogena aññatrācariyakena subhaṃ vimokkhaṃ upasampajja viharituṃ.**“If it’s hard for me to enter and remain in the liberation on the beautiful, since I have a different view, creed, preference, practice, and tradition,*";
P_HTM[580]="*Yo ca me ayaṃ, bhante, bhagavati pasādo, tamevāhaṃ sādhukamanurakkhissāmī”ti.**I shall carefully preserve the confidence that I have in the Buddha.”*";
P_HTM[581]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[582]="*Attamano bhaggavagotto paribbājako bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandīti.**Satisfied, the wanderer Bhaggavagotta was happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[583]="*Pāthikasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[584]="*25. Udumbarikasutta  - The Lion’s Roar at Udumbarikā’s Monastery * **";
P_HTM[585]="*1. Nigrodhaparibbājakavatthu**1. On the Wanderer Nigrodha*";
P_HTM[586]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[587]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā rājagahe viharati gijjhakūṭe pabbate.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Rājagaha, on the Vulture’s Peak Mountain.*";
P_HTM[588]="*Tena kho pana samayena nigrodho paribbājako udumbarikāya paribbājakārāme paṭivasati mahatiyā paribbājakaparisāya saddhiṃ tiṃsamattehi paribbājakasatehi.**Now at that time the wanderer Nigrodha was residing in the lady Udumbarikā’s monastery for wanderers, together with a large assembly of three thousand wanderers.*";
P_HTM[589]="*Atha kho sandhāno gahapati divā divassa rājagahā nikkhami bhagavantaṃ dassanāya.**Then the householder Sandhana left Rājagaha in the middle of the day to see the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[590]="*Atha kho sandhānassa gahapatissa etadahosi:**Then it occurred to him,*";
P_HTM[591]="*“akālo kho bhagavantaṃ dassanāya.**“It’s the wrong time to see the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[592]="*Paṭisallīno bhagavā.**as he’s in retreat.*";
P_HTM[593]="*Manobhāvanīyānampi bhikkhūnaṃ asamayo dassanāya.**And it’s the wrong time to see the esteemed mendicants,*";
P_HTM[594]="*Paṭisallīnā manobhāvanīyā bhikkhū.**as they’re in retreat.*";
P_HTM[595]="*Yannūnāhaṃ yena udumbarikāya paribbājakārāmo, yena nigrodho paribbājako tenupasaṅkameyyan”ti.**Why don’t I visit the wanderer Nigrodha at the lady Udumbarikā’s monastery for wanderers?”*";
P_HTM[596]="*Atha kho sandhāno gahapati yena udumbarikāya paribbājakārāmo, tenupasaṅkami.**So he went to the monastery of the wanderers.*";
P_HTM[597]="*Tena kho pana samayena nigrodho paribbājako mahatiyā paribbājakaparisāya saddhiṃ nisinno hoti unnādiniyā uccāsaddamahāsaddāya anekavihitaṃ tiracchānakathaṃ kathentiyā.**Now at that time, Nigrodha was sitting together with a large assembly of wanderers making an uproar, a dreadful racket. They engaged in all kinds of unworthy talk, such as*";
P_HTM[598]="*Seyyathidaṃ—rājakathaṃ corakathaṃ mahāmattakathaṃ senākathaṃ bhayakathaṃ yuddhakathaṃ annakathaṃ pānakathaṃ vatthakathaṃ sayanakathaṃ mālākathaṃ gandhakathaṃ ñātikathaṃ yānakathaṃ gāmakathaṃ nigamakathaṃ nagarakathaṃ janapadakathaṃ itthikathaṃ sūrakathaṃ visikhākathaṃ kumbhaṭṭhānakathaṃ pubbapetakathaṃ nānattakathaṃ lokakkhāyikaṃ samuddakkhāyikaṃ itibhavābhavakathaṃ iti vā.**talk about kings, bandits, and ministers; talk about armies, threats, and wars; talk about food, drink, clothes, and beds; talk about garlands and fragrances; talk about family, vehicles, villages, towns, cities, and countries; talk about women and heroes; street talk and well talk; talk about the departed; motley talk; tales of land and sea; and talk about being reborn in this or that state of existence.*";
P_HTM[599]="*Addasā kho nigrodho paribbājako sandhānaṃ gahapatiṃ dūratova āgacchantaṃ.**Nigrodha saw Sandhāna coming off in the distance,*";
P_HTM[600]="*Disvā sakaṃ parisaṃ saṇṭhāpesi:**and hushed his own assembly:*";
P_HTM[601]="*“appasaddā bhonto hontu, mā bhonto saddamakattha.**“Be quiet, good sirs, don’t make a sound.*";
P_HTM[602]="*Ayaṃ samaṇassa gotamassa sāvako āgacchati sandhāno gahapati.**The householder Sandhāna, a disciple of the ascetic Gotama, is coming.*";
P_HTM[603]="*Yāvatā kho pana samaṇassa gotamassa sāvakā gihī odātavasanā rājagahe paṭivasanti, ayaṃ tesaṃ aññataro sandhāno gahapati.**He is included among the white-clothed lay disciples of the ascetic Gotama, who is residing near Rājagaha.*";
P_HTM[604]="*Appasaddakāmā kho panete āyasmanto appasaddavinītā, appasaddassa vaṇṇavādino.**Such venerables like the quiet, are educated to be quiet, and praise the quiet.*";
P_HTM[605]="*Appeva nāma appasaddaṃ parisaṃ viditvā upasaṅkamitabbaṃ maññeyyā”ti.**Hopefully if he sees that our assembly is quiet he’ll see fit to approach.”*";
P_HTM[606]="*Evaṃ vutte, te paribbājakā tuṇhī ahesuṃ.**Then those wanderers fell silent.*";
P_HTM[607]="*Atha kho sandhāno gahapati yena nigrodho paribbājako tenupasaṅkami, upasaṅkamitvā nigrodhena paribbājakena saddhiṃ sammodi.**Then Sandhāna went up to the wanderer Nigrodha, and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[608]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho sandhāno gahapati nigrodhaṃ paribbājakaṃ etadavoca:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, he sat down to one side and said to Nigrodha,*";
P_HTM[609]="*“aññathā kho ime bhonto aññatitthiyā paribbājakā saṅgamma samāgamma unnādino uccāsaddamahāsaddā anekavihitaṃ tiracchānakathaṃ anuyuttā viharanti.**“The way the wanderers make an uproar as they sit together and talk about all kinds of unworthy topics is one thing.*";
P_HTM[610]="*Seyyathidaṃ—rājakathaṃ … pe … itibhavābhavakathaṃ iti vā.* **";
P_HTM[611]="*Aññathā kho pana so bhagavā araññavanapatthāni pantāni senāsanāni paṭisevati appasaddāni appanigghosāni vijanavātāni manussarāhasseyyakāni paṭisallānasāruppānī”ti.**It’s quite different to the way the Buddha frequents remote lodgings in the wilderness and the forest that are quiet and still, far from the madding crowd, remote from human settlements, and fit for retreat.”*";
P_HTM[612]="*Evaṃ vutte, nigrodho paribbājako sandhānaṃ gahapatiṃ etadavoca:**When Sandhāna said this, Nigrodha said to him,*";
P_HTM[613]="*“yagghe, gahapati, jāneyyāsi, kena samaṇo gotamo saddhiṃ sallapati, kena sākacchaṃ samāpajjati, kena paññāveyyattiyaṃ samāpajjati?**“Surely, householder, you should know better! With whom does the ascetic Gotama converse? With whom does he engage in discussion? With whom does he achieve lucidity of wisdom?*";
P_HTM[614]="*Suññāgārahatā samaṇassa gotamassa paññā aparisāvacaro samaṇo gotamo nālaṃ sallāpāya.**Staying in empty huts has destroyed the ascetic Gotama’s wisdom. Not frequenting assemblies, he is unable to hold a discussion.*";
P_HTM[615]="*So antamantāneva sevati.**He just lurks on the periphery.*";
P_HTM[616]="*Seyyathāpi nāma gokāṇā pariyantacārinī antamantāneva sevati.**He’s just like the nilgai antelope, circling around and lurking on the periphery.*";
P_HTM[617]="*Evameva suññāgārahatā samaṇassa gotamassa paññā;* **";
P_HTM[618]="*aparisāvacaro samaṇo gotamo;* **";
P_HTM[619]="*nālaṃ sallāpāya.* **";
P_HTM[620]="*So antamantāneva sevati.* **";
P_HTM[621]="*Iṅgha, gahapati, samaṇo gotamo imaṃ parisaṃ āgaccheyya, ekapañheneva naṃ saṃsādeyyāma, tucchakumbhīva naṃ maññe orodheyyāmā”ti.**Please, householder, let the ascetic Gotama come to this assembly. I’ll sink him with just one question! I’ll roll him over and wrap him up like a hollow pot!”*";
P_HTM[622]="*Assosi kho bhagavā dibbāya sotadhātuyā visuddhāya atikkantamānusikāya sandhānassa gahapatissa nigrodhena paribbājakena saddhiṃ imaṃ kathāsallāpaṃ.**With clairaudience that is purified and superhuman, the Buddha heard this discussion between the householder Sandhāna and the wanderer Nigrodha.*";
P_HTM[623]="*Atha kho bhagavā gijjhakūṭā pabbatā orohitvā yena sumāgadhāya tīre moranivāpo tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā sumāgadhāya tīre moranivāpe abbhokāse caṅkami.**Then the Buddha descended Vulture’s Peak Mountain and went to the peacocks’ feeding ground on the bank of the Sumāgadhā, where he practiced walking meditation in the open air.*";
P_HTM[624]="*Addasā kho nigrodho paribbājako bhagavantaṃ sumāgadhāya tīre moranivāpe abbhokāse caṅkamantaṃ.**Nigrodha saw him,*";
P_HTM[625]="*Disvāna sakaṃ parisaṃ saṇṭhāpesi:**and hushed his own assembly:*";
P_HTM[626]="*“appasaddā bhonto hontu, mā bhonto saddamakattha, ayaṃ samaṇo gotamo sumāgadhāya tīre moranivāpe abbhokāse caṅkamati.**“Be quiet, good sirs, don’t make a sound. The ascetic Gotama is walking meditation on the bank of the Sumāgadhā.*";
P_HTM[627]="*Appasaddakāmo kho pana so āyasmā, appasaddassa vaṇṇavādī.**The venerable likes quiet and praises quiet.*";
P_HTM[628]="*Appeva nāma appasaddaṃ parisaṃ viditvā upasaṅkamitabbaṃ maññeyya.**Hopefully if he sees that our assembly is quiet he’ll see fit to approach.*";
P_HTM[629]="*Sace samaṇo gotamo imaṃ parisaṃ āgaccheyya, imaṃ taṃ pañhaṃ puccheyyāma:**If he comes, I’ll ask him this question:*";
P_HTM[630]="*‘ko nāma so, bhante, bhagavato dhammo, yena bhagavā sāvake vineti, yena bhagavatā sāvakā vinītā assāsappattā paṭijānanti ajjhāsayaṃ ādibrahmacariyan’”ti?**‘Sir, what teaching do you use to guide your disciples, through which they claim solace in the fundamental purpose of the spiritual life?’”*";
P_HTM[631]="*Evaṃ vutte, te paribbājakā tuṇhī ahesuṃ.**Then those wanderers fell silent.*";
P_HTM[632]="*2. Tapojigucchāvāda**2. Mortification in Disgust of Sin*";
P_HTM[633]="*Atha kho bhagavā yena nigrodho paribbājako tenupasaṅkami.**Then the Buddha went up to the wanderer Nigrodha,*";
P_HTM[634]="*Atha kho nigrodho paribbājako bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**who said to him,*";
P_HTM[635]="*“etu kho, bhante, bhagavā, svāgataṃ, bhante, bhagavato.**“Come, Blessed One! Welcome, Blessed One!*";
P_HTM[636]="*Cirassaṃ kho, bhante, bhagavā imaṃ pariyāyamakāsi yadidaṃ idhāgamanāya.**It’s been a long time since you took the opportunity to come here.*";
P_HTM[637]="*Nisīdatu, bhante, bhagavā, idamāsanaṃ paññattan”ti.**Please, sir, sit down, this seat is ready.”*";
P_HTM[638]="*Nisīdi bhagavā paññatte āsane.**The Buddha sat on the seat spread out,*";
P_HTM[639]="*Nigrodhopi kho paribbājako aññataraṃ nīcāsanaṃ gahetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi.**while Nigrodha took a low seat and sat to one side.*";
P_HTM[640]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho nigrodhaṃ paribbājakaṃ bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said to him,*";
P_HTM[641]="*“kāya nuttha, nigrodha, etarahi kathāya sannisinnā, kā ca pana vo antarākathā vippakatā”ti?**“Nigrodha, what were you sitting talking about just now? What conversation was unfinished?”*";
P_HTM[642]="*Evaṃ vutte, nigrodho paribbājako bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Nigrodha said,*";
P_HTM[643]="*“idha mayaṃ, bhante, addasāma bhagavantaṃ sumāgadhāya tīre moranivāpe abbhokāse caṅkamantaṃ, disvāna evaṃ avocumhā:**“Well, sir, I saw you walking meditation and said:*";
P_HTM[644]="*‘sace samaṇo gotamo imaṃ parisaṃ āgaccheyya, imaṃ taṃ pañhaṃ puccheyyāma:**‘If the ascetic Gotama comes, I’ll ask him this question:*";
P_HTM[645]="*“ko nāma so, bhante, bhagavato dhammo, yena bhagavā sāvake vineti, yena bhagavatā sāvakā vinītā assāsappattā paṭijānanti ajjhāsayaṃ ādibrahmacariyan”’ti?**“Sir, what teaching do you use to guide your disciples, through which they claim solace in the fundamental purpose of the spiritual life?”’*";
P_HTM[646]="*Ayaṃ kho no, bhante, antarākathā vippakatā; atha bhagavā anuppatto”ti.**This is the conversation that was unfinished when the Buddha arrived.”*";
P_HTM[647]="*“Dujjānaṃ kho etaṃ, nigrodha, tayā aññadiṭṭhikena aññakhantikena aññarucikena aññatrāyogena aññatrācariyakena, yenāhaṃ sāvake vinemi, yena mayā sāvakā vinītā assāsappattā paṭijānanti ajjhāsayaṃ ādibrahmacariyaṃ.**“It’s hard for you to understand this, Nigrodha, since you have a different view, creed, preference, practice, and tradition.*";
P_HTM[648]="*Iṅgha tvaṃ maṃ, nigrodha, sake ācariyake adhijegucche pañhaṃ puccha:**Please ask me a question about the higher mortification in disgust of sin in your own tradition:*";
P_HTM[649]="*‘kathaṃ santā nu kho, bhante, tapojigucchā paripuṇṇā hoti, kathaṃ aparipuṇṇā’”ti?**‘How are the conditions for the mortification in disgust of sin completed, and how are they incomplete?’”*";
P_HTM[650]="*Evaṃ vutte, te paribbājakā unnādino uccāsaddamahāsaddā ahesuṃ:**When he said this, those wanderers made an uproar,*";
P_HTM[651]="*“acchariyaṃ vata bho, abbhutaṃ vata bho, samaṇassa gotamassa mahiddhikatā mahānubhāvatā, yatra hi nāma sakavādaṃ ṭhapessati, paravādena pavāressatī”ti.**“It’s incredible, it’s amazing! The ascetic Gotama has such power and might! For he sets aside his own doctrine and invites discussion on the doctrine of others!”*";
P_HTM[652]="*Atha kho nigrodho paribbājako te paribbājake appasadde katvā bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Nigrodha, having quieted those wanderers, said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[653]="*“mayaṃ kho, bhante, tapojigucchāvādā tapojigucchāsārā tapojigucchāallīnā viharāma.**“Sir, we teach mortification in disgust of sin, regarding it as essential and clinging to it.*";
P_HTM[654]="*Kathaṃ santā nu kho, bhante, tapojigucchā paripuṇṇā hoti, kathaṃ aparipuṇṇā”ti?**How are the conditions for the mortification in disgust of sin completed, and how are they incomplete?”*";
P_HTM[655]="*“Idha, nigrodha, tapassī acelako hoti muttācāro, hatthāpalekhano, naehibhaddantiko, natiṭṭhabhaddantiko, nābhihaṭaṃ, na uddissakataṃ, na nimantanaṃ sādiyati,**“It’s when a mortifier goes naked, ignoring conventions. They lick their hands, and don’t come or wait when asked. They don’t consent to food brought to them, or food prepared on purpose for them, or an invitation for a meal.*";
P_HTM[656]="*so na kumbhimukhā paṭiggaṇhāti, na kaḷopimukhā paṭiggaṇhāti, na eḷakamantaraṃ, na daṇḍamantaraṃ, na musalamantaraṃ, na dvinnaṃ bhuñjamānānaṃ, na gabbhiniyā, na pāyamānāya, na purisantaragatāya, na saṅkittīsu, na yattha sā upaṭṭhito hoti, na yattha makkhikā saṇḍasaṇḍacārinī, na macchaṃ, na maṃsaṃ, na suraṃ, na merayaṃ, na thusodakaṃ pivati,**They don’t receive anything from a pot or bowl; or from someone who keeps sheep, or who has a weapon or a shovel in their home; or where a couple is eating; or where there is a woman who is pregnant, breast-feeding, or who has a man in her home; or where there’s a dog waiting or flies buzzing. They accept no fish or meat or liquor or wine, and drink no beer.*";
P_HTM[657]="*so ekāgāriko vā hoti ekālopiko, dvāgāriko vā hoti dvālopiko, sattāgāriko vā hoti sattālopiko, ekissāpi dattiyā yāpeti, dvīhipi dattīhi yāpeti, sattahipi dattīhi yāpeti;**They go to just one house for alms, taking just one mouthful, or two houses and two mouthfuls, up to seven houses and seven mouthfuls. They feed on one saucer a day, two saucers a day, up to seven saucers a day.*";
P_HTM[658]="*ekāhikampi āhāraṃ āhāreti, dvīhikampi āhāraṃ āhāreti, sattāhikampi āhāraṃ āhāreti, iti evarūpaṃ addhamāsikampi pariyāyabhattabhojanānuyogamanuyutto viharati.**They eat once a day, once every second day, up to once a week, and so on, even up to once a fortnight. They live committed to the practice of eating food at set intervals.*";
P_HTM[659]="*So sākabhakkho vā hoti, sāmākabhakkho vā hoti, nīvārabhakkho vā hoti, daddulabhakkho vā hoti, haṭabhakkho vā hoti, kaṇabhakkho vā hoti, ācāmabhakkho vā hoti, piññākabhakkho vā hoti, tiṇabhakkho vā hoti, gomayabhakkho vā hoti; vanamūlaphalāhāro yāpeti pavattaphalabhojī.**They eat herbs, millet, wild rice, poor rice, water lettuce, rice bran, scum from boiling rice, sesame flour, grass, or cow dung. They survive on forest roots and fruits, or eating fallen fruit.*";
P_HTM[660]="*So sāṇānipi dhāreti, masāṇānipi dhāreti, chavadussānipi dhāreti, paṃsukūlānipi dhāreti, tirīṭānipi dhāreti, ajinampi dhāreti, ajinakkhipampi dhāreti, kusacīrampi dhāreti, vākacīrampi dhāreti, phalakacīrampi dhāreti, kesakambalampi dhāreti, vāḷakambalampi dhāreti, ulūkapakkhampi dhāreti,**They wear robes of sunn hemp, mixed hemp, corpse-wrapping cloth, rags, lodh tree bark, antelope hide (whole or in strips), kusa grass, bark, wood-chips, human hair, horse-tail hair, or owls’ wings.*";
P_HTM[661]="*kesamassulocakopi hoti kesamassulocanānuyogamanuyutto,**They tear out their hair and beard, committed to this practice.*";
P_HTM[662]="*ubbhaṭṭhakopi hoti āsanapaṭikkhitto,**They constantly stand, refusing seats.*";
P_HTM[663]="*ukkuṭikopi hoti ukkuṭikappadhānamanuyutto,**They squat, committed to persisting in the squatting position.*";
P_HTM[664]="*kaṇṭakāpassayikopi hoti kaṇṭakāpassaye seyyaṃ kappeti,**They lie on a mat of thorns, making a mat of thorns their bed.*";
P_HTM[665]="*phalakaseyyampi kappeti, thaṇḍilaseyyampi kappeti,**They make their bed on a plank, or the bare ground.*";
P_HTM[666]="*ekapassayikopi hoti**They lie only on one side.*";
P_HTM[667]="*rajojalladharo,**They wear dust and dirt.*";
P_HTM[668]="*abbhokāsikopi hoti**They stay in the open air.*";
P_HTM[669]="*yathāsanthatiko,**They sleep wherever they lay their mat.*";
P_HTM[670]="*vekaṭikopi hoti vikaṭabhojanānuyogamanuyutto,**They eat unnatural things, committed to the practice of eating unnatural foods.*";
P_HTM[671]="*apānakopi hoti apānakattamanuyutto,**They don’t drink, committed to the practice of not drinking liquids.*";
P_HTM[672]="*sāyatatiyakampi udakorohanānuyogamanuyutto viharati.**They’re committed to the practice of immersion in water three times a day, including the evening.*";
P_HTM[673]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, nigrodha,**What do you think, Nigrodha?*";
P_HTM[674]="*yadi evaṃ sante tapojigucchā paripuṇṇā vā hoti aparipuṇṇā vā”ti?**If this is so, is the mortification in disgust of sin complete, or incomplete?”*";
P_HTM[675]="*“Addhā kho, bhante, evaṃ sante tapojigucchā paripuṇṇā hoti, no aparipuṇṇā”ti.**“Clearly, sir, if that is so the mortification in disgust of sin is complete, not incomplete.”*";
P_HTM[676]="*“Evaṃ paripuṇṇāyapi kho ahaṃ, nigrodha, tapojigucchāya anekavihite upakkilese vadāmī”ti.**“But even such a completed mortification has many defects, I say.”*";
P_HTM[677]="*2.1. Upakkilesa**2.1. Defects*";
P_HTM[678]="*“Yathā kathaṃ pana, bhante, bhagavā evaṃ paripuṇṇāya tapojigucchāya anekavihite upakkilese vadatī”ti?**“But how does the Buddha say that even such a completed mortification has many defects?”*";
P_HTM[679]="*“Idha, nigrodha, tapassī tapaṃ samādiyati, so tena tapasā attamano hoti paripuṇṇasaṅkappo.**“Firstly, a mortifier undertakes a practice of mortification. They’re happy with that, as they’ve got all they wished for.*";
P_HTM[680]="*Yampi, nigrodha, tapassī tapaṃ samādiyati, so tena tapasā attamano hoti paripuṇṇasaṅkappo.* **";
P_HTM[681]="*Ayampi kho, nigrodha, tapassino upakkileso hoti.**This is a defect in that mortifier.*";
P_HTM[682]="*Puna caparaṃ, nigrodha, tapassī tapaṃ samādiyati, so tena tapasā attānukkaṃseti paraṃ vambheti.**Furthermore, a mortifier undertakes a practice of mortification. They glorify themselves and put others down on account of that.*";
P_HTM[683]="*Yampi, nigrodha, tapassī tapaṃ samādiyati, so tena tapasā attānukkaṃseti paraṃ vambheti.* **";
P_HTM[684]="*Ayampi kho, nigrodha, tapassino upakkileso hoti.**This too is a defect in that mortifier.*";
P_HTM[685]="*Puna caparaṃ, nigrodha, tapassī tapaṃ samādiyati, so tena tapasā majjati mucchati pamādamāpajjati.**Furthermore, a mortifier undertakes a practice of mortification. They become indulgent and infatuated and fall into negligence on account of that.*";
P_HTM[686]="*Yampi, nigrodha, tapassī tapaṃ samādiyati, so tena tapasā majjati mucchati pamādamāpajjati.* **";
P_HTM[687]="*Ayampi kho, nigrodha, tapassino upakkileso hoti.**This too is a defect in that mortifier.*";
P_HTM[688]="*Puna caparaṃ, nigrodha, tapassī tapaṃ samādiyati, so tena tapasā lābhasakkārasilokaṃ abhinibbatteti, so tena lābhasakkārasilokena attamano hoti paripuṇṇasaṅkappo.**Furthermore, a mortifier undertakes a practice of mortification. They generate possessions, honor, and popularity through that mortification. They’re happy with that, as they’ve got all they wished for.*";
P_HTM[689]="*Yampi, nigrodha, tapassī tapaṃ samādiyati, so tena tapasā lābhasakkārasilokaṃ abhinibbatteti, so tena lābhasakkārasilokena attamano hoti paripuṇṇasaṅkappo.* **";
P_HTM[690]="*Ayampi kho, nigrodha, tapassino upakkileso hoti.**This too is a defect in that mortifier.*";
P_HTM[691]="*Puna caparaṃ, nigrodha, tapassī tapaṃ samādiyati, so tena tapasā lābhasakkārasilokaṃ abhinibbatteti, so tena lābhasakkārasilokena attānukkaṃseti paraṃ vambheti.**Furthermore, a mortifier undertakes a practice of mortification. They generate possessions, honor, and popularity through that mortification. They glorify themselves and put others down on account of that.*";
P_HTM[692]="*Yampi, nigrodha, tapassī tapaṃ samādiyati, so tena tapasā lābhasakkārasilokaṃ abhinibbatteti, so tena lābhasakkārasilokena attānukkaṃseti paraṃ vambheti.* **";
P_HTM[693]="*Ayampi kho, nigrodha, tapassino upakkileso hoti.**This too is a defect in that mortifier.*";
P_HTM[694]="*Puna caparaṃ, nigrodha, tapassī tapaṃ samādiyati, so tena tapasā lābhasakkārasilokaṃ abhinibbatteti, so tena lābhasakkārasilokena majjati mucchati pamādamāpajjati.**Furthermore, a mortifier undertakes a practice of mortification. They generate possessions, honor, and popularity through that mortification. They become indulgent and infatuated and fall into negligence on account of that.*";
P_HTM[695]="*Yampi, nigrodha, tapassī tapaṃ samādiyati, so tena tapasā lābhasakkārasilokaṃ abhinibbatteti, so tena lābhasakkārasilokena majjati mucchati pamādamāpajjati.* **";
P_HTM[696]="*Ayampi kho, nigrodha, tapassino upakkileso hoti.**This too is a defect in that mortifier.*";
P_HTM[697]="*Puna caparaṃ, nigrodha, tapassī bhojanesu vodāsaṃ āpajjati:**Furthermore, a mortifier becomes fussy about food, saying,*";
P_HTM[698]="*‘idaṃ me khamati, idaṃ me nakkhamatī’ti.**‘This agrees with me, this doesn’t agree with me.’*";
P_HTM[699]="*So yañca khvassa nakkhamati, taṃ sāpekkho pajahati.**What doesn’t agree with them they reluctantly give up.*";
P_HTM[700]="*Yaṃ panassa khamati, taṃ gadhito mucchito ajjhāpanno anādīnavadassāvī anissaraṇapañño paribhuñjati … pe …**But what does agree with them they eat tied, infatuated, attached, blind to the drawbacks, and not understanding the escape.*";
P_HTM[701]="*ayampi kho, nigrodha, tapassino upakkileso hoti.**This too is a defect in that mortifier.*";
P_HTM[702]="*Puna caparaṃ, nigrodha, tapassī tapaṃ samādiyati lābhasakkārasilokanikantihetu:**Furthermore, a mortifier undertakes a practice of mortification out of longing for possessions, honor, and popularity, thinking,*";
P_HTM[703]="*‘sakkarissanti maṃ rājāno rājamahāmattā khattiyā brāhmaṇā gahapatikā titthiyā’ti … pe …**‘Kings, royal ministers, aristocrats, brahmins, householders, and sectarians will honor me!’*";
P_HTM[704]="*ayampi kho, nigrodha, tapassino upakkileso hoti.**This too is a defect in that mortifier.*";
P_HTM[705]="*Puna caparaṃ, nigrodha, tapassī aññataraṃ samaṇaṃ vā brāhmaṇaṃ vā apasādetā hoti:**Furthermore, a mortifier rebukes a certain ascetic or brahmin,*";
P_HTM[706]="*‘kiṃ panāyaṃ sambahulājīvo sabbaṃ sambhakkheti.**‘But what is this one doing, living in abundance! According to this ascetic’s doctrine, everything—*";
P_HTM[707]="*Seyyathidaṃ—mūlabījaṃ khandhabījaṃ phaḷubījaṃ aggabījaṃ bījabījameva pañcamaṃ, asanivicakkaṃ dantakūṭaṃ, samaṇappavādenā’ti … pe …**plants propagated from roots, stems, cuttings, or joints; and those from regular seeds as the fifth—is crunched together like the thunder of a tooth-hammer!’*";
P_HTM[708]="*ayampi kho, nigrodha, tapassino upakkileso hoti.**This too is a defect in that mortifier.*";
P_HTM[709]="*Puna caparaṃ, nigrodha, tapassī passati aññataraṃ samaṇaṃ vā brāhmaṇaṃ vā kulesu sakkariyamānaṃ garukariyamānaṃ māniyamānaṃ pūjiyamānaṃ.**Furthermore, a mortifier sees a certain ascetic or brahmin being honored, respected, esteemed, and venerated among good families.*";
P_HTM[710]="*Disvā tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think,*";
P_HTM[711]="*‘imañhi nāma sambahulājīvaṃ kulesu sakkaronti garuṃ karonti mānenti pūjenti.**‘This one, who lives in abundance, is honored, respected, esteemed, and venerated among good families.*";
P_HTM[712]="*Maṃ pana tapassiṃ lūkhājīviṃ kulesu na sakkaronti na garuṃ karonti na mānenti na pūjentī’ti, iti so issāmacchariyaṃ kulesu uppādetā hoti … pe …**But I, a self-mortifier who lives rough, am not honored, respected, esteemed, and venerated among good families.’ Thus they give rise to jealousy and stinginess regarding families.*";
P_HTM[713]="*ayampi kho, nigrodha, tapassino upakkileso hoti.**This too is a defect in that mortifier.*";
P_HTM[714]="*Puna caparaṃ, nigrodha, tapassī āpāthakanisādī hoti … pe …**Furthermore, a mortifier sits meditation only when people can see them.*";
P_HTM[715]="*ayampi kho, nigrodha, tapassino upakkileso hoti.**This too is a defect in that mortifier.*";
P_HTM[716]="*Puna caparaṃ, nigrodha, tapassī attānaṃ adassayamāno kulesu carati:**Furthermore, a mortifier sneaks about among families, thinking,*";
P_HTM[717]="*‘idampi me tapasmiṃ idampi me tapasmin’ti … pe …**‘This is part of my mortification; this is part of my mortification.’*";
P_HTM[718]="*ayampi kho, nigrodha, tapassino upakkileso hoti.**This too is a defect in that mortifier.*";
P_HTM[719]="*Puna caparaṃ, nigrodha, tapassī kiñcideva paṭicchannaṃ sevati.**Furthermore, a mortifier sometimes behaves in an underhand manner.*";
P_HTM[720]="*So ‘khamati te idan’ti puṭṭho samāno akkhamamānaṃ āha: ‘khamatī’ti.**When asked whether something agrees with them, they say it does, even though it doesn’t.*";
P_HTM[721]="*Khamamānaṃ āha: ‘nakkhamatī’ti.**Or they say it doesn’t, even though it does.*";
P_HTM[722]="*Iti so sampajānamusā bhāsitā hoti … pe …**Thus they tell a deliberate lie.*";
P_HTM[723]="*ayampi kho, nigrodha, tapassino upakkileso hoti.**This too is a defect in that mortifier.*";
P_HTM[724]="*Puna caparaṃ, nigrodha, tapassī tathāgatassa vā tathāgatasāvakassa vā dhammaṃ desentassa santaṃyeva pariyāyaṃ anuññeyyaṃ nānujānāti … pe …**Furthermore, a mortifier disagrees with the way that the Realized One or their disciple teaches Dhamma, even when they make a valid point.*";
P_HTM[725]="*ayampi kho, nigrodha, tapassino upakkileso hoti.**This too is a defect in that mortifier.*";
P_HTM[726]="*Puna caparaṃ, nigrodha, tapassī kodhano hoti upanāhī.**Furthermore, a mortifier is irritable and hostile …*";
P_HTM[727]="*Yampi, nigrodha, tapassī kodhano hoti upanāhī.* **";
P_HTM[728]="*Ayampi kho, nigrodha, tapassino upakkileso hoti.* **";
P_HTM[729]="*Puna caparaṃ, nigrodha, tapassī makkhī hoti paḷāsī … pe …**offensive and contemptuous …*";
P_HTM[730]="*issukī hoti maccharī …**jealous and stingy …*";
P_HTM[731]="*saṭho hoti māyāvī …**devious and deceitful …*";
P_HTM[732]="*thaddho hoti atimānī …**obstinate and vain …*";
P_HTM[733]="*pāpiccho hoti pāpikānaṃ icchānaṃ vasaṃ gato …**they have wicked desires, falling under the sway of wicked desires …*";
P_HTM[734]="*micchādiṭṭhiko hoti antaggāhikāya diṭṭhiyā samannāgato …**they have wrong view, being attached to an extremist view …*";
P_HTM[735]="*sandiṭṭhiparāmāsī hoti ādhānaggāhī duppaṭinissaggī.**they’re attached to their own views, holding them tight, and refusing to let go.*";
P_HTM[736]="*Yampi, nigrodha, tapassī sandiṭṭhiparāmāsī hoti ādhānaggāhī duppaṭinissaggī.* **";
P_HTM[737]="*Ayampi kho, nigrodha, tapassino upakkileso hoti.**This too is a defect in that mortifier.*";
P_HTM[738]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, nigrodha,**What do you think, Nigrodha?*";
P_HTM[739]="*yadime tapojigucchā upakkilesā vā anupakkilesā vā”ti?**Are such mortifications defective or not?”*";
P_HTM[740]="*“Addhā kho ime, bhante, tapojigucchā upakkilesā, no anupakkilesā.**“Clearly, sir, they’re defective.*";
P_HTM[741]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, bhante, vijjati yaṃ idhekacco tapassī sabbeheva imehi upakkilesehi samannāgato assa;**It’s possible that a mortifier might have all of these defects,*";
P_HTM[742]="*ko pana vādo aññataraññatarenā”ti.**let alone one or other of them.”*";
P_HTM[743]="*2.2. Parisuddhapapaṭikappattakathā**2.2. On Reaching the Shoots*";
P_HTM[744]="*“Idha, nigrodha, tapassī tapaṃ samādiyati, so tena tapasā na attamano hoti na paripuṇṇasaṅkappo.**“Firstly, Nigrodha, a mortifier undertakes a practice of mortification. But they’re not happy with that, as they still haven’t got all they wished for.*";
P_HTM[745]="*Yampi, nigrodha, tapassī tapaṃ samādiyati, so tena tapasā na attamano hoti na paripuṇṇasaṅkappo.* **";
P_HTM[746]="*Evaṃ so tasmiṃ ṭhāne parisuddho hoti.**So they’re pure on that point.*";
P_HTM[747]="*Puna caparaṃ, nigrodha, tapassī tapaṃ samādiyati, so tena tapasā na attānukkaṃseti na paraṃ vambheti … pe …**Furthermore, a mortifier undertakes a practice of mortification. They don’t glorify themselves or put others down on account of that.*";
P_HTM[748]="*evaṃ so tasmiṃ ṭhāne parisuddho hoti.**So they’re pure on that point.*";
P_HTM[749]="*Puna caparaṃ, nigrodha, tapassī tapaṃ samādiyati, so tena tapasā na majjati na mucchati na pamādamāpajjati … pe …**They don’t become indulgent …*";
P_HTM[750]="*evaṃ so tasmiṃ ṭhāne parisuddho hoti.* **";
P_HTM[751]="*Puna caparaṃ, nigrodha, tapassī tapaṃ samādiyati, so tena tapasā lābhasakkārasilokaṃ abhinibbatteti, so tena lābhasakkārasilokena na attamano hoti na paripuṇṇasaṅkappo … pe …**Furthermore, a mortifier undertakes a practice of mortification. They generate possessions, honor, and popularity through that mortification. They’re not happy with that, as they still haven’t got all they wished for …*";
P_HTM[752]="*evaṃ so tasmiṃ ṭhāne parisuddho hoti.* **";
P_HTM[753]="*Puna caparaṃ, nigrodha, tapassī tapaṃ samādiyati, so tena tapasā lābhasakkārasilokaṃ abhinibbatteti, so tena lābhasakkārasilokena na attānukkaṃseti na paraṃ vambheti … pe …**They don’t glorify themselves and put others down on account of possessions, honor, and popularity …*";
P_HTM[754]="*evaṃ so tasmiṃ ṭhāne parisuddho hoti.* **";
P_HTM[755]="*Puna caparaṃ, nigrodha, tapassī tapaṃ samādiyati, so tena tapasā lābhasakkārasilokaṃ abhinibbatteti, so tena lābhasakkārasilokena na majjati na mucchati na pamādamāpajjati … pe …**They don’t become indulgent because of it …*";
P_HTM[756]="*evaṃ so tasmiṃ ṭhāne parisuddho hoti.**So they’re pure on that point.*";
P_HTM[757]="*Puna caparaṃ, nigrodha, tapassī bhojanesu na vodāsaṃ āpajjati:**Furthermore, a mortifier doesn’t become fussy about food, saying,*";
P_HTM[758]="*‘idaṃ me khamati, idaṃ me nakkhamatī’ti.**‘This agrees with me, this doesn’t agree with me.’*";
P_HTM[759]="*So yañca khvassa nakkhamati, taṃ anapekkho pajahati.**What doesn’t agree with them they readily give up.*";
P_HTM[760]="*Yaṃ panassa khamati, taṃ agadhito amucchito anajjhāpanno ādīnavadassāvī nissaraṇapañño paribhuñjati … pe …**But what does agree with them they eat without being tied, infatuated, attached, blind to the drawbacks, and not understanding the escape.*";
P_HTM[761]="*evaṃ so tasmiṃ ṭhāne parisuddho hoti.**So they’re pure on that point.*";
P_HTM[762]="*Puna caparaṃ, nigrodha, tapassī na tapaṃ samādiyati lābhasakkārasilokanikantihetu:**Furthermore, a mortifier doesn’t undertake a practice of mortification out of longing for possessions, honor, and popularity …*";
P_HTM[763]="*‘sakkarissanti maṃ rājāno rājamahāmattā khattiyā brāhmaṇā gahapatikā titthiyā’ti … pe …**‘Kings, royal ministers, aristocrats, brahmins, householders, and sectarians will honor me!’*";
P_HTM[764]="*evaṃ so tasmiṃ ṭhāne parisuddho hoti.**So they’re pure on that point.*";
P_HTM[765]="*Puna caparaṃ, nigrodha, tapassī aññataraṃ samaṇaṃ vā brāhmaṇaṃ vā nāpasādetā hoti:**Furthermore, a mortifier doesn’t rebuke a certain ascetic or brahmin,*";
P_HTM[766]="*‘kiṃ panāyaṃ sambahulājīvo sabbaṃ sambhakkheti.**‘But what is this one doing, living in abundance! According to this ascetic’s doctrine, everything—*";
P_HTM[767]="*Seyyathidaṃ—mūlabījaṃ khandhabījaṃ phaḷubījaṃ aggabījaṃ bījabījameva pañcamaṃ, asanivicakkaṃ dantakūṭaṃ, samaṇappavādenā’ti … pe …**plants propagated from roots, stems, cuttings, or joints; and those from regular seeds as the fifth—is crunched together like the thunder of a tooth-hammer!’*";
P_HTM[768]="*evaṃ so tasmiṃ ṭhāne parisuddho hoti.**So they’re pure on that point.*";
P_HTM[769]="*Puna caparaṃ, nigrodha, tapassī passati aññataraṃ samaṇaṃ vā brāhmaṇaṃ vā kulesu sakkariyamānaṃ garu kariyamānaṃ māniyamānaṃ pūjiyamānaṃ.**Furthermore, a mortifier sees a certain ascetic or brahmin being honored, respected, esteemed, and venerated among good families.*";
P_HTM[770]="*Disvā tassa na evaṃ hoti:**It never occurs to them,*";
P_HTM[771]="*‘imañhi nāma sambahulājīvaṃ kulesu sakkaronti garuṃ karonti mānenti pūjenti.**‘This one, who lives in abundance, is honored, respected, esteemed, and venerated among good families.*";
P_HTM[772]="*Maṃ pana tapassiṃ lūkhājīviṃ kulesu na sakkaronti na garuṃ karonti na mānenti na pūjentī’ti, iti so issāmacchariyaṃ kulesu nuppādetā hoti … pe …**But I, a self-mortifier who lives rough, am not honored, respected, esteemed, and venerated among good families.’ Thus they don’t give rise to jealousy and stinginess regarding families.*";
P_HTM[773]="*evaṃ so tasmiṃ ṭhāne parisuddho hoti.**So they’re pure on that point.*";
P_HTM[774]="*Puna caparaṃ, nigrodha, tapassī na āpāthakanisādī hoti … pe …**Furthermore, a mortifier doesn’t sit meditation only when people can see them.*";
P_HTM[775]="*evaṃ so tasmiṃ ṭhāne parisuddho hoti.**So they’re pure on that point.*";
P_HTM[776]="*Puna caparaṃ, nigrodha, tapassī na attānaṃ adassayamāno kulesu carati:**Furthermore, a mortifier doesn’t sneak about among families, thinking,*";
P_HTM[777]="*‘idampi me tapasmiṃ, idampi me tapasmin’ti … pe …**‘This is part of my mortification; this is part of my mortification.’*";
P_HTM[778]="*evaṃ so tasmiṃ ṭhāne parisuddho hoti.**So they’re pure on that point.*";
P_HTM[779]="*Puna caparaṃ, nigrodha, tapassī na kiñcideva paṭicchannaṃ sevati, so:**Furthermore, a mortifier never behaves in an underhand manner.*";
P_HTM[780]="*‘khamati te idan’ti puṭṭho samāno akkhamamānaṃ āha:**When asked whether something agrees with them, they say it doesn’t when it doesn’t.*";
P_HTM[781]="*‘nakkhamatī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[782]="*Khamamānaṃ āha:**Or they say it does when it does.*";
P_HTM[783]="*‘khamatī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[784]="*Iti so sampajānamusā na bhāsitā hoti … pe …**Thus they don’t tell a deliberate lie.*";
P_HTM[785]="*evaṃ so tasmiṃ ṭhāne parisuddho hoti.**So they’re pure on that point.*";
P_HTM[786]="*Puna caparaṃ, nigrodha, tapassī tathāgatassa vā tathāgatasāvakassa vā dhammaṃ desentassa santaṃyeva pariyāyaṃ anuññeyyaṃ anujānāti … pe …**Furthermore, a mortifier agrees with the way that the Realized One or their disciple teaches Dhamma when they make a valid point.*";
P_HTM[787]="*evaṃ so tasmiṃ ṭhāne parisuddho hoti.**So they’re pure on that point.*";
P_HTM[788]="*Puna caparaṃ, nigrodha, tapassī akkodhano hoti anupanāhī.**Furthermore, a mortifier is not irritable and hostile …*";
P_HTM[789]="*Yampi, nigrodha, tapassī akkodhano hoti anupanāhī evaṃ so tasmiṃ ṭhāne parisuddho hoti.* **";
P_HTM[790]="*Puna caparaṃ, nigrodha, tapassī amakkhī hoti apaḷāsī … pe …**offensive and contemptuous …*";
P_HTM[791]="*anissukī hoti amaccharī …**jealous and stingy …*";
P_HTM[792]="*asaṭho hoti amāyāvī …**devious and deceitful …*";
P_HTM[793]="*atthaddho hoti anatimānī …**obstinate and vain …*";
P_HTM[794]="*na pāpiccho hoti na pāpikānaṃ icchānaṃ vasaṃ gato …**they don’t have wicked desires …*";
P_HTM[795]="*na micchādiṭṭhiko hoti na antaggāhikāya diṭṭhiyā samannāgato …**and wrong view …*";
P_HTM[796]="*na sandiṭṭhiparāmāsī hoti na ādhānaggāhī suppaṭinissaggī.**they’re not attached to their own views, holding them tight, and refusing to let go.*";
P_HTM[797]="*Yampi, nigrodha, tapassī na sandiṭṭhiparāmāsī hoti na ādhānaggāhī suppaṭinissaggī.* **";
P_HTM[798]="*Evaṃ so tasmiṃ ṭhāne parisuddho hoti.**So they’re pure on that point.*";
P_HTM[799]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, nigrodha,**What do you think, Nigrodha?*";
P_HTM[800]="*yadi evaṃ sante tapojigucchā parisuddhā vā hoti aparisuddhā vā”ti?**If this is so, is the mortification in disgust of sin purified or not?”*";
P_HTM[801]="*“Addhā kho, bhante, evaṃ sante tapojigucchā parisuddhā hoti no aparisuddhā, aggappattā ca sārappattā cā”ti.**“Clearly, sir, it is purified. It has reached the peak and the pith.”*";
P_HTM[802]="*“Na kho, nigrodha, ettāvatā tapojigucchā aggappattā ca hoti sārappattā ca;**“No, Nigrodha, at this point the mortification in disgust of sin has not yet reached the peak and the pith.*";
P_HTM[803]="*api ca kho papaṭikappattā hotī”ti.**Rather, it has only reached the shoots.”*";
P_HTM[804]="*2.3. Parisuddhatacappattakathā**2.3. On Reaching the Bark*";
P_HTM[805]="*“Kittāvatā pana, bhante, tapojigucchā aggappattā ca hoti sārappattā ca?**“But at what point, sir, does the mortification in disgust of sin reach the peak and the pith?*";
P_HTM[806]="*Sādhu me, bhante, bhagavā tapojigucchāya aggaññeva pāpetu, sāraññeva pāpetū”ti.**Please help me reach the peak and the pith!”*";
P_HTM[807]="*“Idha, nigrodha, tapassī cātuyāmasaṃvarasaṃvuto hoti.**“Nigrodha, take a mortifier who is restrained in the fourfold restraint.*";
P_HTM[808]="*Kathañca, nigrodha, tapassī cātuyāmasaṃvarasaṃvuto hoti?**And how is a mortifier restrained in the fourfold restraint?*";
P_HTM[809]="*Idha, nigrodha, tapassī na pāṇaṃ atipāteti, na pāṇaṃ atipātayati, na pāṇamatipātayato samanuñño hoti.**It’s when a mortifier doesn’t kill living creatures, doesn’t get others to kill, and doesn’t approve of killing.*";
P_HTM[810]="*Na adinnaṃ ādiyati, na adinnaṃ ādiyāpeti, na adinnaṃ ādiyato samanuñño hoti.**They don’t steal, get others to steal, or approve of stealing.*";
P_HTM[811]="*Na musā bhaṇati, na musā bhaṇāpeti, na musā bhaṇato samanuñño hoti.**They don’t lie, get others to lie, or approve of lying.*";
P_HTM[812]="*Na bhāvitamāsīsati, na bhāvitamāsīsāpeti, na bhāvitamāsīsato samanuñño hoti.**They don’t expect rewards from their practice, they don’t lead others to expect rewards, and they don’t approve of expecting rewards.*";
P_HTM[813]="*Evaṃ kho, nigrodha, tapassī cātuyāmasaṃvarasaṃvuto hoti.**That’s how a mortifier is restrained in the fourfold restraint.*";
P_HTM[814]="*Yato kho, nigrodha, tapassī cātuyāmasaṃvarasaṃvuto hoti, aduṃ cassa hoti tapassitāya.**When a mortifier has the fourfold restraint, that is their mortification.*";
P_HTM[815]="*So abhiharati no hīnāyāvattati.**They step forward, not falling back.*";
P_HTM[816]="*So vivittaṃ senāsanaṃ bhajati araññaṃ rukkhamūlaṃ pabbataṃ kandaraṃ giriguhaṃ susānaṃ vanapatthaṃ abbhokāsaṃ palālapuñjaṃ.**They frequent a secluded lodging—a wilderness, the root of a tree, a hill, a ravine, a mountain cave, a charnel ground, a forest, the open air, a heap of straw.*";
P_HTM[817]="*So pacchābhattaṃ piṇḍapātapaṭikkanto nisīdati pallaṅkaṃ ābhujitvā ujuṃ kāyaṃ paṇidhāya parimukhaṃ satiṃ upaṭṭhapetvā.**After the meal, they return from alms-round, sit down cross-legged with their body straight, and establish mindfulness right there.*";
P_HTM[818]="*So abhijjhaṃ loke pahāya vigatābhijjhena cetasā viharati, abhijjhāya cittaṃ parisodheti.**Giving up desire for the world, they meditate with a heart rid of desire, cleansing the mind of desire.*";
P_HTM[819]="*Byāpādappadosaṃ pahāya abyāpannacitto viharati sabbapāṇabhūtahitānukampī, byāpādappadosā cittaṃ parisodheti.**Giving up ill will and malevolence, they meditate with a mind rid of ill will, full of compassion for all living beings, cleansing the mind of ill will.*";
P_HTM[820]="*Thinamiddhaṃ pahāya vigatathinamiddho viharati ālokasaññī sato sampajāno, thinamiddhā cittaṃ parisodheti.**Giving up dullness and drowsiness, they meditate with a mind rid of dullness and drowsiness, perceiving light, mindful and aware, cleansing the mind of dullness and drowsiness.*";
P_HTM[821]="*Uddhaccakukkuccaṃ pahāya anuddhato viharati ajjhattaṃ vūpasantacitto, uddhaccakukkuccā cittaṃ parisodheti.**Giving up restlessness and remorse, they meditate without restlessness, their mind peaceful inside, cleansing the mind of restlessness and remorse.*";
P_HTM[822]="*Vicikicchaṃ pahāya tiṇṇavicikiccho viharati akathaṃkathī kusalesu dhammesu, vicikicchāya cittaṃ parisodheti.**Giving up doubt, they meditate having gone beyond doubt, not undecided about skillful qualities, cleansing the mind of doubt.*";
P_HTM[823]="*So ime pañca nīvaraṇe pahāya cetaso upakkilese paññāya dubbalīkaraṇe**They give up these five hindrances, corruptions of the heart that weaken wisdom.*";
P_HTM[824]="*mettāsahagatena cetasā ekaṃ disaṃ pharitvā viharati. Tathā dutiyaṃ. Tathā tatiyaṃ. Tathā catutthaṃ. Iti uddhamadho tiriyaṃ sabbadhi sabbattatāya sabbāvantaṃ lokaṃ mettāsahagatena cetasā vipulena mahaggatena appamāṇena averena abyāpajjena pharitvā viharati.**Then they meditate spreading a heart full of love to one direction, and to the second, and to the third, and to the fourth. In the same way above, below, across, everywhere, all around, they spread a heart full of love to the whole world—abundant, expansive, limitless, free of enmity and ill will.*";
P_HTM[825]="*Karuṇāsahagatena cetasā … pe …**They meditate spreading a heart full of compassion …*";
P_HTM[826]="*muditāsahagatena cetasā … pe …**They meditate spreading a heart full of rejoicing …*";
P_HTM[827]="*upekkhāsahagatena cetasā ekaṃ disaṃ pharitvā viharati. Tathā dutiyaṃ. Tathā tatiyaṃ. Tathā catutthaṃ. Iti uddhamadho tiriyaṃ sabbadhi sabbattatāya sabbāvantaṃ lokaṃ upekkhāsahagatena cetasā vipulena mahaggatena appamāṇena averena abyāpajjena pharitvā viharati.**They meditate spreading a heart full of equanimity to one direction, and to the second, and to the third, and to the fourth. In the same way above, below, across, everywhere, all around, they spread a heart full of equanimity to the whole world—abundant, expansive, limitless, free of enmity and ill will.*";
P_HTM[828]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, nigrodha.**What do you think, Nigrodha?*";
P_HTM[829]="*Yadi evaṃ sante tapojigucchā parisuddhā vā hoti aparisuddhā vā”ti?**If this is so, is the mortification in disgust of sin purified or not?”*";
P_HTM[830]="*“Addhā kho, bhante, evaṃ sante tapojigucchā parisuddhā hoti no aparisuddhā, aggappattā ca sārappattā cā”ti.**“Clearly, sir, it is purified. It has reached the peak and the pith.”*";
P_HTM[831]="*“Na kho, nigrodha, ettāvatā tapojigucchā aggappattā ca hoti sārappattā ca;**“No, Nigrodha, at this point the mortification in disgust of sin has not yet reached the peak and the pith.*";
P_HTM[832]="*api ca kho tacappattā hotī”ti.**Rather, it has only reached the bark.”*";
P_HTM[833]="*2.4. Parisuddhaphegguppattakathā**2.4. On Reaching the Softwood*";
P_HTM[834]="*“Kittāvatā pana, bhante, tapojigucchā aggappattā ca hoti sārappattā ca?**“But at what point, sir, does the mortification in disgust of sin reach the peak and the pith?*";
P_HTM[835]="*Sādhu me, bhante, bhagavā tapojigucchāya aggaññeva pāpetu, sāraññeva pāpetū”ti.**Please help me reach the peak and the pith!”*";
P_HTM[836]="*“Idha, nigrodha, tapassī cātuyāmasaṃvarasaṃvuto hoti.**“Nigrodha, take a mortifier who is restrained in the fourfold restraint.*";
P_HTM[837]="*Kathañca, nigrodha, tapassī cātuyāmasaṃvarasaṃvuto hoti … pe …* **";
P_HTM[838]="*yato kho, nigrodha, tapassī cātuyāmasaṃvarasaṃvuto hoti, aduṃ cassa hoti tapassitāya.* **";
P_HTM[839]="*So abhiharati no hīnāyāvattati.* **";
P_HTM[840]="*So vivittaṃ senāsanaṃ bhajati … pe …* **";
P_HTM[841]="*so ime pañca nīvaraṇe pahāya cetaso upakkilese paññāya dubbalīkaraṇe**They give up these five hindrances, corruptions of the heart that weaken wisdom.*";
P_HTM[842]="*mettāsahagatena cetasā … pe …**Then they meditate spreading a heart full of love …*";
P_HTM[843]="*karuṇāsahagatena cetasā … pe …**compassion …*";
P_HTM[844]="*muditāsahagatena cetasā … pe …**rejoicing …*";
P_HTM[845]="*upekkhāsahagatena cetasā vipulena mahaggatena appamāṇena averena abyāpajjena pharitvā viharati.**equanimity.*";
P_HTM[846]="*So anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati seyyathidaṃ—ekampi jātiṃ dvepi jātiyo tissopi jātiyo catassopi jātiyo pañcapi jātiyo dasapi jātiyo vīsampi jātiyo tiṃsampi jātiyo cattālīsampi jātiyo paññāsampi jātiyo jātisatampi jātisahassampi jātisatasahassampi anekepi saṃvaṭṭakappe anekepi vivaṭṭakappe anekepi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭakappe: ‘amutrāsiṃ evaṃnāmo evaṃgotto evaṃvaṇṇo evamāhāro evaṃsukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī evamāyupariyanto, so tato cuto amutra udapādiṃ, tatrāpāsiṃ evaṃnāmo evaṃgotto evaṃvaṇṇo evamāhāro evaṃsukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī evamāyupariyanto, so tato cuto idhūpapanno’ti. Iti sākāraṃ sauddesaṃ anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati.**They recollect many kinds of past lives, that is, one, two, three, four, five, ten, twenty, thirty, forty, fifty, a hundred, a thousand, a hundred thousand rebirths; many eons of the world contracting, many eons of the world expanding, many eons of the world contracting and expanding. They remember: ‘There, I was named this, my clan was that, I looked like this, and that was my food. This was how I felt pleasure and pain, and that was how my life ended. When I passed away from that place I was reborn somewhere else. There, too, I was named this, my clan was that, I looked like this, and that was my food. This was how I felt pleasure and pain, and that was how my life ended. When I passed away from that place I was reborn here.’ And so they recollect their many kinds of past lives, with features and details.*";
P_HTM[847]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, nigrodha,**What do you think, Nigrodha?*";
P_HTM[848]="*yadi evaṃ sante tapojigucchā parisuddhā vā hoti aparisuddhā vā”ti?**If this is so, is the mortification in disgust of sin purified or not?”*";
P_HTM[849]="*“Addhā kho, bhante, evaṃ sante tapojigucchā parisuddhā hoti, no aparisuddhā, aggappattā ca sārappattā cā”ti.**“Clearly, sir, it is purified. It has reached the peak and the pith.”*";
P_HTM[850]="*“Na kho, nigrodha, ettāvatā tapojigucchā aggappattā ca hoti sārappattā ca;**“No, Nigrodha, at this point the mortification in disgust of sin has not yet reached the peak and the pith.*";
P_HTM[851]="*api ca kho phegguppattā hotī”ti.**Rather, it has only reached the softwood.”*";
P_HTM[852]="*3. Parisuddhaaggappattasārappattakathā**3. On Reaching the Heartwood*";
P_HTM[853]="*“Kittāvatā pana, bhante, tapojigucchā aggappattā ca hoti sārappattā ca?**“But at what point, sir, does the mortification in disgust of sin reach the peak and the pith?*";
P_HTM[854]="*Sādhu me, bhante, bhagavā tapojigucchāya aggaññeva pāpetu, sāraññeva pāpetū”ti.**Please help me reach the peak and the pith!”*";
P_HTM[855]="*“Idha, nigrodha, tapassī cātuyāmasaṃvarasaṃvuto hoti.**“Nigrodha, take a mortifier who is restrained in the fourfold restraint.*";
P_HTM[856]="*Kathañca, nigrodha, tapassī cātuyāmasaṃvarasaṃvuto hoti … pe …* **";
P_HTM[857]="*yato kho, nigrodha, tapassī cātuyāmasaṃvarasaṃvuto hoti, aduṃ cassa hoti tapassitāya.* **";
P_HTM[858]="*So abhiharati no hīnāyāvattati.* **";
P_HTM[859]="*So vivittaṃ senāsanaṃ bhajati … pe …* **";
P_HTM[860]="*so ime pañca nīvaraṇe pahāya cetaso upakkilese paññāya dubbalīkaraṇe**They give up these five hindrances, corruptions of the heart that weaken wisdom.*";
P_HTM[861]="*mettāsahagatena cetasā … pe …**Then they meditate spreading a heart full of love …*";
P_HTM[862]="*upekkhāsahagatena cetasā vipulena mahaggatena appamāṇena averena abyāpajjena pharitvā viharati.**equanimity …*";
P_HTM[863]="*So anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati. Seyyathidaṃ—ekampi jātiṃ dvepi jātiyo tissopi jātiyo catassopi jātiyo pañcapi jātiyo … pe … iti sākāraṃ sauddesaṃ anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati.**They recollect many kinds of past lives, with features and details.*";
P_HTM[864]="*So dibbena cakkhunā visuddhena atikkantamānusakena satte passati cavamāne upapajjamāne hīne paṇīte suvaṇṇe dubbaṇṇe sugate duggate, yathākammūpage satte pajānāti: ‘ime vata bhonto sattā kāyaduccaritena samannāgatā vacīduccaritena samannāgatā manoduccaritena samannāgatā ariyānaṃ upavādakā micchādiṭṭhikā micchādiṭṭhikammasamādānā. Te kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapannā. Ime vā pana bhonto sattā kāyasucaritena samannāgatā vacīsucaritena samannāgatā manosucaritena samannāgatā ariyānaṃ anupavādakā sammādiṭṭhikā sammādiṭṭhikammasamādānā. Te kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapannā’ti. Iti dibbena cakkhunā visuddhena atikkantamānusakena satte passati cavamāne upapajjamāne hīne paṇīte suvaṇṇe dubbaṇṇe sugate duggate, yathākammūpage satte pajānāti.**With clairvoyance that is purified and superhuman, they see sentient beings passing away and being reborn—inferior and superior, beautiful and ugly, in a good place or a bad place. They understand how sentient beings are reborn according to their deeds: ‘These dear beings did bad things by way of body, speech, and mind. They spoke ill of the noble ones; they had wrong view; and they chose to act out of that wrong view. When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell. These dear beings, however, did good things by way of body, speech, and mind. They never spoke ill of the noble ones; they had right view; and they chose to act out of that right view. When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.’ And so, with clairvoyance that is purified and superhuman, they see sentient beings passing away and being reborn—inferior and superior, beautiful and ugly, in a good place or a bad place. They understand how sentient beings are reborn according to their deeds.*";
P_HTM[865]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, nigrodha,**What do you think, Nigrodha?*";
P_HTM[866]="*yadi evaṃ sante tapojigucchā parisuddhā vā hoti aparisuddhā vā”ti?**If this is so, is the mortification in disgust of sin purified or not?”*";
P_HTM[867]="*“Addhā kho, bhante, evaṃ sante tapojigucchā parisuddhā hoti no aparisuddhā, aggappattā ca sārappattā cā”ti.**“Clearly, sir, it is purified. It has reached the peak and the pith.”*";
P_HTM[868]="*“Ettāvatā kho, nigrodha, tapojigucchā aggappattā ca hoti sārappattā ca.**“Nigrodha, at this point the mortification in disgust of sin has reached the peak and the pith.*";
P_HTM[869]="*Iti kho, nigrodha, yaṃ maṃ tvaṃ avacāsi:**Nigrodha, remember you said this to me:*";
P_HTM[870]="*‘ko nāma so, bhante, bhagavato dhammo, yena bhagavā sāvake vineti, yena bhagavatā sāvakā vinītā assāsappattā paṭijānanti ajjhāsayaṃ ādibrahmacariyan’ti.**‘Sir, what teaching do you use to guide your disciples, through which they claim solace in the fundamental purpose of the spiritual life?’*";
P_HTM[871]="*Iti kho taṃ, nigrodha, ṭhānaṃ uttaritarañca paṇītatarañca, yenāhaṃ sāvake vinemi, yena mayā sāvakā vinītā assāsappattā paṭijānanti ajjhāsayaṃ ādibrahmacariyan”ti.**Well, there is something better and finer than this. That’s what I use to guide my disciples, through which they claim solace in the fundamental purpose of the spiritual life.”*";
P_HTM[872]="*Evaṃ vutte, te paribbājakā unnādino uccāsaddamahāsaddā ahesuṃ:**When he said this, those wanderers made an uproar,*";
P_HTM[873]="*“ettha mayaṃ anassāma sācariyakā, na mayaṃ ito bhiyyo uttaritaraṃ pajānāmā”ti.**“In that case, we’re lost, and so is our tradition! We don’t know anything better or finer than that!”*";
P_HTM[874]="*4. Nigrodhassapajjhāyana**4. Nigrodha Feels Depressed*";
P_HTM[875]="*Yadā aññāsi sandhāno gahapati:**Then the householder Sandhāna realized,*";
P_HTM[876]="*“aññadatthu kho dānime aññatitthiyā paribbājakā bhagavato bhāsitaṃ sussūsanti, sotaṃ odahanti, aññācittaṃ upaṭṭhāpentī”ti.**“Obviously, now these wanderers want to listen to what the Buddha says. They’re paying attention and applying their minds to understand!”*";
P_HTM[877]="*Atha nigrodhaṃ paribbājakaṃ etadavoca:**So he said to the wanderer Nigrodha,*";
P_HTM[878]="*“iti kho, bhante nigrodha, yaṃ maṃ tvaṃ avacāsi:**“Nigrodha, remember you said this to me:*";
P_HTM[879]="*‘yagghe, gahapati, jāneyyāsi, kena samaṇo gotamo saddhiṃ sallapati, kena sākacchaṃ samāpajjati, kena paññāveyyattiyaṃ samāpajjati,**‘Surely, householder, you should know better! With whom does the ascetic Gotama converse? With whom does he engage in discussion? With whom does he achieve lucidity of wisdom?*";
P_HTM[880]="*suññāgārahatā samaṇassa gotamassa paññā, aparisāvacaro samaṇo gotamo nālaṃ sallāpāya, so antamantāneva sevati;**Staying in empty huts has destroyed the ascetic Gotama’s wisdom. Not frequenting assemblies, he is unable to hold a discussion. He just lurks on the periphery.*";
P_HTM[881]="*seyyathāpi nāma gokāṇā pariyantacārinī antamantāneva sevati.**He’s just like the nilgai antelope, circling around and lurking on the periphery.*";
P_HTM[882]="*Evameva suññāgārahatā samaṇassa gotamassa paññā, aparisāvacaro samaṇo gotamo nālaṃ sallāpāya; so antamantāneva sevati;* **";
P_HTM[883]="*iṅgha, gahapati, samaṇo gotamo imaṃ parisaṃ āgaccheyya, ekapañheneva naṃ saṃsādeyyāma, tucchakumbhīva naṃ maññe orodheyyāmā’ti.**Please, householder, let the ascetic Gotama come to this assembly. I’ll sink him with just one question! I’ll roll him over and wrap him up like a hollow pot!’*";
P_HTM[884]="*Ayaṃ kho so, bhante, bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho idhānuppatto, aparisāvacaraṃ pana naṃ karotha, gokāṇaṃ pariyantacāriniṃ karotha, ekapañheneva naṃ saṃsādetha, tucchakumbhīva naṃ orodhethā”ti.**Now the Blessed One, perfected and fully awakened, has arrived here. Why don’t you send him out of the assembly to the periphery like a nilgai antelope? Why don’t you sink him with just one question? Why don’t you roll him over and wrap him up like a hollow pot?”*";
P_HTM[885]="*Evaṃ vutte, nigrodho paribbājako tuṇhībhūto maṅkubhūto pattakkhandho adhomukho pajjhāyanto appaṭibhāno nisīdi.**When he said this, Nigrodha sat silent, embarrassed, shoulders drooping, downcast, depressed, with nothing to say.*";
P_HTM[886]="*Atha kho bhagavā nigrodhaṃ paribbājakaṃ tuṇhībhūtaṃ maṅkubhūtaṃ pattakkhandhaṃ adhomukhaṃ pajjhāyantaṃ appaṭibhānaṃ viditvā nigrodhaṃ paribbājakaṃ etadavoca:**Knowing this, the Buddha said to him,*";
P_HTM[887]="*“saccaṃ kira, nigrodha, bhāsitā te esā vācā”ti?**“Is it really true, Nigrodha—are those your words?”*";
P_HTM[888]="*“Saccaṃ, bhante, bhāsitā me esā vācā, yathābālena yathāmūḷhena yathāakusalenā”ti.**“It’s true, sir, those are my words. It was foolish, stupid, and unskillful of me.”*";
P_HTM[889]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, nigrodha.**“What do you think, Nigrodha?*";
P_HTM[890]="*Kinti te sutaṃ paribbājakānaṃ vuḍḍhānaṃ mahallakānaṃ ācariyapācariyānaṃ bhāsamānānaṃ:**Have you heard that wanderers of the past who were elderly and senior, the teachers of teachers, said that*";
P_HTM[891]="*‘ye te ahesuṃ atītamaddhānaṃ arahanto sammāsambuddhā, evaṃ su te bhagavanto saṅgamma samāgamma unnādino uccāsaddamahāsaddā anekavihitaṃ tiracchānakathaṃ anuyuttā viharanti.**when the perfected ones, the fully awakened Buddhas of the past came together, they made an uproar, a dreadful racket as they sat and talked about all kinds of unworthy topics,*";
P_HTM[892]="*Seyyathidaṃ—rājakathaṃ corakathaṃ … pe … itibhavābhavakathaṃ iti vā.* **";
P_HTM[893]="*Seyyathāpi tvaṃ etarahi sācariyako.**like you do in your tradition these days?*";
P_HTM[894]="*Udāhu, evaṃ su te bhagavanto araññavanapatthāni pantāni senāsanāni paṭisevanti appasaddāni appanigghosāni vijanavātāni manussarāhasseyyakāni paṭisallānasāruppāni, seyyathāpāhaṃ etarahī’”ti.**Or did they say that the Buddhas frequented remote lodgings in the wilderness and the forest that are quiet and still, far from the madding crowd, remote from human settlements, and fit for retreat, like I do these days?”*";
P_HTM[895]="*“Sutaṃ metaṃ, bhante. Paribbājakānaṃ vuḍḍhānaṃ mahallakānaṃ ācariyapācariyānaṃ bhāsamānānaṃ:**“I have heard that wanderers of the past who were elderly and senior, said that*";
P_HTM[896]="*‘ye te ahesuṃ atītamaddhānaṃ arahanto sammāsambuddhā, na evaṃ su te bhagavanto saṅgamma samāgamma unnādino uccāsaddamahāsaddā anekavihitaṃ tiracchānakathaṃ anuyuttā viharanti.**when the perfected ones, the fully awakened Buddhas of the past came together, they didn’t make an uproar,*";
P_HTM[897]="*Seyyathidaṃ—rājakathaṃ corakathaṃ … pe … itibhavābhavakathaṃ iti vā,* **";
P_HTM[898]="*seyyathāpāhaṃ etarahi sācariyako.**like I do in my tradition these days.*";
P_HTM[899]="*Evaṃ su te bhagavanto araññavanapatthāni pantāni senāsanāni paṭisevanti appasaddāni appanigghosāni vijanavātāni manussarāhasseyyakāni paṭisallānasāruppāni, seyyathāpi bhagavā etarahī’”ti.**They said that the Buddhas of the past frequented remote lodgings in the wilderness, like the Buddha does these days.”*";
P_HTM[900]="*“Tassa te, nigrodha, viññussa sato mahallakassa na etadahosi:**“Nigrodha, you are a sensible and mature man. Did it not occur to you:*";
P_HTM[901]="*‘buddho so bhagavā bodhāya dhammaṃ deseti, danto so bhagavā damathāya dhammaṃ deseti, santo so bhagavā samathāya dhammaṃ deseti, tiṇṇo so bhagavā taraṇāya dhammaṃ deseti, parinibbuto so bhagavā parinibbānāya dhammaṃ desetī’”ti?**‘The Blessed One is awakened, tamed, serene, crossed over, and extinguished. And he teaches Dhamma for awakening, taming, serenity, crossing over, and extinguishment’?”*";
P_HTM[902]="*5. Brahmacariyapariyosānasacchikiriyā**5. The Culmination of the Spiritual Path*";
P_HTM[903]="*Evaṃ vutte, nigrodho paribbājako bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Nigrodha said,*";
P_HTM[904]="*“accayo maṃ, bhante, accagamā yathābālaṃ yathāmūḷhaṃ yathāakusalaṃ, yvāhaṃ evaṃ bhagavantaṃ avacāsiṃ.**“I have made a mistake, sir. It was foolish, stupid, and unskillful of me to speak in that way.*";
P_HTM[905]="*Tassa me, bhante, bhagavā accayaṃ accayato paṭiggaṇhātu āyatiṃ saṃvarāyā”ti.**Please, sir, accept my mistake for what it is, so I will restrain myself in future.”*";
P_HTM[906]="*“Taggha tvaṃ, nigrodha, accayo accagamā yathābālaṃ yathāmūḷhaṃ yathāakusalaṃ, yo maṃ tvaṃ evaṃ avacāsi.**“Indeed, Nigrodha, you made a mistake. It was foolish, stupid, and unskillful of you to speak in that way.*";
P_HTM[907]="*Yato ca kho tvaṃ, nigrodha, accayaṃ accayato disvā yathādhammaṃ paṭikarosi, taṃ te mayaṃ paṭiggaṇhāma.**But since you have recognized your mistake for what it is, and have dealt with it properly, I accept it.*";
P_HTM[908]="*Vuddhi hesā, nigrodha, ariyassa vinaye, yo accayaṃ accayato disvā yathādhammaṃ paṭikaroti āyatiṃ saṃvaraṃ āpajjati.**For it is growth in the training of the noble one to recognize a mistake for what it is, deal with it properly, and commit to restraint in the future.*";
P_HTM[909]="*Ahaṃ kho pana, nigrodha, evaṃ vadāmi:**Nigrodha, this is what I say:*";
P_HTM[910]="*‘Etu viññū puriso asaṭho amāyāvī ujujātiko, ahamanusāsāmi ahaṃ dhammaṃ desemi.**Let a sensible person come—neither devious nor deceitful, a person of integrity. I teach and instruct them.*";
P_HTM[911]="*Yathānusiṭṭhaṃ tathā paṭipajjamāno—yassatthāya kulaputtā sammadeva agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajanti, tadanuttaraṃ—brahmacariyapariyosānaṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharissati sattavassāni.**By practicing as instructed they will realize the supreme end of the spiritual path in this very life, in seven years. They will live having achieved with their own insight the goal for which gentlemen rightly go forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[912]="*Tiṭṭhantu, nigrodha, satta vassāni.**Let alone seven years.*";
P_HTM[913]="*Etu viññū puriso asaṭho amāyāvī ujujātiko, ahamanusāsāmi ahaṃ dhammaṃ desemi.**Let a sensible person come—neither devious nor deceitful, a person of integrity. I teach and instruct them.*";
P_HTM[914]="*Yathānusiṭṭhaṃ tathā paṭipajjamāno—yassatthāya kulaputtā sammadeva agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajanti, tadanuttaraṃ—brahmacariyapariyosānaṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharissati cha vassāni.**By practicing as instructed they will realize the supreme end of the spiritual path in this very life, in six years …*";
P_HTM[915]="*Pañca vassāni …**five years …*";
P_HTM[916]="*cattāri vassāni …**four years …*";
P_HTM[917]="*tīṇi vassāni …**three years …*";
P_HTM[918]="*dve vassāni …**two years …*";
P_HTM[919]="*ekaṃ vassaṃ.**one year …*";
P_HTM[920]="*Tiṭṭhatu, nigrodha, ekaṃ vassaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[921]="*Etu viññū puriso asaṭho amāyāvī ujujātiko ahamanusāsāmi ahaṃ dhammaṃ desemi.* **";
P_HTM[922]="*Yathānusiṭṭhaṃ tathā paṭipajjamāno—yassatthāya kulaputtā sammadeva agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajanti, tadanuttaraṃ—brahmacariyapariyosānaṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharissati satta māsāni.**seven months …*";
P_HTM[923]="*Tiṭṭhantu, nigrodha, satta māsāni …* **";
P_HTM[924]="*cha māsāni …**six months …*";
P_HTM[925]="*pañca māsāni …**five months …*";
P_HTM[926]="*cattāri māsāni …**four months …*";
P_HTM[927]="*tīṇi māsāni …**three months …*";
P_HTM[928]="*dve māsāni …**two months …*";
P_HTM[929]="*ekaṃ māsaṃ …**one month …*";
P_HTM[930]="*aḍḍhamāsaṃ.**a fortnight.*";
P_HTM[931]="*Tiṭṭhatu, nigrodha, aḍḍhamāso.**Let alone a fortnight.*";
P_HTM[932]="*Etu viññū puriso asaṭho amāyāvī ujujātiko, ahamanusāsāmi ahaṃ dhammaṃ desemi.**Let a sensible person come—neither devious nor deceitful, a person of integrity. I teach and instruct them.*";
P_HTM[933]="*Yathānusiṭṭhaṃ tathā paṭipajjamāno—yassatthāya kulaputtā sammadeva agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajanti, tadanuttaraṃ—brahmacariyapariyosānaṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharissati sattāhaṃ’.**By practicing as instructed they will realize the supreme end of the spiritual path in this very life, in seven days.*";
P_HTM[934]="*6. Paribbājakānaṃpajjhāyana**6. The Wanderers Feel Depressed*";
P_HTM[935]="*Siyā kho pana te, nigrodha, evamassa:**Nigrodha, you might think,*";
P_HTM[936]="*‘antevāsikamyatā no samaṇo gotamo evamāhā’ti.**‘The ascetic Gotama speaks like this because he wants pupils.’*";
P_HTM[937]="*Na kho panetaṃ, nigrodha, evaṃ daṭṭhabbaṃ.**But you should not see it like this.*";
P_HTM[938]="*Yo eva vo ācariyo, so eva vo ācariyo hotu.**Let your teacher remain your teacher.*";
P_HTM[939]="*Siyā kho pana te, nigrodha, evamassa:**You might think,*";
P_HTM[940]="*‘uddesā no cāvetukāmo samaṇo gotamo evamāhā’ti.**‘The ascetic Gotama speaks like this because he wants us to give up our recitation.’*";
P_HTM[941]="*Na kho panetaṃ, nigrodha, evaṃ daṭṭhabbaṃ.**But you should not see it like this.*";
P_HTM[942]="*Yo eva vo uddeso so eva vo uddeso hotu.**Let your recitation remain as it is.*";
P_HTM[943]="*Siyā kho pana te, nigrodha, evamassa:**You might think,*";
P_HTM[944]="*‘ājīvā no cāvetukāmo samaṇo gotamo evamāhā’ti.**‘The ascetic Gotama speaks like this because he wants us to give up our livelihood.’*";
P_HTM[945]="*Na kho panetaṃ, nigrodha, evaṃ daṭṭhabbaṃ.**But you should not see it like this.*";
P_HTM[946]="*Yo eva vo ājīvo, so eva vo ājīvo hotu.**Let your livelihood remain as it is.*";
P_HTM[947]="*Siyā kho pana te, nigrodha, evamassa:**You might think,*";
P_HTM[948]="*‘ye no dhammā akusalā akusalasaṅkhātā sācariyakānaṃ, tesu patiṭṭhāpetukāmo samaṇo gotamo evamāhā’ti.**‘The ascetic Gotama speaks like this because he wants us to start doing things that are unskillful and considered unskillful in our tradition.’*";
P_HTM[949]="*Na kho panetaṃ, nigrodha, evaṃ daṭṭhabbaṃ.**But you should not see it like this.*";
P_HTM[950]="*Akusalā ceva vo te dhammā hontu akusalasaṅkhātā ca sācariyakānaṃ.**Let those things that are unskillful and considered unskillful in your tradition remain as they are.*";
P_HTM[951]="*Siyā kho pana te, nigrodha, evamassa:**You might think,*";
P_HTM[952]="*‘ye no dhammā kusalā kusalasaṅkhātā sācariyakānaṃ, tehi vivecetukāmo samaṇo gotamo evamāhā’ti.**‘The ascetic Gotama speaks like this because he wants us to stop doing things that are skillful and considered skillful in our tradition.’*";
P_HTM[953]="*Na kho panetaṃ, nigrodha, evaṃ daṭṭhabbaṃ.**But you should not see it like this.*";
P_HTM[954]="*Kusalā ceva vo te dhammā hontu kusalasaṅkhātā ca sācariyakānaṃ.**Let those things that are skillful and considered skillful in your tradition remain as they are.*";
P_HTM[955]="*Iti khvāhaṃ, nigrodha, neva antevāsikamyatā evaṃ vadāmi, napi uddesā cāvetukāmo evaṃ vadāmi, napi ājīvā cāvetukāmo evaṃ vadāmi, napi ye vo dhammā akusalā akusalasaṅkhātā sācariyakānaṃ, tesu patiṭṭhāpetukāmo evaṃ vadāmi, napi ye vo dhammā kusalā kusalasaṅkhātā sācariyakānaṃ, tehi vivecetukāmo evaṃ vadāmi.**I do not speak for any of these reasons.*";
P_HTM[956]="*Santi ca kho, nigrodha, akusalā dhammā appahīnā saṃkilesikā ponobbhavikā sadarā dukkhavipākā āyatiṃ jātijarāmaraṇiyā, yesāhaṃ pahānāya dhammaṃ desemi.**Nigrodha, there are things that are unskillful, corrupted, leading to future lives, hurtful, resulting in suffering and future rebirth, old age, and death. I teach Dhamma so that those things may be given up.*";
P_HTM[957]="*Yathāpaṭipannānaṃ vo saṃkilesikā dhammā pahīyissanti, vodānīyā dhammā abhivaḍḍhissanti, paññāpāripūriṃ vepullattañca diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharissathā”ti.**When you practice accordingly, corrupting qualities will be given up in you and cleansing qualities will grow. You’ll enter and remain in the fullness and abundance of wisdom, having realized it with your own insight in this very life.”*";
P_HTM[958]="*Evaṃ vutte, te paribbājakā tuṇhībhūtā maṅkubhūtā pattakkhandhā adhomukhā pajjhāyantā appaṭibhānā nisīdiṃsu yathā taṃ mārena pariyuṭṭhitacittā.**When this was said, those wanderers sat silent, dismayed, shoulders drooping, downcast, depressed, with nothing to say, as if their minds were possessed by Māra.*";
P_HTM[959]="*Atha kho bhagavato etadahosi:**Then the Buddha thought,*";
P_HTM[960]="*“sabbepime moghapurisā phuṭṭhā pāpimatā.**“All these foolish people have been touched by the Wicked One!*";
P_HTM[961]="*Yatra hi nāma ekassapi na evaṃ bhavissati:**For not even a single one thinks,*";
P_HTM[962]="*‘handa mayaṃ aññāṇatthampi samaṇe gotame brahmacariyaṃ carāma, kiṃ karissati sattāho’”ti?**‘Come, let us lead the spiritual life under the ascetic Gotama for the sake of enlightenment—for what do seven days matter?’*";
P_HTM[963]="*Atha kho bhagavā udumbarikāya paribbājakārāme sīhanādaṃ naditvā vehāsaṃ abbhuggantvā gijjhakūṭe pabbate paccupaṭṭhāsi.**Then the Buddha, having roared his lion’s roar in the lady Udumbarikā’s monastery for wanderers, rose into the air and landed on Vulture’s Peak.*";
P_HTM[964]="*Sandhāno pana gahapati tāvadeva rājagahaṃ pāvisīti.**Meanwhile, the householder Sandhāna just went back to Rājagaha.*";
P_HTM[965]="*Udumbarikasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[966]="*26. Cakkavattisutta  - The Wheel-Turning Monarch * **";
P_HTM[967]="*1. Attadīpasaraṇatā**1. Taking Refuge in Oneself*";
P_HTM[968]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[969]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā magadhesu viharati mātulāyaṃ.**At one time the Buddha was staying in the land of the Magadhans at Mātulā.*";
P_HTM[970]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[971]="*“bhikkhavo”ti.**“Mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[972]="*“Bhaddante”ti te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Venerable sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[973]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[974]="*“Attadīpā, bhikkhave, viharatha attasaraṇā anaññasaraṇā, dhammadīpā dhammasaraṇā anaññasaraṇā.**“Mendicants, be your own island, your own refuge, with no other refuge. Let the teaching be your island and your refuge, with no other refuge.*";
P_HTM[975]="*Kathañca pana, bhikkhave, bhikkhu attadīpo viharati attasaraṇo anaññasaraṇo, dhammadīpo dhammasaraṇo anaññasaraṇo?**And how does a mendicant do this?*";
P_HTM[976]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**They meditate observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[977]="*Vedanāsu vedanānupassī … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[978]="*citte cittānupassī … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[979]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[980]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu attadīpo viharati attasaraṇo anaññasaraṇo, dhammadīpo dhammasaraṇo anaññasaraṇo.**That’s how a mendicant is their own island, their own refuge, with no other refuge. That’s how they let the teaching be their island and their refuge, with no other refuge.*";
P_HTM[981]="*Gocare, bhikkhave, caratha sake pettike visaye.**You should roam inside your own territory, the domain of your fathers.*";
P_HTM[982]="*Gocare, bhikkhave, carataṃ sake pettike visaye na lacchati māro otāraṃ, na lacchati māro ārammaṇaṃ.**If you roam inside your own territory, the domain of your fathers, Māra won’t catch you or get hold of you.*";
P_HTM[983]="*Kusalānaṃ, bhikkhave, dhammānaṃ samādānahetu evamidaṃ puññaṃ pavaḍḍhati.**It is due to undertaking skillful qualities that this merit grows.*";
P_HTM[984]="*2. Daḷhanemicakkavattirājā**2. King Daḷhanemi*";
P_HTM[985]="*Bhūtapubbaṃ, bhikkhave, rājā daḷhanemi nāma ahosi cakkavattī dhammiko dhammarājā cāturanto vijitāvī janapadatthāvariyappatto sattaratanasamannāgato.**Once upon a time, mendicants, there was a king named Daḷhanemi who was a wheel-turning monarch, a just and principled king. His dominion extended to all four sides, he achieved stability in the country, and he possessed the seven treasures.*";
P_HTM[986]="*Tassimāni satta ratanāni ahesuṃ seyyathidaṃ—**He had the following seven treasures:*";
P_HTM[987]="*cakkaratanaṃ hatthiratanaṃ assaratanaṃ maṇiratanaṃ itthiratanaṃ gahapatiratanaṃ pariṇāyakaratanameva sattamaṃ.**the wheel, the elephant, the horse, the jewel, the woman, the treasurer, and the counselor as the seventh treasure.*";
P_HTM[988]="*Parosahassaṃ kho panassa puttā ahesuṃ sūrā vīraṅgarūpā parasenappamaddanā.**He had over a thousand sons who were valiant and heroic, crushing the armies of his enemies.*";
P_HTM[989]="*So imaṃ pathaviṃ sāgarapariyantaṃ adaṇḍena asatthena dhammena abhivijiya ajjhāvasi.**After conquering this land girt by sea, he reigned by principle, without rod or sword.*";
P_HTM[990]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, rājā daḷhanemi bahunnaṃ vassānaṃ bahunnaṃ vassasatānaṃ bahunnaṃ vassasahassānaṃ accayena aññataraṃ purisaṃ āmantesi:**Then, after many years, many hundred years, many thousand years had passed, King Daḷhanemi addressed one of his men,*";
P_HTM[991]="*‘yadā tvaṃ, ambho purisa, passeyyāsi dibbaṃ cakkaratanaṃ osakkitaṃ ṭhānā cutaṃ, atha me āroceyyāsī’ti.**‘My good man, when you see that the heavenly wheel-treasure has receded back from its place, please tell me.’*";
P_HTM[992]="*‘Evaṃ, devā’ti kho, bhikkhave, so puriso rañño daḷhanemissa paccassosi.**‘Yes, Your Majesty,’ replied that man.*";
P_HTM[993]="*Addasā kho, bhikkhave, so puriso bahunnaṃ vassānaṃ bahunnaṃ vassasatānaṃ bahunnaṃ vassasahassānaṃ accayena dibbaṃ cakkaratanaṃ osakkitaṃ ṭhānā cutaṃ, disvāna yena rājā daḷhanemi tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā rājānaṃ daḷhanemiṃ etadavoca:**After many thousand years had passed, that man saw that the heavenly wheel-treasure had receded back from its place. So he went to King Daḷhanemi and said,*";
P_HTM[994]="*‘yagghe, deva, jāneyyāsi, dibbaṃ te cakkaratanaṃ osakkitaṃ ṭhānā cutan’ti.**‘Please sire, you should know that your heavenly wheel-treasure has receded back from its place.’*";
P_HTM[995]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, rājā daḷhanemi jeṭṭhaputtaṃ kumāraṃ āmantāpetvā etadavoca:**So the king summoned the crown prince and said,*";
P_HTM[996]="*‘dibbaṃ kira me, tāta kumāra, cakkaratanaṃ osakkitaṃ ṭhānā cutaṃ.**‘Dear prince, my heavenly wheel-treasure has receded back from its place.*";
P_HTM[997]="*Sutaṃ kho pana metaṃ—**I’ve heard that*";
P_HTM[998]="*yassa rañño cakkavattissa dibbaṃ cakkaratanaṃ osakkati ṭhānā cavati, na dāni tena raññā ciraṃ jīvitabbaṃ hotīti.**when this happens to a wheel-turning monarch, he does not have long to live.*";
P_HTM[999]="*Bhuttā kho pana me mānusakā kāmā, samayo dāni me dibbe kāme pariyesituṃ.**I have enjoyed human pleasures. Now it is time for me to seek heavenly pleasures.*";
P_HTM[1000]="*Ehi tvaṃ, tāta kumāra, imaṃ samuddapariyantaṃ pathaviṃ paṭipajja.**Come, dear prince, rule this land surrounded by ocean!*";
P_HTM[1001]="*Ahaṃ pana kesamassuṃ ohāretvā kāsāyāni vatthāni acchādetvā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajissāmī’ti.**I shall shave off my hair and beard, dress in ocher robes, and go forth from the lay life to homelessness.’*";
P_HTM[1002]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, rājā daḷhanemi jeṭṭhaputtaṃ kumāraṃ sādhukaṃ rajje samanusāsitvā kesamassuṃ ohāretvā kāsāyāni vatthāni acchādetvā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbaji.**And so, after carefully instructing the crown prince in kingship, King Daḷhanemi shaved off his hair and beard, dressed in ocher robes, and went forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[1003]="*Sattāhapabbajite kho pana, bhikkhave, rājisimhi dibbaṃ cakkaratanaṃ antaradhāyi.**Seven days later the heavenly wheel-treasure vanished.*";
P_HTM[1004]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, aññataro puriso yena rājā khattiyo muddhābhisitto tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā rājānaṃ khattiyaṃ muddhābhisittaṃ etadavoca:**Then a certain man approached the newly anointed aristocrat king and said,*";
P_HTM[1005]="*‘yagghe, deva, jāneyyāsi, dibbaṃ cakkaratanaṃ antarahitan’ti.**‘Please sire, you should know that the heavenly wheel-treasure has vanished.’*";
P_HTM[1006]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, rājā khattiyo muddhābhisitto dibbe cakkaratane antarahite anattamano ahosi, anattamanatañca paṭisaṃvedesi.**At that the king was unhappy and experienced unhappiness.*";
P_HTM[1007]="*So yena rājisi tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā rājisiṃ etadavoca:**He went to the royal sage and said,*";
P_HTM[1008]="*‘yagghe, deva, jāneyyāsi, dibbaṃ cakkaratanaṃ antarahitan’ti.**‘Please sire, you should know that the heavenly wheel-treasure has vanished.’*";
P_HTM[1009]="*Evaṃ vutte, bhikkhave, rājisi rājānaṃ khattiyaṃ muddhābhisittaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, the royal sage said to him,*";
P_HTM[1010]="*‘mā kho tvaṃ, tāta, dibbe cakkaratane antarahite anattamano ahosi, mā anattamanatañca paṭisaṃvedesi, na hi te, tāta, dibbaṃ cakkaratanaṃ pettikaṃ dāyajjaṃ.**‘Don’t be unhappy at the vanishing of the wheel-treasure. My dear, the wheel-treasure is not inherited from your father.*";
P_HTM[1011]="*Iṅgha tvaṃ, tāta, ariye cakkavattivatte vattāhi.**Come now, my dear, implement the noble duties of a wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[1012]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ vijjati, yaṃ te ariye cakkavattivatte vattamānassa tadahuposathe pannarase sīsaṃnhātassa uposathikassa uparipāsādavaragatassa dibbaṃ cakkaratanaṃ pātubhavissati sahassāraṃ sanemikaṃ sanābhikaṃ sabbākāraparipūran’ti.**If you do so, it’s possible that—on a fifteenth day sabbath, having bathed your head and gone upstairs in the stilt longhouse to observe the sabbath—the heavenly wheel-treasure will appear to you, with a thousand spokes, with rim and hub, complete in every detail.’*";
P_HTM[1013]="*2.1. Cakkavattiariyavatta**2.1. The Noble Duties of a Wheel-Turning Monarch*";
P_HTM[1014]="*‘Katamaṃ pana taṃ, deva, ariyaṃ cakkavattivattan’ti?**‘But sire, what are the noble duties of a wheel-turning monarch?’*";
P_HTM[1015]="*‘Tena hi tvaṃ, tāta, dhammaṃyeva nissāya dhammaṃ sakkaronto dhammaṃ garuṃ karonto dhammaṃ mānento dhammaṃ pūjento dhammaṃ apacāyamāno dhammaddhajo dhammaketu dhammādhipateyyo dhammikaṃ rakkhāvaraṇaguttiṃ saṃvidahassu antojanasmiṃ balakāyasmiṃ khattiyesu anuyantesu brāhmaṇagahapatikesu negamajānapadesu samaṇabrāhmaṇesu migapakkhīsu.**‘Well then, my dear, relying only on principle—honoring, respecting, and venerating principle, having principle as your flag, banner, and authority—provide just protection and security for your court, troops, aristocrats, vassals, brahmins and householders, people of town and country, ascetics and brahmins, beasts and birds.*";
P_HTM[1016]="*Mā ca te, tāta, vijite adhammakāro pavattittha.**Do not let injustice prevail in the realm.*";
P_HTM[1017]="*Ye ca te, tāta, vijite adhanā assu, tesañca dhanamanuppadeyyāsi.**Pay money to the penniless in the realm.*";
P_HTM[1018]="*Ye ca te, tāta, vijite samaṇabrāhmaṇā madappamādā paṭiviratā khantisoracce niviṭṭhā ekamattānaṃ damenti, ekamattānaṃ samenti, ekamattānaṃ parinibbāpenti, te kālena kālaṃ upasaṅkamitvā paripuccheyyāsi pariggaṇheyyāsi:**And there are ascetics and brahmins in the realm who avoid intoxication and negligence, are settled in patience and gentleness, and who tame, calm, and extinguish themselves. From time to time you should go up to them and ask:*";
P_HTM[1019]="*“kiṃ, bhante, kusalaṃ, kiṃ akusalaṃ, kiṃ sāvajjaṃ, kiṃ anavajjaṃ, kiṃ sevitabbaṃ, kiṃ na sevitabbaṃ, kiṃ me karīyamānaṃ dīgharattaṃ ahitāya dukkhāya assa, kiṃ vā pana me karīyamānaṃ dīgharattaṃ hitāya sukhāya assā”ti?**“Sirs, what is skillful? What is unskillful? What is blameworthy? What is blameless? What should be cultivated? What should not be cultivated? Doing what leads to my lasting harm and suffering? Doing what leads to my lasting welfare and happiness?”*";
P_HTM[1020]="*Tesaṃ sutvā yaṃ akusalaṃ taṃ abhinivajjeyyāsi, yaṃ kusalaṃ taṃ samādāya vatteyyāsi.**Having heard them, you should reject what is unskillful and undertake and follow what is skillful.*";
P_HTM[1021]="*Idaṃ kho, tāta, taṃ ariyaṃ cakkavattivattan’ti.**These are the noble duties of a wheel-turning monarch.’*";
P_HTM[1022]="*2.2. Cakkaratanapātubhāva**2.2. The Wheel-Treasure Appears*";
P_HTM[1023]="*‘Evaṃ, devā’ti kho, bhikkhave, rājā khattiyo muddhābhisitto rājisissa paṭissutvā ariye cakkavattivatte vatti.**‘Yes, Your Majesty,’ replied the new king to the royal sage. And he implemented the noble duties of a wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[1024]="*Tassa ariye cakkavattivatte vattamānassa tadahuposathe pannarase sīsaṃnhātassa uposathikassa uparipāsādavaragatassa**While he was implementing them, on a fifteenth day sabbath, he had bathed his head and gone upstairs in the stilt longhouse to observe the sabbath.*";
P_HTM[1025]="*dibbaṃ cakkaratanaṃ pāturahosi sahassāraṃ sanemikaṃ sanābhikaṃ sabbākāraparipūraṃ.**And the heavenly wheel-treasure appeared to him, with a thousand spokes, with rim and hub, complete in every detail.*";
P_HTM[1026]="*Disvāna rañño khattiyassa muddhābhisittassa etadahosi:**Seeing this, the king thought,*";
P_HTM[1027]="*‘sutaṃ kho pana metaṃ—yassa rañño khattiyassa muddhābhisittassa tadahuposathe pannarase sīsaṃnhātassa uposathikassa uparipāsādavaragatassa dibbaṃ cakkaratanaṃ pātubhavati sahassāraṃ sanemikaṃ sanābhikaṃ sabbākāraparipūraṃ, so hoti rājā cakkavattīti.**‘I have heard that when the heavenly wheel-treasure appears to a king in this way, he becomes a wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[1028]="*Assaṃ nu kho ahaṃ rājā cakkavattī’ti.**Am I then a wheel-turning monarch?’*";
P_HTM[1029]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, rājā khattiyo muddhābhisitto uṭṭhāyāsanā ekaṃsaṃ uttarāsaṅgaṃ karitvā vāmena hatthena bhiṅkāraṃ gahetvā dakkhiṇena hatthena cakkaratanaṃ abbhukkiri:**Then the anointed king, rising from his seat and arranging his robe over one shoulder, took a ceremonial vase in his left hand and besprinkled the wheel-treasure with his right hand, saying,*";
P_HTM[1030]="*‘pavattatu bhavaṃ cakkaratanaṃ, abhivijinātu bhavaṃ cakkaratanan’ti.**‘Roll forth, O wheel-treasure! Triumph, O wheel-treasure!’*";
P_HTM[1031]="*Atha kho taṃ, bhikkhave, cakkaratanaṃ puratthimaṃ disaṃ pavatti, anvadeva rājā cakkavattī saddhiṃ caturaṅginiyā senāya. Yasmiṃ kho pana, bhikkhave, padese cakkaratanaṃ patiṭṭhāsi, tattha rājā cakkavattī vāsaṃ upagacchi saddhiṃ caturaṅginiyā senāya.**Then the wheel-treasure rolled towards the east. And the king followed it together with his army of four divisions. In whatever place the wheel-treasure stood still, there the king came to stay together with his army.*";
P_HTM[1032]="*Ye kho pana, bhikkhave, puratthimāya disāya paṭirājāno, te rājānaṃ cakkavattiṃ upasaṅkamitvā evamāhaṃsu:**And any opposing rulers of the eastern quarter came to the wheel-turning monarch and said,*";
P_HTM[1033]="*‘ehi kho, mahārāja, svāgataṃ te mahārāja, sakaṃ te, mahārāja, anusāsa, mahārājā’ti.**‘Come, great king! Welcome, great king! We are yours, great king, instruct us.’*";
P_HTM[1034]="*Rājā cakkavattī evamāha:**The wheel-turning monarch said,*";
P_HTM[1035]="*‘pāṇo na hantabbo, adinnaṃ nādātabbaṃ, kāmesumicchā na caritabbā, musā na bhāsitabbā, majjaṃ na pātabbaṃ, yathābhuttañca bhuñjathā’ti.**‘Do not kill living creatures. Do not steal. Do not commit sexual misconduct. Do not lie. Do not drink alcohol. Maintain the current level of taxation.’*";
P_HTM[1036]="*Ye kho pana, bhikkhave, puratthimāya disāya paṭirājāno, te rañño cakkavattissa anuyantā ahesuṃ.**And so the opposing rulers of the eastern quarter became his vassals.*";
P_HTM[1037]="*Atha kho taṃ, bhikkhave, cakkaratanaṃ puratthimaṃ samuddaṃ ajjhogāhetvā paccuttaritvā dakkhiṇaṃ disaṃ pavatti … pe …**Then the wheel-treasure, having plunged into the eastern ocean and emerged again, rolled towards the south. …*";
P_HTM[1038]="*dakkhiṇaṃ samuddaṃ ajjhogāhetvā paccuttaritvā pacchimaṃ disaṃ pavatti, anvadeva rājā cakkavattī saddhiṃ caturaṅginiyā senāya.**Having plunged into the southern ocean and emerged again, it rolled towards the west. …*";
P_HTM[1039]="*Yasmiṃ kho pana, bhikkhave, padese cakkaratanaṃ patiṭṭhāsi, tattha rājā cakkavattī vāsaṃ upagacchi saddhiṃ caturaṅginiyā senāya.* **";
P_HTM[1040]="*Ye kho pana, bhikkhave, pacchimāya disāya paṭirājāno, te rājānaṃ cakkavattiṃ upasaṅkamitvā evamāhaṃsu:* **";
P_HTM[1041]="*‘ehi kho, mahārāja, svāgataṃ te, mahārāja, sakaṃ te, mahārāja, anusāsa, mahārājā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1042]="*Rājā cakkavattī evamāha:* **";
P_HTM[1043]="*‘pāṇo na hantabbo, adinnaṃ nādātabbaṃ, kāmesumicchā na caritabbā, musā na bhāsitabbā, majjaṃ na pātabbaṃ, yathābhuttañca bhuñjathā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1044]="*Ye kho pana, bhikkhave, pacchimāya disāya paṭirājāno, te rañño cakkavattissa anuyantā ahesuṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1045]="*Atha kho taṃ, bhikkhave, cakkaratanaṃ pacchimaṃ samuddaṃ ajjhogāhetvā paccuttaritvā uttaraṃ disaṃ pavatti, anvadeva rājā cakkavattī saddhiṃ caturaṅginiyā senāya.**Having plunged into the western ocean and emerged again, it rolled towards the north, followed by the king together with his army of four divisions.*";
P_HTM[1046]="*Yasmiṃ kho pana, bhikkhave, padese cakkaratanaṃ patiṭṭhāsi, tattha rājā cakkavattī vāsaṃ upagacchi saddhiṃ caturaṅginiyā senāya.**In whatever place the wheel-treasure stood still, there the king came to stay together with his army.*";
P_HTM[1047]="*Ye kho pana, bhikkhave, uttarāya disāya paṭirājāno, te rājānaṃ cakkavattiṃ upasaṅkamitvā evamāhaṃsu:**And any opposing rulers of the northern quarter came to the wheel-turning monarch and said,*";
P_HTM[1048]="*‘ehi kho, mahārāja, svāgataṃ te, mahārāja, sakaṃ te, mahārāja, anusāsa, mahārājā’ti.**‘Come, great king! Welcome, great king! We are yours, great king, instruct us.’*";
P_HTM[1049]="*Rājā cakkavattī evamāha:**The wheel-turning monarch said,*";
P_HTM[1050]="*‘pāṇo na hantabbo, adinnaṃ nādātabbaṃ, kāmesumicchā na caritabbā, musā na bhāsitabbā, majjaṃ na pātabbaṃ, yathābhuttañca bhuñjathā’ti.**‘Do not kill living creatures. Do not steal. Do not commit sexual misconduct. Do not lie. Do not drink alcohol. Maintain the current level of taxation.’*";
P_HTM[1051]="*Ye kho pana, bhikkhave, uttarāya disāya paṭirājāno, te rañño cakkavattissa anuyantā ahesuṃ.**And so the rulers of the northern quarter became his vassals.*";
P_HTM[1052]="*Atha kho taṃ, bhikkhave, cakkaratanaṃ samuddapariyantaṃ pathaviṃ abhivijinitvā tameva rājadhāniṃ paccāgantvā rañño cakkavattissa antepuradvāre atthakaraṇapamukhe akkhāhataṃ maññe aṭṭhāsi rañño cakkavattissa antepuraṃ upasobhayamānaṃ.**And then the wheel-treasure, having triumphed over this land surrounded by ocean, returned to the royal capital. There it stood still by the gate to the royal compound at the High Court as if fixed to an axle, illuminating the royal compound.*";
P_HTM[1053]="*3. Dutiyādicakkavattikathā**3. On Subsequent Wheel-Turning Monarchs*";
P_HTM[1054]="*Dutiyopi kho, bhikkhave, rājā cakkavattī … pe …**And for a second time,*";
P_HTM[1055]="*tatiyopi kho, bhikkhave, rājā cakkavattī …**and a third,*";
P_HTM[1056]="*catutthopi kho, bhikkhave, rājā cakkavattī …**a fourth,*";
P_HTM[1057]="*pañcamopi kho, bhikkhave, rājā cakkavattī …**a fifth,*";
P_HTM[1058]="*chaṭṭhopi kho, bhikkhave, rājā cakkavattī …**a sixth,*";
P_HTM[1059]="*sattamopi kho, bhikkhave, rājā cakkavattī bahunnaṃ vassānaṃ bahunnaṃ vassasatānaṃ bahunnaṃ vassasahassānaṃ accayena aññataraṃ purisaṃ āmantesi:**and a seventh time, a wheel-turning monarch was established in exactly the same way. And after many years the seventh wheel-turning monarch went forth, handing the realm over to the crown prince.*";
P_HTM[1060]="*‘yadā tvaṃ, ambho purisa, passeyyāsi dibbaṃ cakkaratanaṃ osakkitaṃ ṭhānā cutaṃ, atha me āroceyyāsī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1061]="*‘Evaṃ, devā’ti kho, bhikkhave, so puriso rañño cakkavattissa paccassosi.* **";
P_HTM[1062]="*Addasā kho, bhikkhave, so puriso bahunnaṃ vassānaṃ bahunnaṃ vassasatānaṃ bahunnaṃ vassasahassānaṃ accayena dibbaṃ cakkaratanaṃ osakkitaṃ ṭhānā cutaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1063]="*Disvāna yena rājā cakkavattī tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā rājānaṃ cakkavattiṃ etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[1064]="*‘yagghe, deva, jāneyyāsi, dibbaṃ te cakkaratanaṃ osakkitaṃ ṭhānā cutan’ti?* **";
P_HTM[1065]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, rājā cakkavattī jeṭṭhaputtaṃ kumāraṃ āmantāpetvā etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[1066]="*‘dibbaṃ kira me, tāta kumāra, cakkaratanaṃ osakkitaṃ, ṭhānā cutaṃ, sutaṃ kho pana metaṃ—* **";
P_HTM[1067]="*yassa rañño cakkavattissa dibbaṃ cakkaratanaṃ osakkati, ṭhānā cavati, na dāni tena raññā ciraṃ jīvitabbaṃ hotīti.* **";
P_HTM[1068]="*Bhuttā kho pana me mānusakā kāmā, samayo dāni me dibbe kāme pariyesituṃ, ehi tvaṃ, tāta kumāra, imaṃ samuddapariyantaṃ pathaviṃ paṭipajja.* **";
P_HTM[1069]="*Ahaṃ pana kesamassuṃ ohāretvā kāsāyāni vatthāni acchādetvā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajissāmī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1070]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, rājā cakkavattī jeṭṭhaputtaṃ kumāraṃ sādhukaṃ rajje samanusāsitvā kesamassuṃ ohāretvā kāsāyāni vatthāni acchādetvā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbaji.* **";
P_HTM[1071]="*Sattāhapabbajite kho pana, bhikkhave, rājisimhi dibbaṃ cakkaratanaṃ antaradhāyi.**Seven days later the heavenly wheel-treasure vanished.*";
P_HTM[1072]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, aññataro puriso yena rājā khattiyo muddhābhisitto tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā rājānaṃ khattiyaṃ muddhābhisittaṃ etadavoca:**Then a certain man approached the newly anointed aristocrat king and said,*";
P_HTM[1073]="*‘yagghe, deva, jāneyyāsi, dibbaṃ cakkaratanaṃ antarahitan’ti?**‘Please sire, you should know that the heavenly wheel-treasure has vanished.’*";
P_HTM[1074]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, rājā khattiyo muddhābhisitto dibbe cakkaratane antarahite anattamano ahosi. Anattamanatañca paṭisaṃvedesi;**At that the king was unhappy and experienced unhappiness.*";
P_HTM[1075]="*no ca kho rājisiṃ upasaṅkamitvā ariyaṃ cakkavattivattaṃ pucchi.**But he didn’t go to the royal sage and ask about the noble duties of a wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[1076]="*So samateneva sudaṃ janapadaṃ pasāsati.**He just governed the country according to his own ideas.*";
P_HTM[1077]="*Tassa samatena janapadaṃ pasāsato pubbenāparaṃ janapadā na pabbanti, yathā taṃ pubbakānaṃ rājūnaṃ ariye cakkavattivatte vattamānānaṃ.**So governed, the nations did not prosper like before, as they had when former kings implemented the noble duties of a wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[1078]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, amaccā pārisajjā gaṇakamahāmattā anīkaṭṭhā dovārikā mantassājīvino sannipatitvā rājānaṃ khattiyaṃ muddhābhisittaṃ etadavocuṃ:**Then the ministers and counselors, the treasury officials, military officers, guardsmen, and advisers gathered and said to the king,*";
P_HTM[1079]="*‘na kho te, deva, samatena sudaṃ janapadaṃ pasāsato pubbenāparaṃ janapadā pabbanti, yathā taṃ pubbakānaṃ rājūnaṃ ariye cakkavattivatte vattamānānaṃ.**‘Sire, when governed according to your own ideas, the nations do not prosper like before, as they did when former kings implemented the noble duties of a wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[1080]="*Saṃvijjanti kho te, deva, vijite amaccā pārisajjā gaṇakamahāmattā anīkaṭṭhā dovārikā mantassājīvino mayañceva aññe ca ye mayaṃ ariyaṃ cakkavattivattaṃ dhārema.**In your realm are found ministers and counselors, treasury officials, military officers, guardsmen, and advisers—both ourselves and others—who remember the noble duties of a wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[1081]="*Iṅgha tvaṃ, deva, amhe ariyaṃ cakkavattivattaṃ puccha.**Please, Your Majesty, ask us about the noble duties of a wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[1082]="*Tassa te mayaṃ ariyaṃ cakkavattivattaṃ puṭṭhā byākarissāmā’ti.**We will answer you.’*";
P_HTM[1083]="*4. Āyuvaṇṇādiparihānikathā**4. On the Period of Decline*";
P_HTM[1084]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, rājā khattiyo muddhābhisitto amacce pārisajje gaṇakamahāmatte anīkaṭṭhe dovārike mantassājīvino sannipātetvā ariyaṃ cakkavattivattaṃ pucchi.**So the anointed king asked the assembled ministers and counselors, treasury officials, military officers, guardsmen, and advisers about the noble duties of a wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[1085]="*Tassa te ariyaṃ cakkavattivattaṃ puṭṭhā byākariṃsu.**And they answered him.*";
P_HTM[1086]="*Tesaṃ sutvā dhammikañhi kho rakkhāvaraṇaguttiṃ saṃvidahi, no ca kho adhanānaṃ dhanamanuppadāsi.**But after listening to them, he didn’t provide just protection and security. Nor did he pay money to the penniless in the realm.*";
P_HTM[1087]="*Adhanānaṃ dhane ananuppadiyamāne dāliddiyaṃ vepullamagamāsi.**And so poverty grew widespread.*";
P_HTM[1088]="*Dāliddiye vepullaṃ gate aññataro puriso paresaṃ adinnaṃ theyyasaṅkhātaṃ ādiyi.**When poverty was widespread, a certain person stole from others, with the intention to commit theft.*";
P_HTM[1089]="*Tamenaṃ aggahesuṃ.**They arrested him*";
P_HTM[1090]="*Gahetvā rañño khattiyassa muddhābhisittassa dassesuṃ:**and presented him to the king, saying,*";
P_HTM[1091]="*‘ayaṃ, deva, puriso paresaṃ adinnaṃ theyyasaṅkhātaṃ ādiyī’ti.**‘Your Majesty, this person stole from others with the intention to commit theft.’*";
P_HTM[1092]="*Evaṃ vutte, bhikkhave, rājā khattiyo muddhābhisitto taṃ purisaṃ etadavoca:**The king said to that person,*";
P_HTM[1093]="*‘saccaṃ kira tvaṃ, ambho purisa, paresaṃ adinnaṃ theyyasaṅkhātaṃ ādiyī’ti?**‘Is it really true, mister, that you stole from others with the intention to commit theft?’*";
P_HTM[1094]="*‘Saccaṃ, devā’ti.**‘It’s true, sire.’*";
P_HTM[1095]="*‘Kiṃ kāraṇā’ti?**‘What was the reason?’*";
P_HTM[1096]="*‘Na hi, deva, jīvāmī’ti.**‘Sire, I can’t survive.’*";
P_HTM[1097]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, rājā khattiyo muddhābhisitto tassa purisassa dhanamanuppadāsi:**So the king paid some money to that person, saying,*";
P_HTM[1098]="*‘iminā tvaṃ, ambho purisa, dhanena attanā ca jīvāhi, mātāpitaro ca posehi, puttadārañca posehi, kammante ca payojehi, samaṇabrāhmaṇesu uddhaggikaṃ dakkhiṇaṃ patiṭṭhāpehi sovaggikaṃ sukhavipākaṃ saggasaṃvattanikan’ti.**‘With this money, mister, keep yourself alive, and provide for your mother and father, partners and children. Work for a living, and establish an uplifting religious donation for ascetics and brahmins that’s conducive to heaven, ripens in happiness, and leads to heaven.’*";
P_HTM[1099]="*‘Evaṃ, devā’ti kho, bhikkhave, so puriso rañño khattiyassa muddhābhisittassa paccassosi.**‘Yes, Your Majesty,’ replied that man.*";
P_HTM[1100]="*Aññataropi kho, bhikkhave, puriso paresaṃ adinnaṃ theyyasaṅkhātaṃ ādiyi.**But then another man stole something from others.*";
P_HTM[1101]="*Tamenaṃ aggahesuṃ.**They arrested him*";
P_HTM[1102]="*Gahetvā rañño khattiyassa muddhābhisittassa dassesuṃ:**and presented him to the king, saying,*";
P_HTM[1103]="*‘ayaṃ, deva, puriso paresaṃ adinnaṃ theyyasaṅkhātaṃ ādiyī’ti.**‘Your Majesty, this person stole from others.’*";
P_HTM[1104]="*Evaṃ vutte, bhikkhave, rājā khattiyo muddhābhisitto taṃ purisaṃ etadavoca:**The king said to that person,*";
P_HTM[1105]="*‘saccaṃ kira tvaṃ, ambho purisa, paresaṃ adinnaṃ theyyasaṅkhātaṃ ādiyī’ti?**‘Is it really true, mister, that you stole from others?’*";
P_HTM[1106]="*‘Saccaṃ, devā’ti.**‘It’s true, sire.’*";
P_HTM[1107]="*‘Kiṃ kāraṇā’ti?**‘What was the reason?’*";
P_HTM[1108]="*‘Na hi, deva, jīvāmī’ti.**‘Sire, I can’t survive.’*";
P_HTM[1109]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, rājā khattiyo muddhābhisitto tassa purisassa dhanamanuppadāsi:**So the king paid some money to that person, saying,*";
P_HTM[1110]="*‘iminā tvaṃ, ambho purisa, dhanena attanā ca jīvāhi, mātāpitaro ca posehi, puttadārañca posehi, kammante ca payojehi, samaṇabrāhmaṇesu uddhaggikaṃ dakkhiṇaṃ patiṭṭhāpehi sovaggikaṃ sukhavipākaṃ saggasaṃvattanikan’ti.**‘With this money, mister, keep yourself alive, and provide for your mother and father, partners and children. Work for a living, and establish an uplifting religious donation for ascetics and brahmins that’s conducive to heaven, ripens in happiness, and leads to heaven.’*";
P_HTM[1111]="*‘Evaṃ, devā’ti kho, bhikkhave, so puriso rañño khattiyassa muddhābhisittassa paccassosi.**‘Yes, Your Majesty,’ replied that man.*";
P_HTM[1112]="*Assosuṃ kho, bhikkhave, manussā:**People heard about this:*";
P_HTM[1113]="*‘ye kira, bho, paresaṃ adinnaṃ theyyasaṅkhātaṃ ādiyanti, tesaṃ rājā dhanamanuppadetī’ti.**‘It seems the king is paying money to anyone who steals from others!’*";
P_HTM[1114]="*Sutvāna tesaṃ etadahosi:**It occurred to them,*";
P_HTM[1115]="*‘yannūna mayampi paresaṃ adinnaṃ theyyasaṅkhātaṃ ādiyeyyāmā’ti.**‘Why don’t we steal from others?’*";
P_HTM[1116]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, aññataro puriso paresaṃ adinnaṃ theyyasaṅkhātaṃ ādiyi.**So then another man stole something from others.*";
P_HTM[1117]="*Tamenaṃ aggahesuṃ.**They arrested him*";
P_HTM[1118]="*Gahetvā rañño khattiyassa muddhābhisittassa dassesuṃ:**and presented him to the king, saying,*";
P_HTM[1119]="*‘ayaṃ, deva, puriso paresaṃ adinnaṃ theyyasaṅkhātaṃ ādiyī’ti.**‘Your Majesty, this person stole from others.’*";
P_HTM[1120]="*Evaṃ vutte, bhikkhave, rājā khattiyo muddhābhisitto taṃ purisaṃ etadavoca:**The king said to that person,*";
P_HTM[1121]="*‘saccaṃ kira tvaṃ, ambho purisa, paresaṃ adinnaṃ theyyasaṅkhātaṃ ādiyī’ti?**‘Is it really true, mister, that you stole from others?’*";
P_HTM[1122]="*‘Saccaṃ, devā’ti.**‘It’s true, sire.’*";
P_HTM[1123]="*‘Kiṃ kāraṇā’ti?**‘What was the reason?’*";
P_HTM[1124]="*‘Na hi, deva, jīvāmī’ti.**‘Sire, I can’t survive.’*";
P_HTM[1125]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, rañño khattiyassa muddhābhisittassa etadahosi:**Then the king thought,*";
P_HTM[1126]="*‘sace kho ahaṃ yo yo paresaṃ adinnaṃ theyyasaṅkhātaṃ ādiyissati, tassa tassa dhanamanuppadassāmi, evamidaṃ adinnādānaṃ pavaḍḍhissati.**‘If I pay money to anyone who steals from others, it will only increase the stealing.*";
P_HTM[1127]="*Yannūnāhaṃ imaṃ purisaṃ sunisedhaṃ nisedheyyaṃ, mūlaghaccaṃ kareyyaṃ, sīsamassa chindeyyan’ti.**I’d better make an end of this person, finish him off, and chop off his head.’*";
P_HTM[1128]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, rājā khattiyo muddhābhisitto purise āṇāpesi:**Then he ordered his men,*";
P_HTM[1129]="*‘tena hi, bhaṇe, imaṃ purisaṃ daḷhāya rajjuyā pacchābāhaṃ gāḷhabandhanaṃ bandhitvā khuramuṇḍaṃ karitvā kharassarena paṇavena rathikāya rathikaṃ siṅghāṭakena siṅghāṭakaṃ parinetvā dakkhiṇena dvārena nikkhamitvā dakkhiṇato nagarassa sunisedhaṃ nisedhetha, mūlaghaccaṃ karotha, sīsamassa chindathā’ti.**‘Well then, my men, tie this man’s arms tightly behind his back with a strong rope. Shave his head and march him from street to street and square to square to the beating of a harsh drum. Then take him out the south gate and make an end of him, finish him off, and chop off his head.’*";
P_HTM[1130]="*‘Evaṃ, devā’ti kho, bhikkhave, te purisā rañño khattiyassa muddhābhisittassa paṭissutvā taṃ purisaṃ daḷhāya rajjuyā pacchābāhaṃ gāḷhabandhanaṃ bandhitvā khuramuṇḍaṃ karitvā kharassarena paṇavena rathikāya rathikaṃ siṅghāṭakena siṅghāṭakaṃ parinetvā dakkhiṇena dvārena nikkhamitvā dakkhiṇato nagarassa sunisedhaṃ nisedhesuṃ, mūlaghaccaṃ akaṃsu, sīsamassa chindiṃsu.**‘Yes, Your Majesty,’ they replied, and did as he commanded.*";
P_HTM[1131]="*Assosuṃ kho, bhikkhave, manussā:**People heard about this:*";
P_HTM[1132]="*‘ye kira, bho, paresaṃ adinnaṃ theyyasaṅkhātaṃ ādiyanti, te rājā sunisedhaṃ nisedheti, mūlaghaccaṃ karoti, sīsāni tesaṃ chindatī’ti.**‘It seems the king is chopping the head off anyone who steals from others!’*";
P_HTM[1133]="*Sutvāna tesaṃ etadahosi:**It occurred to them,*";
P_HTM[1134]="*‘yannūna mayampi tiṇhāni satthāni kārāpessāma, tiṇhāni satthāni kārāpetvā yesaṃ adinnaṃ theyyasaṅkhātaṃ ādiyissāma, te sunisedhaṃ nisedhessāma, mūlaghaccaṃ karissāma, sīsāni tesaṃ chindissāmā’ti.**‘We’d better have sharp swords made. Then when we steal from others, we’ll make an end of them, finish them off, and chop off their heads.’*";
P_HTM[1135]="*Te tiṇhāni satthāni kārāpesuṃ, tiṇhāni satthāni kārāpetvā gāmaghātampi upakkamiṃsu kātuṃ, nigamaghātampi upakkamiṃsu kātuṃ, nagaraghātampi upakkamiṃsu kātuṃ, panthaduhanampi upakkamiṃsu kātuṃ.**They had sharp swords made. Then they started to make raids on villages, towns, and cities, and to infest the highways.*";
P_HTM[1136]="*Yesaṃ te adinnaṃ theyyasaṅkhātaṃ ādiyanti, te sunisedhaṃ nisedhenti, mūlaghaccaṃ karonti, sīsāni tesaṃ chindanti.**And they chopped the heads off anyone they stole from.*";
P_HTM[1137]="*Iti kho, bhikkhave, adhanānaṃ dhane ananuppadiyamāne dāliddiyaṃ vepullamagamāsi, dāliddiye vepullaṃ gate adinnādānaṃ vepullamagamāsi, adinnādāne vepullaṃ gate satthaṃ vepullamagamāsi, satthe vepullaṃ gate pāṇātipāto vepullamagamāsi, pāṇātipāte vepullaṃ gate tesaṃ sattānaṃ āyupi parihāyi, vaṇṇopi parihāyi.**And so, mendicants, from not paying money to the penniless, poverty became widespread. When poverty was widespread, theft became widespread. When theft was widespread, swords became widespread. When swords were widespread, killing living creatures became widespread. And for the sentient beings among whom killing was widespread, their lifespan and beauty declined.*";
P_HTM[1138]="*Tesaṃ āyunāpi parihāyamānānaṃ vaṇṇenapi parihāyamānānaṃ asītivassasahassāyukānaṃ manussānaṃ cattārīsavassasahassāyukā puttā ahesuṃ.**Those people lived for 80,000 years, but their children lived for 40,000 years.*";
P_HTM[1139]="*Cattārīsavassasahassāyukesu, bhikkhave, manussesu aññataro puriso paresaṃ adinnaṃ theyyasaṅkhātaṃ ādiyi.**Among the people who lived for 40,000 years, a certain person stole something from others.*";
P_HTM[1140]="*Tamenaṃ aggahesuṃ.**They arrested him*";
P_HTM[1141]="*Gahetvā rañño khattiyassa muddhābhisittassa dassesuṃ:**and presented him to the king, saying,*";
P_HTM[1142]="*‘ayaṃ, deva, puriso paresaṃ adinnaṃ theyyasaṅkhātaṃ ādiyī’ti.**‘Your Majesty, this person stole from others.’*";
P_HTM[1143]="*Evaṃ vutte, bhikkhave, rājā khattiyo muddhābhisitto taṃ purisaṃ etadavoca:**The king said to that person,*";
P_HTM[1144]="*‘saccaṃ kira tvaṃ, ambho purisa, paresaṃ adinnaṃ theyyasaṅkhātaṃ ādiyī’ti?**‘Is it really true, mister, that you stole from others?’*";
P_HTM[1145]="*‘Na hi, devā’ti sampajānamusā abhāsi.**‘No, sire,’ he said, deliberately lying.*";
P_HTM[1146]="*Iti kho, bhikkhave, adhanānaṃ dhane ananuppadiyamāne dāliddiyaṃ vepullamagamāsi. Dāliddiye vepullaṃ gate adinnādānaṃ vepullamagamāsi, adinnādāne vepullaṃ gate satthaṃ vepullamagamāsi. Satthe vepullaṃ gate pāṇātipāto vepullamagamāsi, pāṇātipāte vepullaṃ gate musāvādo vepullamagamāsi, musāvāde vepullaṃ gate tesaṃ sattānaṃ āyupi parihāyi, vaṇṇopi parihāyi.**And so, mendicants, from not paying money to the penniless, poverty, theft, swords, and killing became widespread. When killing was widespread, lying became widespread. And for the sentient beings among whom lying was widespread, their lifespan and beauty declined.*";
P_HTM[1147]="*Tesaṃ āyunāpi parihāyamānānaṃ vaṇṇenapi parihāyamānānaṃ cattārīsavassasahassāyukānaṃ manussānaṃ vīsativassasahassāyukā puttā ahesuṃ.**Those people who lived for 40,000 years had children who lived for 20,000 years.*";
P_HTM[1148]="*Vīsativassasahassāyukesu, bhikkhave, manussesu aññataro puriso paresaṃ adinnaṃ theyyasaṅkhātaṃ ādiyi.**Among the people who lived for 20,000 years, a certain person stole something from others.*";
P_HTM[1149]="*Tamenaṃ aññataro puriso rañño khattiyassa muddhābhisittassa ārocesi:**Someone else reported this to the king,*";
P_HTM[1150]="*‘itthannāmo, deva, puriso paresaṃ adinnaṃ theyyasaṅkhātaṃ ādiyī’ti pesuññamakāsi.**‘Your Majesty, such-and-such person stole from others,’ he said, going behind his back.*";
P_HTM[1151]="*Iti kho, bhikkhave, adhanānaṃ dhane ananuppadiyamāne dāliddiyaṃ vepullamagamāsi. Dāliddiye vepullaṃ gate adinnādānaṃ vepullamagamāsi, adinnādāne vepullaṃ gate satthaṃ vepullamagamāsi, satthe vepullaṃ gate pāṇātipāto vepullamagamāsi, pāṇātipāte vepullaṃ gate musāvādo vepullamagamāsi, musāvāde vepullaṃ gate pisuṇā vācā vepullamagamāsi, pisuṇāya vācāya vepullaṃ gatāya tesaṃ sattānaṃ āyupi parihāyi, vaṇṇopi parihāyi.**And so, mendicants, from not paying money to the penniless, poverty, theft, swords, killing, and lying became widespread. When lying was widespread, backbiting became widespread. And for the sentient beings among whom backbiting was widespread, their lifespan and beauty declined.*";
P_HTM[1152]="*Tesaṃ āyunāpi parihāyamānānaṃ vaṇṇenapi parihāyamānānaṃ vīsativassasahassāyukānaṃ manussānaṃ dasavassasahassāyukā puttā ahesuṃ.**Those people who lived for 20,000 years had children who lived for 10,000 years.*";
P_HTM[1153]="*Dasavassasahassāyukesu, bhikkhave, manussesu ekidaṃ sattā vaṇṇavanto honti, ekidaṃ sattā dubbaṇṇā.**Among the people who lived for 10,000 years, some were more beautiful than others.*";
P_HTM[1154]="*Tattha ye te sattā dubbaṇṇā, te vaṇṇavante satte abhijjhāyantā paresaṃ dāresu cārittaṃ āpajjiṃsu.**And the ugly beings, coveting the beautiful ones, committed adultery with others’ wives.*";
P_HTM[1155]="*Iti kho, bhikkhave, adhanānaṃ dhane ananuppadiyamāne dāliddiyaṃ vepullamagamāsi. Dāliddiye vepullaṃ gate … pe … kāmesumicchācāro vepullamagamāsi, kāmesumicchācāre vepullaṃ gate tesaṃ sattānaṃ āyupi parihāyi, vaṇṇopi parihāyi.**And so, mendicants, from not paying money to the penniless, poverty, theft, swords, killing, lying, and backbiting became widespread. When backbiting was widespread, sexual misconduct became widespread. And for the sentient beings among whom sexual misconduct was widespread, their lifespan and beauty declined.*";
P_HTM[1156]="*Tesaṃ āyunāpi parihāyamānānaṃ vaṇṇenapi parihāyamānānaṃ dasavassasahassāyukānaṃ manussānaṃ pañcavassasahassāyukā puttā ahesuṃ.**Those people who lived for 10,000 years had children who lived for 5,000 years.*";
P_HTM[1157]="*Pañcavassasahassāyukesu, bhikkhave, manussesu dve dhammā vepullamagamaṃsu—**Among the people who lived for 5,000 years, two things became widespread:*";
P_HTM[1158]="*pharusāvācā samphappalāpo ca.**harsh speech and talking nonsense.*";
P_HTM[1159]="*Dvīsu dhammesu vepullaṃ gatesu tesaṃ sattānaṃ āyupi parihāyi, vaṇṇopi parihāyi.**For the sentient beings among whom these two things were widespread, their lifespan and beauty declined.*";
P_HTM[1160]="*Tesaṃ āyunāpi parihāyamānānaṃ vaṇṇenapi parihāyamānānaṃ pañcavassasahassāyukānaṃ manussānaṃ appekacce aḍḍhateyyavassasahassāyukā, appekacce dvevassasahassāyukā puttā ahesuṃ.**Those people who lived for 5,000 years had some children who lived for 2,500 years, while others lived for 2,000 years.*";
P_HTM[1161]="*Aḍḍhateyyavassasahassāyukesu, bhikkhave, manussesu abhijjhābyāpādā vepullamagamaṃsu.**Among the people who lived for 2,500 years, desire and ill will became widespread.*";
P_HTM[1162]="*Abhijjhābyāpādesu vepullaṃ gatesu tesaṃ sattānaṃ āyupi parihāyi, vaṇṇopi parihāyi.**For the sentient beings among whom desire and ill will were widespread, their lifespan and beauty declined.*";
P_HTM[1163]="*Tesaṃ āyunāpi parihāyamānānaṃ vaṇṇenapi parihāyamānānaṃ aḍḍhateyyavassasahassāyukānaṃ manussānaṃ vassasahassāyukā puttā ahesuṃ.**Those people who lived for 2,500 years had children who lived for 1,000 years.*";
P_HTM[1164]="*Vassasahassāyukesu, bhikkhave, manussesu micchādiṭṭhi vepullamagamāsi.**Among the people who lived for 1,000 years, wrong view became widespread.*";
P_HTM[1165]="*Micchādiṭṭhiyā vepullaṃ gatāya tesaṃ sattānaṃ āyupi parihāyi, vaṇṇopi parihāyi.**For the sentient beings among whom wrong view was widespread, their lifespan and beauty declined.*";
P_HTM[1166]="*Tesaṃ āyunāpi parihāyamānānaṃ vaṇṇenapi parihāyamānānaṃ vassasahassāyukānaṃ manussānaṃ pañcavassasatāyukā puttā ahesuṃ.**Those people who lived for 1,000 years had children who lived for five hundred years.*";
P_HTM[1167]="*Pañcavassasatāyukesu, bhikkhave, manussesu tayo dhammā vepullamagamaṃsu—**Among the people who lived for five hundred years, three things became widespread:*";
P_HTM[1168]="*adhammarāgo visamalobho micchādhammo.**illicit desire, immoral greed, and wrong thoughts.*";
P_HTM[1169]="*Tīsu dhammesu vepullaṃ gatesu tesaṃ sattānaṃ āyupi parihāyi, vaṇṇopi parihāyi.**For the sentient beings among whom these three things were widespread, their lifespan and beauty declined.*";
P_HTM[1170]="*Tesaṃ āyunāpi parihāyamānānaṃ vaṇṇenapi parihāyamānānaṃ pañcavassasatāyukānaṃ manussānaṃ appekacce aḍḍhateyyavassasatāyukā, appekacce dvevassasatāyukā puttā ahesuṃ.**Those people who lived for five hundred years had some children who lived for two hundred and fifty years, while others lived for two hundred years.*";
P_HTM[1171]="*Aḍḍhateyyavassasatāyukesu, bhikkhave, manussesu ime dhammā vepullamagamaṃsu.**Among the people who lived for two hundred and fifty years, three things became widespread:*";
P_HTM[1172]="*Amatteyyatā apetteyyatā asāmaññatā abrahmaññatā na kule jeṭṭhāpacāyitā.**lack of due respect for mother and father, ascetics and brahmins, and failure to honor the elders in the family.*";
P_HTM[1173]="*Iti kho, bhikkhave, adhanānaṃ dhane ananuppadiyamāne dāliddiyaṃ vepullamagamāsi.**And so, mendicants, from not paying money to the penniless, all these things became widespread—poverty,*";
P_HTM[1174]="*Dāliddiye vepullaṃ gate adinnādānaṃ vepullamagamāsi.**theft,*";
P_HTM[1175]="*Adinnādāne vepullaṃ gate satthaṃ vepullamagamāsi.**swords,*";
P_HTM[1176]="*Satthe vepullaṃ gate pāṇātipāto vepullamagamāsi.**killing,*";
P_HTM[1177]="*Pāṇātipāte vepullaṃ gate musāvādo vepullamagamāsi.**lying,*";
P_HTM[1178]="*Musāvāde vepullaṃ gate pisuṇā vācā vepullamagamāsi.**backbiting,*";
P_HTM[1179]="*Pisuṇāya vācāya vepullaṃ gatāya kāmesumicchācāro vepullamagamāsi.**sexual misconduct,*";
P_HTM[1180]="*Kāmesumicchācāre vepullaṃ gate dve dhammā vepullamagamaṃsu, pharusā vācā samphappalāpo ca.**harsh speech and talking nonsense,*";
P_HTM[1181]="*Dvīsu dhammesu vepullaṃ gatesu abhijjhābyāpādā vepullamagamaṃsu.**desire and ill will,*";
P_HTM[1182]="*Abhijjhābyāpādesu vepullaṃ gatesu micchādiṭṭhi vepullamagamāsi.**wrong view,*";
P_HTM[1183]="*Micchādiṭṭhiyā vepullaṃ gatāya tayo dhammā vepullamagamaṃsu, adhammarāgo visamalobho micchādhammo.**illicit desire, immoral greed, and wrong thoughts,*";
P_HTM[1184]="*Tīsu dhammesu vepullaṃ gatesu ime dhammā vepullamagamaṃsu, amatteyyatā apetteyyatā asāmaññatā abrahmaññatā na kule jeṭṭhāpacāyitā.**and lack of due respect for mother and father, ascetics and brahmins, and failure to honor the elders in the family.*";
P_HTM[1185]="*Imesu dhammesu vepullaṃ gatesu tesaṃ sattānaṃ āyupi parihāyi, vaṇṇopi parihāyi.**For the sentient beings among whom these things were widespread, their lifespan and beauty declined.*";
P_HTM[1186]="*Tesaṃ āyunāpi parihāyamānānaṃ vaṇṇenapi parihāyamānānaṃ aḍḍhateyyavassasatāyukānaṃ manussānaṃ vassasatāyukā puttā ahesuṃ.**Those people who lived for two hundred and fifty years had children who lived for a hundred years.*";
P_HTM[1187]="*5. Dasavassāyukasamaya**5. When People Live for Ten Years*";
P_HTM[1188]="*Bhavissati, bhikkhave, so samayo, yaṃ imesaṃ manussānaṃ dasavassāyukā puttā bhavissanti.**There will come a time, mendicants, when these people will have children who live for ten years.*";
P_HTM[1189]="*Dasavassāyukesu, bhikkhave, manussesu pañcavassikā kumārikā alaṃpateyyā bhavissanti.**Among the people who live for ten years, girls will be marriageable at five.*";
P_HTM[1190]="*Dasavassāyukesu, bhikkhave, manussesu imāni rasāni antaradhāyissanti, seyyathidaṃ—**The following flavors will disappear:*";
P_HTM[1191]="*sappi navanītaṃ telaṃ madhu phāṇitaṃ loṇaṃ.**ghee, butter, oil, honey, molasses, and salt.*";
P_HTM[1192]="*Dasavassāyukesu, bhikkhave, manussesu kudrūsako aggaṃ bhojanānaṃ bhavissati.**The best kind of food will be finger millet,*";
P_HTM[1193]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, etarahi sālimaṃsodano aggaṃ bhojanānaṃ;**just as fine rice with meat is the best kind of food today.*";
P_HTM[1194]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, dasavassāyukesu manussesu kudrūsako aggaṃ bhojanānaṃ bhavissati.* **";
P_HTM[1195]="*Dasavassāyukesu, bhikkhave, manussesu dasa kusalakammapathā sabbena sabbaṃ antaradhāyissanti, dasa akusalakammapathā atibyādippissanti.**The ten ways of doing skillful deeds will totally disappear, and the ten ways of doing unskillful deeds will explode in popularity.*";
P_HTM[1196]="*Dasavassāyukesu, bhikkhave, manussesu kusalantipi na bhavissati, kuto pana kusalassa kārako.**Those people will not even have the word ‘skillful’, still less anyone who does what is skillful.*";
P_HTM[1197]="*Dasavassāyukesu, bhikkhave, manussesu ye te bhavissanti amatteyyā apetteyyā asāmaññā abrahmaññā na kule jeṭṭhāpacāyino, te pujjā ca bhavissanti pāsaṃsā ca.**And anyone who disrespects mother and father, ascetics and brahmins, and fails to honor the elders in the family will be venerated and praised,*";
P_HTM[1198]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, etarahi matteyyā petteyyā sāmaññā brahmaññā kule jeṭṭhāpacāyino pujjā ca pāsaṃsā ca;**just as the opposite is venerated and praised today.*";
P_HTM[1199]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, dasavassāyukesu manussesu ye te bhavissanti amatteyyā apetteyyā asāmaññā abrahmaññā na kule jeṭṭhāpacāyino, te pujjā ca bhavissanti pāsaṃsā ca.* **";
P_HTM[1200]="*Dasavassāyukesu, bhikkhave, manussesu na bhavissati mātāti vā mātucchāti vā mātulānīti vā ācariyabhariyāti vā garūnaṃ dārāti vā.**There’ll be no recognition of the status of mother, aunts, or wives and partners of teachers and respected people.*";
P_HTM[1201]="*Sambhedaṃ loko gamissati yathā ajeḷakā kukkuṭasūkarā soṇasiṅgālā.**The world will become promiscuous, like goats and sheep, chickens and pigs, and dogs and jackals.*";
P_HTM[1202]="*Dasavassāyukesu, bhikkhave, manussesu tesaṃ sattānaṃ aññamaññamhi tibbo āghāto paccupaṭṭhito bhavissati tibbo byāpādo tibbo manopadoso tibbaṃ vadhakacittaṃ.**They’ll be full of hostility towards each other, with acute ill will, malevolence, and thoughts of murder.*";
P_HTM[1203]="*Mātupi puttamhi puttassapi mātari;**Even a mother will feel like this for her child, and the child for its mother,*";
P_HTM[1204]="*pitupi puttamhi puttassapi pitari;**father for child, child for father,*";
P_HTM[1205]="*bhātupi bhaginiyā bhaginiyāpi bhātari tibbo āghāto paccupaṭṭhito bhavissati tibbo byāpādo tibbo manopadoso tibbaṃ vadhakacittaṃ.**brother for sister, and sister for brother.*";
P_HTM[1206]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, māgavikassa migaṃ disvā tibbo āghāto paccupaṭṭhito hoti tibbo byāpādo tibbo manopadoso tibbaṃ vadhakacittaṃ;**They’ll be just like a deer hunter when he sees a deer—full of hostility, ill will, malevolence, and thoughts of killing.*";
P_HTM[1207]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, dasavassāyukesu manussesu tesaṃ sattānaṃ aññamaññamhi tibbo āghāto paccupaṭṭhito bhavissati tibbo byāpādo tibbo manopadoso tibbaṃ vadhakacittaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1208]="*Mātupi puttamhi puttassapi mātari;* **";
P_HTM[1209]="*pitupi puttamhi puttassapi pitari;* **";
P_HTM[1210]="*bhātupi bhaginiyā bhaginiyāpi bhātari tibbo āghāto paccupaṭṭhito bhavissati tibbo byāpādo tibbo manopadoso tibbaṃ vadhakacittaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1211]="*Dasavassāyukesu, bhikkhave, manussesu sattāhaṃ satthantarakappo bhavissati.**Among the people who live for ten years, there will be an interregnum of swords lasting seven days.*";
P_HTM[1212]="*Te aññamaññamhi migasaññaṃ paṭilabhissanti.**During that time they will see each other as beasts.*";
P_HTM[1213]="*Tesaṃ tiṇhāni satthāni hatthesu pātubhavissanti.**Sharp swords will appear in their hands,*";
P_HTM[1214]="*Te tiṇhena satthena ‘esa migo esa migo’ti aññamaññaṃ jīvitā voropessanti.**with which they’ll take each other’s life, crying, ‘It’s a beast! It’s a beast!’*";
P_HTM[1215]="*Atha kho tesaṃ, bhikkhave, sattānaṃ ekaccānaṃ evaṃ bhavissati:**But then some of those beings will think,*";
P_HTM[1216]="*‘mā ca mayaṃ kañci, mā ca amhe koci, yannūna mayaṃ tiṇagahanaṃ vā vanagahanaṃ vā rukkhagahanaṃ vā nadīviduggaṃ vā pabbatavisamaṃ vā pavisitvā vanamūlaphalāhārā yāpeyyāmā’ti.**‘Let us neither be perpetrators nor victims! Why don’t we hide in thick grass, thick jungle, thick trees, inaccessible riverlands, or rugged mountains and survive on forest roots and fruits?’*";
P_HTM[1217]="*Te tiṇagahanaṃ vā vanagahanaṃ vā rukkhagahanaṃ vā nadīviduggaṃ vā pabbatavisamaṃ vā pavisitvā sattāhaṃ vanamūlaphalāhārā yāpessanti.**So that’s what they do.*";
P_HTM[1218]="*Te tassa sattāhassa accayena tiṇagahanā vanagahanā rukkhagahanā nadīviduggā pabbatavisamā nikkhamitvā aññamaññaṃ āliṅgitvā sabhāgāyissanti samassāsissanti:**When those seven days have passed, having emerged from their hiding places and embraced each other, they will come together in one voice and cry,*";
P_HTM[1219]="*‘diṭṭhā, bho, sattā jīvasi, diṭṭhā, bho, sattā jīvasī’ti.**‘How fantastic, dear being, you live! How fantastic, dear being, you live!’*";
P_HTM[1220]="*6. Āyuvaṇṇādivaḍḍhanakathā**6. The Period of Growth*";
P_HTM[1221]="*Atha kho tesaṃ, bhikkhave, sattānaṃ evaṃ bhavissati:**Then those beings will think,*";
P_HTM[1222]="*‘mayaṃ kho akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ samādānahetu evarūpaṃ āyataṃ ñātikkhayaṃ pattā.**‘It’s because we undertook unskillful things that we suffered such an extensive loss of our relatives.*";
P_HTM[1223]="*Yannūna mayaṃ kusalaṃ kareyyāma.**We’d better do what’s skillful.*";
P_HTM[1224]="*Kiṃ kusalaṃ kareyyāma?**What skillful thing should we do?*";
P_HTM[1225]="*Yannūna mayaṃ pāṇātipātā virameyyāma, idaṃ kusalaṃ dhammaṃ samādāya vatteyyāmā’ti.**Why don’t we refrain from killing living creatures? Having undertaken this skillful thing we’ll live by it.’*";
P_HTM[1226]="*Te pāṇātipātā viramissanti, idaṃ kusalaṃ dhammaṃ samādāya vattissanti.**So that’s what they do.*";
P_HTM[1227]="*Te kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ samādānahetu āyunāpi vaḍḍhissanti, vaṇṇenapi vaḍḍhissanti.**Because of undertaking this skillful thing, their lifespan and beauty will grow.*";
P_HTM[1228]="*Tesaṃ āyunāpi vaḍḍhamānānaṃ vaṇṇenapi vaḍḍhamānānaṃ dasavassāyukānaṃ manussānaṃ vīsativassāyukā puttā bhavissanti.**Those people who live for ten years will have children who live for twenty years.*";
P_HTM[1229]="*Atha kho tesaṃ, bhikkhave, sattānaṃ evaṃ bhavissati:**Then those beings will think,*";
P_HTM[1230]="*‘mayaṃ kho kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ samādānahetu āyunāpi vaḍḍhāma, vaṇṇenapi vaḍḍhāma.**‘Because of undertaking this skillful thing, our lifespan and beauty are growing.*";
P_HTM[1231]="*Yannūna mayaṃ bhiyyoso mattāya kusalaṃ kareyyāma.**Why don’t we do even more skillful things?*";
P_HTM[1232]="*Kiṃ kusalaṃ kareyyāma?**What skillful thing should we do?*";
P_HTM[1233]="*Yannūna mayaṃ adinnādānā virameyyāma …**Why don’t we refrain from stealing …*";
P_HTM[1234]="*kāmesumicchācārā virameyyāma …**sexual misconduct …*";
P_HTM[1235]="*musāvādā virameyyāma …**lying …*";
P_HTM[1236]="*pisuṇāya vācāya virameyyāma …**backbiting …*";
P_HTM[1237]="*pharusāya vācāya virameyyāma …**harsh speech …*";
P_HTM[1238]="*samphappalāpā virameyyāma …**and talking nonsense.*";
P_HTM[1239]="*abhijjhaṃ pajaheyyāma …**Why don’t we give up covetousness …*";
P_HTM[1240]="*byāpādaṃ pajaheyyāma …**ill will …*";
P_HTM[1241]="*micchādiṭṭhiṃ pajaheyyāma …**wrong view …*";
P_HTM[1242]="*tayo dhamme pajaheyyāma—**three things:*";
P_HTM[1243]="*adhammarāgaṃ visamalobhaṃ micchādhammaṃ …**illicit desire, immoral greed, and wrong thoughts.*";
P_HTM[1244]="*yannūna mayaṃ matteyyā assāma petteyyā sāmaññā brahmaññā kule jeṭṭhāpacāyino, idaṃ kusalaṃ dhammaṃ samādāya vatteyyāmā’ti.**Why don’t we pay due respect to mother and father, ascetics and brahmins, honoring the elders in our families? Having undertaken this skillful thing we’ll live by it.’*";
P_HTM[1245]="*Te matteyyā bhavissanti petteyyā sāmaññā brahmaññā kule jeṭṭhāpacāyino, idaṃ kusalaṃ dhammaṃ samādāya vattissanti.**So that’s what they do.*";
P_HTM[1246]="*Te kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ samādānahetu āyunāpi vaḍḍhissanti, vaṇṇenapi vaḍḍhissanti.**Because of undertaking this skillful thing, their lifespan and beauty will grow.*";
P_HTM[1247]="*Tesaṃ āyunāpi vaḍḍhamānānaṃ vaṇṇenapi vaḍḍhamānānaṃ vīsativassāyukānaṃ manussānaṃ cattārīsavassāyukā puttā bhavissanti …**Those people who live for twenty years will have children who live for forty years.*";
P_HTM[1248]="*cattārīsavassāyukānaṃ manussānaṃ asītivassāyukā puttā bhavissanti …**Those people who live for forty years will have children who live for eighty years,*";
P_HTM[1249]="*asītivassāyukānaṃ manussānaṃ saṭṭhivassasatāyukā puttā bhavissanti …**then a hundred and sixty years,*";
P_HTM[1250]="*saṭṭhivassasatāyukānaṃ manussānaṃ vīsatitivassasatāyukā puttā bhavissanti …**three hundred and twenty years,*";
P_HTM[1251]="*vīsatitivassasatāyukānaṃ manussānaṃ cattārīsachabbassasatāyukā puttā bhavissanti.**six hundred and forty years,*";
P_HTM[1252]="*Cattārīsachabbassasatāyukānaṃ manussānaṃ dvevassasahassāyukā puttā bhavissanti …**2,000 years,*";
P_HTM[1253]="*dvevassasahassāyukānaṃ manussānaṃ cattārivassasahassāyukā puttā bhavissanti …**4,000 years,*";
P_HTM[1254]="*cattārivassasahassāyukānaṃ manussānaṃ aṭṭhavassasahassāyukā puttā bhavissanti …**8,000 years,*";
P_HTM[1255]="*aṭṭhavassasahassāyukānaṃ manussānaṃ vīsativassasahassāyukā puttā bhavissanti …**20,000 years,*";
P_HTM[1256]="*vīsativassasahassāyukānaṃ manussānaṃ cattārīsavassasahassāyukā puttā bhavissanti …**40,000 years,*";
P_HTM[1257]="*cattārīsavassasahassāyukānaṃ manussānaṃ asītivassasahassāyukā puttā bhavissanti …**and finally 80,000 years.*";
P_HTM[1258]="*asītivassasahassāyukesu, bhikkhave, manussesu pañcavassasatikā kumārikā alaṃpateyyā bhavissanti.**Among the people who live for 80,000 years, girls will be marriageable at five hundred.*";
P_HTM[1259]="*7. Saṅkharājauppatti**7. The Time of King Saṅkha*";
P_HTM[1260]="*Asītivassasahassāyukesu, bhikkhave, manussesu tayo ābādhā bhavissanti, icchā, anasanaṃ, jarā.**Among the people who live for 80,000 years, there will be just three afflictions: greed, starvation, and old age.*";
P_HTM[1261]="*Asītivassasahassāyukesu, bhikkhave, manussesu ayaṃ jambudīpo iddho ceva bhavissati phīto ca, kukkuṭasampātikā gāmanigamarājadhāniyo.**India will be successful and prosperous. The villages, towns, and capital cities will be no more than a chicken’s flight apart.*";
P_HTM[1262]="*Asītivassasahassāyukesu, bhikkhave, manussesu ayaṃ jambudīpo avīci maññe phuṭo bhavissati manussehi, seyyathāpi naḷavanaṃ vā saravanaṃ vā.**And the land will be as crowded as hell, just full of people, like a thicket of rushes or reeds.*";
P_HTM[1263]="*Asītivassasahassāyukesu, bhikkhave, manussesu ayaṃ bārāṇasī ketumatī nāma rājadhānī bhavissati iddhā ceva phītā ca bahujanā ca ākiṇṇamanussā ca subhikkhā ca.**The royal capital will be our Benares, but renamed Ketumati. And it will be successful, prosperous, populous, full of people, with plenty of food.*";
P_HTM[1264]="*Asītivassasahassāyukesu, bhikkhave, manussesu imasmiṃ jambudīpe caturāsītinagarasahassāni bhavissanti ketumatīrājadhānīpamukhāni.**There will be 84,000 cities in India, with the royal capital of Ketumati foremost.*";
P_HTM[1265]="*Asītivassasahassāyukesu, bhikkhave, manussesu ketumatiyā rājadhāniyā saṅkho nāma rājā uppajjissati cakkavattī dhammiko dhammarājā cāturanto vijitāvī janapadatthāvariyappatto sattaratanasamannāgato.**And in the royal capital of Ketumati a king named Saṅkha will arise, a wheel-turning monarch, a just and principled king. His dominion will extend to all four sides, he will achieve stability in the country, and possess the seven treasures.*";
P_HTM[1266]="*Tassimāni satta ratanāni bhavissanti, seyyathidaṃ—**He will have the following seven treasures:*";
P_HTM[1267]="*cakkaratanaṃ hatthiratanaṃ assaratanaṃ maṇiratanaṃ itthiratanaṃ gahapatiratanaṃ pariṇāyakaratanameva sattamaṃ.**the wheel, the elephant, the horse, the jewel, the woman, the treasurer, and the counselor as the seventh treasure.*";
P_HTM[1268]="*Parosahassaṃ kho panassa puttā bhavissanti sūrā vīraṅgarūpā parasenappamaddanā.**He will have over a thousand sons who are valiant and heroic, crushing the armies of his enemies.*";
P_HTM[1269]="*So imaṃ pathaviṃ sāgarapariyantaṃ adaṇḍena asatthena dhammena abhivijiya ajjhāvasissati.**After conquering this land girt by sea, he will reign by principle, without rod or sword.*";
P_HTM[1270]="*8. Metteyyabuddhuppāda**8. The Arising of the Buddha Metteyya*";
P_HTM[1271]="*Asītivassasahassāyukesu, bhikkhave, manussesu metteyyo nāma bhagavā loke uppajjissati arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā.**And the Blessed One named Metteyya will arise in the world—perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed—*";
P_HTM[1272]="*Seyyathāpāhametarahi loke uppanno arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā.**just as I have arisen today.*";
P_HTM[1273]="*So imaṃ lokaṃ sadevakaṃ samārakaṃ sabrahmakaṃ sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiṃ pajaṃ sadevamanussaṃ sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā pavedessati, seyyathāpāhametarahi imaṃ lokaṃ sadevakaṃ samārakaṃ sabrahmakaṃ sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiṃ pajaṃ sadevamanussaṃ sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā pavedemi.**He will realize with his own insight this world—with its gods, Māras and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, gods and humans—and make it known to others, just as I do today.*";
P_HTM[1274]="*So dhammaṃ desessati ādikalyāṇaṃ majjhekalyāṇaṃ pariyosānakalyāṇaṃ sātthaṃ sabyañjanaṃ kevalaparipuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ pakāsessati;**He will teach the Dhamma that’s good in the beginning, good in the middle, and good in the end, meaningful and well-phrased. And he will reveal a spiritual practice that’s entirely full and pure,*";
P_HTM[1275]="*seyyathāpāhametarahi dhammaṃ desemi ādikalyāṇaṃ majjhekalyāṇaṃ pariyosānakalyāṇaṃ sātthaṃ sabyañjanaṃ kevalaparipuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ pakāsemi.**just as I do today.*";
P_HTM[1276]="*So anekasahassaṃ bhikkhusaṃghaṃ pariharissati, seyyathāpāhametarahi anekasataṃ bhikkhusaṃghaṃ pariharāmi.**He will look after a Saṅgha of many thousand mendicants, just as I look after a Saṅgha of many hundreds today.*";
P_HTM[1277]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, saṅkho nāma rājā yo so yūpo raññā mahāpanādena kārāpito.**Then King Saṅkha will have the sacrificial post that had been built by King Mahāpanāda raised up.*";
P_HTM[1278]="*Taṃ yūpaṃ ussāpetvā ajjhāvasitvā taṃ datvā vissajjitvā samaṇabrāhmaṇakapaṇaddhikavaṇibbakayācakānaṃ dānaṃ datvā metteyyassa bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa santike kesamassuṃ ohāretvā kāsāyāni vatthāni acchādetvā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajissati.**After staying there, he will give it away to ascetics and brahmins, paupers, vagrants, travelers, and beggars. Then, having shaved off his hair and beard and dressed in ocher robes, he will go forth from the lay life to homelessness in the Buddha Metteyya’s presence.*";
P_HTM[1279]="*So evaṃ pabbajito samāno eko vūpakaṭṭho appamatto ātāpī pahitatto viharanto nacirasseva—yassatthāya kulaputtā sammadeva agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajanti, tadanuttaraṃ—brahmacariyapariyosānaṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharissati.**Soon after going forth, living withdrawn, diligent, keen, and resolute, he will realize the supreme end of the spiritual path in this very life. He will live having achieved with his own insight the goal for which gentlemen rightly go forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[1280]="*Attadīpā, bhikkhave, viharatha attasaraṇā anaññasaraṇā, dhammadīpā dhammasaraṇā anaññasaraṇā.**Mendicants, be your own island, your own refuge, with no other refuge. Let the teaching be your island and your refuge, with no other refuge.*";
P_HTM[1281]="*Kathañca, bhikkhave, bhikkhu attadīpo viharati attasaraṇo anaññasaraṇo dhammadīpo dhammasaraṇo anaññasaraṇo?**And how does a mendicant do this?*";
P_HTM[1282]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[1283]="*Vedanāsu vedanānupassī … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[1284]="*citte cittānupassī … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[1285]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[1286]="*Evaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu attadīpo viharati attasaraṇo anaññasaraṇo dhammadīpo dhammasaraṇo anaññasaraṇo.**That’s how a mendicant is their own island, their own refuge, with no other refuge. That’s how they let the teaching be their island and their refuge, with no other refuge.*";
P_HTM[1287]="*9. Bhikkhunoāyuvaṇṇādivaḍḍhanakathā**9. On Long Life and Beauty for Mendicants*";
P_HTM[1288]="*Gocare, bhikkhave, caratha sake pettike visaye.**Mendicants, you should roam inside your own territory, the domain of your fathers.*";
P_HTM[1289]="*Gocare, bhikkhave, carantā sake pettike visaye āyunāpi vaḍḍhissatha, vaṇṇenapi vaḍḍhissatha, sukhenapi vaḍḍhissatha, bhogenapi vaḍḍhissatha, balenapi vaḍḍhissatha.**Doing so, you will grow in life span, beauty, happiness, wealth, and power.*";
P_HTM[1290]="*Kiñca, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno āyusmiṃ?**And what is long life for a mendicant?*";
P_HTM[1291]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu chandasamādhipadhānasaṅkhārasamannāgataṃ iddhipādaṃ bhāveti,**It’s when a mendicant develops the basis of psychic power that has immersion due to enthusiasm, and active effort.*";
P_HTM[1292]="*vīriyasamādhipadhānasaṅkhārasamannāgataṃ iddhipādaṃ bhāveti,**They develop the basis of psychic power that has immersion due to energy, and active effort.*";
P_HTM[1293]="*cittasamādhipadhānasaṅkhārasamannāgataṃ iddhipādaṃ bhāveti,**They develop the basis of psychic power that has immersion due to mental development, and active effort.*";
P_HTM[1294]="*vīmaṃsāsamādhipadhānasaṅkhārasamannāgataṃ iddhipādaṃ bhāveti.**They develop the basis of psychic power that has immersion due to inquiry, and active effort.*";
P_HTM[1295]="*So imesaṃ catunnaṃ iddhipādānaṃ bhāvitattā bahulīkatattā ākaṅkhamāno kappaṃ vā tiṭṭheyya kappāvasesaṃ vā.**Having developed and cultivated these four bases of psychic power they may, if they wish, live on for the eon or what’s left of the eon.*";
P_HTM[1296]="*Idaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno āyusmiṃ.**This is long life for a mendicant.*";
P_HTM[1297]="*Kiñca, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno vaṇṇasmiṃ?**And what is beauty for a mendicant?*";
P_HTM[1298]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu sīlavā hoti, pātimokkhasaṃvarasaṃvuto viharati ācāragocarasampanno, aṇumattesu vajjesu bhayadassāvī, samādāya sikkhati sikkhāpadesu.**It’s when a mendicant is ethical, restrained in the monastic code, conducting themselves well and seeking alms in suitable places. Seeing danger in the slightest fault, they keep the rules they’ve undertaken.*";
P_HTM[1299]="*Idaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno vaṇṇasmiṃ.**This is beauty for a mendicant.*";
P_HTM[1300]="*Kiñca, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno sukhasmiṃ?**And what is happiness for a mendicant?*";
P_HTM[1301]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu vivicceva kāmehi vivicca akusalehi dhammehi savitakkaṃ savicāraṃ vivekajaṃ pītisukhaṃ paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**It’s when a mendicant, quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, enters and remains in the first absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of seclusion, while placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[1302]="*Vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā … pe … dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ …**As the placing of the mind and keeping it connected are stilled, they enter and remain in the second absorption …*";
P_HTM[1303]="*tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ …**third absorption …*";
P_HTM[1304]="*catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**fourth absorption.*";
P_HTM[1305]="*Idaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno, sukhasmiṃ.**This is happiness for a mendicant.*";
P_HTM[1306]="*Kiñca, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno bhogasmiṃ?**And what is wealth for a mendicant?*";
P_HTM[1307]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu mettāsahagatena cetasā ekaṃ disaṃ pharitvā viharati tathā dutiyaṃ. Tathā tatiyaṃ. Tathā catutthaṃ. Iti uddhamadho tiriyaṃ sabbadhi sabbattatāya sabbāvantaṃ lokaṃ mettāsahagatena cetasā vipulena mahaggatena appamāṇena averena abyāpajjena pharitvā viharati.**It’s when a monk meditates spreading a heart full of love to one direction, and to the second, and to the third, and to the fourth. In the same way above, below, across, everywhere, all around, they spread a heart full of love to the whole world—abundant, expansive, limitless, free of enmity and ill will.*";
P_HTM[1308]="*Karuṇāsahagatena cetasā … pe …**They meditate spreading a heart full of compassion …*";
P_HTM[1309]="*muditāsahagatena cetasā … pe …**rejoicing …*";
P_HTM[1310]="*upekkhāsahagatena cetasā ekaṃ disaṃ pharitvā viharati. Tathā dutiyaṃ. Tathā tatiyaṃ. Tathā catutthaṃ. Iti uddhamadho tiriyaṃ sabbadhi sabbattatāya sabbāvantaṃ lokaṃ upekkhāsahagatena cetasā vipulena mahaggatena appamāṇena averena abyāpajjena pharitvā viharati.**equanimity to one direction, and to the second, and to the third, and to the fourth. In the same way above, below, across, everywhere, all around, they spread a heart full of equanimity to the whole world—abundant, expansive, limitless, free of enmity and ill will.*";
P_HTM[1311]="*Idaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno bhogasmiṃ.**This is wealth for a mendicant.*";
P_HTM[1312]="*Kiñca, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno balasmiṃ?**And what is power for a mendicant?*";
P_HTM[1313]="*Idha, bhikkhave, bhikkhu āsavānaṃ khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharati.**It’s when a mendicant realizes the undefiled freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom in this very life. And they live having realized it with their own insight due to the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[1314]="*Idaṃ kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhuno balasmiṃ.**This is power for a mendicant.*";
P_HTM[1315]="*Nāhaṃ, bhikkhave, aññaṃ ekabalampi samanupassāmi yaṃ evaṃ duppasahaṃ, yathayidaṃ, bhikkhave, mārabalaṃ.**Mendicants, I do not see a single power so hard to defeat as the power of Māra.*";
P_HTM[1316]="*Kusalānaṃ, bhikkhave, dhammānaṃ samādānahetu evamidaṃ puññaṃ pavaḍḍhatī”ti.**It is due to undertaking skillful qualities that this merit grows.”*";
P_HTM[1317]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[1318]="*Attamanā te bhikkhū bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, the mendicants were happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[1319]="*Cakkavattisuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1320]="*27. Aggaññasutta  - The Origin of the World * **";
P_HTM[1321]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[1322]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati pubbārāme migāramātupāsāde.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in the Eastern Monastery, in the stilt longhouse of Migāra’s mother.*";
P_HTM[1323]="*Tena kho pana samayena vāseṭṭhabhāradvājā bhikkhūsu parivasanti bhikkhubhāvaṃ ākaṅkhamānā.**Now at that time Vāseṭṭha and Bhāradvāja were living on probation among the mendicants in hopes of being ordained.*";
P_HTM[1324]="*Atha kho bhagavā sāyanhasamayaṃ paṭisallānā vuṭṭhito pāsādā orohitvā pāsādapacchāyāyaṃ abbhokāse caṅkamati.**Then in the late afternoon, the Buddha came downstairs from the longhouse and was walking meditation in the open air, beneath the shade of the longhouse.*";
P_HTM[1325]="*Addasā kho vāseṭṭho bhagavantaṃ sāyanhasamayaṃ paṭisallānā vuṭṭhitaṃ pāsādā orohitvā pāsādapacchāyāyaṃ abbhokāse caṅkamantaṃ.**Vāseṭṭha saw him*";
P_HTM[1326]="*Disvāna bhāradvājaṃ āmantesi:**and said to Bhāradvāja,*";
P_HTM[1327]="*“ayaṃ, āvuso bhāradvāja, bhagavā sāyanhasamayaṃ paṭisallānā vuṭṭhito pāsādā orohitvā pāsādapacchāyāyaṃ abbhokāse caṅkamati.**“Reverend Bhāradvāja, the Buddha is walking meditation in the open air, beneath the shade of the longhouse.*";
P_HTM[1328]="*Āyāmāvuso bhāradvāja, yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamissāma;**Come, reverend, let’s go to the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1329]="*appeva nāma labheyyāma bhagavato santikā dhammiṃ kathaṃ savanāyā”ti.**Hopefully we’ll get to hear a Dhamma talk from him.”*";
P_HTM[1330]="*“Evamāvuso”ti kho bhāradvājo vāseṭṭhassa paccassosi.**“Yes, reverend,” replied Bhāradvāja.*";
P_HTM[1331]="*Atha kho vāseṭṭhabhāradvājā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā bhagavantaṃ caṅkamantaṃ anucaṅkamiṃsu.**So they went to the Buddha, bowed, and walked beside him.*";
P_HTM[1332]="*Atha kho bhagavā vāseṭṭhaṃ āmantesi:**Then the Buddha said to Vāseṭṭha,*";
P_HTM[1333]="*“tumhe khvattha, vāseṭṭha, brāhmaṇajaccā brāhmaṇakulīnā brāhmaṇakulā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajitā, kacci vo, vāseṭṭha, brāhmaṇā na akkosanti na paribhāsantī”ti?**“Vāseṭṭha, you are both brahmins by birth and clan, and have gone forth from the lay life to homelessness from a brahmin family. I hope you don’t have to suffer abuse and insults from the brahmins.”*";
P_HTM[1334]="*“Taggha no, bhante, brāhmaṇā akkosanti paribhāsanti attarūpāya paribhāsāya paripuṇṇāya, no aparipuṇṇāyā”ti.**“Actually, sir, the brahmins do insult and abuse us with their typical insults to the fullest extent.”*";
P_HTM[1335]="*“Yathā kathaṃ pana vo, vāseṭṭha, brāhmaṇā akkosanti paribhāsanti attarūpāya paribhāsāya paripuṇṇāya, no aparipuṇṇāyā”ti?**“But how do the brahmins insult you?”*";
P_HTM[1336]="*“Brāhmaṇā, bhante, evamāhaṃsu:**“Sir, the brahmins say:*";
P_HTM[1337]="*‘brāhmaṇova seṭṭho vaṇṇo, hīnā aññe vaṇṇā.**‘Only brahmins are the highest caste; other castes are inferior.*";
P_HTM[1338]="*Brāhmaṇova sukko vaṇṇo, kaṇhā aññe vaṇṇā.**Only brahmins are the light caste; other castes are dark.*";
P_HTM[1339]="*Brāhmaṇāva sujjhanti, no abrāhmaṇā.**Only brahmins are purified, not others.*";
P_HTM[1340]="*Brāhmaṇāva brahmuno puttā orasā mukhato jātā brahmajā brahmanimmitā brahmadāyādā.**Only brahmins are Brahmā’s rightful sons, born of his mouth, born of Brahmā, created by Brahmā, heirs of Brahmā.*";
P_HTM[1341]="*Te tumhe seṭṭhaṃ vaṇṇaṃ hitvā hīnamattha vaṇṇaṃ ajjhupagatā, yadidaṃ muṇḍake samaṇake ibbhe kaṇhe bandhupādāpacce.**You’ve both abandoned the best caste to join an inferior caste, namely these shavelings, fake ascetics, riffraff, black spawn from the feet of our Kinsman.*";
P_HTM[1342]="*Tayidaṃ na sādhu, tayidaṃ nappatirūpaṃ, yaṃ tumhe seṭṭhaṃ vaṇṇaṃ hitvā hīnamattha vaṇṇaṃ ajjhupagatā yadidaṃ muṇḍake samaṇake ibbhe kaṇhe bandhupādāpacce’ti.**This is not right, it’s not proper!’*";
P_HTM[1343]="*Evaṃ kho no, bhante, brāhmaṇā akkosanti paribhāsanti attarūpāya paribhāsāya paripuṇṇāya, no aparipuṇṇāyā”ti.**That’s how the brahmins insult us.”*";
P_HTM[1344]="*“Taggha vo, vāseṭṭha, brāhmaṇā porāṇaṃ assarantā evamāhaṃsu:**“Actually, Vāseṭṭha, the brahmins are forgetting their tradition when they say this to you.*";
P_HTM[1345]="*‘brāhmaṇova seṭṭho vaṇṇo, hīnā aññe vaṇṇā;* **";
P_HTM[1346]="*brāhmaṇova sukko vaṇṇo, kaṇhā aññe vaṇṇā;* **";
P_HTM[1347]="*brāhmaṇāva sujjhanti, no abrāhmaṇā;* **";
P_HTM[1348]="*brāhmaṇāva brahmuno puttā orasā mukhato jātā brahmajā brahmanimmitā brahmadāyādā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1349]="*Dissanti kho pana, vāseṭṭha, brāhmaṇānaṃ brāhmaṇiyo utuniyopi gabbhiniyopi vijāyamānāpi pāyamānāpi.**For brahmin women are seen menstruating, being pregnant, giving birth, and breast-feeding.*";
P_HTM[1350]="*Te ca brāhmaṇā yonijāva samānā evamāhaṃsu:**Yet even though they’re born from a brahmin womb they say:*";
P_HTM[1351]="*‘brāhmaṇova seṭṭho vaṇṇo, hīnā aññe vaṇṇā;**‘Only brahmins are the highest caste; other castes are inferior.*";
P_HTM[1352]="*brāhmaṇova sukko vaṇṇo, kaṇhā aññe vaṇṇā;**Only brahmins are the light caste; other castes are dark.*";
P_HTM[1353]="*brāhmaṇāva sujjhanti, no abrāhmaṇā;**Only brahmins are purified, not others.*";
P_HTM[1354]="*brāhmaṇāva brahmuno puttā orasā mukhato jātā brahmajā brahmanimmitā brahmadāyādā’ti.**Only brahmins are Brahmā’s rightful sons, born of his mouth, born of Brahmā, created by Brahmā, heirs of Brahmā.’*";
P_HTM[1355]="*Te brahmānañceva abbhācikkhanti, musā ca bhāsanti, bahuñca apuññaṃ pasavanti.**They misrepresent the brahmins, speak falsely, and make much bad karma.*";
P_HTM[1356]="*1. Catuvaṇṇasuddhi**1. Purification in the Four Castes*";
P_HTM[1357]="*Cattārome, vāseṭṭha, vaṇṇā—**Vāseṭṭha, there are these four castes:*";
P_HTM[1358]="*khattiyā, brāhmaṇā, vessā, suddā.**aristocrats, brahmins, merchants, and workers.*";
P_HTM[1359]="*Khattiyopi kho, vāseṭṭha, idhekacco pāṇātipātī hoti adinnādāyī kāmesumicchācārī musāvādī pisuṇavāco pharusavāco samphappalāpī abhijjhālu byāpannacitto micchādiṭṭhī.**Some aristocrats kill living creatures, steal, and commit sexual misconduct. They use speech that’s false, divisive, harsh, and nonsensical. And they’re covetous, malicious, with wrong view.*";
P_HTM[1360]="*Iti kho, vāseṭṭha, yeme dhammā akusalā akusalasaṅkhātā sāvajjā sāvajjasaṅkhātā asevitabbā asevitabbasaṅkhātā naalamariyā naalamariyasaṅkhātā kaṇhā kaṇhavipākā viññugarahitā, khattiyepi te idhekacce sandissanti.**These things are unskillful, blameworthy, not to be cultivated, unworthy of the noble ones—and are reckoned as such. They are dark deeds with dark results, criticized by sensible people. Such things are seen in some aristocrats.*";
P_HTM[1361]="*Brāhmaṇopi kho, vāseṭṭha … pe …**And they are also seen among some brahmins,*";
P_HTM[1362]="*vessopi kho, vāseṭṭha … pe …**merchants,*";
P_HTM[1363]="*suddopi kho, vāseṭṭha, idhekacco pāṇātipātī hoti adinnādāyī kāmesumicchācārī musāvādī pisuṇavāco pharusavāco samphappalāpī abhijjhālu byāpannacitto micchādiṭṭhī.**and workers.*";
P_HTM[1364]="*Iti kho, vāseṭṭha, yeme dhammā akusalā akusalasaṅkhātā … pe …* **";
P_HTM[1365]="*kaṇhā kaṇhavipākā viññugarahitā;* **";
P_HTM[1366]="*suddepi te idhekacce sandissanti.* **";
P_HTM[1367]="*Khattiyopi kho, vāseṭṭha, idhekacco pāṇātipātā paṭivirato hoti, adinnādānā paṭivirato, kāmesumicchācārā paṭivirato, musāvādā paṭivirato, pisuṇāya vācāya paṭivirato, pharusāya vācāya paṭivirato, samphappalāpā paṭivirato, anabhijjhālu abyāpannacitto, sammādiṭṭhī.**But some aristocrats refrain from killing living creatures, stealing, and committing sexual misconduct. They refrain from speech that’s false, divisive, harsh, and nonsensical. And they’re content, kind-hearted, with right view.*";
P_HTM[1368]="*Iti kho, vāseṭṭha, yeme dhammā kusalā kusalasaṅkhātā anavajjā anavajjasaṅkhātā sevitabbā sevitabbasaṅkhātā alamariyā alamariyasaṅkhātā sukkā sukkavipākā viññuppasatthā, khattiyepi te idhekacce sandissanti.**These things are skillful, blameless, to be cultivated, worthy of the noble ones—and are reckoned as such. They are bright deeds with bright results, praised by sensible people. Such things are seen in some aristocrats.*";
P_HTM[1369]="*Brāhmaṇopi kho, vāseṭṭha … pe …**And they are also seen among some brahmins,*";
P_HTM[1370]="*vessopi kho, vāseṭṭha … pe …**merchants,*";
P_HTM[1371]="*suddopi kho, vāseṭṭha, idhekacco pāṇātipātā paṭivirato hoti … pe …**and workers.*";
P_HTM[1372]="*anabhijjhālu, abyāpannacitto, sammādiṭṭhī.* **";
P_HTM[1373]="*Iti kho, vāseṭṭha, yeme dhammā kusalā kusalasaṅkhātā anavajjā anavajjasaṅkhātā sevitabbā sevitabbasaṅkhātā alamariyā alamariyasaṅkhātā sukkā sukkavipākā viññuppasatthā;* **";
P_HTM[1374]="*suddepi te idhekacce sandissanti.* **";
P_HTM[1375]="*Imesu kho, vāseṭṭha, catūsu vaṇṇesu evaṃ ubhayavokiṇṇesu vattamānesu kaṇhasukkesu dhammesu viññugarahitesu ceva viññuppasatthesu ca yadettha brāhmaṇā evamāhaṃsu:**Both these things occur like this, mixed up in these four castes—the dark and the bright, that which is praised and that which is criticized by sensible people. Yet of this the brahmins say:*";
P_HTM[1376]="*‘brāhmaṇova seṭṭho vaṇṇo, hīnā aññe vaṇṇā;**‘Only brahmins are the highest caste; other castes are inferior.*";
P_HTM[1377]="*brāhmaṇova sukko vaṇṇo, kaṇhā aññe vaṇṇā;**Only brahmins are the light caste; other castes are dark.*";
P_HTM[1378]="*brāhmaṇāva sujjhanti, no abrāhmaṇā;**Only brahmins are purified, not others.*";
P_HTM[1379]="*brāhmaṇāva brahmuno puttā orasā mukhato jātā brahmajā brahmanimmitā brahmadāyādā’ti.**Only brahmins are Brahmā’s rightful sons, born of his mouth, born of Brahmā, created by Brahmā, heirs of Brahmā.’*";
P_HTM[1380]="*Taṃ tesaṃ viññū nānujānanti.**Sensible people don’t acknowledge this.*";
P_HTM[1381]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[1382]="*Imesañhi, vāseṭṭha, catunnaṃ vaṇṇānaṃ yo hoti bhikkhu arahaṃ khīṇāsavo vusitavā katakaraṇīyo ohitabhāro anuppattasadattho parikkhīṇabhavasaṃyojano sammadaññāvimutto, so nesaṃ aggamakkhāyati dhammeneva, no adhammena.**Because any mendicant from these four castes who is perfected—with defilements ended, who has completed the spiritual journey, done what had to be done, laid down the burden, achieved their own true goal, utterly ended the fetters of rebirth, and is rightly freed through enlightenment—is said to be the best by virtue of principle, not without principle.*";
P_HTM[1383]="*Dhammo hi, vāseṭṭha, seṭṭho janetasmiṃ, diṭṭhe ceva dhamme abhisamparāyañca.**For principle, Vāseṭṭha, is the best thing about people in both this life and the next.*";
P_HTM[1384]="*Tadamināpetaṃ, vāseṭṭha, pariyāyena veditabbaṃ, yathā dhammova seṭṭho janetasmiṃ, diṭṭhe ceva dhamme abhisamparāyañca.**And here’s a way to understand how this is so.*";
P_HTM[1385]="*Jānāti kho, vāseṭṭha, rājā pasenadi kosalo:**King Pasenadi of Kosala knows that*";
P_HTM[1386]="*‘samaṇo gotamo anantarā sakyakulā pabbajito’ti.**the ascetic Gotama has gone forth from the neighboring clan of the Sakyans.*";
P_HTM[1387]="*Sakyā kho pana, vāseṭṭha, rañño pasenadissa kosalassa anuyuttā bhavanti.**And the Sakyans are his vassals.*";
P_HTM[1388]="*Karonti kho, vāseṭṭha, sakyā raññe pasenadimhi kosale nipaccakāraṃ abhivādanaṃ paccuṭṭhānaṃ añjalikammaṃ sāmīcikammaṃ.**The Sakyans show deference to King Pasenadi by bowing down, rising up, greeting him with joined palms, and observing proper etiquette for him.*";
P_HTM[1389]="*Iti kho, vāseṭṭha, yaṃ karonti sakyā raññe pasenadimhi kosale nipaccakāraṃ abhivādanaṃ paccuṭṭhānaṃ añjalikammaṃ sāmīcikammaṃ, karoti taṃ rājā pasenadi kosalo tathāgate nipaccakāraṃ abhivādanaṃ paccuṭṭhānaṃ añjalikammaṃ sāmīcikammaṃ, na naṃ ‘sujāto samaṇo gotamo, dujjātohamasmi.**Now, King Pasenadi shows the same kind of deference to the Realized One. But he doesn’t think: ‘The ascetic Gotama is well-born, I am ill-born.*";
P_HTM[1390]="*Balavā samaṇo gotamo, dubbalohamasmi.**He is powerful, I am weak.*";
P_HTM[1391]="*Pāsādiko samaṇo gotamo, dubbaṇṇohamasmi.**He is handsome, I am ugly.*";
P_HTM[1392]="*Mahesakkho samaṇo gotamo, appesakkhohamasmī’ti.**He is influential, I am insignificant.’*";
P_HTM[1393]="*Atha kho naṃ dhammaṃyeva sakkaronto dhammaṃ garuṃ karonto dhammaṃ mānento dhammaṃ pūjento dhammaṃ apacāyamāno evaṃ rājā pasenadi kosalo tathāgate nipaccakāraṃ karoti, abhivādanaṃ paccuṭṭhānaṃ añjalikammaṃ sāmīcikammaṃ.**Rather, in showing such deference to the Realized One he is only honoring, respecting, and venerating principle.*";
P_HTM[1394]="*Imināpi kho etaṃ, vāseṭṭha, pariyāyena veditabbaṃ, yathā dhammova seṭṭho janetasmiṃ, diṭṭhe ceva dhamme abhisamparāyañca.**And here’s another way to understand how principle is the best thing about people in both this life and the next.*";
P_HTM[1395]="*Tumhe khvattha, vāseṭṭha, nānājaccā nānānāmā nānāgottā nānākulā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajitā.**Vāseṭṭha, you have different births, names, and clans, and have gone forth from the lay life to homelessness from different families.*";
P_HTM[1396]="*‘Ke tumhe’ti—puṭṭhā samānā ‘samaṇā sakyaputtiyāmhā’ti—paṭijānātha.**When they ask you what you are, you claim to be ascetics, followers of the Sakyan.*";
P_HTM[1397]="*Yassa kho panassa, vāseṭṭha, tathāgate saddhā niviṭṭhā mūlajātā patiṭṭhitā daḷhā asaṃhāriyā samaṇena vā brāhmaṇena vā devena vā mārena vā brahmunā vā kenaci vā lokasmiṃ, tassetaṃ kallaṃ vacanāya:**But only when someone has faith in the Realized One—settled, rooted, and planted deep, strong, not to be shifted by any ascetic or brahmin or god or Māra or Brahmā or by anyone in the world—is it appropriate for them to say:*";
P_HTM[1398]="*‘bhagavatomhi putto oraso mukhato jāto dhammajo dhammanimmito dhammadāyādo’ti.**‘I am the Buddha’s true-born child, born from his mouth, born of principle, created by principle, heir to principle.’*";
P_HTM[1399]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[1400]="*Tathāgatassa hetaṃ, vāseṭṭha, adhivacanaṃ ‘dhammakāyo’ itipi, ‘brahmakāyo’ itipi, ‘dhammabhūto’ itipi, ‘brahmabhūto’ itipi.**For these are terms for the Realized One: ‘the embodiment of truth’, and ‘the embodiment of holiness’, and ‘the one who has become the truth’, and ‘the one who has become holy’.*";
P_HTM[1401]="*Hoti kho so, vāseṭṭha, samayo yaṃ kadāci karahaci dīghassa addhuno accayena ayaṃ loko saṃvaṭṭati.**There comes a time when, Vāseṭṭha, after a very long period has passed, this cosmos contracts.*";
P_HTM[1402]="*Saṃvaṭṭamāne loke yebhuyyena sattā ābhassarasaṃvattanikā honti.**As the cosmos contracts, sentient beings are mostly headed for the realm of streaming radiance.*";
P_HTM[1403]="*Te tattha honti manomayā pītibhakkhā sayaṃpabhā antalikkhacarā subhaṭṭhāyino ciraṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ tiṭṭhanti.**There they are mind-made, feeding on rapture, self-luminous, moving through the sky, steadily glorious, and they remain like that for a very long time.*";
P_HTM[1404]="*Hoti kho so, vāseṭṭha, samayo yaṃ kadāci karahaci dīghassa addhuno accayena ayaṃ loko vivaṭṭati.**There comes a time when, after a very long period has passed, this cosmos expands.*";
P_HTM[1405]="*Vivaṭṭamāne loke yebhuyyena sattā ābhassarakāyā cavitvā itthattaṃ āgacchanti.**As the cosmos expands, sentient beings mostly pass away from that host of radiant deities and come back to this realm.*";
P_HTM[1406]="*Tedha honti manomayā pītibhakkhā sayaṃpabhā antalikkhacarā subhaṭṭhāyino ciraṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ tiṭṭhanti.**Here they are mind-made, feeding on rapture, self-luminous, moving through the sky, steadily glorious, and they remain like that for a very long time.*";
P_HTM[1407]="*2. Rasapathavipātubhāva**2. Solid Nectar Appears*";
P_HTM[1408]="*Ekodakībhūtaṃ kho pana, vāseṭṭha, tena samayena hoti andhakāro andhakāratimisā.**But the single mass of water at that time was utterly dark.*";
P_HTM[1409]="*Na candimasūriyā paññāyanti, na nakkhattāni tārakarūpāni paññāyanti, na rattindivā paññāyanti, na māsaḍḍhamāsā paññāyanti, na utusaṃvaccharā paññāyanti, na itthipumā paññāyanti, sattā sattātveva saṅkhyaṃ gacchanti.**The moon and sun were not found, nor were stars and constellations, day and night, months and fortnights, years and seasons, or male and female. Beings were simply known as ‘beings’.*";
P_HTM[1410]="*Atha kho tesaṃ, vāseṭṭha, sattānaṃ kadāci karahaci dīghassa addhuno accayena rasapathavī udakasmiṃ samatani;**After a very long period had passed, solid nectar curdled in the water.*";
P_HTM[1411]="*seyyathāpi nāma payaso tattassa nibbāyamānassa upari santānakaṃ hoti;**It appeared just like the curd on top of hot milk as it cools.*";
P_HTM[1412]="*evameva pāturahosi.* **";
P_HTM[1413]="*Sā ahosi vaṇṇasampannā gandhasampannā rasasampannā, seyyathāpi nāma sampannaṃ vā sappi sampannaṃ vā navanītaṃ evaṃvaṇṇā ahosi.**It was beautiful, fragrant, and delicious, like ghee or butter.*";
P_HTM[1414]="*Seyyathāpi nāma khuddamadhuṃ aneḷakaṃ;**And it was as sweet as pure manuka honey.*";
P_HTM[1415]="*evamassādā ahosi.* **";
P_HTM[1416]="*Atha kho, vāseṭṭha, aññataro satto lolajātiko:**Now, one of those beings was reckless.*";
P_HTM[1417]="*‘ambho, kimevidaṃ bhavissatī’ti rasapathaviṃ aṅguliyā sāyi.**Thinking, ‘Oh my, what might this be?’ they tasted the solid nectar with their finger.*";
P_HTM[1418]="*Tassa rasapathaviṃ aṅguliyā sāyato acchādesi, taṇhā cassa okkami.**They enjoyed it, and craving was born in them.*";
P_HTM[1419]="*Aññepi kho, vāseṭṭha, sattā tassa sattassa diṭṭhānugatiṃ āpajjamānā rasapathaviṃ aṅguliyā sāyiṃsu.**And other beings, following that being’s example, tasted solid nectar with their fingers.*";
P_HTM[1420]="*Tesaṃ rasapathaviṃ aṅguliyā sāyataṃ acchādesi, taṇhā ca tesaṃ okkami.**They too enjoyed it, and craving was born in them.*";
P_HTM[1421]="*3. Candimasūriyādipātubhāva**3. The Moon and Sun Appear*";
P_HTM[1422]="*Atha kho te, vāseṭṭha, sattā rasapathaviṃ hatthehi āluppakārakaṃ upakkamiṃsu paribhuñjituṃ.**Then those beings started to eat the solid nectar, breaking it into lumps.*";
P_HTM[1423]="*Yato kho te, vāseṭṭha, sattā rasapathaviṃ hatthehi āluppakārakaṃ upakkamiṃsu paribhuñjituṃ.**But when they did this*";
P_HTM[1424]="*Atha tesaṃ sattānaṃ sayaṃpabhā antaradhāyi.**their luminosity vanished.*";
P_HTM[1425]="*Sayaṃpabhāya antarahitāya candimasūriyā pāturahesuṃ.**And with the vanishing of their luminosity the moon and sun appeared,*";
P_HTM[1426]="*Candimasūriyesu pātubhūtesu nakkhattāni tārakarūpāni pāturahesuṃ.**stars and constellations appeared,*";
P_HTM[1427]="*Nakkhattesu tārakarūpesu pātubhūtesu rattindivā paññāyiṃsu.**days and nights were distinguished,*";
P_HTM[1428]="*Rattindivesu paññāyamānesu māsaḍḍhamāsā paññāyiṃsu.**and so were months and fortnights,*";
P_HTM[1429]="*Māsaḍḍhamāsesu paññāyamānesu utusaṃvaccharā paññāyiṃsu.**and years and seasons.*";
P_HTM[1430]="*Ettāvatā kho, vāseṭṭha, ayaṃ loko puna vivaṭṭo hoti.**To this extent the world had evolved once more.*";
P_HTM[1431]="*Atha kho te, vāseṭṭha, sattā rasapathaviṃ paribhuñjantā tambhakkhā tadāhārā ciraṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ aṭṭhaṃsu.**Then those beings eating the solid nectar, with that as their food and nourishment, remained for a very long time.*";
P_HTM[1432]="*Yathā yathā kho te, vāseṭṭha, sattā rasapathaviṃ paribhuñjantā tambhakkhā tadāhārā ciraṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ aṭṭhaṃsu tathā tathā tesaṃ sattānaṃ rasapathaviṃ paribhuñjantānaṃ kharattañceva kāyasmiṃ okkami, vaṇṇavevaṇṇatā ca paññāyittha.**But so long as they ate that solid nectar, their bodies became more solid and they diverged in appearance;*";
P_HTM[1433]="*Ekidaṃ sattā vaṇṇavanto honti, ekidaṃ sattā dubbaṇṇā.**some beautiful, some ugly.*";
P_HTM[1434]="*Tattha ye te sattā vaṇṇavanto, te dubbaṇṇe satte atimaññanti:**And the beautiful beings looked down on the ugly ones:*";
P_HTM[1435]="*‘mayametehi vaṇṇavantatarā, amhehete dubbaṇṇatarā’ti.**‘We’re more beautiful, they’re the ugly ones!’*";
P_HTM[1436]="*Tesaṃ vaṇṇātimānapaccayā mānātimānajātikānaṃ rasapathavī antaradhāyi.**And the vanity of the beautiful ones made the solid nectar vanish.*";
P_HTM[1437]="*Rasāya pathaviyā antarahitāya sannipatiṃsu.**They gathered together and bemoaned,*";
P_HTM[1438]="*Sannipatitvā anutthuniṃsu:* **";
P_HTM[1439]="*‘aho rasaṃ, aho rasan’ti.**‘Oh, what a taste! Oh, what a taste!’*";
P_HTM[1440]="*Tadetarahipi manussā kañcideva surasaṃ labhitvā evamāhaṃsu:**And even today when people get something tasty they say:*";
P_HTM[1441]="*‘aho rasaṃ, aho rasan’ti.**‘Oh, what a taste! Oh, what a taste!’*";
P_HTM[1442]="*Tadeva porāṇaṃ aggaññaṃ akkharaṃ anusaranti, na tvevassa atthaṃ ājānanti.**They’re just remembering an ancient traditional saying, but they don’t understand what it means.*";
P_HTM[1443]="*4. Bhūmipappaṭakapātubhāva**4. Ground-Sprouts*";
P_HTM[1444]="*Atha kho tesaṃ, vāseṭṭha, sattānaṃ rasāya pathaviyā antarahitāya bhūmipappaṭako pāturahosi.**When the solid nectar had vanished, ground-sprouts appeared to those beings.*";
P_HTM[1445]="*Seyyathāpi nāma ahicchattako; evameva pāturahosi.**They appeared just like mushrooms.*";
P_HTM[1446]="*So ahosi vaṇṇasampanno gandhasampanno rasasampanno, seyyathāpi nāma sampannaṃ vā sappi sampannaṃ vā navanītaṃ evaṃvaṇṇo ahosi.**They were beautiful, fragrant, and delicious, like ghee or butter.*";
P_HTM[1447]="*Seyyathāpi nāma khuddamadhuṃ aneḷakaṃ; evamassādo ahosi.**And they were as sweet as pure manuka honey.*";
P_HTM[1448]="*Atha kho te, vāseṭṭha, sattā bhūmipappaṭakaṃ upakkamiṃsu paribhuñjituṃ.**Then those beings started to eat the ground-sprouts.*";
P_HTM[1449]="*Te taṃ paribhuñjantā tambhakkhā tadāhārā ciraṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ aṭṭhaṃsu.**With that as their food and nourishment, they remained for a very long time.*";
P_HTM[1450]="*Yathā yathā kho te, vāseṭṭha, sattā bhūmipappaṭakaṃ paribhuñjantā tambhakkhā tadāhārā ciraṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ aṭṭhaṃsu tathā tathā tesaṃ sattānaṃ bhiyyoso mattāya kharattañceva kāyasmiṃ okkami, vaṇṇavevaṇṇatā ca paññāyittha.**But so long as they ate those ground-sprouts, their bodies became more solid and they diverged in appearance;*";
P_HTM[1451]="*Ekidaṃ sattā vaṇṇavanto honti, ekidaṃ sattā dubbaṇṇā.**some beautiful, some ugly.*";
P_HTM[1452]="*Tattha ye te sattā vaṇṇavanto, te dubbaṇṇe satte atimaññanti:**And the beautiful beings looked down on the ugly ones:*";
P_HTM[1453]="*‘mayametehi vaṇṇavantatarā, amhehete dubbaṇṇatarā’ti.**‘We’re more beautiful, they’re the ugly ones!’*";
P_HTM[1454]="*Tesaṃ vaṇṇātimānapaccayā mānātimānajātikānaṃ bhūmipappaṭako antaradhāyi.**And the vanity of the beautiful ones made the ground-sprouts vanish.*";
P_HTM[1455]="*5. Padālatāpātubhāva**5. Bursting Pods*";
P_HTM[1456]="*Bhūmipappaṭake antarahite padālatā pāturahosi, seyyathāpi nāma kalambukā; evameva pāturahosi.**When the ground-sprouts had vanished, bursting pods appeared, like the fruit of the kadam tree.*";
P_HTM[1457]="*Sā ahosi vaṇṇasampannā gandhasampannā rasasampannā, seyyathāpi nāma sampannaṃ vā sappi sampannaṃ vā navanītaṃ evaṃvaṇṇā ahosi.**They were beautiful, fragrant, and delicious, like ghee or butter.*";
P_HTM[1458]="*Seyyathāpi nāma khuddamadhuṃ aneḷakaṃ; evamassādā ahosi.**And they were as sweet as pure manuka honey.*";
P_HTM[1459]="*Atha kho te, vāseṭṭha, sattā padālataṃ upakkamiṃsu paribhuñjituṃ.**Then those beings started to eat the bursting pods.*";
P_HTM[1460]="*Te taṃ paribhuñjantā tambhakkhā tadāhārā ciraṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ aṭṭhaṃsu.**With that as their food and nourishment, they remained for a very long time.*";
P_HTM[1461]="*Yathā yathā kho te, vāseṭṭha, sattā padālataṃ paribhuñjantā tambhakkhā tadāhārā ciraṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ aṭṭhaṃsu tathā tathā tesaṃ sattānaṃ bhiyyoso mattāya kharattañceva kāyasmiṃ okkami, vaṇṇavevaṇṇatā ca paññāyittha.**But so long as they ate those bursting pods, their bodies became more solid and they diverged in appearance;*";
P_HTM[1462]="*Ekidaṃ sattā vaṇṇavanto honti, ekidaṃ sattā dubbaṇṇā.**some beautiful, some ugly.*";
P_HTM[1463]="*Tattha ye te sattā vaṇṇavanto, te dubbaṇṇe satte atimaññanti:**And the beautiful beings looked down on the ugly ones:*";
P_HTM[1464]="*‘mayametehi vaṇṇavantatarā, amhehete dubbaṇṇatarā’ti.**‘We’re more beautiful, they’re the ugly ones!’*";
P_HTM[1465]="*Tesaṃ vaṇṇātimānapaccayā mānātimānajātikānaṃ padālatā antaradhāyi.**And the vanity of the beautiful ones made the bursting pods vanish.*";
P_HTM[1466]="*Padālatāya antarahitāya sannipatiṃsu. Sannipatitvā anutthuniṃsu:**They gathered together and bemoaned,*";
P_HTM[1467]="*‘ahu vata no, ahāyi vata no padālatā’ti.**‘Oh, what we’ve lost! Oh, what we’ve lost—those bursting pods!’*";
P_HTM[1468]="*Tadetarahipi manussā kenaci dukkhadhammena phuṭṭhā evamāhaṃsu:**And even today when people experience suffering they say:*";
P_HTM[1469]="*‘ahu vata no, ahāyi vata no’ti.**‘Oh, what we’ve lost! Oh, what we’ve lost!’*";
P_HTM[1470]="*Tadeva porāṇaṃ aggaññaṃ akkharaṃ anusaranti, na tvevassa atthaṃ ājānanti.**They’re just remembering an ancient traditional saying, but they don’t understand what it means.*";
P_HTM[1471]="*6. Akaṭṭhapākasālipātubhāva**6. Ripe Untilled Rice*";
P_HTM[1472]="*Atha kho tesaṃ, vāseṭṭha, sattānaṃ padālatāya antarahitāya akaṭṭhapāko sāli pāturahosi akaṇo athuso suddho sugandho taṇḍulapphalo.**When the bursting pods had vanished, ripe untilled rice appeared to those beings. It had no powder or husk, pure and fragrant, with only the rice-grain.*";
P_HTM[1473]="*Yaṃ taṃ sāyaṃ sāyamāsāya āharanti, pāto taṃ hoti pakkaṃ paṭivirūḷhaṃ.**What they took for supper in the evening, by the morning had grown back and ripened.*";
P_HTM[1474]="*Yaṃ taṃ pāto pātarāsāya āharanti, sāyaṃ taṃ hoti pakkaṃ paṭivirūḷhaṃ;**And what they took for breakfast in the morning had grown back and ripened by the evening,*";
P_HTM[1475]="*nāpadānaṃ paññāyati.**so the cutting didn’t show.*";
P_HTM[1476]="*Atha kho te, vāseṭṭha, sattā akaṭṭhapākaṃ sāliṃ paribhuñjantā tambhakkhā tadāhārā ciraṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ aṭṭhaṃsu.**Then those beings eating the ripe untilled rice, with that as their food and nourishment, remained for a very long time.*";
P_HTM[1477]="*7. Itthipurisaliṅgapātubhāva**7. Gender Appears*";
P_HTM[1478]="*Yathā yathā kho te, vāseṭṭha, sattā akaṭṭhapākaṃ sāliṃ paribhuñjantā tambhakkhā tadāhārā ciraṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ aṭṭhaṃsu tathā tathā tesaṃ sattānaṃ bhiyyoso mattāya kharattañceva kāyasmiṃ okkami, vaṇṇavevaṇṇatā ca paññāyittha, itthiyā ca itthiliṅgaṃ pāturahosi purisassa ca purisaliṅgaṃ.**But so long as they ate that ripe untilled rice, their bodies became more solid and they diverged in appearance. And female characteristics appeared on women, while male characteristics appeared on men.*";
P_HTM[1479]="*Itthī ca purisaṃ ativelaṃ upanijjhāyati puriso ca itthiṃ.**Women spent too much time gazing at men, and men at women.*";
P_HTM[1480]="*Tesaṃ ativelaṃ aññamaññaṃ upanijjhāyataṃ sārāgo udapādi, pariḷāho kāyasmiṃ okkami.**They became lustful, and their bodies burned with fever.*";
P_HTM[1481]="*Te pariḷāhapaccayā methunaṃ dhammaṃ paṭiseviṃsu.**Due to this fever they had sex with each other.*";
P_HTM[1482]="*Ye kho pana te, vāseṭṭha, tena samayena sattā passanti methunaṃ dhammaṃ paṭisevante, aññe paṃsuṃ khipanti, aññe seṭṭhiṃ khipanti, aññe gomayaṃ khipanti:**Those who saw them having sex pelted them with dirt, ashes, or cow-dung, saying,*";
P_HTM[1483]="*‘nassa asuci, nassa asucī’ti.**‘Get lost, filth! Get lost, filth!*";
P_HTM[1484]="*‘Kathañhi nāma satto sattassa evarūpaṃ karissatī’ti.**How on earth can one being do that to another?’*";
P_HTM[1485]="*Tadetarahipi manussā ekaccesu janapadesu vadhuyā nibbuyhamānāya aññe paṃsuṃ khipanti, aññe seṭṭhiṃ khipanti, aññe gomayaṃ khipanti.**And even today people in some countries, when a bride is carried off, pelt her with dirt, ashes, or cow-dung.*";
P_HTM[1486]="*Tadeva porāṇaṃ aggaññaṃ akkharaṃ anusaranti, na tvevassa atthaṃ ājānanti.**They’re just remembering an ancient traditional saying, but they don’t understand what it means.*";
P_HTM[1487]="*8. Methunadhammasamācāra**8. Sexual Intercourse*";
P_HTM[1488]="*Adhammasammataṃ kho pana, vāseṭṭha, tena samayena hoti, tadetarahi dhammasammataṃ.**What was reckoned as immoral at that time, these days is reckoned as moral.*";
P_HTM[1489]="*Ye kho pana, vāseṭṭha, tena samayena sattā methunaṃ dhammaṃ paṭisevanti, te māsampi dvemāsampi na labhanti gāmaṃ vā nigamaṃ vā pavisituṃ.**The beings who had sex together weren’t allowed to enter a village or town for one or two months.*";
P_HTM[1490]="*Yato kho te, vāseṭṭha, sattā tasmiṃ asaddhamme ativelaṃ pātabyataṃ āpajjiṃsu.**Ever since they excessively threw themselves into immorality,*";
P_HTM[1491]="*Atha agārāni upakkamiṃsu kātuṃ tasseva asaddhammassa paṭicchādanatthaṃ.**they started to make buildings to hide their immoral deeds.*";
P_HTM[1492]="*Atha kho, vāseṭṭha, aññatarassa sattassa alasajātikassa etadahosi:**Then one of those beings of idle disposition thought,*";
P_HTM[1493]="*‘ambho, kimevāhaṃ vihaññāmi sāliṃ āharanto sāyaṃ sāyamāsāya pāto pātarāsāya.**‘Hey now, why should I be bothered to gather rice in the evening for supper, and in the morning for breakfast?*";
P_HTM[1494]="*Yannūnāhaṃ sāliṃ āhareyyaṃ sakideva sāyapātarāsāyā’ti.**Why don’t I gather rice for supper and breakfast all at once?’*";
P_HTM[1495]="*Atha kho so, vāseṭṭha, satto sāliṃ āhāsi sakideva sāyapātarāsāya.**So that’s what he did.*";
P_HTM[1496]="*Atha kho, vāseṭṭha, aññataro satto yena so satto tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā taṃ sattaṃ etadavoca:**Then one of the other beings approached that being and said,*";
P_HTM[1497]="*‘ehi, bho satta, sālāhāraṃ gamissāmā’ti.**‘Come, good being, we shall go to gather rice.’*";
P_HTM[1498]="*‘Alaṃ, bho satta, āhato me sāli sakideva sāyapātarāsāyā’ti.**‘There’s no need, good being! I gathered rice for supper and breakfast all at once.’*";
P_HTM[1499]="*Atha kho so, vāseṭṭha, satto tassa sattassa diṭṭhānugatiṃ āpajjamāno sāliṃ āhāsi sakideva dvīhāya. ‘Evampi kira, bho, sādhū’ti.**So that being, following their example, gathered rice for two days all at once, thinking: ‘This seems fine.’*";
P_HTM[1500]="*Atha kho, vāseṭṭha, aññataro satto yena so satto tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā taṃ sattaṃ etadavoca:**Then one of the other beings approached that being and said,*";
P_HTM[1501]="*‘ehi, bho satta, sālāhāraṃ gamissāmā’ti.**‘Come, good being, we shall go to gather rice.’*";
P_HTM[1502]="*‘Alaṃ, bho satta, āhato me sāli sakideva dvīhāyā’ti.**‘There’s no need, good being! I gathered rice for two days all at once.’*";
P_HTM[1503]="*Atha kho so, vāseṭṭha, satto tassa sattassa diṭṭhānugatiṃ āpajjamāno sāliṃ āhāsi sakideva catūhāya, ‘evampi kira, bho, sādhū’ti.**So that being, following their example, gathered rice for four days all at once, thinking: ‘This seems fine.’*";
P_HTM[1504]="*Atha kho, vāseṭṭha, aññataro satto yena so satto tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā taṃ sattaṃ etadavoca:**Then one of the other beings approached that being and said,*";
P_HTM[1505]="*‘ehi, bho satta, sālāhāraṃ gamissāmā’ti.**‘Come, good being, we shall go to gather rice.’*";
P_HTM[1506]="*‘Alaṃ, bho satta, āhato me sāli sakideva catūhāyā’ti.**‘There’s no need, good being! I gathered rice for four days all at once.’*";
P_HTM[1507]="*Atha kho so, vāseṭṭha, satto tassa sattassa diṭṭhānugatiṃ āpajjamāno sāliṃ āhāsi sakideva aṭṭhāhāya, ‘evampi kira, bho, sādhū’ti.**So that being, following their example, gathered rice for eight days all at once, thinking: ‘This seems fine.’*";
P_HTM[1508]="*Yato kho te, vāseṭṭha, sattā sannidhikārakaṃ sāliṃ upakkamiṃsu paribhuñjituṃ.**But when they started to store up rice to eat,*";
P_HTM[1509]="*Atha kaṇopi taṇḍulaṃ pariyonandhi, thusopi taṇḍulaṃ pariyonandhi;**the rice grains became wrapped in powder and husk,*";
P_HTM[1510]="*lūnampi nappaṭivirūḷhaṃ, apadānaṃ paññāyittha, saṇḍasaṇḍā sālayo aṭṭhaṃsu.**it didn’t grow back after reaping, the cutting showed, and the rice stood in clumps.*";
P_HTM[1511]="*9. Sālivibhāga**9. Dividing the Fields*";
P_HTM[1512]="*Atha kho te, vāseṭṭha, sattā sannipatiṃsu, sannipatitvā anutthuniṃsu:**Then those beings gathered together and bemoaned,*";
P_HTM[1513]="*‘pāpakā vata, bho, dhammā sattesu pātubhūtā.**‘Oh, how wicked things have appeared among beings!*";
P_HTM[1514]="*Mayañhi pubbe manomayā ahumhā pītibhakkhā sayaṃpabhā antalikkhacarā subhaṭṭhāyino, ciraṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ aṭṭhamhā.**For we used to be mind-made, feeding on rapture, self-luminous, moving through the sky, steadily glorious, and we remained like that for a very long time.*";
P_HTM[1515]="*Tesaṃ no amhākaṃ kadāci karahaci dīghassa addhuno accayena rasapathavī udakasmiṃ samatani.**After a very long period had passed, solid nectar curdled in the water.*";
P_HTM[1516]="*Sā ahosi vaṇṇasampannā gandhasampannā rasasampannā.* **";
P_HTM[1517]="*Te mayaṃ rasapathaviṃ hatthehi āluppakārakaṃ upakkamimha paribhuñjituṃ, tesaṃ no rasapathaviṃ hatthehi āluppakārakaṃ upakkamataṃ paribhuñjituṃ sayaṃpabhā antaradhāyi.* **";
P_HTM[1518]="*Sayaṃpabhāya antarahitāya candimasūriyā pāturahesuṃ, candimasūriyesu pātubhūtesu nakkhattāni tārakarūpāni pāturahesuṃ, nakkhattesu tārakarūpesu pātubhūtesu rattindivā paññāyiṃsu, rattindivesu paññāyamānesu māsaḍḍhamāsā paññāyiṃsu.* **";
P_HTM[1519]="*Māsaḍḍhamāsesu paññāyamānesu utusaṃvaccharā paññāyiṃsu.* **";
P_HTM[1520]="*Te mayaṃ rasapathaviṃ paribhuñjantā tambhakkhā tadāhārā ciraṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ aṭṭhamhā.* **";
P_HTM[1521]="*Tesaṃ no pāpakānaṃyeva akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ pātubhāvā rasapathavī antaradhāyi.**But due to bad, unskillful things among us, the savory nectar vanished,*";
P_HTM[1522]="*Rasapathaviyā antarahitāya bhūmipappaṭako pāturahosi.* **";
P_HTM[1523]="*So ahosi vaṇṇasampanno gandhasampanno rasasampanno.* **";
P_HTM[1524]="*Te mayaṃ bhūmipappaṭakaṃ upakkamimha paribhuñjituṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1525]="*Te mayaṃ taṃ paribhuñjantā tambhakkhā tadāhārā ciraṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ aṭṭhamhā.* **";
P_HTM[1526]="*Tesaṃ no pāpakānaṃyeva akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ pātubhāvā bhūmipappaṭako antaradhāyi.**the ground-sprouts vanished,*";
P_HTM[1527]="*Bhūmipappaṭake antarahite padālatā pāturahosi.* **";
P_HTM[1528]="*Sā ahosi vaṇṇasampannā gandhasampannā rasasampannā.* **";
P_HTM[1529]="*Te mayaṃ padālataṃ upakkamimha paribhuñjituṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1530]="*Te mayaṃ taṃ paribhuñjantā tambhakkhā tadāhārā ciraṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ aṭṭhamhā.* **";
P_HTM[1531]="*Tesaṃ no pāpakānaṃyeva akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ pātubhāvā padālatā antaradhāyi.**the bursting pods vanished,*";
P_HTM[1532]="*Padālatāya antarahitāya akaṭṭhapāko sāli pāturahosi akaṇo athuso suddho sugandho taṇḍulapphalo.* **";
P_HTM[1533]="*Yaṃ taṃ sāyaṃ sāyamāsāya āharāma, pāto taṃ hoti pakkaṃ paṭivirūḷhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1534]="*Yaṃ taṃ pāto pātarāsāya āharāma, sāyaṃ taṃ hoti pakkaṃ paṭivirūḷhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1535]="*Nāpadānaṃ paññāyittha.* **";
P_HTM[1536]="*Te mayaṃ akaṭṭhapākaṃ sāliṃ paribhuñjantā tambhakkhā tadāhārā ciraṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ aṭṭhamhā.* **";
P_HTM[1537]="*Tesaṃ no pāpakānaṃyeva akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ pātubhāvā kaṇopi taṇḍulaṃ pariyonandhi, thusopi taṇḍulaṃ pariyonandhi, lūnampi nappaṭivirūḷhaṃ, apadānaṃ paññāyittha, saṇḍasaṇḍā sālayo ṭhitā.**and now the rice grains have become wrapped in powder and husk, it doesn’t grow back after reaping, the cutting shows, and the rice stands in clumps.*";
P_HTM[1538]="*Yannūna mayaṃ sāliṃ vibhajeyyāma, mariyādaṃ ṭhapeyyāmā’ti.**We’d better divide up the rice and set boundaries.’*";
P_HTM[1539]="*Atha kho te, vāseṭṭha, sattā sāliṃ vibhajiṃsu, mariyādaṃ ṭhapesuṃ.**So that’s what they did.*";
P_HTM[1540]="*Atha kho, vāseṭṭha, aññataro satto lolajātiko sakaṃ bhāgaṃ parirakkhanto aññataraṃ bhāgaṃ adinnaṃ ādiyitvā paribhuñji.**Now, one of those beings was reckless. While guarding their own share they took another’s share without it being given, and ate it.*";
P_HTM[1541]="*Tamenaṃ aggahesuṃ, gahetvā etadavocuṃ:**They grabbed the one who had done this and said,*";
P_HTM[1542]="*‘pāpakaṃ vata, bho satta, karosi, yatra hi nāma sakaṃ bhāgaṃ parirakkhanto aññataraṃ bhāgaṃ adinnaṃ ādiyitvā paribhuñjasi.**‘You have done a bad thing, good being, in that while guarding your own share you took another’s share without it being given, and ate it.*";
P_HTM[1543]="*Māssu, bho satta, punapi evarūpamakāsī’ti.**Do not do such a thing again.’*";
P_HTM[1544]="*‘Evaṃ, bho’ti kho, vāseṭṭha, so satto tesaṃ sattānaṃ paccassosi.**‘Yes, sirs,’ replied that being.*";
P_HTM[1545]="*Dutiyampi kho, vāseṭṭha, so satto … pe …**But for a second time,*";
P_HTM[1546]="*tatiyampi kho, vāseṭṭha, so satto sakaṃ bhāgaṃ parirakkhanto aññataraṃ bhāgaṃ adinnaṃ ādiyitvā paribhuñji.**and a third time they did the same thing, and were told not to continue.*";
P_HTM[1547]="*Tamenaṃ aggahesuṃ, gahetvā etadavocuṃ:* **";
P_HTM[1548]="*‘pāpakaṃ vata, bho satta, karosi, yatra hi nāma sakaṃ bhāgaṃ parirakkhanto aññataraṃ bhāgaṃ adinnaṃ ādiyitvā paribhuñjasi.* **";
P_HTM[1549]="*Māssu, bho satta, punapi evarūpamakāsī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1550]="*Aññe pāṇinā pahariṃsu, aññe leḍḍunā pahariṃsu, aññe daṇḍena pahariṃsu.**And then they struck that being, some with fists, others with stones, and still others with rods.*";
P_HTM[1551]="*Tadagge kho, vāseṭṭha, adinnādānaṃ paññāyati, garahā paññāyati, musāvādo paññāyati, daṇḍādānaṃ paññāyati.**From that day on stealing was found, and blaming and lying and the taking up of rods.*";
P_HTM[1552]="*10. Mahāsammatarājā**10. The Elected King*";
P_HTM[1553]="*Atha kho te, vāseṭṭha, sattā sannipatiṃsu, sannipatitvā anutthuniṃsu:**Then those beings gathered together and bemoaned,*";
P_HTM[1554]="*‘pāpakā vata bho dhammā sattesu pātubhūtā, yatra hi nāma adinnādānaṃ paññāyissati, garahā paññāyissati, musāvādo paññāyissati, daṇḍādānaṃ paññāyissati.**‘Oh, how wicked things have appeared among beings, in that stealing is found, and blaming and lying and the taking up of rods!*";
P_HTM[1555]="*Yannūna mayaṃ ekaṃ sattaṃ sammanneyyāma, yo no sammā khīyitabbaṃ khīyeyya, sammā garahitabbaṃ garaheyya, sammā pabbājetabbaṃ pabbājeyya.**Why don’t we elect one being who would rightly accuse those who deserve it, blame those who deserve it, and expel those who deserve it?*";
P_HTM[1556]="*Mayaṃ panassa sālīnaṃ bhāgaṃ anuppadassāmā’ti.**We shall pay them with a share of rice.’*";
P_HTM[1557]="*Atha kho te, vāseṭṭha, sattā yo nesaṃ satto abhirūpataro ca dassanīyataro ca pāsādikataro ca mahesakkhataro ca taṃ sattaṃ upasaṅkamitvā etadavocuṃ:**Then those beings approached the being among them who was most attractive, good-looking, lovely, and illustrious, and said,*";
P_HTM[1558]="*‘ehi, bho satta, sammā khīyitabbaṃ khīya, sammā garahitabbaṃ garaha, sammā pabbājetabbaṃ pabbājehi.**‘Come, good being, rightly accuse those who deserve it, blame those who deserve it, and banish those who deserve it.*";
P_HTM[1559]="*Mayaṃ pana te sālīnaṃ bhāgaṃ anuppadassāmā’ti.**We shall pay you with a share of rice.’*";
P_HTM[1560]="*‘Evaṃ, bho’ti kho, vāseṭṭha, so satto tesaṃ sattānaṃ paṭissuṇitvā sammā khīyitabbaṃ khīyi, sammā garahitabbaṃ garahi, sammā pabbājetabbaṃ pabbājesi.**‘Yes, sirs,’ replied that being. They acted accordingly,*";
P_HTM[1561]="*Te panassa sālīnaṃ bhāgaṃ anuppadaṃsu.**and were paid with a share of rice.*";
P_HTM[1562]="*Mahājanasammatoti kho, vāseṭṭha, ‘mahāsammato, mahāsammato’ tveva paṭhamaṃ akkharaṃ upanibbattaṃ.**‘Elected by the people’, Vāseṭṭha, is the meaning of ‘elected one’, the first term to be specifically invented for them.*";
P_HTM[1563]="*Khettānaṃ adhipatīti kho, vāseṭṭha, ‘khattiyo, khattiyo’ tveva dutiyaṃ akkharaṃ upanibbattaṃ.**‘Lord of the fields’ is the meaning of ‘aristocrat’, the second term to be specifically invented.*";
P_HTM[1564]="*Dhammena pare rañjetīti kho, vāseṭṭha, ‘rājā, rājā’ tveva tatiyaṃ akkharaṃ upanibbattaṃ.**‘They please others with principle’ is the meaning of ‘king’, the third term to be specifically invented.*";
P_HTM[1565]="*Iti kho, vāseṭṭha, evametassa khattiyamaṇḍalassa porāṇena aggaññena akkharena abhinibbatti ahosi tesaṃyeva sattānaṃ, anaññesaṃ. Sadisānaṃyeva, no asadisānaṃ. Dhammeneva, no adhammena.**And that, Vāseṭṭha, is how the ancient traditional terms for the circle of aristocrats were created; for those very beings, not others; for those like them, not unlike; legitimately, not illegitimately.*";
P_HTM[1566]="*Dhammo hi, vāseṭṭha, seṭṭho janetasmiṃ diṭṭhe ceva dhamme abhisamparāyañca.**For principle, Vāseṭṭha, is the best thing about people in both this life and the next.*";
P_HTM[1567]="*11. Brāhmaṇamaṇḍala**11. The Circle of Brahmins*";
P_HTM[1568]="*Atha kho tesaṃ, vāseṭṭha, sattānaṃyeva ekaccānaṃ etadahosi:**Then some of those same beings thought,*";
P_HTM[1569]="*‘pāpakā vata, bho, dhammā sattesu pātubhūtā, yatra hi nāma adinnādānaṃ paññāyissati, garahā paññāyissati, musāvādo paññāyissati, daṇḍādānaṃ paññāyissati, pabbājanaṃ paññāyissati.**‘Oh, how wicked things have appeared among beings, in that stealing is found, and blaming and lying and the taking up of rods and banishment!*";
P_HTM[1570]="*Yannūna mayaṃ pāpake akusale dhamme vāheyyāmā’ti.**Why don’t we set aside bad, unskillful things?’*";
P_HTM[1571]="*Te pāpake akusale dhamme vāhesuṃ.**So that’s what they did.*";
P_HTM[1572]="*Pāpake akusale dhamme vāhentīti kho, vāseṭṭha, ‘brāhmaṇā, brāhmaṇā’ tveva paṭhamaṃ akkharaṃ upanibbattaṃ.**‘They set aside bad, unskillful things’ is the meaning of ‘brahmin’, the first term to be specifically invented for them.*";
P_HTM[1573]="*Te araññāyatane paṇṇakuṭiyo karitvā paṇṇakuṭīsu jhāyanti vītaṅgārā vītadhūmā pannamusalā sāyaṃ sāyamāsāya pāto pātarāsāya gāmanigamarājadhāniyo osaranti ghāsamesamānā.**They built leaf huts in a wilderness region where they meditated pure and bright, without lighting cooking fires or digging the soil. They came down in the morning for breakfast and in the evening for supper to the village, town, or royal capital seeking a meal.*";
P_HTM[1574]="*Te ghāsaṃ paṭilabhitvā punadeva araññāyatane paṇṇakuṭīsu jhāyanti.**When they had obtained food they continued to meditate in the leaf huts.*";
P_HTM[1575]="*Tamenaṃ manussā disvā evamāhaṃsu:**When people noticed this they said,*";
P_HTM[1576]="*‘ime kho, bho, sattā araññāyatane paṇṇakuṭiyo karitvā paṇṇakuṭīsu jhāyanti, vītaṅgārā vītadhūmā pannamusalā sāyaṃ sāyamāsāya pāto pātarāsāya gāmanigamarājadhāniyo osaranti ghāsamesamānā.**‘These beings build leaf huts in a wilderness region where they meditate pure and bright, without lighting cooking fires or digging the soil. They come down in the morning for breakfast and in the evening for supper to the village, town, or royal capital seeking a meal.*";
P_HTM[1577]="*Te ghāsaṃ paṭilabhitvā punadeva araññāyatane paṇṇakuṭīsu jhāyantī’ti,**When they have obtained food they continue to meditate in the leaf huts.’*";
P_HTM[1578]="*jhāyantīti kho, vāseṭṭha, ‘jhāyakā, jhāyakā’ tveva dutiyaṃ akkharaṃ upanibbattaṃ.**‘They meditate’ is the meaning of ‘meditator’, the second term to be specifically invented for them.*";
P_HTM[1579]="*Tesaṃyeva kho, vāseṭṭha, sattānaṃ ekacce sattā araññāyatane paṇṇakuṭīsu taṃ jhānaṃ anabhisambhuṇamānā gāmasāmantaṃ nigamasāmantaṃ osaritvā ganthe karontā acchanti.**But some of those beings were unable to keep up with their meditation in the leaf huts in the wilderness. They came down to the neighborhood of a village or town where they dwelt compiling texts.*";
P_HTM[1580]="*Tamenaṃ manussā disvā evamāhaṃsu:**When people noticed this they said,*";
P_HTM[1581]="*‘ime kho, bho, sattā araññāyatane paṇṇakuṭīsu taṃ jhānaṃ anabhisambhuṇamānā gāmasāmantaṃ nigamasāmantaṃ osaritvā ganthe karontā acchanti, na dānime jhāyantī’ti.**‘These beings were unable to keep up with their meditation in the leaf huts in the wilderness. They came down to the neighborhood of a village or town where they dwelt compiling texts. Now they don’t meditate.’*";
P_HTM[1582]="*Na dānime jhāyantīti kho, vāseṭṭha, ‘ajjhāyakā, ajjhāyakā’ tveva tatiyaṃ akkharaṃ upanibbattaṃ.**‘Now they don’t meditate’ is the meaning of ‘reciter’, the third term to be specifically invented for them.*";
P_HTM[1583]="*Hīnasammataṃ kho pana, vāseṭṭha, tena samayena hoti, tadetarahi seṭṭhasammataṃ.**What was reckoned as lesser at that time, these days is reckoned as better.*";
P_HTM[1584]="*Iti kho, vāseṭṭha, evametassa brāhmaṇamaṇḍalassa porāṇena aggaññena akkharena abhinibbatti ahosi tesaṃyeva sattānaṃ, anaññesaṃ sadisānaṃyeva no asadisānaṃ dhammeneva, no adhammena.**And that, Vāseṭṭha, is how the ancient traditional terms for the circle of brahmins were created; for those very beings, not others; for those like them, not unlike; legitimately, not illegitimately.*";
P_HTM[1585]="*Dhammo hi, vāseṭṭha, seṭṭho janetasmiṃ diṭṭhe ceva dhamme abhisamparāyañca.**For principle, Vāseṭṭha, is the best thing about people in both this life and the next.*";
P_HTM[1586]="*12. Vessamaṇḍala**12. The Circle of Merchants*";
P_HTM[1587]="*Tesaṃyeva kho, vāseṭṭha, sattānaṃ ekacce sattā methunaṃ dhammaṃ samādāya visukammante payojesuṃ.**Some of those same beings, taking up an active sex life, applied themselves to various jobs.*";
P_HTM[1588]="*Methunaṃ dhammaṃ samādāya visukammante payojentīti kho, vāseṭṭha, ‘vessā, vessā’ tveva akkharaṃ upanibbattaṃ.**‘Having taken up an active sex life, they apply themselves to various jobs’ is the meaning of ‘merchant’, the term specifically invented for them.*";
P_HTM[1589]="*Iti kho, vāseṭṭha, evametassa vessamaṇḍalassa porāṇena aggaññena akkharena abhinibbatti ahosi tesaññeva sattānaṃ anaññesaṃ sadisānaṃyeva, no asadisānaṃ, dhammeneva no adhammena.**And that, Vāseṭṭha, is how the ancient traditional term for the circle of merchants was created; for those very beings, not others; for those like them, not unlike; legitimately, not illegitimately.*";
P_HTM[1590]="*Dhammo hi, vāseṭṭha, seṭṭho janetasmiṃ diṭṭhe ceva dhamme abhisamparāyañca.**For principle, Vāseṭṭha, is the best thing about people in both this life and the next.*";
P_HTM[1591]="*13. Suddamaṇḍala**13. The Circle of Workers*";
P_HTM[1592]="*Tesaññeva kho, vāseṭṭha, sattānaṃ ye te sattā avasesā te luddācārā khuddācārā ahesuṃ.**The remaining beings lived by hunting and menial tasks.*";
P_HTM[1593]="*Luddācārā khuddācārāti kho, vāseṭṭha, ‘suddā, suddā’ tveva akkharaṃ upanibbattaṃ.**‘They live by hunting and menial tasks’ is the meaning of ‘worker’, the term specifically invented for them.*";
P_HTM[1594]="*Iti kho, vāseṭṭha, evametassa suddamaṇḍalassa porāṇena aggaññena akkharena abhinibbatti ahosi tesaṃyeva sattānaṃ anaññesaṃ, sadisānaṃyeva no asadisānaṃ, dhammeneva, no adhammena.**And that, Vāseṭṭha, is how the ancient traditional term for the circle of workers was created; for those very beings, not others; for those like them, not unlike; legitimately, not illegitimately.*";
P_HTM[1595]="*Dhammo hi, vāseṭṭha, seṭṭho janetasmiṃ diṭṭhe ceva dhamme abhisamparāyañca.**For principle, Vāseṭṭha, is the best thing about people in both this life and the next.*";
P_HTM[1596]="*Ahu kho so, vāseṭṭha, samayo, yaṃ khattiyopi sakaṃ dhammaṃ garahamāno agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajati:**There came a time when an aristocrat, brahmin, merchant, or worker, deprecating their own vocation, went forth from the lay life to homelessness, thinking,*";
P_HTM[1597]="*‘samaṇo bhavissāmī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1598]="*Brāhmaṇopi kho, vāseṭṭha … pe …* **";
P_HTM[1599]="*vessopi kho, vāseṭṭha … pe …* **";
P_HTM[1600]="*suddopi kho, vāseṭṭha, sakaṃ dhammaṃ garahamāno agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajati:* **";
P_HTM[1601]="*‘samaṇo bhavissāmī’ti.**‘I will be an ascetic.’*";
P_HTM[1602]="*Imehi kho, vāseṭṭha, catūhi maṇḍalehi samaṇamaṇḍalassa abhinibbatti ahosi, tesaṃyeva sattānaṃ anaññesaṃ, sadisānaṃyeva no asadisānaṃ, dhammeneva no adhammena.**And that, Vāseṭṭha, is how these four circles were created; for those very beings, not others; for those like them, not unlike; legitimately, not illegitimately.*";
P_HTM[1603]="*Dhammo hi, vāseṭṭha, seṭṭho janetasmiṃ diṭṭhe ceva dhamme abhisamparāyañca.**For principle, Vāseṭṭha, is the best thing about people in both this life and the next.*";
P_HTM[1604]="*14. Duccaritādikathā**14. On Bad Conduct*";
P_HTM[1605]="*Khattiyopi kho, vāseṭṭha, kāyena duccaritaṃ caritvā vācāya duccaritaṃ caritvā manasā duccaritaṃ caritvā micchādiṭṭhiko micchādiṭṭhikammasamādāno micchādiṭṭhikammasamādānahetu kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati.**An aristocrat, brahmin, merchant, worker, or ascetic may do bad things by way of body, speech, and mind. They have wrong view, and they act out of that wrong view. And because of that, when their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell.*";
P_HTM[1606]="*Brāhmaṇopi kho, vāseṭṭha … pe …* **";
P_HTM[1607]="*vessopi kho, vāseṭṭha …* **";
P_HTM[1608]="*suddopi kho, vāseṭṭha …* **";
P_HTM[1609]="*samaṇopi kho, vāseṭṭha, kāyena duccaritaṃ caritvā vācāya duccaritaṃ caritvā manasā duccaritaṃ caritvā micchādiṭṭhiko micchādiṭṭhikammasamādāno micchādiṭṭhikammasamādānahetu kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati.* **";
P_HTM[1610]="*Khattiyopi kho, vāseṭṭha, kāyena sucaritaṃ caritvā vācāya sucaritaṃ caritvā manasā sucaritaṃ caritvā sammādiṭṭhiko sammādiṭṭhikammasamādāno sammādiṭṭhikammasamādānahetu kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati.* **";
P_HTM[1611]="*Brāhmaṇopi kho, vāseṭṭha … pe …* **";
P_HTM[1612]="*vessopi kho, vāseṭṭha …* **";
P_HTM[1613]="*suddopi kho, vāseṭṭha …* **";
P_HTM[1614]="*samaṇopi kho, vāseṭṭha, kāyena sucaritaṃ caritvā vācāya sucaritaṃ caritvā manasā sucaritaṃ caritvā sammādiṭṭhiko sammādiṭṭhikammasamādāno sammādiṭṭhikammasamādānahetu kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati.**An aristocrat, brahmin, merchant, worker, or ascetic may do good things by way of body, speech, and mind. They have right view, and they act out of that right view. And because of that, when their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[1615]="*Khattiyopi kho, vāseṭṭha, kāyena dvayakārī, vācāya dvayakārī, manasā dvayakārī, vimissadiṭṭhiko vimissadiṭṭhikammasamādāno vimissadiṭṭhikammasamādānahetu kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī hoti.* **";
P_HTM[1616]="*Brāhmaṇopi kho, vāseṭṭha … pe …* **";
P_HTM[1617]="*vessopi kho, vāseṭṭha …* **";
P_HTM[1618]="*suddopi kho, vāseṭṭha …* **";
P_HTM[1619]="*samaṇopi kho, vāseṭṭha, kāyena dvayakārī, vācāya dvayakārī, manasā dvayakārī, vimissadiṭṭhiko vimissadiṭṭhikammasamādāno vimissadiṭṭhikammasamādānahetu kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī hoti.* **";
P_HTM[1620]="*15. Bodhipakkhiyabhāvanā**15. The Qualities That Lead to Awakening*";
P_HTM[1621]="*Khattiyopi kho, vāseṭṭha, kāyena saṃvuto vācāya saṃvuto manasā saṃvuto sattannaṃ bodhipakkhiyānaṃ dhammānaṃ bhāvanamanvāya diṭṭheva dhamme parinibbāyati.**An aristocrat, brahmin, merchant, worker, or ascetic who is restrained in body, speech, and mind, and develops the seven qualities that lead to awakening, becomes extinguished in this very life.*";
P_HTM[1622]="*Brāhmaṇopi kho, vāseṭṭha … pe …* **";
P_HTM[1623]="*vessopi kho, vāseṭṭha …* **";
P_HTM[1624]="*suddopi kho, vāseṭṭha …* **";
P_HTM[1625]="*samaṇopi kho, vāseṭṭha, kāyena saṃvuto vācāya saṃvuto manasā saṃvuto sattannaṃ bodhipakkhiyānaṃ dhammānaṃ bhāvanamanvāya diṭṭheva dhamme parinibbāyati.* **";
P_HTM[1626]="*Imesañhi, vāseṭṭha, catunnaṃ vaṇṇānaṃ yo hoti bhikkhu arahaṃ khīṇāsavo vusitavā katakaraṇīyo ohitabhāro anuppattasadattho parikkhīṇabhavasaṃyojano sammadaññāvimutto, so nesaṃ aggamakkhāyati dhammeneva, no adhammena.**Any mendicant from these four castes who is perfected—with defilements ended, who has completed the spiritual journey, done what had to be done, laid down the burden, achieved their own true goal, utterly ended the fetters of rebirth, and is rightly freed through enlightenment—is said to be the best by virtue of principle, not without principle.*";
P_HTM[1627]="*Dhammo hi, vāseṭṭha, seṭṭho janetasmiṃ diṭṭhe ceva dhamme abhisamparāyañca.**For principle, Vāseṭṭha, is the best thing about people in both this life and the next.*";
P_HTM[1628]="*Brahmunā pesā, vāseṭṭha, sanaṅkumārena gāthā bhāsitā:**Brahmā Sanaṅkumāra also spoke this verse:*";
P_HTM[1629]="*‘Khattiyo seṭṭho janetasmiṃ,**‘The aristocrat is best of those people*";
P_HTM[1630]="*ye gottapaṭisārino;**who take clan as the standard.*";
P_HTM[1631]="*Vijjācaraṇasampanno,**But one accomplished in knowledge and conduct*";
P_HTM[1632]="*so seṭṭho devamānuse’ti.**is best of gods and humans.’*";
P_HTM[1633]="*Sā kho panesā, vāseṭṭha, brahmunā sanaṅkumārena gāthā sugītā, no duggītā. Subhāsitā, no dubbhāsitā. Atthasaṃhitā, no anatthasaṃhitā. Anumatā mayā.**That verse was well sung by Brahmā Sanaṅkumāra, not poorly sung; well spoken, not poorly spoken; beneficial, not harmful, and I agree with it.*";
P_HTM[1634]="*Ahampi, vāseṭṭha, evaṃ vadāmi—**I also say:*";
P_HTM[1635]="*Khattiyo seṭṭho janetasmiṃ,**The aristocrat is best of those people*";
P_HTM[1636]="*ye gottapaṭisārino;**who take clan as the standard.*";
P_HTM[1637]="*Vijjācaraṇasampanno,**But one accomplished in knowledge and conduct*";
P_HTM[1638]="*so seṭṭho devamānuse”ti.**is best of gods and humans.”*";
P_HTM[1639]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[1640]="*Attamanā vāseṭṭhabhāradvājā bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, Vāseṭṭha and Bhāradvāja were happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[1641]="*Aggaññasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1642]="*28. Sampasādanīyasutta  - Inspiring Confidence * **";
P_HTM[1643]="*1. Sāriputtasīhanāda**1. Sāriputta’s Lion’s Roar*";
P_HTM[1644]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[1645]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā nāḷandāyaṃ viharati pāvārikambavane.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Nālandā in Pāvārika’s mango grove.*";
P_HTM[1646]="*Atha kho āyasmā sāriputto yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā sāriputto bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Sāriputta went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him:*";
P_HTM[1647]="*“evaṃpasanno ahaṃ, bhante, bhagavati, na cāhu na ca bhavissati na cetarahi vijjati añño samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā bhagavatā bhiyyobhiññataro yadidaṃ sambodhiyan”ti.**“Sir, I have such confidence in the Buddha that I believe there’s no other ascetic or brahmin—whether past, future, or present—whose direct knowledge is superior to the Buddha when it comes to awakening.”*";
P_HTM[1648]="*“Uḷārā kho te ayaṃ, sāriputta, āsabhī vācā bhāsitā, ekaṃso gahito, sīhanādo nadito:**“That’s a grand and dramatic statement, Sāriputta. You’ve roared a definitive, categorical lion’s roar, saying:*";
P_HTM[1649]="*‘evaṃpasanno ahaṃ, bhante, bhagavati;**‘I have such confidence in the Buddha that*";
P_HTM[1650]="*na cāhu na ca bhavissati na cetarahi vijjati añño samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā bhagavatā bhiyyobhiññataro yadidaṃ sambodhiyan’ti.**I believe there’s no other ascetic or brahmin—whether past, future, or present—whose direct knowledge is superior to the Buddha when it comes to awakening.’*";
P_HTM[1651]="*Kiṃ te, sāriputta, ye te ahesuṃ atītamaddhānaṃ arahanto sammāsambuddhā, sabbe te bhagavanto cetasā ceto paricca viditā:**What about all the perfected ones, the fully awakened Buddhas who lived in the past? Have you comprehended their minds to know that*";
P_HTM[1652]="*‘evaṃsīlā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ itipi, evaṃdhammā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ itipi, evaṃpaññā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ itipi, evaṃvihārī te bhagavanto ahesuṃ itipi, evaṃvimuttā te bhagavanto ahesuṃ itipī’”ti?**those Buddhas had such ethics, or such qualities, or such wisdom, or such meditation, or such freedom?”*";
P_HTM[1653]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1654]="*“Kiṃ pana te, sāriputta, ye te bhavissanti anāgatamaddhānaṃ arahanto sammāsambuddhā, sabbe te bhagavanto cetasā ceto paricca viditā:**“And what about all the perfected ones, the fully awakened Buddhas who will live in the future? Have you comprehended their minds to know that*";
P_HTM[1655]="*‘evaṃsīlā te bhagavanto bhavissanti itipi, evaṃdhammā … evaṃpaññā … evaṃvihārī … evaṃvimuttā te bhagavanto bhavissanti itipī’”ti?**those Buddhas will have such ethics, or such qualities, or such wisdom, or such meditation, or such freedom?”*";
P_HTM[1656]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1657]="*“Kiṃ pana te, sāriputta, ahaṃ etarahi arahaṃ sammāsambuddho cetasā ceto paricca vidito:**“And what about me, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha at present? Have you comprehended my mind to know that*";
P_HTM[1658]="*‘evaṃsīlo bhagavā itipi, evaṃdhammo … evaṃpañño … evaṃvihārī … evaṃvimutto bhagavā itipī’”ti?**I have such ethics, or such qualities, or such wisdom, or such meditation, or such freedom?”*";
P_HTM[1659]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1660]="*“Ettha ca hi te, sāriputta, atītānāgatapaccuppannesu arahantesu sammāsambuddhesu cetopariyañāṇaṃ natthi.**“Well then, Sāriputta, given that you don’t comprehend the minds of Buddhas past, future, or present,*";
P_HTM[1661]="*Atha kiṃ carahi te ayaṃ, sāriputta, uḷārā āsabhī vācā bhāsitā, ekaṃso gahito, sīhanādo nadito:**what exactly are you doing, making such a grand and dramatic statement, roaring such a definitive, categorical lion’s roar?”*";
P_HTM[1662]="*‘evaṃpasanno ahaṃ, bhante, bhagavati, na cāhu na ca bhavissati na cetarahi vijjati añño samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā bhagavatā bhiyyobhiññataro yadidaṃ sambodhiyan’”ti?* **";
P_HTM[1663]="*“Na kho me, bhante, atītānāgatapaccuppannesu arahantesu sammāsambuddhesu cetopariyañāṇaṃ atthi.**“Sir, though I don’t comprehend the minds of Buddhas past, future, and present,*";
P_HTM[1664]="*Api ca me dhammanvayo vidito.**still I understand this by inference from the teaching.*";
P_HTM[1665]="*Seyyathāpi, bhante, rañño paccantimaṃ nagaraṃ daḷhuddhāpaṃ daḷhapākāratoraṇaṃ ekadvāraṃ.**Suppose there were a king’s frontier citadel with fortified embankments, ramparts, and arches, and a single gate.*";
P_HTM[1666]="*Tatrassa dovāriko paṇḍito byatto medhāvī aññātānaṃ nivāretā, ñātānaṃ pavesetā.**And it has a gatekeeper who is astute, competent, and clever. He keeps strangers out and lets known people in.*";
P_HTM[1667]="*So tassa nagarassa samantā anupariyāyapathaṃ anukkamamāno na passeyya pākārasandhiṃ vā pākāravivaraṃ vā antamaso biḷāranikkhamanamattampi.**As he walks around the patrol path, he doesn’t see a hole or cleft in the wall, not even one big enough for a cat to slip out.*";
P_HTM[1668]="*Tassa evamassa:**They’d think,*";
P_HTM[1669]="*‘ye kho keci oḷārikā pāṇā imaṃ nagaraṃ pavisanti vā nikkhamanti vā, sabbe te imināva dvārena pavisanti vā nikkhamanti vā’ti.**‘Whatever sizable creatures enter or leave the citadel, all of them do so via this gate.’*";
P_HTM[1670]="*Evameva kho me, bhante, dhammanvayo vidito.**In the same way, I understand this by inference from the teaching:*";
P_HTM[1671]="*Ye te, bhante, ahesuṃ atītamaddhānaṃ arahanto sammāsambuddhā, sabbe te bhagavanto pañca nīvaraṇe pahāya cetaso upakkilese paññāya dubbalīkaraṇe catūsu satipaṭṭhānesu suppatiṭṭhitacittā, satta sambojjhaṅge yathābhūtaṃ bhāvetvā anuttaraṃ sammāsambodhiṃ abhisambujjhiṃsu.**‘All the perfected ones, fully awakened Buddhas—whether past, future, or present—give up the five hindrances, corruptions of the heart that weaken wisdom. Their mind is firmly established in the four kinds of mindfulness meditation. They correctly develop the seven awakening factors. And they wake up to the supreme perfect awakening.’*";
P_HTM[1672]="*Yepi te, bhante, bhavissanti anāgatamaddhānaṃ arahanto sammāsambuddhā, sabbe te bhagavanto pañca nīvaraṇe pahāya cetaso upakkilese paññāya dubbalīkaraṇe catūsu satipaṭṭhānesu suppatiṭṭhitacittā, satta sambojjhaṅge yathābhūtaṃ bhāvetvā anuttaraṃ sammāsambodhiṃ abhisambujjhissanti.* **";
P_HTM[1673]="*Bhagavāpi, bhante, etarahi arahaṃ sammāsambuddho pañca nīvaraṇe pahāya cetaso upakkilese paññāya dubbalīkaraṇe catūsu satipaṭṭhānesu suppatiṭṭhitacitto satta sambojjhaṅge yathābhūtaṃ bhāvetvā anuttaraṃ sammāsambodhiṃ abhisambuddho.* **";
P_HTM[1674]="*Idhāhaṃ, bhante, yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃ dhammassavanāya.**Sir, once I approached the Buddha to listen to the teaching.*";
P_HTM[1675]="*Tassa me, bhante, bhagavā dhammaṃ deseti uttaruttaraṃ paṇītapaṇītaṃ kaṇhasukkasappaṭibhāgaṃ.**He explained Dhamma with its higher and higher stages, with its better and better stages, with its dark and bright sides.*";
P_HTM[1676]="*Yathā yathā me, bhante, bhagavā dhammaṃ desesi uttaruttaraṃ paṇītapaṇītaṃ kaṇhasukkasappaṭibhāgaṃ tathā tathāhaṃ tasmiṃ dhamme abhiññā idhekaccaṃ dhammaṃ dhammesu niṭṭhamagamaṃ; satthari pasīdiṃ:**When I directly knew a certain principle of those teachings, in accordance with how I was taught, I came to a conclusion about the teachings. I had confidence in the Teacher:*";
P_HTM[1677]="*‘sammāsambuddho bhagavā, svākkhāto bhagavatā dhammo, suppaṭipanno sāvakasaṅgho’ti.**‘The Blessed One is a fully awakened Buddha. The teaching is well explained. The Saṅgha is practicing well.’*";
P_HTM[1678]="*1.1. Kusaladhammadesanā**1.1. Teaching Skillful Qualities*";
P_HTM[1679]="*Aparaṃ pana, bhante, etadānuttariyaṃ, yathā bhagavā dhammaṃ deseti kusalesu dhammesu.**And moreover, sir, how the Buddha teaches skillful qualities is unsurpassable.*";
P_HTM[1680]="*Tatrime kusalā dhammā seyyathidaṃ—**This consists of such skillful qualities as*";
P_HTM[1681]="*cattāro satipaṭṭhānā, cattāro sammappadhānā, cattāro iddhipādā, pañcindriyāni, pañca balāni, satta bojjhaṅgā, ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo.**the four kinds of mindfulness meditation, the four right efforts, the four bases of psychic power, the five faculties, the five powers, the seven awakening factors, and the noble eightfold path.*";
P_HTM[1682]="*Idha, bhante, bhikkhu āsavānaṃ khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharati.**By these a mendicant realizes the undefiled freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom in this very life. And they live having realized it with their own insight due to the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[1683]="*Etadānuttariyaṃ, bhante, kusalesu dhammesu.**This is unsurpassable when it comes to skillful qualities.*";
P_HTM[1684]="*Taṃ bhagavā asesamabhijānāti, taṃ bhagavato asesamabhijānato uttari abhiññeyyaṃ natthi, yadabhijānaṃ añño samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā bhagavatā bhiyyobhiññataro assa, yadidaṃ kusalesu dhammesu.**The Buddha understands this without exception. There is nothing to be understood beyond this whereby another ascetic or brahmin might be superior in direct knowledge to the Buddha when it comes to skillful qualities.*";
P_HTM[1685]="*1.2. Āyatanapaṇṇattidesanā**1.2. Describing the Sense Fields*";
P_HTM[1686]="*Aparaṃ pana, bhante, etadānuttariyaṃ, yathā bhagavā dhammaṃ deseti āyatanapaṇṇattīsu.**And moreover, sir, how the Buddha teaches the description of the sense fields is unsurpassable.*";
P_HTM[1687]="*Chayimāni, bhante, ajjhattikabāhirāni āyatanāni.**There are these six interior and exterior sense fields.*";
P_HTM[1688]="*Cakkhuñceva rūpā ca, sotañceva saddā ca, ghānañceva gandhā ca, jivhā ceva rasā ca, kāyo ceva phoṭṭhabbā ca, mano ceva dhammā ca.**The eye and sights, the ear and sounds, the nose and smells, the tongue and tastes, the body and touches, and the mind and thoughts.*";
P_HTM[1689]="*Etadānuttariyaṃ, bhante, āyatanapaṇṇattīsu.**This is unsurpassable when it comes to describing the sense fields.*";
P_HTM[1690]="*Taṃ bhagavā asesamabhijānāti, taṃ bhagavato asesamabhijānato uttari abhiññeyyaṃ natthi, yadabhijānaṃ añño samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā bhagavatā bhiyyobhiññataro assa yadidaṃ āyatanapaṇṇattīsu.**The Buddha understands this without exception. There is nothing to be understood beyond this whereby another ascetic or brahmin might be superior in direct knowledge to the Buddha when it comes to describing the sense fields.*";
P_HTM[1691]="*1.3. Gabbhāvakkantidesanā**1.3. The Conception of the Embryo*";
P_HTM[1692]="*Aparaṃ pana, bhante, etadānuttariyaṃ, yathā bhagavā dhammaṃ deseti gabbhāvakkantīsu.**And moreover, sir, how the Buddha teaches the conception of the embryo is unsurpassable.*";
P_HTM[1693]="*Catasso imā, bhante, gabbhāvakkantiyo.**There are these four kinds of conception.*";
P_HTM[1694]="*Idha, bhante, ekacco asampajāno mātukucchiṃ okkamati; asampajāno mātukucchismiṃ ṭhāti; asampajāno mātukucchimhā nikkhamati. Ayaṃ paṭhamā gabbhāvakkanti.**Firstly, someone is unaware when conceived in their mother’s womb, unaware as they remain there, and unaware as they emerge. This is the first kind of conception.*";
P_HTM[1695]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhante, idhekacco sampajāno mātukucchiṃ okkamati; asampajāno mātukucchismiṃ ṭhāti; asampajāno mātukucchimhā nikkhamati. Ayaṃ dutiyā gabbhāvakkanti.**Furthermore, someone is aware when conceived in their mother’s womb, but unaware as they remain there, and unaware as they emerge. This is the second kind of conception.*";
P_HTM[1696]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhante, idhekacco sampajāno mātukucchiṃ okkamati; sampajāno mātukucchismiṃ ṭhāti; asampajāno mātukucchimhā nikkhamati. Ayaṃ tatiyā gabbhāvakkanti.**Furthermore, someone is aware when conceived in their mother’s womb, aware as they remain there, but unaware as they emerge. This is the third kind of conception.*";
P_HTM[1697]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhante, idhekacco sampajāno mātukucchiṃ okkamati; sampajāno mātukucchismiṃ ṭhāti; sampajāno mātukucchimhā nikkhamati. Ayaṃ catutthā gabbhāvakkanti.**Furthermore, someone is aware when conceived in their mother’s womb, aware as they remain there, and aware as they emerge. This is the fourth kind of conception.*";
P_HTM[1698]="*Etadānuttariyaṃ, bhante, gabbhāvakkantīsu.**This is unsurpassable when it comes to the conception of the embryo.*";
P_HTM[1699]="*1.4. Ādesanavidhādesanā**1.4. Ways of Revealing*";
P_HTM[1700]="*Aparaṃ pana, bhante, etadānuttariyaṃ, yathā bhagavā dhammaṃ deseti ādesanavidhāsu.**And moreover, sir, how the Buddha teaches the different ways of revealing is unsurpassable.*";
P_HTM[1701]="*Catasso imā, bhante, ādesanavidhā.**There are these four ways of revealing.*";
P_HTM[1702]="*Idha, bhante, ekacco nimittena ādisati:**Firstly, someone reveals by means of a sign,*";
P_HTM[1703]="*‘evampi te mano, itthampi te mano, itipi te cittan’ti.**‘This is what you’re thinking, such is your thought, and thus is your state of mind.’*";
P_HTM[1704]="*So bahuñcepi ādisati, tatheva taṃ hoti, no aññathā.**And even if they reveal this many times, it turns out exactly so, not otherwise.*";
P_HTM[1705]="*Ayaṃ paṭhamā ādesanavidhā.**This is the first way of revealing.*";
P_HTM[1706]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhante, idhekacco na heva kho nimittena ādisati. Api ca kho manussānaṃ vā amanussānaṃ vā devatānaṃ vā saddaṃ sutvā ādisati:**Furthermore, someone reveals after hearing it from humans or non-humans or deities,*";
P_HTM[1707]="*‘evampi te mano, itthampi te mano, itipi te cittan’ti.**‘This is what you’re thinking, such is your thought, and thus is your state of mind.’*";
P_HTM[1708]="*So bahuñcepi ādisati, tatheva taṃ hoti, no aññathā.**And even if they reveal this many times, it turns out exactly so, not otherwise.*";
P_HTM[1709]="*Ayaṃ dutiyā ādesanavidhā.**This is the second way of revealing.*";
P_HTM[1710]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhante, idhekacco na heva kho nimittena ādisati, nāpi manussānaṃ vā amanussānaṃ vā devatānaṃ vā saddaṃ sutvā ādisati. Api ca kho vitakkayato vicārayato vitakkavipphārasaddaṃ sutvā ādisati:**Furthermore, someone reveals by hearing the sound of thought spreading as someone thinks and considers,*";
P_HTM[1711]="*‘evampi te mano, itthampi te mano, itipi te cittan’ti.**‘This is what you’re thinking, such is your thought, and thus is your state of mind.’*";
P_HTM[1712]="*So bahuñcepi ādisati, tatheva taṃ hoti, no aññathā.**And even if they reveal this many times, it turns out exactly so, not otherwise.*";
P_HTM[1713]="*Ayaṃ tatiyā ādesanavidhā.**This is the third way of revealing.*";
P_HTM[1714]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhante, idhekacco na heva kho nimittena ādisati, nāpi manussānaṃ vā amanussānaṃ vā devatānaṃ vā saddaṃ sutvā ādisati, nāpi vitakkayato vicārayato vitakkavipphārasaddaṃ sutvā ādisati. Api ca kho avitakkaṃ avicāraṃ samādhiṃ samāpannassa cetasā ceto paricca pajānāti:**Furthermore, someone comprehends the mind of a person who has attained the immersion that’s free of placing the mind and keeping it connected. They understand,*";
P_HTM[1715]="*‘yathā imassa bhoto manosaṅkhārā paṇihitā. Tathā imassa cittassa anantarā imaṃ nāma vitakkaṃ vitakkessatī’ti.**‘Judging by the way this person’s intentions are directed, immediately after this mind state, they’ll think this thought.’*";
P_HTM[1716]="*So bahuñcepi ādisati, tatheva taṃ hoti, no aññathā.**And even if they reveal this many times, it turns out exactly so, not otherwise.*";
P_HTM[1717]="*Ayaṃ catutthā ādesanavidhā.**This is the fourth way of revealing.*";
P_HTM[1718]="*Etadānuttariyaṃ, bhante, ādesanavidhāsu.**This is unsurpassable when it comes to the ways of revealing.*";
P_HTM[1719]="*1.5. Dassanasamāpattidesanā**1.5. Attainments of Vision*";
P_HTM[1720]="*Aparaṃ pana, bhante, etadānuttariyaṃ, yathā bhagavā dhammaṃ deseti dassanasamāpattīsu.**And moreover, sir, how the Buddha teaches the attainments of vision is unsurpassable.*";
P_HTM[1721]="*Catasso imā, bhante, dassanasamāpattiyo.**There are these four attainments of vision.*";
P_HTM[1722]="*Idha, bhante, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā ātappamanvāya padhānamanvāya anuyogamanvāya appamādamanvāya sammāmanasikāramanvāya tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusati, yathāsamāhite citte imameva kāyaṃ uddhaṃ pādatalā adho kesamatthakā tacapariyantaṃ pūraṃ nānappakārassa asucino paccavekkhati:**Firstly, some ascetic or brahmin—by dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus—experiences an immersion of the heart of such a kind that they examine their own body up from the soles of the feet and down from the tips of the hairs, wrapped in skin and full of many kinds of filth.*";
P_HTM[1723]="*‘atthi imasmiṃ kāye kesā lomā nakhā dantā taco maṃsaṃ nhāru aṭṭhi aṭṭhimiñjaṃ vakkaṃ hadayaṃ yakanaṃ kilomakaṃ pihakaṃ papphāsaṃ antaṃ antaguṇaṃ udariyaṃ karīsaṃ pittaṃ semhaṃ pubbo lohitaṃ sedo medo assu vasā kheḷo siṅghānikā lasikā muttan’ti.**‘In this body there is head hair, body hair, nails, teeth, skin, flesh, sinews, bones, bone marrow, kidneys, heart, liver, diaphragm, spleen, lungs, intestines, mesentery, undigested food, feces, bile, phlegm, pus, blood, sweat, fat, tears, grease, saliva, snot, synovial fluid, urine.’*";
P_HTM[1724]="*Ayaṃ paṭhamā dassanasamāpatti.**This is the first attainment of vision.*";
P_HTM[1725]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhante, idhekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā ātappamanvāya … pe … tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusati, yathāsamāhite citte imameva kāyaṃ uddhaṃ pādatalā adho kesamatthakā tacapariyantaṃ pūraṃ nānappakārassa asucino paccavekkhati:**Furthermore, some ascetic or brahmin attains that and goes beyond it.*";
P_HTM[1726]="*‘atthi imasmiṃ kāye kesā lomā … pe … lasikā muttan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1727]="*Atikkamma ca purisassa chavimaṃsalohitaṃ aṭṭhiṃ paccavekkhati.**They examine a person’s bones with skin, flesh, and blood.*";
P_HTM[1728]="*Ayaṃ dutiyā dassanasamāpatti.**This is the second attainment of vision.*";
P_HTM[1729]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhante, idhekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā ātappamanvāya … pe … tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusati, yathāsamāhite citte imameva kāyaṃ uddhaṃ pādatalā adho kesamatthakā tacapariyantaṃ pūraṃ nānappakārassa asucino paccavekkhati:**Furthermore, some ascetic or brahmin attains that and goes beyond it.*";
P_HTM[1730]="*‘atthi imasmiṃ kāye kesā lomā … pe … lasikā muttan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1731]="*Atikkamma ca purisassa chavimaṃsalohitaṃ aṭṭhiṃ paccavekkhati.* **";
P_HTM[1732]="*Purisassa ca viññāṇasotaṃ pajānāti, ubhayato abbocchinnaṃ idha loke patiṭṭhitañca paraloke patiṭṭhitañca.**They understand a person’s stream of consciousness, unbroken on both sides, established in both this world and the next.*";
P_HTM[1733]="*Ayaṃ tatiyā dassanasamāpatti.**This is the third attainment of vision.*";
P_HTM[1734]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhante, idhekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā ātappamanvāya … pe … tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusati, yathāsamāhite citte imameva kāyaṃ uddhaṃ pādatalā adho kesamatthakā tacapariyantaṃ pūraṃ nānappakārassa asucino paccavekkhati:**Furthermore, some ascetic or brahmin attains that and goes beyond it.*";
P_HTM[1735]="*‘atthi imasmiṃ kāye kesā lomā … pe … lasikā muttan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1736]="*Atikkamma ca purisassa chavimaṃsalohitaṃ aṭṭhiṃ paccavekkhati.* **";
P_HTM[1737]="*Purisassa ca viññāṇasotaṃ pajānāti, ubhayato abbocchinnaṃ idha loke appatiṭṭhitañca paraloke appatiṭṭhitañca.**They understand a person’s stream of consciousness, unbroken on both sides, not established in either this world or the next.*";
P_HTM[1738]="*Ayaṃ catutthā dassanasamāpatti.**This is the fourth attainment of vision.*";
P_HTM[1739]="*Etadānuttariyaṃ, bhante, dassanasamāpattīsu.**This is unsurpassable when it comes to attainments of vision.*";
P_HTM[1740]="*1.6. Puggalapaṇṇattidesanā**1.6. Descriptions of Individuals*";
P_HTM[1741]="*Aparaṃ pana, bhante, etadānuttariyaṃ, yathā bhagavā dhammaṃ deseti puggalapaṇṇattīsu.**And moreover, sir, how the Buddha teaches the description of individuals is unsurpassable.*";
P_HTM[1742]="*Sattime, bhante, puggalā.**There are these seven individuals.*";
P_HTM[1743]="*Ubhatobhāgavimutto paññāvimutto kāyasakkhi diṭṭhippatto saddhāvimutto dhammānusārī saddhānusārī.**One freed both ways, one freed by wisdom, a personal witness, one attained to view, one freed by faith, a follower of the teachings, a follower by faith.*";
P_HTM[1744]="*Etadānuttariyaṃ, bhante, puggalapaṇṇattīsu.**This is unsurpassable when it comes to the description of individuals.*";
P_HTM[1745]="*1.7. Padhānadesanā**1.7. Kinds of Striving*";
P_HTM[1746]="*Aparaṃ pana, bhante, etadānuttariyaṃ, yathā bhagavā dhammaṃ deseti padhānesu.**And moreover, sir, how the Buddha teaches the kinds of striving is unsurpassable.*";
P_HTM[1747]="*Sattime, bhante, sambojjhaṅgā satisambojjhaṅgo dhammavicayasambojjhaṅgo vīriyasambojjhaṅgo pītisambojjhaṅgo passaddhisambojjhaṅgo samādhisambojjhaṅgo upekkhāsambojjhaṅgo.**There are these seven awakening factors: the awakening factors of mindfulness, investigation of principles, energy, rapture, tranquility, immersion, and equanimity.*";
P_HTM[1748]="*Etadānuttariyaṃ, bhante, padhānesu.**This is unsurpassable when it comes to the kinds of striving.*";
P_HTM[1749]="*1.8. Paṭipadādesanā**1.8. Ways of Practice*";
P_HTM[1750]="*Aparaṃ pana, bhante, etadānuttariyaṃ, yathā bhagavā dhammaṃ deseti paṭipadāsu.**And moreover, sir, how the Buddha teaches the ways of practice is unsurpassable.*";
P_HTM[1751]="*Catasso imā, bhante, paṭipadā dukkhā paṭipadā dandhābhiññā, dukkhā paṭipadā khippābhiññā, sukhā paṭipadā dandhābhiññā, sukhā paṭipadā khippābhiññāti.**~Painful practice with slow insight, ~painful practice with swift insight, ~pleasant practice with slow insight, and ~pleasant practice with swift insight.*";
P_HTM[1752]="*Tatra, bhante, yāyaṃ paṭipadā dukkhā dandhābhiññā, ayaṃ, bhante, paṭipadā ubhayeneva hīnā akkhāyati dukkhattā ca dandhattā ca.**Of these, the painful practice with slow insight is said to be inferior both ways: because it’s painful and because it’s slow.*";
P_HTM[1753]="*Tatra, bhante, yāyaṃ paṭipadā dukkhā khippābhiññā, ayaṃ pana, bhante, paṭipadā dukkhattā hīnā akkhāyati.**The painful practice with swift insight is said to be inferior because it’s painful.*";
P_HTM[1754]="*Tatra, bhante, yāyaṃ paṭipadā sukhā dandhābhiññā, ayaṃ pana, bhante, paṭipadā dandhattā hīnā akkhāyati.**The pleasant practice with slow insight is said to be inferior because it’s slow.*";
P_HTM[1755]="*Tatra, bhante, yāyaṃ paṭipadā sukhā khippābhiññā, ayaṃ pana, bhante, paṭipadā ubhayeneva paṇītā akkhāyati sukhattā ca khippattā ca.**But the pleasant practice with swift insight is said to be superior both ways: because it’s pleasant and because it’s swift.*";
P_HTM[1756]="*Etadānuttariyaṃ, bhante, paṭipadāsu.**This is unsurpassable when it comes to the ways of practice.*";
P_HTM[1757]="*1.9. Bhassasamācārādidesanā**1.9. Behavior in Speech*";
P_HTM[1758]="*Aparaṃ pana, bhante, etadānuttariyaṃ, yathā bhagavā dhammaṃ deseti bhassasamācāre.**And moreover, sir, how the Buddha teaches behavior in speech is unsurpassable.*";
P_HTM[1759]="*Idha, bhante, ekacco na ceva musāvādupasañhitaṃ vācaṃ bhāsati na ca vebhūtiyaṃ na ca pesuṇiyaṃ na ca sārambhajaṃ jayāpekkho;**It’s when someone doesn’t use speech that’s connected with lying, or divisive, or backbiting, or aggressively trying to win.*";
P_HTM[1760]="*mantā mantā ca vācaṃ bhāsati nidhānavatiṃ kālena.**They speak only wise counsel, valuable and timely.*";
P_HTM[1761]="*Etadānuttariyaṃ, bhante, bhassasamācāre.**This is unsurpassable when it comes to behavior in speech.*";
P_HTM[1762]="*Aparaṃ pana, bhante, etadānuttariyaṃ, yathā bhagavā dhammaṃ deseti purisasīlasamācāre.**And moreover, sir, how the Buddha teaches a person’s ethical behavior is unsurpassable.*";
P_HTM[1763]="*Idha, bhante, ekacco sacco cassa saddho ca, na ca kuhako, na ca lapako, na ca nemittiko, na ca nippesiko, na ca lābhena lābhaṃ nijigīsanako, indriyesu guttadvāro, bhojane mattaññū, samakārī, jāgariyānuyogamanuyutto, atandito, āraddhavīriyo, jhāyī, satimā, kalyāṇapaṭibhāno, gatimā, dhitimā, matimā, na ca kāmesu giddho, sato ca nipako ca.**It’s when someone is honest and faithful. They don’t use deceit, flattery, hinting, or belittling, and they don’t use material possessions to pursue other material possessions. They guard the sense doors and eat in moderation. They’re fair, dedicated to wakefulness, tireless, energetic, and meditative. They have good memory, eloquence, range, retention, and thoughtfulness. They’re not greedy for sensual pleasures. They are mindful and alert.*";
P_HTM[1764]="*Etadānuttariyaṃ, bhante, purisasīlasamācāre.**This is unsurpassable when it comes to a person’s ethical behavior.*";
P_HTM[1765]="*1.10. Anusāsanavidhādesanā**1.10. Responsiveness to Instruction*";
P_HTM[1766]="*Aparaṃ pana, bhante, etadānuttariyaṃ, yathā bhagavā dhammaṃ deseti anusāsanavidhāsu.**And moreover, sir, how the Buddha teaches the different degrees of responsiveness to instruction is unsurpassable.*";
P_HTM[1767]="*Catasso imā, bhante, anusāsanavidhā—**There are these four degrees of responsiveness to instruction.*";
P_HTM[1768]="*jānāti, bhante, bhagavā aparaṃ puggalaṃ paccattaṃ yonisomanasikārā**The Buddha knows by investigating inside another individual:*";
P_HTM[1769]="*‘ayaṃ puggalo yathānusiṭṭhaṃ tathā paṭipajjamāno tiṇṇaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā sotāpanno bhavissati avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyaṇo’ti.**‘By practicing as instructed this individual will, with the ending of three fetters, become a stream-enterer, not liable to be reborn in the underworld, bound for awakening.’*";
P_HTM[1770]="*Jānāti, bhante, bhagavā paraṃ puggalaṃ paccattaṃ yonisomanasikārā:**The Buddha knows by investigating inside another individual:*";
P_HTM[1771]="*‘ayaṃ puggalo yathānusiṭṭhaṃ tathā paṭipajjamāno tiṇṇaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā rāgadosamohānaṃ tanuttā sakadāgāmī bhavissati, sakideva imaṃ lokaṃ āgantvā dukkhassantaṃ karissatī’ti.**‘By practicing as instructed this individual will, with the ending of three fetters, and the weakening of greed, hate, and delusion, become a once-returner. They will come back to this world once only, then make an end of suffering.’*";
P_HTM[1772]="*Jānāti, bhante, bhagavā paraṃ puggalaṃ paccattaṃ yonisomanasikārā:**The Buddha knows by investigating inside another individual:*";
P_HTM[1773]="*‘ayaṃ puggalo yathānusiṭṭhaṃ tathā paṭipajjamāno pañcannaṃ orambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā opapātiko bhavissati tattha parinibbāyī anāvattidhammo tasmā lokā’ti.**‘By practicing as instructed this individual will, with the ending of the five lower fetters, be reborn spontaneously. They will be extinguished there, and are not liable to return from that world.’*";
P_HTM[1774]="*Jānāti, bhante, bhagavā paraṃ puggalaṃ paccattaṃ yonisomanasikārā:**The Buddha knows by investigating inside another individual:*";
P_HTM[1775]="*‘ayaṃ puggalo yathānusiṭṭhaṃ tathā paṭipajjamāno āsavānaṃ khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharissatī’ti.**‘By practicing as instructed this individual will realize the undefiled freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom in this very life, and live having realized it with their own insight due to the ending of defilements.’*";
P_HTM[1776]="*Etadānuttariyaṃ, bhante, anusāsanavidhāsu.**This is unsurpassable when it comes to the different degrees of responsiveness to instruction.*";
P_HTM[1777]="*1.11. Parapuggalavimuttiñāṇadesanā**1.11. The Knowledge and Freedom of Others*";
P_HTM[1778]="*Aparaṃ pana, bhante, etadānuttariyaṃ, yathā bhagavā dhammaṃ deseti parapuggalavimuttiñāṇe.**And moreover, sir, how the Buddha teaches the knowledge and freedom of other individuals is unsurpassable.*";
P_HTM[1779]="*Jānāti, bhante, bhagavā paraṃ puggalaṃ paccattaṃ yonisomanasikārā:**The Buddha knows by investigating inside another individual:*";
P_HTM[1780]="*‘ayaṃ puggalo tiṇṇaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā sotāpanno bhavissati avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyaṇo’ti.**‘With the ending of three fetters this individual will become a stream-enterer, not liable to be reborn in the underworld, bound for awakening.’*";
P_HTM[1781]="*Jānāti, bhante, bhagavā paraṃ puggalaṃ paccattaṃ yonisomanasikārā:**The Buddha knows by investigating inside another individual:*";
P_HTM[1782]="*‘ayaṃ puggalo tiṇṇaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā rāgadosamohānaṃ tanuttā sakadāgāmī bhavissati, sakideva imaṃ lokaṃ āgantvā dukkhassantaṃ karissatī’ti.**‘With the ending of three fetters, and the weakening of greed, hate, and delusion, this individual will become a once-returner. They will come back to this world once only, then make an end of suffering.’*";
P_HTM[1783]="*Jānāti, bhante, bhagavā paraṃ puggalaṃ paccattaṃ yonisomanasikārā:**The Buddha knows by investigating inside another individual:*";
P_HTM[1784]="*‘ayaṃ puggalo pañcannaṃ orambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā opapātiko bhavissati tattha parinibbāyī anāvattidhammo tasmā lokā’ti.**‘With the ending of the five lower fetters, this individual will be reborn spontaneously. They will be extinguished there, and are not liable to return from that world.’*";
P_HTM[1785]="*Jānāti, bhante, bhagavā paraṃ puggalaṃ paccattaṃ yonisomanasikārā:**The Buddha knows by investigating inside another individual:*";
P_HTM[1786]="*‘ayaṃ puggalo āsavānaṃ khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharissatī’ti.**‘This individual will realize the undefiled freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom in this very life, and live having realized it with their own insight due to the ending of defilements.’*";
P_HTM[1787]="*Etadānuttariyaṃ, bhante, parapuggalavimuttiñāṇe.**This is unsurpassable when it comes to the knowledge and freedom of other individuals.*";
P_HTM[1788]="*1.12. Sassatavādadesanā**1.12. Eternalism*";
P_HTM[1789]="*Aparaṃ pana, bhante, etadānuttariyaṃ, yathā bhagavā dhammaṃ deseti sassatavādesu.**And moreover, sir, how the Buddha teaches eternalist doctrines is unsurpassable.*";
P_HTM[1790]="*Tayome, bhante, sassatavādā.**There are these three eternalist doctrines.*";
P_HTM[1791]="*Idha, bhante, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā ātappamanvāya … pe … tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusati, yathāsamāhite citte anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati.**Firstly, some ascetic or brahmin—by dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus—experiences an immersion of the heart of such a kind that they recollect many hundreds of thousands of past lives,*";
P_HTM[1792]="*Seyyathidaṃ—ekampi jātiṃ dvepi jātiyo tissopi jātiyo catassopi jātiyo pañcapi jātiyo dasapi jātiyo vīsampi jātiyo tiṃsampi jātiyo cattālīsampi jātiyo paññāsampi jātiyo jātisatampi jātisahassampi jātisatasahassampi anekānipi jātisatāni anekānipi jātisahassāni anekānipi jātisatasahassāni, ‘amutrāsiṃ evaṃnāmo evaṃgotto evaṃvaṇṇo evamāhāro evaṃsukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī evamāyupariyanto, so tato cuto amutra udapādiṃ; tatrāpāsiṃ evaṃnāmo evaṃgotto evaṃvaṇṇo evamāhāro evaṃsukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī evamāyupariyanto, so tato cuto idhūpapanno’ti. Iti sākāraṃ sauddesaṃ anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati.**with features and details.*";
P_HTM[1793]="*So evamāha:**They say,*";
P_HTM[1794]="*‘atītampāhaṃ addhānaṃ jānāmi—saṃvaṭṭi vā loko vivaṭṭi vāti.**‘I know that in the past the cosmos expanded or contracted.*";
P_HTM[1795]="*Anāgataṃpāhaṃ addhānaṃ jānāmi—saṃvaṭṭissati vā loko vivaṭṭissati vāti.**I don’t know whether in the future the cosmos will expand or contract.*";
P_HTM[1796]="*Sassato attā ca loko ca vañjho kūṭaṭṭho esikaṭṭhāyiṭṭhito. Te ca sattā sandhāvanti saṃsaranti cavanti upapajjanti, atthi tveva sassatisaman’ti.**The self and the cosmos are eternal, barren, steady as a mountain peak, standing firm like a pillar. They remain the same for all eternity, while these sentient beings wander and transmigrate and pass away and rearise.’*";
P_HTM[1797]="*Ayaṃ paṭhamo sassatavādo.**This is the first eternalist doctrine.*";
P_HTM[1798]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhante, idhekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā ātappamanvāya … pe … tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusati, yathāsamāhite citte anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati.**Furthermore, some ascetic or brahmin—by dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus—experiences an immersion of the heart of such a kind that they recollect their past lives for as many as ten eons of the expansion and contraction of the cosmos,*";
P_HTM[1799]="*Seyyathidaṃ—ekampi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭaṃ dvepi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭāni tīṇipi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭāni cattāripi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭāni pañcapi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭāni dasapi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭāni, ‘amutrāsiṃ evaṃnāmo evaṅgotto evaṃvaṇṇo evamāhāro evaṃsukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī evamāyupariyanto, so tato cuto amutra udapādiṃ; tatrāpāsiṃ evaṃnāmo evaṅgotto evaṃvaṇṇo evamāhāro evaṃsukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī evamāyupariyanto, so tato cuto idhūpapanno’ti. Iti sākāraṃ sauddesaṃ anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati.**with features and details.*";
P_HTM[1800]="*So evamāha:**They say,*";
P_HTM[1801]="*‘atītampāhaṃ addhānaṃ jānāmi saṃvaṭṭi vā loko vivaṭṭi vāti.**‘I know that in the past the cosmos expanded or contracted.*";
P_HTM[1802]="*Anāgataṃpāhaṃ addhānaṃ jānāmi saṃvaṭṭissati vā loko vivaṭṭissati vāti.**I don’t know whether in the future the cosmos will expand or contract.*";
P_HTM[1803]="*Sassato attā ca loko ca vañjho kūṭaṭṭho esikaṭṭhāyiṭṭhito.**The self and the cosmos are eternal, barren, steady as a mountain peak, standing firm like a pillar.*";
P_HTM[1804]="*Te ca sattā sandhāvanti saṃsaranti cavanti upapajjanti, atthi tveva sassatisaman’ti.**They remain the same for all eternity, while these sentient beings wander and transmigrate and pass away and rearise.’*";
P_HTM[1805]="*Ayaṃ dutiyo sassatavādo.**This is the second eternalist doctrine.*";
P_HTM[1806]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhante, idhekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā ātappamanvāya … pe … tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusati, yathāsamāhite citte anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati.**Furthermore, some ascetic or brahmin—by dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus—experiences an immersion of the heart of such a kind that they recollect their past lives for as many as forty eons of the expansion and contraction of the cosmos,*";
P_HTM[1807]="*Seyyathidaṃ—dasapi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭāni vīsampi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭāni tiṃsampi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭāni cattālīsampi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭāni, ‘amutrāsiṃ evaṃnāmo evaṅgotto evaṃvaṇṇo evamāhāro evaṃsukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī evamāyupariyanto, so tato cuto amutra udapādiṃ; tatrāpāsiṃ evaṃnāmo evaṅgotto evaṃvaṇṇo evamāhāro evaṃsukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī evamāyupariyanto, so tato cuto idhūpapanno’ti. Iti sākāraṃ sauddesaṃ anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati.**with features and details.*";
P_HTM[1808]="*So evamāha:**They say,*";
P_HTM[1809]="*‘atītampāhaṃ addhānaṃ jānāmi saṃvaṭṭipi loko vivaṭṭipīti;**‘I know that in the past the cosmos expanded or contracted.*";
P_HTM[1810]="*anāgataṃpāhaṃ addhānaṃ jānāmi saṃvaṭṭissatipi loko vivaṭṭissatipīti.**I don’t know whether in the future the cosmos will expand or contract.*";
P_HTM[1811]="*Sassato attā ca loko ca vañjho kūṭaṭṭho esikaṭṭhāyiṭṭhito.**The self and the cosmos are eternal, barren, steady as a mountain peak, standing firm like a pillar.*";
P_HTM[1812]="*Te ca sattā sandhāvanti saṃsaranti cavanti upapajjanti, atthi tveva sassatisaman’ti.**They remain the same for all eternity, while these sentient beings wander and transmigrate and pass away and rearise.’*";
P_HTM[1813]="*Ayaṃ tatiyo sassatavādo,**This is the third eternalist doctrine.*";
P_HTM[1814]="*etadānuttariyaṃ, bhante, sassatavādesu.**This is unsurpassable when it comes to eternalist doctrines.*";
P_HTM[1815]="*1.13. Pubbenivāsānussatiñāṇadesanā**1.13. Recollecting Past Lives*";
P_HTM[1816]="*Aparaṃ pana, bhante, etadānuttariyaṃ, yathā bhagavā dhammaṃ deseti pubbenivāsānussatiñāṇe.**And moreover, sir, how the Buddha teaches the knowledge of recollecting past lives is unsurpassable.*";
P_HTM[1817]="*Idha, bhante, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā ātappamanvāya … pe … tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusati, yathāsamāhite citte anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati.**It’s when some ascetic or brahmin—by dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus—experiences an immersion of the heart of such a kind that they recollect their many kinds of past lives.*";
P_HTM[1818]="*Seyyathidaṃ—ekampi jātiṃ dvepi jātiyo tissopi jātiyo catassopi jātiyo pañcapi jātiyo dasapi jātiyo vīsampi jātiyo tiṃsampi jātiyo cattālīsampi jātiyo paññāsampi jātiyo jātisatampi jātisahassampi jātisatasahassampi anekepi saṃvaṭṭakappe anekepi vivaṭṭakappe anekepi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭakappe,**That is: one, two, three, four, five, ten, twenty, thirty, forty, fifty, a hundred, a thousand, a hundred thousand rebirths; many eons of the world contracting, many eons of the world expanding, many eons of the world contracting and expanding. They remember:*";
P_HTM[1819]="*‘amutrāsiṃ evaṃnāmo evaṃgotto evaṃvaṇṇo evamāhāro evaṃsukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī evamāyupariyanto, so tato cuto amutra udapādiṃ; tatrāpāsiṃ evaṃnāmo evaṃgotto evaṃvaṇṇo evamāhāro evaṃsukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī evamāyupariyanto, so tato cuto idhūpapanno’ti. Iti sākāraṃ sauddesaṃ anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati.**‘There, I was named this, my clan was that, I looked like this, and that was my food. This was how I felt pleasure and pain, and that was how my life ended. When I passed away from that place I was reborn somewhere else. There, too, I was named this, my clan was that, I looked like this, and that was my food. This was how I felt pleasure and pain, and that was how my life ended. When I passed away from that place I was reborn here.’ And so they recollect their many kinds of past lives, with features and details.*";
P_HTM[1820]="*Santi, bhante, devā, yesaṃ na sakkā gaṇanāya vā saṅkhānena vā āyu saṅkhātuṃ.**Sir, there are gods whose life span cannot be reckoned or calculated.*";
P_HTM[1821]="*Api ca yasmiṃ yasmiṃ attabhāve abhinivuṭṭhapubbo hoti yadi vā rūpīsu yadi vā arūpīsu yadi vā saññīsu yadi vā asaññīsu yadi vā nevasaññīnāsaññīsu.**Still, no matter what incarnation they have previously been reborn in—whether physical or formless or percipient or non-percipient or neither percipient nor non-percipient—*";
P_HTM[1822]="*Iti sākāraṃ sauddesaṃ anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati.**they recollect their many kinds of past lives, with features and details.*";
P_HTM[1823]="*Etadānuttariyaṃ, bhante, pubbenivāsānussatiñāṇe.**This is unsurpassable when it comes to the knowledge of recollecting past lives.*";
P_HTM[1824]="*1.14. Cutūpapātañāṇadesanā**1.14. Death and Rebirth*";
P_HTM[1825]="*Aparaṃ pana, bhante, etadānuttariyaṃ, yathā bhagavā dhammaṃ deseti sattānaṃ cutūpapātañāṇe.**And moreover, sir, how the Buddha teaches the knowledge of the death and rebirth of sentient beings is unsurpassable.*";
P_HTM[1826]="*Idha, bhante, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā ātappamanvāya … pe … tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusati, yathāsamāhite citte dibbena cakkhunā visuddhena atikkantamānusakena satte passati cavamāne upapajjamāne**It’s when some ascetic or brahmin—by dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus—experiences an immersion of the heart of such a kind that with clairvoyance that is purified and superhuman, they see sentient beings passing away and being reborn*";
P_HTM[1827]="*hīne paṇīte suvaṇṇe dubbaṇṇe sugate duggate yathākammūpage satte pajānāti: ‘ime vata bhonto sattā kāyaduccaritena samannāgatā vacīduccaritena samannāgatā manoduccaritena samannāgatā ariyānaṃ upavādakā micchādiṭṭhikā micchādiṭṭhikammasamādānā. Te kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapannā. Ime vā pana bhonto sattā kāyasucaritena samannāgatā vacīsucaritena samannāgatā manosucaritena samannāgatā ariyānaṃ anupavādakā sammādiṭṭhikā sammādiṭṭhikammasamādānā. Te kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapannā’ti. Iti dibbena cakkhunā visuddhena atikkantamānusakena satte passati cavamāne upapajjamāne hīne paṇīte suvaṇṇe dubbaṇṇe sugate duggate yathākammūpage satte pajānāti.**—inferior and superior, beautiful and ugly, in a good place or a bad place. They understand how sentient beings are reborn according to their deeds: ‘These dear beings did bad things by way of body, speech, and mind. They spoke ill of the noble ones; they had wrong view; and they chose to act out of that wrong view. When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell. These dear beings, however, did good things by way of body, speech, and mind. They never spoke ill of the noble ones; they had right view; and they chose to act out of that right view. When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.’ And so, with clairvoyance that is purified and superhuman, they see sentient beings passing away and being reborn—inferior and superior, beautiful and ugly, in a good place or a bad place. They understand how sentient beings are reborn according to their deeds.*";
P_HTM[1828]="*Etadānuttariyaṃ, bhante, sattānaṃ cutūpapātañāṇe.**This is unsurpassable when it comes to the knowledge of death and rebirth.*";
P_HTM[1829]="*1.15. Iddhividhadesanā**1.15. Psychic Powers*";
P_HTM[1830]="*Aparaṃ pana, bhante, etadānuttariyaṃ, yathā bhagavā dhammaṃ deseti iddhividhāsu.**And moreover, sir, how the Buddha teaches psychic power is unsurpassable.*";
P_HTM[1831]="*Dvemā, bhante, iddhividhāyo—**There are these two kinds of psychic power.*";
P_HTM[1832]="*atthi, bhante, iddhi sāsavā saupadhikā, ‘no ariyā’ti vuccati.**There are psychic powers that are accompanied by defilements and attachments, and are said to be ignoble.*";
P_HTM[1833]="*Atthi, bhante, iddhi anāsavā anupadhikā ‘ariyā’ti vuccati.**And there are psychic powers that are free of defilements and attachments, and are said to be noble.*";
P_HTM[1834]="*Katamā ca, bhante, iddhi sāsavā saupadhikā, ‘no ariyā’ti vuccati?**What are the psychic powers that are accompanied by defilements and attachments, and are said to be ignoble?*";
P_HTM[1835]="*idha, bhante, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā ātappamanvāya … pe … tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusati, yathāsamāhite citte anekavihitaṃ iddhividhaṃ paccanubhoti—**It’s when some ascetic or brahmin—by dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus—experiences an immersion of the heart of such a kind that they wield the many kinds of psychic power:*";
P_HTM[1836]="*ekopi hutvā bahudhā hoti, bahudhāpi hutvā eko hoti; āvibhāvaṃ tirobhāvaṃ tirokuṭṭaṃ tiropākāraṃ tiropabbataṃ asajjamāno gacchati seyyathāpi ākāse; pathaviyāpi ummujjanimujjaṃ karoti seyyathāpi udake; udakepi abhijjamāne gacchati seyyathāpi pathaviyaṃ; ākāsepi pallaṅkena kamati seyyathāpi pakkhī sakuṇo; imepi candimasūriye evaṃmahiddhike evaṃmahānubhāve pāṇinā parāmasati parimajjati; yāva brahmalokāpi kāyena vasaṃ vatteti.**multiplying themselves and becoming one again; going unimpeded through a wall, a rampart, or a mountain as if through space; diving in and out of the earth as if it were water; walking on water as if it were earth; flying cross-legged through the sky like a bird; touching and stroking with the hand the sun and moon, so mighty and powerful; controlling the body as far as the Brahmā realm.*";
P_HTM[1837]="*Ayaṃ, bhante, iddhi sāsavā saupadhikā, ‘no ariyā’ti vuccati.**These are the psychic powers that are accompanied by defilements and attachments, and are said to be ignoble.*";
P_HTM[1838]="*Katamā pana, bhante, iddhi anāsavā anupadhikā, ‘ariyā’ti vuccati?**But what are the psychic powers that are free of defilements and attachments, and are said to be noble?*";
P_HTM[1839]="*Idha, bhante, bhikkhu sace ākaṅkhati: ‘paṭikūle appaṭikūlasaññī vihareyyan’ti, appaṭikūlasaññī tattha viharati.**It’s when, if a mendicant wishes: ‘May I meditate perceiving the unrepulsive in the repulsive,’ that’s what they do.*";
P_HTM[1840]="*Sace ākaṅkhati: ‘appaṭikūle paṭikūlasaññī vihareyyan’ti, paṭikūlasaññī tattha viharati.**If they wish: ‘May I meditate perceiving the repulsive in the unrepulsive,’ that’s what they do.*";
P_HTM[1841]="*Sace ākaṅkhati: ‘paṭikūle ca appaṭikūle ca appaṭikūlasaññī vihareyyan’ti, appaṭikūlasaññī tattha viharati.**If they wish: ‘May I meditate perceiving the unrepulsive in the repulsive and the unrepulsive,’ that’s what they do.*";
P_HTM[1842]="*Sace ākaṅkhati: ‘paṭikūle ca appaṭikūle ca paṭikūlasaññī vihareyyan’ti, paṭikūlasaññī tattha viharati.**If they wish: ‘May I meditate perceiving the repulsive in the unrepulsive and the repulsive,’ that’s what they do.*";
P_HTM[1843]="*Sace ākaṅkhati: ‘paṭikūlañca appaṭikūlañca tadubhayaṃ abhinivajjetvā upekkhako vihareyyaṃ sato sampajāno’ti, upekkhako tattha viharati sato sampajāno.**If they wish: ‘May I meditate staying equanimous, mindful and aware, rejecting both the repulsive and the unrepulsive,’ that’s what they do.*";
P_HTM[1844]="*Ayaṃ, bhante, iddhi anāsavā anupadhikā ‘ariyā’ti vuccati.**These are the psychic powers that are free of defilements and attachments, and are said to be noble.*";
P_HTM[1845]="*Etadānuttariyaṃ, bhante, iddhividhāsu.**This is unsurpassable when it comes to psychic powers.*";
P_HTM[1846]="*Taṃ bhagavā asesamabhijānāti, taṃ bhagavato asesamabhijānato uttari abhiññeyyaṃ natthi, yadabhijānaṃ añño samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā bhagavatā bhiyyobhiññataro assa yadidaṃ iddhividhāsu.**The Buddha understands this without exception. There is nothing to be understood beyond this whereby another ascetic or brahmin might be superior in direct knowledge to the Buddha when it comes to psychic powers.*";
P_HTM[1847]="*1.16. Aññathāsatthuguṇadassana**1.16. The Four Absorptions*";
P_HTM[1848]="*Yaṃ taṃ, bhante, saddhena kulaputtena pattabbaṃ āraddhavīriyena thāmavatā purisathāmena purisavīriyena purisaparakkamena purisadhorayhena, anuppattaṃ taṃ bhagavatā.**The Buddha has achieved what should be achieved by a faithful gentleman by being energetic and strong, by manly strength, energy, vigor, and exertion.*";
P_HTM[1849]="*Na ca, bhante, bhagavā kāmesu kāmasukhallikānuyogamanuyutto hīnaṃ gammaṃ pothujjanikaṃ anariyaṃ anatthasaṃhitaṃ, na ca attakilamathānuyogamanuyutto dukkhaṃ anariyaṃ anatthasaṃhitaṃ.**The Buddha doesn’t indulge in sensual pleasures, which are low, crude, ordinary, ignoble, and pointless. And he doesn’t indulge in self-mortification, which is painful, ignoble, and pointless.*";
P_HTM[1850]="*Catunnañca bhagavā jhānānaṃ ābhicetasikānaṃ diṭṭhadhammasukhavihārānaṃ nikāmalābhī akicchalābhī akasiralābhī.**He gets the four absorptions—blissful meditations in the present life that belong to the higher mind—when he wants, without trouble or difficulty.*";
P_HTM[1851]="*1.17. Anuyogadānappakāra**1.17. On Being Questioned*";
P_HTM[1852]="*Sace maṃ, bhante, evaṃ puccheyya:**Sir, if they were to ask me,*";
P_HTM[1853]="*‘kiṃ nu kho, āvuso sāriputta, ahesuṃ atītamaddhānaṃ aññe samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā bhagavatā bhiyyobhiññatarā sambodhiyan’ti, evaṃ puṭṭho ahaṃ, bhante, ‘no’ti vadeyyaṃ.**‘Reverend Sāriputta, is there any other ascetic or brahmin—whether past, future, or present—whose direct knowledge is superior to the Buddha when it comes to awakening?’ I would tell them ‘No.’*";
P_HTM[1854]="*‘Kiṃ panāvuso sāriputta, bhavissanti anāgatamaddhānaṃ aññe samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā bhagavatā bhiyyobhiññatarā sambodhiyan’ti, evaṃ puṭṭho ahaṃ, bhante, ‘no’ti vadeyyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1855]="*‘Kiṃ panāvuso sāriputta, atthetarahi añño samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā bhagavatā bhiyyobhiññataro sambodhiyan’ti, evaṃ puṭṭho ahaṃ, bhante, ‘no’ti vadeyyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1856]="*Sace pana maṃ, bhante, evaṃ puccheyya:**But if they were to ask me,*";
P_HTM[1857]="*‘kiṃ nu kho, āvuso sāriputta, ahesuṃ atītamaddhānaṃ aññe samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā bhagavatā samasamā sambodhiyan’ti, evaṃ puṭṭho ahaṃ, bhante, ‘evan’ti vadeyyaṃ.**‘Reverend Sāriputta, is there any other ascetic or brahmin—whether past or future—whose direct knowledge is equal to the Buddha when it comes to awakening?’ I would tell them ‘Yes.’*";
P_HTM[1858]="*‘Kiṃ panāvuso sāriputta, bhavissanti anāgatamaddhānaṃ aññe samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā bhagavatā samasamā sambodhiyan’ti, evaṃ puṭṭho ahaṃ, bhante, ‘evan’ti vadeyyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1859]="*‘Kiṃ panāvuso sāriputta, atthetarahi aññe samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā bhagavatā samasamā sambodhiyan’ti, evaṃ puṭṭho ahaṃ, bhante, ‘no’ti vadeyyaṃ.**But if they were to ask: ‘Reverend Sāriputta, is there any other ascetic or brahmin at present whose direct knowledge is equal to the Buddha when it comes to awakening?’ I would tell them ‘No.’*";
P_HTM[1860]="*Sace pana maṃ, bhante, evaṃ puccheyya:**But if they were to ask me,*";
P_HTM[1861]="*‘kiṃ panāyasmā sāriputto ekaccaṃ abbhanujānāti, ekaccaṃ na abbhanujānātī’ti, evaṃ puṭṭho ahaṃ, bhante, evaṃ byākareyyaṃ:**‘But why does Venerable Sāriputta grant this in respect of some but not others?’ I would answer them like this,*";
P_HTM[1862]="*‘sammukhā metaṃ, āvuso, bhagavato sutaṃ, sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ:**‘Reverends, I have heard and learned this in the presence of the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[1863]="*“ahesuṃ atītamaddhānaṃ arahanto sammāsambuddhā mayā samasamā sambodhiyan”ti.**“The perfected ones, fully awakened Buddhas of the past and the future are equal to myself when it comes to awakening.”*";
P_HTM[1864]="*Sammukhā metaṃ, āvuso, bhagavato sutaṃ, sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[1865]="*“bhavissanti anāgatamaddhānaṃ arahanto sammāsambuddhā mayā samasamā sambodhiyan”ti.* **";
P_HTM[1866]="*Sammukhā metaṃ, āvuso, bhagavato sutaṃ sammukhā paṭiggahitaṃ:**And I have also heard and learned this in the presence of the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[1867]="*“aṭṭhānametaṃ anavakāso yaṃ ekissā lokadhātuyā dve arahanto sammāsambuddhā apubbaṃ acarimaṃ uppajjeyyuṃ, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjatī”’ti.**“It’s impossible for two perfected ones, fully awakened Buddhas to arise in the same solar system at the same time.”’*";
P_HTM[1868]="*Kaccāhaṃ, bhante, evaṃ puṭṭho evaṃ byākaramāno vuttavādī ceva bhagavato homi, na ca bhagavantaṃ abhūtena abbhācikkhāmi, dhammassa cānudhammaṃ byākaromi, na ca koci sahadhammiko vādānuvādo gārayhaṃ ṭhānaṃ āgacchatī”ti?**Answering this way, I trust that I repeated what the Buddha has said, and didn’t misrepresent him with an untruth. I trust my explanation was in line with the teaching, and that there are no legitimate grounds for rebuke or criticism.”*";
P_HTM[1869]="*“Taggha tvaṃ, sāriputta, evaṃ puṭṭho evaṃ byākaramāno vuttavādī ceva me hosi, na ca maṃ abhūtena abbhācikkhasi, dhammassa cānudhammaṃ byākarosi, na ca koci sahadhammiko vādānuvādo gārayhaṃ ṭhānaṃ āgacchatī”ti.**“Indeed, Sāriputta, in answering this way you repeat what I’ve said, and don’t misrepresent me with an untruth. Your explanation is in line with the teaching, and there are no legitimate grounds for rebuke or criticism.”*";
P_HTM[1870]="*2. Acchariyaabbhuta**2. Incredible and Amazing*";
P_HTM[1871]="*Evaṃ vutte, āyasmā udāyī bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he had spoken, Venerable Udāyī said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[1872]="*“acchariyaṃ, bhante, abbhutaṃ, bhante, tathāgatassa appicchatā santuṭṭhitā sallekhatā.**“It’s incredible, sir, it’s amazing! The Realized One has so few wishes, such contentment, such self-effacement!*";
P_HTM[1873]="*Yatra hi nāma tathāgato evaṃmahiddhiko evaṃmahānubhāvo, atha ca pana nevattānaṃ pātukarissati.**For even though the Realized One has such power and might, he will not make a display of himself.*";
P_HTM[1874]="*Ekamekañcepi ito, bhante, dhammaṃ aññatitthiyā paribbājakā attani samanupasseyyuṃ, te tāvatakeneva paṭākaṃ parihareyyuṃ.**If the wanderers following other paths were to see even a single one of these qualities in themselves they’d carry around a banner to that effect.*";
P_HTM[1875]="*Acchariyaṃ, bhante, abbhutaṃ, bhante, tathāgatassa appicchatā santuṭṭhitā sallekhatā.**It’s incredible, sir, it’s amazing! The Realized One has so few wishes, such contentment, such self-effacement!*";
P_HTM[1876]="*Yatra hi nāma tathāgato evaṃmahiddhiko evaṃmahānubhāvo. Atha ca pana nevattānaṃ pātukarissatī”ti.**For even though the Realized One has such power and might, he will not make a display of himself.”*";
P_HTM[1877]="*“Passa kho tvaṃ, udāyi, ‘tathāgatassa appicchatā santuṭṭhitā sallekhatā.**“See, Udāyī, how the Realized One has so few wishes, such contentment, such self-effacement.*";
P_HTM[1878]="*Yatra hi nāma tathāgato evaṃmahiddhiko evaṃmahānubhāvo, atha ca pana nevattānaṃ pātukarissati’.**For even though the Realized One has such power and might, he will not make a display of himself.*";
P_HTM[1879]="*Ekamekañcepi ito, udāyi, dhammaṃ aññatitthiyā paribbājakā attani samanupasseyyuṃ, te tāvatakeneva paṭākaṃ parihareyyuṃ.**If the wanderers following other paths were to see even a single one of these qualities in themselves they’d carry around a banner to that effect.*";
P_HTM[1880]="*Passa kho tvaṃ, udāyi, ‘tathāgatassa appicchatā santuṭṭhitā sallekhatā.**See, Udāyī, how the Realized One has so few wishes, such contentment, such self-effacement.*";
P_HTM[1881]="*Yatra hi nāma tathāgato evaṃmahiddhiko evaṃmahānubhāvo, atha ca pana nevattānaṃ pātukarissatī’”ti.**For even though the Realized One has such power and might, he will not make a display of himself.”*";
P_HTM[1882]="*Atha kho bhagavā āyasmantaṃ sāriputtaṃ āmantesi:**Then the Buddha said to Venerable Sāriputta,*";
P_HTM[1883]="*“Tasmātiha tvaṃ, sāriputta, imaṃ dhammapariyāyaṃ abhikkhaṇaṃ bhāseyyāsi bhikkhūnaṃ bhikkhunīnaṃ upāsakānaṃ upāsikānaṃ.**“So Sāriputta, you should frequently speak this exposition of the teaching to the monks, nuns, laymen, and laywomen.*";
P_HTM[1884]="*Yesampi hi, sāriputta, moghapurisānaṃ bhavissati tathāgate kaṅkhā vā vimati vā, tesamimaṃ dhammapariyāyaṃ sutvā tathāgate kaṅkhā vā vimati vā, sā pahīyissatī”ti.**Though there will be some foolish people who have doubt or uncertainty regarding the Realized One, when they hear this exposition of the teaching they’ll give up that doubt or uncertainty.”*";
P_HTM[1885]="*Iti hidaṃ āyasmā sāriputto bhagavato sammukhā sampasādaṃ pavedesi.**That’s how Venerable Sāriputta declared his confidence in the Buddha’s presence.*";
P_HTM[1886]="*Tasmā imassa veyyākaraṇassa sampasādanīyantveva adhivacananti.**And that’s why the name of this discussion is “Inspiring Confidence”.*";
P_HTM[1887]="*Sampasādanīyasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1888]="*29. Pāsādikasutta  - An Impressive Discourse * **";
P_HTM[1889]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[1890]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sakkesu viharati vedhaññā nāma sakyā, tesaṃ ambavane pāsāde.**At one time the Buddha was staying in the land of the Sakyans in a stilt longhouse in a mango grove belonging to the Sakyan family named Vedhañña.*";
P_HTM[1891]="*Tena kho pana samayena nigaṇṭho nāṭaputto pāvāyaṃ adhunākālaṅkato hoti.**Now at that time the Nigaṇṭha Nātaputta had recently passed away at Pāvā.*";
P_HTM[1892]="*Tassa kālaṃkiriyāya bhinnā nigaṇṭhā dvedhikajātā bhaṇḍanajātā kalahajātā vivādāpannā aññamaññaṃ mukhasattīhi vitudantā viharanti:**With his passing the Jain ascetics split, dividing into two factions, arguing, quarreling, and fighting, continually wounding each other with barbed words:*";
P_HTM[1893]="*“na tvaṃ imaṃ dhammavinayaṃ ājānāsi, ahaṃ imaṃ dhammavinayaṃ ājānāmi, kiṃ tvaṃ imaṃ dhammavinayaṃ ājānissasi? Micchāpaṭipanno tvamasi, ahamasmi sammāpaṭipanno. Sahitaṃ me, asahitaṃ te. Purevacanīyaṃ pacchā avaca, pacchāvacanīyaṃ pure avaca. Adhiciṇṇaṃ te viparāvattaṃ, āropito te vādo, niggahito tvamasi, cara vādappamokkhāya, nibbeṭhehi vā sace pahosī”ti.**“You don’t understand this teaching and training. I understand this teaching and training. What, you understand this teaching and training? You’re practicing wrong. I’m practicing right. I stay on topic, you don’t. You said last what you should have said first. You said first what you should have said last. What you’ve thought so much about has been disproved. Your doctrine is refuted. Go on, save your doctrine! You’re trapped; get yourself out of this—if you can!”*";
P_HTM[1894]="*Vadhoyeva kho maññe nigaṇṭhesu nāṭaputtiyesu vattati.**You’d think there was nothing but slaughter going on among the Jain ascetics.*";
P_HTM[1895]="*Yepi nigaṇṭhassa nāṭaputtassa sāvakā gihī odātavasanā, tepi nigaṇṭhesu nāṭaputtiyesu nibbinnarūpā virattarūpā paṭivānarūpā, yathā taṃ durakkhāte dhammavinaye duppavedite aniyyānike anupasamasaṃvattanike asammāsambuddhappavedite bhinnathūpe appaṭisaraṇe.**And the Nigaṇṭha Nātaputta’s white-clothed lay disciples were disillusioned, dismayed, and disappointed in the Jain ascetics. They were equally disappointed with a teaching and training so poorly explained and poorly propounded, not emancipating, not leading to peace, proclaimed by someone who is not a fully awakened Buddha, with broken monument and without a refuge.*";
P_HTM[1896]="*Atha kho cundo samaṇuddeso pāvāyaṃ vassaṃvuṭṭho yena sāmagāmo, yenāyasmā ānando tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho cundo samaṇuddeso āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ etadavoca:**And then, after completing the rainy season residence near Pāvā, the novice Cunda went to see Venerable Ānanda at Sāma village. He bowed, sat down to one side, and told him what had happened.*";
P_HTM[1897]="*“nigaṇṭho, bhante, nāṭaputto pāvāyaṃ adhunākālaṅkato.* **";
P_HTM[1898]="*Tassa kālaṃkiriyāya bhinnā nigaṇṭhā dvedhikajātā … pe … bhinnathūpe appaṭisaraṇe”ti.* **";
P_HTM[1899]="*Evaṃ vutte, āyasmā ānando cundaṃ samaṇuddesaṃ etadavoca:**Ānanda said to him,*";
P_HTM[1900]="*“atthi kho idaṃ, āvuso cunda, kathāpābhataṃ bhagavantaṃ dassanāya.**“Reverend Cunda, we should see the Buddha about this matter.*";
P_HTM[1901]="*Āyāmāvuso cunda, yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamissāma; upasaṅkamitvā etamatthaṃ bhagavato ārocessāmā”ti.**Come, let’s go to the Buddha and tell him about this.”*";
P_HTM[1902]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho cundo samaṇuddeso āyasmato ānandassa paccassosi.**“Yes, sir,” replied Cunda.*";
P_HTM[1903]="*Atha kho āyasmā ca ānando cundo ca samaṇuddeso yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho āyasmā ānando bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Ānanda and Cunda went to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and told him what had happened.*";
P_HTM[1904]="*“ayaṃ, bhante, cundo samaṇuddeso evamāha, ‘nigaṇṭho, bhante, nāṭaputto pāvāyaṃ adhunākālaṅkato,* **";
P_HTM[1905]="*tassa kālaṅkiriyāya bhinnā nigaṇṭhā … pe … bhinnathūpe appaṭisaraṇe’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[1906]="*1. Asammāsambuddhappaveditadhammavinaya**1. The Teaching of the Unawakened*";
P_HTM[1907]="*“Evaṃ hetaṃ, cunda, hoti durakkhāte dhammavinaye duppavedite aniyyānike anupasamasaṃvattanike asammāsambuddhappavedite.**“That’s what happens, Cunda, when a teaching and training is poorly explained and poorly propounded, not emancipating, not leading to peace, proclaimed by someone who is not a fully awakened Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1908]="*Idha, cunda, satthā ca hoti asammāsambuddho, dhammo ca durakkhāto duppavedito aniyyāniko anupasamasaṃvattaniko asammāsambuddhappavedito,**Take the case where a teacher is not awakened, and the teaching is poorly explained and poorly propounded, not emancipating, not leading to peace, proclaimed by someone who is not a fully awakened Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1909]="*sāvako ca tasmiṃ dhamme na dhammānudhammappaṭipanno viharati na sāmīcippaṭipanno na anudhammacārī, vokkamma ca tamhā dhammā vattati.**A disciple in that teaching does not practice in line with the teachings, does not practice following that procedure, does not live in line with the teaching. They proceed having turned away from that teaching.*";
P_HTM[1910]="*So evamassa vacanīyo:**You should say this to them,*";
P_HTM[1911]="*‘tassa te, āvuso, lābhā, tassa te suladdhaṃ,**‘You’re fortunate, reverend, you’re so very fortunate!*";
P_HTM[1912]="*satthā ca te asammāsambuddho, dhammo ca durakkhāto duppavedito aniyyāniko anupasamasaṃvattaniko asammāsambuddhappavedito.**For your teacher is not awakened, and their teaching is poorly explained and poorly propounded, not emancipating, not leading to peace, proclaimed by someone who is not a fully awakened Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1913]="*Tvañca tasmiṃ dhamme na dhammānudhammappaṭipanno viharasi, na sāmīcippaṭipanno, na anudhammacārī, vokkamma ca tamhā dhammā vattasī’ti.**But you don’t practice in line with that teaching, you don’t practice following that procedure, you don’t live in line with the teaching. You proceed having turned away from that teaching.’*";
P_HTM[1914]="*Iti kho, cunda, satthāpi tattha gārayho, dhammopi tattha gārayho, sāvako ca tattha evaṃ pāsaṃso.**In such a case the teacher and the teaching are to blame, but the disciple deserves praise.*";
P_HTM[1915]="*Yo kho, cunda, evarūpaṃ sāvakaṃ evaṃ vadeyya:**Suppose someone was to say to such a disciple,*";
P_HTM[1916]="*‘etāyasmā tathā paṭipajjatu, yathā te satthārā dhammo desito paññatto’ti.**‘Come on, venerable, practice as taught and pointed out by your teacher.’*";
P_HTM[1917]="*Yo ca samādapeti, yañca samādapeti, yo ca samādapito tathattāya paṭipajjati. Sabbe te bahuṃ apuññaṃ pasavanti.**The one who encourages, the one who they encourage, and the one who practices accordingly all make much bad karma.*";
P_HTM[1918]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[1919]="*Evaṃ hetaṃ, cunda, hoti durakkhāte dhammavinaye duppavedite aniyyānike anupasamasaṃvattanike asammāsambuddhappavedite.**It’s because that teaching and training is poorly explained and poorly propounded, not emancipating, not leading to peace, proclaimed by someone who is not a fully awakened Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1920]="*Idha pana, cunda, satthā ca hoti asammāsambuddho, dhammo ca durakkhāto duppavedito aniyyāniko anupasamasaṃvattaniko asammāsambuddhappavedito,**Take the case where a teacher is not awakened, and the teaching is poorly explained and poorly propounded, not emancipating, not leading to peace, proclaimed by someone who is not a fully awakened Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1921]="*sāvako ca tasmiṃ dhamme dhammānudhammappaṭipanno viharati sāmīcippaṭipanno anudhammacārī, samādāya taṃ dhammaṃ vattati.**A disciple in that teaching practices in line with the teachings, practices following that procedure, lives in line with the teaching. They proceed having undertaken that teaching.*";
P_HTM[1922]="*So evamassa vacanīyo:**You should say this to them,*";
P_HTM[1923]="*‘tassa te, āvuso, alābhā, tassa te dulladdhaṃ, satthā ca te asammāsambuddho, dhammo ca durakkhāto duppavedito aniyyāniko anupasamasaṃvattaniko asammāsambuddhappavedito.**‘It’s your loss, reverend, it’s your misfortune! For your teacher is not awakened, and their teaching is poorly explained and poorly propounded, not emancipating, not leading to peace, proclaimed by someone who is not a fully awakened Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1924]="*Tvañca tasmiṃ dhamme dhammānudhammappaṭipanno viharasi sāmīcippaṭipanno anudhammacārī, samādāya taṃ dhammaṃ vattasī’ti.**And you practice in line with that teaching, you practice following that procedure, you live in line with the teaching. You proceed having undertaken that teaching.’*";
P_HTM[1925]="*Iti kho, cunda, satthāpi tattha gārayho, dhammopi tattha gārayho, sāvakopi tattha evaṃ gārayho.**In such a case the teacher, the teaching, and the disciple are all to blame.*";
P_HTM[1926]="*Yo kho, cunda, evarūpaṃ sāvakaṃ evaṃ vadeyya:**Suppose someone was to say to such a disciple,*";
P_HTM[1927]="*‘addhāyasmā ñāyappaṭipanno ñāyamārādhessatī’ti.**‘Clearly the venerable is practicing methodically and will succeed in completing that method.’*";
P_HTM[1928]="*Yo ca pasaṃsati, yañca pasaṃsati, yo ca pasaṃsito bhiyyoso mattāya vīriyaṃ ārabhati. Sabbe te bahuṃ apuññaṃ pasavanti.**The one who praises, the one who they praise, and the one who, being praised, rouses up even more energy all make much bad karma.*";
P_HTM[1929]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[1930]="*Evañhetaṃ, cunda, hoti durakkhāte dhammavinaye duppavedite aniyyānike anupasamasaṃvattanike asammāsambuddhappavedite.**It’s because that teaching and training is poorly explained and poorly propounded, not emancipating, not leading to peace, proclaimed by someone who is not a fully awakened Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1931]="*2. Sammāsambuddhappaveditadhammavinaya**2. The Teaching of the Awakened*";
P_HTM[1932]="*Idha pana, cunda, satthā ca hoti sammāsambuddho, dhammo ca svākkhāto suppavedito niyyāniko upasamasaṃvattaniko sammāsambuddhappavedito,**Take the case where a teacher is awakened, and the teaching is well explained and well propounded, emancipating, leading to peace, proclaimed by someone who is a fully awakened Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1933]="*sāvako ca tasmiṃ dhamme na dhammānudhammappaṭipanno viharati, na sāmīcippaṭipanno, na anudhammacārī, vokkamma ca tamhā dhammā vattati.**A disciple in that teaching does not practice in line with the teachings, does not practice following that procedure, does not live in line with the teaching. They proceed having turned away from that teaching.*";
P_HTM[1934]="*So evamassa vacanīyo:**You should say this to them,*";
P_HTM[1935]="*‘tassa te, āvuso, alābhā, tassa te dulladdhaṃ, satthā ca te sammāsambuddho, dhammo ca svākkhāto suppavedito niyyāniko upasamasaṃvattaniko sammāsambuddhappavedito.**‘It’s your loss, reverend, it’s your misfortune! For your teacher is awakened, and their teaching is well explained and well propounded, emancipating, leading to peace, proclaimed by someone who is a fully awakened Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1936]="*Tvañca tasmiṃ dhamme na dhammānudhammappaṭipanno viharasi, na sāmīcippaṭipanno, na anudhammacārī, vokkamma ca tamhā dhammā vattasī’ti.**But you don’t practice in line with that teaching, you don’t practice following that procedure, you don’t live in line with the teaching. You proceed having turned away from that teaching.’*";
P_HTM[1937]="*Iti kho, cunda, satthāpi tattha pāsaṃso, dhammopi tattha pāsaṃso, sāvako ca tattha evaṃ gārayho.**In such a case the teacher and the teaching deserve praise, but the disciple is to blame.*";
P_HTM[1938]="*Yo kho, cunda, evarūpaṃ sāvakaṃ evaṃ vadeyya:**Suppose someone was to say to such a disciple,*";
P_HTM[1939]="*‘etāyasmā tathā paṭipajjatu yathā te satthārā dhammo desito paññatto’ti.**‘Come on, venerable, practice as taught and pointed out by your teacher.’*";
P_HTM[1940]="*Yo ca samādapeti, yañca samādapeti, yo ca samādapito tathattāya paṭipajjati. Sabbe te bahuṃ puññaṃ pasavanti.**The one who encourages, the one who they encourage, and the one who practices accordingly all make much merit.*";
P_HTM[1941]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[1942]="*Evañhetaṃ, cunda, hoti svākkhāte dhammavinaye suppavedite niyyānike upasamasaṃvattanike sammāsambuddhappavedite.**It’s because that teaching and training is well explained and well propounded, emancipating, leading to peace, proclaimed by someone who is a fully awakened Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1943]="*Idha pana, cunda, satthā ca hoti sammāsambuddho, dhammo ca svākkhāto suppavedito niyyāniko upasamasaṃvattaniko sammāsambuddhappavedito,**Take the case where a teacher is awakened, and the teaching is well explained and well propounded, emancipating, leading to peace, proclaimed by someone who is a fully awakened Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1944]="*sāvako ca tasmiṃ dhamme dhammānudhammappaṭipanno viharati sāmīcippaṭipanno anudhammacārī, samādāya taṃ dhammaṃ vattati.**A disciple in that teaching practices in line with the teachings, practices following that procedure, lives in line with the teaching. They proceed having undertaken that teaching.*";
P_HTM[1945]="*So evamassa vacanīyo:**You should say this to them,*";
P_HTM[1946]="*‘tassa te, āvuso, lābhā, tassa te suladdhaṃ,**‘You’re fortunate, reverend, you’re so very fortunate!*";
P_HTM[1947]="*satthā ca te sammāsambuddho, dhammo ca svākkhāto suppavedito niyyāniko upasamasaṃvattaniko sammāsambuddhappavedito.**For your teacher is awakened, and their teaching is well explained and well propounded, emancipating, leading to peace, proclaimed by someone who is a fully awakened Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1948]="*Tvañca tasmiṃ dhamme dhammānudhammappaṭipanno viharasi sāmīcippaṭipanno anudhammacārī, samādāya taṃ dhammaṃ vattasī’ti.**And you practice in line with that teaching, you practice following that procedure, you live in line with the teaching. You proceed having undertaken that teaching.’*";
P_HTM[1949]="*Iti kho, cunda, satthāpi tattha pāsaṃso, dhammopi tattha pāsaṃso, sāvakopi tattha evaṃ pāsaṃso.**In such a case the teacher, the teaching, and the disciple all deserve praise.*";
P_HTM[1950]="*Yo kho, cunda, evarūpaṃ sāvakaṃ evaṃ vadeyya:**Suppose someone was to say to such a disciple,*";
P_HTM[1951]="*‘addhāyasmā ñāyappaṭipanno ñāyamārādhessatī’ti.**‘Clearly the venerable is practicing methodically and will succeed in completing that method.’*";
P_HTM[1952]="*Yo ca pasaṃsati, yañca pasaṃsati, yo ca pasaṃsito bhiyyoso mattāya vīriyaṃ ārabhati. Sabbe te bahuṃ puññaṃ pasavanti.**The one who praises, the one who they praise, and the one who, being praised, rouses up even more energy all make much merit.*";
P_HTM[1953]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[1954]="*Evañhetaṃ, cunda, hoti svākkhāte dhammavinaye suppavedite niyyānike upasamasaṃvattanike sammāsambuddhappavedite.**It’s because that teaching and training is well explained and well propounded, emancipating, leading to peace, proclaimed by someone who is a fully awakened Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1955]="*3. Sāvakānutappasatthu**3. When Disciples Have Regrets*";
P_HTM[1956]="*Idha pana, cunda, satthā ca loke udapādi arahaṃ sammāsambuddho, dhammo ca svākkhāto suppavedito niyyāniko upasamasaṃvattaniko sammāsambuddhappavedito,**Take the case where a teacher arises in the world who is perfected, a fully awakened Buddha. The teaching is well explained and well propounded, emancipating, leading to peace, proclaimed by someone who is fully awakened.*";
P_HTM[1957]="*aviññāpitatthā cassa honti sāvakā saddhamme, na ca tesaṃ kevalaṃ paripūraṃ brahmacariyaṃ āvikataṃ hoti uttānīkataṃ sabbasaṅgāhapadakataṃ sappāṭihīrakataṃ yāva devamanussehi suppakāsitaṃ.**But the disciples haven’t inquired about the meaning of that good teaching. And the spiritual practice that’s entirely full and pure has not been disclosed and revealed to them with all its collected sayings, with its demonstrable basis, well proclaimed wherever there are gods and humans.*";
P_HTM[1958]="*Atha nesaṃ satthuno antaradhānaṃ hoti.**And then their teacher passes away.*";
P_HTM[1959]="*Evarūpo kho, cunda, satthā sāvakānaṃ kālaṅkato anutappo hoti.**When such a teacher has passed away the disciples are tormented by regrets.*";
P_HTM[1960]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[1961]="*‘Satthā ca no loke udapādi arahaṃ sammāsambuddho, dhammo ca svākkhāto suppavedito niyyāniko upasamasaṃvattaniko sammāsambuddhappavedito, aviññāpitatthā camha saddhamme, na ca no kevalaṃ paripūraṃ brahmacariyaṃ āvikataṃ hoti uttānīkataṃ sabbasaṅgāhapadakataṃ sappāṭihīrakataṃ yāva devamanussehi suppakāsitaṃ.**They think: ‘Our teacher was perfected, a fully awakened Buddha. His teaching was well explained, but we didn’t inquire about the meaning, and the spiritual practice was not fully disclosed to us.*";
P_HTM[1962]="*Atha no satthuno antaradhānaṃ hotī’ti.**And then our teacher passed away.’*";
P_HTM[1963]="*Evarūpo kho, cunda, satthā sāvakānaṃ kālaṅkato anutappo hoti.**When such a teacher has passed away the disciples are tormented by regrets.*";
P_HTM[1964]="*4. Sāvakānanutappasatthu**4. When Disciples Have No Regrets*";
P_HTM[1965]="*Idha pana, cunda, satthā ca loke udapādi arahaṃ sammāsambuddho. Dhammo ca svākkhāto suppavedito niyyāniko upasamasaṃvattaniko sammāsambuddhappavedito.**Take the case where a teacher arises in the world who is perfected, a fully awakened Buddha. The teaching is well explained and well propounded, emancipating, leading to peace, proclaimed by someone who is fully awakened.*";
P_HTM[1966]="*Viññāpitatthā cassa honti sāvakā saddhamme, kevalañca tesaṃ paripūraṃ brahmacariyaṃ āvikataṃ hoti uttānīkataṃ sabbasaṅgāhapadakataṃ sappāṭihīrakataṃ yāva devamanussehi suppakāsitaṃ.**The disciples have inquired about the meaning of that good teaching. And the spiritual practice that’s entirely full and pure has been disclosed and revealed to them with all its collected sayings, with its demonstrable basis, well proclaimed wherever there are gods and humans.*";
P_HTM[1967]="*Atha nesaṃ satthuno antaradhānaṃ hoti.**And then their teacher passes away.*";
P_HTM[1968]="*Evarūpo kho, cunda, satthā sāvakānaṃ kālaṅkato ananutappo hoti.**When such a teacher has passed away the disciples are free of regrets.*";
P_HTM[1969]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[1970]="*‘Satthā ca no loke udapādi arahaṃ sammāsambuddho.**They think: ‘Our teacher was perfected, a fully awakened Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1971]="*Dhammo ca svākkhāto suppavedito niyyāniko upasamasaṃvattaniko sammāsambuddhappavedito.**His teaching was well explained,*";
P_HTM[1972]="*Viññāpitatthā camha saddhamme, kevalañca no paripūraṃ brahmacariyaṃ āvikataṃ hoti uttānīkataṃ sabbasaṅgāhapadakataṃ sappāṭihīrakataṃ yāva devamanussehi suppakāsitaṃ.**we inquired about the meaning, and the spiritual practice was fully disclosed to us.*";
P_HTM[1973]="*Atha no satthuno antaradhānaṃ hotī’ti.**And then our teacher passed away.’*";
P_HTM[1974]="*Evarūpo kho, cunda, satthā sāvakānaṃ kālaṅkato ananutappo hoti.**When such a teacher has passed away the disciples are free of regrets.*";
P_HTM[1975]="*5. Brahmacariyaaparipūrādikathā**5. On the Incomplete Spiritual Path, Etc.*";
P_HTM[1976]="*Etehi cepi, cunda, aṅgehi samannāgataṃ brahmacariyaṃ hoti, no ca kho satthā hoti thero rattaññū cirapabbajito addhagato vayoanuppatto.**Now suppose, Cunda, that a spiritual path possesses those factors. But the teacher is not senior, long standing, long gone forth, advanced in years, and reached the final stage of life.*";
P_HTM[1977]="*Evaṃ taṃ brahmacariyaṃ aparipūraṃ hoti tenaṅgena.**Then that spiritual path is incomplete in that respect.*";
P_HTM[1978]="*Yato ca kho, cunda, etehi ceva aṅgehi samannāgataṃ brahmacariyaṃ hoti, satthā ca hoti thero rattaññū cirapabbajito addhagato vayoanuppatto.**But when a spiritual path possesses those factors and the teacher is senior,*";
P_HTM[1979]="*Evaṃ taṃ brahmacariyaṃ paripūraṃ hoti tenaṅgena.**then that spiritual path is complete in that respect.*";
P_HTM[1980]="*Etehi cepi, cunda, aṅgehi samannāgataṃ brahmacariyaṃ hoti, satthā ca hoti thero rattaññū cirapabbajito addhagato vayoanuppatto, no ca khvassa therā bhikkhū sāvakā honti viyattā vinītā visāradā pattayogakkhemā.**Now suppose that a spiritual path possesses those factors and the teacher is senior. But there are no senior monk disciples who are competent, educated, assured, have attained sanctuary,*";
P_HTM[1981]="*Alaṃ samakkhātuṃ saddhammassa, alaṃ uppannaṃ parappavādaṃ sahadhammehi suniggahitaṃ niggahetvā sappāṭihāriyaṃ dhammaṃ desetuṃ.**who can rightly explain the true teaching, and who can legitimately and completely refute the doctrines of others that come up, and teach with a demonstrable basis.*";
P_HTM[1982]="*Evaṃ taṃ brahmacariyaṃ aparipūraṃ hoti tenaṅgena.**Then that spiritual path is incomplete in that respect.*";
P_HTM[1983]="*Yato ca kho, cunda, etehi ceva aṅgehi samannāgataṃ brahmacariyaṃ hoti, satthā ca hoti thero rattaññū cirapabbajito addhagato vayoanuppatto, therā cassa bhikkhū sāvakā honti viyattā vinītā visāradā pattayogakkhemā.**But when a spiritual path possesses those factors and the teacher is senior and there are competent senior monks,*";
P_HTM[1984]="*Alaṃ samakkhātuṃ saddhammassa, alaṃ uppannaṃ parappavādaṃ sahadhammehi suniggahitaṃ niggahetvā sappāṭihāriyaṃ dhammaṃ desetuṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1985]="*Evaṃ taṃ brahmacariyaṃ paripūraṃ hoti tenaṅgena.**then that spiritual path is complete in that respect.*";
P_HTM[1986]="*Etehi cepi, cunda, aṅgehi samannāgataṃ brahmacariyaṃ hoti, satthā ca hoti thero rattaññū cirapabbajito addhagato vayoanuppatto, therā cassa bhikkhū sāvakā honti viyattā vinītā visāradā pattayogakkhemā.**Now suppose that a spiritual path possesses those factors and the teacher is senior and there are competent senior monks.*";
P_HTM[1987]="*Alaṃ samakkhātuṃ saddhammassa, alaṃ uppannaṃ parappavādaṃ sahadhammehi suniggahitaṃ niggahetvā sappāṭihāriyaṃ dhammaṃ desetuṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1988]="*No ca khvassa majjhimā bhikkhū sāvakā honti … pe …**But there are no competent middle monks,*";
P_HTM[1989]="*majjhimā cassa bhikkhū sāvakā honti, no ca khvassa navā bhikkhū sāvakā honti … pe …**junior monks,*";
P_HTM[1990]="*navā cassa bhikkhū sāvakā honti, no ca khvassa therā bhikkhuniyo sāvikā honti … pe …**senior nuns,*";
P_HTM[1991]="*therā cassa bhikkhuniyo sāvikā honti, no ca khvassa majjhimā bhikkhuniyo sāvikā honti … pe …**middle nuns,*";
P_HTM[1992]="*majjhimā cassa bhikkhuniyo sāvikā honti, no ca khvassa navā bhikkhuniyo sāvikā honti … pe …**junior nuns,*";
P_HTM[1993]="*navā cassa bhikkhuniyo sāvikā honti, no ca khvassa upāsakā sāvakā honti gihī odātavasanā brahmacārino … pe …**celibate white-clothed laymen,*";
P_HTM[1994]="*upāsakā cassa sāvakā honti gihī odātavasanā brahmacārino, no ca khvassa upāsakā sāvakā honti gihī odātavasanā kāmabhogino … pe …**white-clothed laymen enjoying sensual pleasures,*";
P_HTM[1995]="*upāsakā cassa sāvakā honti gihī odātavasanā kāmabhogino, no ca khvassa upāsikā sāvikā honti gihiniyo odātavasanā brahmacāriniyo … pe …**celibate white-clothed laywomen,*";
P_HTM[1996]="*upāsikā cassa sāvikā honti gihiniyo odātavasanā brahmacāriniyo, no ca khvassa upāsikā sāvikā honti gihiniyo odātavasanā kāmabhoginiyo … pe …**white-clothed laywomen enjoying sensual pleasures. …*";
P_HTM[1997]="*upāsikā cassa sāvikā honti gihiniyo odātavasanā kāmabhoginiyo, no ca khvassa brahmacariyaṃ hoti iddhañceva phītañca vitthārikaṃ bāhujaññaṃ puthubhūtaṃ yāva devamanussehi suppakāsitaṃ … pe …**There are white-clothed laywomen enjoying sensual pleasures, but the spiritual path is not successful and prosperous, extensive, popular, widespread, and well proclaimed wherever there are gods and humans …*";
P_HTM[1998]="*brahmacariyañcassa hoti iddhañceva phītañca vitthārikaṃ bāhujaññaṃ puthubhūtaṃ yāva devamanussehi suppakāsitaṃ, no ca kho lābhaggayasaggappattaṃ.**the spiritual path is successful and prosperous, extensive, popular, widespread, and well proclaimed wherever there are gods and humans, but it has not reached the peak of material possessions and fame.*";
P_HTM[1999]="*Evaṃ taṃ brahmacariyaṃ aparipūraṃ hoti tenaṅgena.**Then that spiritual path is incomplete in that respect.*";
P_HTM[2000]="*Yato ca kho, cunda, etehi ceva aṅgehi samannāgataṃ brahmacariyaṃ hoti, satthā ca hoti thero rattaññū cirapabbajito addhagato vayoanuppatto, therā cassa bhikkhū sāvakā honti viyattā vinītā visāradā pattayogakkhemā.**But when a spiritual path possesses those factors and the teacher is senior and there are competent senior monks,*";
P_HTM[2001]="*Alaṃ samakkhātuṃ saddhammassa, alaṃ uppannaṃ parappavādaṃ sahadhammehi suniggahitaṃ niggahetvā sappāṭihāriyaṃ dhammaṃ desetuṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2002]="*Majjhimā cassa bhikkhū sāvakā honti …**middle monks,*";
P_HTM[2003]="*navā cassa bhikkhū sāvakā honti …**junior monks,*";
P_HTM[2004]="*therā cassa bhikkhuniyo sāvikā honti …**senior nuns,*";
P_HTM[2005]="*majjhimā cassa bhikkhuniyo sāvikā honti …**middle nuns,*";
P_HTM[2006]="*navā cassa bhikkhuniyo sāvikā honti …**junior nuns,*";
P_HTM[2007]="*upāsakā cassa sāvakā honti … gihī odātavasanā brahmacārino.**celibate laymen,*";
P_HTM[2008]="*Upāsakā cassa sāvakā honti gihī odātavasanā kāmabhogino …**laymen enjoying sensual pleasures,*";
P_HTM[2009]="*upāsikā cassa sāvikā honti gihiniyo odātavasanā brahmacāriniyo …**celibate laywomen,*";
P_HTM[2010]="*upāsikā cassa sāvikā honti gihiniyo odātavasanā kāmabhoginiyo …**laywomen enjoying sensual pleasures,*";
P_HTM[2011]="*brahmacariyañcassa hoti iddhañceva phītañca vitthārikaṃ bāhujaññaṃ puthubhūtaṃ yāva devamanussehi suppakāsitaṃ, lābhaggappattañca yasaggappattañca.**and the spiritual path is successful and prosperous, extensive, popular, widespread, and well proclaimed wherever there are gods and humans, and it has reached the peak of material possessions and fame,*";
P_HTM[2012]="*Evaṃ taṃ brahmacariyaṃ paripūraṃ hoti tenaṅgena.**then that spiritual path is complete in that respect.*";
P_HTM[2013]="*Ahaṃ kho pana, cunda, etarahi satthā loke uppanno arahaṃ sammāsambuddho.**I, Cunda, am a teacher who has arisen in the world today, perfected and fully awakened.*";
P_HTM[2014]="*Dhammo ca svākkhāto suppavedito niyyāniko upasamasaṃvattaniko sammāsambuddhappavedito.**The teaching is well explained and well propounded, emancipating, leading to peace, proclaimed by someone who is fully awakened.*";
P_HTM[2015]="*Viññāpitatthā ca me sāvakā saddhamme, kevalañca tesaṃ paripūraṃ brahmacariyaṃ āvikataṃ uttānīkataṃ sabbasaṅgāhapadakataṃ sappāṭihīrakataṃ yāva devamanussehi suppakāsitaṃ.**My disciples have inquired about the meaning of that good teaching. And the spiritual practice that’s entirely full and pure has been disclosed and revealed to them with all its collected sayings, with its demonstrable basis, well proclaimed wherever there are gods and humans.*";
P_HTM[2016]="*Ahaṃ kho pana, cunda, etarahi satthā thero rattaññū cirapabbajito addhagato vayoanuppatto.**I am a teacher today who is senior, long standing, long gone forth, advanced in years, and have reached the final stage of life.*";
P_HTM[2017]="*Santi kho pana me, cunda, etarahi therā bhikkhū sāvakā honti viyattā vinītā visāradā pattayogakkhemā.**I have today disciples who are competent senior monks,*";
P_HTM[2018]="*Alaṃ samakkhātuṃ saddhammassa, alaṃ uppannaṃ parappavādaṃ sahadhammehi suniggahitaṃ niggahetvā sappāṭihāriyaṃ dhammaṃ desetuṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2019]="*Santi kho pana me, cunda, etarahi majjhimā bhikkhū sāvakā …**middle monks,*";
P_HTM[2020]="*santi kho pana me, cunda, etarahi navā bhikkhū sāvakā …**junior monks,*";
P_HTM[2021]="*santi kho pana me, cunda, etarahi therā bhikkhuniyo sāvikā …**senior nuns,*";
P_HTM[2022]="*santi kho pana me, cunda, etarahi majjhimā bhikkhuniyo sāvikā …**middle nuns,*";
P_HTM[2023]="*santi kho pana me, cunda, etarahi navā bhikkhuniyo sāvikā …**junior nuns,*";
P_HTM[2024]="*santi kho pana me, cunda, etarahi upāsakā sāvakā gihī odātavasanā brahmacārino …**celibate laymen,*";
P_HTM[2025]="*santi kho pana me, cunda, etarahi upāsakā sāvakā gihī odātavasanā kāmabhogino …**laymen enjoying sensual pleasures,*";
P_HTM[2026]="*santi kho pana me, cunda, etarahi upāsikā sāvikā gihiniyo odātavasanā brahmacāriniyo …**celibate laywomen,*";
P_HTM[2027]="*santi kho pana me, cunda, etarahi upāsikā sāvikā gihiniyo odātavasanā kāmabhoginiyo …**and laywomen enjoying sensual pleasures.*";
P_HTM[2028]="*etarahi kho pana me, cunda, brahmacariyaṃ iddhañceva phītañca vitthārikaṃ bāhujaññaṃ puthubhūtaṃ yāva devamanussehi suppakāsitaṃ.**Today my spiritual life is successful and prosperous, extensive, popular, widespread, and well proclaimed wherever there are gods and humans.*";
P_HTM[2029]="*Yāvatā kho, cunda, etarahi satthāro loke uppannā, nāhaṃ, cunda, aññaṃ ekasatthārampi samanupassāmi evaṃlābhaggayasaggappattaṃ yatharivāhaṃ.**Of all the teachers in the world today, Cunda, I don’t see even a single one who has reached the peak of material possessions and fame like me.*";
P_HTM[2030]="*Yāvatā kho pana, cunda, etarahi saṅgho vā gaṇo vā loke uppanno;**Of all the spiritual communities and groups in the world today, Cunda, I don’t see even a single one who has reached the pinnacle of material possessions and fame like the mendicant Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[2031]="*nāhaṃ, cunda, aññaṃ ekasaṅghampi samanupassāmi evaṃlābhaggayasaggappattaṃ yatharivāyaṃ, cunda, bhikkhusaṅgho.* **";
P_HTM[2032]="*Yaṃ kho taṃ, cunda, sammā vadamāno vadeyya:**And if there’s any spiritual path of which it may be rightly said that*";
P_HTM[2033]="*‘sabbākārasampannaṃ sabbākāraparipūraṃ anūnamanadhikaṃ svākkhātaṃ kevalaṃ paripūraṃ brahmacariyaṃ suppakāsitan’ti.**it’s endowed with all good qualities, complete in all good qualities, neither too little nor too much, well explained, whole, full, and well propounded,*";
P_HTM[2034]="*Idameva taṃ sammā vadamāno vadeyya:**it’s of this spiritual path that this should be said.*";
P_HTM[2035]="*‘sabbākārasampannaṃ … pe … suppakāsitan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2036]="*Udako sudaṃ, cunda, rāmaputto evaṃ vācaṃ bhāsati:**Uddaka, son of Rāma, used to say:*";
P_HTM[2037]="*‘passaṃ na passatī’ti.**‘Seeing, one does not see.’*";
P_HTM[2038]="*Kiñca passaṃ na passatīti?**But seeing what does one not see?*";
P_HTM[2039]="*Khurassa sādhunisitassa talamassa passati, dhārañca khvassa na passati.**You can see the blade of a well-sharpened razor, but not the edge.*";
P_HTM[2040]="*Idaṃ vuccati:**Thus it is said:*";
P_HTM[2041]="*‘passaṃ na passatī’ti.**‘Seeing, one does not see.’*";
P_HTM[2042]="*Yaṃ kho panetaṃ, cunda, udakena rāmaputtena bhāsitaṃ hīnaṃ gammaṃ pothujjanikaṃ anariyaṃ anatthasaṃhitaṃ khurameva sandhāya.**But that saying of Uddaka’s is low, crude, ordinary, ignoble, and pointless, as it’s only concerning a razor.*";
P_HTM[2043]="*Yañca taṃ, cunda, sammā vadamāno vadeyya:**If there’s anything of which it may be rightly said:*";
P_HTM[2044]="*‘passaṃ na passatī’ti, idameva taṃ sammā vadamāno vadeyya:**‘Seeing, one does not see,’ it’s of this that it should be said.*";
P_HTM[2045]="*‘passaṃ na passatī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2046]="*Kiñca passaṃ na passatīti?**Seeing what does one not see?*";
P_HTM[2047]="*Evaṃ sabbākārasampannaṃ sabbākāraparipūraṃ anūnamanadhikaṃ svākkhātaṃ kevalaṃ paripūraṃ brahmacariyaṃ suppakāsitanti, iti hetaṃ passati.**One sees this: a spiritual path endowed with all good qualities, complete in all good qualities, neither too little nor too much, well explained, whole, full, and well propounded.*";
P_HTM[2048]="*Idamettha apakaḍḍheyya, evaṃ taṃ parisuddhataraṃ assāti, iti hetaṃ na passati.**One does not see this: anything that, were it to be removed, would make it purer.*";
P_HTM[2049]="*Idamettha upakaḍḍheyya, evaṃ taṃ paripūraṃ assāti, iti hetaṃ na passati.**One does not see this: anything that, were it to be added, would make it more complete.*";
P_HTM[2050]="*Idaṃ vuccati, cunda:**Thus it is rightly said:*";
P_HTM[2051]="*‘passaṃ na passatī’ti.**‘Seeing, one does not see.’*";
P_HTM[2052]="*Yaṃ kho taṃ, cunda, sammā vadamāno vadeyya:* **";
P_HTM[2053]="*‘sabbākārasampannaṃ … pe …* **";
P_HTM[2054]="*brahmacariyaṃ suppakāsitan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2055]="*Idameva taṃ sammā vadamāno vadeyya:* **";
P_HTM[2056]="*‘sabbākārasampannaṃ sabbākāraparipūraṃ anūnamanadhikaṃ svākkhātaṃ kevalaṃ paripūraṃ brahmacariyaṃ suppakāsitan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2057]="*6. Saṅgāyitabbadhamma**6. Teachings Should be Recited in Concert*";
P_HTM[2058]="*Tasmātiha, cunda, ye vo mayā dhammā abhiññā desitā, tattha sabbeheva saṅgamma samāgamma atthena atthaṃ byañjanena byañjanaṃ saṅgāyitabbaṃ na vivaditabbaṃ, yathayidaṃ brahmacariyaṃ addhaniyaṃ assa ciraṭṭhitikaṃ, tadassa bahujanahitāya bahujanasukhāya lokānukampāya atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānaṃ.**So, Cunda, you should all come together and recite in concert, without disputing, those things I have taught you from my direct knowledge, comparing meaning with meaning and phrasing with phrasing, so that this spiritual path may last for a long time. That would be for the welfare and happiness of the people, for the benefit, welfare, and happiness of gods and humans.*";
P_HTM[2059]="*Katame ca te, cunda, dhammā mayā abhiññā desitā, yattha sabbeheva saṅgamma samāgamma atthena atthaṃ byañjanena byañjanaṃ saṅgāyitabbaṃ na vivaditabbaṃ, yathayidaṃ brahmacariyaṃ addhaniyaṃ assa ciraṭṭhitikaṃ, tadassa bahujanahitāya bahujanasukhāya lokānukampāya atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānaṃ?**And what are those things I have taught from my direct knowledge?*";
P_HTM[2060]="*Seyyathidaṃ—cattāro satipaṭṭhānā, cattāro sammappadhānā, cattāro iddhipādā, pañcindriyāni, pañca balāni, satta bojjhaṅgā, ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo.**They are the four kinds of mindfulness meditation, the four right efforts, the four bases of psychic power, the five faculties, the five powers, the seven awakening factors, and the noble eightfold path.*";
P_HTM[2061]="*Ime kho te, cunda, dhammā mayā abhiññā desitā.**These are the things I have taught from my own direct knowledge.*";
P_HTM[2062]="*Yattha sabbeheva saṅgamma samāgamma atthena atthaṃ byañjanena byañjanaṃ saṅgāyitabbaṃ na vivaditabbaṃ, yathayidaṃ brahmacariyaṃ addhaniyaṃ assa ciraṭṭhitikaṃ, tadassa bahujanahitāya bahujanasukhāya lokānukampāya atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2063]="*7. Saññāpetabbavidhi**7. Reaching Agreement*";
P_HTM[2064]="*Tesañca vo, cunda, samaggānaṃ sammodamānānaṃ avivadamānānaṃ sikkhataṃ aññataro sabrahmacārī saṃghe dhammaṃ bhāseyya.**Suppose one of those spiritual companions who is training in harmony and mutual appreciation, without fighting, were to recite the teaching in the Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[2065]="*Tatra ce tumhākaṃ evamassa:**Now, you might think,*";
P_HTM[2066]="*‘ayaṃ kho āyasmā atthañceva micchā gaṇhāti, byañjanāni ca micchā ropetī’ti.**‘This venerable misconstrues the meaning and mistakes the phrasing.’*";
P_HTM[2067]="*Tassa neva abhinanditabbaṃ na paṭikkositabbaṃ, anabhinanditvā appaṭikkositvā so evamassa vacanīyo:**You should neither approve nor dismiss them, but say,*";
P_HTM[2068]="*‘imassa nu kho, āvuso, atthassa imāni vā byañjanāni etāni vā byañjanāni katamāni opāyikatarāni, imesañca byañjanānaṃ ayaṃ vā attho eso vā attho katamo opāyikataro’ti?**‘Reverend, if this is the meaning, the phrasing may either be this or that: which is more fitting? And if this is the phrasing, the meaning may be either this or that: which is more fitting?’*";
P_HTM[2069]="*So ce evaṃ vadeyya:**Suppose they reply,*";
P_HTM[2070]="*‘imassa kho, āvuso, atthassa imāneva byañjanāni opāyikatarāni, yā ceva etāni; imesañca byañjanānaṃ ayameva attho opāyikataro, yā ceva eso’ti.**‘This phrasing fits the meaning better than that. And this meaning fits the phrasing better than that.’*";
P_HTM[2071]="*So neva ussādetabbo na apasādetabbo, anussādetvā anapasādetvā sveva sādhukaṃ saññāpetabbo tassa ca atthassa tesañca byañjanānaṃ nisantiyā.**Without flattering or rebuking them, you should carefully convince them by examining that meaning and that phrasing.*";
P_HTM[2072]="*Aparopi ce, cunda, sabrahmacārī saṅghe dhammaṃ bhāseyya.**Suppose another spiritual companion were to recite the teaching in the Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[2073]="*Tatra ce tumhākaṃ evamassa:**Now, you might think,*";
P_HTM[2074]="*‘ayaṃ kho āyasmā atthañhi kho micchā gaṇhāti byañjanāni sammā ropetī’ti.**‘This venerable misconstrues the meaning but gets the phrasing right.’*";
P_HTM[2075]="*Tassa neva abhinanditabbaṃ na paṭikkositabbaṃ, anabhinanditvā appaṭikkositvā so evamassa vacanīyo:**You should neither approve nor dismiss them, but say,*";
P_HTM[2076]="*‘imesaṃ nu kho, āvuso, byañjanānaṃ ayaṃ vā attho eso vā attho katamo opāyikataro’ti?**‘Reverend, if this is the phrasing, the meaning may be either this or that: which is more fitting?’*";
P_HTM[2077]="*So ce evaṃ vadeyya:**Suppose they reply,*";
P_HTM[2078]="*‘imesaṃ kho, āvuso, byañjanānaṃ ayameva attho opāyikataro, yā ceva eso’ti.**‘This meaning fits the phrasing better than that.’*";
P_HTM[2079]="*So neva ussādetabbo na apasādetabbo, anussādetvā anapasādetvā sveva sādhukaṃ saññāpetabbo tasseva atthassa nisantiyā.**Without flattering or rebuking, you should carefully convince them by examining that meaning.*";
P_HTM[2080]="*Aparopi ce, cunda, sabrahmacārī saṅghe dhammaṃ bhāseyya.**Suppose another spiritual companion were to recite the teaching in the Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[2081]="*Tatra ce tumhākaṃ evamassa:**Now, you might think,*";
P_HTM[2082]="*‘ayaṃ kho āyasmā atthañhi kho sammā gaṇhāti byañjanāni micchā ropetī’ti.**‘This venerable construes the meaning correctly but mistakes the phrasing.’*";
P_HTM[2083]="*Tassa neva abhinanditabbaṃ na paṭikkositabbaṃ; anabhinanditvā appaṭikkositvā so evamassa vacanīyo:**You should neither approve nor dismiss them, but say,*";
P_HTM[2084]="*‘imassa nu kho, āvuso, atthassa imāni vā byañjanāni etāni vā byañjanāni katamāni opāyikatarānī’ti?**‘Reverend, if this is the meaning, the phrasing may be either this or that: which is more fitting?’*";
P_HTM[2085]="*So ce evaṃ vadeyya:**Suppose they reply,*";
P_HTM[2086]="*‘imassa kho, āvuso, atthassa imāneva byañjanāni opayikatarāni, yā ceva etānī’ti.**‘This phrasing fits the meaning better than that.’*";
P_HTM[2087]="*So neva ussādetabbo na apasādetabbo; anussādetvā anapasādetvā sveva sādhukaṃ saññāpetabbo tesaññeva byañjanānaṃ nisantiyā.**Without flattering or rebuking, you should carefully convince them by examining that phrasing.*";
P_HTM[2088]="*Aparopi ce, cunda, sabrahmacārī saṅghe dhammaṃ bhāseyya.**Suppose another spiritual companion were to recite the teaching in the Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[2089]="*Tatra ce tumhākaṃ evamassa:**Now, you might think,*";
P_HTM[2090]="*‘ayaṃ kho āyasmā atthañceva sammā gaṇhāti byañjanāni ca sammā ropetī’ti.**‘This venerable construes the meaning correctly and gets the phrasing right.’*";
P_HTM[2091]="*Tassa ‘sādhū’ti bhāsitaṃ abhinanditabbaṃ anumoditabbaṃ;**Saying ‘Good!’ you should applaud and cheer that mendicant’s statement,*";
P_HTM[2092]="*tassa ‘sādhū’ti bhāsitaṃ abhinanditvā anumoditvā so evamassa vacanīyo:**and then say to them,*";
P_HTM[2093]="*‘lābhā no, āvuso, suladdhaṃ no, āvuso,**‘We are fortunate, reverend, so very fortunate*";
P_HTM[2094]="*ye mayaṃ āyasmantaṃ tādisaṃ sabrahmacāriṃ passāma evaṃ atthupetaṃ byañjanupetan’ti.**to see a venerable such as yourself, so well-versed in the meaning and the phrasing, as one of our spiritual companions!’*";
P_HTM[2095]="*8. Paccayānuññātakāraṇa**8. The Reasons for Allowing Requisites*";
P_HTM[2096]="*Na vo ahaṃ, cunda, diṭṭhadhammikānaṃyeva āsavānaṃ saṃvarāya dhammaṃ desemi.**Cunda, I do not teach you solely for restraining defilements that affect the present life.*";
P_HTM[2097]="*Na panāhaṃ, cunda, samparāyikānaṃyeva āsavānaṃ paṭighātāya dhammaṃ desemi.**Nor do I teach solely for protecting against defilements that affect lives to come.*";
P_HTM[2098]="*Diṭṭhadhammikānaṃ cevāhaṃ, cunda, āsavānaṃ saṃvarāya dhammaṃ desemi;**I teach both for restraining defilements that affect the present life and*";
P_HTM[2099]="*samparāyikānañca āsavānaṃ paṭighātāya.**protecting against defilements that affect lives to come.*";
P_HTM[2100]="*Tasmātiha, cunda, yaṃ vo mayā cīvaraṃ anuññātaṃ, alaṃ vo taṃ**And that’s why I have allowed robes for you that suffice*";
P_HTM[2101]="*yāvadeva sītassa paṭighātāya, uṇhassa paṭighātāya, ḍaṃsamakasavātātapasarīsapasamphassānaṃ paṭighātāya, yāvadeva hirikopīnapaṭicchādanatthaṃ.**only for the sake of warding off cold and heat; for warding off the touch of flies, mosquitoes, wind, sun, and reptiles; and for covering up the private parts.*";
P_HTM[2102]="*Yo vo mayā piṇḍapāto anuññāto, alaṃ vo so**I have allowed alms-food for you that suffices*";
P_HTM[2103]="*yāvadeva imassa kāyassa ṭhitiyā yāpanāya vihiṃsūparatiyā brahmacariyānuggahāya, iti purāṇañca vedanaṃ paṭihaṅkhāmi, navañca vedanaṃ na uppādessāmi, yātrā ca me bhavissati anavajjatā ca phāsuvihāro ca.**only to continue and sustain this body, avoid harm, and support spiritual practice; so that you will put an end to old discomfort and not give rise to new discomfort, and will keep on living blamelessly and at ease.*";
P_HTM[2104]="*Yaṃ vo mayā senāsanaṃ anuññātaṃ, alaṃ vo taṃ**I have allowed lodgings for you that suffice*";
P_HTM[2105]="*yāvadeva sītassa paṭighātāya, uṇhassa paṭighātāya, ḍaṃsamakasavātātapasarīsapasamphassānaṃ paṭighātāya, yāvadeva utuparissayavinodanapaṭisallānārāmatthaṃ.**only for the sake of warding off cold and heat; for warding off the touch of flies, mosquitoes, wind, sun, and reptiles; to shelter from harsh weather and to enjoy retreat.*";
P_HTM[2106]="*Yo vo mayā gilānapaccayabhesajjaparikkhāro anuññāto, alaṃ vo so**I have allowed medicines and supplies for the sick for you that suffice*";
P_HTM[2107]="*yāvadeva uppannānaṃ veyyābādhikānaṃ vedanānaṃ paṭighātāya abyāpajjaparamatāya.**only for the sake of warding off the pains of illness and to promote good health.*";
P_HTM[2108]="*9. Sukhallikānuyoga**9. Indulgence in Pleasure*";
P_HTM[2109]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, cunda, vijjati yaṃ aññatitthiyā paribbājakā evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**It’s possible that wanderers who follow other paths might say,*";
P_HTM[2110]="*‘sukhallikānuyogamanuyuttā samaṇā sakyaputtiyā viharantī’ti.**‘The ascetics who follow the Sakyan live indulging in pleasure.’*";
P_HTM[2111]="*Evaṃvādino, cunda, aññatitthiyā paribbājakā evamassu vacanīyā:**You should say to them,*";
P_HTM[2112]="*‘katamo so, āvuso, sukhallikānuyogo?**‘What is that indulgence in pleasure?*";
P_HTM[2113]="*Sukhallikānuyogā hi bahū anekavihitā nānappakārakā’ti.**For there are many different kinds of indulgence in pleasure.’*";
P_HTM[2114]="*Cattārome, cunda, sukhallikānuyogā hīnā gammā pothujjanikā anariyā anatthasaṃhitā na nibbidāya na virāgāya na nirodhāya na upasamāya na abhiññāya na sambodhāya na nibbānāya saṃvattanti.**These four kinds of indulgence in pleasure, Cunda, are low, crude, ordinary, ignoble, and pointless. They don’t lead to disillusionment, dispassion, cessation, peace, insight, awakening, and extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[2115]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[2116]="*Idha, cunda, ekacco bālo pāṇe vadhitvā vadhitvā attānaṃ sukheti pīṇeti.**It’s when some fool makes themselves happy and pleased by killing living creatures.*";
P_HTM[2117]="*Ayaṃ paṭhamo sukhallikānuyogo.**This is the first kind of indulgence in pleasure.*";
P_HTM[2118]="*Puna caparaṃ, cunda, idhekacco adinnaṃ ādiyitvā ādiyitvā attānaṃ sukheti pīṇeti.**Furthermore, someone makes themselves happy and pleased by theft.*";
P_HTM[2119]="*Ayaṃ dutiyo sukhallikānuyogo.**This is the second kind of indulgence in pleasure.*";
P_HTM[2120]="*Puna caparaṃ, cunda, idhekacco musā bhaṇitvā bhaṇitvā attānaṃ sukheti pīṇeti.**Furthermore, someone makes themselves happy and pleased by lying.*";
P_HTM[2121]="*Ayaṃ tatiyo sukhallikānuyogo.**This is the third kind of indulgence in pleasure.*";
P_HTM[2122]="*Puna caparaṃ, cunda, idhekacco pañcahi kāmaguṇehi samappito samaṅgībhūto paricāreti.**Furthermore, someone amuses themselves, supplied and provided with the five kinds of sensual stimulation.*";
P_HTM[2123]="*Ayaṃ catuttho sukhallikānuyogo.**This is the fourth kind of indulgence in pleasure.*";
P_HTM[2124]="*Ime kho, cunda, cattāro sukhallikānuyogā hīnā gammā pothujjanikā anariyā anatthasaṃhitā na nibbidāya na virāgāya na nirodhāya na upasamāya na abhiññāya na sambodhāya na nibbānāya saṃvattanti.**These are the four kinds of indulgence in pleasure that are low, crude, ordinary, ignoble, and pointless. They don’t lead to disillusionment, dispassion, cessation, peace, insight, awakening, and extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[2125]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, cunda, vijjati yaṃ aññatitthiyā paribbājakā evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**It’s possible that wanderers who follow other paths might say,*";
P_HTM[2126]="*‘ime cattāro sukhallikānuyoge anuyuttā samaṇā sakyaputtiyā viharantī’ti.**‘The ascetics who follow the Sakyan live indulging in pleasure in these four ways.’*";
P_HTM[2127]="*Te vo ‘mā hevaṃ’ tissu vacanīyā.**They should be told, ‘Not so!’*";
P_HTM[2128]="*Na te vo sammā vadamānā vadeyyuṃ, abbhācikkheyyuṃ asatā abhūtena.**It isn’t right to say that about you; it misrepresents you with an untruth.*";
P_HTM[2129]="*Cattārome, cunda, sukhallikānuyogā ekantanibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya upasamāya abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattanti.**These four kinds of indulgence in pleasure, when developed and cultivated, lead solely to disillusionment, dispassion, cessation, peace, insight, awakening, and extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[2130]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[2131]="*Idha, cunda, bhikkhu vivicceva kāmehi vivicca akusalehi dhammehi savitakkaṃ savicāraṃ vivekajaṃ pītisukhaṃ paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**It’s when a mendicant, quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, enters and remains in the first absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of seclusion, while placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[2132]="*Ayaṃ paṭhamo sukhallikānuyogo.**This is the first kind of indulgence in pleasure.*";
P_HTM[2133]="*Puna caparaṃ, cunda, bhikkhu vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā … pe … dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, as the placing of the mind and keeping it connected are stilled, a mendicant enters and remains in the second absorption. It has the rapture and bliss born of immersion, with internal clarity and confidence, and unified mind, without placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[2134]="*Ayaṃ dutiyo sukhallikānuyogo.**This is the second kind of indulgence in pleasure.*";
P_HTM[2135]="*Puna caparaṃ, cunda, bhikkhu pītiyā ca virāgā … pe … tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, with the fading away of rapture, a mendicant enters and remains in the third absorption. They meditate with equanimity, mindful and aware, personally experiencing the bliss of which the noble ones declare, ‘Equanimous and mindful, one meditates in bliss.’*";
P_HTM[2136]="*Ayaṃ tatiyo sukhallikānuyogo.**This is the third kind of indulgence in pleasure.*";
P_HTM[2137]="*Puna caparaṃ, cunda, bhikkhu sukhassa ca pahānā dukkhassa ca pahānā … pe … catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, giving up pleasure and pain, and ending former happiness and sadness, a mendicant enters and remains in the fourth absorption. It is without pleasure or pain, with pure equanimity and mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[2138]="*Ayaṃ catuttho sukhallikānuyogo.**This is the fourth kind of indulgence in pleasure.*";
P_HTM[2139]="*Ime kho, cunda, cattāro sukhallikānuyogā ekantanibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya upasamāya abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattanti.**These are the four kinds of indulgence in pleasure which, when developed and cultivated, lead solely to disillusionment, dispassion, cessation, peace, insight, awakening, and extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[2140]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, cunda, vijjati yaṃ aññatitthiyā paribbājakā evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**It’s possible that wanderers who follow other paths might say,*";
P_HTM[2141]="*‘ime cattāro sukhallikānuyoge anuyuttā samaṇā sakyaputtiyā viharantī’ti.**‘The ascetics who follow the Sakyan live indulging in pleasure in these four ways.’*";
P_HTM[2142]="*Te vo ‘evaṃ’ tissu vacanīyā.**They should be told, ‘Exactly so!’*";
P_HTM[2143]="*Sammā te vo vadamānā vadeyyuṃ, na te vo abbhācikkheyyuṃ asatā abhūtena.**It’s right to say that about you; it doesn’t misrepresent you with an untruth.*";
P_HTM[2144]="*10. Sukhallikānuyogānisaṃsa**10. The Benefits of Indulgence in Pleasure*";
P_HTM[2145]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, cunda, vijjati, yaṃ aññatitthiyā paribbājakā evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**It’s possible that wanderers who follow other paths might say,*";
P_HTM[2146]="*‘ime panāvuso, cattāro sukhallikānuyoge anuyuttānaṃ viharataṃ kati phalāni katānisaṃsā pāṭikaṅkhā’ti?**‘How many fruits and benefits may be expected by those who live indulging in pleasure in these four ways?’*";
P_HTM[2147]="*Evaṃvādino, cunda, aññatitthiyā paribbājakā evamassu vacanīyā:**You should say to them,*";
P_HTM[2148]="*‘ime kho, āvuso, cattāro sukhallikānuyoge anuyuttānaṃ viharataṃ cattāri phalāni cattāro ānisaṃsā pāṭikaṅkhā.**‘Four benefits may be expected by those who live indulging in pleasure in these four ways.*";
P_HTM[2149]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[2150]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu tiṇṇaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā sotāpanno hoti avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyaṇo.**Firstly, with the ending of three fetters a mendicant becomes a stream-enterer, not liable to be reborn in the underworld, bound for awakening.*";
P_HTM[2151]="*Idaṃ paṭhamaṃ phalaṃ, paṭhamo ānisaṃso.**This is the first fruit and benefit.*";
P_HTM[2152]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu tiṇṇaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā rāgadosamohānaṃ tanuttā sakadāgāmī hoti, sakideva imaṃ lokaṃ āgantvā dukkhassantaṃ karoti.**Furthermore, a mendicant—with the ending of three fetters, and the weakening of greed, hate, and delusion—becomes a once-returner. They come back to this world once only, then make an end of suffering.*";
P_HTM[2153]="*Idaṃ dutiyaṃ phalaṃ, dutiyo ānisaṃso.**This is the second fruit and benefit.*";
P_HTM[2154]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu pañcannaṃ orambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā opapātiko hoti, tattha parinibbāyī anāvattidhammo tasmā lokā.**Furthermore, with the ending of the five lower fetters, a mendicant is reborn spontaneously and will become extinguished there, not liable to return from that world.*";
P_HTM[2155]="*Idaṃ tatiyaṃ phalaṃ, tatiyo ānisaṃso.**This is the third fruit and benefit.*";
P_HTM[2156]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu āsavānaṃ khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, a mendicant realizes the undefiled freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom in this very life, and lives having realized it with their own insight due to the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[2157]="*Idaṃ catutthaṃ phalaṃ catuttho ānisaṃso.**This is the fourth fruit and benefit.*";
P_HTM[2158]="*Ime kho, āvuso, cattāro sukhallikānuyoge anuyuttānaṃ viharataṃ imāni cattāri phalāni, cattāro ānisaṃsā pāṭikaṅkhā’ti.**These four benefits may be expected by those who live indulging in pleasure in these four ways.’*";
P_HTM[2159]="*11. Khīṇāsavaabhabbaṭhāna**11. Things Impossible for the Perfected*";
P_HTM[2160]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, cunda, vijjati yaṃ aññatitthiyā paribbājakā evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**It’s possible that wanderers who follow other paths might say,*";
P_HTM[2161]="*‘aṭṭhitadhammā samaṇā sakyaputtiyā viharantī’ti.**‘The ascetics who follow the Sakyan are inconsistent.’*";
P_HTM[2162]="*Evaṃvādino, cunda, aññatitthiyā paribbājakā evamassu vacanīyā:**You should say to them,*";
P_HTM[2163]="*‘atthi kho, āvuso, tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena sāvakānaṃ dhammā desitā paññattā yāvajīvaṃ anatikkamanīyā.**‘Reverends, these things have been taught and pointed out for his disciples by the Blessed One, who knows and sees, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha, not to be transgressed so long as life lasts.*";
P_HTM[2164]="*Seyyathāpi, āvuso, indakhīlo vā ayokhīlo vā gambhīranemo sunikhāto acalo asampavedhī;**Suppose there was a boundary pillar or an iron pillar with deep foundations, firmly embedded, imperturbable and unshakable.*";
P_HTM[2165]="*evameva kho, āvuso, tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena sāvakānaṃ dhammā desitā paññattā yāvajīvaṃ anatikkamanīyā.**In the same way, these things have been taught and pointed out for his disciples by the Blessed One, who knows and sees, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha, not to be transgressed so long as life lasts.*";
P_HTM[2166]="*Yo so, āvuso, bhikkhu arahaṃ khīṇāsavo vusitavā katakaraṇīyo ohitabhāro anuppattasadattho parikkhīṇabhavasaṃyojano sammadaññāvimutto, abhabbo so nava ṭhānāni ajjhācarituṃ.**A mendicant who is perfected—with defilements ended, who has completed the spiritual journey, done what had to be done, laid down the burden, achieved their own true goal, utterly ended the fetters of rebirth, and is rightly freed through enlightenment—can’t transgress in nine respects.*";
P_HTM[2167]="*Abhabbo, āvuso, khīṇāsavo bhikkhu sañcicca pāṇaṃ jīvitā voropetuṃ; abhabbo khīṇāsavo bhikkhu adinnaṃ theyyasaṅkhātaṃ ādiyituṃ; abhabbo khīṇāsavo bhikkhu methunaṃ dhammaṃ paṭisevituṃ; abhabbo khīṇāsavo bhikkhu sampajānamusā bhāsituṃ; abhabbo khīṇāsavo bhikkhu sannidhikārakaṃ kāme paribhuñjituṃ, seyyathāpi pubbe āgārikabhūto; abhabbo khīṇāsavo bhikkhu chandāgatiṃ gantuṃ; abhabbo khīṇāsavo bhikkhu dosāgatiṃ gantuṃ; abhabbo khīṇāsavo bhikkhu mohāgatiṃ gantuṃ; abhabbo khīṇāsavo bhikkhu bhayāgatiṃ gantuṃ.**A mendicant with defilements ended can’t deliberately take the life of a living creature, take something with the intention to steal, have sex, tell a deliberate lie, or store up goods for their own enjoyment like they did as a lay person. And they can’t make decisions prejudiced by favoritism, hostility, stupidity, or cowardice.*";
P_HTM[2168]="*Yo so, āvuso, bhikkhu arahaṃ khīṇāsavo vusitavā katakaraṇīyo ohitabhāro anuppattasadattho parikkhīṇabhavasaṃyojano sammadaññāvimutto, abhabbo so imāni nava ṭhānāni ajjhācaritun’ti.**A mendicant who is perfected can’t transgress in these nine respects.’*";
P_HTM[2169]="*12. Pañhābyākaraṇa**12. Questions and Answers*";
P_HTM[2170]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, cunda, vijjati, yaṃ aññatitthiyā paribbājakā evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**It’s possible that wanderers who follow other paths might say,*";
P_HTM[2171]="*‘atītaṃ kho addhānaṃ ārabbha samaṇo gotamo atīrakaṃ ñāṇadassanaṃ paññapeti, no ca kho anāgataṃ addhānaṃ ārabbha atīrakaṃ ñāṇadassanaṃ paññapeti, tayidaṃ kiṃsu tayidaṃ kathaṃsū’ti?**‘The ascetic Gotama demonstrates boundless knowledge and vision of the past, but not of the future. What’s up with that?’*";
P_HTM[2172]="*Te ca aññatitthiyā paribbājakā aññavihitakena ñāṇadassanena aññavihitakaṃ ñāṇadassanaṃ paññapetabbaṃ maññanti yathariva bālā abyattā.**Those wanderers, like incompetent fools, seem to imagine that one kind of knowledge and vision can be demonstrated by means of another kind of knowledge and vision.*";
P_HTM[2173]="*Atītaṃ kho, cunda, addhānaṃ ārabbha tathāgatassa satānusāriñāṇaṃ hoti;**Regarding the past, the Realized One has knowledge stemming from memory.*";
P_HTM[2174]="*so yāvatakaṃ ākaṅkhati tāvatakaṃ anussarati.**He recollects as far as he wants.*";
P_HTM[2175]="*Anāgatañca kho addhānaṃ ārabbha tathāgatassa bodhijaṃ ñāṇaṃ uppajjati:**Regarding the future, the Realized One has the knowledge born of awakening:*";
P_HTM[2176]="*‘ayamantimā jāti, natthi dāni punabbhavo’ti.**‘This is my last rebirth. Now there are no more future lives.’*";
P_HTM[2177]="*Atītañcepi, cunda, hoti abhūtaṃ atacchaṃ anatthasaṃhitaṃ, na taṃ tathāgato byākaroti.**If a question about the past is untrue, false, and pointless, the Realized One does not reply.*";
P_HTM[2178]="*Atītañcepi, cunda, hoti bhūtaṃ tacchaṃ anatthasaṃhitaṃ, tampi tathāgato na byākaroti.**If a question about the past is true and substantive, but pointless, he does not reply.*";
P_HTM[2179]="*Atītañcepi, cunda, hoti bhūtaṃ tacchaṃ atthasaṃhitaṃ, tatra kālaññū tathāgato hoti tassa pañhassa veyyākaraṇāya.**If a question about the past is true, substantive, and beneficial, he knows the right time to reply.*";
P_HTM[2180]="*Anāgatañcepi, cunda, hoti abhūtaṃ atacchaṃ anatthasaṃhitaṃ, na taṃ tathāgato byākaroti … pe … tassa pañhassa veyyākaraṇāya.**And the Realized One replies to questions about the future or the present in the same way.*";
P_HTM[2181]="*Paccuppannañcepi, cunda, hoti abhūtaṃ atacchaṃ anatthasaṃhitaṃ, na taṃ tathāgato byākaroti.* **";
P_HTM[2182]="*Paccuppannañcepi, cunda, hoti bhūtaṃ tacchaṃ anatthasaṃhitaṃ, tampi tathāgato na byākaroti.* **";
P_HTM[2183]="*Paccuppannañcepi, cunda, hoti bhūtaṃ tacchaṃ atthasaṃhitaṃ, tatra kālaññū tathāgato hoti tassa pañhassa veyyākaraṇāya.* **";
P_HTM[2184]="*Iti kho, cunda, atītānāgatapaccuppannesu dhammesu tathāgato kālavādī bhūtavādī atthavādī dhammavādī vinayavādī, tasmā ‘tathāgato’ti vuccati.**And so the Realized One has speech that’s well-timed, true, meaningful, in line with the teaching and training. That’s why he’s called the ‘Realized One’.*";
P_HTM[2185]="*Yañca kho, cunda, sadevakassa lokassa samārakassa sabrahmakassa sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiyā pajāya sadevamanussāya diṭṭhaṃ sutaṃ mutaṃ viññātaṃ pattaṃ pariyesitaṃ anuvicaritaṃ manasā, sabbaṃ tathāgatena abhisambuddhaṃ,**In this world—with its gods, Māras, and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, its gods and humans—whatever is seen, heard, thought, known, sought, and explored by the mind, all that has been understood by the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[2186]="*tasmā ‘tathāgato’ti vuccati.**That’s why he’s called the ‘Realized One’.*";
P_HTM[2187]="*Yañca, cunda, rattiṃ tathāgato anuttaraṃ sammāsambodhiṃ abhisambujjhati, yañca rattiṃ anupādisesāya nibbānadhātuyā parinibbāyati, yaṃ etasmiṃ antare bhāsati lapati niddisati. Sabbaṃ taṃ tatheva hoti no aññathā,**From the night when the Realized One understands the supreme perfect awakening until the night he becomes fully extinguished—through the natural principle of extinguishment, without anything left over—everything he speaks, says, and expresses is real, not otherwise.*";
P_HTM[2188]="*tasmā ‘tathāgato’ti vuccati.**That’s why he’s called the ‘Realized One’.*";
P_HTM[2189]="*Yathāvādī, cunda, tathāgato tathākārī, yathākārī tathāvādī.**The Realized One does as he says, and says as he does.*";
P_HTM[2190]="*Iti yathāvādī tathākārī, yathākārī tathāvādī, tasmā ‘tathāgato’ti vuccati.**Since this is so, that’s why he’s called the ‘Realized One’.*";
P_HTM[2191]="*Sadevake loke, cunda, samārake sabrahmake sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiyā pajāya sadevamanussāya tathāgato abhibhū anabhibhūto aññadatthudaso vasavattī, tasmā ‘tathāgato’ti vuccati.**In this world—with its gods, Māras and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, gods and humans—the Realized One is the undefeated, the champion, the universal seer, the wielder of power.*";
P_HTM[2192]="*13. Abyākataṭṭhāna**13. The Undeclared Points*";
P_HTM[2193]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, cunda, vijjati yaṃ aññatitthiyā paribbājakā evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**It’s possible that wanderers who follow other paths might say,*";
P_HTM[2194]="*‘kiṃ nu kho, āvuso, hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti?**‘Is this your view: “A Realized One exists after death. This is the only truth, other ideas are silly”?’*";
P_HTM[2195]="*Evaṃvādino, cunda, aññatitthiyā paribbājakā evamassu vacanīyā:**You should say to them,*";
P_HTM[2196]="*‘abyākataṃ kho etaṃ, āvuso, bhagavatā:**‘Reverend, this has not been declared by the Buddha.’*";
P_HTM[2197]="*“hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan”’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2198]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, cunda, vijjati, yaṃ aññatitthiyā paribbājakā evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**The wanderers might say,*";
P_HTM[2199]="*‘kiṃ panāvuso, na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti?**‘Then is this your view: “A Realized One doesn’t exist after death. This is the only truth, other ideas are silly”?’*";
P_HTM[2200]="*Evaṃvādino, cunda, aññatitthiyā paribbājakā evamassu vacanīyā:**You should say to them,*";
P_HTM[2201]="*‘etampi kho, āvuso, bhagavatā abyākataṃ:**‘This too has not been declared by the Buddha.’*";
P_HTM[2202]="*“na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan”’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2203]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, cunda, vijjati, yaṃ aññatitthiyā paribbājakā evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**The wanderers might say,*";
P_HTM[2204]="*‘kiṃ panāvuso, hoti ca na ca hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti?**‘Then is this your view: “A Realized One both exists and doesn’t exist after death. This is the only truth, other ideas are silly”?’*";
P_HTM[2205]="*Evaṃvādino, cunda, aññatitthiyā paribbājakā evamassu vacanīyā:**You should say to them,*";
P_HTM[2206]="*‘abyākataṃ kho etaṃ, āvuso, bhagavatā:**‘This too has not been declared by the Buddha.’*";
P_HTM[2207]="*“hoti ca na ca hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan”’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2208]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, cunda, vijjati, yaṃ aññatitthiyā paribbājakā evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**The wanderers might say,*";
P_HTM[2209]="*‘kiṃ panāvuso, neva hoti na na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti?**‘Then is this your view: “A Realized One neither exists nor doesn’t exist after death. This is the only truth, other ideas are silly”?’*";
P_HTM[2210]="*Evaṃvādino, cunda, aññatitthiyā paribbājakā evamassu vacanīyā:**You should say to them,*";
P_HTM[2211]="*‘etampi kho, āvuso, bhagavatā abyākataṃ:**‘This too has not been declared by the Buddha.’*";
P_HTM[2212]="*“neva hoti na na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan”’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2213]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, cunda, vijjati, yaṃ aññatitthiyā paribbājakā evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**The wanderers might say,*";
P_HTM[2214]="*‘kasmā panetaṃ, āvuso, samaṇena gotamena abyākatan’ti?**‘But why has this not been declared by the ascetic Gotama?’*";
P_HTM[2215]="*Evaṃvādino, cunda, aññatitthiyā paribbājakā evamassu vacanīyā:**You should say to them,*";
P_HTM[2216]="*‘na hetaṃ, āvuso, atthasaṃhitaṃ na dhammasaṃhitaṃ na ādibrahmacariyakaṃ na nibbidāya na virāgāya na nirodhāya na upasamāya na abhiññāya na sambodhāya na nibbānāya saṃvattati, tasmā taṃ bhagavatā abyākatan’ti.**‘Because it’s not beneficial or relevant to the fundamentals of the spiritual life. It doesn’t lead to disillusionment, dispassion, cessation, peace, insight, awakening, and extinguishment. That’s why it hasn’t been declared by the Buddha.’*";
P_HTM[2217]="*14. Byākataṭṭhāna**14. The Declared Points*";
P_HTM[2218]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, cunda, vijjati, yaṃ aññatitthiyā paribbājakā evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**It’s possible that wanderers who follow other paths might say,*";
P_HTM[2219]="*‘kiṃ panāvuso, samaṇena gotamena byākatan’ti?**‘But what has been declared by the ascetic Gotama?’*";
P_HTM[2220]="*Evaṃvādino, cunda, aññatitthiyā paribbājakā evamassu vacanīyā:**You should say to them,*";
P_HTM[2221]="*‘idaṃ dukkhanti kho, āvuso, bhagavatā byākataṃ, ayaṃ dukkhasamudayoti kho, āvuso, bhagavatā byākataṃ, ayaṃ dukkhanirodhoti kho, āvuso, bhagavatā byākataṃ, ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadāti kho, āvuso, bhagavatā byākatan’ti.**‘What has been declared by the Buddha is this: “This is suffering”—“This is the origin of suffering”—“This is the cessation of suffering”—“This is the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.”’*";
P_HTM[2222]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, cunda, vijjati, yaṃ aññatitthiyā paribbājakā evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**The wanderers might say,*";
P_HTM[2223]="*‘kasmā panetaṃ, āvuso, samaṇena gotamena byākatan’ti?**‘But why has this been declared by the ascetic Gotama?’*";
P_HTM[2224]="*Evaṃvādino, cunda, aññatitthiyā paribbājakā evamassu vacanīyā:**You should say to them,*";
P_HTM[2225]="*‘etañhi, āvuso, atthasaṃhitaṃ, etaṃ dhammasaṃhitaṃ, etaṃ ādibrahmacariyakaṃ ekantanibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya upasamāya abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattati. Tasmā taṃ bhagavatā byākatan’ti.**‘Because it’s beneficial and relevant to the fundamentals of the spiritual life. It leads to disillusionment, dispassion, cessation, peace, insight, awakening, and extinguishment. That’s why it has been declared by the Buddha.’*";
P_HTM[2226]="*15. Pubbantasahagatadiṭṭhinissaya**15. Views of the Past*";
P_HTM[2227]="*Yepi te, cunda, pubbantasahagatā diṭṭhinissayā, tepi vo mayā byākatā, yathā te byākātabbā.**Cunda, I have explained to you as they should be explained the views that some rely on regarding the past.*";
P_HTM[2228]="*Yathā ca te na byākātabbā, kiṃ vo ahaṃ te tathā byākarissāmi?**Shall I explain them to you in the wrong way?*";
P_HTM[2229]="*Yepi te, cunda, aparantasahagatā diṭṭhinissayā, tepi vo mayā byākatā, yathā te byākātabbā.**I have explained to you as they should be explained the views that some rely on regarding the future.*";
P_HTM[2230]="*Yathā ca te na byākātabbā, kiṃ vo ahaṃ te tathā byākarissāmi?**Shall I explain them to you in the wrong way?*";
P_HTM[2231]="*Katame ca te, cunda, pubbantasahagatā diṭṭhinissayā, ye vo mayā byākatā, yathā te byākātabbā.**What are the views that some rely on regarding the past?*";
P_HTM[2232]="*Yathā ca te na byākātabbā, kiṃ vo ahaṃ te tathā byākarissāmi?* **";
P_HTM[2233]="*Santi kho, cunda, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā evaṃvādino evaṃdiṭṭhino:**There are some ascetics and brahmins who have this doctrine and view:*";
P_HTM[2234]="*‘sassato attā ca loko ca, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti.**‘The self and the cosmos are eternal. This is the only truth, other ideas are silly.’*";
P_HTM[2235]="*Santi pana, cunda, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā evaṃvādino evaṃdiṭṭhino:**There are some ascetics and brahmins who have this doctrine and view:*";
P_HTM[2236]="*‘asassato attā ca loko ca … pe …**‘The self and the cosmos are not eternal,*";
P_HTM[2237]="*sassato ca asassato ca attā ca loko ca …**or both eternal and not eternal,*";
P_HTM[2238]="*neva sassato nāsassato attā ca loko ca …**or neither eternal nor not eternal.*";
P_HTM[2239]="*sayaṃkato attā ca loko ca …**The self and the cosmos are made by oneself,*";
P_HTM[2240]="*paraṃkato attā ca loko ca …**or made by another,*";
P_HTM[2241]="*sayaṃkato ca paraṃkato ca attā ca loko ca …**or made by both oneself and another,*";
P_HTM[2242]="*asayaṅkāro aparaṅkāro adhiccasamuppanno attā ca loko ca, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti.**or they have arisen by chance, not made by oneself or another.*";
P_HTM[2243]="*‘Sassataṃ sukhadukkhaṃ …**Pleasure and pain are eternal,*";
P_HTM[2244]="*asassataṃ sukhadukkhaṃ …**or not eternal,*";
P_HTM[2245]="*sassatañca asassatañca sukhadukkhaṃ …**or both eternal and not eternal,*";
P_HTM[2246]="*nevasassataṃ nāsassataṃ sukhadukkhaṃ …**or neither eternal nor not eternal.*";
P_HTM[2247]="*sayaṃkataṃ sukhadukkhaṃ …**Pleasure and pain are made by oneself,*";
P_HTM[2248]="*paraṃkataṃ sukhadukkhaṃ …**or made by another,*";
P_HTM[2249]="*sayaṃkatañca paraṃkatañca sukhadukkhaṃ …**or made by both oneself and another,*";
P_HTM[2250]="*asayaṃkāraṃ aparaṅkāraṃ adhiccasamuppannaṃ sukhadukkhaṃ, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti.**or they have arisen by chance, not made by oneself or another. This is the only truth, other ideas are silly.’*";
P_HTM[2251]="*Tatra, cunda, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā evaṃvādino evaṃdiṭṭhino:**Regarding this, I go up to the ascetics and brahmins whose view is that*";
P_HTM[2252]="*‘sassato attā ca loko ca, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti.**the self and the cosmos are eternal,*";
P_HTM[2253]="*Tyāhaṃ upasaṅkamitvā evaṃ vadāmi:**and say,*";
P_HTM[2254]="*‘atthi nu kho idaṃ, āvuso, vuccati:**‘Reverends, is this what you say,*";
P_HTM[2255]="*“sassato attā ca loko cā”’ti?**“The self and the cosmos are eternal”?’*";
P_HTM[2256]="*Yañca kho te evamāhaṃsu:**But when they say, ‘Yes!*";
P_HTM[2257]="*‘idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti.**This is the only truth, other ideas are silly,’*";
P_HTM[2258]="*Taṃ tesaṃ nānujānāmi.**I don’t acknowledge that.*";
P_HTM[2259]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[2260]="*Aññathāsaññinopi hettha, cunda, santeke sattā.**Because there are beings who have different opinions on this topic.*";
P_HTM[2261]="*Imāyapi kho ahaṃ, cunda, paññattiyā neva attanā samasamaṃ samanupassāmi kuto bhiyyo.**I don’t see any such expositions that are equal to my own, still less superior.*";
P_HTM[2262]="*Atha kho ahameva tattha bhiyyo yadidaṃ adhipaññatti.**Rather, I am the one who is superior when it comes to the higher exposition.*";
P_HTM[2263]="*Tatra, cunda, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā evaṃvādino evaṃdiṭṭhino:**Regarding this, I go up to the ascetics and brahmins who assert all the other views as described above.*";
P_HTM[2264]="*‘asassato attā ca loko ca …* **";
P_HTM[2265]="*sassato ca asassato ca attā ca loko ca …* **";
P_HTM[2266]="*nevasassato nāsassato attā ca loko ca …* **";
P_HTM[2267]="*sayaṃkato attā ca loko ca …* **";
P_HTM[2268]="*paraṃkato attā ca loko ca …* **";
P_HTM[2269]="*sayaṃkato ca paraṃkato ca attā ca loko ca …* **";
P_HTM[2270]="*asayaṅkāro aparaṅkāro adhiccasamuppanno attā ca loko ca …* **";
P_HTM[2271]="*sassataṃ sukhadukkhaṃ …* **";
P_HTM[2272]="*asassataṃ sukhadukkhaṃ …* **";
P_HTM[2273]="*sassatañca asassatañca sukhadukkhaṃ …* **";
P_HTM[2274]="*nevasassataṃ nāsassataṃ sukhadukkhaṃ …* **";
P_HTM[2275]="*sayaṃkataṃ sukhadukkhaṃ …* **";
P_HTM[2276]="*paraṃkataṃ sukhadukkhaṃ …* **";
P_HTM[2277]="*sayaṃkatañca paraṃkatañca sukhadukkhaṃ …* **";
P_HTM[2278]="*asayaṃkāraṃ aparaṅkāraṃ adhiccasamuppannaṃ sukhadukkhaṃ, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2279]="*Tyāhaṃ upasaṅkamitvā evaṃ vadāmi:* **";
P_HTM[2280]="*‘atthi nu kho idaṃ, āvuso, vuccati:* **";
P_HTM[2281]="*“asayaṃkāraṃ aparaṅkāraṃ adhiccasamuppannaṃ sukhadukkhan”’ti?* **";
P_HTM[2282]="*Yañca kho te evamāhaṃsu:* **";
P_HTM[2283]="*‘idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2284]="*Taṃ tesaṃ nānujānāmi.**And in each case, I don’t acknowledge that.*";
P_HTM[2285]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[2286]="*Aññathāsaññinopi hettha, cunda, santeke sattā.**Because there are beings who have different opinions on this topic.*";
P_HTM[2287]="*Imāyapi kho ahaṃ, cunda, paññattiyā neva attanā samasamaṃ samanupassāmi kuto bhiyyo.**I don’t see any such expositions that are equal to my own, still less superior.*";
P_HTM[2288]="*Atha kho ahameva tattha bhiyyo yadidaṃ adhipaññatti.**Rather, I am the one who is superior when it comes to the higher exposition.*";
P_HTM[2289]="*Ime kho te, cunda, pubbantasahagatā diṭṭhinissayā, ye vo mayā byākatā, yathā te byākātabbā.**These are the views that some rely on regarding the past.*";
P_HTM[2290]="*Yathā ca te na byākātabbā, kiṃ vo ahaṃ te tathā byākarissāmi?* **";
P_HTM[2291]="*16. Aparantasahagatadiṭṭhinissaya**16. Views of the Future*";
P_HTM[2292]="*Katame ca te, cunda, aparantasahagatā diṭṭhinissayā, ye vo mayā byākatā, yathā te byākātabbā.**What are the views that some rely on regarding the future?*";
P_HTM[2293]="*Yathā ca te na byākātabbā, kiṃ vo ahaṃ te tathā byākarissāmi?* **";
P_HTM[2294]="*Santi, cunda, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā evaṃvādino evaṃdiṭṭhino:**There are some ascetics and brahmins who have this doctrine and view:*";
P_HTM[2295]="*‘rūpī attā hoti arogo paraṃ maraṇā, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti.**‘The self is physical and sound after death,*";
P_HTM[2296]="*Santi pana, cunda, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā evaṃvādino evaṃdiṭṭhino:* **";
P_HTM[2297]="*‘arūpī attā hoti …**or it is non-physical,*";
P_HTM[2298]="*rūpī ca arūpī ca attā hoti …**or both physical and non-physical,*";
P_HTM[2299]="*nevarūpī nārūpī attā hoti …**or neither physical nor non-physical,*";
P_HTM[2300]="*saññī attā hoti …**or percipient,*";
P_HTM[2301]="*asaññī attā hoti …**or non-percipient,*";
P_HTM[2302]="*nevasaññīnāsaññī attā hoti …**or neither percipient nor non-percipient,*";
P_HTM[2303]="*attā ucchijjati vinassati na hoti paraṃ maraṇā, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti.**or the self is annihilated and destroyed when the body breaks up, and doesn’t exist after death. This is the only truth, other ideas are silly.’*";
P_HTM[2304]="*Tatra, cunda, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā evaṃvādino evaṃdiṭṭhino:**Regarding this, I go up to the ascetics and brahmins whose view is that*";
P_HTM[2305]="*‘rūpī attā hoti arogo paraṃ maraṇā, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti.**the self is physical and sound after death,*";
P_HTM[2306]="*Tyāhaṃ upasaṅkamitvā evaṃ vadāmi:**and say,*";
P_HTM[2307]="*‘atthi nu kho idaṃ, āvuso, vuccati:**‘Reverends, is this what you say,*";
P_HTM[2308]="*“rūpī attā hoti arogo paraṃ maraṇā”’ti?**“The self is physical and sound after death”?’*";
P_HTM[2309]="*Yañca kho te evamāhaṃsu:**But when they say, ‘Yes!*";
P_HTM[2310]="*‘idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti.**This is the only truth, other ideas are silly,’*";
P_HTM[2311]="*Taṃ tesaṃ nānujānāmi.**I don’t acknowledge that.*";
P_HTM[2312]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[2313]="*Aññathāsaññinopi hettha, cunda, santeke sattā.**Because there are beings who have different opinions on this topic.*";
P_HTM[2314]="*Imāyapi kho ahaṃ, cunda, paññattiyā neva attanā samasamaṃ samanupassāmi kuto bhiyyo.**I don’t see any such expositions that are equal to my own, still less superior.*";
P_HTM[2315]="*Atha kho ahameva tattha bhiyyo yadidaṃ adhipaññatti.**Rather, I am the one who is superior when it comes to the higher exposition.*";
P_HTM[2316]="*Tatra, cunda, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā evaṃvādino evaṃdiṭṭhino:**Regarding this, I go up to the ascetics and brahmins who assert all the other views as described above.*";
P_HTM[2317]="*‘arūpī attā hoti …* **";
P_HTM[2318]="*rūpī ca arūpī ca attā hoti …* **";
P_HTM[2319]="*nevarūpīnārūpī attā hoti …* **";
P_HTM[2320]="*saññī attā hoti …* **";
P_HTM[2321]="*asaññī attā hoti …* **";
P_HTM[2322]="*nevasaññīnāsaññī attā hoti …* **";
P_HTM[2323]="*attā ucchijjati vinassati na hoti paraṃ maraṇā, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2324]="*Tyāhaṃ upasaṅkamitvā evaṃ vadāmi:* **";
P_HTM[2325]="*‘atthi nu kho idaṃ, āvuso, vuccati:* **";
P_HTM[2326]="*“attā ucchijjati vinassati na hoti paraṃ maraṇā”’ti?* **";
P_HTM[2327]="*Yañca kho te, cunda, evamāhaṃsu:* **";
P_HTM[2328]="*‘idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2329]="*Taṃ tesaṃ nānujānāmi.**And in each case, I don’t acknowledge that.*";
P_HTM[2330]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[2331]="*Aññathāsaññinopi hettha, cunda, santeke sattā.**Because there are beings who have different opinions on this topic.*";
P_HTM[2332]="*Imāyapi kho ahaṃ, cunda, paññattiyā neva attanā samasamaṃ samanupassāmi, kuto bhiyyo.**I don’t see any such expositions that are equal to my own, still less superior.*";
P_HTM[2333]="*Atha kho ahameva tattha bhiyyo yadidaṃ adhipaññatti.**Rather, I am the one who is superior when it comes to the higher exposition.*";
P_HTM[2334]="*Ime kho te, cunda, aparantasahagatā diṭṭhinissayā, ye vo mayā byākatā, yathā te byākātabbā.**These are the views that some rely on regarding the future, which I have explained to you as they should be explained.*";
P_HTM[2335]="*Yathā ca te na byākātabbā, kiṃ vo ahaṃ te tathā byākarissāmi?**Shall I explain them to you in the wrong way?*";
P_HTM[2336]="*Imesañca, cunda, pubbantasahagatānaṃ diṭṭhinissayānaṃ imesañca aparantasahagatānaṃ diṭṭhinissayānaṃ pahānāya samatikkamāya evaṃ mayā cattāro satipaṭṭhānā desitā paññattā.**I have taught and pointed out the four kinds of mindfulness meditation for giving up and going beyond all these views of the past and the future.*";
P_HTM[2337]="*Katame cattāro?**What four?*";
P_HTM[2338]="*Idha, cunda, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[2339]="*Vedanāsu vedanānupassī … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[2340]="*citte cittānupassī … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[2341]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[2342]="*Imesañca, cunda, pubbantasahagatānaṃ diṭṭhinissayānaṃ imesañca aparantasahagatānaṃ diṭṭhinissayānaṃ pahānāya samatikkamāya. Evaṃ mayā ime cattāro satipaṭṭhānā desitā paññattā”ti.**These are the four kinds of mindfulness meditation that I have taught for giving up and going beyond all these views of the past and the future.”*";
P_HTM[2343]="*Tena kho pana samayena āyasmā upavāṇo bhagavato piṭṭhito ṭhito hoti bhagavantaṃ bījayamāno.**Now at that time Venerable Upavāṇa was standing behind the Buddha fanning him.*";
P_HTM[2344]="*Atha kho āyasmā upavāṇo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**He said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[2345]="*“acchariyaṃ, bhante, abbhutaṃ, bhante.**“It’s incredible, sir, it’s amazing!*";
P_HTM[2346]="*Pāsādiko vatāyaṃ, bhante, dhammapariyāyo;**This exposition of the teaching is impressive, sir,*";
P_HTM[2347]="*supāsādiko vatāyaṃ, bhante, dhammapariyāyo, ko nāmāyaṃ, bhante, dhammapariyāyo”ti?**it is very impressive. Sir, what is the name of this exposition of the teaching?”*";
P_HTM[2348]="*“Tasmātiha tvaṃ, upavāṇa, imaṃ dhammapariyāyaṃ ‘pāsādiko’ tveva naṃ dhārehī”ti.**“Well, Upavāṇa, you may remember this exposition of the teaching as ‘The Impressive Discourse’.”*";
P_HTM[2349]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2350]="*Attamano āyasmā upavāṇo bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandīti.**Satisfied, Venerable Upavāṇa was happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2351]="*Pāsādikasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2352]="*30. Lakkhaṇasutta  - The Marks of a Great Man * **";
P_HTM[2353]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[2354]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[2355]="*Tatra kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**There the Buddha addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[2356]="*“bhikkhavo”ti.**“Mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[2357]="*“Bhaddante”ti te bhikkhū bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Venerable sir,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[2358]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[2359]="*“Dvattiṃsimāni, bhikkhave, mahāpurisassa mahāpurisalakkhaṇāni, yehi samannāgatassa mahāpurisassa dveva gatiyo bhavanti anaññā.**“There are thirty-two marks of a great man. A great man who possesses these has only two possible destinies, no other.*";
P_HTM[2360]="*Sace agāraṃ ajjhāvasati, rājā hoti cakkavattī dhammiko dhammarājā cāturanto vijitāvī janapadatthāvariyappatto sattaratanasamannāgato.**If he stays at home he becomes a king, a wheel-turning monarch, a just and principled king. His dominion extends to all four sides, he achieves stability in the country, and he possesses the seven treasures.*";
P_HTM[2361]="*Tassimāni satta ratanāni bhavanti;**He has the following seven treasures:*";
P_HTM[2362]="*Seyyathidaṃ—cakkaratanaṃ hatthiratanaṃ assaratanaṃ maṇiratanaṃ itthiratanaṃ gahapatiratanaṃ pariṇāyakaratanameva sattamaṃ.**the wheel, the elephant, the horse, the jewel, the woman, the treasurer, and the counselor as the seventh treasure.*";
P_HTM[2363]="*Parosahassaṃ kho panassa puttā bhavanti sūrā vīraṅgarūpā parasenappamaddanā.**He has over a thousand sons who are valiant and heroic, crushing the armies of his enemies.*";
P_HTM[2364]="*So imaṃ pathaviṃ sāgarapariyantaṃ adaṇḍena asatthena dhammena abhivijiya ajjhāvasati.**After conquering this land girt by sea, he reigns by principle, without rod or sword.*";
P_HTM[2365]="*Sace kho pana agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajati, arahaṃ hoti sammāsambuddho loke vivaṭṭacchado.**But if he goes forth from the lay life to homelessness, he becomes a perfected one, a fully awakened Buddha, who draws back the veil from the world.*";
P_HTM[2366]="*Katamāni ca tāni, bhikkhave, dvattiṃsa mahāpurisassa mahāpurisalakkhaṇāni, yehi samannāgatassa mahāpurisassa dveva gatiyo bhavanti anaññā?**And what are the thirty-two marks?*";
P_HTM[2367]="*Sace agāraṃ ajjhāvasati, rājā hoti cakkavattī … pe …* **";
P_HTM[2368]="*sace kho pana agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajati, arahaṃ hoti sammāsambuddho loke vivaṭṭacchado.* **";
P_HTM[2369]="*Idha, bhikkhave, mahāpuriso suppatiṭṭhitapādo hoti. Yampi, bhikkhave, mahāpuriso suppatiṭṭhitapādo hoti, idampi, bhikkhave, mahāpurisassa mahāpurisalakkhaṇaṃ bhavati.**He has well-planted feet.*";
P_HTM[2370]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, mahāpurisassa heṭṭhāpādatalesu cakkāni jātāni honti sahassārāni sanemikāni sanābhikāni sabbākāraparipūrāni. Yampi, bhikkhave, mahāpurisassa heṭṭhāpādatalesu cakkāni jātāni honti sahassārāni sanemikāni sanābhikāni sabbākāraparipūrāni, idampi, bhikkhave, mahāpurisassa mahāpurisalakkhaṇaṃ bhavati.**On the soles of his feet there are thousand-spoked wheels, with rims and hubs, complete in every detail.*";
P_HTM[2371]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, mahāpuriso āyatapaṇhi hoti … pe …**He has projecting heels.*";
P_HTM[2372]="*dīghaṅguli hoti …**He has long fingers.*";
P_HTM[2373]="*mudutalunahatthapādo hoti …**His hands and feet are tender.*";
P_HTM[2374]="*jālahatthapādo hoti …**His hands and feet cling gracefully.*";
P_HTM[2375]="*ussaṅkhapādo hoti …**His feet are arched.*";
P_HTM[2376]="*eṇijaṅgho hoti …**His calves are like those of an antelope.*";
P_HTM[2377]="*ṭhitakova anonamanto ubhohi pāṇitalehi jaṇṇukāni parimasati parimajjati …**When standing upright and not bending over, the palms of both hands touch the knees.*";
P_HTM[2378]="*kosohitavatthaguyho hoti …**His private parts are retracted.*";
P_HTM[2379]="*suvaṇṇavaṇṇo hoti kañcanasannibhattaco …**He is gold colored; his skin has a golden sheen.*";
P_HTM[2380]="*sukhumacchavi hoti, sukhumattā chaviyā rajojallaṃ kāye na upalimpati …**He has delicate skin, so delicate that dust and dirt don’t stick to his body.*";
P_HTM[2381]="*ekekalomo hoti, ekekāni lomāni lomakūpesu jātāni …**His hairs grow one per pore.*";
P_HTM[2382]="*uddhaggalomo hoti, uddhaggāni lomāni jātāni nīlāni añjanavaṇṇāni kuṇḍalāvaṭṭāni dakkhiṇāvaṭṭakajātāni …**His hairs stand up; they’re blue-black and curl clockwise.*";
P_HTM[2383]="*brahmujugatto hoti …**His body is as straight as Brahmā’s.*";
P_HTM[2384]="*sattussado hoti …**He has bulging muscles in seven places.*";
P_HTM[2385]="*sīhapubbaddhakāyo hoti …**His chest is like that of a lion.*";
P_HTM[2386]="*citantaraṃso hoti …**The gap between the shoulder-blades is filled in.*";
P_HTM[2387]="*nigrodhaparimaṇḍalo hoti, yāvatakvassa kāyo tāvatakvassa byāmo yāvatakvassa byāmo tāvatakvassa kāyo …**He has the proportional circumference of a banyan tree: the span of his arms equals the height of his body.*";
P_HTM[2388]="*samavaṭṭakkhandho hoti …**His torso is cylindrical.*";
P_HTM[2389]="*rasaggasaggī hoti …**He has an excellent sense of taste.*";
P_HTM[2390]="*sīhahanu hoti …**His jaw is like that of a lion.*";
P_HTM[2391]="*cattālīsadanto hoti …**He has forty teeth.*";
P_HTM[2392]="*samadanto hoti …**His teeth are even.*";
P_HTM[2393]="*aviraḷadanto hoti …**His teeth have no gaps.*";
P_HTM[2394]="*susukkadāṭho hoti …**His teeth are perfectly white.*";
P_HTM[2395]="*pahūtajivho hoti …**He has a large tongue.*";
P_HTM[2396]="*brahmassaro hoti karavīkabhāṇī …**He has the voice of Brahmā, like a cuckoo’s call.*";
P_HTM[2397]="*abhinīlanetto hoti …**His eyes are deep blue.*";
P_HTM[2398]="*gopakhumo hoti …**He has eyelashes like a cow’s.*";
P_HTM[2399]="*uṇṇā bhamukantare jātā hoti, odātā mudutūlasannibhā. Yampi, bhikkhave, mahāpurisassa uṇṇā bhamukantare jātā hoti, odātā mudutūlasannibhā, idampi, bhikkhave, mahāpurisassa mahāpurisalakkhaṇaṃ bhavati.**Between his eyebrows there grows a tuft, soft and white like cotton-wool.*";
P_HTM[2400]="*Puna caparaṃ, bhikkhave, mahāpuriso uṇhīsasīso hoti. Yampi, bhikkhave, mahāpuriso uṇhīsasīso hoti, idampi, bhikkhave, mahāpurisassa mahāpurisalakkhaṇaṃ bhavati.**His head is shaped like a turban.*";
P_HTM[2401]="*Imāni kho tāni, bhikkhave, dvattiṃsa mahāpurisassa mahāpurisalakkhaṇāni, yehi samannāgatassa mahāpurisassa dveva gatiyo bhavanti anaññā.**These are the thirty-two marks of a great man. A great man who possesses these has only two possible destinies, no other.*";
P_HTM[2402]="*Sace agāraṃ ajjhāvasati, rājā hoti cakkavattī … pe …* **";
P_HTM[2403]="*sace kho pana agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajati, arahaṃ hoti sammāsambuddho loke vivaṭṭacchado.* **";
P_HTM[2404]="*Imāni kho, bhikkhave, dvattiṃsa mahāpurisassa mahāpurisalakkhaṇāni bāhirakāpi isayo dhārenti, no ca kho te jānanti:**Seers outside of Buddhism remember these marks, but they do not know*";
P_HTM[2405]="*‘imassa kammassa kaṭattā idaṃ lakkhaṇaṃ paṭilabhatī’ti.**the specific deeds performed in the past to obtain each mark.*";
P_HTM[2406]="*1. Suppatiṭṭhitapādatālakkhaṇaṃ**1. Well-Planted Feet*";
P_HTM[2407]="*Yampi, bhikkhave, tathāgato purimaṃ jātiṃ purimaṃ bhavaṃ purimaṃ niketaṃ pubbe manussabhūto samāno daḷhasamādāno ahosi kusalesu dhammesu, avatthitasamādāno kāyasucarite vacīsucarite manosucarite dānasaṃvibhāge sīlasamādāne uposathupavāse matteyyatāya petteyyatāya sāmaññatāya brahmaññatāya kule jeṭṭhāpacāyitāya aññataraññataresu ca adhikusalesu dhammesu.**In some past lives, past existences, past abodes the Realized One was reborn as a human being. He firmly undertook and persisted in skillful behaviors such as good conduct by way of body, speech, giving and sharing, taking precepts, observing the sabbath, paying due respect to mother and father, ascetics and brahmins, honoring the elders in the family, and various other things pertaining to skillful behaviors.*";
P_HTM[2408]="*So tassa kammassa kaṭattā upacitattā ussannattā vipulattā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati.**Due to performing, accumulating, heaping up, and amassing those deeds, when his body broke up, after death, he was reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[2409]="*So tattha aññe deve dasahi ṭhānehi adhiggaṇhāti dibbena āyunā dibbena vaṇṇena dibbena sukhena dibbena yasena dibbena ādhipateyyena dibbehi rūpehi dibbehi saddehi dibbehi gandhehi dibbehi rasehi dibbehi phoṭṭhabbehi.**There he surpassed the other gods in ten respects: divine life span, beauty, happiness, glory, sovereignty, sights, sounds, smells, tastes, and touches.*";
P_HTM[2410]="*So tato cuto itthattaṃ āgato samāno imaṃ mahāpurisalakkhaṇaṃ paṭilabhati.**When he passed away from there and came back to this state of existence he obtained this mark of a great man:*";
P_HTM[2411]="*Suppatiṭṭhitapādo hoti.**he has well-planted feet.*";
P_HTM[2412]="*Samaṃ pādaṃ bhūmiyaṃ nikkhipati, samaṃ uddharati, samaṃ sabbāvantehi pādatalehi bhūmiṃ phusati.**He places his foot on the ground evenly, raises it evenly, and touches the ground evenly with the whole sole of his foot.*";
P_HTM[2413]="*So tena lakkhaṇena samannāgato sace agāraṃ ajjhāvasati, rājā hoti cakkavattī dhammiko dhammarājā cāturanto vijitāvī janapadatthāvariyappatto sattaratanasamannāgato.**Possessing this mark, if he stays at home he becomes a wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[2414]="*Tassimāni satta ratanāni bhavanti;**He has the following seven treasures:*";
P_HTM[2415]="*Seyyathidaṃ—cakkaratanaṃ hatthiratanaṃ assaratanaṃ maṇiratanaṃ itthiratanaṃ gahapatiratanaṃ pariṇāyakaratanameva sattamaṃ.**the wheel, the elephant, the horse, the jewel, the woman, the treasurer, and the counselor as the seventh treasure.*";
P_HTM[2416]="*Parosahassaṃ kho panassa puttā bhavanti sūrā vīraṅgarūpā parasenappamaddanā.**He has over a thousand sons who are valiant and heroic, crushing the armies of his enemies.*";
P_HTM[2417]="*So imaṃ pathaviṃ sāgarapariyantaṃ akhilamanimittamakaṇṭakaṃ iddhaṃ phītaṃ khemaṃ sivaṃ nirabbudaṃ adaṇḍena asatthena dhammena abhivijiya ajjhāvasati.**After conquering this land girt by sea—free of harassment by bandits, successful and prosperous, safe, blessed, and untroubled—he reigns by principle, without rod or sword.*";
P_HTM[2418]="*Rājā samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as king?*";
P_HTM[2419]="*Akkhambhiyo hoti kenaci manussabhūtena paccatthikena paccāmittena.**He can’t be stopped by any human foe or enemy.*";
P_HTM[2420]="*Rājā samāno idaṃ labhati.**That’s what he obtains as king.*";
P_HTM[2421]="*Sace kho pana agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajati, arahaṃ hoti sammāsambuddho loke vivaṭṭacchado.**But if he goes forth from the lay life to homelessness, he becomes a perfected one, a fully awakened Buddha, who draws back the veil from the world.*";
P_HTM[2422]="*Buddho samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as Buddha?*";
P_HTM[2423]="*Akkhambhiyo hoti abbhantarehi vā bāhirehi vā paccatthikehi paccāmittehi rāgena vā dosena vā mohena vā samaṇena vā brāhmaṇena vā devena vā mārena vā brahmunā vā kenaci vā lokasmiṃ.**He can’t be stopped by any foe or enemy whether internal or external; nor by greed, hate, or delusion; nor by any ascetic or brahmin or god or Māra or Brahmā or by anyone in the world.*";
P_HTM[2424]="*Buddho samāno idaṃ labhati”.**That’s what he obtains as Buddha.”*";
P_HTM[2425]="*Etamatthaṃ bhagavā avoca.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2426]="*Tatthetaṃ vuccati:**On this it is said:*";
P_HTM[2427]="*“Sacce ca dhamme ca dame ca saṃyame,**“Truth, principle, self-control, and restraint;*";
P_HTM[2428]="*Soceyyasīlālayuposathesu ca;**purity, precepts, and observing the sabbath;*";
P_HTM[2429]="*Dāne ahiṃsāya asāhase rato,**giving, harmlessness, delighting in non-violence—*";
P_HTM[2430]="*Daḷhaṃ samādāya samattamācari.**firmly undertaking these things, he lived accordingly.*";
P_HTM[2431]="*So tena kammena divaṃ samakkami,**By means of these deeds he went to heaven,*";
P_HTM[2432]="*Sukhañca khiḍḍāratiyo ca anvabhi;**where he enjoyed happiness and merriment.*";
P_HTM[2433]="*Tato cavitvā punarāgato idha,**After passing away from there to here,*";
P_HTM[2434]="*Samehi pādehi phusī vasundharaṃ.**he steps evenly on this rich earth.*";
P_HTM[2435]="*Byākaṃsu veyyañjanikā samāgatā,**The gathered soothsayers predicted*";
P_HTM[2436]="*Samappatiṭṭhassa na hoti khambhanā;**that there is no stopping one of such even tread,*";
P_HTM[2437]="*Gihissa vā pabbajitassa vā puna,**as householder or renunciate.*";
P_HTM[2438]="*Taṃ lakkhaṇaṃ bhavati tadatthajotakaṃ.**That’s the meaning shown by this mark.*";
P_HTM[2439]="*Akkhambhiyo hoti agāramāvasaṃ,**While living at home he cannot be stopped,*";
P_HTM[2440]="*Parābhibhū sattubhi nappamaddano;**he defeats his foes, and cannot be beaten.*";
P_HTM[2441]="*Manussabhūtenidha hoti kenaci,**Due to the fruit of that deed,*";
P_HTM[2442]="*Akkhambhiyo tassa phalena kammuno.**he cannot be stopped by any human.*";
P_HTM[2443]="*Sace ca pabbajjamupeti tādiso,**But if he chooses the life gone forth,*";
P_HTM[2444]="*Nekkhammachandābhirato vicakkhaṇo;**seeing clearly, loving renunciation,*";
P_HTM[2445]="*Aggo na so gacchati jātu khambhanaṃ,**not even the best can hope to stop him;*";
P_HTM[2446]="*Naruttamo esa hi tassa dhammatā”ti.**this is the nature of the supreme person.”*";
P_HTM[2447]="*2. Pādatalacakkalakkhaṇaṃ**2. Wheels on the Feet*";
P_HTM[2448]="*“Yampi, bhikkhave, tathāgato purimaṃ jātiṃ purimaṃ bhavaṃ purimaṃ niketaṃ pubbe manussabhūto samāno**“Mendicants, in some past lives the Realized One was reborn as a human being.*";
P_HTM[2449]="*bahujanassa sukhāvaho ahosi, ubbegauttāsabhayaṃ apanuditā, dhammikañca rakkhāvaraṇaguttiṃ saṃvidhātā, saparivārañca dānaṃ adāsi.**He brought happiness to many people, eliminating threats, terror, and danger, providing just protection and security, and giving gifts with all the trimmings.*";
P_HTM[2450]="*So tassa kammassa kaṭattā upacitattā ussannattā vipulattā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati … pe …**Due to performing those deeds he was reborn in a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[2451]="*so tato cuto itthattaṃ āgato samāno imaṃ mahāpurisalakkhaṇaṃ paṭilabhati.**When he came back to this state of existence he obtained this mark:*";
P_HTM[2452]="*Heṭṭhāpādatalesu cakkāni jātāni honti sahassārāni sanemikāni sanābhikāni sabbākāraparipūrāni suvibhattantarāni.**on the soles of his feet there are thousand-spoked wheels, with rims and hubs, complete in every detail and well divided inside.*";
P_HTM[2453]="*So tena lakkhaṇena samannāgato sace agāraṃ ajjhāvasati, rājā hoti cakkavattī … pe …**Possessing this mark, if he stays at home he becomes a wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[2454]="*rājā samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as king?*";
P_HTM[2455]="*Mahāparivāro hoti;**He has a large following*";
P_HTM[2456]="*mahāssa honti parivārā brāhmaṇagahapatikā negamajānapadā gaṇakamahāmattā anīkaṭṭhā dovārikā amaccā pārisajjā rājāno bhogiyā kumārā.**of brahmins and householders, people of town and country, treasury officials, military officers, guardsmen, ministers, counselors, rulers, tax beneficiaries, and princes.*";
P_HTM[2457]="*Rājā samāno idaṃ labhati.**That’s what he obtains as king.*";
P_HTM[2458]="*Sace kho pana agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajati, arahaṃ hoti sammāsambuddho loke vivaṭṭacchado.**But if he goes forth from the lay life to homelessness, he becomes a fully awakened Buddha.*";
P_HTM[2459]="*Buddho samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as Buddha?*";
P_HTM[2460]="*Mahāparivāro hoti;**He has a large following*";
P_HTM[2461]="*mahāssa honti parivārā bhikkhū bhikkhuniyo upāsakā upāsikāyo devā manussā asurā nāgā gandhabbā.**of monks, nuns, laymen, laywomen, gods, humans, demons, dragons, and fairies.*";
P_HTM[2462]="*Buddho samāno idaṃ labhati”.**That’s what he obtains as Buddha.”*";
P_HTM[2463]="*Etamatthaṃ bhagavā avoca.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2464]="*Tatthetaṃ vuccati:**On this it is said:*";
P_HTM[2465]="*“Pure puratthā purimāsu jātisu,**“In olden days, in past lives,*";
P_HTM[2466]="*Manussabhūto bahunaṃ sukhāvaho;**he brought happiness to many people,*";
P_HTM[2467]="*Ubbhegauttāsabhayāpanūdano,**ridding them of fear, terror, and danger,*";
P_HTM[2468]="*Guttīsu rakkhāvaraṇesu ussuko.**zealously guarding and protecting them.*";
P_HTM[2469]="*So tena kammena divaṃ samakkami,**By means of these deeds he went to heaven,*";
P_HTM[2470]="*Sukhañca khiḍḍāratiyo ca anvabhi;**where he enjoyed happiness and merriment.*";
P_HTM[2471]="*Tato cavitvā punarāgato idha,**After passing away from there to here,*";
P_HTM[2472]="*Cakkāni pādesu duvesu vindati.**wheels on his two feet are found,*";
P_HTM[2473]="*Samantanemīni sahassarāni ca,**all rimmed around and thousand-spoked.*";
P_HTM[2474]="*Byākaṃsu veyyañjanikā samāgatā;**The gathered soothsayers predicted,*";
P_HTM[2475]="*Disvā kumāraṃ satapuññalakkhaṇaṃ,**seeing the prince with the hundred-fold mark of merits,*";
P_HTM[2476]="*Parivāravā hessati sattumaddano.**that he’d have a following, subduing foes,*";
P_HTM[2477]="*Tathā hi cakkāni samantanemini,**which is why he has wheels all rimmed around.*";
P_HTM[2478]="*Sace na pabbajjamupeti tādiso;**If he doesn’t choose the life gone forth,*";
P_HTM[2479]="*Vatteti cakkaṃ pathaviṃ pasāsati,**he’ll roll the wheel and rule the land.*";
P_HTM[2480]="*Tassānuyantādha bhavanti khattiyā.**The aristocrats will be his vassals,*";
P_HTM[2481]="*Mahāyasaṃ samparivārayanti naṃ,**flocking to his glory.*";
P_HTM[2482]="*Sace ca pabbajjamupeti tādiso;**But if he chooses the life gone forth,*";
P_HTM[2483]="*Nekkhammachandābhirato vicakkhaṇo,**seeing clearly, loving renunciation,*";
P_HTM[2484]="*Devā manussāsurasakkarakkhasā.**the gods, humans, demons, Sakka, and monsters;*";
P_HTM[2485]="*Gandhabbanāgā vihagā catuppadā,**fairies and dragons, birds and beasts,*";
P_HTM[2486]="*Anuttaraṃ devamanussapūjitaṃ;**will flock to his glory,*";
P_HTM[2487]="*Mahāyasaṃ samparivārayanti nan”ti.**the supreme, honored by gods and humans.”*";
P_HTM[2488]="*3–5. Āyatapaṇhitāditilakkhaṇaṃ**3–5. Projecting Heels, Etc.*";
P_HTM[2489]="*“Yampi, bhikkhave, tathāgato purimaṃ jātiṃ purimaṃ bhavaṃ purimaṃ niketaṃ pubbe manussabhūto samāno**“Mendicants, in some past lives the Realized One was reborn as a human being.*";
P_HTM[2490]="*pāṇātipātaṃ pahāya pāṇātipātā paṭivirato ahosi nihitadaṇḍo nihitasattho lajjī dayāpanno, sabbapāṇabhūtahitānukampī vihāsi.**He gave up killing living creatures, renouncing the rod and the sword. He was scrupulous and kind, living full of compassion for all living beings.*";
P_HTM[2491]="*So tassa kammassa kaṭattā upacitattā ussannattā vipulattā … pe …**Due to performing those deeds he was reborn in a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[2492]="*so tato cuto itthattaṃ āgato samāno imāni tīṇi mahāpurisalakkhaṇāni paṭilabhati.**When he came back to this state of existence he obtained these three marks:*";
P_HTM[2493]="*Āyatapaṇhi ca hoti, dīghaṅguli ca brahmujugatto ca.**he has projecting heels, long fingers, and his body is as straight as Brahmā’s.*";
P_HTM[2494]="*So tehi lakkhaṇehi samannāgato sace agāraṃ ajjhāvasati, rājā hoti cakkavattī … pe …**Possessing these marks, if he stays at home he becomes a wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[2495]="*rājā samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as king?*";
P_HTM[2496]="*Dīghāyuko hoti ciraṭṭhitiko, dīghamāyuṃ pāleti, na sakkā hoti antarā jīvitā voropetuṃ kenaci manussabhūtena paccatthikena paccāmittena.**He’s long lived, preserving his life for a long time. No human foe or enemy is able to take his life before his time.*";
P_HTM[2497]="*Rājā samāno idaṃ labhati … pe …**That’s what he obtains as king.*";
P_HTM[2498]="*buddho samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as Buddha?*";
P_HTM[2499]="*Dīghāyuko hoti ciraṭṭhitiko, dīghamāyuṃ pāleti, na sakkā hoti antarā jīvitā voropetuṃ paccatthikehi paccāmittehi samaṇena vā brāhmaṇena vā devena vā mārena vā brahmunā vā kenaci vā lokasmiṃ.**He’s long lived, preserving his life for a long time. No foes or enemies—nor any ascetic or brahmin or god or Māra or Brahmā or anyone in the world—is able to take his life before his time.*";
P_HTM[2500]="*Buddho samāno idaṃ labhati”.**That’s what he obtains as Buddha.”*";
P_HTM[2501]="*Etamatthaṃ bhagavā avoca.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2502]="*Tatthetaṃ vuccati:**On this it is said:*";
P_HTM[2503]="*“Māraṇavadhabhayattano viditvā,**“Realizing for himself the horrors of death,*";
P_HTM[2504]="*Paṭivirato paraṃ māraṇāyahosi;**he refrained from killing other creatures.*";
P_HTM[2505]="*Tena sucaritena saggamagamā,**By that good conduct he went to heaven,*";
P_HTM[2506]="*Sukataphalavipākamanubhosi.**where he enjoyed the fruit of deeds well done.*";
P_HTM[2507]="*Caviya punaridhāgato samāno,**Passing away, on his return to here,*";
P_HTM[2508]="*Paṭilabhati idha tīṇi lakkhaṇāni;**he obtained these three marks:*";
P_HTM[2509]="*Bhavati vipuladīghapāsaṇhiko,**his projecting heels are full and long,*";
P_HTM[2510]="*Brahmāva suju subho sujātagatto.**and he’s straight, beautiful, and well-formed, like Brahmā.*";
P_HTM[2511]="*Subhujo susu susaṇṭhito sujāto,**Fair of limb, youthful, of good posture and breeding,*";
P_HTM[2512]="*Mudutalunaṅguliyassa honti;**his fingers are soft and tender and long.*";
P_HTM[2513]="*Dīghā tībhi purisavaraggalakkhaṇehi,**By these three marks of an excellent man,*";
P_HTM[2514]="*Cirayapanāya kumāramādisanti.**they indicated that the prince’s life would be long:*";
P_HTM[2515]="*Bhavati yadi gihī ciraṃ yapeti,**‘As a householder he will live long;*";
P_HTM[2516]="*Cirataraṃ pabbajati yadi tato hi;**longer still if he goes forth, due to*";
P_HTM[2517]="*Yāpayati ca vasiddhibhāvanāya,**mastery in the development of psychic power.*";
P_HTM[2518]="*Iti dīghāyukatāya taṃ nimittan”ti.**Thus this is the sign of long life.’”*";
P_HTM[2519]="*6. Sattussadatālakkhaṇaṃ**6. Seven Bulges*";
P_HTM[2520]="*“Yampi, bhikkhave, tathāgato purimaṃ jātiṃ purimaṃ bhavaṃ purimaṃ niketaṃ pubbe manussabhūto samāno**“Mendicants, in some past lives the Realized One was reborn as a human being.*";
P_HTM[2521]="*dātā ahosi paṇītānaṃ rasitānaṃ khādanīyānaṃ bhojanīyānaṃ sāyanīyānaṃ lehanīyānaṃ pānānaṃ.**He was a donor of fine and tasty foods and drinks of all kinds, delicious and scrumptious.*";
P_HTM[2522]="*So tassa kammassa kaṭattā … pe …**Due to performing those deeds he was reborn in a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[2523]="*so tato cuto itthattaṃ āgato samāno imaṃ mahāpurisalakkhaṇaṃ paṭilabhati, sattussado hoti, sattassa ussadā honti;**When he came back to this state of existence he obtained this mark: he has bulging muscles in seven places.*";
P_HTM[2524]="*ubhosu hatthesu ussadā honti, ubhosu pādesu ussadā honti, ubhosu aṃsakūṭesu ussadā honti, khandhe ussado hoti.**He has bulges on both hands, both feet, both shoulders, and his chest.*";
P_HTM[2525]="*So tena lakkhaṇena samannāgato sace agāraṃ ajjhāvasati, rājā hoti cakkavattī … pe …**Possessing this mark, if he stays at home he becomes a wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[2526]="*rājā samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as king?*";
P_HTM[2527]="*Lābhī hoti paṇītānaṃ rasitānaṃ khādanīyānaṃ bhojanīyānaṃ sāyanīyānaṃ lehanīyānaṃ pānānaṃ.**He gets fine and tasty foods and drinks of all kinds, delicious and scrumptious.*";
P_HTM[2528]="*Rājā samāno idaṃ labhati … pe …**That’s what he obtains as king.*";
P_HTM[2529]="*buddho samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as Buddha?*";
P_HTM[2530]="*Lābhī hoti paṇītānaṃ rasitānaṃ khādanīyānaṃ bhojanīyānaṃ sāyanīyānaṃ lehanīyānaṃ pānānaṃ.**He gets fine and tasty foods and drinks of all kinds, delicious and scrumptious.*";
P_HTM[2531]="*Buddho samāno idaṃ labhati”.**That’s what he obtains as Buddha.”*";
P_HTM[2532]="*Etamatthaṃ bhagavā avoca.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2533]="*Tatthetaṃ vuccati:**On this it is said:*";
P_HTM[2534]="*“Khajjabhojjamatha leyya sāyiyaṃ,**“He used to give the very best of flavors—*";
P_HTM[2535]="*Uttamaggarasadāyako ahu;**scrumptious foods of every kind.*";
P_HTM[2536]="*Tena so sucaritena kammunā,**Because of that good deed,*";
P_HTM[2537]="*Nandane ciramabhippamodati.**he rejoiced long in Nandana heaven.*";
P_HTM[2538]="*Satta cussade idhādhigacchati,**On returning to here, he got seven bulging muscles*";
P_HTM[2539]="*Hatthapādamudutañca vindati;**and tender hands and feet are found.*";
P_HTM[2540]="*Āhu byañjananimittakovidā,**The soothsayers expert in signs declared:*";
P_HTM[2541]="*Khajjabhojjarasalābhitāya naṃ.**‘He’ll get tasty foods of all sorts*";
P_HTM[2542]="*Yaṃ gihissapi tadatthajotakaṃ,**as a householder, that’s what that means.*";
P_HTM[2543]="*Pabbajjampi ca tadādhigacchati;**But even if he goes forth he’ll get the same,*";
P_HTM[2544]="*Khajjabhojjarasalābhiruttamaṃ,**supreme in gaining tasty foods of all sorts,*";
P_HTM[2545]="*Āhu sabbagihibandhanacchidan”ti.**cutting all bonds of the lay life.’”*";
P_HTM[2546]="*7–8. Karacaraṇamudujālatālakkhaṇāni**7–8. Tender and Clinging Hands*";
P_HTM[2547]="*“Yampi, bhikkhave, tathāgato purimaṃ jātiṃ purimaṃ bhavaṃ purimaṃ niketaṃ pubbe manussabhūto samāno**“Mendicants, in some past lives the Realized One was reborn as a human being.*";
P_HTM[2548]="*catūhi saṅgahavatthūhi janaṃ saṅgāhako ahosi—**He brought people together using the four ways of being inclusive:*";
P_HTM[2549]="*dānena peyyavajjena atthacariyāya samānattatāya.**giving, kindly words, taking care, and equality.*";
P_HTM[2550]="*So tassa kammassa kaṭattā … pe …**Due to performing those deeds he was reborn in a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[2551]="*so tato cuto itthattaṃ āgato samāno imāni dve mahāpurisalakkhaṇāni paṭilabhati.**When he came back to this state of existence he obtained these two marks:*";
P_HTM[2552]="*Mudutalunahatthapādo ca hoti jālahatthapādo ca.**his hands and feet are tender, and they cling gracefully.*";
P_HTM[2553]="*So tehi lakkhaṇehi samannāgato sace agāraṃ ajjhāvasati, rājā hoti cakkavattī … pe …**Possessing these marks, if he stays at home he becomes a wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[2554]="*rājā samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as king?*";
P_HTM[2555]="*Susaṅgahitaparijano hoti, susaṅgahitāssa honti brāhmaṇagahapatikā negamajānapadā gaṇakamahāmattā anīkaṭṭhā dovārikā amaccā pārisajjā rājāno bhogiyā kumārā.**His retinue is inclusive, cohesive, and well-managed. This includes brahmins and householders, people of town and country, treasury officials, military officers, guardsmen, ministers, counselors, rulers, tax beneficiaries, and princes.*";
P_HTM[2556]="*Rājā samāno idaṃ labhati …**That’s what he obtains as king.*";
P_HTM[2557]="*buddho samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as Buddha?*";
P_HTM[2558]="*Susaṅgahitaparijano hoti, susaṅgahitāssa honti bhikkhū bhikkhuniyo upāsakā upāsikāyo devā manussā asurā nāgā gandhabbā.**His retinue is inclusive, cohesive, and well-managed. This includes monks, nuns, laymen, laywomen, gods, humans, demons, dragons, and fairies.*";
P_HTM[2559]="*Buddho samāno idaṃ labhati”.**That’s what he obtains as Buddha.”*";
P_HTM[2560]="*Etamatthaṃ bhagavā avoca.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2561]="*Tatthetaṃ vuccati:**On this it is said:*";
P_HTM[2562]="*“Dānampi catthacariyatañca,**“By giving and helping others,*";
P_HTM[2563]="*Piyavāditañca samānattatañca;**kindly speech, and equal treatment,*";
P_HTM[2564]="*Kariyacariyasusaṅgahaṃ bahūnaṃ,**such action and conduct as brought people together,*";
P_HTM[2565]="*Anavamatena guṇena yāti saggaṃ.**he went to heaven due to his esteemed virtue.*";
P_HTM[2566]="*Caviya punaridhāgato samāno,**Passing away, on his return to here,*";
P_HTM[2567]="*Karacaraṇamudutañca jālino ca;**the young baby prince obtained*";
P_HTM[2568]="*Atirucirasuvaggudassaneyyaṃ,**hands and feet so tender and clinging,*";
P_HTM[2569]="*Paṭilabhati daharo susu kumāro.**lovely, graceful, and good-looking.*";
P_HTM[2570]="*Bhavati parijanassavo vidheyyo,**His retinue is loyal and manageable,*";
P_HTM[2571]="*Mahimaṃ āvasito susaṅgahito;**staying agreeably all over this broad land.*";
P_HTM[2572]="*Piyavadū hitasukhataṃ jigīsamāno,**Speaking kindly, desiring happiness,*";
P_HTM[2573]="*Abhirucitāni guṇāni ācarati.**he practices the good qualities he’s adopted.*";
P_HTM[2574]="*Yadi ca jahati sabbakāmabhogaṃ,**But if he gives up all sensual enjoyments,*";
P_HTM[2575]="*Kathayati dhammakathaṃ jino janassa;**as victor he speaks Dhamma to the people.*";
P_HTM[2576]="*Vacanapaṭikarassābhippasannā,**Devoted, they respond to his words;*";
P_HTM[2577]="*Sutvāna dhammānudhammamācarantī”ti.**after listening, they practice in line with the teaching.”*";
P_HTM[2578]="*9–10. Ussaṅkhapāda-uddhaggalomatālakkhaṇāni**9–10. Arched Feet and Upright Hair*";
P_HTM[2579]="*“Yampi, bhikkhave, tathāgato purimaṃ jātiṃ purimaṃ bhavaṃ purimaṃ niketaṃ pubbe manussabhūto samāno**“Mendicants, in some past lives the Realized One was reborn as a human being.*";
P_HTM[2580]="*atthūpasaṃhitaṃ dhammūpasaṃhitaṃ vācaṃ bhāsitā ahosi, bahujanaṃ nidaṃsesi, pāṇīnaṃ hitasukhāvaho dhammayāgī.**His speech was meaningful and principled. He educated many people, bringing welfare and happiness, offering the teaching.*";
P_HTM[2581]="*So tassa kammassa kaṭattā … pe …**Due to performing those deeds he was reborn in a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[2582]="*so tato cuto itthattaṃ āgato samāno imāni dve mahāpurisalakkhaṇāni paṭilabhati.**When he came back to this state of existence he obtained these two marks:*";
P_HTM[2583]="*Ussaṅkhapādo ca hoti, uddhaggalomo ca.**his feet are arched and his hairs stand up.*";
P_HTM[2584]="*So tehi lakkhaṇehi samannāgato, sace agāraṃ ajjhāvasati, rājā hoti cakkavattī … pe …**Possessing these marks, if he stays at home he becomes a wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[2585]="*rājā samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as king?*";
P_HTM[2586]="*Aggo ca hoti seṭṭho ca pāmokkho ca uttamo ca pavaro ca kāmabhogīnaṃ.**He is the foremost, best, chief, highest, and finest of those who enjoy sensual pleasures.*";
P_HTM[2587]="*Rājā samāno idaṃ labhati … pe …**That’s what he obtains as king.*";
P_HTM[2588]="*buddho samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as Buddha?*";
P_HTM[2589]="*Aggo ca hoti seṭṭho ca pāmokkho ca uttamo ca pavaro ca sabbasattānaṃ.**He is the foremost, best, chief, highest, and finest of all sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[2590]="*Buddho samāno idaṃ labhati”.**That’s what he obtains as Buddha.”*";
P_HTM[2591]="*Etamatthaṃ bhagavā avoca.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2592]="*Tatthetaṃ vuccati:**On this it is said:*";
P_HTM[2593]="*“Atthadhammasahitaṃ pure giraṃ,**“His word was meaningful and principled,*";
P_HTM[2594]="*Erayaṃ bahujanaṃ nidaṃsayi;**moving the people with his explanations.*";
P_HTM[2595]="*Pāṇinaṃ hitasukhāvaho ahu,**He brought welfare and happiness to creatures,*";
P_HTM[2596]="*Dhammayāgamayajī amaccharī.**unstintingly offering up teaching.*";
P_HTM[2597]="*Tena so sucaritena kammunā,**Because of that good deed,*";
P_HTM[2598]="*Suggatiṃ vajati tattha modati;**he went to heaven, and there rejoiced.*";
P_HTM[2599]="*Lakkhaṇāni ca duve idhāgato,**On return to here two marks are found,*";
P_HTM[2600]="*Uttamappamukhatāya vindati.**of excellence and supremacy.*";
P_HTM[2601]="*Ubbhamuppatitalomavā saso,**His hairs stand upright,*";
P_HTM[2602]="*Pādagaṇṭhirahu sādhusaṇṭhitā;**and his ankles stand out well.*";
P_HTM[2603]="*Maṃsalohitācitā tacotthatā,**Swollen with flesh and blood, and wrapped in skin,*";
P_HTM[2604]="*Uparicaraṇasobhanā ahu.**they make it pretty above the feet.*";
P_HTM[2605]="*Gehamāvasati ce tathāvidho,**If such a one lives in the home,*";
P_HTM[2606]="*Aggataṃ vajati kāmabhoginaṃ;**he becomes best of those who enjoy sensual pleasures.*";
P_HTM[2607]="*Tena uttaritaro na vijjati,**There’ll be none better than him;*";
P_HTM[2608]="*Jambudīpamabhibhuyya iriyati.**he’ll live having mastered all India.*";
P_HTM[2609]="*Pabbajampi ca anomanikkamo,**But going forth the peerless renunciate*";
P_HTM[2610]="*Aggataṃ vajati sabbapāṇinaṃ;**becomes best of all creatures.*";
P_HTM[2611]="*Tena uttaritaro na vijjati,**There’ll be none better than him,*";
P_HTM[2612]="*Sabbalokamabhibhuyya viharatī”ti.**he’ll live having mastered the whole world.”*";
P_HTM[2613]="*11. Eṇijaṅghalakkhaṇaṃ**11. Antelope Calves*";
P_HTM[2614]="*“Yampi, bhikkhave, tathāgato purimaṃ jātiṃ purimaṃ bhavaṃ purimaṃ niketaṃ pubbe manussabhūto samāno**“Mendicants, in some past lives the Realized One was reborn as a human being.*";
P_HTM[2615]="*sakkaccaṃ vācetā ahosi sippaṃ vā vijjaṃ vā caraṇaṃ vā kammaṃ vā:**He was a thorough teacher of a profession, a branch of knowledge, conduct, or action, thinking:*";
P_HTM[2616]="*‘kintime khippaṃ vijāneyyuṃ, khippaṃ paṭipajjeyyuṃ, na ciraṃ kilisseyyun’”ti.**‘How might they quickly learn and practice, without getting exhausted?’*";
P_HTM[2617]="*So tassa kammassa kaṭattā … pe …**Due to performing those deeds he was reborn in a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[2618]="*so tato cuto itthattaṃ āgato samāno imaṃ mahāpurisalakkhaṇaṃ paṭilabhati.**When he came back to this state of existence he obtained this mark:*";
P_HTM[2619]="*Eṇijaṅgho hoti.**his calves are like those of an antelope.*";
P_HTM[2620]="*So tena lakkhaṇena samannāgato sace agāraṃ ajjhāvasati, rājā hoti cakkavattī … pe …**Possessing this mark, if he stays at home he becomes a wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[2621]="*rājā samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as king?*";
P_HTM[2622]="*Yāni tāni rājārahāni rājaṅgāni rājūpabhogāni rājānucchavikāni tāni khippaṃ paṭilabhati.**He quickly obtains the things worthy of a king, the factors, supports, and things befitting a king.*";
P_HTM[2623]="*Rājā samāno idaṃ labhati … pe …**That’s what he obtains as king.*";
P_HTM[2624]="*buddho samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as Buddha?*";
P_HTM[2625]="*Yāni tāni samaṇārahāni samaṇaṅgāni samaṇūpabhogāni samaṇānucchavikāni, tāni khippaṃ paṭilabhati.**He quickly obtains the things worthy of an ascetic, the factors, supports, and things befitting an ascetic.*";
P_HTM[2626]="*Buddho samāno idaṃ labhati”.**That’s what he obtains as Buddha.”*";
P_HTM[2627]="*Etamatthaṃ bhagavā avoca.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2628]="*Tatthetaṃ vuccati:**On this it is said:*";
P_HTM[2629]="*“Sippesu vijjācaraṇesu kammesu,**“In professions, knowledge, conduct, and deeds,*";
P_HTM[2630]="*Kathaṃ vijāneyyuṃ lahunti icchati;**he thought of how they might swiftly learn.*";
P_HTM[2631]="*Yadūpaghātāya na hoti kassaci,**Things that harm no-one at all,*";
P_HTM[2632]="*Vāceti khippaṃ na ciraṃ kilissati.**he quickly taught so they would not get tired.*";
P_HTM[2633]="*Taṃ kammaṃ katvā kusalaṃ sukhudrayaṃ,**Having done that skillful deed whose outcome is happiness,*";
P_HTM[2634]="*Jaṅghā manuññā labhate susaṇṭhitā;**he gains prominent and elegant calves.*";
P_HTM[2635]="*Vaṭṭā sujātā anupubbamuggatā,**Well-formed in graceful spirals,*";
P_HTM[2636]="*Uddhaggalomā sukhumattacotthatā.**he’s covered in fine rising hairs.*";
P_HTM[2637]="*Eṇeyyajaṅghoti tamāhu puggalaṃ,**They say that person has antelope calves,*";
P_HTM[2638]="*Sampattiyā khippamidhāhu lakkhaṇaṃ;**and that this is the mark of swift success.*";
P_HTM[2639]="*Gehānulomāni yadābhikaṅkhati,**If he desires the things of the household life,*";
P_HTM[2640]="*Apabbajaṃ khippamidhādhigacchati.**not going forth, they’ll quickly be his.*";
P_HTM[2641]="*Sace ca pabbajjamupeti tādiso,**But if he chooses the life gone forth,*";
P_HTM[2642]="*Nekkhammachandābhirato vicakkhaṇo;**seeing clearly, loving renunciation,*";
P_HTM[2643]="*Anucchavikassa yadānulomikaṃ,**the peerless renunciate will quickly find*";
P_HTM[2644]="*Taṃ vindati khippamanomavikkamo”ti.**what is fitting and suitable.”*";
P_HTM[2645]="*12. Sukhumacchavilakkhaṇaṃ**12. Delicate Skin*";
P_HTM[2646]="*“Yampi, bhikkhave, tathāgato purimaṃ jātiṃ purimaṃ bhavaṃ purimaṃ niketaṃ pubbe manussabhūto samāno**“Mendicants, in some past lives the Realized One was reborn as a human being.*";
P_HTM[2647]="*samaṇaṃ vā brāhmaṇaṃ vā upasaṅkamitvā paripucchitā ahosi:**He approached an ascetic or brahmin and asked:*";
P_HTM[2648]="*‘kiṃ, bhante, kusalaṃ, kiṃ akusalaṃ, kiṃ sāvajjaṃ, kiṃ anavajjaṃ, kiṃ sevitabbaṃ, kiṃ na sevitabbaṃ, kiṃ me karīyamānaṃ dīgharattaṃ ahitāya dukkhāya assa, kiṃ vā pana me karīyamānaṃ dīgharattaṃ hitāya sukhāya assā’ti.**‘Sirs, what is skillful? What is unskillful? What is blameworthy? What is blameless? What should be cultivated? What should not be cultivated? Doing what leads to my lasting harm and suffering? Doing what leads to my lasting welfare and happiness?’*";
P_HTM[2649]="*So tassa kammassa kaṭattā … pe …**Due to performing those deeds he was reborn in a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[2650]="*so tato cuto itthattaṃ āgato samāno imaṃ mahāpurisalakkhaṇaṃ paṭilabhati.**When he came back to this state of existence he obtained this mark:*";
P_HTM[2651]="*Sukhumacchavi hoti, sukhumattā chaviyā rajojallaṃ kāye na upalimpati.**he has delicate skin, so delicate that dust and dirt don’t stick to his body.*";
P_HTM[2652]="*So tena lakkhaṇena samannāgato sace agāraṃ ajjhāvasati, rājā hoti cakkavattī … pe …**Possessing this mark, if he stays at home he becomes a wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[2653]="*rājā samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as king?*";
P_HTM[2654]="*Mahāpañño hoti, nāssa hoti koci paññāya sadiso vā seṭṭho vā kāmabhogīnaṃ.**He has great wisdom. Of those who enjoy sensual pleasures, none is his equal or better in wisdom.*";
P_HTM[2655]="*Rājā samāno idaṃ labhati … pe …**That’s what he obtains as king.*";
P_HTM[2656]="*buddho samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as Buddha?*";
P_HTM[2657]="*Mahāpañño hoti puthupañño hāsapañño javanapañño tikkhapañño nibbedhikapañño, nāssa hoti koci paññāya sadiso vā seṭṭho vā sabbasattānaṃ.**He has great wisdom, widespread wisdom, laughing wisdom, swift wisdom, sharp wisdom, and penetrating wisdom. No sentient being is his equal or better in wisdom.*";
P_HTM[2658]="*Buddho samāno idaṃ labhati”.**That’s what he obtains as Buddha.”*";
P_HTM[2659]="*Etamatthaṃ bhagavā avoca.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2660]="*Tatthetaṃ vuccati:**On this it is said:*";
P_HTM[2661]="*“Pure puratthā purimāsu jātisu,**“In olden days, in past lives,*";
P_HTM[2662]="*Aññātukāmo paripucchitā ahu;**eager to understand, he asked questions.*";
P_HTM[2663]="*Sussūsitā pabbajitaṃ upāsitā,**Keen to learn, he waited on renunciates,*";
P_HTM[2664]="*Atthantaro atthakathaṃ nisāmayi.**heeding their explanation with pure intent.*";
P_HTM[2665]="*Paññāpaṭilābhagatena kammunā,**Due to that deed of acquiring wisdom,*";
P_HTM[2666]="*Manussabhūto sukhumacchavī ahu;**as a human being his skin is delicate.*";
P_HTM[2667]="*Byākaṃsu uppādanimittakovidā,**At his birth the soothsayers expert in signs prophesied:*";
P_HTM[2668]="*Sukhumāni atthāni avecca dakkhiti.**‘He’ll discern delicate matters.’*";
P_HTM[2669]="*Sace na pabbajjamupeti tādiso,**If he doesn’t choose the life gone forth,*";
P_HTM[2670]="*Vatteti cakkaṃ pathaviṃ pasāsati;**he’ll roll the wheel and rule the land.*";
P_HTM[2671]="*Atthānusiṭṭhīsu pariggahesu ca,**Among those with material possessions who have been educated,*";
P_HTM[2672]="*Na tena seyyo sadiso ca vijjati.**none equal or better than him is found.*";
P_HTM[2673]="*Sace ca pabbajjamupeti tādiso,**But if he chooses the life gone forth,*";
P_HTM[2674]="*Nekkhammachandābhirato vicakkhaṇo;**seeing clearly, loving renunciation,*";
P_HTM[2675]="*Paññāvisiṭṭhaṃ labhate anuttaraṃ,**gaining wisdom that’s supreme and eminent,*";
P_HTM[2676]="*Pappoti bodhiṃ varabhūrimedhaso”ti.**the one of superb, vast intelligence attains awakening.”*";
P_HTM[2677]="*13. Suvaṇṇavaṇṇalakkhaṇaṃ**13. Golden Skin*";
P_HTM[2678]="*“Yampi, bhikkhave, tathāgato purimaṃ jātiṃ purimaṃ bhavaṃ purimaṃ niketaṃ pubbe manussabhūto samāno**“Mendicants, in some past lives the Realized One was reborn as a human being.*";
P_HTM[2679]="*akkodhano ahosi anupāyāsabahulo,**He wasn’t irritable or bad-tempered.*";
P_HTM[2680]="*bahumpi vutto samāno nābhisajji na kuppi na byāpajji na patitthīyi, na kopañca dosañca appaccayañca pātvākāsi.**Even when heavily criticized he didn’t lose his temper, become annoyed, hostile, and hard-hearted, or display annoyance, hate, and bitterness.*";
P_HTM[2681]="*Dātā ca ahosi sukhumānaṃ mudukānaṃ attharaṇānaṃ pāvuraṇānaṃ khomasukhumānaṃ kappāsikasukhumānaṃ koseyyasukhumānaṃ kambalasukhumānaṃ.**He donated soft and fine mats and blankets, and fine cloths of linen, cotton, silk, and wool.*";
P_HTM[2682]="*So tassa kammassa kaṭattā upacitattā … pe …**Due to performing those deeds he was reborn in a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[2683]="*so tato cuto itthattaṃ āgato samāno imaṃ mahāpurisalakkhaṇaṃ paṭilabhati.**When he came back to this state of existence he obtained this mark:*";
P_HTM[2684]="*Suvaṇṇavaṇṇo hoti kañcanasannibhattaco.**he is gold colored; his skin has a golden sheen.*";
P_HTM[2685]="*So tena lakkhaṇena samannāgato sace agāraṃ ajjhāvasati, rājā hoti cakkavattī … pe …**Possessing this mark, if he stays at home he becomes a wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[2686]="*rājā samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as king?*";
P_HTM[2687]="*Lābhī hoti sukhumānaṃ mudukānaṃ attharaṇānaṃ pāvuraṇānaṃ khomasukhumānaṃ kappāsikasukhumānaṃ koseyyasukhumānaṃ kambalasukhumānaṃ.**He obtains soft and fine mats and blankets, and fine cloths of linen, cotton, silk, and wool.*";
P_HTM[2688]="*Rājā samāno idaṃ labhati … pe …**That’s what he obtains as king.*";
P_HTM[2689]="*buddho samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as Buddha?*";
P_HTM[2690]="*Lābhī hoti sukhumānaṃ mudukānaṃ attharaṇānaṃ pāvuraṇānaṃ khomasukhumānaṃ kappāsikasukhumānaṃ koseyyasukhumānaṃ kambalasukhumānaṃ.**He obtains soft and fine mats and blankets, and fine cloths of linen, cotton, silk, and wool.*";
P_HTM[2691]="*Buddho samāno idaṃ labhati”.**That’s what he obtains as Buddha.”*";
P_HTM[2692]="*Etamatthaṃ bhagavā avoca.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2693]="*Tatthetaṃ vuccati:**On this it is said:*";
P_HTM[2694]="*“Akkodhañca adhiṭṭhahi adāsi,**“Dedicated to good will, he gave gifts.*";
P_HTM[2695]="*Dānañca vatthāni sukhumāni succhavīni;**In an earlier life he poured forth cloth*";
P_HTM[2696]="*Purimatarabhave ṭhito abhivissaji,**fine and soft to touch,*";
P_HTM[2697]="*Mahimiva suro abhivassaṃ.**like a god pouring rain on this broad earth.*";
P_HTM[2698]="*Taṃ katvāna ito cuto dibbaṃ,**So doing he passed from here to heaven,*";
P_HTM[2699]="*Upapajji sukataphalavipākamanubhutvā;**where he enjoyed the fruits of deeds well done.*";
P_HTM[2700]="*Kanakatanusannibho idhābhibhavati,**Here he wins a figure of gold,*";
P_HTM[2701]="*Suravarataroriva indo.**like Inda, the finest of gods.*";
P_HTM[2702]="*Gehañcāvasati naro apabbajja,**If that man stays in the house, not wishing to go forth,*";
P_HTM[2703]="*Micchaṃ mahatimahiṃ anusāsati;**he conquers and rules this vast, broad earth.*";
P_HTM[2704]="*Pasayha sahidha sattaratanaṃ,**He obtains abundant excellent cloth,*";
P_HTM[2705]="*Paṭilabhati vimalasukhumacchaviṃ suciñca.**so fine and soft to touch.*";
P_HTM[2706]="*Lābhī acchādanavatthamokkhapāvuraṇānaṃ,**He receives robes, cloth, and the finest garments*";
P_HTM[2707]="*Bhavati yadi anāgāriyataṃ upeti;**if he chooses the life gone forth.*";
P_HTM[2708]="*Sahito purimakataphalaṃ anubhavati,**For he still partakes of past deed’s fruit;*";
P_HTM[2709]="*Na bhavati katassa panāso”ti.**what’s been done is never lost.”*";
P_HTM[2710]="*14. Kosohitavatthaguyhalakkhaṇaṃ**14. Retracted Privates*";
P_HTM[2711]="*“Yampi, bhikkhave, tathāgato purimaṃ jātiṃ purimaṃ bhavaṃ purimaṃ niketaṃ pubbe manussabhūto samāno**“Mendicants, in some past lives the Realized One was reborn as a human being.*";
P_HTM[2712]="*cirappanaṭṭhe sucirappavāsino ñātimitte suhajje sakhino samānetā ahosi.**He reunited long-lost and long-separated relatives, friends, loved ones, and companions.*";
P_HTM[2713]="*Mātarampi puttena samānetā ahosi, puttampi mātarā samānetā ahosi, pitarampi puttena samānetā ahosi, puttampi pitarā samānetā ahosi, bhātarampi bhātarā samānetā ahosi, bhātarampi bhaginiyā samānetā ahosi, bhaginimpi bhātarā samānetā ahosi, bhaginimpi bhaginiyā samānetā ahosi, samaṅgīkatvā ca abbhanumoditā ahosi.**He reunited mother with child and child with mother; father with child and child with father; brother with brother, brother with sister, sister with brother, and sister with sister, bringing them together with rejoicing.*";
P_HTM[2714]="*So tassa kammassa kaṭattā … pe …**Due to performing those deeds he was reborn in a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[2715]="*so tato cuto itthattaṃ āgato samāno imaṃ mahāpurisalakkhaṇaṃ paṭilabhati—**When he came back to this state of existence he obtained this mark:*";
P_HTM[2716]="*kosohitavatthaguyho hoti.**his private parts are retracted.*";
P_HTM[2717]="*So tena lakkhaṇena samannāgato sace agāraṃ ajjhāvasati, rājā hoti cakkavattī … pe …**Possessing this mark, if he stays at home he becomes a wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[2718]="*rājā samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as king?*";
P_HTM[2719]="*Pahūtaputto hoti, parosahassaṃ kho panassa puttā bhavanti sūrā vīraṅgarūpā parasenappamaddanā.**He has many sons, over a thousand sons who are valiant and heroic, crushing the armies of his enemies.*";
P_HTM[2720]="*Rājā samāno idaṃ labhati … pe …**That’s what he obtains as king.*";
P_HTM[2721]="*buddho samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as Buddha?*";
P_HTM[2722]="*Pahūtaputto hoti, anekasahassaṃ kho panassa puttā bhavanti sūrā vīraṅgarūpā parasenappamaddanā.**He has many sons, many thousands of sons who are valiant and heroic, crushing the armies of his enemies.*";
P_HTM[2723]="*Buddho samāno idaṃ labhati”.**That’s what he obtains as Buddha.”*";
P_HTM[2724]="*Etamatthaṃ bhagavā avoca.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2725]="*Tatthetaṃ vuccati:**On this it is said:*";
P_HTM[2726]="*“Pure puratthā purimāsu jātisu,**“In olden days, in past lives,*";
P_HTM[2727]="*Cirappanaṭṭhe sucirappavāsino;**he reunited long-lost*";
P_HTM[2728]="*Ñātī suhajje sakhino samānayi,**and long-separated friends and family,*";
P_HTM[2729]="*Samaṅgikatvā anumoditā ahu.**bringing them together with joy.*";
P_HTM[2730]="*So tena kammena divaṃ samakkami,**By means of these deeds he went to heaven,*";
P_HTM[2731]="*Sukhañca khiḍḍāratiyo ca anvabhi;**where he enjoyed happiness and merriment.*";
P_HTM[2732]="*Tato cavitvā punarāgato idha,**After passing away from there to here,*";
P_HTM[2733]="*Kosohitaṃ vindati vatthachādiyaṃ.**his private parts are retracted.*";
P_HTM[2734]="*Pahūtaputto bhavatī tathāvidho,**Such a one has many sons,*";
P_HTM[2735]="*Parosahassañca bhavanti atrajā;**over a thousand descendants,*";
P_HTM[2736]="*Sūrā ca vīrā ca amittatāpanā,**valiant and heroic, devastating foes,*";
P_HTM[2737]="*Gihissa pītiṃ jananā piyaṃvadā.**a layman’s joy, speaking kindly.*";
P_HTM[2738]="*Bahūtarā pabbajitassa iriyato,**But if he lives the renunciate life*";
P_HTM[2739]="*Bhavanti puttā vacanānusārino;**he has even more sons following his word.*";
P_HTM[2740]="*Gihissa vā pabbajitassa vā puna,**As householder or renunciate,*";
P_HTM[2741]="*Taṃ lakkhaṇaṃ jāyati tadatthajotakan”ti.**that’s the meaning shown by this mark.”*";
P_HTM[2742]="*Paṭhamabhāṇavāro niṭṭhito.**The first recitation section is finished.*";
P_HTM[2743]="*15–16. Parimaṇḍalaanonamajaṇṇuparimasanalakkhaṇāni**15–16. Equal Proportions and Touching the Knees*";
P_HTM[2744]="*“Yampi, bhikkhave, tathāgato purimaṃ jātiṃ purimaṃ bhavaṃ purimaṃ niketaṃ pubbe manussabhūto samāno**“Mendicants, in some past lives the Realized One was reborn as a human being.*";
P_HTM[2745]="*mahājanasaṅgahaṃ samekkhamāno samaṃ jānāti sāmaṃ jānāti, purisaṃ jānāti purisavisesaṃ jānāti:**He regarded the gathered population equally. He knew what they had in common and what was their own. He knew each person, and he knew the distinctions between people.*";
P_HTM[2746]="*‘ayamidamarahati ayamidamarahatī’ti tattha tattha purisavisesakaro ahosi.**In each case, he made appropriate distinctions between people: ‘This one deserves that; that one deserves this.’*";
P_HTM[2747]="*So tassa kammassa kaṭattā … pe …**Due to performing those deeds he was reborn in a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[2748]="*so tato cuto itthattaṃ āgato samāno imāni dve mahāpurisalakkhaṇāni paṭilabhati.**When he came back to this state of existence he obtained these two marks:*";
P_HTM[2749]="*Nigrodhaparimaṇḍalo ca hoti, ṭhitakoyeva ca anonamanto ubhohi pāṇitalehi jaṇṇukāni parimasati parimajjati.**he has the proportional circumference of a banyan tree; and when standing upright and not bending over, the palms of both hands touch the knees.*";
P_HTM[2750]="*So tehi lakkhaṇehi samannāgato sace agāraṃ ajjhāvasati, rājā hoti cakkavattī … pe …**Possessing these marks, if he stays at home he becomes a wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[2751]="*rājā samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as king?*";
P_HTM[2752]="*Aḍḍho hoti mahaddhano mahābhogo pahūtajātarūparajato pahūtavittūpakaraṇo pahūtadhanadhañño paripuṇṇakosakoṭṭhāgāro.**He is rich, affluent, and wealthy, with lots of gold and silver, lots of property and assets, lots of money and grain, and a full treasury and storehouses.*";
P_HTM[2753]="*Rājā samāno idaṃ labhati … pe …**That’s what he obtains as king.*";
P_HTM[2754]="*buddho samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as Buddha?*";
P_HTM[2755]="*Aḍḍho hoti mahaddhano mahābhogo.**He is rich, affluent, and wealthy.*";
P_HTM[2756]="*Tassimāni dhanāni honti, seyyathidaṃ—**He has these kinds of wealth:*";
P_HTM[2757]="*saddhādhanaṃ sīladhanaṃ hiridhanaṃ ottappadhanaṃ sutadhanaṃ cāgadhanaṃ paññādhanaṃ.**the wealth of faith, ethical conduct, conscience, prudence, learning, generosity, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[2758]="*Buddho samāno idaṃ labhati”.**That’s what he obtains as Buddha.”*";
P_HTM[2759]="*Etamatthaṃ bhagavā avoca.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2760]="*Tatthetaṃ vuccati:**On this it is said:*";
P_HTM[2761]="*“Tuliya paṭivicaya cintayitvā,**“Observing the many people in a community,*";
P_HTM[2762]="*Mahājanasaṅgahanaṃ samekkhamāno;**he weighed, evaluated, and judged each case:*";
P_HTM[2763]="*Ayamidamarahati tattha tattha,**‘This one deserves that.’*";
P_HTM[2764]="*Purisavisesakaro pure ahosi.**That’s how he used to draw distinctions between people.*";
P_HTM[2765]="*Mahiñca pana ṭhito anonamanto,**Now standing without bending*";
P_HTM[2766]="*Phusati karehi ubhohi jaṇṇukāni;**he can touch his knees with both hands.*";
P_HTM[2767]="*Mahiruhaparimaṇḍalo ahosi,**With the remaining ripening of the fruit of good deeds,*";
P_HTM[2768]="*Sucaritakammavipākasesakena.**his circumference was that of a great tree.*";
P_HTM[2769]="*Bahuvividhanimittalakkhaṇaññū,**Learned experts in the many different*";
P_HTM[2770]="*Atinipuṇā manujā byākariṃsu;**signs and marks prophesied:*";
P_HTM[2771]="*Bahuvividhā gihīnaṃ arahāni,**‘The young prince will obtain*";
P_HTM[2772]="*Paṭilabhati daharo susu kumāro.**many different things that householders deserve.*";
P_HTM[2773]="*Idha ca mahīpatissa kāmabhogī,**Here there are many suitable pleasures*";
P_HTM[2774]="*Gihipatirūpakā bahū bhavanti;**for the ruler of the land to enjoy as householder.*";
P_HTM[2775]="*Yadi ca jahati sabbakāmabhogaṃ,**But if he gives up all sensual enjoyments,*";
P_HTM[2776]="*Labhati anuttaraṃ uttamadhanaggan”ti.**he will gain the supreme, highest peak of wealth.’”*";
P_HTM[2777]="*17–19. Sīhapubbaddhakāyāditilakkhaṇaṃ**17–19. A Lion’s Chest, Etc.*";
P_HTM[2778]="*“Yampi, bhikkhave, tathāgato purimaṃ jātiṃ purimaṃ bhavaṃ purimaṃ niketaṃ pubbe manussabhūto samāno**“Mendicants, in some past lives the Realized One was reborn as a human being.*";
P_HTM[2779]="*bahujanassa atthakāmo ahosi hitakāmo phāsukāmo yogakkhemakāmo:**He desired the good, the welfare, the comfort, and sanctuary of the people, thinking:*";
P_HTM[2780]="*‘kintime saddhāya vaḍḍheyyuṃ, sīlena vaḍḍheyyuṃ, sutena vaḍḍheyyuṃ, cāgena vaḍḍheyyuṃ, dhammena vaḍḍheyyuṃ, paññāya vaḍḍheyyuṃ, dhanadhaññena vaḍḍheyyuṃ, khettavatthunā vaḍḍheyyuṃ, dvipadacatuppadehi vaḍḍheyyuṃ, puttadārehi vaḍḍheyyuṃ, dāsakammakaraporisehi vaḍḍheyyuṃ, ñātīhi vaḍḍheyyuṃ, mittehi vaḍḍheyyuṃ, bandhavehi vaḍḍheyyun’ti.**‘How might they flourish in faith, ethics, learning, generosity, teachings, and wisdom; in wealth and grain, fields and land, birds and beasts, children and partners; in bondservants, workers, and staff; in family, friends, and kin?’*";
P_HTM[2781]="*So tassa kammassa kaṭattā … pe …**Due to performing those deeds he was reborn in a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[2782]="*so tato cuto itthattaṃ āgato samāno imāni tīṇi mahāpurisalakkhaṇāni paṭilabhati.**When he came back to this state of existence he obtained these three marks:*";
P_HTM[2783]="*Sīhapubbaddhakāyo ca hoti citantaraṃso ca samavaṭṭakkhandho ca.**his chest is like that of a lion; the gap between the shoulder-blades is filled in; and his torso is cylindrical.*";
P_HTM[2784]="*So tehi lakkhaṇehi samannāgato sace agāraṃ ajjhāvasati, rājā hoti cakkavattī … pe …**Possessing these marks, if he stays at home he becomes a wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[2785]="*rājā samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as king?*";
P_HTM[2786]="*Aparihānadhammo hoti, na parihāyati dhanadhaññena khettavatthunā dvipadacatuppadehi puttadārehi dāsakammakaraporisehi ñātīhi mittehi bandhavehi, na parihāyati sabbasampattiyā.**He’s not liable to decline. He doesn’t decline in wealth and grain, fields and land, birds and beasts, children and partners; in bondservants, workers, and staff; in family, friends, and kin. He doesn’t decline in any of his accomplishments.*";
P_HTM[2787]="*Rājā samāno idaṃ labhati … pe …**That’s what he obtains as king.*";
P_HTM[2788]="*buddho samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as Buddha?*";
P_HTM[2789]="*Aparihānadhammo hoti, na parihāyati saddhāya sīlena sutena cāgena paññāya, na parihāyati sabbasampattiyā.**He’s not liable to decline. He doesn’t decline in faith, ethics, learning, generosity, and wisdom. He doesn’t decline in any of his accomplishments.*";
P_HTM[2790]="*Buddho samāno idaṃ labhati”.**That’s what he obtains as Buddha.”*";
P_HTM[2791]="*Etamatthaṃ bhagavā avoca.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2792]="*Tatthetaṃ vuccati:**On this it is said:*";
P_HTM[2793]="*“Saddhāya sīlena sutena buddhiyā,**“His wish was this: ‘How may others not decline*";
P_HTM[2794]="*Cāgena dhammena bahūhi sādhuhi;**in faith, ethics, learning, and intelligence,*";
P_HTM[2795]="*Dhanena dhaññena ca khettavatthunā,**in generosity, teachings, and much good else,*";
P_HTM[2796]="*Puttehi dārehi catuppadehi ca.**in coin and corn, fields and lands,*";
P_HTM[2797]="*Ñātīhi mittehi ca bandhavehi ca,**in children, partners, and livestock,*";
P_HTM[2798]="*Balena vaṇṇena sukhena cūbhayaṃ;**in family, friends, and kin,*";
P_HTM[2799]="*Kathaṃ na hāyeyyuṃ pareti icchati,**in health, and both beauty and happiness?’*";
P_HTM[2800]="*Atthassa middhī ca panābhikaṅkhati.**And so he ever desired their success.*";
P_HTM[2801]="*Sa sīhapubbaddhasusaṇṭhito ahu,**His chest was full like that of a lion,*";
P_HTM[2802]="*Samavaṭṭakhandho ca citantaraṃso;**his shoulder-gap filled in, and torso cylindrical.*";
P_HTM[2803]="*Pubbe suciṇṇena katena kammunā,**Due to the well-done deeds of the past,*";
P_HTM[2804]="*Ahāniyaṃ pubbanimittamassa taṃ.**he had that portent of non-decline.*";
P_HTM[2805]="*Gihīpi dhaññena dhanena vaḍḍhati,**Even as layman he grows in corn and coin,*";
P_HTM[2806]="*Puttehi dārehi catuppadehi ca;**in wives, children, and livestock.*";
P_HTM[2807]="*Akiñcano pabbajito anuttaraṃ,**But once gone forth, owning nothing, he attains*";
P_HTM[2808]="*Pappoti bodhiṃ asahānadhammatan”ti.**the supreme awakening which may never decline.”*";
P_HTM[2809]="*20. Rasaggasaggitālakkhaṇaṃ**20. Excellent Sense of Taste*";
P_HTM[2810]="*“Yampi, bhikkhave, tathāgato purimaṃ jātiṃ purimaṃ bhavaṃ purimaṃ niketaṃ pubbe manussabhūto samāno**“Mendicants, in some past lives the Realized One was reborn as a human being.*";
P_HTM[2811]="*sattānaṃ aviheṭhakajātiko ahosi pāṇinā vā leḍḍunā vā daṇḍena vā satthena vā.**He would never hurt any sentient being with fists, stones, rods, or swords.*";
P_HTM[2812]="*So tassa kammassa kaṭattā upacitattā … pe …**Due to performing those deeds he was reborn in a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[2813]="*so tato cuto itthattaṃ āgato samāno imaṃ mahāpurisalakkhaṇaṃ paṭilabhati, rasaggasaggī hoti, uddhaggāssa rasaharaṇīyo gīvāya jātā honti samābhivāhiniyo.**When he came back to this state of existence he obtained this mark: he has an excellent sense of taste. Taste-buds are produced in the throat for the tongue-tip and dispersed evenly.*";
P_HTM[2814]="*So tena lakkhaṇena samannāgato sace agāraṃ ajjhāvasati, rājā hoti cakkavattī … pe …**Possessing this mark, if he stays at home he becomes a wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[2815]="*rājā samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as king?*";
P_HTM[2816]="*Appābādho hoti appātaṅko, samavepākiniyā gahaṇiyā samannāgato nātisītāya nāccuṇhāya.**He is rarely ill or unwell. His stomach digests well, being neither too hot nor too cold.*";
P_HTM[2817]="*Rājā samāno idaṃ labhati … pe …**That’s what he obtains as king.*";
P_HTM[2818]="*buddho samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as Buddha?*";
P_HTM[2819]="*Appābādho hoti appātaṅko samavepākiniyā gahaṇiyā samannāgato nātisītāya nāccuṇhāya majjhimāya padhānakkhamāya.**He is rarely ill or unwell. His stomach digests well, being neither too hot nor too cold, but just right, and fit for meditation.*";
P_HTM[2820]="*Buddho samāno idaṃ labhati”.**That’s what he obtains as Buddha.”*";
P_HTM[2821]="*Etamatthaṃ bhagavā avoca.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2822]="*Tatthetaṃ vuccati:**On this it is said:*";
P_HTM[2823]="*“Na pāṇidaṇḍehi panātha leḍḍunā,**“Not with fist or rod or stone,*";
P_HTM[2824]="*Satthena vā maraṇavadhena vā pana;**or sword or beating to death,*";
P_HTM[2825]="*Ubbādhanāya paritajjanāya vā,**or by bondage or threats*";
P_HTM[2826]="*Na heṭhayī janatamaheṭhako ahu.**did he ever harm anyone.*";
P_HTM[2827]="*Teneva so sugatimupecca modati,**For that very reason he rejoiced in heaven after passing away,*";
P_HTM[2828]="*Sukhapphalaṃ kariya sukhāni vindati;**finding happiness as a fruit of happy deeds.*";
P_HTM[2829]="*Samojasā rasaharaṇī susaṇṭhitā,**With taste-buds well formed and even,*";
P_HTM[2830]="*Idhāgato labhati rasaggasaggitaṃ.**on his return here he has an excellent sense of taste.*";
P_HTM[2831]="*Tenāhu naṃ atinipuṇā vicakkhaṇā,**That’s why the clever visionaries said:*";
P_HTM[2832]="*Ayaṃ naro sukhabahulo bhavissati;**‘This man will have much happiness*";
P_HTM[2833]="*Gihissa vā pabbajitassa vā puna,**as householder or renunciate.*";
P_HTM[2834]="*Taṃ lakkhaṇaṃ bhavati tadatthajotakan”ti.**That’s the meaning shown by this mark.’”*";
P_HTM[2835]="*21–22. Abhinīlanettagopakhumalakkhaṇāni**21–22. Deep Blue Eyes*";
P_HTM[2836]="*“Yampi, bhikkhave, tathāgato purimaṃ jātiṃ purimaṃ bhavaṃ purimaṃ niketaṃ pubbe manussabhūto samāno**“Mendicants, in some past lives the Realized One was reborn as a human being.*";
P_HTM[2837]="*na ca visaṭaṃ, na ca visāci, na ca pana viceyya pekkhitā, ujuṃ tathā pasaṭamujumano, piyacakkhunā bahujanaṃ udikkhitā ahosi.**When looking at others he didn’t glare, look askance, or avert his eyes. Being straightforward, he reached out to others with straightforward intentions, looking at people with kindly eyes.*";
P_HTM[2838]="*So tassa kammassa kaṭattā … pe …**Due to performing those deeds he was reborn in a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[2839]="*so tato cuto itthattaṃ āgato samāno imāni dve mahāpurisalakkhaṇāni paṭilabhati.**When he came back to this state of existence he obtained these two marks:*";
P_HTM[2840]="*Abhinīlanetto ca hoti gopakhumo ca.**his eyes are deep blue, and he has eyelashes like a cow’s.*";
P_HTM[2841]="*So tehi lakkhaṇehi samannāgato, sace agāraṃ ajjhāvasati, rājā hoti cakkavattī … pe …**Possessing these marks, if he stays at home he becomes a wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[2842]="*rājā samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as king?*";
P_HTM[2843]="*Piyadassano hoti bahuno janassa, piyo hoti manāpo brāhmaṇagahapatikānaṃ negamajānapadānaṃ gaṇakamahāmattānaṃ anīkaṭṭhānaṃ dovārikānaṃ amaccānaṃ pārisajjānaṃ rājūnaṃ bhogiyānaṃ kumārānaṃ.**The people look on him with kindly eyes. He is dear and beloved to the brahmins and householders, people of town and country, treasury officials, military officers, guardsmen, ministers, counselors, rulers, tax beneficiaries, and princes.*";
P_HTM[2844]="*Rājā samāno idaṃ labhati … pe …**That’s what he obtains as king.*";
P_HTM[2845]="*buddho samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as Buddha?*";
P_HTM[2846]="*Piyadassano hoti bahuno janassa, piyo hoti manāpo bhikkhūnaṃ bhikkhunīnaṃ upāsakānaṃ upāsikānaṃ devānaṃ manussānaṃ asurānaṃ nāgānaṃ gandhabbānaṃ.**The people look on him with kindly eyes. He is dear and beloved to the monks, nuns, laymen, laywomen, gods, humans, demons, dragons, and fairies.*";
P_HTM[2847]="*Buddho samāno idaṃ labhati”.**That’s what he obtains as Buddha.”*";
P_HTM[2848]="*Etamatthaṃ bhagavā avoca.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2849]="*Tatthetaṃ vuccati:**On this it is said:*";
P_HTM[2850]="*“Na ca visaṭaṃ na ca visāci,**“With not a glare or glance askance,*";
P_HTM[2851]="*Na ca pana viceyyapekkhitā;**nor averting of the eyes;*";
P_HTM[2852]="*Ujuṃ tathā pasaṭamujumano,**straightforward, he reached out straightforwardly,*";
P_HTM[2853]="*Piyacakkhunā bahujanaṃ udikkhitā.**looking at people with kindly eyes.*";
P_HTM[2854]="*Sugatīsu so phalavipākaṃ,**In good rebirths he enjoyed the fruit*";
P_HTM[2855]="*Anubhavati tattha modati;**and result, rejoicing there.*";
P_HTM[2856]="*Idha ca pana bhavati gopakhumo,**But here he has a cow’s eyelashes,*";
P_HTM[2857]="*Abhinīlanettanayano sudassano.**and eyes deep blue so fair to see.*";
P_HTM[2858]="*Abhiyogino ca nipuṇā,**Many soothsayers, men clever*";
P_HTM[2859]="*Bahū pana nimittakovidā;**and learned in prognostic texts,*";
P_HTM[2860]="*Sukhumanayanakusalā manujā,**expert in cow-like lashes, indicated he’d*";
P_HTM[2861]="*Piyadassanoti abhiniddisanti naṃ.**be looked upon with kindly eyes.*";
P_HTM[2862]="*Piyadassano gihīpi santo ca,**Even as a householder he’d be regarded kindly,*";
P_HTM[2863]="*Bhavati bahujanapiyāyito;**beloved of the people.*";
P_HTM[2864]="*Yadi ca na bhavati gihī samaṇo hoti,**But if he becomes an ascetic, not lay,*";
P_HTM[2865]="*Piyo bahūnaṃ sokanāsano”ti.**as destroyer of sorrow he’ll be loved by many.”*";
P_HTM[2866]="*23. Uṇhīsasīsalakkhaṇaṃ**23. Head Like a Turban*";
P_HTM[2867]="*“Yampi, bhikkhave, tathāgato purimaṃ jātiṃ purimaṃ bhavaṃ purimaṃ niketaṃ pubbe manussabhūto samāno**“Mendicants, in some past lives the Realized One was reborn as a human being.*";
P_HTM[2868]="*bahujanapubbaṅgamo ahosi kusalesu dhammesu bahujanapāmokkho kāyasucarite vacīsucarite manosucarite dānasaṃvibhāge sīlasamādāne uposathupavāse matteyyatāya petteyyatāya sāmaññatāya brahmaññatāya kule jeṭṭhāpacāyitāya aññataraññataresu ca adhikusalesu dhammesu.**He was the leader and forerunner of people in skillful behaviors such as good conduct by way of body, speech, giving and sharing, taking precepts, observing the sabbath, paying due respect to mother and father, ascetics and brahmins, honoring the elders in the family, and various other things pertaining to skillful behaviors.*";
P_HTM[2869]="*So tassa kammassa kaṭattā … pe …**Due to performing those deeds he was reborn in a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[2870]="*so tato cuto itthattaṃ āgato samāno imaṃ mahāpurisalakkhaṇaṃ paṭilabhati—**When he came back to this state of existence he obtained this mark:*";
P_HTM[2871]="*uṇhīsasīso hoti.**his head is shaped like a turban.*";
P_HTM[2872]="*So tena lakkhaṇena samannāgato sace agāraṃ ajjhāvasati, rājā hoti cakkavattī … pe …**Possessing this mark, if he stays at home he becomes a wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[2873]="*rājā samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as king?*";
P_HTM[2874]="*Mahāssa jano anvāyiko hoti, brāhmaṇagahapatikā negamajānapadā gaṇakamahāmattā anīkaṭṭhā dovārikā amaccā pārisajjā rājāno bhogiyā kumārā.**He has a large following of brahmins and householders, people of town and country, treasury officials, military officers, guardsmen, ministers, counselors, rulers, tax beneficiaries, and princes.*";
P_HTM[2875]="*Rājā samāno idaṃ labhati … pe …**That’s what he obtains as king.*";
P_HTM[2876]="*buddho samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as Buddha?*";
P_HTM[2877]="*Mahāssa jano anvāyiko hoti, bhikkhū bhikkhuniyo upāsakā upāsikāyo devā manussā asurā nāgā gandhabbā.**He has a large following of monks, nuns, laymen, laywomen, gods, humans, demons, dragons, and fairies.*";
P_HTM[2878]="*Buddho samāno idaṃ labhati”.**That’s what he obtains as Buddha.”*";
P_HTM[2879]="*Etamatthaṃ bhagavā avoca.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2880]="*Tatthetaṃ vuccati:**On this it is said:*";
P_HTM[2881]="*“Pubbaṅgamo sucaritesu ahu,**“Among people of good conduct, he was the leader,*";
P_HTM[2882]="*Dhammesu dhammacariyābhirato;**devoted to a life of principle among the principled.*";
P_HTM[2883]="*Anvāyiko bahujanassa ahu,**The people followed him,*";
P_HTM[2884]="*Saggesu vedayittha puññaphalaṃ.**and he experienced the fruit of good deeds in heaven.*";
P_HTM[2885]="*Veditvā so sucaritassa phalaṃ,**Having experienced that fruit,*";
P_HTM[2886]="*Uṇhīsasīsattamidhajjhagamā;**he acquires a head shaped like a turban.*";
P_HTM[2887]="*Byākaṃsu byañjananimittadharā,**The experts in omens and signs prophesied:*";
P_HTM[2888]="*Pubbaṅgamo bahujanaṃ hessati.**‘He will be leader of the people.*";
P_HTM[2889]="*Paṭibhogiyā manujesu idha,**Among people then, as before,*";
P_HTM[2890]="*Pubbeva tassa abhiharanti tadā;**they will bring presents for him.*";
P_HTM[2891]="*Yadi khattiyo bhavati bhūmipati,**If he becomes an aristocrat, ruler of the land,*";
P_HTM[2892]="*Paṭihārakaṃ bahujane labhati.**he’ll gain the service of the people.*";
P_HTM[2893]="*Atha cepi pabbajati so manujo,**But if that man goes forth,*";
P_HTM[2894]="*Dhammesu hoti paguṇo visavī;**he’ll be sophisticated, proficient in the teachings.*";
P_HTM[2895]="*Tassānusāsaniguṇābhirato,**Devoted to the virtues of his instruction,*";
P_HTM[2896]="*Anvāyiko bahujano bhavatī”ti.**the people will become his followers.’”*";
P_HTM[2897]="*24–25. Ekekalomatāuṇṇālakkhaṇāni**24–25. One Hair Per Pore, and a Tuft*";
P_HTM[2898]="*“Yampi, bhikkhave, tathāgato purimaṃ jātiṃ purimaṃ bhavaṃ purimaṃ niketaṃ pubbe manussabhūto samāno**“Mendicants, in some past lives the Realized One was reborn as a human being.*";
P_HTM[2899]="*musāvādaṃ pahāya musāvādā paṭivirato ahosi, saccavādī saccasandho theto paccayiko avisaṃvādako lokassa.**He refrained from lying. He spoke the truth and stuck to the truth. He was honest and trustworthy, and didn’t trick the world with his words.*";
P_HTM[2900]="*So tassa kammassa kaṭattā upacitattā … pe …**Due to performing those deeds he was reborn in a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[2901]="*so tato cuto itthattaṃ āgato samāno imāni dve mahāpurisalakkhaṇāni paṭilabhati.**When he came back to this state of existence he obtained these two marks:*";
P_HTM[2902]="*Ekekalomo ca hoti, uṇṇā ca bhamukantare jātā hoti odātā mudutūlasannibhā.**his hairs grow one per pore, and between his eyebrows there grows a tuft, soft and white like cotton-wool.*";
P_HTM[2903]="*So tehi lakkhaṇehi samannāgato, sace agāraṃ ajjhāvasati, rājā hoti cakkavattī … pe …**Possessing these marks, if he stays at home he becomes a wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[2904]="*rājā samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as king?*";
P_HTM[2905]="*Mahāssa jano upavattati, brāhmaṇagahapatikā negamajānapadā gaṇakamahāmattā anīkaṭṭhā dovārikā amaccā pārisajjā rājāno bhogiyā kumārā.**He has many close adherents among the brahmins and householders, people of town and country, treasury officials, military officers, guardsmen, ministers, counselors, rulers, tax beneficiaries, and princes.*";
P_HTM[2906]="*Rājā samāno idaṃ labhati … pe …**That’s what he obtains as king.*";
P_HTM[2907]="*buddho samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as Buddha?*";
P_HTM[2908]="*Mahāssa jano upavattati, bhikkhū bhikkhuniyo upāsakā upāsikāyo devā manussā asurā nāgā gandhabbā.**He has many close adherents among the monks, nuns, laymen, laywomen, gods, humans, demons, dragons, and fairies.*";
P_HTM[2909]="*Buddho samāno idaṃ labhati”.**That’s what he obtains as Buddha.”*";
P_HTM[2910]="*Etamatthaṃ bhagavā avoca.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2911]="*Tatthetaṃ vuccati:**On this it is said:*";
P_HTM[2912]="*“Saccappaṭiñño purimāsu jātisu,**“In past lives he was true to his promise,*";
P_HTM[2913]="*Advejjhavāco alikaṃ vivajjayi;**with no forked tongue, he shunned lies.*";
P_HTM[2914]="*Na so visaṃvādayitāpi kassaci,**He never broke his word to anyone,*";
P_HTM[2915]="*Bhūtena tacchena tathena bhāsayi.**but spoke what was true, real, and factual.*";
P_HTM[2916]="*Setā susukkā mudutūlasannibhā,**A tuft so very white like cotton-wool*";
P_HTM[2917]="*Uṇṇā sujātā bhamukantare ahu;**grew prettily between his eyebrows.*";
P_HTM[2918]="*Na lomakūpesu duve ajāyisuṃ,**And never two, but only one,*";
P_HTM[2919]="*Ekekalomūpacitaṅgavā ahu.**hair grew in each of his pores.*";
P_HTM[2920]="*Taṃ lakkhaṇaññū bahavo samāgatā,**Many soothsayers learned in marks*";
P_HTM[2921]="*Byākaṃsu uppādanimittakovidā;**and expert in signs gathered and prophesied:*";
P_HTM[2922]="*Uṇṇā ca lomā ca yathā susaṇṭhitā,**‘One like this, with tuft and hair so well-formed,*";
P_HTM[2923]="*Upavattatī īdisakaṃ bahujjano.**will have many as his close adherents.*";
P_HTM[2924]="*Gihimpi santaṃ upavattatī jano,**Even as householder many people will follow him,*";
P_HTM[2925]="*Bahu puratthāpakatena kammunā;**due to the power of deeds in the past.*";
P_HTM[2926]="*Akiñcanaṃ pabbajitaṃ anuttaraṃ,**But once gone forth, owning nothing,*";
P_HTM[2927]="*Buddhampi santaṃ upavattati jano”ti.**as Buddha the people will follow him.’”*";
P_HTM[2928]="*26–27. Cattālīsaaviraḷadantalakkhaṇāni**26–27. Forty Gapless Teeth*";
P_HTM[2929]="*“Yampi, bhikkhave tathāgato purimaṃ jātiṃ purimaṃ bhavaṃ purimaṃ niketaṃ pubbe manussabhūto samāno**“Mendicants, in some past lives the Realized One was reborn as a human being.*";
P_HTM[2930]="*pisuṇaṃ vācaṃ pahāya pisuṇāya vācāya paṭivirato ahosi. Ito sutvā na amutra akkhātā imesaṃ bhedāya, amutra vā sutvā na imesaṃ akkhātā amūsaṃ bhedāya, iti bhinnānaṃ vā sandhātā, sahitānaṃ vā anuppadātā, samaggārāmo samaggarato samagganandī samaggakaraṇiṃ vācaṃ bhāsitā ahosi.**He refrained from divisive speech. He didn’t repeat in one place what he heard in another so as to divide people against each other. Instead, he reconciled those who were divided, supporting unity, delighting in harmony, loving harmony, speaking words that promote harmony.*";
P_HTM[2931]="*So tassa kammassa kaṭattā … pe …**Due to performing those deeds he was reborn in a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[2932]="*so tato cuto itthattaṃ āgato samāno imāni dve mahāpurisalakkhaṇāni paṭilabhati.**When he came back to this state of existence he obtained these two marks:*";
P_HTM[2933]="*Cattālīsadanto ca hoti aviraḷadanto ca.**he has forty teeth, and his teeth have no gaps.*";
P_HTM[2934]="*So tehi lakkhaṇehi samannāgato sace agāraṃ ajjhāvasati, rājā hoti cakkavattī … pe …**Possessing these marks, if he stays at home he becomes a wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[2935]="*rājā samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as king?*";
P_HTM[2936]="*Abhejjapariso hoti, abhejjāssa honti parisā, brāhmaṇagahapatikā negamajānapadā gaṇakamahāmattā anīkaṭṭhā dovārikā amaccā pārisajjā rājāno bhogiyā kumārā.**His retinue cannot be divided. This includes brahmins and householders, people of town and country, treasury officials, military officers, guardsmen, ministers, counselors, rulers, tax beneficiaries, and princes.*";
P_HTM[2937]="*Rājā samāno idaṃ labhati …**That’s what he obtains as king.*";
P_HTM[2938]="*buddho samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as Buddha?*";
P_HTM[2939]="*Abhejjapariso hoti, abhejjāssa honti parisā, bhikkhū bhikkhuniyo upāsakā upāsikāyo devā manussā asurā nāgā gandhabbā.**His retinue cannot be divided. This includes monks, nuns, laymen, laywomen, gods, humans, demons, dragons, and fairies.*";
P_HTM[2940]="*Buddho samāno idaṃ labhati”.**That’s what he obtains as Buddha.”*";
P_HTM[2941]="*Etamatthaṃ bhagavā avoca.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2942]="*Tatthetaṃ vuccati:**On this it is said:*";
P_HTM[2943]="*“Vebhūtiyaṃ sahitabhedakāriṃ,**“He spoke no untruth causing friends to split,*";
P_HTM[2944]="*Bhedappavaḍḍhanavivādakāriṃ;**creating disputes that foster division,*";
P_HTM[2945]="*Kalahappavaḍḍhanaākiccakāriṃ,**acting improperly by fostering quarrels,*";
P_HTM[2946]="*Sahitānaṃ bhedajananiṃ na bhaṇi.**creating division among friends.*";
P_HTM[2947]="*Avivādavaḍḍhanakariṃ sugiraṃ,**He spoke kind words to foster harmony,*";
P_HTM[2948]="*Bhinnānusandhijananiṃ abhaṇi;**uniting those who are divided.*";
P_HTM[2949]="*Kalahaṃ janassa panudī samaṅgī,**He eliminated quarrels among the people,*";
P_HTM[2950]="*Sahitehi nandati pamodati ca.**rejoicing together with the united.*";
P_HTM[2951]="*Sugatīsu so phalavipākaṃ,**In good rebirths he enjoyed the fruit*";
P_HTM[2952]="*Anubhavati tattha modati;**and result, rejoicing there.*";
P_HTM[2953]="*Dantā idha honti aviraḷā sahitā,**Here his teeth are gapless, close together,*";
P_HTM[2954]="*Caturo dasassa mukhajā susaṇṭhitā.**forty standing upright in his mouth.*";
P_HTM[2955]="*Yadi khattiyo bhavati bhūmipati,**If he becomes an aristocrat, ruler of the land,*";
P_HTM[2956]="*Avibhediyāssa parisā bhavati;**his assembly will be indivisible.*";
P_HTM[2957]="*Samaṇo ca hoti virajo vimalo,**And as an ascetic, stainless, immaculate,*";
P_HTM[2958]="*Parisāssa hoti anugatā acalā”ti.**his assembly will follow him, unshakable.”*";
P_HTM[2959]="*28–29. Pahūtajivhābrahmassaralakkhaṇāni**28–29. A Large Tongue and the Voice of Brahmā*";
P_HTM[2960]="*“Yampi, bhikkhave, tathāgato purimaṃ jātiṃ purimaṃ bhavaṃ purimaṃ niketaṃ pubbe manussabhūto samāno**“Mendicants, in some past lives the Realized One was reborn as a human being.*";
P_HTM[2961]="*pharusaṃ vācaṃ pahāya pharusāya vācāya paṭivirato ahosi. Yā sā vācā nelā kaṇṇasukhā pemanīyā hadayaṅgamā porī bahujanakantā bahujanamanāpā, tathārūpiṃ vācaṃ bhāsitā ahosi.**He refrained from harsh speech. He spoke in a way that’s mellow, pleasing to the ear, lovely, going to the heart, polite, likable and agreeable to the people.*";
P_HTM[2962]="*So tassa kammassa kaṭattā upacitattā … pe …**Due to performing those deeds he was reborn in a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[2963]="*so tato cuto itthattaṃ āgato samāno imāni dve mahāpurisalakkhaṇāni paṭilabhati.**When he came back to this state of existence he obtained these two marks:*";
P_HTM[2964]="*Pahūtajivho ca hoti brahmassaro ca karavīkabhāṇī.**he has a large tongue, and the voice of Brahmā, like a cuckoo’s call.*";
P_HTM[2965]="*So tehi lakkhaṇehi samannāgato sace agāraṃ ajjhāvasati, rājā hoti cakkavattī … pe …**Possessing these marks, if he stays at home he becomes a wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[2966]="*rājā samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as king?*";
P_HTM[2967]="*Ādeyyavāco hoti, ādiyantissa vacanaṃ brāhmaṇagahapatikā negamajānapadā gaṇakamahāmattā anīkaṭṭhā dovārikā amaccā pārisajjā rājāno bhogiyā kumārā.**He has a persuasive voice. His words are persuasive to brahmins and householders, people of town and country, treasury officials, military officers, guardsmen, ministers, counselors, rulers, tax beneficiaries, and princes.*";
P_HTM[2968]="*Rājā samāno idaṃ labhati … pe …**That’s what he obtains as king.*";
P_HTM[2969]="*buddho samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as Buddha?*";
P_HTM[2970]="*Ādeyyavāco hoti, ādiyantissa vacanaṃ bhikkhū bhikkhuniyo upāsakā upāsikāyo devā manussā asurā nāgā gandhabbā.**He has a persuasive voice. His words are persuasive to monks, nuns, laymen, laywomen, gods, humans, demons, dragons, and fairies.*";
P_HTM[2971]="*Buddho samāno idaṃ labhati”.**That’s what he obtains as Buddha.”*";
P_HTM[2972]="*Etamatthaṃ bhagavā avoca.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2973]="*Tatthetaṃ vuccati:**On this it is said:*";
P_HTM[2974]="*“Akkosabhaṇḍanavihesakāriṃ,**“He never spoke a loud harsh word,*";
P_HTM[2975]="*Ubbādhikaṃ bahujanappamaddanaṃ;**insulting, quarrelsome,*";
P_HTM[2976]="*Abāḷhaṃ giraṃ so na bhaṇi pharusaṃ,**causing harm, rude, crushing the people.*";
P_HTM[2977]="*Madhuraṃ bhaṇi susaṃhitaṃ sakhilaṃ.**His speech was sweet, helpful, and kind.*";
P_HTM[2978]="*Manaso piyā hadayagāminiyo,**He uttered words dear to the mind,*";
P_HTM[2979]="*Vācā so erayati kaṇṇasukhā;**going to the heart, pleasing to the ear.*";
P_HTM[2980]="*Vācāsuciṇṇaphalamanubhavi,**He enjoyed the fruit of his good verbal conduct,*";
P_HTM[2981]="*Saggesu vedayatha puññaphalaṃ.**experiencing the fruit of good deeds in heaven.*";
P_HTM[2982]="*Veditvā so sucaritassa phalaṃ,**Having experienced that fruit,*";
P_HTM[2983]="*Brahmassarattamidhamajjhagamā;**on his return to here he acquired the voice of Brahmā.*";
P_HTM[2984]="*Jivhāssa hoti vipulā puthulā,**His tongue was long and wide,*";
P_HTM[2985]="*Ādeyyavākyavacano bhavati.**and his speech was persuasive.*";
P_HTM[2986]="*Gihinopi ijjhati yathā bhaṇato,**Even as householder his speech brings prosperity.*";
P_HTM[2987]="*Atha ce pabbajati so manujo;**But if that man goes forth,*";
P_HTM[2988]="*Ādiyantissa vacanaṃ janatā,**speaking often to the people,*";
P_HTM[2989]="*Bahuno bahuṃ subhaṇitaṃ bhaṇato”ti.**they’ll be persuaded by his fair words.”*";
P_HTM[2990]="*30. Sīhahanulakkhaṇaṃ**30. A Lion-Like Jaw*";
P_HTM[2991]="*“Yampi, bhikkhave, tathāgato purimaṃ jātiṃ purimaṃ bhavaṃ purimaṃ niketaṃ pubbe manussabhūto samāno**“Mendicants, in some past lives the Realized One was reborn as a human being.*";
P_HTM[2992]="*samphappalāpaṃ pahāya samphappalāpā paṭivirato ahosi kālavādī bhūtavādī atthavādī dhammavādī vinayavādī, nidhānavatiṃ vācaṃ bhāsitā ahosi kālena sāpadesaṃ pariyantavatiṃ atthasaṃhitaṃ.**He refrained from talking nonsense. His words were timely, true, and meaningful, in line with the teaching and training. He said things at the right time which were valuable, reasonable, succinct, and beneficial.*";
P_HTM[2993]="*So tassa kammassa kaṭattā … pe …**Due to performing those deeds he was reborn in a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[2994]="*so tato cuto itthattaṃ āgato samāno imaṃ mahāpurisalakkhaṇaṃ paṭilabhati,**When he came back to this state of existence he obtained this mark:*";
P_HTM[2995]="*sīhahanu hoti.**his jaw is like that of a lion.*";
P_HTM[2996]="*So tena lakkhaṇena samannāgato sace agāraṃ ajjhāvasati, rājā hoti cakkavattī … pe …**Possessing this mark, if he stays at home he becomes a wheel-turning monarch.*";
P_HTM[2997]="*rājā samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as king?*";
P_HTM[2998]="*Appadhaṃsiyo hoti kenaci manussabhūtena paccatthikena paccāmittena.**He can’t be destroyed by any human foe or enemy.*";
P_HTM[2999]="*Rājā samāno idaṃ labhati … pe …**That’s what he obtains as king.*";
P_HTM[3000]="*buddho samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as Buddha?*";
P_HTM[3001]="*Appadhaṃsiyo hoti abbhantarehi vā bāhirehi vā paccatthikehi paccāmittehi, rāgena vā dosena vā mohena vā samaṇena vā brāhmaṇena vā devena vā mārena vā brahmunā vā kenaci vā lokasmiṃ.**He can’t be destroyed by any foe or enemy whether internal or external; nor by greed, hate, or delusion; nor by any ascetic or brahmin or god or Māra or Brahmā or by anyone in the world.*";
P_HTM[3002]="*Buddho samāno idaṃ labhati”.**That’s what he obtains as Buddha.”*";
P_HTM[3003]="*Etamatthaṃ bhagavā avoca.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[3004]="*Tatthetaṃ vuccati:**On this it is said:*";
P_HTM[3005]="*“Na samphappalāpaṃ na muddhataṃ,**“Neither nonsensical nor silly,*";
P_HTM[3006]="*Avikiṇṇavacanabyappatho ahosi;**his way of speaking was never loose.*";
P_HTM[3007]="*Ahitamapi ca apanudi,**He eliminated what was useless,*";
P_HTM[3008]="*Hitamapi ca bahujanasukhañca abhaṇi.**and spoke for the welfare and happiness of the people.*";
P_HTM[3009]="*Taṃ katvā ito cuto divamupapajji,**So doing he passed from here to be reborn in heaven,*";
P_HTM[3010]="*Sukataphalavipākamanubhosi;**where he enjoyed the fruit of deeds well done.*";
P_HTM[3011]="*Caviya punaridhāgato samāno,**Passing away, on his return to here,*";
P_HTM[3012]="*Dvidugamavaratarahanuttamalattha.**he gained a jaw like the finest of beasts.*";
P_HTM[3013]="*Rājā hoti suduppadhaṃsiyo,**He became a king so very hard to defeat,*";
P_HTM[3014]="*Manujindo manujādhipati mahānubhāvo;**a mighty lord and ruler of men.*";
P_HTM[3015]="*Tidivapuravarasamo bhavati,**He was equal to the best in the city of the Three and Thirty,*";
P_HTM[3016]="*Suravarataroriva indo.**like Inda, the finest of gods.*";
P_HTM[3017]="*Gandhabbāsurayakkharakkhasebhi,**One such as that is not easily beaten by fairies,*";
P_HTM[3018]="*Surehi na hi bhavati suppadhaṃsiyo;**demons, spirits, monsters, or gods.*";
P_HTM[3019]="*Tathatto yadi bhavati tathāvidho,**If he becomes of such a kind,*";
P_HTM[3020]="*Idha disā ca paṭidisā ca vidisā cā”ti.**he illuminates the quarters and in-between.”*";
P_HTM[3021]="*31–32. Samadantasusukkadāṭhālakkhaṇāni**31–32. Even and White Teeth*";
P_HTM[3022]="*“Yampi, bhikkhave, tathāgato purimaṃ jātiṃ purimaṃ bhavaṃ purimaṃ niketaṃ pubbe manussabhūto samāno**“Mendicants, in some past lives the Realized One was reborn as a human being.*";
P_HTM[3023]="*micchājīvaṃ pahāya sammāājīvena jīvikaṃ kappesi, tulākūṭakaṃsakūṭamānakūṭaukkoṭanavañcananikatisāciyogachedanavadhabandhanaviparāmosaālopasahasākārā paṭivirato ahosi.**He gave up wrong livelihood and earned a living by right livelihood. He refrained from falsifying weights, metals, or measures; bribery, fraud, cheating, and duplicity; mutilation, murder, abduction, banditry, plunder, and violence.*";
P_HTM[3024]="*So tassa kammassa kaṭattā upacitattā ussannattā vipulattā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati.**Due to performing, accumulating, heaping up, and amassing those deeds, when his body broke up, after death, he was reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[3025]="*So tattha aññe deve dasahi ṭhānehi adhigaṇhāti dibbena āyunā dibbena vaṇṇena dibbena sukhena dibbena yasena dibbena ādhipateyyena dibbehi rūpehi dibbehi saddehi dibbehi gandhehi dibbehi rasehi dibbehi phoṭṭhabbehi.**There he surpassed the other gods in ten respects: divine life span, beauty, happiness, glory, sovereignty, sights, sounds, smells, tastes, and touches.*";
P_HTM[3026]="*So tato cuto itthattaṃ āgato samāno imāni dve mahāpurisalakkhaṇāni paṭilabhati, samadanto ca hoti susukkadāṭho ca.**When he came back to this state of existence he obtained these two marks: his teeth are even and perfectly white.*";
P_HTM[3027]="*So tehi lakkhaṇehi samannāgato sace agāraṃ ajjhāvasati, rājā hoti cakkavattī dhammiko dhammarājā cāturanto vijitāvī janapadatthāvariyappatto sattaratanasamannāgato.**Possessing these marks, if he stays at home he becomes a king, a wheel-turning monarch, a just and principled king. His dominion extends to all four sides, he achieves stability in the country, and he possesses the seven treasures.*";
P_HTM[3028]="*Tassimāni satta ratanāni bhavanti, seyyathidaṃ—**He has the following seven treasures:*";
P_HTM[3029]="*cakkaratanaṃ hatthiratanaṃ assaratanaṃ maṇiratanaṃ itthiratanaṃ gahapatiratanaṃ pariṇāyakaratanameva sattamaṃ.**the wheel, the elephant, the horse, the jewel, the woman, the treasurer, and the counselor as the seventh treasure.*";
P_HTM[3030]="*Parosahassaṃ kho panassa puttā bhavanti sūrā vīraṅgarūpā parasenappamaddanā.**He has over a thousand sons who are valiant and heroic, crushing the armies of his enemies.*";
P_HTM[3031]="*So imaṃ pathaviṃ sāgarapariyantaṃ akhilamanimittamakaṇṭakaṃ iddhaṃ phītaṃ khemaṃ sivaṃ nirabbudaṃ adaṇḍena asatthena dhammena abhivijiya ajjhāvasati.**After conquering this land girt by sea—free of harassment by bandits, successful and prosperous, safe, blessed, and untroubled—he reigns by principle, without rod or sword.*";
P_HTM[3032]="*Rājā samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as king?*";
P_HTM[3033]="*Suciparivāro hoti sucissa honti parivārā brāhmaṇagahapatikā negamajānapadā gaṇakamahāmattā anīkaṭṭhā dovārikā amaccā pārisajjā rājāno bhogiyā kumārā.**His retinue is pure. This includes brahmins and householders, people of town and country, treasury officials, military officers, guardsmen, ministers, counselors, rulers, tax beneficiaries, and princes.*";
P_HTM[3034]="*Rājā samāno idaṃ labhati.**That’s what he obtains as king.*";
P_HTM[3035]="*Sace kho pana agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajati, arahaṃ hoti sammāsambuddho loke vivaṭṭacchado.**But if he goes forth from the lay life to homelessness, he becomes a perfected one, a fully awakened Buddha, who draws back the veil from the world.*";
P_HTM[3036]="*Buddho samāno kiṃ labhati?**And what does he obtain as Buddha?*";
P_HTM[3037]="*Suciparivāro hoti, sucissa honti parivārā, bhikkhū bhikkhuniyo upāsakā upāsikāyo devā manussā asurā nāgā gandhabbā.**His retinue is pure. This includes monks, nuns, laymen, laywomen, gods, humans, demons, dragons, and fairies.*";
P_HTM[3038]="*Buddho samāno idaṃ labhati”.**That’s what he obtains as Buddha.”*";
P_HTM[3039]="*Etamatthaṃ bhagavā avoca.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[3040]="*Tatthetaṃ vuccati:**On this it is said:*";
P_HTM[3041]="*“Micchājīvañca avassaji samena vuttiṃ,**“He abandoned wrong livelihood, and created*";
P_HTM[3042]="*Sucinā so janayittha dhammikena;**a way of life that’s fair, pure, and just.*";
P_HTM[3043]="*Ahitamapi ca apanudi,**He eliminated what was useless,*";
P_HTM[3044]="*Hitamapi ca bahujanasukhañca acari.**and lived for the welfare and happiness of the people.*";
P_HTM[3045]="*Sagge vedayati naro sukhapphalāni,**Having done what’s praised by the clever, the wise, and the good,*";
P_HTM[3046]="*Karitvā nipuṇebhi vidūhi sabbhi;**that man experienced the fruit in heaven.*";
P_HTM[3047]="*Vaṇṇitāni tidivapuravarasamo,**Equal to the best in the heaven of Three and Thirty,*";
P_HTM[3048]="*Abhiramati ratikhiḍḍāsamaṅgī.**he enjoyed himself with pleasure and play.*";
P_HTM[3049]="*Laddhāna mānusakaṃ bhavaṃ tato,**From there he passed back to a human life.*";
P_HTM[3050]="*Cavitvāna sukataphalavipākaṃ;**With the remaining ripening of the fruit of good deeds,*";
P_HTM[3051]="*Sesakena paṭilabhati lapanajaṃ,**he obtained teeth that are even,*";
P_HTM[3052]="*Samamapi sucisusukkaṃ.**gleaming, bright, and white.*";
P_HTM[3053]="*Taṃ veyyañjanikā samāgatā bahavo,**Many soothsayers regarded as wise men*";
P_HTM[3054]="*Byākaṃsu nipuṇasammatā manujā;**gathered and predicted of him:*";
P_HTM[3055]="*Sucijanaparivāragaṇo bhavati,**‘With twice-born teeth so even, so white, so clean and bright*";
P_HTM[3056]="*Dijasamasukkasucisobhanadanto.**his retinue will be so pure.*";
P_HTM[3057]="*Rañño hoti bahujano,**As king, his people will also be pure,*";
P_HTM[3058]="*Suciparivāro mahatiṃ mahiṃ anusāsato;**when he rules having conquered this earth so broad.*";
P_HTM[3059]="*Pasayha na ca janapadatudanaṃ,**They won’t harm the country,*";
P_HTM[3060]="*Hitamapi ca bahujanasukhañca caranti.**but will live for the welfare and happiness of the people.*";
P_HTM[3061]="*Atha ce pabbajati bhavati vipāpo,**But if he goes forth he’ll be an ascetic free of ill,*";
P_HTM[3062]="*Samaṇo samitarajo vivaṭṭacchado;**his passions quelled, the veil drawn back.*";
P_HTM[3063]="*Vigatadarathakilamatho,**Rid of stress and weariness,*";
P_HTM[3064]="*Imamapi ca paramapi ca passati lokaṃ.**he sees this world and the next.*";
P_HTM[3065]="*Tassovādakarā bahugihī ca pabbajitā ca,**Those who do his bidding, both lay and renunciate,*";
P_HTM[3066]="*Asuciṃ garahitaṃ dhunanti pāpaṃ;**shake off wickedness, impure and blameworthy.*";
P_HTM[3067]="*Sa hi sucibhi parivuto bhavati,**He’s surrounded by pure people, who dispel*";
P_HTM[3068]="*Malakhilakalikilese panudehī”ti.**stains, callousness, sin, and corruptions.’”*";
P_HTM[3069]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[3070]="*Attamanā te bhikkhū bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, the mendicants were happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[3071]="*Lakkhaṇasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3072]="*31. Siṅgālasutta  - Advice to Sigālaka * **";
P_HTM[3073]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[3074]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā rājagahe viharati veḷuvane kalandakanivāpe.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Rājagaha, in the Bamboo Grove, the squirrels’ feeding ground.*";
P_HTM[3075]="*Tena kho pana samayena siṅgālako gahapatiputto kālasseva uṭṭhāya rājagahā nikkhamitvā allavattho allakeso pañjaliko puthudisā namassati—**Now at that time the householder’s son Sigālaka rose early and left Rājagaha. With his clothes and hair all wet, he raised his joined palms to revere the quarters—*";
P_HTM[3076]="*puratthimaṃ disaṃ dakkhiṇaṃ disaṃ pacchimaṃ disaṃ uttaraṃ disaṃ heṭṭhimaṃ disaṃ uparimaṃ disaṃ.**east, south, west, north, below, and above.*";
P_HTM[3077]="*Atha kho bhagavā pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya rājagahaṃ piṇḍāya pāvisi.**Then the Buddha robed up in the morning and, taking his bowl and robe, entered Rājagaha for alms.*";
P_HTM[3078]="*Addasā kho bhagavā siṅgālakaṃ gahapatiputtaṃ kālasseva vuṭṭhāya rājagahā nikkhamitvā allavatthaṃ allakesaṃ pañjalikaṃ puthudisā namassantaṃ—**He saw Sigālaka revering the quarters*";
P_HTM[3079]="*puratthimaṃ disaṃ dakkhiṇaṃ disaṃ pacchimaṃ disaṃ uttaraṃ disaṃ heṭṭhimaṃ disaṃ uparimaṃ disaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3080]="*Disvā siṅgālakaṃ gahapatiputtaṃ etadavoca:**and said to him,*";
P_HTM[3081]="*“kiṃ nu kho tvaṃ, gahapatiputta, kālasseva vuṭṭhāya rājagahā nikkhamitvā allavattho allakeso pañjaliko puthudisā namassasi—**“Householder’s son, why are you revering the quarters in this way?”*";
P_HTM[3082]="*puratthimaṃ disaṃ dakkhiṇaṃ disaṃ pacchimaṃ disaṃ uttaraṃ disaṃ heṭṭhimaṃ disaṃ uparimaṃ disan”ti?* **";
P_HTM[3083]="*“Pitā maṃ, bhante, kālaṃ karonto evaṃ avaca:**“Sir, on his deathbed my father said to me:*";
P_HTM[3084]="*‘disā, tāta, namasseyyāsī’ti.**‘My dear, please revere the quarters.’*";
P_HTM[3085]="*So kho ahaṃ, bhante, pituvacanaṃ sakkaronto garuṃ karonto mānento pūjento kālasseva uṭṭhāya rājagahā nikkhamitvā allavattho allakeso pañjaliko puthudisā namassāmi—**Honoring, respecting, and venerating my father’s words, I rose early and left Rājagaha and, with my clothes and hair all wet, raised my joined palms to revere the quarters—*";
P_HTM[3086]="*puratthimaṃ disaṃ dakkhiṇaṃ disaṃ pacchimaṃ disaṃ uttaraṃ disaṃ heṭṭhimaṃ disaṃ uparimaṃ disan”ti.**east, south, west, north, below, and above.”*";
P_HTM[3087]="*1. Cha disā**1. The Six Quarters*";
P_HTM[3088]="*“Na kho, gahapatiputta, ariyassa vinaye evaṃ cha disā namassitabbā”ti.**“Householder’s son, that’s not how the six quarters should be revered in the training of the noble one.”*";
P_HTM[3089]="*“Yathā kathaṃ pana, bhante, ariyassa vinaye cha disā namassitabbā?**“But sir, how should the six quarters be revered in the training of the noble one?*";
P_HTM[3090]="*Sādhu me, bhante, bhagavā tathā dhammaṃ desetu, yathā ariyassa vinaye cha disā namassitabbā”ti.**Sir, please teach me this.”*";
P_HTM[3091]="*“Tena hi, gahapatiputta, suṇohi sādhukaṃ manasikarohi bhāsissāmī”ti.**“Well then, householder’s son, listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[3092]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho siṅgālako gahapatiputto bhagavato paccassosi.**“Yes, sir,” replied Sigālaka.*";
P_HTM[3093]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[3094]="*“Yato kho, gahapatiputta, ariyasāvakassa cattāro kammakilesā pahīnā honti, catūhi ca ṭhānehi pāpakammaṃ na karoti, cha ca bhogānaṃ apāyamukhāni na sevati, so evaṃ cuddasa pāpakāpagato chaddisāpaṭicchādī**“Householder’s son, a noble disciple gives up four corrupt deeds, doesn’t do bad deeds on four grounds, and avoids six drains on wealth. When they’ve left these fourteen bad things behind they have the six quarters covered.*";
P_HTM[3095]="*ubholokavijayāya paṭipanno hoti. Tassa ayañceva loko āraddho hoti paro ca loko.**They’re practicing to win in both worlds, and they succeed in this world and the next.*";
P_HTM[3096]="*So kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati.**When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[3097]="*2. Cattāro kammakilesā**2. Four Corrupt Deeds*";
P_HTM[3098]="*Katamassa cattāro kammakilesā pahīnā honti?**What four corrupt deeds have they given up?*";
P_HTM[3099]="*Pāṇātipāto kho, gahapatiputta, kammakileso, adinnādānaṃ kammakileso, kāmesumicchācāro kammakileso, musāvādo kammakileso.**Killing living creatures, stealing, sexual misconduct, and lying: these are corrupt deeds.*";
P_HTM[3100]="*Imassa cattāro kammakilesā pahīnā hontī”ti.**These are the four corrupt deeds they’ve given up.”*";
P_HTM[3101]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[3102]="*Idaṃ vatvāna sugato athāparaṃ etadavoca satthā:**Then the Holy One, the Teacher, went on to say:*";
P_HTM[3103]="*“Pāṇātipāto adinnādānaṃ,**“Killing, stealing,*";
P_HTM[3104]="*Musāvādo ca vuccati;**telling lies,*";
P_HTM[3105]="*Paradāragamanañceva,**and committing adultery:*";
P_HTM[3106]="*Nappasaṃsanti paṇḍitā”ti.**astute people don’t praise these things.”*";
P_HTM[3107]="*3. Catuṭhānaṃ**3. Four Grounds*";
P_HTM[3108]="*“Katamehi catūhi ṭhānehi pāpakammaṃ na karoti?**“On what four grounds do they not do bad deeds?*";
P_HTM[3109]="*Chandāgatiṃ gacchanto pāpakammaṃ karoti, dosāgatiṃ gacchanto pāpakammaṃ karoti, mohāgatiṃ gacchanto pāpakammaṃ karoti, bhayāgatiṃ gacchanto pāpakammaṃ karoti.**One does bad deeds prejudiced by favoritism, hostility, stupidity, and cowardice.*";
P_HTM[3110]="*Yato kho, gahapatiputta, ariyasāvako neva chandāgatiṃ gacchati, na dosāgatiṃ gacchati, na mohāgatiṃ gacchati, na bhayāgatiṃ gacchati;**When a noble disciple is not prejudiced by favoritism, hostility, stupidity, and cowardice,*";
P_HTM[3111]="*imehi catūhi ṭhānehi pāpakammaṃ na karotī”ti.**they don’t do bad deeds on these four grounds.”*";
P_HTM[3112]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[3113]="*Idaṃ vatvāna sugato athāparaṃ etadavoca satthā:**Then the Holy One, the Teacher, went on to say:*";
P_HTM[3114]="*“Chandā dosā bhayā mohā,**“If you act against the teaching*";
P_HTM[3115]="*yo dhammaṃ ativattati;**out of favoritism, hostility, cowardice, or stupidity,*";
P_HTM[3116]="*Nihīyati yaso tassa,**your fame shrinks,*";
P_HTM[3117]="*kāḷapakkheva candimā.**like the moon in the waning fortnight.*";
P_HTM[3118]="*Chandā dosā bhayā mohā,**If you don’t act against the teaching*";
P_HTM[3119]="*yo dhammaṃ nātivattati;**out of favoritism, hostility, cowardice, and stupidity,*";
P_HTM[3120]="*Āpūrati yaso tassa,**your fame swells,*";
P_HTM[3121]="*sukkapakkheva candimā”ti.**like the moon in the waxing fortnight.”*";
P_HTM[3122]="*4. Cha apāyamukhāni**4. Six Drains on Wealth*";
P_HTM[3123]="*“Katamāni cha bhogānaṃ apāyamukhāni na sevati?**“What six drains on wealth do they avoid?*";
P_HTM[3124]="*Surāmerayamajjappamādaṭṭhānānuyogo kho, gahapatiputta, bhogānaṃ apāyamukhaṃ, vikālavisikhācariyānuyogo bhogānaṃ apāyamukhaṃ, samajjābhicaraṇaṃ bhogānaṃ apāyamukhaṃ, jūtappamādaṭṭhānānuyogo bhogānaṃ apāyamukhaṃ, pāpamittānuyogo bhogānaṃ apāyamukhaṃ, ālasyānuyogo bhogānaṃ apāyamukhaṃ.**Habitually engaging in the following things is a drain on wealth: drinking alcohol; roaming the streets at night; frequenting festivals; gambling; bad friends; laziness.*";
P_HTM[3125]="*5. Surāmerayassa cha ādīnavā**5. Six Drawbacks of Drinking*";
P_HTM[3126]="*Cha khome, gahapatiputta, ādīnavā surāmerayamajjappamādaṭṭhānānuyoge.**There are these six drawbacks of habitually drinking alcohol.*";
P_HTM[3127]="*Sandiṭṭhikā dhanajāni, kalahappavaḍḍhanī, rogānaṃ āyatanaṃ, akittisañjananī, kopīnanidaṃsanī, paññāya dubbalikaraṇītveva chaṭṭhaṃ padaṃ bhavati.**Immediate loss of wealth, promotion of quarrels, susceptibility to illness, disrepute, indecent exposure; and weakened wisdom is the sixth thing.*";
P_HTM[3128]="*Ime kho, gahapatiputta, cha ādīnavā surāmerayamajjappamādaṭṭhānānuyoge.**These are the six drawbacks of habitually drinking alcohol.*";
P_HTM[3129]="*6. Vikālacariyāya cha ādīnavā**6. Six Drawbacks of Roaming the Streets at Night*";
P_HTM[3130]="*Cha khome, gahapatiputta, ādīnavā vikālavisikhācariyānuyoge.**There are these six drawbacks of roaming the streets at night.*";
P_HTM[3131]="*Attāpissa agutto arakkhito hoti, puttadāropissa agutto arakkhito hoti, sāpateyyampissa aguttaṃ arakkhitaṃ hoti, saṅkiyo ca hoti pāpakesu ṭhānesu, abhūtavacanañca tasmiṃ rūhati, bahūnañca dukkhadhammānaṃ purakkhato hoti.**Yourself, your partners and children, and your property are all left unguarded. You’re suspected of bad deeds. Untrue rumors spread about you. You’re at the forefront of many things that entail suffering.*";
P_HTM[3132]="*Ime kho, gahapatiputta, cha ādīnavā vikālavisikhācariyānuyoge.**These are the six drawbacks of roaming the streets at night.*";
P_HTM[3133]="*7. Samajjābhicaraṇassa cha ādīnavā**7. Six Drawbacks of Festivals*";
P_HTM[3134]="*Cha khome, gahapatiputta, ādīnavā samajjābhicaraṇe.**There are these six drawbacks of frequenting festivals.*";
P_HTM[3135]="*Kva naccaṃ, kva gītaṃ, kva vāditaṃ, kva akkhānaṃ, kva pāṇissaraṃ, kva kumbhathunanti.**You’re always thinking: ‘Where’s the dancing? Where’s the singing? Where’s the music? Where are the stories? Where’s the applause? Where are the kettle-drums?’*";
P_HTM[3136]="*Ime kho, gahapatiputta, cha ādīnavā samajjābhicaraṇe.**These are the six drawbacks of frequenting festivals.*";
P_HTM[3137]="*8. Jūtappamādassa cha ādīnavā**8. Six Drawbacks of Gambling*";
P_HTM[3138]="*Cha khome, gahapatiputta, ādīnavā jūtappamādaṭṭhānānuyoge.**There are these six drawbacks of habitually gambling.*";
P_HTM[3139]="*Jayaṃ veraṃ pasavati, jino vittamanusocati, sandiṭṭhikā dhanajāni, sabhāgatassa vacanaṃ na rūhati, mittāmaccānaṃ paribhūto hoti, āvāhavivāhakānaṃ apatthito hoti:**Victory breeds enmity. The loser mourns their money. There is immediate loss of wealth. A gambler’s word carries no weight in public assembly. Friends and colleagues treat them with contempt. And no-one wants to marry a gambler, for they think:*";
P_HTM[3140]="*‘akkhadhutto ayaṃ purisapuggalo nālaṃ dārabharaṇāyā’ti.**‘This individual is a gambler—they’re not able to support a partner.’*";
P_HTM[3141]="*Ime kho, gahapatiputta, cha ādīnavā jūtappamādaṭṭhānānuyoge.**These are the six drawbacks of habitually gambling.*";
P_HTM[3142]="*9. Pāpamittatāya cha ādīnavā**9. Six Drawbacks of Bad Friends*";
P_HTM[3143]="*Cha khome, gahapatiputta, ādīnavā pāpamittānuyoge.**There are these six drawbacks of bad friends.*";
P_HTM[3144]="*Ye dhuttā, ye soṇḍā, ye pipāsā, ye nekatikā, ye vañcanikā, ye sāhasikā. Tyāssa mittā honti te sahāyā.**You become friends and companions with those who are scoundrels, drunkards, addicts, frauds, swindlers, and thugs.*";
P_HTM[3145]="*Ime kho, gahapatiputta, cha ādīnavā pāpamittānuyoge.**These are the six drawbacks of bad friends.*";
P_HTM[3146]="*10. Ālasyassa cha ādīnavā**10. Six Drawbacks of Laziness*";
P_HTM[3147]="*Cha khome, gahapatiputta, ādīnavā ālasyānuyoge.**There are these six drawbacks of habitual laziness.*";
P_HTM[3148]="*Atisītanti kammaṃ na karoti, atiuṇhanti kammaṃ na karoti, atisāyanti kammaṃ na karoti, atipātoti kammaṃ na karoti, atichātosmīti kammaṃ na karoti, atidhātosmīti kammaṃ na karoti.**You don’t get your work done because you think: ‘It’s too cold! It’s too hot. It’s too late! It’s too early! I’m too hungry! I’m too full!’*";
P_HTM[3149]="*Tassa evaṃ kiccāpadesabahulassa viharato anuppannā ceva bhogā nuppajjanti, uppannā ca bhogā parikkhayaṃ gacchanti.**By dwelling on so many excuses for not working, you don’t make any more money, and the money you already have runs out.*";
P_HTM[3150]="*Ime kho, gahapatiputta, cha ādīnavā ālasyānuyoge”ti.**These are the six drawbacks of habitual laziness.”*";
P_HTM[3151]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[3152]="*Idaṃ vatvāna sugato athāparaṃ etadavoca satthā:**Then the Holy One, the Teacher, went on to say:*";
P_HTM[3153]="*“Hoti pānasakhā nāma,**“Some are just drinking buddies,*";
P_HTM[3154]="*hoti sammiyasammiyo;**some call you their dear, dear friend,*";
P_HTM[3155]="*Yo ca atthesu jātesu,**but a true friend is one*";
P_HTM[3156]="*sahāyo hoti so sakhā.**who stands by you in need.*";
P_HTM[3157]="*Ussūraseyyā paradārasevanā,**Sleeping late, adultery,*";
P_HTM[3158]="*Verappasavo ca anatthatā ca;**making enemies, harmfulness,*";
P_HTM[3159]="*Pāpā ca mittā sukadariyatā ca,**bad friends, and avarice:*";
P_HTM[3160]="*Ete cha ṭhānā purisaṃ dhaṃsayanti.**these six grounds ruin a person.*";
P_HTM[3161]="*Pāpamitto pāpasakho,**With bad friends, bad companions,*";
P_HTM[3162]="*pāpaācāragocaro;**bad behavior and alms-resort,*";
P_HTM[3163]="*Asmā lokā paramhā ca,**a man falls to ruin*";
P_HTM[3164]="*ubhayā dhaṃsate naro.**in both this world and the next.*";
P_HTM[3165]="*Akkhitthiyo vāruṇī naccagītaṃ,**Dice, women, drink, song and dance;*";
P_HTM[3166]="*Divā soppaṃ pāricariyā akāle;**sleeping by day and roaming at night;*";
P_HTM[3167]="*Pāpā ca mittā sukadariyatā ca,**bad friends, and avarice:*";
P_HTM[3168]="*Ete cha ṭhānā purisaṃ dhaṃsayanti.**these six grounds ruin a person.*";
P_HTM[3169]="*Akkhehi dibbanti suraṃ pivanti,**They play dice and drink liquor,*";
P_HTM[3170]="*Yantitthiyo pāṇasamā paresaṃ;**and consort with women loved by others.*";
P_HTM[3171]="*Nihīnasevī na ca vuddhasevī,**Associating with the worse, not the better,*";
P_HTM[3172]="*Nihīyate kāḷapakkheva cando.**they diminish like the waning moon.*";
P_HTM[3173]="*Yo vāruṇī addhano akiñcano,**A drunkard, broke, and destitute,*";
P_HTM[3174]="*Pipāso pivaṃ papāgato;**thirsty, drinking in the bar,*";
P_HTM[3175]="*Udakamiva iṇaṃ vigāhati,**drowning in debt,*";
P_HTM[3176]="*Akulaṃ kāhiti khippamattano.**will quickly lose their way.*";
P_HTM[3177]="*Na divā soppasīlena,**When you’re in the habit of sleeping late,*";
P_HTM[3178]="*rattimuṭṭhānadessinā;**seeing night as time to rise,*";
P_HTM[3179]="*Niccaṃ mattena soṇḍena,**and always getting drunk,*";
P_HTM[3180]="*sakkā āvasituṃ gharaṃ.**you can’t keep up the household life.*";
P_HTM[3181]="*Atisītaṃ atiuṇhaṃ,**‘Too cold, too hot,*";
P_HTM[3182]="*atisāyamidaṃ ahu;**too late,’ they say.*";
P_HTM[3183]="*Iti vissaṭṭhakammante,**When the young neglect their work like this,*";
P_HTM[3184]="*atthā accenti māṇave.**riches pass them by.*";
P_HTM[3185]="*Yodha sītañca uṇhañca,**But one who considers hot and cold*";
P_HTM[3186]="*tiṇā bhiyyo na maññati;**as nothing more than blades of grass—*";
P_HTM[3187]="*Karaṃ purisakiccāni,**he does his manly duty,*";
P_HTM[3188]="*so sukhaṃ na vihāyatī”ti.**and happiness never fails.”*";
P_HTM[3189]="*11. Mittapatirūpaka**11. Fake Friends*";
P_HTM[3190]="*“Cattārome, gahapatiputta, amittā mittapatirūpakā veditabbā.**“Householder’s son, you should recognize these four enemies disguised as friends:*";
P_HTM[3191]="*Aññadatthuharo amitto mittapatirūpako veditabbo, vacīparamo amitto mittapatirūpako veditabbo, anuppiyabhāṇī amitto mittapatirūpako veditabbo, apāyasahāyo amitto mittapatirūpako veditabbo.**the taker, the talker, the flatterer, the spender.*";
P_HTM[3192]="*Catūhi kho, gahapatiputta, ṭhānehi aññadatthuharo amitto mittapatirūpako veditabbo.**You can recognize a fake friend who’s all take on four grounds.*";
P_HTM[3193]="*Aññadatthuharo hoti,**Your possessions end up theirs.*";
P_HTM[3194]="*appena bahumicchati;**Giving little, they expect a lot.*";
P_HTM[3195]="*Bhayassa kiccaṃ karoti,**They do their duty out of fear.*";
P_HTM[3196]="*sevati atthakāraṇā.**They associate for their own advantage.*";
P_HTM[3197]="*Imehi kho, gahapatiputta, catūhi ṭhānehi aññadatthuharo amitto mittapatirūpako veditabbo.**You can recognize a fake friend who’s all take on these four grounds.*";
P_HTM[3198]="*Catūhi kho, gahapatiputta, ṭhānehi vacīparamo amitto mittapatirūpako veditabbo.**You can recognize a fake friend who’s all talk on four grounds.*";
P_HTM[3199]="*Atītena paṭisantharati, anāgatena paṭisantharati, niratthakena saṅgaṇhāti, paccuppannesu kiccesu byasanaṃ dasseti.**They’re hospitable in the past. They’re hospitable in the future. They’re full of meaningless pleasantries. When something needs doing in the present they point to their own misfortune.*";
P_HTM[3200]="*Imehi kho, gahapatiputta, catūhi ṭhānehi vacīparamo amitto mittapatirūpako veditabbo.**You can recognize a fake friend who’s all talk on these four grounds.*";
P_HTM[3201]="*Catūhi kho, gahapatiputta, ṭhānehi anuppiyabhāṇī amitto mittapatirūpako veditabbo.**You can recognize a fake friend who’s a flatterer on four grounds.*";
P_HTM[3202]="*Pāpakampissa anujānāti, kalyāṇampissa anujānāti, sammukhāssa vaṇṇaṃ bhāsati, parammukhāssa avaṇṇaṃ bhāsati.**They support you equally in doing bad and doing good. They praise you to your face, and put you down behind your back.*";
P_HTM[3203]="*Imehi kho, gahapatiputta, catūhi ṭhānehi anuppiyabhāṇī amitto mittapatirūpako veditabbo.**You can recognize a fake friend who’s a flatterer on these four grounds.*";
P_HTM[3204]="*Catūhi kho, gahapatiputta, ṭhānehi apāyasahāyo amitto mittapatirūpako veditabbo.**You can recognize a fake friend who’s a spender on four grounds.*";
P_HTM[3205]="*Surāmerayamajjappamādaṭṭhānānuyoge sahāyo hoti, vikālavisikhācariyānuyoge sahāyo hoti, samajjābhicaraṇe sahāyo hoti, jūtappamādaṭṭhānānuyoge sahāyo hoti.**They accompany you when drinking, roaming the streets at night, frequenting festivals, and gambling.*";
P_HTM[3206]="*Imehi kho, gahapatiputta, catūhi ṭhānehi apāyasahāyo amitto mittapatirūpako veditabbo”ti.**You can recognize a fake friend who’s a spender on these four grounds.”*";
P_HTM[3207]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[3208]="*Idaṃ vatvāna sugato athāparaṃ etadavoca satthā:**Then the Holy One, the Teacher, went on to say:*";
P_HTM[3209]="*“Aññadatthuharo mitto,**“One friend is all take,*";
P_HTM[3210]="*yo ca mitto vacīparo;**another all talk;*";
P_HTM[3211]="*Anuppiyañca yo āha,**one’s just a flatterer,*";
P_HTM[3212]="*apāyesu ca yo sakhā.**and one’s a friend who spends.*";
P_HTM[3213]="*Ete amitte cattāro,**An astute person understands*";
P_HTM[3214]="*iti viññāya paṇḍito;**these four enemies for what they are*";
P_HTM[3215]="*Ārakā parivajjeyya,**and keeps them at a distance,*";
P_HTM[3216]="*maggaṃ paṭibhayaṃ yathā”ti.**as they’d shun a risky road.”*";
P_HTM[3217]="*12. Suhadamitta**12. Good-Hearted Friends*";
P_HTM[3218]="*“Cattārome, gahapatiputta, mittā suhadā veditabbā.**“Householder’s son, you should recognize these four good-hearted friends:*";
P_HTM[3219]="*Upakāro mitto suhado veditabbo, samānasukhadukkho mitto suhado veditabbo, atthakkhāyī mitto suhado veditabbo, anukampako mitto suhado veditabbo.**the helper, the friend in good times and bad, the counselor, and the one who’s compassionate.*";
P_HTM[3220]="*Catūhi kho, gahapatiputta, ṭhānehi upakāro mitto suhado veditabbo.**You can recognize a good-hearted friend who’s a helper on four grounds.*";
P_HTM[3221]="*Pamattaṃ rakkhati, pamattassa sāpateyyaṃ rakkhati, bhītassa saraṇaṃ hoti, uppannesu kiccakaraṇīyesu taddiguṇaṃ bhogaṃ anuppadeti.**They guard you when you’re negligent. They guard your property when you’re negligent. They keep you safe in times of danger. When something needs doing, they supply you with twice the money you need.*";
P_HTM[3222]="*Imehi kho, gahapatiputta, catūhi ṭhānehi upakāro mitto suhado veditabbo.**You can recognize a good-hearted friend who’s a helper on these four grounds.*";
P_HTM[3223]="*Catūhi kho, gahapatiputta, ṭhānehi samānasukhadukkho mitto suhado veditabbo.**You can recognize a good-hearted friend who’s the same in good times and bad on four grounds.*";
P_HTM[3224]="*Guyhamassa ācikkhati, guyhamassa parigūhati, āpadāsu na vijahati, jīvitaṃpissa atthāya pariccattaṃ hoti.**They tell you secrets. They keep your secrets. They don’t abandon you in times of trouble. They’d even give their life for you.*";
P_HTM[3225]="*Imehi kho, gahapatiputta, catūhi ṭhānehi samānasukhadukkho mitto suhado veditabbo.**You can recognize a good-hearted friend who’s the same in good times and bad on these four grounds.*";
P_HTM[3226]="*Catūhi kho, gahapatiputta, ṭhānehi atthakkhāyī mitto suhado veditabbo.**You can recognize a good-hearted friend who’s a counselor on four grounds.*";
P_HTM[3227]="*Pāpā nivāreti, kalyāṇe niveseti, assutaṃ sāveti, saggassa maggaṃ ācikkhati.**They keep you from doing bad. They support you in doing good. They teach you what you do not know. They explain the path to heaven.*";
P_HTM[3228]="*Imehi kho, gahapatiputta, catūhi ṭhānehi atthakkhāyī mitto suhado veditabbo.**You can recognize a good-hearted friend who’s a counselor on these four grounds.*";
P_HTM[3229]="*Catūhi kho, gahapatiputta, ṭhānehi anukampako mitto suhado veditabbo.**You can recognize a good-hearted friend who’s compassionate on four grounds.*";
P_HTM[3230]="*Abhavenassa na nandati, bhavenassa nandati, avaṇṇaṃ bhaṇamānaṃ nivāreti, vaṇṇaṃ bhaṇamānaṃ pasaṃsati.**They don’t delight in your misfortune. They delight in your good fortune. They keep others from criticizing you. They encourage praise of you.*";
P_HTM[3231]="*Imehi kho, gahapatiputta, catūhi ṭhānehi anukampako mitto suhado veditabbo”ti.**You can recognize a good-hearted friend who’s compassionate on these four grounds.”*";
P_HTM[3232]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[3233]="*Idaṃ vatvāna sugato athāparaṃ etadavoca satthā:**Then the Holy One, the Teacher, went on to say:*";
P_HTM[3234]="*“Upakāro ca yo mitto,**“A friend who’s a helper,*";
P_HTM[3235]="*sukhe dukkhe ca yo sakhā;**one the same in both pleasure and pain,*";
P_HTM[3236]="*Atthakkhāyī ca yo mitto,**a friend of good counsel,*";
P_HTM[3237]="*yo ca mittānukampako.**and one of compassion;*";
P_HTM[3238]="*Etepi mitte cattāro,**an astute person understands*";
P_HTM[3239]="*iti viññāya paṇḍito;**these four friends for what they are*";
P_HTM[3240]="*Sakkaccaṃ payirupāseyya,**and carefully looks after them,*";
P_HTM[3241]="*mātā puttaṃva orasaṃ;**like a mother the child at her breast.*";
P_HTM[3242]="*Paṇḍito sīlasampanno,**The astute and virtuous*";
P_HTM[3243]="*jalaṃ aggīva bhāsati.**shine like a burning flame.*";
P_HTM[3244]="*Bhoge saṃharamānassa,**They pick up riches as bees*";
P_HTM[3245]="*bhamarasseva irīyato;**roaming round pick up pollen.*";
P_HTM[3246]="*Bhogā sannicayaṃ yanti,**And their riches proceed to grow,*";
P_HTM[3247]="*vammikovupacīyati.**like an ant-hill piling up.*";
P_HTM[3248]="*Evaṃ bhoge samāhatvā,**In gathering wealth like this,*";
P_HTM[3249]="*alamatto kule gihī;**a householder does enough for their family.*";
P_HTM[3250]="*Catudhā vibhaje bhoge,**And they’d hold on to friends*";
P_HTM[3251]="*sa ve mittāni ganthati.**by dividing their wealth in four.*";
P_HTM[3252]="*Ekena bhoge bhuñjeyya,**One portion is to enjoy.*";
P_HTM[3253]="*dvīhi kammaṃ payojaye;**Two parts invest in work.*";
P_HTM[3254]="*Catutthañca nidhāpeyya,**And the fourth should be kept*";
P_HTM[3255]="*āpadāsu bhavissatī”ti.**for times of trouble.”*";
P_HTM[3256]="*13. Chaddisāpaṭicchādanakaṇḍa**13. Covering the Six Quarters*";
P_HTM[3257]="*“Kathañca, gahapatiputta, ariyasāvako chaddisāpaṭicchādī hoti?**“And how, householder’s son, does a noble disciple cover the six quarters?*";
P_HTM[3258]="*Cha imā, gahapatiputta, disā veditabbā.**These six quarters should be recognized:*";
P_HTM[3259]="*Puratthimā disā mātāpitaro veditabbā, dakkhiṇā disā ācariyā veditabbā, pacchimā disā puttadārā veditabbā, uttarā disā mittāmaccā veditabbā, heṭṭhimā disā dāsakammakarā veditabbā, uparimā disā samaṇabrāhmaṇā veditabbā.**parents as the east, teachers as the south, partner and children as the west, friends and colleagues as the north, bondservants and workers as beneath, and ascetics and brahmins as above.*";
P_HTM[3260]="*Pañcahi kho, gahapatiputta, ṭhānehi puttena puratthimā disā mātāpitaro paccupaṭṭhātabbā—**A child should serve their parents as the eastern quarter in five ways, thinking:*";
P_HTM[3261]="*bhato ne bharissāmi, kiccaṃ nesaṃ karissāmi, kulavaṃsaṃ ṭhapessāmi, dāyajjaṃ paṭipajjāmi, atha vā pana petānaṃ kālaṅkatānaṃ dakkhiṇaṃ anuppadassāmīti.**‘I will support those who supported me. I’ll do my duty for them. I’ll maintain the family traditions. I’ll take care of the inheritance. When they have passed away, I’ll make an offering on their behalf.’*";
P_HTM[3262]="*Imehi kho, gahapatiputta, pañcahi ṭhānehi puttena puratthimā disā mātāpitaro paccupaṭṭhitā pañcahi ṭhānehi puttaṃ anukampanti.**Parents served by the children in these five ways show compassion to them in five ways.*";
P_HTM[3263]="*Pāpā nivārenti, kalyāṇe nivesenti, sippaṃ sikkhāpenti, patirūpena dārena saṃyojenti, samaye dāyajjaṃ niyyādenti.**They keep them from doing bad. They support them in doing good. They train them in a profession. They connect them with a suitable partner. They transfer the inheritance in due time.*";
P_HTM[3264]="*Imehi kho, gahapatiputta, pañcahi ṭhānehi puttena puratthimā disā mātāpitaro paccupaṭṭhitā imehi pañcahi ṭhānehi puttaṃ anukampanti.**Parents served by their children in these five ways show compassion to them in these five ways.*";
P_HTM[3265]="*Evamassa esā puratthimā disā paṭicchannā hoti khemā appaṭibhayā.**And that’s how the eastern quarter is covered, kept safe and free of peril.*";
P_HTM[3266]="*Pañcahi kho, gahapatiputta, ṭhānehi antevāsinā dakkhiṇā disā ācariyā paccupaṭṭhātabbā—**A student should serve their teacher as the southern quarter in five ways:*";
P_HTM[3267]="*uṭṭhānena upaṭṭhānena sussusāya pāricariyāya sakkaccaṃ sippapaṭiggahaṇena.**by rising for them, by serving them, by listening well, by looking after them, and by carefully learning their profession.*";
P_HTM[3268]="*Imehi kho, gahapatiputta, pañcahi ṭhānehi antevāsinā dakkhiṇā disā ācariyā paccupaṭṭhitā pañcahi ṭhānehi antevāsiṃ anukampanti—**Teachers served by their students in these five ways show compassion to them in five ways.*";
P_HTM[3269]="*suvinītaṃ vinenti, suggahitaṃ gāhāpenti, sabbasippassutaṃ samakkhāyino bhavanti, mittāmaccesu paṭiyādenti, disāsu parittāṇaṃ karonti.**They make sure they’re well trained and well educated. They clearly explain all the knowledge of the profession. They introduce them to their friends and colleagues. They provide protection in every region.*";
P_HTM[3270]="*Imehi kho, gahapatiputta, pañcahi ṭhānehi antevāsinā dakkhiṇā disā ācariyā paccupaṭṭhitā imehi pañcahi ṭhānehi antevāsiṃ anukampanti.**Teachers served by their students in these five ways show compassion to them in these five ways.*";
P_HTM[3271]="*Evamassa esā dakkhiṇā disā paṭicchannā hoti khemā appaṭibhayā.**And that’s how the southern quarter is covered, kept safe and free of peril.*";
P_HTM[3272]="*Pañcahi kho, gahapatiputta, ṭhānehi sāmikena pacchimā disā bhariyā paccupaṭṭhātabbā—**A husband should serve his wife as the western quarter in five ways:*";
P_HTM[3273]="*sammānanāya anavamānanāya anaticariyāya issariyavossaggena alaṅkārānuppadānena.**by treating her with honor, by not looking down on her, by not being unfaithful, by relinquishing authority to her, and by presenting her with adornments.*";
P_HTM[3274]="*Imehi kho, gahapatiputta, pañcahi ṭhānehi sāmikena pacchimā disā bhariyā paccupaṭṭhitā pañcahi ṭhānehi sāmikaṃ anukampati—**A wife served by her husband in these five ways shows compassion to him in five ways.*";
P_HTM[3275]="*susaṃvihitakammantā ca hoti, saṅgahitaparijanā ca, anaticārinī ca, sambhatañca anurakkhati, dakkhā ca hoti analasā sabbakiccesu.**She’s well-organized in her work. She manages the domestic help. She’s not unfaithful. She preserves his earnings. She’s deft and tireless in all her duties.*";
P_HTM[3276]="*Imehi kho, gahapatiputta, pañcahi ṭhānehi sāmikena pacchimā disā bhariyā paccupaṭṭhitā imehi pañcahi ṭhānehi sāmikaṃ anukampati.**A wife served by her husband in these five ways shows compassion to him in these five ways.*";
P_HTM[3277]="*Evamassa esā pacchimā disā paṭicchannā hoti khemā appaṭibhayā.**And that’s how the western quarter is covered, kept safe and free of peril.*";
P_HTM[3278]="*Pañcahi kho, gahapatiputta, ṭhānehi kulaputtena uttarā disā mittāmaccā paccupaṭṭhātabbā—**A gentleman should serve their friends and colleagues as the northern quarter in five ways:*";
P_HTM[3279]="*dānena peyyavajjena atthacariyāya samānattatāya avisaṃvādanatāya.**giving, kindly words, taking care, equality, and not using tricky words.*";
P_HTM[3280]="*Imehi kho, gahapatiputta, pañcahi ṭhānehi kulaputtena uttarā disā mittāmaccā paccupaṭṭhitā pañcahi ṭhānehi kulaputtaṃ anukampanti—**Friends and colleagues served by a gentleman in these five ways show compassion to them in five ways.*";
P_HTM[3281]="*pamattaṃ rakkhanti, pamattassa sāpateyyaṃ rakkhanti, bhītassa saraṇaṃ honti, āpadāsu na vijahanti, aparapajā cassa paṭipūjenti.**They guard them when they’re negligent. They guard their property when they’re negligent. They keep them safe in times of danger. They don’t abandon them in times of trouble. They honor their descendants.*";
P_HTM[3282]="*Imehi kho, gahapatiputta, pañcahi ṭhānehi kulaputtena uttarā disā mittāmaccā paccupaṭṭhitā imehi pañcahi ṭhānehi kulaputtaṃ anukampanti.**Friends and colleagues served by a gentleman in these five ways show compassion to them in these five ways.*";
P_HTM[3283]="*Evamassa esā uttarā disā paṭicchannā hoti khemā appaṭibhayā.**And that’s how the northern quarter is covered, kept safe and free of peril.*";
P_HTM[3284]="*Pañcahi kho, gahapatiputta, ṭhānehi ayyirakena heṭṭhimā disā dāsakammakarā paccupaṭṭhātabbā—**A master should serve their bondservants and workers as the lower quarter in five ways:*";
P_HTM[3285]="*yathābalaṃ kammantasaṃvidhānena bhattavetanānuppadānena gilānupaṭṭhānena acchariyānaṃ rasānaṃ saṃvibhāgena samaye vossaggena.**by organizing work according to ability, by paying food and wages, by nursing them when sick, by sharing special treats, and by giving time off work.*";
P_HTM[3286]="*Imehi kho, gahapatiputta, pañcahi ṭhānehi ayyirakena heṭṭhimā disā dāsakammakarā paccupaṭṭhitā pañcahi ṭhānehi ayyirakaṃ anukampanti—**Bondservants and workers served by a master in these five ways show compassion to them in five ways.*";
P_HTM[3287]="*pubbuṭṭhāyino ca honti, pacchā nipātino ca, dinnādāyino ca, sukatakammakarā ca, kittivaṇṇaharā ca.**They get up first, and go to bed last. They don’t steal. They do their work well. And they promote a good reputation.*";
P_HTM[3288]="*Imehi kho, gahapatiputta, pañcahi ṭhānehi ayyirakena heṭṭhimā disā dāsakammakarā paccupaṭṭhitā imehi pañcahi ṭhānehi ayyirakaṃ anukampanti.**Bondservants and workers served by a master in these five ways show compassion to them in these five ways.*";
P_HTM[3289]="*Evamassa esā heṭṭhimā disā paṭicchannā hoti khemā appaṭibhayā.**And that’s how the lower quarter is covered, kept safe and free of peril.*";
P_HTM[3290]="*Pañcahi kho, gahapatiputta, ṭhānehi kulaputtena uparimā disā samaṇabrāhmaṇā paccupaṭṭhātabbā—**A gentleman should serve ascetics and brahmins as the upper quarter in five ways:*";
P_HTM[3291]="*mettena kāyakammena mettena vacīkammena mettena manokammena anāvaṭadvāratāya āmisānuppadānena.**by loving deeds of body, speech, and mind, by not turning them away at the gate, and by providing them with material needs.*";
P_HTM[3292]="*Imehi kho, gahapatiputta, pañcahi ṭhānehi kulaputtena uparimā disā samaṇabrāhmaṇā paccupaṭṭhitā chahi ṭhānehi kulaputtaṃ anukampanti—**Ascetics and brahmins served by a gentleman in these five ways show compassion to them in five ways.*";
P_HTM[3293]="*pāpā nivārenti, kalyāṇe nivesenti, kalyāṇena manasā anukampanti, assutaṃ sāventi, sutaṃ pariyodāpenti, saggassa maggaṃ ācikkhanti.**They keep them from doing bad. They support them in doing good. They think of them with kindly thoughts. They teach them what they do not know. They clarify what they’ve already learned. They explain the path to heaven.*";
P_HTM[3294]="*Imehi kho, gahapatiputta, pañcahi ṭhānehi kulaputtena uparimā disā samaṇabrāhmaṇā paccupaṭṭhitā imehi chahi ṭhānehi kulaputtaṃ anukampanti.**Ascetics and brahmins served by a gentleman in these five ways show compassion to them in these five ways.*";
P_HTM[3295]="*Evamassa esā uparimā disā paṭicchannā hoti khemā appaṭibhayā”ti.**And that’s how the upper quarter is covered, kept safe and free of peril.”*";
P_HTM[3296]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[3297]="*Idaṃ vatvāna sugato athāparaṃ etadavoca satthā:**Then the Holy One, the Teacher, went on to say:*";
P_HTM[3298]="*“Mātāpitā disā pubbā,**“Parents are the east,*";
P_HTM[3299]="*ācariyā dakkhiṇā disā;**teachers the south,*";
P_HTM[3300]="*Puttadārā disā pacchā,**wives and child the west,*";
P_HTM[3301]="*mittāmaccā ca uttarā.**friends and colleagues the north,*";
P_HTM[3302]="*Dāsakammakarā heṭṭhā,**servants and workers below,*";
P_HTM[3303]="*uddhaṃ samaṇabrāhmaṇā;**and ascetics and brahmins above.*";
P_HTM[3304]="*Etā disā namasseyya,**By honoring these quarters*";
P_HTM[3305]="*alamatto kule gihī.**a householder does enough for their family.*";
P_HTM[3306]="*Paṇḍito sīlasampanno,**The astute and the virtuous,*";
P_HTM[3307]="*saṇho ca paṭibhānavā;**the gentle and the articulate,*";
P_HTM[3308]="*Nivātavutti atthaddho,**the humble and the kind:*";
P_HTM[3309]="*tādiso labhate yasaṃ.**they’re who win glory.*";
P_HTM[3310]="*Uṭṭhānako analaso,**The diligent, not lazy,*";
P_HTM[3311]="*āpadāsu na vedhati;**those not disturbed by troubles,*";
P_HTM[3312]="*Acchinnavutti medhāvī,**those consistent in conduct, the intelligent:*";
P_HTM[3313]="*tādiso labhate yasaṃ.**they’re who win glory.*";
P_HTM[3314]="*Saṅgāhako mittakaro,**The inclusive, the makers of friends,*";
P_HTM[3315]="*vadaññū vītamaccharo;**the kind, those rid of stinginess,*";
P_HTM[3316]="*Netā vinetā anunetā,**those who lead, train, and persuade:*";
P_HTM[3317]="*tādiso labhate yasaṃ.**they’re who win glory.*";
P_HTM[3318]="*Dānañca peyyavajjañca,**Giving and kindly words,*";
P_HTM[3319]="*atthacariyā ca yā idha;**taking care here,*";
P_HTM[3320]="*Samānattatā ca dhammesu,**and treating equally in worldly conditions,*";
P_HTM[3321]="*tattha tattha yathārahaṃ;**as befits them in each case;*";
P_HTM[3322]="*Ete kho saṅgahā loke,**these ways of being inclusive in the world*";
P_HTM[3323]="*rathassāṇīva yāyato.**are like a moving chariot’s linchpin.*";
P_HTM[3324]="*Ete ca saṅgahā nāssu,**If there were no such ways of being inclusive,*";
P_HTM[3325]="*na mātā puttakāraṇā;**neither mother nor father*";
P_HTM[3326]="*Labhetha mānaṃ pūjaṃ vā,**would be respected and honored*";
P_HTM[3327]="*pitā vā puttakāraṇā.**for what they’ve done for their children.*";
P_HTM[3328]="*Yasmā ca saṅgahā ete,**But since these ways of being inclusive do exist,*";
P_HTM[3329]="*sammapekkhanti paṇḍitā;**the astute do regard them well,*";
P_HTM[3330]="*Tasmā mahattaṃ papponti,**so they achieve greatness*";
P_HTM[3331]="*pāsaṃsā ca bhavanti te”ti.**and are praised.”*";
P_HTM[3332]="*Evaṃ vutte, siṅgālako gahapatiputto bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When this was said, Sigālaka the householder’s son said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[3333]="*“abhikkantaṃ, bhante, abhikkantaṃ, bhante.**“Excellent, sir! Excellent!*";
P_HTM[3334]="*Seyyathāpi, bhante, nikkujjitaṃ vā ukkujjeyya, paṭicchannaṃ vā vivareyya, mūḷhassa vā maggaṃ ācikkheyya, andhakāre vā telapajjotaṃ dhāreyya ‘cakkhumanto rūpāni dakkhantī’ti; evamevaṃ bhagavatā anekapariyāyena dhammo pakāsito.**As if he were righting the overturned, or revealing the hidden, or pointing out the path to the lost, or lighting a lamp in the dark so people with good eyes can see what’s there, the Buddha has made the teaching clear in many ways.*";
P_HTM[3335]="*Esāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavantaṃ saraṇaṃ gacchāmi dhammañca bhikkhusaṅghañca.**I go for refuge to the Buddha, to the teaching, and to the mendicant Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[3336]="*Upāsakaṃ maṃ bhagavā dhāretu, ajjatagge pāṇupetaṃ saraṇaṃ gatan”ti.**From this day forth, may the Buddha remember me as a lay follower who has gone for refuge for life.”*";
P_HTM[3337]="*Siṅgālasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3338]="*32. Āṭānāṭiyasutta  - The Āṭānāṭiya Protection * **";
P_HTM[3339]="*1. Paṭhamabhāṇavāra**1. The First Recitation Section*";
P_HTM[3340]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[3341]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā rājagahe viharati gijjhakūṭe pabbate.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Rājagaha, on the Vulture’s Peak Mountain.*";
P_HTM[3342]="*Atha kho cattāro mahārājā mahatiyā ca yakkhasenāya mahatiyā ca gandhabbasenāya mahatiyā ca kumbhaṇḍasenāya mahatiyā ca nāgasenāya catuddisaṃ rakkhaṃ ṭhapetvā catuddisaṃ gumbaṃ ṭhapetvā catuddisaṃ ovaraṇaṃ ṭhapetvā abhikkantāya rattiyā abhikkantavaṇṇā kevalakappaṃ gijjhakūṭaṃ pabbataṃ obhāsetvā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu.**Then, late at night, the Four Great Kings—with large armies of spirits, fairies, goblins, and dragons—set guards, troops, and wards at the four quarters and then, lighting up the entire Vulture’s Peak with their beauty, went up to the Buddha, bowed, and sat down to one side.*";
P_HTM[3343]="*Tepi kho yakkhā appekacce bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu, appekacce bhagavatā saddhiṃ sammodiṃsu, sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu, appekacce yena bhagavā tenañjaliṃ paṇāmetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu, appekacce nāmagottaṃ sāvetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu, appekacce tuṇhībhūtā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu.**Before sitting down to one side, some spirits bowed, some exchanged greetings and polite conversation, some held up their joined palms toward the Buddha, some announced their name and clan, while some kept silent.*";
P_HTM[3344]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho vessavaṇo mahārājā bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Seated to one side, the Great King Vessavaṇa said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[3345]="*“santi hi, bhante, uḷārā yakkhā bhagavato appasannā.**“Sir, some high spirits have confidence in the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[3346]="*Santi hi, bhante, uḷārā yakkhā bhagavato pasannā.**some do not.*";
P_HTM[3347]="*Santi hi, bhante, majjhimā yakkhā bhagavato appasannā.**Some middling spirits have confidence in the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[3348]="*Santi hi, bhante, majjhimā yakkhā bhagavato pasannā.**some do not.*";
P_HTM[3349]="*Santi hi, bhante, nīcā yakkhā bhagavato appasannā.**Some low spirits have confidence in the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[3350]="*Santi hi, bhante, nīcā yakkhā bhagavato pasannā.**some do not.*";
P_HTM[3351]="*Yebhuyyena kho pana, bhante, yakkhā appasannāyeva bhagavato.**But mostly the spirits don’t have confidence in the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[3352]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[3353]="*Bhagavā hi, bhante, pāṇātipātā veramaṇiyā dhammaṃ deseti, adinnādānā veramaṇiyā dhammaṃ deseti, kāmesumicchācārā veramaṇiyā dhammaṃ deseti, musāvādā veramaṇiyā dhammaṃ deseti, surāmerayamajjappamādaṭṭhānā veramaṇiyā dhammaṃ deseti.**Because the Buddha teaches them to refrain from killing living creatures, stealing, lying, sexual misconduct, and drinking alcohol.*";
P_HTM[3354]="*Yebhuyyena kho pana, bhante, yakkhā appaṭiviratāyeva pāṇātipātā, appaṭiviratā adinnādānā, appaṭiviratā kāmesumicchācārā, appaṭiviratā musāvādā, appaṭiviratā surāmerayamajjappamādaṭṭhānā.**But mostly they don’t refrain from such things.*";
P_HTM[3355]="*Tesaṃ taṃ hoti appiyaṃ amanāpaṃ.**They don’t like that or approve of it.*";
P_HTM[3356]="*Santi hi, bhante, bhagavato sāvakā araññavanapatthāni pantāni senāsanāni paṭisevanti appasaddāni appanigghosāni vijanavātāni manussarāhasseyyakāni paṭisallānasāruppāni.**Sir, there are disciples of the Buddha who frequent remote lodgings in the wilderness and the forest that are quiet and still, far from the madding crowd, remote from human settlements, and fit for retreat.*";
P_HTM[3357]="*Tattha santi uḷārā yakkhā nivāsino, ye imasmiṃ bhagavato pāvacane appasannā.**There dwell high spirits who have no confidence in the Buddha’s dispensation.*";
P_HTM[3358]="*Tesaṃ pasādāya uggaṇhātu, bhante, bhagavā āṭānāṭiyaṃ rakkhaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ bhikkhunīnaṃ upāsakānaṃ upāsikānaṃ guttiyā rakkhāya avihiṃsāya phāsuvihārāyā”ti.**To give them confidence, may the Buddha please learn the Āṭānāṭiya protection for the guarding, protection, safety, and comfort of the monks, nuns, laymen, and laywomen.”*";
P_HTM[3359]="*Adhivāsesi bhagavā tuṇhībhāvena.**The Buddha consented in silence.*";
P_HTM[3360]="*Atha kho vessavaṇo mahārājā bhagavato adhivāsanaṃ viditvā tāyaṃ velāyaṃ imaṃ āṭānāṭiyaṃ rakkhaṃ abhāsi:**Then, knowing that the Buddha had consented, on that occasion Great King Vessavaṇa recited the Āṭānāṭiya protection.*";
P_HTM[3361]="*“Vipassissa ca namatthu,**“Hail Vipassī,*";
P_HTM[3362]="*cakkhumantassa sirīmato;**the glorious seer!*";
P_HTM[3363]="*Sikhissapi ca namatthu,**Hail Sikhī,*";
P_HTM[3364]="*sabbabhūtānukampino.**compassionate for all beings!*";
P_HTM[3365]="*Vessabhussa ca namatthu,**Hail Vesabhū,*";
P_HTM[3366]="*nhātakassa tapassino;**cleansed and austere!*";
P_HTM[3367]="*Namatthu kakusandhassa,**Hail Kakusandha,*";
P_HTM[3368]="*mārasenāpamaddino.**crusher of Māra’s army!*";
P_HTM[3369]="*Koṇāgamanassa namatthu,**Hail Koṇāgamana,*";
P_HTM[3370]="*brāhmaṇassa vusīmato;**the accomplished brahmin!*";
P_HTM[3371]="*Kassapassa ca namatthu,**Hail Kassapa,*";
P_HTM[3372]="*vippamuttassa sabbadhi.**freed in every way!*";
P_HTM[3373]="*Aṅgīrasassa namatthu,**Hail Aṅgīrasa,*";
P_HTM[3374]="*sakyaputtassa sirīmato;**the glorious Sakyan!*";
P_HTM[3375]="*Yo imaṃ dhammaṃ desesi,**He taught this Dhamma*";
P_HTM[3376]="*sabbadukkhāpanūdanaṃ.**that dispels all suffering.*";
P_HTM[3377]="*Ye cāpi nibbutā loke,**Those in the world who are extinguished,*";
P_HTM[3378]="*yathābhūtaṃ vipassisuṃ;**truly discerning,*";
P_HTM[3379]="*Te janā apisuṇātha,**not backbiters; such people*";
P_HTM[3380]="*mahantā vītasāradā.**being great of heart and rid of naivety,*";
P_HTM[3381]="*Hitaṃ devamanussānaṃ,**revere that Gotama;*";
P_HTM[3382]="*yaṃ namassanti gotamaṃ;**he who is helpful to gods and humans,*";
P_HTM[3383]="*Vijjācaraṇasampannaṃ,**accomplished in knowledge and conduct,*";
P_HTM[3384]="*mahantaṃ vītasāradaṃ.**great of heart and rid of naivety.*";
P_HTM[3385]="*Yato uggacchati sūriyo,**Where rises the sun—*";
P_HTM[3386]="*ādicco maṇḍalī mahā;**Aditi’s child, the great circle,*";
P_HTM[3387]="*Yassa cuggacchamānassa,**who in his rising*";
P_HTM[3388]="*saṃvarīpi nirujjhati;**dispels the night,*";
P_HTM[3389]="*Yassa cuggate sūriye,**and of whom, when sun has risen,*";
P_HTM[3390]="*‘divaso’ti pavuccati.**it’s said to be the day—*";
P_HTM[3391]="*Rahadopi tattha gambhīro,**there is a deep lake*";
P_HTM[3392]="*samuddo saritodako;**an ocean, where water flows.*";
P_HTM[3393]="*Evaṃ taṃ tattha jānanti,**So they know that in that place*";
P_HTM[3394]="*‘samuddo saritodako’.**there is an ocean where waters flow.*";
P_HTM[3395]="*Ito ‘sā purimā disā’,**From here that is the eastern quarter,*";
P_HTM[3396]="*iti naṃ ācikkhatī jano;**so the people say.*";
P_HTM[3397]="*Yaṃ disaṃ abhipāleti,**That quarter is warded*";
P_HTM[3398]="*mahārājā yasassi so.**by a great king, glorious,*";
P_HTM[3399]="*Gandhabbānaṃ adhipati,**the lord of the fairies;*";
P_HTM[3400]="*dhataraṭṭho’ti nāmaso;**his name is Dhataraṭṭha.*";
P_HTM[3401]="*Ramatī naccagītehi,**He delights in song and dance,*";
P_HTM[3402]="*gandhabbehi purakkhato.**honored by the fairies.*";
P_HTM[3403]="*Puttāpi tassa bahavo,**And he has many mighty sons*";
P_HTM[3404]="*ekanāmāti me sutaṃ;**all of one name, so I’ve heard.*";
P_HTM[3405]="*Asīti dasa eko ca,**Eighty, and ten, and one—*";
P_HTM[3406]="*indanāmā mahabbalā.**all of them named Inda.*";
P_HTM[3407]="*Te cāpi buddhaṃ disvāna,**After seeing the Awakened One,*";
P_HTM[3408]="*buddhaṃ ādiccabandhunaṃ;**the Buddha, Kinsman of the Sun,*";
P_HTM[3409]="*Dūratova namassanti,**they revere him from afar,*";
P_HTM[3410]="*mahantaṃ vītasāradaṃ.**the one great of heart and rid of naivety.*";
P_HTM[3411]="*Namo te purisājañña,**Homage to you, O thoroughbred!*";
P_HTM[3412]="*namo te purisuttama;**Homage to you, supreme among men!*";
P_HTM[3413]="*Kusalena samekkhasi,**You’ve seen us with clarity and kindness.*";
P_HTM[3414]="*amanussāpi taṃ vandanti;**The non-humans bow to you.*";
P_HTM[3415]="*Sutaṃ netaṃ abhiṇhaso,**We’ve been asked many a time,*";
P_HTM[3416]="*tasmā evaṃ vademase.**‘Do you bow to Gotama the victor?’*";
P_HTM[3417]="*‘Jinaṃ vandatha gotamaṃ’,**And so we ought to declare:*";
P_HTM[3418]="*‘jinaṃ vandāma gotamaṃ;**‘We bow to Gotama the victor,*";
P_HTM[3419]="*Vijjācaraṇasampannaṃ,**accomplished in knowledge and conduct!*";
P_HTM[3420]="*buddhaṃ vandāma gotamaṃ’.**We bow to Gotama the awakened!’*";
P_HTM[3421]="*Yena petā pavuccanti,**It’s where the departed go, they say,*";
P_HTM[3422]="*pisuṇā piṭṭhimaṃsikā;**who are dividers and backbiters,*";
P_HTM[3423]="*Pāṇātipātino luddā,**killers and hunters,*";
P_HTM[3424]="*corā nekatikā janā.**bandits and frauds.*";
P_HTM[3425]="*Ito ‘sā dakkhiṇā disā’,**From here that is the southern quarter,*";
P_HTM[3426]="*iti naṃ ācikkhatī jano;**so the people say.*";
P_HTM[3427]="*Yaṃ disaṃ abhipāleti,**That quarter is warded*";
P_HTM[3428]="*mahārājā yasassi so.**by a great king, glorious,*";
P_HTM[3429]="*Kumbhaṇḍānaṃ adhipati,**the lord of the goblins;*";
P_HTM[3430]="*‘virūḷho’ iti nāmaso;**his name is Virūḷha.*";
P_HTM[3431]="*Ramatī naccagītehi,**He delights in song and dance,*";
P_HTM[3432]="*kumbhaṇḍehi purakkhato.**honored by the goblins.*";
P_HTM[3433]="*Puttāpi tassa bahavo,**And he has many mighty sons*";
P_HTM[3434]="*ekanāmāti me sutaṃ;**all of one name, so I’ve heard.*";
P_HTM[3435]="*Asīti dasa eko ca,**Eighty, and ten, and one—*";
P_HTM[3436]="*indanāmā mahabbalā.**all of them named Inda.*";
P_HTM[3437]="*Te cāpi buddhaṃ disvāna,**After seeing the Awakened One,*";
P_HTM[3438]="*buddhaṃ ādiccabandhunaṃ;**the Buddha, Kinsman of the Sun,*";
P_HTM[3439]="*Dūratova namassanti,**they revere him from afar,*";
P_HTM[3440]="*mahantaṃ vītasāradaṃ.**the one great of heart and rid of naivety.*";
P_HTM[3441]="*Namo te purisājañña,**Homage to you, O thoroughbred!*";
P_HTM[3442]="*namo te purisuttama;**Homage to you, supreme among men!*";
P_HTM[3443]="*Kusalena samekkhasi,**You’ve seen us with clarity and kindness.*";
P_HTM[3444]="*amanussāpi taṃ vandanti;**The non-humans bow to you.*";
P_HTM[3445]="*Sutaṃ netaṃ abhiṇhaso,**We’ve been asked many a time,*";
P_HTM[3446]="*tasmā evaṃ vademase.**‘Do you bow to Gotama the victor?’*";
P_HTM[3447]="*‘Jinaṃ vandatha gotamaṃ’,**And so we ought to declare:*";
P_HTM[3448]="*‘jinaṃ vandāma gotamaṃ;**‘We bow to Gotama the victor,*";
P_HTM[3449]="*Vijjācaraṇasampannaṃ,**accomplished in knowledge and conduct!*";
P_HTM[3450]="*buddhaṃ vandāma gotamaṃ’.**We bow to Gotama the awakened!’*";
P_HTM[3451]="*Yattha coggacchati sūriyo,**Where sets the sun—*";
P_HTM[3452]="*ādicco maṇḍalī mahā;**Aditi’s child, the great circle,*";
P_HTM[3453]="*Yassa coggacchamānassa,**who in his setting*";
P_HTM[3454]="*divasopi nirujjhati;**closes the day,*";
P_HTM[3455]="*Yassa coggate sūriye,**and of whom, when sun has set,*";
P_HTM[3456]="*‘saṃvarī’ti pavuccati.**it’s said to be the night—*";
P_HTM[3457]="*Rahadopi tattha gambhīro,**there is a deep lake*";
P_HTM[3458]="*samuddo saritodako;**an ocean, where water flows.*";
P_HTM[3459]="*Evaṃ taṃ tattha jānanti,**So they know that in that place*";
P_HTM[3460]="*‘samuddo saritodako’.**there is an ocean where waters flow.*";
P_HTM[3461]="*Ito ‘sā pacchimā disā’,**From here that is the western quarter,*";
P_HTM[3462]="*iti naṃ ācikkhatī jano;**so the people say.*";
P_HTM[3463]="*Yaṃ disaṃ abhipāleti,**That quarter is warded*";
P_HTM[3464]="*mahārājā yasassi so.**by a great king, glorious,*";
P_HTM[3465]="*Nāgānañca adhipati,**the lord of the dragons;*";
P_HTM[3466]="*‘virūpakkho’ti nāmaso;**his name is Virūpakkha.*";
P_HTM[3467]="*Ramatī naccagītehi,**He delights in song and dance,*";
P_HTM[3468]="*nāgeheva purakkhato.**honored by the dragons.*";
P_HTM[3469]="*Puttāpi tassa bahavo,**And he has many mighty sons*";
P_HTM[3470]="*ekanāmāti me sutaṃ;**all of one name, so I’ve heard.*";
P_HTM[3471]="*Asīti dasa eko ca,**Eighty, and ten, and one—*";
P_HTM[3472]="*indanāmā mahabbalā.**all of them named Inda.*";
P_HTM[3473]="*Te cāpi buddhaṃ disvāna,**After seeing the Awakened One,*";
P_HTM[3474]="*buddhaṃ ādiccabandhunaṃ;**the Buddha, Kinsman of the Sun,*";
P_HTM[3475]="*Dūratova namassanti,**they revere him from afar,*";
P_HTM[3476]="*mahantaṃ vītasāradaṃ.**the one great of heart and rid of naivety.*";
P_HTM[3477]="*Namo te purisājañña,**Homage to you, O thoroughbred!*";
P_HTM[3478]="*namo te purisuttama;**Homage to you, supreme among men!*";
P_HTM[3479]="*Kusalena samekkhasi,**You’ve seen us with clarity and kindness.*";
P_HTM[3480]="*amanussāpi taṃ vandanti;**The non-humans bow to you.*";
P_HTM[3481]="*Sutaṃ netaṃ abhiṇhaso,**We’ve been asked many a time,*";
P_HTM[3482]="*tasmā evaṃ vademase.**‘Do you bow to Gotama the victor?’*";
P_HTM[3483]="*‘Jinaṃ vandatha gotamaṃ’,**And so we ought to declare:*";
P_HTM[3484]="*‘jinaṃ vandāma gotamaṃ;**‘We bow to Gotama the victor,*";
P_HTM[3485]="*Vijjācaraṇasampannaṃ,**accomplished in knowledge and conduct!*";
P_HTM[3486]="*buddhaṃ vandāma gotamaṃ’.**We bow to Gotama the awakened!’*";
P_HTM[3487]="*Yena uttarakuruvho,**Where lovely Uttarakuru is,*";
P_HTM[3488]="*mahāneru sudassano;**and the beautiful Mount Meru,*";
P_HTM[3489]="*Manussā tattha jāyanti,**humans born there*";
P_HTM[3490]="*amamā apariggahā.**are unselfish, not possessive.*";
P_HTM[3491]="*Na te bījaṃ pavapanti,**They do not sow the seed,*";
P_HTM[3492]="*napi nīyanti naṅgalā;**nor do they draw the plough.*";
P_HTM[3493]="*Akaṭṭhapākimaṃ sāliṃ,**The rice eaten by people*";
P_HTM[3494]="*paribhuñjanti mānusā.**ripens in untilled soil,*";
P_HTM[3495]="*Akaṇaṃ athusaṃ suddhaṃ,**free of powder or husk, pure,*";
P_HTM[3496]="*sugandhaṃ taṇḍulapphalaṃ;**fragrant, with only the rice-grain.*";
P_HTM[3497]="*Tuṇḍikīre pacitvāna,**They eat that food*";
P_HTM[3498]="*tato bhuñjanti bhojanaṃ.**after cooking it in a ‘parrot’s beak’.*";
P_HTM[3499]="*Gāviṃ ekakhuraṃ katvā,**Having prepared a cow with hooves uncloven,*";
P_HTM[3500]="*anuyanti disodisaṃ;**they’re drawn about from place to place.*";
P_HTM[3501]="*Pasuṃ ekakhuraṃ katvā,**Having prepared a beast with hooves uncloven,*";
P_HTM[3502]="*anuyanti disodisaṃ.**they’re drawn about from place to place.*";
P_HTM[3503]="*Itthiṃ vā vāhanaṃ katvā,**Having prepared a woman-drawn carriage,*";
P_HTM[3504]="*anuyanti disodisaṃ;**they’re drawn about from place to place.*";
P_HTM[3505]="*Purisaṃ vāhanaṃ katvā,**Having prepared a man-drawn carriage,*";
P_HTM[3506]="*anuyanti disodisaṃ.**they’re drawn about from place to place.*";
P_HTM[3507]="*Kumāriṃ vāhanaṃ katvā,**Having prepared a girl-drawn carriage,*";
P_HTM[3508]="*anuyanti disodisaṃ;**they’re drawn about from place to place.*";
P_HTM[3509]="*Kumāraṃ vāhanaṃ katvā,**Having prepared a boy-drawn carriage,*";
P_HTM[3510]="*anuyanti disodisaṃ.**they’re drawn about from place to place.*";
P_HTM[3511]="*Te yāne abhiruhitvā,**Having ascended their vehicle,*";
P_HTM[3512]="*Sabbā disā anupariyāyanti;**that king’s servants*";
P_HTM[3513]="*Pacārā tassa rājino.**tour about in every quarter,*";
P_HTM[3514]="*Hatthiyānaṃ assayānaṃ,**provided with vehicles,*";
P_HTM[3515]="*dibbaṃ yānaṃ upaṭṭhitaṃ;**elephant, horse, and divine.*";
P_HTM[3516]="*Pāsādā sivikā ceva,**And there are mansions and palanquins*";
P_HTM[3517]="*mahārājassa yasassino.**for that great and glorious king.*";
P_HTM[3518]="*Tassa ca nagarā ahu,**And he has cities, too,*";
P_HTM[3519]="*Antalikkhe sumāpitā;**well-built in the sky:*";
P_HTM[3520]="*Āṭānāṭā kusināṭā parakusināṭā,**Āṭānāṭā, Kusināṭā, Parakusināṭā,*";
P_HTM[3521]="*Nāṭasuriyā parakusiṭanāṭā.**Nāṭasuriyā, and Parakusiṭanāṭā.*";
P_HTM[3522]="*Uttarena kasivanto,**To the north is Kapīvanta,*";
P_HTM[3523]="*Janoghamaparena ca;**and Jonogha lies beyond.*";
P_HTM[3524]="*Navanavutiyo ambaraambaravatiyo,**And there’s Navanavutiya, Ambara-ambaravatiya,*";
P_HTM[3525]="*Āḷakamandā nāma rājadhānī.**and the royal capital named Āḷakamandā.*";
P_HTM[3526]="*Kuverassa kho pana mārisa,**The Great King Kuvera, dear sir,*";
P_HTM[3527]="*Mahārājassa visāṇā nāma rājadhānī;**has a capital named Visāṇā,*";
P_HTM[3528]="*Tasmā kuvero mahārājā,**which is why the great king*";
P_HTM[3529]="*‘Vessavaṇo’ti pavuccati.**is called ‘Vessavaṇa’.*";
P_HTM[3530]="*Paccesanto pakāsenti,**These each individually inform the King:*";
P_HTM[3531]="*Tatolā tattalā tatotalā;**Tatolā, Tattalā, Tatotalā,*";
P_HTM[3532]="*Ojasi tejasi tatojasī,**Ojasi, Tejasi, Tatojasi,*";
P_HTM[3533]="*Sūro rājā ariṭṭho nemi.**Sūra, Rājā, Ariṭṭha, and Nemi.*";
P_HTM[3534]="*Rahadopi tattha dharaṇī nāma,**There is a lake there too named Dharaṇī,*";
P_HTM[3535]="*Yato meghā pavassanti;**from whence the clouds rain down,*";
P_HTM[3536]="*Vassā yato patāyanti,**and the rains disperse.*";
P_HTM[3537]="*Sabhāpi tattha sālavatī nāma.**There is a hall there too named Bhagalavatī,*";
P_HTM[3538]="*Yattha yakkhā payirupāsanti,**where the spirits frequent.*";
P_HTM[3539]="*Tattha niccaphalā rukkhā;**There the trees are ever in fruit,*";
P_HTM[3540]="*Nānā dijagaṇā yutā,**with many different flocks of birds.*";
P_HTM[3541]="*Mayūrakoñcābhirudā;**Peacocks and herons call out there,*";
P_HTM[3542]="*Kokilādīhi vagguhi.**and the sweet cuckoos too.*";
P_HTM[3543]="*Jīvañjīvakasaddettha,**One bird cries out ‘Live, live!’,*";
P_HTM[3544]="*atho oṭṭhavacittakā;**another ‘Lift up your heart!’*";
P_HTM[3545]="*Kukkuṭakā kuḷīrakā,**There are cocks and kookaburras,*";
P_HTM[3546]="*vane pokkharasātakā.**and in the wood the lotus-crane.*";
P_HTM[3547]="*Sukasāḷikasaddettha,**The parrots and mynah cry out there,*";
P_HTM[3548]="*daṇḍamāṇavakāni ca;**and the ‘little stick-boy’ birds.*";
P_HTM[3549]="*Sobhati sabbakālaṃ sā,**Kuvera’s pond of rushes*";
P_HTM[3550]="*kuveranaḷinī sadā.**is lovely all the time.*";
P_HTM[3551]="*Ito ‘sā uttarā disā’,**From here that is the northern quarter,*";
P_HTM[3552]="*iti naṃ ācikkhatī jano;**so the people say.*";
P_HTM[3553]="*Yaṃ disaṃ abhipāleti,**That quarter is warded*";
P_HTM[3554]="*mahārājā yasassi so.**by a great king, glorious,*";
P_HTM[3555]="*Yakkhānañca adhipati,**the lord of spirits;*";
P_HTM[3556]="*‘kuvero’ iti nāmaso;**his name is ‘Kuvera’.*";
P_HTM[3557]="*Ramatī naccagītehi,**He delights in song and dance,*";
P_HTM[3558]="*yakkheheva purakkhato.**honored by the spirits.*";
P_HTM[3559]="*Puttāpi tassa bahavo,**And he has many mighty sons*";
P_HTM[3560]="*ekanāmāti me sutaṃ;**all of one name, so I’ve heard.*";
P_HTM[3561]="*Asīti dasa eko ca,**Eighty, and ten, and one—*";
P_HTM[3562]="*indanāmā mahabbalā.**all of them named Inda.*";
P_HTM[3563]="*Te cāpi buddhaṃ disvāna,**After seeing the Awakened One,*";
P_HTM[3564]="*buddhaṃ ādiccabandhunaṃ;**the Buddha, Kinsman of the Sun,*";
P_HTM[3565]="*Dūratova namassanti,**they revere him from afar,*";
P_HTM[3566]="*mahantaṃ vītasāradaṃ.**the one great of heart and rid of naivety.*";
P_HTM[3567]="*Namo te purisājañña,**Homage to you, O thoroughbred!*";
P_HTM[3568]="*namo te purisuttama;**Homage to you, supreme among men!*";
P_HTM[3569]="*Kusalena samekkhasi,**You’ve seen us with clarity and kindness.*";
P_HTM[3570]="*amanussāpi taṃ vandanti;**The non-humans bow to you.*";
P_HTM[3571]="*Sutaṃ netaṃ abhiṇhaso,**We’ve been asked many a time,*";
P_HTM[3572]="*tasmā evaṃ vademase.**‘Do you bow to Gotama the victor?’*";
P_HTM[3573]="*‘Jinaṃ vandatha gotamaṃ’,**And so we ought to declare:*";
P_HTM[3574]="*‘jinaṃ vandāma gotamaṃ;**‘We bow to Gotama the victor,*";
P_HTM[3575]="*Vijjācaraṇasampannaṃ,**accomplished in knowledge and conduct!*";
P_HTM[3576]="*buddhaṃ vandāma gotaman’ti.**We bow to Gotama the awakened!’”*";
P_HTM[3577]="*Ayaṃ kho sā, mārisa, āṭānāṭiyā rakkhā bhikkhūnaṃ bhikkhunīnaṃ upāsakānaṃ upāsikānaṃ guttiyā rakkhāya avihiṃsāya phāsuvihārāya.**This, dear sir, is the Āṭānāṭiya protection for the guarding, protection, safety, and comfort of the monks, nuns, laymen, and laywomen.*";
P_HTM[3578]="*Yassa kassaci, mārisa, bhikkhussa vā bhikkhuniyā vā upāsakassa vā upāsikāya vā ayaṃ āṭānāṭiyā rakkhā suggahitā bhavissati samattā pariyāputā.**The monks, nuns, laymen, and laywomen should learn this Āṭānāṭiya protection well and completely memorize it.*";
P_HTM[3579]="*Tañce amanusso yakkho vā yakkhinī vā yakkhapotako vā yakkhapotikā vā yakkhamahāmatto vā yakkhapārisajjo vā yakkhapacāro vā, gandhabbo vā gandhabbī vā gandhabbapotako vā gandhabbapotikā vā gandhabbamahāmatto vā gandhabbapārisajjo vā gandhabbapacāro vā, kumbhaṇḍo vā kumbhaṇḍī vā kumbhaṇḍapotako vā kumbhaṇḍapotikā vā kumbhaṇḍamahāmatto vā kumbhaṇḍapārisajjo vā kumbhaṇḍapacāro vā, nāgo vā nāgī vā nāgapotako vā nāgapotikā vā nāgamahāmatto vā nāgapārisajjo vā nāgapacāro vā, paduṭṭhacitto bhikkhuṃ vā bhikkhuniṃ vā upāsakaṃ vā upāsikaṃ vā gacchantaṃ vā anugaccheyya, ṭhitaṃ vā upatiṭṭheyya, nisinnaṃ vā upanisīdeyya, nipannaṃ vā upanipajjeyya.**If anyone who does so is approached while walking, standing, sitting, or lying down by any non-human being with malicious intent—including males, females, boys, girls, ministers, counselors, and servants among the spirits, fairies, goblins, and dragons—*";
P_HTM[3580]="*Na me so, mārisa, amanusso labheyya gāmesu vā nigamesu vā sakkāraṃ vā garukāraṃ vā.**that non-human will receive no homage or respect in any village or town.*";
P_HTM[3581]="*Na me so, mārisa, amanusso labheyya āḷakamandāya nāma rājadhāniyā vatthuṃ vā vāsaṃ vā.**And they will receive no ground or dwelling in my capital of Ālakamandā.*";
P_HTM[3582]="*Na me so, mārisa, amanusso labheyya yakkhānaṃ samitiṃ gantuṃ.**Nor will they get to go to the conference of the spirits.*";
P_HTM[3583]="*Apissu naṃ, mārisa, amanussā anāvayhampi naṃ kareyyuṃ avivayhaṃ.**In addition, the non-humans would not give or take them in marriage.*";
P_HTM[3584]="*Apissu naṃ, mārisa, amanussā attāhipi paripuṇṇāhi paribhāsāhi paribhāseyyuṃ.**They’d heap personal abuse on them,*";
P_HTM[3585]="*Apissu naṃ, mārisa, amanussā rittampissa pattaṃ sīse nikkujjeyyuṃ.**drop an empty bowl on their head,*";
P_HTM[3586]="*Apissu naṃ, mārisa, amanussā sattadhāpissa muddhaṃ phāleyyuṃ.**and even split their head into seven pieces!*";
P_HTM[3587]="*Santi hi, mārisa, amanussā caṇḍā ruddhā rabhasā, te neva mahārājānaṃ ādiyanti, na mahārājānaṃ purisakānaṃ ādiyanti, na mahārājānaṃ purisakānaṃ purisakānaṃ ādiyanti.**For there are, dear sir, non-humans who are fierce, cruel, and violent. They don’t obey the Great Kings or their men or their men’s men.*";
P_HTM[3588]="*Te kho te, mārisa, amanussā mahārājānaṃ avaruddhā nāma vuccanti.**They’re said to be rebelling against the Great Kings.*";
P_HTM[3589]="*Seyyathāpi, mārisa, rañño māgadhassa vijite mahācorā.**They’re just like the bandits in the king of Magadha’s realm*";
P_HTM[3590]="*Te neva rañño māgadhassa ādiyanti, na rañño māgadhassa purisakānaṃ ādiyanti, na rañño māgadhassa purisakānaṃ purisakānaṃ ādiyanti.**who don’t obey the king, his men, or his men’s men,*";
P_HTM[3591]="*Te kho te, mārisa, mahācorā rañño māgadhassa avaruddhā nāma vuccanti.**and are said to be rebelling against the king.*";
P_HTM[3592]="*Evameva kho, mārisa, santi amanussā caṇḍā ruddhā rabhasā, te neva mahārājānaṃ ādiyanti, na mahārājānaṃ purisakānaṃ ādiyanti, na mahārājānaṃ purisakānaṃ purisakānaṃ ādiyanti.* **";
P_HTM[3593]="*Te kho te, mārisa, amanussā mahārājānaṃ avaruddhā nāma vuccanti.* **";
P_HTM[3594]="*Yo hi koci, mārisa, amanusso yakkho vā yakkhinī vā … pe … gandhabbo vā gandhabbī vā … pe … kumbhaṇḍo vā kumbhaṇḍī vā … pe … nāgo vā nāgī vā nāgapotako vā nāgapotikā vā nāgamahāmatto vā nāgapārisajjo vā nāgapacāro vā paduṭṭhacitto bhikkhuṃ vā bhikkhuniṃ vā upāsakaṃ vā upāsikaṃ vā gacchantaṃ vā anugaccheyya, ṭhitaṃ vā upatiṭṭheyya, nisinnaṃ vā upanisīdeyya, nipannaṃ vā upanipajjeyya.**If any non-human being with malicious intent—including males, females, boys, girls, ministers, counselors, and servants among the spirits, fairies, goblins, and dragons—approaches a monk, nun, layman, or laywoman while walking, standing, sitting, or lying down,*";
P_HTM[3595]="*Imesaṃ yakkhānaṃ mahāyakkhānaṃ senāpatīnaṃ mahāsenāpatīnaṃ ujjhāpetabbaṃ vikkanditabbaṃ viravitabbaṃ:**one ought to yell, cry, and scream to the spirits, great spirits, generals, great generals:*";
P_HTM[3596]="*‘ayaṃ yakkho gaṇhāti, ayaṃ yakkho āvisati, ayaṃ yakkho heṭheti, ayaṃ yakkho viheṭheti, ayaṃ yakkho hiṃsati, ayaṃ yakkho vihiṃsati, ayaṃ yakkho na muñcatī’ti.**‘This spirit’s got me! This spirit’s entered me! This spirit’s annoying me! This spirit’s harassing me! This spirit’s hurting me! This spirit’s harming me! This spirit won’t let me go!’*";
P_HTM[3597]="*Katamesaṃ yakkhānaṃ mahāyakkhānaṃ senāpatīnaṃ mahāsenāpatīnaṃ?**To what spirits, great spirits, generals, great generals?*";
P_HTM[3598]="*Indo somo varuṇo ca,**‘Inda, Soma, and Varuṇa,*";
P_HTM[3599]="*bhāradvājo pajāpati;**Bhāradvāja, Pajāpati,*";
P_HTM[3600]="*Candano kāmaseṭṭho ca,**Candana and Kāmaseṭṭha,*";
P_HTM[3601]="*kinnughaṇḍu nighaṇḍu ca.**Kinnughaṇḍu and Nighaṇḍu,*";
P_HTM[3602]="*Panādo opamañño ca,**Panāda and Opamañña,*";
P_HTM[3603]="*devasūto ca mātali;**and Mātali, the god’s charioteer.*";
P_HTM[3604]="*Cittaseno ca gandhabbo,**Cittasena the fairy,*";
P_HTM[3605]="*naḷo rājā janesabho.**and the kings Nala and Janesabha,*";
P_HTM[3606]="*Sātāgiro hemavato,**Sātāgira, Hemavata,*";
P_HTM[3607]="*puṇṇako karatiyo guḷo;**Puṇṇaka, Karatiya, and Guḷa;*";
P_HTM[3608]="*Sivako mucalindo ca,**Sivaka and Mucalinda,*";
P_HTM[3609]="*vessāmitto yugandharo.**Vessāmitta, Yugandhara,*";
P_HTM[3610]="*Gopālo supparodho ca,**Gopāla, Supparodha,*";
P_HTM[3611]="*Hiri netti ca mandiyo;**Hiri, Netti, and Mandiya;*";
P_HTM[3612]="*Pañcālacaṇḍo āḷavako,**Pañcālacaṇḍa, Āḷavaka,*";
P_HTM[3613]="*Pajjunno sumano sumukho;**Pajjunna, Sumana, Sumukha,*";
P_HTM[3614]="*Dadhimukho maṇi māṇivaro dīgho,**Dadhimukha, Maṇi, Māṇivara, Dīgha,*";
P_HTM[3615]="*Atho serīsako saha.**together with Serīsaka.’*";
P_HTM[3616]="*Imesaṃ yakkhānaṃ mahāyakkhānaṃ senāpatīnaṃ mahāsenāpatīnaṃ ujjhāpetabbaṃ vikkanditabbaṃ viravitabbaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[3617]="*‘ayaṃ yakkho gaṇhāti, ayaṃ yakkho āvisati, ayaṃ yakkho heṭheti, ayaṃ yakkho viheṭheti, ayaṃ yakkho hiṃsati, ayaṃ yakkho vihiṃsati, ayaṃ yakkho na muñcatī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3618]="*Ayaṃ kho sā, mārisa, āṭānāṭiyā rakkhā bhikkhūnaṃ bhikkhunīnaṃ upāsakānaṃ upāsikānaṃ guttiyā rakkhāya avihiṃsāya phāsuvihārāya.**This, dear sir, is the Āṭānāṭiya protection for the guarding, protection, safety, and comfort of the monks, nuns, laymen, and laywomen.*";
P_HTM[3619]="*Handa ca dāni mayaṃ, mārisa, gacchāma bahukiccā mayaṃ bahukaraṇīyā”ti.**Well, now, dear sir, I must go. I have many duties, and much to do.”*";
P_HTM[3620]="*“Yassadāni tumhe, mahārājāno, kālaṃ maññathā”ti.**“Please, Great Kings, go at your convenience.”*";
P_HTM[3621]="*Atha kho cattāro mahārājā uṭṭhāyāsanā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā tatthevantaradhāyiṃsu.**Then the Four Great Kings got up from their seats, bowed, and respectfully circled the Buddha, keeping him on their right side, before vanishing right there.*";
P_HTM[3622]="*Tepi kho yakkhā uṭṭhāyāsanā appekacce bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā tatthevantaradhāyiṃsu. Appekacce bhagavatā saddhiṃ sammodiṃsu, sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā tatthevantaradhāyiṃsu. Appekacce yena bhagavā tenañjaliṃ paṇāmetvā tatthevantaradhāyiṃsu. Appekacce nāmagottaṃ sāvetvā tatthevantaradhāyiṃsu. Appekacce tuṇhībhūtā tatthevantaradhāyiṃsūti.**And before the other spirits present vanished, some bowed and respectfully circled the Buddha, keeping him on their right side, some exchanged greetings and polite conversation, some held up their joined palms toward the Buddha, some announced their name and clan, while some kept silent.*";
P_HTM[3623]="*Paṭhamabhāṇavāro niṭṭhito.**The first recitation section is finished.*";
P_HTM[3624]="*2. Dutiyabhāṇavāra**2. The Second Recitation Section*";
P_HTM[3625]="*Atha kho bhagavā tassā rattiyā accayena bhikkhū āmantesi:**Then, when the night had passed, the Buddha told the mendicants all that had happened, repeating all the verses spoken. Then he added:*";
P_HTM[3626]="*“imaṃ, bhikkhave, rattiṃ cattāro mahārājā mahatiyā ca yakkhasenāya mahatiyā ca gandhabbasenāya mahatiyā ca kumbhaṇḍasenāya mahatiyā ca nāgasenāya catuddisaṃ rakkhaṃ ṭhapetvā catuddisaṃ gumbaṃ ṭhapetvā catuddisaṃ ovaraṇaṃ ṭhapetvā abhikkantāya rattiyā abhikkantavaṇṇā kevalakappaṃ gijjhakūṭaṃ pabbataṃ obhāsetvā yenāhaṃ tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā maṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu.* **";
P_HTM[3627]="*Tepi kho, bhikkhave, yakkhā appekacce maṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Appekacce mayā saddhiṃ sammodiṃsu, sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Appekacce yenāhaṃ tenañjaliṃ paṇāmetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Appekacce nāmagottaṃ sāvetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Appekacce tuṇhībhūtā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu.* **";
P_HTM[3628]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho, bhikkhave, vessavaṇo mahārājā maṃ etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[3629]="*‘santi hi, bhante, uḷārā yakkhā bhagavato appasannā … pe … santi hi, bhante, nīcā yakkhā bhagavato pasannā.* **";
P_HTM[3630]="*Yebhuyyena kho pana, bhante, yakkhā appasannāyeva bhagavato.* **";
P_HTM[3631]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?* **";
P_HTM[3632]="*Bhagavā hi, bhante, pāṇātipātā veramaṇiyā dhammaṃ deseti … surāmerayamajjappamādaṭṭhānā veramaṇiyā dhammaṃ deseti.* **";
P_HTM[3633]="*Yebhuyyena kho pana, bhante, yakkhā appaṭiviratāyeva pāṇātipātā … appaṭiviratā surāmerayamajjappamādaṭṭhānā.* **";
P_HTM[3634]="*Tesaṃ taṃ hoti appiyaṃ amanāpaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3635]="*Santi hi, bhante, bhagavato sāvakā araññavanapatthāni pantāni senāsanāni paṭisevanti appasaddāni appanigghosāni vijanavātāni manussarāhasseyyakāni paṭisallānasāruppāni.* **";
P_HTM[3636]="*Tattha santi uḷārā yakkhā nivāsino, ye imasmiṃ bhagavato pāvacane appasannā, tesaṃ pasādāya uggaṇhātu, bhante, bhagavā āṭānāṭiyaṃ rakkhaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ bhikkhunīnaṃ upāsakānaṃ upāsikānaṃ guttiyā rakkhāya avihiṃsāya phāsuvihārāyā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3637]="*Adhivāsesiṃ kho ahaṃ, bhikkhave, tuṇhībhāvena.* **";
P_HTM[3638]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, vessavaṇo mahārājā me adhivāsanaṃ viditvā tāyaṃ velāyaṃ imaṃ āṭānāṭiyaṃ rakkhaṃ abhāsi:* **";
P_HTM[3639]="*‘Vipassissa ca namatthu,* **";
P_HTM[3640]="*cakkhumantassa sirīmato;* **";
P_HTM[3641]="*Sikhissapi ca namatthu,* **";
P_HTM[3642]="*sabbabhūtānukampino.* **";
P_HTM[3643]="*Vessabhussa ca namatthu,* **";
P_HTM[3644]="*nhātakassa tapassino;* **";
P_HTM[3645]="*Namatthu kakusandhassa,* **";
P_HTM[3646]="*mārasenāpamaddino.* **";
P_HTM[3647]="*Koṇāgamanassa namatthu,* **";
P_HTM[3648]="*brāhmaṇassa vusīmato;* **";
P_HTM[3649]="*Kassapassa ca namatthu,* **";
P_HTM[3650]="*vippamuttassa sabbadhi.* **";
P_HTM[3651]="*Aṅgīrasassa namatthu,* **";
P_HTM[3652]="*sakyaputtassa sirīmato;* **";
P_HTM[3653]="*Yo imaṃ dhammaṃ desesi,* **";
P_HTM[3654]="*sabbadukkhāpanūdanaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3655]="*Ye cāpi nibbutā loke,* **";
P_HTM[3656]="*yathābhūtaṃ vipassisuṃ;* **";
P_HTM[3657]="*Te janā apisuṇātha,* **";
P_HTM[3658]="*mahantā vītasāradā.* **";
P_HTM[3659]="*Hitaṃ devamanussānaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[3660]="*yaṃ namassanti gotamaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[3661]="*Vijjācaraṇasampannaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[3662]="*mahantaṃ vītasāradaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3663]="*Yato uggacchati sūriyo,* **";
P_HTM[3664]="*ādicco maṇḍalī mahā;* **";
P_HTM[3665]="*Yassa cuggacchamānassa,* **";
P_HTM[3666]="*saṃvarīpi nirujjhati;* **";
P_HTM[3667]="*Yassa cuggate sūriye,* **";
P_HTM[3668]="*“divaso”ti pavuccati.* **";
P_HTM[3669]="*Rahadopi tattha gambhīro,* **";
P_HTM[3670]="*samuddo saritodako;* **";
P_HTM[3671]="*Evaṃ taṃ tattha jānanti,* **";
P_HTM[3672]="*“samuddo saritodako”.* **";
P_HTM[3673]="*Ito “sā purimā disā”,* **";
P_HTM[3674]="*iti naṃ ācikkhatī jano;* **";
P_HTM[3675]="*Yaṃ disaṃ abhipāleti,* **";
P_HTM[3676]="*mahārājā yasassi so.* **";
P_HTM[3677]="*Gandhabbānaṃ adhipati,* **";
P_HTM[3678]="*“dhataraṭṭho”ti nāmaso;* **";
P_HTM[3679]="*Ramatī naccagītehi,* **";
P_HTM[3680]="*gandhabbehi purakkhato.* **";
P_HTM[3681]="*Puttāpi tassa bahavo,* **";
P_HTM[3682]="*ekanāmāti me sutaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[3683]="*Asīti dasa eko ca,* **";
P_HTM[3684]="*indanāmā mahabbalā.* **";
P_HTM[3685]="*Te cāpi buddhaṃ disvāna,* **";
P_HTM[3686]="*buddhaṃ ādiccabandhunaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[3687]="*Dūratova namassanti,* **";
P_HTM[3688]="*mahantaṃ vītasāradaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3689]="*Namo te purisājañña,* **";
P_HTM[3690]="*namo te purisuttama;* **";
P_HTM[3691]="*Kusalena samekkhasi,* **";
P_HTM[3692]="*amanussāpi taṃ vandanti;* **";
P_HTM[3693]="*Sutaṃ netaṃ abhiṇhaso,* **";
P_HTM[3694]="*tasmā evaṃ vademase.* **";
P_HTM[3695]="*“Jinaṃ vandatha gotamaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[3696]="*jinaṃ vandāma gotamaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[3697]="*Vijjācaraṇasampannaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[3698]="*buddhaṃ vandāma gotamaṃ”.* **";
P_HTM[3699]="*Yena petā pavuccanti,* **";
P_HTM[3700]="*pisuṇā piṭṭhimaṃsikā;* **";
P_HTM[3701]="*Pāṇātipātino luddā,* **";
P_HTM[3702]="*corā nekatikā janā.* **";
P_HTM[3703]="*Ito “sā dakkhiṇā disā”,* **";
P_HTM[3704]="*iti naṃ ācikkhatī jano;* **";
P_HTM[3705]="*Yaṃ disaṃ abhipāleti,* **";
P_HTM[3706]="*mahārājā yasassi so.* **";
P_HTM[3707]="*Kumbhaṇḍānaṃ adhipati,* **";
P_HTM[3708]="*“virūḷho” iti nāmaso;* **";
P_HTM[3709]="*Ramatī naccagītehi,* **";
P_HTM[3710]="*kumbhaṇḍehi purakkhato.* **";
P_HTM[3711]="*Puttāpi tassa bahavo,* **";
P_HTM[3712]="*ekanāmāti me sutaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[3713]="*Asīti dasa eko ca,* **";
P_HTM[3714]="*indanāmā mahabbalā.* **";
P_HTM[3715]="*Te cāpi buddhaṃ disvāna,* **";
P_HTM[3716]="*buddhaṃ ādiccabandhunaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[3717]="*Dūratova namassanti,* **";
P_HTM[3718]="*mahantaṃ vītasāradaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3719]="*Namo te purisājañña,* **";
P_HTM[3720]="*namo te purisuttama;* **";
P_HTM[3721]="*Kusalena samekkhasi,* **";
P_HTM[3722]="*amanussāpi taṃ vandanti;* **";
P_HTM[3723]="*Sutaṃ netaṃ abhiṇhaso,* **";
P_HTM[3724]="*tasmā evaṃ vademase.* **";
P_HTM[3725]="*“Jinaṃ vandatha gotamaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[3726]="*jinaṃ vandāma gotamaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[3727]="*Vijjācaraṇasampannaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[3728]="*buddhaṃ vandāma gotamaṃ”.* **";
P_HTM[3729]="*Yattha coggacchati sūriyo,* **";
P_HTM[3730]="*ādicco maṇḍalī mahā;* **";
P_HTM[3731]="*Yassa coggacchamānassa,* **";
P_HTM[3732]="*divasopi nirujjhati;* **";
P_HTM[3733]="*Yassa coggate sūriye,* **";
P_HTM[3734]="*“saṃvarī”ti pavuccati.* **";
P_HTM[3735]="*Rahadopi tattha gambhīro,* **";
P_HTM[3736]="*samuddo saritodako;* **";
P_HTM[3737]="*Evaṃ taṃ tattha jānanti,* **";
P_HTM[3738]="*samuddo saritodako.* **";
P_HTM[3739]="*Ito “sā pacchimā disā”,* **";
P_HTM[3740]="*iti naṃ ācikkhatī jano;* **";
P_HTM[3741]="*Yaṃ disaṃ abhipāleti,* **";
P_HTM[3742]="*mahārājā yasassi so.* **";
P_HTM[3743]="*Nāgānañca adhipati,* **";
P_HTM[3744]="*“virūpakkho”ti nāmaso;* **";
P_HTM[3745]="*Ramatī naccagītehi,* **";
P_HTM[3746]="*nāgeheva purakkhato.* **";
P_HTM[3747]="*Puttāpi tassa bahavo,* **";
P_HTM[3748]="*ekanāmāti me sutaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[3749]="*Asīti dasa eko ca,* **";
P_HTM[3750]="*indanāmā mahabbalā.* **";
P_HTM[3751]="*Te cāpi buddhaṃ disvāna,* **";
P_HTM[3752]="*buddhaṃ ādiccabandhunaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[3753]="*Dūratova namassanti,* **";
P_HTM[3754]="*mahantaṃ vītasāradaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3755]="*Namo te purisājañña,* **";
P_HTM[3756]="*namo te purisuttama;* **";
P_HTM[3757]="*Kusalena samekkhasi,* **";
P_HTM[3758]="*amanussāpi taṃ vandanti;* **";
P_HTM[3759]="*Sutaṃ netaṃ abhiṇhaso,* **";
P_HTM[3760]="*tasmā evaṃ vademase.* **";
P_HTM[3761]="*“Jinaṃ vandatha gotamaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[3762]="*jinaṃ vandāma gotamaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[3763]="*Vijjācaraṇasampannaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[3764]="*buddhaṃ vandāma gotamaṃ”.* **";
P_HTM[3765]="*Yena uttarakuruvho,* **";
P_HTM[3766]="*mahāneru sudassano;* **";
P_HTM[3767]="*Manussā tattha jāyanti,* **";
P_HTM[3768]="*amamā apariggahā.* **";
P_HTM[3769]="*Na te bījaṃ pavapanti,* **";
P_HTM[3770]="*nāpi nīyanti naṅgalā;* **";
P_HTM[3771]="*Akaṭṭhapākimaṃ sāliṃ,* **";
P_HTM[3772]="*paribhuñjanti mānusā.* **";
P_HTM[3773]="*Akaṇaṃ athusaṃ suddhaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[3774]="*sugandhaṃ taṇḍulapphalaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[3775]="*Tuṇḍikīre pacitvāna,* **";
P_HTM[3776]="*tato bhuñjanti bhojanaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3777]="*Gāviṃ ekakhuraṃ katvā,* **";
P_HTM[3778]="*anuyanti disodisaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[3779]="*Pasuṃ ekakhuraṃ katvā,* **";
P_HTM[3780]="*anuyanti disodisaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3781]="*Itthiṃ vā vāhanaṃ katvā,* **";
P_HTM[3782]="*anuyanti disodisaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[3783]="*Purisaṃ vāhanaṃ katvā,* **";
P_HTM[3784]="*anuyanti disodisaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3785]="*Kumāriṃ vāhanaṃ katvā,* **";
P_HTM[3786]="*anuyanti disodisaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[3787]="*Kumāraṃ vāhanaṃ katvā,* **";
P_HTM[3788]="*anuyanti disodisaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3789]="*Te yāne abhiruhitvā,* **";
P_HTM[3790]="*Sabbā disā anupariyāyanti;* **";
P_HTM[3791]="*Pacārā tassa rājino.* **";
P_HTM[3792]="*Hatthiyānaṃ assayānaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[3793]="*dibbaṃ yānaṃ upaṭṭhitaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[3794]="*Pāsādā sivikā ceva,* **";
P_HTM[3795]="*mahārājassa yasassino.* **";
P_HTM[3796]="*Tassa ca nagarā ahu,* **";
P_HTM[3797]="*Antalikkhe sumāpitā;* **";
P_HTM[3798]="*Āṭānāṭā kusināṭā parakusināṭā,* **";
P_HTM[3799]="*Nāṭasuriyā parakusiṭanāṭā.* **";
P_HTM[3800]="*Uttarena kasivanto,* **";
P_HTM[3801]="*Janoghamaparena ca;* **";
P_HTM[3802]="*Navanavutiyo ambaraambaravatiyo,* **";
P_HTM[3803]="*Āḷakamandā nāma rājadhānī.* **";
P_HTM[3804]="*Kuverassa kho pana mārisa,* **";
P_HTM[3805]="*Mahārājassa visāṇā nāma rājadhānī;* **";
P_HTM[3806]="*Tasmā kuvero mahārājā,* **";
P_HTM[3807]="*“Vessavaṇo”ti pavuccati.* **";
P_HTM[3808]="*Paccesanto pakāsenti,* **";
P_HTM[3809]="*Tatolā tattalā tatotalā;* **";
P_HTM[3810]="*Ojasi tejasi tatojasī,* **";
P_HTM[3811]="*Sūro rājā ariṭṭho nemi.* **";
P_HTM[3812]="*Rahadopi tattha dharaṇī nāma,* **";
P_HTM[3813]="*Yato meghā pavassanti;* **";
P_HTM[3814]="*Vassā yato patāyanti,* **";
P_HTM[3815]="*Sabhāpi tattha sālavatī nāma.* **";
P_HTM[3816]="*Yattha yakkhā payirupāsanti,* **";
P_HTM[3817]="*Tattha niccaphalā rukkhā;* **";
P_HTM[3818]="*Nānā dijagaṇā yutā,* **";
P_HTM[3819]="*Mayūrakoñcābhirudā;* **";
P_HTM[3820]="*Kokilādīhi vagguhi.* **";
P_HTM[3821]="*Jīvañjīvakasaddettha,* **";
P_HTM[3822]="*atho oṭṭhavacittakā;* **";
P_HTM[3823]="*Kukkuṭakā kuḷīrakā,* **";
P_HTM[3824]="*vane pokkharasātakā.* **";
P_HTM[3825]="*Sukasāḷika saddettha,* **";
P_HTM[3826]="*daṇḍamāṇavakāni ca;* **";
P_HTM[3827]="*Sobhati sabbakālaṃ sā,* **";
P_HTM[3828]="*kuveranaḷinī sadā.* **";
P_HTM[3829]="*Ito “sā uttarā disā”,* **";
P_HTM[3830]="*iti naṃ ācikkhatī jano;* **";
P_HTM[3831]="*Yaṃ disaṃ abhipāleti,* **";
P_HTM[3832]="*mahārājā yasassi so.* **";
P_HTM[3833]="*Yakkhānañca adhipati,* **";
P_HTM[3834]="*“kuvero” iti nāmaso;* **";
P_HTM[3835]="*Ramatī naccagītehi,* **";
P_HTM[3836]="*yakkheheva purakkhato.* **";
P_HTM[3837]="*Puttāpi tassa bahavo,* **";
P_HTM[3838]="*ekanāmāti me sutaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[3839]="*Asīti dasa eko ca,* **";
P_HTM[3840]="*indanāmā mahabbalā.* **";
P_HTM[3841]="*Te cāpi buddhaṃ disvāna,* **";
P_HTM[3842]="*buddhaṃ ādiccabandhunaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[3843]="*Dūratova namassanti,* **";
P_HTM[3844]="*mahantaṃ vītasāradaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3845]="*Namo te purisājañña,* **";
P_HTM[3846]="*namo te purisuttama;* **";
P_HTM[3847]="*Kusalena samekkhasi,* **";
P_HTM[3848]="*amanussāpi taṃ vandanti;* **";
P_HTM[3849]="*Sutaṃ netaṃ abhiṇhaso,* **";
P_HTM[3850]="*tasmā evaṃ vademase.* **";
P_HTM[3851]="*“Jinaṃ vandatha gotamaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[3852]="*jinaṃ vandāma gotamaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[3853]="*Vijjācaraṇasampannaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[3854]="*buddhaṃ vandāma gotaman”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3855]="*Ayaṃ kho sā, mārisa, āṭānāṭiyā rakkhā bhikkhūnaṃ bhikkhunīnaṃ upāsakānaṃ upāsikānaṃ guttiyā rakkhāya avihiṃsāya phāsuvihārāya.* **";
P_HTM[3856]="*Yassa kassaci, mārisa, bhikkhussa vā bhikkhuniyā vā upāsakassa vā upāsikāya vā ayaṃ āṭānāṭiyā rakkhā suggahitā bhavissati samattā pariyāputā tañce amanusso yakkho vā yakkhinī vā … pe … gandhabbo vā gandhabbī vā … pe … kumbhaṇḍo vā kumbhaṇḍī vā … pe … nāgo vā nāgī vā nāgapotako vā nāgapotikā vā nāgamahāmatto vā nāgapārisajjo vā nāgapacāro vā, paduṭṭhacitto bhikkhuṃ vā bhikkhuniṃ vā upāsakaṃ vā upāsikaṃ vā gacchantaṃ vā anugaccheyya, ṭhitaṃ vā upatiṭṭheyya, nisinnaṃ vā upanisīdeyya, nipannaṃ vā upanipajjeyya.* **";
P_HTM[3857]="*Na me so, mārisa, amanusso labheyya gāmesu vā nigamesu vā sakkāraṃ vā garukāraṃ vā.* **";
P_HTM[3858]="*Na me so, mārisa, amanusso labheyya āḷakamandāya nāma rājadhāniyā vatthuṃ vā vāsaṃ vā.* **";
P_HTM[3859]="*Na me so, mārisa, amanusso labheyya yakkhānaṃ samitiṃ gantuṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3860]="*Apissu naṃ, mārisa, amanussā anāvayhampi naṃ kareyyuṃ avivayhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3861]="*Apissu naṃ, mārisa, amanussā attāhi paripuṇṇāhi paribhāsāhi paribhāseyyuṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3862]="*Apissu naṃ, mārisa, amanussā rittampissa pattaṃ sīse nikkujjeyyuṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3863]="*Apissu naṃ, mārisa, amanussā sattadhāpissa muddhaṃ phāleyyuṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3864]="*Santi hi, mārisa, amanussā caṇḍā ruddhā rabhasā, te neva mahārājānaṃ ādiyanti, na mahārājānaṃ purisakānaṃ ādiyanti, na mahārājānaṃ purisakānaṃ purisakānaṃ ādiyanti.* **";
P_HTM[3865]="*Te kho te, mārisa, amanussā mahārājānaṃ avaruddhā nāma vuccanti.* **";
P_HTM[3866]="*Seyyathāpi, mārisa, rañño māgadhassa vijite mahācorā.* **";
P_HTM[3867]="*Te neva rañño māgadhassa ādiyanti, na rañño māgadhassa purisakānaṃ ādiyanti, na rañño māgadhassa purisakānaṃ purisakānaṃ ādiyanti.* **";
P_HTM[3868]="*Te kho te, mārisa, mahācorā rañño māgadhassa avaruddhā nāma vuccanti.* **";
P_HTM[3869]="*Evameva kho, mārisa, santi amanussā caṇḍā ruddhā rabhasā, te neva mahārājānaṃ ādiyanti, na mahārājānaṃ purisakānaṃ ādiyanti, na mahārājānaṃ purisakānaṃ purisakānaṃ ādiyanti.* **";
P_HTM[3870]="*Te kho te, mārisa, amanussā mahārājānaṃ avaruddhā nāma vuccanti.* **";
P_HTM[3871]="*Yo hi koci, mārisa, amanusso yakkho vā yakkhinī vā … pe … gandhabbo vā gandhabbī vā … pe … kumbhaṇḍo vā kumbhaṇḍī vā … pe … nāgo vā nāgī vā … pe … paduṭṭhacitto bhikkhuṃ vā bhikkhuniṃ vā upāsakaṃ vā upāsikaṃ vā gacchantaṃ vā upagaccheyya, ṭhitaṃ vā upatiṭṭheyya, nisinnaṃ vā upanisīdeyya, nipannaṃ vā upanipajjeyya.* **";
P_HTM[3872]="*Imesaṃ yakkhānaṃ mahāyakkhānaṃ senāpatīnaṃ mahāsenāpatīnaṃ ujjhāpetabbaṃ vikkanditabbaṃ viravitabbaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[3873]="*“ayaṃ yakkho gaṇhāti, ayaṃ yakkho āvisati, ayaṃ yakkho heṭheti, ayaṃ yakkho viheṭheti, ayaṃ yakkho hiṃsati, ayaṃ yakkho vihiṃsati, ayaṃ yakkho na muñcatī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3874]="*Katamesaṃ yakkhānaṃ mahāyakkhānaṃ senāpatīnaṃ mahāsenāpatīnaṃ?* **";
P_HTM[3875]="*Indo somo varuṇo ca,* **";
P_HTM[3876]="*bhāradvājo pajāpati;* **";
P_HTM[3877]="*Candano kāmaseṭṭho ca,* **";
P_HTM[3878]="*kinnughaṇḍu nighaṇḍu ca.* **";
P_HTM[3879]="*Panādo opamañño ca,* **";
P_HTM[3880]="*devasūto ca mātali;* **";
P_HTM[3881]="*Cittaseno ca gandhabbo,* **";
P_HTM[3882]="*naḷo rājā janesabho.* **";
P_HTM[3883]="*Sātāgiro hemavato,* **";
P_HTM[3884]="*puṇṇako karatiyo guḷo;* **";
P_HTM[3885]="*Sivako mucalindo ca,* **";
P_HTM[3886]="*vessāmitto yugandharo.* **";
P_HTM[3887]="*Gopālo supparodho ca,* **";
P_HTM[3888]="*Hiri netti ca mandiyo;* **";
P_HTM[3889]="*Pañcālacaṇḍo āḷavako,* **";
P_HTM[3890]="*Pajjunno sumano sumukho;* **";
P_HTM[3891]="*Dadhimukho maṇi māṇivaro dīgho,* **";
P_HTM[3892]="*Atho serīsako saha.* **";
P_HTM[3893]="*Imesaṃ yakkhānaṃ mahāyakkhānaṃ senāpatīnaṃ mahāsenāpatīnaṃ ujjhāpetabbaṃ vikkanditabbaṃ viravitabbaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[3894]="*“ayaṃ yakkho gaṇhāti, ayaṃ yakkho āvisati, ayaṃ yakkho heṭheti, ayaṃ yakkho viheṭheti, ayaṃ yakkho hiṃsati, ayaṃ yakkho vihiṃsati, ayaṃ yakkho na muñcatī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3895]="*Ayaṃ kho, mārisa, āṭānāṭiyā rakkhā bhikkhūnaṃ bhikkhunīnaṃ upāsakānaṃ upāsikānaṃ guttiyā rakkhāya avihiṃsāya phāsuvihārāya.* **";
P_HTM[3896]="*Handa ca dāni mayaṃ, mārisa, gacchāma, bahukiccā mayaṃ bahukaraṇīyā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3897]="*‘Yassadāni tumhe, mahārājāno, kālaṃ maññathā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3898]="*Atha kho, bhikkhave, cattāro mahārājā uṭṭhāyāsanā maṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā tatthevantaradhāyiṃsu.* **";
P_HTM[3899]="*Tepi kho, bhikkhave, yakkhā uṭṭhāyāsanā appekacce maṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā tatthevantaradhāyiṃsu.* **";
P_HTM[3900]="*Appekacce mayā saddhiṃ sammodiṃsu, sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā tatthevantaradhāyiṃsu.* **";
P_HTM[3901]="*Appekacce yenāhaṃ tenañjaliṃ paṇāmetvā tatthevantaradhāyiṃsu.* **";
P_HTM[3902]="*Appekacce nāmagottaṃ sāvetvā tatthevantaradhāyiṃsu.* **";
P_HTM[3903]="*Appekacce tuṇhībhūtā tatthevantaradhāyiṃsu.* **";
P_HTM[3904]="*Uggaṇhātha, bhikkhave, āṭānāṭiyaṃ rakkhaṃ.**“Mendicants, learn the Āṭānāṭiya protection!*";
P_HTM[3905]="*Pariyāpuṇātha, bhikkhave, āṭānāṭiyaṃ rakkhaṃ.**Memorize the Āṭānāṭiya protection!*";
P_HTM[3906]="*Dhāretha, bhikkhave, āṭānāṭiyaṃ rakkhaṃ.**Remember the Āṭānāṭiya protection!*";
P_HTM[3907]="*Atthasaṃhitā, bhikkhave, āṭānāṭiyā rakkhā bhikkhūnaṃ bhikkhunīnaṃ upāsakānaṃ upāsikānaṃ guttiyā rakkhāya avihiṃsāya phāsuvihārāyā”ti.**The Āṭānāṭiya protection is beneficial, and is for the guarding, protection, safety, and comfort of the monks, nuns, laymen, and laywomen.”*";
P_HTM[3908]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[3909]="*Attamanā te bhikkhū bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, the mendicants were happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[3910]="*Āṭānāṭiyasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3911]="*33. Saṅgītisutta  - Reciting in Concert * **";
P_HTM[3912]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[3913]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā mallesu cārikaṃ caramāno mahatā bhikkhusaṅghena saddhiṃ pañcamattehi bhikkhusatehi yena pāvā nāma mallānaṃ nagaraṃ tadavasari.**At one time the Buddha was wandering in the land of the Mallas together with a large Saṅgha of five hundred mendicants when he arrived at a Mallian town named Pāvā.*";
P_HTM[3914]="*Tatra sudaṃ bhagavā pāvāyaṃ viharati cundassa kammāraputtassa ambavane.**There he stayed in Cunda the smith’s mango grove.*";
P_HTM[3915]="*Tena kho pana samayena pāveyyakānaṃ mallānaṃ ubbhatakaṃ nāma navaṃ sandhāgāraṃ acirakāritaṃ hoti anajjhāvuṭṭhaṃ samaṇena vā brāhmaṇena vā kenaci vā manussabhūtena.**Now at that time a new town hall named Ubbhaṭaka had recently been constructed for the Mallas of Pāvā. It had not yet been occupied by an ascetic or brahmin or any person at all.*";
P_HTM[3916]="*Assosuṃ kho pāveyyakā mallā: “bhagavā kira mallesu cārikaṃ caramāno mahatā bhikkhusaṃghena saddhiṃ pañcamattehi bhikkhusatehi pāvaṃ anuppatto pāvāyaṃ viharati cundassa kammāraputtassa ambavane”ti.**The Mallas of Pāvā also heard that the Buddha had arrived and was staying in Cunda’s mango grove.*";
P_HTM[3917]="*Atha kho pāveyyakā mallā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinnā kho pāveyyakā mallā bhagavantaṃ etadavocuṃ:**Then they went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him,*";
P_HTM[3918]="*“idha, bhante, pāveyyakānaṃ mallānaṃ ubbhatakaṃ nāma navaṃ sandhāgāraṃ acirakāritaṃ hoti anajjhāvuṭṭhaṃ samaṇena vā brāhmaṇena vā kenaci vā manussabhūtena.**“Sir, a new town hall named Ubbhaṭaka has recently been constructed for the Mallas of Pāvā. It has not yet been occupied by an ascetic or brahmin or any person at all.*";
P_HTM[3919]="*Tañca kho, bhante, bhagavā paṭhamaṃ paribhuñjatu, bhagavatā paṭhamaṃ paribhuttaṃ pacchā pāveyyakā mallā paribhuñjissanti.**May the Buddha be the first to use it, and only then will the Mallas of Pāvā use it.*";
P_HTM[3920]="*Tadassa pāveyyakānaṃ mallānaṃ dīgharattaṃ hitāya sukhāyā”ti.**That would be for the lasting welfare and happiness of the Mallas of Pāvā.”*";
P_HTM[3921]="*Adhivāsesi kho bhagavā tuṇhībhāvena.**The Buddha consented in silence.*";
P_HTM[3922]="*Atha kho pāveyyakā mallā bhagavato adhivāsanaṃ viditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā yena sandhāgāraṃ tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā sabbasanthariṃ sandhāgāraṃ santharitvā bhagavato āsanāni paññāpetvā udakamaṇikaṃ patiṭṭhapetvā telapadīpaṃ āropetvā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu;**Then, knowing that the Buddha had consented, the Mallas got up from their seat, bowed, and respectfully circled the Buddha, keeping him on their right. Then they went to the new town hall, where they spread carpets all over, prepared seats, set up a water jar, and placed a lamp. Then they went back to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[3923]="*upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhaṃsu.**bowed, stood to one side,*";
P_HTM[3924]="*Ekamantaṃ ṭhitā kho te pāveyyakā mallā bhagavantaṃ etadavocuṃ:**and told him of their preparations, saying,*";
P_HTM[3925]="*“sabbasantharisanthataṃ, bhante, sandhāgāraṃ, bhagavato āsanāni paññattāni, udakamaṇiko patiṭṭhāpito, telapadīpo āropito.* **";
P_HTM[3926]="*Yassadāni, bhante, bhagavā kālaṃ maññatī”ti.**“Please, sir, come at your convenience.”*";
P_HTM[3927]="*Atha kho bhagavā nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya saddhiṃ bhikkhusaṅghena yena sandhāgāraṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā pāde pakkhāletvā sandhāgāraṃ pavisitvā majjhimaṃ thambhaṃ nissāya puratthābhimukho nisīdi.**Then the Buddha robed up and, taking his bowl and robe, went to the new town hall together with the Saṅgha of mendicants. Having washed his feet he entered the town hall and sat against the central column facing east.*";
P_HTM[3928]="*Bhikkhusaṅghopi kho pāde pakkhāletvā sandhāgāraṃ pavisitvā pacchimaṃ bhittiṃ nissāya puratthābhimukho nisīdi bhagavantaṃyeva purakkhatvā.**The Saṅgha of mendicants also washed their feet, entered the town hall, and sat against the west wall facing east, with the Buddha right in front of them.*";
P_HTM[3929]="*Pāveyyakāpi kho mallā pāde pakkhāletvā sandhāgāraṃ pavisitvā puratthimaṃ bhittiṃ nissāya pacchimābhimukhā nisīdiṃsu bhagavantaṃyeva purakkhatvā.**The Mallas of Pāvā also washed their feet, entered the town hall, and sat against the east wall facing west, with the Buddha right in front of them.*";
P_HTM[3930]="*Atha kho bhagavā pāveyyake malle bahudeva rattiṃ dhammiyā kathāya sandassetvā samādapetvā samuttejetvā sampahaṃsetvā uyyojesi:**The Buddha spent most of the night educating, encouraging, firing up, and inspiring the Mallas with a Dhamma talk. Then he dismissed them,*";
P_HTM[3931]="*“abhikkantā kho, vāseṭṭhā, ratti.**“The night is getting late, Vāseṭṭhas.*";
P_HTM[3932]="*Yassadāni tumhe kālaṃ maññathā”ti.**Please go at your convenience.”*";
P_HTM[3933]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho pāveyyakā mallā bhagavato paṭissutvā uṭṭhāyāsanā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā pakkamiṃsu.**“Yes, sir,” replied the Mallas. They got up from their seat, bowed, and respectfully circled the Buddha, keeping him on their right, before leaving.*";
P_HTM[3934]="*Atha kho bhagavā acirapakkantesu pāveyyakesu mallesu tuṇhībhūtaṃ tuṇhībhūtaṃ bhikkhusaṃghaṃ anuviloketvā āyasmantaṃ sāriputtaṃ āmantesi:**Soon after they left, the Buddha looked around the Saṅgha of monks, who were so very silent. He addressed Venerable Sāriputta,*";
P_HTM[3935]="*“vigatathinamiddho kho, sāriputta, bhikkhusaṃgho.**“Sāriputta, the Saṅgha of mendicants is rid of dullness and drowsiness.*";
P_HTM[3936]="*Paṭibhātu taṃ, sāriputta, bhikkhūnaṃ dhammīkathā.**Give them some Dhamma talk as you feel inspired.*";
P_HTM[3937]="*Piṭṭhi me āgilāyati.**My back is sore,*";
P_HTM[3938]="*Tamahaṃ āyamissāmī”ti.**I’ll stretch it.”*";
P_HTM[3939]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho āyasmā sāriputto bhagavato paccassosi.**“Yes, sir,” Sāriputta replied.*";
P_HTM[3940]="*Atha kho bhagavā catugguṇaṃ saṅghāṭiṃ paññāpetvā dakkhiṇena passena sīhaseyyaṃ kappesi pāde pādaṃ accādhāya, sato sampajāno uṭṭhānasaññaṃ manasi karitvā.**And then the Buddha spread out his outer robe folded in four and laid down in the lion’s posture—on the right side, placing one foot on top of the other—mindful and aware, and focused on the time of getting up.*";
P_HTM[3941]="*Tena kho pana samayena nigaṇṭho nāṭaputto pāvāyaṃ adhunākālaṅkato hoti.**Now at that time the Nigaṇṭha Nātaputta had recently passed away at Pāvā.*";
P_HTM[3942]="*Tassa kālaṃkiriyāya bhinnā nigaṇṭhā dvedhikajātā bhaṇḍanajātā kalahajātā vivādāpannā aññamaññaṃ mukhasattīhi vitudantā viharanti:**With his passing the Jain ascetics split, dividing into two factions, arguing, quarreling, and fighting, continually wounding each other with barbed words:*";
P_HTM[3943]="*“na tvaṃ imaṃ dhammavinayaṃ ājānāsi, ahaṃ imaṃ dhammavinayaṃ ājānāmi, kiṃ tvaṃ imaṃ dhammavinayaṃ ājānissasi. Micchāpaṭipanno tvamasi, ahamasmi sammāpaṭipanno. Sahitaṃ me, asahitaṃ te. Purevacanīyaṃ pacchā avaca, pacchāvacanīyaṃ pure avaca. Adhiciṇṇaṃ te viparāvattaṃ, āropito te vādo, niggahito tvamasi, cara vādappamokkhāya, nibbeṭhehi vā sace pahosī”ti.**“You don’t understand this teaching and training. I understand this teaching and training. What, you understand this teaching and training? You’re practicing wrong. I’m practicing right. I stay on topic, you don’t. You said last what you should have said first. You said first what you should have said last. What you’ve thought so much about has been disproved. Your doctrine is refuted. Go on, save your doctrine! You’re trapped; get yourself out of this—if you can!”*";
P_HTM[3944]="*Vadhoyeva kho maññe nigaṇṭhesu nāṭaputtiyesu vattati.**You’d think there was nothing but slaughter going on among the Jain ascetics.*";
P_HTM[3945]="*Yepi nigaṇṭhassa nāṭaputtassa sāvakā gihī odātavasanā, tepi nigaṇṭhesu nāṭaputtiyesu nibbinnarūpā virattarūpā paṭivānarūpā, yathā taṃ durakkhāte dhammavinaye duppavedite aniyyānike anupasamasaṃvattanike asammāsambuddhappavedite bhinnathūpe appaṭisaraṇe.**And the Nigaṇṭha Nātaputta’s white-clothed lay disciples were disillusioned, dismayed, and disappointed in the Jain ascetics. They were equally disappointed with a teaching and training so poorly explained and poorly propounded, not emancipating, not leading to peace, proclaimed by someone who is not a fully awakened Buddha, with broken monument and without a refuge.*";
P_HTM[3946]="*Atha kho āyasmā sāriputto bhikkhū āmantesi:**Then Sāriputta told the mendicants about these things. He went on to say,*";
P_HTM[3947]="*“nigaṇṭho, āvuso, nāṭaputto pāvāyaṃ adhunākālaṅkato,* **";
P_HTM[3948]="*tassa kālaṃkiriyāya bhinnā nigaṇṭhā dvedhikajātā … pe … bhinnathūpe appaṭisaraṇe.* **";
P_HTM[3949]="*Evañhetaṃ, āvuso, hoti durakkhāte dhammavinaye duppavedite aniyyānike anupasamasaṃvattanike asammāsambuddhappavedite.**“That’s what happens, reverends, when a teaching and training is poorly explained and poorly propounded, not emancipating, not leading to peace, proclaimed by someone who is not a fully awakened Buddha.*";
P_HTM[3950]="*Ayaṃ kho panāvuso, amhākaṃ bhagavatā dhammo svākkhāto suppavedito niyyāniko upasamasaṃvattaniko sammāsambuddhappavedito.**But this teaching is well explained and well propounded to us by the Blessed One, emancipating, leading to peace, proclaimed by someone who is a fully awakened Buddha.*";
P_HTM[3951]="*Tattha sabbeheva saṅgāyitabbaṃ, na vivaditabbaṃ, yathayidaṃ brahmacariyaṃ addhaniyaṃ assa ciraṭṭhitikaṃ, tadassa bahujanahitāya bahujanasukhāya lokānukampāya atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānaṃ.**You should all recite this in concert, without disputing, so that this spiritual path may last for a long time. That would be for the welfare and happiness of the people, for the benefit, welfare, and happiness of gods and humans.*";
P_HTM[3952]="*Katamo cāvuso, amhākaṃ bhagavatā dhammo svākkhāto suppavedito niyyāniko upasamasaṃvattaniko sammāsambuddhappavedito;**And what is that teaching?*";
P_HTM[3953]="*yattha sabbeheva saṅgāyitabbaṃ, na vivaditabbaṃ, yathayidaṃ brahmacariyaṃ addhaniyaṃ assa ciraṭṭhitikaṃ, tadassa bahujanahitāya bahujanasukhāya lokānukampāya atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānaṃ?* **";
P_HTM[3954]="*1. Ekaka**1. Ones*";
P_HTM[3955]="*Atthi kho, āvuso, tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena eko dhammo sammadakkhāto.**There are teachings grouped by one that have been rightly explained by the Blessed One, who knows and sees, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha.*";
P_HTM[3956]="*Tattha sabbeheva saṅgāyitabbaṃ, na vivaditabbaṃ, yathayidaṃ brahmacariyaṃ addhaniyaṃ assa ciraṭṭhitikaṃ, tadassa bahujanahitāya bahujanasukhāya lokānukampāya atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānaṃ.**You should all recite these in concert, without disputing, so that this spiritual path may last for a long time. That would be for the welfare and happiness of the people, for the benefit, welfare, and happiness of gods and humans.*";
P_HTM[3957]="*Katamo eko dhammo?**What are the teachings grouped by one?*";
P_HTM[3958]="*Sabbe sattā āhāraṭṭhitikā.**‘All sentient beings are sustained by food.’*";
P_HTM[3959]="*Sabbe sattā saṅkhāraṭṭhitikā.**‘All sentient beings are sustained by conditions.’*";
P_HTM[3960]="*Ayaṃ kho, āvuso, tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena eko dhammo sammadakkhāto.**These are the teachings grouped by one that have been rightly explained by the Blessed One, who knows and sees, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha.*";
P_HTM[3961]="*Tattha sabbeheva saṅgāyitabbaṃ, na vivaditabbaṃ, yathayidaṃ brahmacariyaṃ addhaniyaṃ assa ciraṭṭhitikaṃ, tadassa bahujanahitāya bahujanasukhāya lokānukampāya atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānaṃ.**You should all recite these in concert, without disputing, so that this spiritual path may last for a long time. That would be for the welfare and happiness of the people, for the benefit, welfare, and happiness of gods and humans.*";
P_HTM[3962]="*2. Duka**2. Twos*";
P_HTM[3963]="*Atthi kho, āvuso, tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena dve dhammā sammadakkhātā.**There are teachings grouped by two that have been rightly explained by the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[3964]="*Tattha sabbeheva saṅgāyitabbaṃ, na vivaditabbaṃ, yathayidaṃ brahmacariyaṃ addhaniyaṃ assa ciraṭṭhitikaṃ, tadassa bahujanahitāya bahujanasukhāya lokānukampāya atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānaṃ.**You should all recite these in concert.*";
P_HTM[3965]="*Katame dve?**What are the teachings grouped by two?*";
P_HTM[3966]="*Nāmañca rūpañca. (1)**Name and form.*";
P_HTM[3967]="*Avijjā ca bhavataṇhā ca. (2)**Ignorance and craving for continued existence.*";
P_HTM[3968]="*Bhavadiṭṭhi ca vibhavadiṭṭhi ca. (3)**Views favoring continued existence and views favoring ending existence.*";
P_HTM[3969]="*Ahirikañca anottappañca. (4)**Lack of conscience and prudence.*";
P_HTM[3970]="*Hirī ca ottappañca. (5)**Conscience and prudence.*";
P_HTM[3971]="*Dovacassatā ca pāpamittatā ca. (6)**Being hard to admonish and having bad friends.*";
P_HTM[3972]="*Sovacassatā ca kalyāṇamittatā ca. (7)**Being easy to admonish and having good friends.*";
P_HTM[3973]="*Āpattikusalatā ca āpattivuṭṭhānakusalatā ca. (8)**Skill in offenses and skill in rehabilitation from offenses.*";
P_HTM[3974]="*Samāpattikusalatā ca samāpattivuṭṭhānakusalatā ca. (9)**Skill in meditative attainments and skill in emerging from those attainments.*";
P_HTM[3975]="*Dhātukusalatā ca manasikārakusalatā ca. (10)**Skill in the elements and skill in attention.*";
P_HTM[3976]="*Āyatanakusalatā ca paṭiccasamuppādakusalatā ca. (11)**Skill in the sense fields and skill in dependent origination.*";
P_HTM[3977]="*Ṭhānakusalatā ca aṭṭhānakusalatā ca. (12)**Skill in what is possible and skill in what is impossible.*";
P_HTM[3978]="*Ajjavañca lajjavañca. (13)**Integrity and scrupulousness.*";
P_HTM[3979]="*Khanti ca soraccañca. (14)**Patience and gentleness.*";
P_HTM[3980]="*Sākhalyañca paṭisanthāro ca. (15)**Friendliness and hospitality.*";
P_HTM[3981]="*Avihiṃsā ca soceyyañca. (16)**Harmlessness and purity.*";
P_HTM[3982]="*Muṭṭhassaccañca asampajaññañca. (17)**Lack of mindfulness and lack of situational awareness.*";
P_HTM[3983]="*Sati ca sampajaññañca. (18)**Mindfulness and situational awareness.*";
P_HTM[3984]="*Indriyesu aguttadvāratā ca bhojane amattaññutā ca. (19)**Not guarding the sense doors and eating too much.*";
P_HTM[3985]="*Indriyesu guttadvāratā ca bhojane mattaññutā ca. (20)**Guarding the sense doors and moderation in eating.*";
P_HTM[3986]="*Paṭisaṅkhānabalañca bhāvanābalañca. (21)**The power of reflection and the power of development.*";
P_HTM[3987]="*Satibalañca samādhibalañca. (22)**The power of mindfulness and the power of immersion.*";
P_HTM[3988]="*Samatho ca vipassanā ca. (23)**Serenity and discernment.*";
P_HTM[3989]="*Samathanimittañca paggahanimittañca. (24)**The foundation of serenity and the foundation of exertion.*";
P_HTM[3990]="*Paggaho ca avikkhepo ca. (25)**Exertion, and not being distracted.*";
P_HTM[3991]="*Sīlavipatti ca diṭṭhivipatti ca. (26)**Failure in ethics and failure in view.*";
P_HTM[3992]="*Sīlasampadā ca diṭṭhisampadā ca. (27)**Accomplishment in ethics and accomplishment in view.*";
P_HTM[3993]="*Sīlavisuddhi ca diṭṭhivisuddhi ca. (28)**Purification of ethics and purification of view.*";
P_HTM[3994]="*Diṭṭhivisuddhi kho pana yathā diṭṭhissa ca padhānaṃ. (29)**Purification of view and making an effort in line with that view.*";
P_HTM[3995]="*Saṃvego ca saṃvejanīyesu ṭhānesu saṃviggassa ca yoniso padhānaṃ. (30)**Inspiration, and making a suitable effort when inspired by inspiring places.*";
P_HTM[3996]="*Asantuṭṭhitā ca kusalesu dhammesu appaṭivānitā ca padhānasmiṃ. (31)**To never be content with skillful qualities, and to never stop trying.*";
P_HTM[3997]="*Vijjā ca vimutti ca. (32)**Knowledge and freedom.*";
P_HTM[3998]="*Khayeñāṇaṃ anuppādeñāṇaṃ. (33)**Knowledge of ending and knowledge of non-arising.*";
P_HTM[3999]="*Ime kho, āvuso, tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena dve dhammā sammadakkhātā.**These are the teachings grouped by two that have been rightly explained by the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[4000]="*Tattha sabbeheva saṅgāyitabbaṃ, na vivaditabbaṃ, yathayidaṃ brahmacariyaṃ addhaniyaṃ assa ciraṭṭhitikaṃ, tadassa bahujanahitāya bahujanasukhāya lokānukampāya atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānaṃ.**You should all recite these in concert.*";
P_HTM[4001]="*3. Tika**3. Threes*";
P_HTM[4002]="*Atthi kho, āvuso, tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena tayo dhammā sammadakkhātā.**There are teachings grouped by three that have been rightly explained by the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[4003]="*Tattha sabbeheva saṅgāyitabbaṃ … pe … atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānaṃ.**You should all recite these in concert.*";
P_HTM[4004]="*Katame tayo?**What are the teachings grouped by three?*";
P_HTM[4005]="*Tīṇi akusalamūlāni—**Three unskillful roots:*";
P_HTM[4006]="*lobho akusalamūlaṃ, doso akusalamūlaṃ, moho akusalamūlaṃ. (1)**greed, hate, and delusion.*";
P_HTM[4007]="*Tīṇi kusalamūlāni—**Three skillful roots:*";
P_HTM[4008]="*alobho kusalamūlaṃ, adoso kusalamūlaṃ, amoho kusalamūlaṃ. (2)**non-greed, non-hate, and non-delusion.*";
P_HTM[4009]="*Tīṇi duccaritāni—**Three ways of performing bad conduct:*";
P_HTM[4010]="*kāyaduccaritaṃ, vacīduccaritaṃ, manoduccaritaṃ. (3)**by body, speech, and mind.*";
P_HTM[4011]="*Tīṇi sucaritāni—**Three ways of performing good conduct:*";
P_HTM[4012]="*kāyasucaritaṃ, vacīsucaritaṃ, manosucaritaṃ. (4)**by body, speech, and mind.*";
P_HTM[4013]="*Tayo akusalavitakkā—**Three unskillful thoughts:*";
P_HTM[4014]="*kāmavitakko, byāpādavitakko, vihiṃsāvitakko. (5)**sensuality, malice, and cruelty.*";
P_HTM[4015]="*Tayo kusalavitakkā—**Three skillful thoughts:*";
P_HTM[4016]="*nekkhammavitakko, abyāpādavitakko, avihiṃsāvitakko. (6)**renunciation, good will, and harmlessness.*";
P_HTM[4017]="*Tayo akusalasaṅkappā—**Three unskillful intentions:*";
P_HTM[4018]="*kāmasaṅkappo, byāpādasaṅkappo, vihiṃsāsaṅkappo. (7)**sensuality, malice, and cruelty.*";
P_HTM[4019]="*Tayo kusalasaṅkappā—**Three skillful intentions:*";
P_HTM[4020]="*nekkhammasaṅkappo, abyāpādasaṅkappo, avihiṃsāsaṅkappo. (8)**renunciation, good will, and harmlessness.*";
P_HTM[4021]="*Tisso akusalasaññā—**Three unskillful perceptions:*";
P_HTM[4022]="*kāmasaññā, byāpādasaññā, vihiṃsāsaññā. (9)**sensuality, malice, and cruelty.*";
P_HTM[4023]="*Tisso kusalasaññā—**Three skillful perceptions:*";
P_HTM[4024]="*nekkhammasaññā, abyāpādasaññā, avihiṃsāsaññā. (10)**renunciation, good will, and harmlessness.*";
P_HTM[4025]="*Tisso akusaladhātuyo—**Three unskillful elements:*";
P_HTM[4026]="*kāmadhātu, byāpādadhātu, vihiṃsādhātu. (11)**sensuality, malice, and cruelty.*";
P_HTM[4027]="*Tisso kusaladhātuyo—**Three skillful elements:*";
P_HTM[4028]="*nekkhammadhātu, abyāpādadhātu, avihiṃsādhātu. (12)**renunciation, good will, and harmlessness.*";
P_HTM[4029]="*Aparāpi tisso dhātuyo—**Another three elements:*";
P_HTM[4030]="*kāmadhātu, rūpadhātu, arūpadhātu. (13)**sensuality, form, and formlessness.*";
P_HTM[4031]="*Aparāpi tisso dhātuyo—**Another three elements:*";
P_HTM[4032]="*rūpadhātu, arūpadhātu, nirodhadhātu. (14)**form, formlessness, and cessation.*";
P_HTM[4033]="*Aparāpi tisso dhātuyo—**Another three elements:*";
P_HTM[4034]="*hīnadhātu, majjhimadhātu, paṇītadhātu. (15)**lower, middle, and higher.*";
P_HTM[4035]="*Tisso taṇhā—**Three cravings:*";
P_HTM[4036]="*kāmataṇhā, bhavataṇhā, vibhavataṇhā. (16)**for sensual pleasures, to continue existence, and to end existence.*";
P_HTM[4037]="*Aparāpi tisso taṇhā—**Another three cravings:*";
P_HTM[4038]="*kāmataṇhā, rūpataṇhā, arūpataṇhā. (17)**sensuality, form, and formlessness.*";
P_HTM[4039]="*Aparāpi tisso taṇhā—**Another three cravings:*";
P_HTM[4040]="*rūpataṇhā, arūpataṇhā, nirodhataṇhā. (18)**form, formlessness, and cessation.*";
P_HTM[4041]="*Tīṇi saṃyojanāni—**Three fetters:*";
P_HTM[4042]="*sakkāyadiṭṭhi, vicikicchā, sīlabbataparāmāso. (19)**identity view, doubt, and misapprehension of precepts and observances.*";
P_HTM[4043]="*Tayo āsavā—**Three defilements:*";
P_HTM[4044]="*kāmāsavo, bhavāsavo, avijjāsavo. (20)**sensuality, desire for continued existence, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[4045]="*Tayo bhavā—**Three realms of existence:*";
P_HTM[4046]="*kāmabhavo, rūpabhavo, arūpabhavo. (21)**sensual, form, and formless.*";
P_HTM[4047]="*Tisso esanā—**Three searches:*";
P_HTM[4048]="*kāmesanā, bhavesanā, brahmacariyesanā. (22)**for sensual pleasures, for continued existence, and for a spiritual path.*";
P_HTM[4049]="*Tisso vidhā—**Three kinds of discrimination:*";
P_HTM[4050]="*seyyohamasmīti vidhā, sadisohamasmīti vidhā, hīnohamasmīti vidhā. (23)**‘I’m better’, ‘I’m equal’, and ‘I’m worse’.*";
P_HTM[4051]="*Tayo addhā—**Three periods:*";
P_HTM[4052]="*atīto addhā, anāgato addhā, paccuppanno addhā. (24)**past, future, and present.*";
P_HTM[4053]="*Tayo antā—**Three extremes:*";
P_HTM[4054]="*sakkāyo anto, sakkāyasamudayo anto, sakkāyanirodho anto. (25)**identity, the origin of identity, and the cessation of identity.*";
P_HTM[4055]="*Tisso vedanā—**Three feelings:*";
P_HTM[4056]="*sukhā vedanā, dukkhā vedanā, adukkhamasukhā vedanā. (26)**pleasure, pain, and neutral.*";
P_HTM[4057]="*Tisso dukkhatā—**Three forms of suffering:*";
P_HTM[4058]="*dukkhadukkhatā, saṅkhāradukkhatā, vipariṇāmadukkhatā. (27)**the suffering inherent in painful feeling, the suffering inherent in conditions, and the suffering inherent in perishing.*";
P_HTM[4059]="*Tayo rāsī—**Three heaps:*";
P_HTM[4060]="*micchattaniyato rāsi, sammattaniyato rāsi, aniyato rāsi. (28)**inevitability regarding the wrong way, inevitability regarding the right way, and lack of inevitability.*";
P_HTM[4061]="*Tayo tamā—**Three darknesses:*";
P_HTM[4062]="*atītaṃ vā addhānaṃ ārabbha kaṅkhati vicikicchati nādhimuccati na sampasīdati, anāgataṃ vā addhānaṃ ārabbha kaṅkhati vicikicchati nādhimuccati na sampasīdati, etarahi vā paccuppannaṃ addhānaṃ ārabbha kaṅkhati vicikicchati nādhimuccati na sampasīdati. (29)**one is doubtful, uncertain, undecided, and lacking confidence about the past, future, and present.*";
P_HTM[4063]="*Tīṇi tathāgatassa arakkheyyāni—**Three things a Realized One need not hide.*";
P_HTM[4064]="*parisuddhakāyasamācāro āvuso tathāgato, natthi tathāgatassa kāyaduccaritaṃ, yaṃ tathāgato rakkheyya:**The Realized One’s behavior by way of body, speech, and mind is pure. He has no misconduct in these three ways that need be hidden, thinking:*";
P_HTM[4065]="*‘mā me idaṃ paro aññāsī’ti.**‘May others not know this of me.’*";
P_HTM[4066]="*Parisuddhavacīsamācāro āvuso, tathāgato, natthi tathāgatassa vacīduccaritaṃ, yaṃ tathāgato rakkheyya:* **";
P_HTM[4067]="*‘mā me idaṃ paro aññāsī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[4068]="*Parisuddhamanosamācāro, āvuso, tathāgato, natthi tathāgatassa manoduccaritaṃ yaṃ tathāgato rakkheyya:* **";
P_HTM[4069]="*‘mā me idaṃ paro aññāsī’ti. (30)* **";
P_HTM[4070]="*Tayo kiñcanā—**Three possessions:*";
P_HTM[4071]="*rāgo kiñcanaṃ, doso kiñcanaṃ, moho kiñcanaṃ. (31)**greed, hate, and delusion.*";
P_HTM[4072]="*Tayo aggī—**Three fires:*";
P_HTM[4073]="*rāgaggi, dosaggi, mohaggi. (32)**greed, hate, and delusion.*";
P_HTM[4074]="*Aparepi tayo aggī—**Another three fires:*";
P_HTM[4075]="*āhuneyyaggi, gahapataggi, dakkhiṇeyyaggi. (33)**a fire for those worthy of offerings dedicated to the gods, a fire for householders, and a fire for those worthy of a religious donation.*";
P_HTM[4076]="*Tividhena rūpasaṅgaho—**A threefold classification of the physical:*";
P_HTM[4077]="*sanidassanasappaṭighaṃ rūpaṃ, anidassanasappaṭighaṃ rūpaṃ, anidassanaappaṭighaṃ rūpaṃ. (34)**visible and resistant, invisible and resistant, and invisible and non-resistant.*";
P_HTM[4078]="*Tayo saṅkhārā—**Three choices:*";
P_HTM[4079]="*puññābhisaṅkhāro, apuññābhisaṅkhāro, āneñjābhisaṅkhāro. (35)**good choices, bad choices, and imperturbable choices.*";
P_HTM[4080]="*Tayo puggalā—**Three individuals:*";
P_HTM[4081]="*sekkho puggalo, asekkho puggalo, nevasekkho nāsekkho puggalo. (36)**a trainee, an adept, and one who is neither a trainee nor an adept.*";
P_HTM[4082]="*Tayo therā—**Three seniors:*";
P_HTM[4083]="*jātithero, dhammathero, sammutithero. (37)**a senior by birth, a senior in the teaching, and a senior by convention.*";
P_HTM[4084]="*Tīṇi puññakiriyavatthūni—**Three grounds for making merit:*";
P_HTM[4085]="*dānamayaṃ puññakiriyavatthu, sīlamayaṃ puññakiriyavatthu, bhāvanāmayaṃ puññakiriyavatthu. (38)**giving, ethical conduct, and meditation.*";
P_HTM[4086]="*Tīṇi codanāvatthūni—**Three grounds for accusations:*";
P_HTM[4087]="*diṭṭhena, sutena, parisaṅkāya. (39)**what is seen, heard, and suspected.*";
P_HTM[4088]="*Tisso kāmūpapattiyo—**Three kinds of sensual rebirth.*";
P_HTM[4089]="*santāvuso sattā paccupaṭṭhitakāmā, te paccupaṭṭhitesu kāmesu vasaṃ vattenti, seyyathāpi manussā ekacce ca devā ekacce ca vinipātikā.**There are sentient beings who desire what is present. They fall under the sway of presently arisen sensual pleasures. Namely, humans, some gods, and some beings in the underworld.*";
P_HTM[4090]="*Ayaṃ paṭhamā kāmūpapatti.**This is the first kind of sensual rebirth.*";
P_HTM[4091]="*Santāvuso, sattā nimmitakāmā, te nimminitvā nimminitvā kāmesu vasaṃ vattenti, seyyathāpi devā nimmānaratī.**There are sentient beings who desire to create. Having repeatedly created, they fall under the sway of sensual pleasures. Namely, the Gods Who Love to Create.*";
P_HTM[4092]="*Ayaṃ dutiyā kāmūpapatti.**This is the second kind of sensual rebirth.*";
P_HTM[4093]="*Santāvuso sattā paranimmitakāmā, te paranimmitesu kāmesu vasaṃ vattenti, seyyathāpi devā paranimmitavasavattī.**There are sentient beings who desire what is created by others. They fall under the sway of sensual pleasures created by others. Namely, the Gods Who Control the Creations of Others.*";
P_HTM[4094]="*Ayaṃ tatiyā kāmūpapatti. (40)**This is the third kind of sensual rebirth.*";
P_HTM[4095]="*Tisso sukhūpapattiyo—**Three kinds of pleasant rebirth.*";
P_HTM[4096]="*santāvuso sattā uppādetvā uppādetvā sukhaṃ viharanti, seyyathāpi devā brahmakāyikā.**There are sentient beings who, having repeatedly given rise to it, dwell in pleasure. Namely, the gods of Brahmā’s Host.*";
P_HTM[4097]="*Ayaṃ paṭhamā sukhūpapatti.**This is the first pleasant rebirth.*";
P_HTM[4098]="*Santāvuso, sattā sukhena abhisannā parisannā paripūrā paripphuṭā.**There are sentient beings who are drenched, steeped, filled, and soaked with pleasure.*";
P_HTM[4099]="*Te kadāci karahaci udānaṃ udānenti:**Every so often they feel inspired to exclaim:*";
P_HTM[4100]="*‘aho sukhaṃ, aho sukhan’ti, seyyathāpi devā ābhassarā.**‘Oh, what bliss! Oh, what bliss!’ Namely, the gods of streaming radiance.*";
P_HTM[4101]="*Ayaṃ dutiyā sukhūpapatti.**This is the second pleasant rebirth.*";
P_HTM[4102]="*Santāvuso, sattā sukhena abhisannā parisannā paripūrā paripphuṭā.**There are sentient beings who are drenched, steeped, filled, and soaked with pleasure.*";
P_HTM[4103]="*Te santaṃyeva tusitā sukhaṃ paṭisaṃvedenti, seyyathāpi devā subhakiṇhā.**Since they’re truly content, they experience pleasure. Namely, the gods replete with glory.*";
P_HTM[4104]="*Ayaṃ tatiyā sukhūpapatti. (41)**This is the third pleasant rebirth.*";
P_HTM[4105]="*Tisso paññā—**Three kinds of wisdom:*";
P_HTM[4106]="*sekkhā paññā, asekkhā paññā, nevasekkhānāsekkhā paññā. (42)**the wisdom of a trainee, the wisdom of an adept, and the wisdom of one who is neither a trainee nor an adept.*";
P_HTM[4107]="*Aparāpi tisso paññā—**Another three kinds of wisdom:*";
P_HTM[4108]="*cintāmayā paññā, sutamayā paññā, bhāvanāmayā paññā. (43)**wisdom produced by thought, learning, and meditation.*";
P_HTM[4109]="*Tīṇāvudhāni—**Three weapons:*";
P_HTM[4110]="*sutāvudhaṃ, pavivekāvudhaṃ, paññāvudhaṃ. (44)**learning, seclusion, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[4111]="*Tīṇindriyāni—**Three faculties:*";
P_HTM[4112]="*anaññātaññassāmītindriyaṃ, aññindriyaṃ, aññātāvindriyaṃ. (45)**the faculty of understanding that one’s enlightenment is imminent, the faculty of enlightenment, and the faculty of one who is enlightened.*";
P_HTM[4113]="*Tīṇi cakkhūni—**Three eyes:*";
P_HTM[4114]="*maṃsacakkhu, dibbacakkhu, paññācakkhu. (46)**the eye of the flesh, the eye of clairvoyance, and the eye of wisdom.*";
P_HTM[4115]="*Tisso sikkhā—**Three trainings:*";
P_HTM[4116]="*adhisīlasikkhā, adhicittasikkhā, adhipaññāsikkhā. (47)**in higher ethics, higher mind, and higher wisdom.*";
P_HTM[4117]="*Tisso bhāvanā—**Three kinds of development:*";
P_HTM[4118]="*kāyabhāvanā, cittabhāvanā, paññābhāvanā. (48)**the development of physical endurance, the development of the mind, and the development of wisdom.*";
P_HTM[4119]="*Tīṇi anuttariyāni—**Three unsurpassable things:*";
P_HTM[4120]="*dassanānuttariyaṃ, paṭipadānuttariyaṃ, vimuttānuttariyaṃ. (49)**unsurpassable seeing, practice, and freedom.*";
P_HTM[4121]="*Tayo samādhī—**Three kinds of immersion.*";
P_HTM[4122]="*savitakkasavicāro samādhi, avitakkavicāramatto samādhi, avitakkaavicāro samādhi. (50)**Immersion with placing the mind and keeping it connected. Immersion without placing the mind, but just keeping it connected. Immersion without placing the mind or keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[4123]="*Aparepi tayo samādhī—**Another three kinds of immersion:*";
P_HTM[4124]="*suññato samādhi, animitto samādhi, appaṇihito samādhi. (51)**emptiness, signless, and undirected.*";
P_HTM[4125]="*Tīṇi soceyyāni—**Three purities:*";
P_HTM[4126]="*kāyasoceyyaṃ, vacīsoceyyaṃ, manosoceyyaṃ. (52)**purity of body, speech, and mind.*";
P_HTM[4127]="*Tīṇi moneyyāni—**Three kinds of sagacity:*";
P_HTM[4128]="*kāyamoneyyaṃ, vacīmoneyyaṃ, manomoneyyaṃ. (53)**sagacity of body, speech, and mind.*";
P_HTM[4129]="*Tīṇi kosallāni—**Three skills:*";
P_HTM[4130]="*āyakosallaṃ, apāyakosallaṃ, upāyakosallaṃ. (54)**skill in progress, skill in regress, and skill in means.*";
P_HTM[4131]="*Tayo madā—**Three vanities:*";
P_HTM[4132]="*ārogyamado, yobbanamado, jīvitamado. (55)**the vanity of health, the vanity of youth, and the vanity of life.*";
P_HTM[4133]="*Tīṇi ādhipateyyāni—**Three ways of putting something in charge:*";
P_HTM[4134]="*attādhipateyyaṃ, lokādhipateyyaṃ, dhammādhipateyyaṃ. (56)**putting oneself, the world, or the teaching in charge.*";
P_HTM[4135]="*Tīṇi kathāvatthūni—**Three topics of discussion.*";
P_HTM[4136]="*atītaṃ vā addhānaṃ ārabbha kathaṃ katheyya:**You might discuss the past:*";
P_HTM[4137]="*‘evaṃ ahosi atītamaddhānan’ti;**‘That is how it was in the past.’*";
P_HTM[4138]="*anāgataṃ vā addhānaṃ ārabbha kathaṃ katheyya:**You might discuss the future:*";
P_HTM[4139]="*‘evaṃ bhavissati anāgatamaddhānan’ti;**‘That is how it will be in the future.’*";
P_HTM[4140]="*etarahi vā paccuppannaṃ addhānaṃ ārabbha kathaṃ katheyya:**Or you might discuss the present:*";
P_HTM[4141]="*‘evaṃ hoti etarahi paccuppannaṃ addhānan’ti. (57)**‘This is how it is at present.’*";
P_HTM[4142]="*Tisso vijjā—**Three knowledges:*";
P_HTM[4143]="*pubbenivāsānussatiñāṇaṃ vijjā, sattānaṃ cutūpapāteñāṇaṃ vijjā, āsavānaṃ khayeñāṇaṃ vijjā. (58)**recollection of past lives, knowledge of the death and rebirth of sentient beings, and knowledge of the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[4144]="*Tayo vihārā—**Three meditative abidings:*";
P_HTM[4145]="*dibbo vihāro, brahmā vihāro, ariyo vihāro. (59)**the meditation of the gods, the meditation of Brahmā, and the meditation of the noble ones.*";
P_HTM[4146]="*Tīṇi pāṭihāriyāni—**Three demonstrations:*";
P_HTM[4147]="*iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ, ādesanāpāṭihāriyaṃ, anusāsanīpāṭihāriyaṃ. (60)**a demonstration of psychic power, a demonstration of revealing, and an instructional demonstration.*";
P_HTM[4148]="*Ime kho, āvuso, tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena tayo dhammā sammadakkhātā.**These are the teachings grouped by three that have been rightly explained by the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[4149]="*Tattha sabbeheva saṅgāyitabbaṃ … pe … atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānaṃ.**You should all recite these in concert.*";
P_HTM[4150]="*4. Catukka**4. Fours*";
P_HTM[4151]="*Atthi kho, āvuso, tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena cattāro dhammā sammadakkhātā.**There are teachings grouped by four that have been rightly explained by the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[4152]="*Tattha sabbeheva saṅgāyitabbaṃ, na vivaditabbaṃ … pe … atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānaṃ.**You should all recite these in concert.*";
P_HTM[4153]="*Katame cattāro?**What are the teachings grouped by four?*";
P_HTM[4154]="*Cattāro satipaṭṭhānā.**Four kinds of mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[4155]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā, vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**It’s when a mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[4156]="*Vedanāsu vedanānupassī … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[4157]="*citte cittānupassī … pe …**mind …*";
P_HTM[4158]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ. (1)**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[4159]="*Cattāro sammappadhānā.**Four right efforts.*";
P_HTM[4160]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu anuppannānaṃ pāpakānaṃ akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ anuppādāya chandaṃ janeti vāyamati vīriyaṃ ārabhati cittaṃ paggaṇhāti padahati.**A mendicant generates enthusiasm, tries, makes an effort, exerts the mind, and strives so that bad, unskillful qualities don’t arise.*";
P_HTM[4161]="*Uppannānaṃ pāpakānaṃ akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ pahānāya chandaṃ janeti vāyamati vīriyaṃ ārabhati cittaṃ paggaṇhāti padahati.**They generate enthusiasm, try, make an effort, exert the mind, and strive so that bad, unskillful qualities that have arisen are given up.*";
P_HTM[4162]="*Anuppannānaṃ kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ uppādāya chandaṃ janeti vāyamati vīriyaṃ ārabhati cittaṃ paggaṇhāti padahati.**They generate enthusiasm, try, make an effort, exert the mind, and strive so that skillful qualities arise.*";
P_HTM[4163]="*Uppannānaṃ kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ ṭhitiyā asammosāya bhiyyobhāvāya vepullāya bhāvanāya pāripūriyā chandaṃ janeti vāyamati vīriyaṃ ārabhati cittaṃ paggaṇhāti padahati. (2)**They generate enthusiasm, try, make an effort, exert the mind, and strive so that skillful qualities that have arisen remain, are not lost, but increase, mature, and are completed by development.*";
P_HTM[4164]="*Cattāro iddhipādā.**Four bases of psychic power.*";
P_HTM[4165]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu chandasamādhipadhānasaṅkhārasamannāgataṃ iddhipādaṃ bhāveti.**A mendicant develops the basis of psychic power that has immersion due to enthusiasm, and active effort.*";
P_HTM[4166]="*Cittasamādhipadhānasaṅkhārasamannāgataṃ iddhipādaṃ bhāveti.**They develop the basis of psychic power that has immersion due to mental development, and active effort.*";
P_HTM[4167]="*Vīriyasamādhipadhānasaṅkhārasamannāgataṃ iddhipādaṃ bhāveti.**They develop the basis of psychic power that has immersion due to energy, and active effort.*";
P_HTM[4168]="*Vīmaṃsāsamādhipadhānasaṅkhārasamannāgataṃ iddhipādaṃ bhāveti. (3)**They develop the basis of psychic power that has immersion due to inquiry, and active effort.*";
P_HTM[4169]="*Cattāri jhānāni.**Four absorptions.*";
P_HTM[4170]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu vivicceva kāmehi vivicca akusalehi dhammehi savitakkaṃ savicāraṃ vivekajaṃ pītisukhaṃ paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**A mendicant, quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, enters and remains in the first absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of seclusion, while placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[4171]="*Vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā ajjhattaṃ sampasādanaṃ cetaso ekodibhāvaṃ avitakkaṃ avicāraṃ samādhijaṃ pītisukhaṃ dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**As the placing of the mind and keeping it connected are stilled, they enter and remain in the second absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of immersion, with internal clarity and confidence, and unified mind, without placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[4172]="*Pītiyā ca virāgā upekkhako ca viharati sato ca sampajāno, sukhañca kāyena paṭisaṃvedeti, yaṃ taṃ ariyā ācikkhanti: ‘upekkhako satimā sukhavihārī’ti tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**And with the fading away of rapture, they enter and remain in the third absorption, where they meditate with equanimity, mindful and aware, personally experiencing the bliss of which the noble ones declare, ‘Equanimous and mindful, one meditates in bliss.’*";
P_HTM[4173]="*Sukhassa ca pahānā dukkhassa ca pahānā, pubbeva somanassadomanassānaṃ atthaṅgamā, adukkhamasukhaṃ upekkhāsatipārisuddhiṃ catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati. (4)**Giving up pleasure and pain, and ending former happiness and sadness, they enter and remain in the fourth absorption, without pleasure or pain, with pure equanimity and mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[4174]="*Catasso samādhibhāvanā.**Four ways of developing immersion further.*";
P_HTM[4175]="*Atthāvuso, samādhibhāvanā bhāvitā bahulīkatā diṭṭhadhammasukhavihārāya saṃvattati.**There is a way of developing immersion further that leads to blissful meditation in the present life.*";
P_HTM[4176]="*Atthāvuso, samādhibhāvanā bhāvitā bahulīkatā ñāṇadassanapaṭilābhāya saṃvattati.**There is a way of developing immersion further that leads to gaining knowledge and vision.*";
P_HTM[4177]="*Atthāvuso samādhibhāvanā bhāvitā bahulīkatā satisampajaññāya saṃvattati.**There is a way of developing immersion further that leads to mindfulness and awareness.*";
P_HTM[4178]="*Atthāvuso samādhibhāvanā bhāvitā bahulīkatā āsavānaṃ khayāya saṃvattati.**There is a way of developing immersion further that leads to the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[4179]="*Katamā cāvuso, samādhibhāvanā bhāvitā bahulīkatā diṭṭhadhammasukhavihārāya saṃvattati?**And what is the way of developing immersion further that leads to blissful meditation in the present life?*";
P_HTM[4180]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu vivicceva kāmehi vivicca akusalehi dhammehi savitakkaṃ …**It’s when a mendicant, quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, enters and remains in the first absorption …*";
P_HTM[4181]="*pe …**second absorption …*";
P_HTM[4182]="*catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**fourth absorption.*";
P_HTM[4183]="*Ayaṃ, āvuso, samādhibhāvanā bhāvitā bahulīkatā diṭṭhadhammasukhavihārāya saṃvattati. (5.1)**This is the way of developing immersion further that leads to blissful meditation in the present life.*";
P_HTM[4184]="*Katamā cāvuso, samādhibhāvanā bhāvitā bahulīkatā ñāṇadassanapaṭilābhāya saṃvattati?**And what is the way of developing immersion further that leads to gaining knowledge and vision?*";
P_HTM[4185]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu ālokasaññaṃ manasi karoti, divāsaññaṃ adhiṭṭhāti yathā divā tathā rattiṃ, yathā rattiṃ tathā divā.**A mendicant focuses on the perception of light, concentrating on the perception of day regardless of whether it is night or day.*";
P_HTM[4186]="*Iti vivaṭena cetasā apariyonaddhena sappabhāsaṃ cittaṃ bhāveti.**And so, with an open and unenveloped heart, they develop a mind that’s full of radiance.*";
P_HTM[4187]="*Ayaṃ, āvuso, samādhibhāvanā bhāvitā bahulīkatā ñāṇadassanapaṭilābhāya saṃvattati. (5.2)**This is the way of developing immersion further that leads to gaining knowledge and vision.*";
P_HTM[4188]="*Katamā cāvuso, samādhibhāvanā bhāvitā bahulīkatā satisampajaññāya saṃvattati?**And what is the way of developing immersion further that leads to mindfulness and awareness?*";
P_HTM[4189]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhuno viditā vedanā uppajjanti, viditā upaṭṭhahanti, viditā abbhatthaṃ gacchanti.**A mendicant knows feelings as they arise, as they remain, and as they go away.*";
P_HTM[4190]="*Viditā saññā uppajjanti, viditā upaṭṭhahanti, viditā abbhatthaṃ gacchanti.**They know perceptions as they arise, as they remain, and as they go away.*";
P_HTM[4191]="*Viditā vitakkā uppajjanti, viditā upaṭṭhahanti, viditā abbhatthaṃ gacchanti.**They know thoughts as they arise, as they remain, and as they go away.*";
P_HTM[4192]="*Ayaṃ, āvuso, samādhibhāvanā bhāvitā bahulīkatā satisampajaññāya saṃvattati. (5.3)**This is the way of developing immersion further that leads to mindfulness and awareness.*";
P_HTM[4193]="*Katamā cāvuso, samādhibhāvanā bhāvitā bahulīkatā āsavānaṃ khayāya saṃvattati?**And what is the way of developing immersion further that leads to the ending of defilements?*";
P_HTM[4194]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu pañcasu upādānakkhandhesu udayabbayānupassī viharati.**A mendicant meditates observing rise and fall in the five grasping aggregates.*";
P_HTM[4195]="*Iti rūpaṃ, iti rūpassa samudayo, iti rūpassa atthaṅgamo.**‘Such is form, such is the origin of form, such is the ending of form.*";
P_HTM[4196]="*Iti vedanā … pe …**Such are feelings …*";
P_HTM[4197]="*iti saññā …**perceptions …*";
P_HTM[4198]="*iti saṅkhārā …**choices …*";
P_HTM[4199]="*iti viññāṇaṃ, iti viññāṇassa samudayo, iti viññāṇassa atthaṅgamo.**consciousness, such is the origin of consciousness, such is the ending of consciousness.’*";
P_HTM[4200]="*Ayaṃ, āvuso, samādhibhāvanā bhāvitā bahulīkatā āsavānaṃ khayāya saṃvattati. (5.4)**This is the way of developing immersion further that leads to the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[4201]="*Catasso appamaññā.**Four immeasurables.*";
P_HTM[4202]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu mettāsahagatena cetasā ekaṃ disaṃ pharitvā viharati. Tathā dutiyaṃ. Tathā tatiyaṃ. Tathā catutthaṃ. Iti uddhamadho tiriyaṃ sabbadhi sabbattatāya sabbāvantaṃ lokaṃ mettāsahagatena cetasā vipulena mahaggatena appamāṇena averena abyāpajjena pharitvā viharati.**A mendicant meditates spreading a heart full of love to one direction, and to the second, and to the third, and to the fourth. In the same way above, below, across, everywhere, all around, they spread a heart full of love to the whole world—abundant, expansive, limitless, free of enmity and ill will.*";
P_HTM[4203]="*Karuṇāsahagatena cetasā … pe …**They meditate spreading a heart full of compassion …*";
P_HTM[4204]="*muditāsahagatena cetasā … pe …**rejoicing …*";
P_HTM[4205]="*upekkhāsahagatena cetasā ekaṃ disaṃ pharitvā viharati. Tathā dutiyaṃ. Tathā tatiyaṃ. Tathā catutthaṃ. Iti uddhamadho tiriyaṃ sabbadhi sabbattatāya sabbāvantaṃ lokaṃ upekkhāsahagatena cetasā vipulena mahaggatena appamāṇena averena abyāpajjena pharitvā viharati. (6)**equanimity to one direction, and to the second, and to the third, and to the fourth. In the same way above, below, across, everywhere, all around, they spread a heart full of equanimity to the whole world—abundant, expansive, limitless, free of enmity and ill will.*";
P_HTM[4206]="*Cattāro āruppā.**Four formless states.*";
P_HTM[4207]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu sabbaso rūpasaññānaṃ samatikkamā paṭighasaññānaṃ atthaṅgamā nānattasaññānaṃ amanasikārā ‘ananto ākāso’ti ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**A mendicant, going totally beyond perceptions of form, with the ending of perceptions of impingement, not focusing on perceptions of diversity, aware that ‘space is infinite’, enters and remains in the dimension of infinite space.*";
P_HTM[4208]="*Sabbaso ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma ‘anantaṃ viññāṇan’ti viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Going totally beyond the dimension of infinite space, aware that ‘consciousness is infinite’, they enter and remain in the dimension of infinite consciousness.*";
P_HTM[4209]="*Sabbaso viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma ‘natthi kiñcī’ti ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Going totally beyond the dimension of infinite consciousness, aware that ‘there is nothing at all’, they enter and remain in the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[4210]="*Sabbaso ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati. (7)**Going totally beyond the dimension of nothingness, they enter and remain in the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.*";
P_HTM[4211]="*Cattāri apassenāni.**Four supports.*";
P_HTM[4212]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu saṅkhāyekaṃ paṭisevati, saṅkhāyekaṃ adhivāseti, saṅkhāyekaṃ parivajjeti, saṅkhāyekaṃ vinodeti. (8)**After reflection, a mendicant uses some things, endures some things, avoids some things, and gets rid of some things.*";
P_HTM[4213]="*Cattāro ariyavaṃsā.**Four noble traditions.*";
P_HTM[4214]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu santuṭṭho hoti itarītarena cīvarena, itarītaracīvarasantuṭṭhiyā ca vaṇṇavādī, na ca cīvarahetu anesanaṃ appatirūpaṃ āpajjati; aladdhā ca cīvaraṃ na paritassati, laddhā ca cīvaraṃ agadhito amucchito anajjhāpanno ādīnavadassāvī nissaraṇapañño paribhuñjati; tāya ca pana itarītaracīvarasantuṭṭhiyā nevattānukkaṃseti na paraṃ vambheti.**A mendicant is content with any kind of robe, and praises such contentment. They don’t try to get hold of a robe in an improper way. They don’t get upset if they don’t get a robe. And if they do get a robe, they use it untied, uninfatuated, unattached, seeing the drawback, and understanding the escape. And on account of that they don’t glorify themselves or put others down.*";
P_HTM[4215]="*Yo hi tattha dakkho analaso sampajāno paṭissato, ayaṃ vuccatāvuso: ‘bhikkhu porāṇe aggaññe ariyavaṃse ṭhito’. (9.1)**A mendicant who is deft, tireless, aware, and mindful in this is said to stand in the ancient, original noble tradition.*";
P_HTM[4216]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu santuṭṭho hoti itarītarena piṇḍapātena, itarītarapiṇḍapātasantuṭṭhiyā ca vaṇṇavādī, na ca piṇḍapātahetu anesanaṃ appatirūpaṃ āpajjati; aladdhā ca piṇḍapātaṃ na paritassati, laddhā ca piṇḍapātaṃ agadhito amucchito anajjhāpanno ādīnavadassāvī nissaraṇapañño paribhuñjati; tāya ca pana itarītarapiṇḍapātasantuṭṭhiyā nevattānukkaṃseti na paraṃ vambheti.**Furthermore, a mendicant is content with any kind of alms-food …*";
P_HTM[4217]="*Yo hi tattha dakkho analaso sampajāno paṭissato, ayaṃ vuccatāvuso: ‘bhikkhu porāṇe aggaññe ariyavaṃse ṭhito’. (9.2)* **";
P_HTM[4218]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu santuṭṭho hoti itarītarena senāsanena, itarītarasenāsanasantuṭṭhiyā ca vaṇṇavādī, na ca senāsanahetu anesanaṃ appatirūpaṃ āpajjati; aladdhā ca senāsanaṃ na paritassati, laddhā ca senāsanaṃ agadhito amucchito anajjhāpanno ādīnavadassāvī nissaraṇapañño paribhuñjati; tāya ca pana itarītarasenāsanasantuṭṭhiyā nevattānukkaṃseti na paraṃ vambheti.**Furthermore, a mendicant is content with any kind of lodgings …*";
P_HTM[4219]="*Yo hi tattha dakkho analaso sampajāno paṭissato, ayaṃ vuccatāvuso: ‘bhikkhu porāṇe aggaññe ariyavaṃse ṭhito’. (9.3)* **";
P_HTM[4220]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu pahānārāmo hoti pahānarato, bhāvanārāmo hoti bhāvanārato; tāya ca pana pahānārāmatāya pahānaratiyā bhāvanārāmatāya bhāvanāratiyā nevattānukkaṃseti na paraṃ vambheti.**Furthermore, a mendicant enjoys giving up and loves to give up. They enjoy meditation and love to meditate. But they don’t glorify themselves or put down others on account of their love for giving up and meditation.*";
P_HTM[4221]="*Yo hi tattha dakkho analaso sampajāno paṭissato ayaṃ vuccatāvuso: ‘bhikkhu porāṇe aggaññe ariyavaṃse ṭhito’. (9.4)**A mendicant who is deft, tireless, aware, and mindful in this is said to stand in the ancient, original noble tradition.*";
P_HTM[4222]="*Cattāri padhānāni.**Four efforts.*";
P_HTM[4223]="*Saṃvarapadhānaṃ pahānapadhānaṃ bhāvanāpadhānaṃ anurakkhaṇāpadhānaṃ.**The efforts to restrain, to give up, to develop, and to preserve.*";
P_HTM[4224]="*Katamañcāvuso, saṃvarapadhānaṃ?**And what is the effort to restrain?*";
P_HTM[4225]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu cakkhunā rūpaṃ disvā na nimittaggāhī hoti nānubyañjanaggāhī.**When a mendicant sees a sight with their eyes, they don’t get caught up in the features and details.*";
P_HTM[4226]="*Yatvādhikaraṇamenaṃ cakkhundriyaṃ asaṃvutaṃ viharantaṃ abhijjhādomanassā pāpakā akusalā dhammā anvāssaveyyuṃ, tassa saṃvarāya paṭipajjati, rakkhati cakkhundriyaṃ, cakkhundriye saṃvaraṃ āpajjati.**If the faculty of sight were left unrestrained, bad unskillful qualities of desire and aversion would become overwhelming. For this reason, they practice restraint, protecting the faculty of sight, and achieving its restraint.*";
P_HTM[4227]="*Sotena saddaṃ sutvā …**When they hear a sound with their ears …*";
P_HTM[4228]="*ghānena gandhaṃ ghāyitvā …**When they smell an odor with their nose …*";
P_HTM[4229]="*jivhāya rasaṃ sāyitvā …**When they taste a flavor with their tongue …*";
P_HTM[4230]="*kāyena phoṭṭhabbaṃ phusitvā …**When they feel a touch with their body …*";
P_HTM[4231]="*manasā dhammaṃ viññāya na nimittaggāhī hoti nānubyañjanaggāhī.**When they know a thought with their mind, they don’t get caught up in the features and details.*";
P_HTM[4232]="*Yatvādhikaraṇamenaṃ manindriyaṃ asaṃvutaṃ viharantaṃ abhijjhādomanassā pāpakā akusalā dhammā anvāssaveyyuṃ, tassa saṃvarāya paṭipajjati, rakkhati manindriyaṃ, manindriye saṃvaraṃ āpajjati.**If the faculty of mind were left unrestrained, bad unskillful qualities of desire and aversion would become overwhelming. For this reason, they practice restraint, protecting the faculty of mind, and achieving its restraint.*";
P_HTM[4233]="*Idaṃ vuccatāvuso, saṃvarapadhānaṃ. (10.1)**This is called the effort to restrain.*";
P_HTM[4234]="*Katamañcāvuso, pahānapadhānaṃ?**And what is the effort to give up?*";
P_HTM[4235]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu uppannaṃ kāmavitakkaṃ nādhivāseti pajahati vinodeti byantiṃ karoti anabhāvaṃ gameti. Uppannaṃ byāpādavitakkaṃ … pe … uppannaṃ vihiṃsāvitakkaṃ … uppannuppanne pāpake akusale dhamme nādhivāseti pajahati vinodeti byantiṃ karoti anabhāvaṃ gameti.**It’s when a mendicant doesn’t tolerate a sensual, malicious, or cruel thought that has arisen, but gives it up, gets rid of it, eliminates it, and exterminates it. They don’t tolerate any bad, unskillful qualities that have arisen, but give them up, get rid of them, eliminate them, and obliterate them.*";
P_HTM[4236]="*Idaṃ vuccatāvuso, pahānapadhānaṃ. (10.2)**This is called the effort to give up.*";
P_HTM[4237]="*Katamañcāvuso, bhāvanāpadhānaṃ?**And what is the effort to develop?*";
P_HTM[4238]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu satisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ. Dhammavicayasambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti … vīriyasambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti … pītisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti … passaddhisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti … samādhisambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti … upekkhāsambojjhaṅgaṃ bhāveti vivekanissitaṃ virāganissitaṃ nirodhanissitaṃ vossaggapariṇāmiṃ.**It’s when a mendicant develops the awakening factors of mindfulness, investigation of principles, energy, rapture, tranquility, immersion, and equanimity, which rely on seclusion, fading away, and cessation, and ripen as letting go.*";
P_HTM[4239]="*Idaṃ vuccatāvuso, bhāvanāpadhānaṃ. (10.3)**This is called the effort to develop.*";
P_HTM[4240]="*Katamañcāvuso, anurakkhaṇāpadhānaṃ?**And what is the effort to preserve?*";
P_HTM[4241]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu uppannaṃ bhadrakaṃ samādhinimittaṃ anurakkhati—aṭṭhikasaññaṃ, puḷuvakasaññaṃ, vinīlakasaññaṃ, vicchiddakasaññaṃ, uddhumātakasaññaṃ.**It’s when a mendicant preserves a meditation subject that’s a fine foundation of immersion: the perception of a skeleton, a worm-infested corpse, a livid corpse, a split open corpse, or a bloated corpse.*";
P_HTM[4242]="*Idaṃ vuccatāvuso, anurakkhaṇāpadhānaṃ. (10.4)**This is called the effort to preserve.*";
P_HTM[4243]="*Cattāri ñāṇāni—**Four knowledges:*";
P_HTM[4244]="*dhamme ñāṇaṃ, anvaye ñāṇaṃ, pariye ñāṇaṃ, sammutiyā ñāṇaṃ. (11)**knowledge of the present phenomena, inferential knowledge, knowledge of others’ minds, and conventional knowledge.*";
P_HTM[4245]="*Aparānipi cattāri ñāṇāni—**Another four knowledges:*";
P_HTM[4246]="*dukkhe ñāṇaṃ, dukkhasamudaye ñāṇaṃ, dukkhanirodhe ñāṇaṃ, dukkhanirodhagāminiyā paṭipadāya ñāṇaṃ. (12)**knowing about suffering, the origin of suffering, the cessation of suffering, and the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.*";
P_HTM[4247]="*Cattāri sotāpattiyaṅgāni—**Four factors of stream-entry:*";
P_HTM[4248]="*sappurisasaṃsevo, saddhammassavanaṃ, yonisomanasikāro, dhammānudhammappaṭipatti. (13)**associating with good people, listening to the true teaching, proper attention, and practicing in line with the teaching.*";
P_HTM[4249]="*Cattāri sotāpannassa aṅgāni.**Four factors of a stream-enterer.*";
P_HTM[4250]="*Idhāvuso, ariyasāvako buddhe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti:**A noble disciple has experiential confidence in the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[4251]="*‘itipi so bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho, bhagavā’ti.**‘That Blessed One is perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.’*";
P_HTM[4252]="*Dhamme aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti:**They have experiential confidence in the teaching:*";
P_HTM[4253]="*‘svākkhāto bhagavatā dhammo sandiṭṭhiko akāliko ehipassiko opaneyyiko paccattaṃ veditabbo viññūhī’ti.**‘The teaching is well explained by the Buddha—visible in this very life, immediately effective, inviting inspection, relevant, so that sensible people can know it for themselves.’*";
P_HTM[4254]="*Saṃghe aveccappasādena samannāgato hoti:**They have experiential confidence in the Saṅgha:*";
P_HTM[4255]="*‘suppaṭipanno bhagavato sāvakasaṃgho ujuppaṭipanno bhagavato sāvakasaṃgho ñāyappaṭipanno bhagavato sāvakasaṃgho sāmīcippaṭipanno bhagavato sāvakasaṃgho yadidaṃ cattāri purisayugāni aṭṭha purisapuggalā, esa bhagavato sāvakasaṃgho āhuneyyo pāhuneyyo dakkhiṇeyyo añjalikaraṇīyo anuttaraṃ puññakkhettaṃ lokassā’ti.**‘The Saṅgha of the Buddha’s disciples is practicing the way that’s good, straightforward, methodical, and proper. It consists of the four pairs, the eight individuals. This is the Saṅgha of the Buddha’s disciples that is worthy of offerings dedicated to the gods, worthy of hospitality, worthy of a religious donation, worthy of greeting with joined palms, and is the supreme field of merit for the world.’*";
P_HTM[4256]="*Ariyakantehi sīlehi samannāgato hoti akhaṇḍehi acchiddehi asabalehi akammāsehi bhujissehi viññuppasatthehi aparāmaṭṭhehi samādhisaṃvattanikehi. (14)**And a noble disciple’s ethical conduct is loved by the noble ones, unbroken, impeccable, spotless, and unmarred, liberating, praised by sensible people, not mistaken, and leading to immersion.*";
P_HTM[4257]="*Cattāri sāmaññaphalāni—**Four fruits of the ascetic life:*";
P_HTM[4258]="*sotāpattiphalaṃ, sakadāgāmiphalaṃ, anāgāmiphalaṃ, arahattaphalaṃ. (15)**stream-entry, once-return, non-return, and perfection.*";
P_HTM[4259]="*Catasso dhātuyo—**Four elements:*";
P_HTM[4260]="*pathavīdhātu, āpodhātu, tejodhātu, vāyodhātu. (16)**earth, water, fire, and air.*";
P_HTM[4261]="*Cattāro āhārā—**Four foods:*";
P_HTM[4262]="*kabaḷīkāro āhāro oḷāriko vā sukhumo vā, phasso dutiyo, manosañcetanā tatiyā, viññāṇaṃ catutthaṃ. (17)**solid food, whether coarse or fine; contact is the second, mental intention the third, and consciousness the fourth.*";
P_HTM[4263]="*Catasso viññāṇaṭṭhitiyo.**Four bases for consciousness to remain.*";
P_HTM[4264]="*Rūpūpāyaṃ vā, āvuso, viññāṇaṃ tiṭṭhamānaṃ tiṭṭhati rūpārammaṇaṃ rūpappatiṭṭhaṃ nandūpasecanaṃ vuddhiṃ virūḷhiṃ vepullaṃ āpajjati;**As long as consciousness remains, it remains involved with form, supported by form, founded on form. And with a sprinkle of relishing, it grows, increases, and matures.*";
P_HTM[4265]="*vedanūpāyaṃ vā āvuso …**Or consciousness remains involved with feeling …*";
P_HTM[4266]="*saññūpāyaṃ vā, āvuso … pe …**Or consciousness remains involved with perception …*";
P_HTM[4267]="*saṅkhārūpāyaṃ vā, āvuso, viññāṇaṃ tiṭṭhamānaṃ tiṭṭhati saṅkhārārammaṇaṃ saṅkhārappatiṭṭhaṃ nandūpasecanaṃ vuddhiṃ virūḷhiṃ vepullaṃ āpajjati. (18)**Or as long as consciousness remains, it remains involved with choices, supported by choices, grounded on choices. And with a sprinkle of relishing, it grows, increases, and matures.*";
P_HTM[4268]="*Cattāri agatigamanāni—**Four prejudices:*";
P_HTM[4269]="*chandāgatiṃ gacchati, dosāgatiṃ gacchati, mohāgatiṃ gacchati, bhayāgatiṃ gacchati. (19)**making decisions prejudiced by favoritism, hostility, stupidity, and cowardice.*";
P_HTM[4270]="*Cattāro taṇhuppādā—**Four things that give rise to craving.*";
P_HTM[4271]="*cīvarahetu vā, āvuso, bhikkhuno taṇhā uppajjamānā uppajjati;**Craving arises in a mendicant for the sake of robes,*";
P_HTM[4272]="*piṇḍapātahetu vā, āvuso, bhikkhuno taṇhā uppajjamānā uppajjati;**alms-food,*";
P_HTM[4273]="*senāsanahetu vā, āvuso, bhikkhuno taṇhā uppajjamānā uppajjati;**lodgings,*";
P_HTM[4274]="*itibhavābhavahetu vā, āvuso, bhikkhuno taṇhā uppajjamānā uppajjati. (20)**or rebirth in this or that state.*";
P_HTM[4275]="*Catasso paṭipadā—**Four ways of practice:*";
P_HTM[4276]="*dukkhā paṭipadā dandhābhiññā, dukkhā paṭipadā khippābhiññā, sukhā paṭipadā dandhābhiññā, sukhā paṭipadā khippābhiññā. (21)**painful practice with slow insight, painful practice with swift insight, pleasant practice with slow insight, and pleasant practice with swift insight.*";
P_HTM[4277]="*Aparāpi catasso paṭipadā—**Another four ways of practice:*";
P_HTM[4278]="*akkhamā paṭipadā, khamā paṭipadā, damā paṭipadā, samā paṭipadā. (22)**impatient practice, patient practice, taming practice, and calming practice.*";
P_HTM[4279]="*Cattāri dhammapadāni—**Four basic principles:*";
P_HTM[4280]="*anabhijjhā dhammapadaṃ, abyāpādo dhammapadaṃ, sammāsati dhammapadaṃ, sammāsamādhi dhammapadaṃ. (23)**contentment, good will, right mindfulness, and right immersion.*";
P_HTM[4281]="*Cattāri dhammasamādānāni—**Four ways of taking up practices.*";
P_HTM[4282]="*atthāvuso, dhammasamādānaṃ paccuppannadukkhañceva āyatiñca dukkhavipākaṃ.**There is a way of taking up practices that is painful now and results in future pain.*";
P_HTM[4283]="*Atthāvuso, dhammasamādānaṃ paccuppannadukkhaṃ āyatiṃ sukhavipākaṃ.**There is a way of taking up practices that is painful now but results in future pleasure.*";
P_HTM[4284]="*Atthāvuso, dhammasamādānaṃ paccuppannasukhaṃ āyatiṃ dukkhavipākaṃ.**There is a way of taking up practices that is pleasant now but results in future pain.*";
P_HTM[4285]="*Atthāvuso, dhammasamādānaṃ paccuppannasukhañceva āyatiñca sukhavipākaṃ. (24)**There is a way of taking up practices that is pleasant now and results in future pleasure.*";
P_HTM[4286]="*Cattāro dhammakkhandhā—**Four spectrums of the teaching:*";
P_HTM[4287]="*sīlakkhandho, samādhikkhandho, paññākkhandho, vimuttikkhandho. (25)**ethics, immersion, wisdom, and freedom.*";
P_HTM[4288]="*Cattāri balāni—**Four powers:*";
P_HTM[4289]="*vīriyabalaṃ, satibalaṃ, samādhibalaṃ, paññābalaṃ. (26)**energy, mindfulness, immersion, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[4290]="*Cattāri adhiṭṭhānāni—**Four foundations:*";
P_HTM[4291]="*paññādhiṭṭhānaṃ, saccādhiṭṭhānaṃ, cāgādhiṭṭhānaṃ, upasamādhiṭṭhānaṃ. (27)**the foundations of wisdom, truth, generosity, and peace.*";
P_HTM[4292]="*Cattāri pañhabyākaraṇāni—**Four ways of answering questions.*";
P_HTM[4293]="*ekaṃsabyākaraṇīyo pañho, paṭipucchābyākaraṇīyo pañho, vibhajjabyākaraṇīyo pañho, ṭhapanīyo pañho. (28)**There is a question that should be answered definitively. There is a question that should be answered analytically. There is a question that should be answered with a counter-question. There is a question that should be set aside.*";
P_HTM[4294]="*Cattāri kammāni—**Four deeds.*";
P_HTM[4295]="*atthāvuso, kammaṃ kaṇhaṃ kaṇhavipākaṃ.**There are deeds that are dark with dark result.*";
P_HTM[4296]="*Atthāvuso, kammaṃ sukkaṃ sukkavipākaṃ.**There are deeds that are bright with bright result.*";
P_HTM[4297]="*Atthāvuso, kammaṃ kaṇhasukkaṃ kaṇhasukkavipākaṃ.**There are deeds that are dark and bright with dark and bright result.*";
P_HTM[4298]="*Atthāvuso, kammaṃ akaṇhaasukkaṃ akaṇhaasukkavipākaṃ kammakkhayāya saṃvattati. (29)**There are neither dark nor bright deeds with neither dark nor bright results, which lead to the end of deeds.*";
P_HTM[4299]="*Cattāro sacchikaraṇīyā dhammā—**Four things to be realized.*";
P_HTM[4300]="*pubbenivāso satiyā sacchikaraṇīyo;**Past lives are to be realized through recollection.*";
P_HTM[4301]="*sattānaṃ cutūpapāto cakkhunā sacchikaraṇīyo;**The passing away and rebirth of sentient beings is to be realized through vision.*";
P_HTM[4302]="*aṭṭha vimokkhā kāyena sacchikaraṇīyā;**The eight liberations are to be realized through direct meditative experience.*";
P_HTM[4303]="*āsavānaṃ khayo paññāya sacchikaraṇīyo. (30)**The ending of defilements is to be realized through wisdom.*";
P_HTM[4304]="*Cattāro oghā—**Four floods:*";
P_HTM[4305]="*kāmogho, bhavogho, diṭṭhogho, avijjogho. (31)**sensuality, desire for rebirth, views, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[4306]="*Cattāro yogā—**Four bonds:*";
P_HTM[4307]="*kāmayogo, bhavayogo, diṭṭhiyogo, avijjāyogo. (32)**sensuality, desire for rebirth, views, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[4308]="*Cattāro visaññogā—**Four detachments:*";
P_HTM[4309]="*kāmayogavisaññogo, bhavayogavisaññogo, diṭṭhiyogavisaññogo, avijjāyogavisaññogo. (33)**detachment from the bonds of sensuality, desire for rebirth, views, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[4310]="*Cattāro ganthā—**Four ties:*";
P_HTM[4311]="*abhijjhā kāyagantho, byāpādo kāyagantho, sīlabbataparāmāso kāyagantho, idaṃsaccābhiniveso kāyagantho. (34)**the personal ties to covetousness, ill will, misapprehension of precepts and observances, and the insistence that this is the only truth.*";
P_HTM[4312]="*Cattāri upādānāni—**Four kinds of grasping:*";
P_HTM[4313]="*kāmupādānaṃ, diṭṭhupādānaṃ, sīlabbatupādānaṃ, attavādupādānaṃ. (35)**grasping at sensual pleasures, views, precepts and observances, and theories of a self.*";
P_HTM[4314]="*Catasso yoniyo—**Four kinds of reproduction:*";
P_HTM[4315]="*aṇḍajayoni, jalābujayoni, saṃsedajayoni, opapātikayoni. (36)**reproduction for creatures born from an egg, from a womb, from moisture, or spontaneously.*";
P_HTM[4316]="*Catasso gabbhāvakkantiyo.**Four kinds of conception.*";
P_HTM[4317]="*Idhāvuso, ekacco asampajāno mātukucchiṃ okkamati, asampajāno mātukucchismiṃ ṭhāti, asampajāno mātukucchimhā nikkhamati, ayaṃ paṭhamā gabbhāvakkanti.**Someone is unaware when conceived in their mother’s womb, unaware as they remain there, and unaware as they emerge. This is the first kind of conception.*";
P_HTM[4318]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, idhekacco sampajāno mātukucchiṃ okkamati, asampajāno mātukucchismiṃ ṭhāti, asampajāno mātukucchimhā nikkhamati, ayaṃ dutiyā gabbhāvakkanti.**Furthermore, someone is aware when conceived in their mother’s womb, but unaware as they remain there, and unaware as they emerge. This is the second kind of conception.*";
P_HTM[4319]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, idhekacco sampajāno mātukucchiṃ okkamati, sampajāno mātukucchismiṃ ṭhāti, asampajāno mātukucchimhā nikkhamati, ayaṃ tatiyā gabbhāvakkanti.**Furthermore, someone is aware when conceived in their mother’s womb, aware as they remain there, but unaware as they emerge. This is the third kind of conception.*";
P_HTM[4320]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, idhekacco sampajāno mātukucchiṃ okkamati, sampajāno mātukucchismiṃ ṭhāti, sampajāno mātukucchimhā nikkhamati, ayaṃ catutthā gabbhāvakkanti. (37)**Furthermore, someone is aware when conceived in their mother’s womb, aware as they remain there, and aware as they emerge. This is the fourth kind of conception.*";
P_HTM[4321]="*Cattāro attabhāvapaṭilābhā.**Four kinds of reincarnation.*";
P_HTM[4322]="*Atthāvuso, attabhāvapaṭilābho, yasmiṃ attabhāvapaṭilābhe attasañcetanāyeva kamati, no parasañcetanā.**There is a reincarnation where only one’s own intention is effective, not that of others.*";
P_HTM[4323]="*Atthāvuso, attabhāvapaṭilābho, yasmiṃ attabhāvapaṭilābhe parasañcetanāyeva kamati, no attasañcetanā.**There is a reincarnation where only the intention of others is effective, not one’s own.*";
P_HTM[4324]="*Atthāvuso, attabhāvapaṭilābho, yasmiṃ attabhāvapaṭilābhe attasañcetanā ceva kamati parasañcetanā ca.**There is a reincarnation where both one’s own and others’ intentions are effective.*";
P_HTM[4325]="*Atthāvuso, attabhāvapaṭilābho, yasmiṃ attabhāvapaṭilābhe neva attasañcetanā kamati, no parasañcetanā. (38)**There is a reincarnation where neither one’s own nor others’ intentions are effective.*";
P_HTM[4326]="*Catasso dakkhiṇāvisuddhiyo.**Four ways of purifying a religious donation.*";
P_HTM[4327]="*Atthāvuso, dakkhiṇā dāyakato visujjhati no paṭiggāhakato.**There’s a religious donation that’s purified by the giver, not the recipient.*";
P_HTM[4328]="*Atthāvuso, dakkhiṇā paṭiggāhakato visujjhati no dāyakato.**There’s a religious donation that’s purified by the recipient, not the giver.*";
P_HTM[4329]="*Atthāvuso, dakkhiṇā neva dāyakato visujjhati no paṭiggāhakato.**There’s a religious donation that’s purified by neither the giver nor the recipient.*";
P_HTM[4330]="*Atthāvuso, dakkhiṇā dāyakato ceva visujjhati paṭiggāhakato ca. (39)**There’s a religious donation that’s purified by both the giver and the recipient.*";
P_HTM[4331]="*Cattāri saṅgahavatthūni—**Four ways of being inclusive:*";
P_HTM[4332]="*dānaṃ, peyyavajjaṃ, atthacariyā, samānattatā. (40)**giving, kindly words, taking care, and equality.*";
P_HTM[4333]="*Cattāro anariyavohārā—**Four ignoble expressions:*";
P_HTM[4334]="*musāvādo, pisuṇāvācā, pharusāvācā, samphappalāpo. (41)**speech that’s false, divisive, harsh, or nonsensical.*";
P_HTM[4335]="*Cattāro ariyavohārā—**Four noble expressions:*";
P_HTM[4336]="*musāvādā veramaṇī, pisuṇāya vācāya veramaṇī, pharusāya vācāya veramaṇī, samphappalāpā veramaṇī. (42)**refraining from speech that’s false, divisive, harsh, or nonsensical.*";
P_HTM[4337]="*Aparepi cattāro anariyavohārā—**Another four ignoble expressions:*";
P_HTM[4338]="*adiṭṭhe diṭṭhavāditā, assute sutavāditā, amute mutavāditā, aviññāte viññātavāditā. (43)**saying you’ve seen, heard, thought, or known something, but you haven’t.*";
P_HTM[4339]="*Aparepi cattāro ariyavohārā—**Another four noble expressions:*";
P_HTM[4340]="*adiṭṭhe adiṭṭhavāditā, assute assutavāditā, amute amutavāditā, aviññāte aviññātavāditā. (44)**saying you haven’t seen, heard, thought, or known something, and you haven’t.*";
P_HTM[4341]="*Aparepi cattāro anariyavohārā—**Another four ignoble expressions:*";
P_HTM[4342]="*diṭṭhe adiṭṭhavāditā, sute assutavāditā, mute amutavāditā, viññāte aviññātavāditā. (45)**saying you haven’t seen, heard, thought, or known something, and you have.*";
P_HTM[4343]="*Aparepi cattāro ariyavohārā—**Another four noble expressions:*";
P_HTM[4344]="*diṭṭhe diṭṭhavāditā, sute sutavāditā, mute mutavāditā, viññāte viññātavāditā. (46)**saying you’ve seen, heard, thought, or known something, and you have.*";
P_HTM[4345]="*Cattāro puggalā.**Four persons.*";
P_HTM[4346]="*Idhāvuso, ekacco puggalo attantapo hoti attaparitāpanānuyogamanuyutto.**One person mortifies themselves, committed to the practice of mortifying themselves.*";
P_HTM[4347]="*Idhāvuso, ekacco puggalo parantapo hoti paraparitāpanānuyogamanuyutto.**One person mortifies others, committed to the practice of mortifying others.*";
P_HTM[4348]="*Idhāvuso, ekacco puggalo attantapo ca hoti attaparitāpanānuyogamanuyutto, parantapo ca paraparitāpanānuyogamanuyutto.**One person mortifies themselves and others, committed to the practice of mortifying themselves and others.*";
P_HTM[4349]="*Idhāvuso, ekacco puggalo neva attantapo hoti na attaparitāpanānuyogamanuyutto na parantapo na paraparitāpanānuyogamanuyutto.**One person doesn’t mortify either themselves or others, committed to the practice of not mortifying themselves or others.*";
P_HTM[4350]="*So anattantapo aparantapo diṭṭheva dhamme nicchāto nibbuto sītībhūto sukhappaṭisaṃvedī brahmabhūtena attanā viharati. (47)**They live without wishes in the present life, extinguished, cooled, experiencing bliss, having become holy in themselves.*";
P_HTM[4351]="*Aparepi cattāro puggalā.**Another four persons.*";
P_HTM[4352]="*Idhāvuso, ekacco puggalo attahitāya paṭipanno hoti no parahitāya.**One person practices to benefit themselves, but not others.*";
P_HTM[4353]="*Idhāvuso, ekacco puggalo parahitāya paṭipanno hoti no attahitāya.**One person practices to benefit others, but not themselves.*";
P_HTM[4354]="*Idhāvuso, ekacco puggalo neva attahitāya paṭipanno hoti no parahitāya.**One person practices to benefit neither themselves nor others.*";
P_HTM[4355]="*Idhāvuso, ekacco puggalo attahitāya ceva paṭipanno hoti parahitāya ca. (48)**One person practices to benefit both themselves and others.*";
P_HTM[4356]="*Aparepi cattāro puggalā—**Another four persons:*";
P_HTM[4357]="*tamo tamaparāyano, tamo jotiparāyano, joti tamaparāyano, joti jotiparāyano. (49)**the dark bound for darkness, the dark bound for light, the light bound for darkness, and the light bound for light.*";
P_HTM[4358]="*Aparepi cattāro puggalā—**Another four persons:*";
P_HTM[4359]="*samaṇamacalo, samaṇapadumo, samaṇapuṇḍarīko, samaṇesu samaṇasukhumālo. (50)**the confirmed ascetic, the white lotus ascetic, the pink lotus ascetic, and the exquisite ascetic of ascetics.*";
P_HTM[4360]="*Ime kho, āvuso, tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena cattāro dhammā sammadakkhātā;**These are the teachings grouped by four that have been rightly explained by the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[4361]="*tattha sabbeheva saṅgāyitabbaṃ … pe … atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānaṃ.**You should all recite these in concert.*";
P_HTM[4362]="*Paṭhamabhāṇavāro niṭṭhito.**The first recitation section is finished.*";
P_HTM[4363]="*5. Pañcaka**5. Fives*";
P_HTM[4364]="*Atthi kho, āvuso, tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena pañca dhammā sammadakkhātā.**There are teachings grouped by five that have been rightly explained by the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[4365]="*Tattha sabbeheva saṅgāyitabbaṃ … pe … atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānaṃ.**You should all recite these in concert.*";
P_HTM[4366]="*Katame pañca?**What are the teachings grouped by five?*";
P_HTM[4367]="*Pañcakkhandhā.**Five aggregates:*";
P_HTM[4368]="*Rūpakkhandho vedanākkhandho saññākkhandho saṅkhārakkhandho viññāṇakkhandho. (1)**form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[4369]="*Pañcupādānakkhandhā.**Five grasping aggregates:*";
P_HTM[4370]="*Rūpupādānakkhandho vedanupādānakkhandho saññupādānakkhandho saṅkhārupādānakkhandho viññāṇupādānakkhandho. (2)**form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[4371]="*Pañca kāmaguṇā.**Five kinds of sensual stimulation.*";
P_HTM[4372]="*Cakkhuviññeyyā rūpā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasañhitā rajanīyā,**Sights known by the eye that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[4373]="*sotaviññeyyā saddā …**Sounds known by the ear …*";
P_HTM[4374]="*ghānaviññeyyā gandhā …**Smells known by the nose …*";
P_HTM[4375]="*jivhāviññeyyā rasā …**Tastes known by the tongue …*";
P_HTM[4376]="*kāyaviññeyyā phoṭṭhabbā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasañhitā rajanīyā. (3)**Touches known by the body that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[4377]="*Pañca gatiyo—**Five destinations:*";
P_HTM[4378]="*nirayo, tiracchānayoni, pettivisayo, manussā, devā. (4)**hell, the animal realm, the ghost realm, humanity, and the gods.*";
P_HTM[4379]="*Pañca macchariyāni—**Five kinds of stinginess:*";
P_HTM[4380]="*āvāsamacchariyaṃ, kulamacchariyaṃ, lābhamacchariyaṃ, vaṇṇamacchariyaṃ, dhammamacchariyaṃ. (5)**stinginess with dwellings, families, material possessions, praise, and the teachings.*";
P_HTM[4381]="*Pañca nīvaraṇāni—**Five hindrances:*";
P_HTM[4382]="*kāmacchandanīvaraṇaṃ, byāpādanīvaraṇaṃ, thinamiddhanīvaraṇaṃ, uddhaccakukkuccanīvaraṇaṃ, vicikicchānīvaraṇaṃ. (6)**sensual desire, ill will, dullness and drowsiness, restlessness and remorse, and doubt.*";
P_HTM[4383]="*Pañca orambhāgiyāni saṃyojanāni—**Five lower fetters:*";
P_HTM[4384]="*sakkāyadiṭṭhi, vicikicchā, sīlabbataparāmāso, kāmacchando, byāpādo. (7)**identity view, doubt, misapprehension of precepts and observances, sensual desire, and ill will.*";
P_HTM[4385]="*Pañca uddhambhāgiyāni saṃyojanāni—**Five higher fetters:*";
P_HTM[4386]="*rūparāgo, arūparāgo, māno, uddhaccaṃ, avijjā. (8)**desire for rebirth in the realm of luminous form, desire for rebirth in the formless realm, conceit, restlessness, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[4387]="*Pañca sikkhāpadāni—**Five precepts:*";
P_HTM[4388]="*pāṇātipātā veramaṇī, adinnādānā veramaṇī, kāmesumicchācārā veramaṇī, musāvādā veramaṇī, surāmerayamajjappamādaṭṭhānā veramaṇī. (9)**refraining from killing living creatures, stealing, sexual misconduct, lying, and drinking alcohol, which is a basis for negligence.*";
P_HTM[4389]="*Pañca abhabbaṭṭhānāni.**Five things that can’t be done.*";
P_HTM[4390]="*Abhabbo, āvuso, khīṇāsavo bhikkhu sañcicca pāṇaṃ jīvitā voropetuṃ. Abhabbo khīṇāsavo bhikkhu adinnaṃ theyyasaṅkhātaṃ ādiyituṃ. Abhabbo khīṇāsavo bhikkhu methunaṃ dhammaṃ paṭisevituṃ. Abhabbo khīṇāsavo bhikkhu sampajānamusā bhāsituṃ. Abhabbo khīṇāsavo bhikkhu sannidhikārakaṃ kāme paribhuñjituṃ, seyyathāpi pubbe āgārikabhūto. (10)**A mendicant with defilements ended can’t deliberately take the life of a living creature, take something with the intention to steal, have sex, tell a deliberate lie, or store up goods for their own enjoyment like they did as a lay person.*";
P_HTM[4391]="*Pañca byasanāni—**Five losses:*";
P_HTM[4392]="*ñātibyasanaṃ, bhogabyasanaṃ, rogabyasanaṃ, sīlabyasanaṃ, diṭṭhibyasanaṃ.**loss of relatives, wealth, health, ethics, and view.*";
P_HTM[4393]="*Nāvuso, sattā ñātibyasanahetu vā bhogabyasanahetu vā rogabyasanahetu vā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjanti.**It is not because of loss of relatives, wealth, or health that sentient beings, when their body breaks up, after death, are reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell.*";
P_HTM[4394]="*Sīlabyasanahetu vā, āvuso, sattā diṭṭhibyasanahetu vā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjanti. (11)**It is because of loss of ethics or view that sentient beings, when their body breaks up, after death, are reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell.*";
P_HTM[4395]="*Pañca sampadā—**Five endowments:*";
P_HTM[4396]="*ñātisampadā, bhogasampadā, ārogyasampadā, sīlasampadā, diṭṭhisampadā.**endowment with relatives, wealth, health, ethics, and view.*";
P_HTM[4397]="*Nāvuso, sattā ñātisampadāhetu vā bhogasampadāhetu vā ārogyasampadāhetu vā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjanti.**It is not because of endowment with family, wealth, or health that sentient beings, when their body breaks up, after death, are reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[4398]="*Sīlasampadāhetu vā, āvuso, sattā diṭṭhisampadāhetu vā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjanti. (12)**It is because of endowment with ethics or view that sentient beings, when their body breaks up, after death, are reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[4399]="*Pañca ādīnavā dussīlassa sīlavipattiyā.**Five drawbacks for an unethical person because of their failure in ethics.*";
P_HTM[4400]="*Idhāvuso, dussīlo sīlavipanno pamādādhikaraṇaṃ mahatiṃ bhogajāniṃ nigacchati,**Firstly, an unethical person loses substantial wealth on account of negligence.*";
P_HTM[4401]="*ayaṃ paṭhamo ādīnavo dussīlassa sīlavipattiyā.**This is the first drawback.*";
P_HTM[4402]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, dussīlassa sīlavipannassa pāpako kittisaddo abbhuggacchati,**Furthermore, an unethical person gets a bad reputation.*";
P_HTM[4403]="*ayaṃ dutiyo ādīnavo dussīlassa sīlavipattiyā.**This is the second drawback.*";
P_HTM[4404]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, dussīlo sīlavipanno yaññadeva parisaṃ upasaṅkamati yadi khattiyaparisaṃ yadi brāhmaṇaparisaṃ yadi gahapatiparisaṃ yadi samaṇaparisaṃ, avisārado upasaṅkamati maṅkubhūto,**Furthermore, an unethical person enters any kind of assembly timid and embarrassed, whether it’s an assembly of aristocrats, brahmins, householders, or ascetics.*";
P_HTM[4405]="*ayaṃ tatiyo ādīnavo dussīlassa sīlavipattiyā.**This is the third drawback.*";
P_HTM[4406]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, dussīlo sīlavipanno sammūḷho kālaṃ karoti,**Furthermore, an unethical person dies feeling lost.*";
P_HTM[4407]="*ayaṃ catuttho ādīnavo dussīlassa sīlavipattiyā.**This is the fourth drawback.*";
P_HTM[4408]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, dussīlo sīlavipanno kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjati,**Furthermore, an unethical person, when their body breaks up, after death, is reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell.*";
P_HTM[4409]="*ayaṃ pañcamo ādīnavo dussīlassa sīlavipattiyā. (13)**This is the fifth drawback.*";
P_HTM[4410]="*Pañca ānisaṃsā sīlavato sīlasampadāya.**Five benefits for an ethical person because of their accomplishment in ethics.*";
P_HTM[4411]="*Idhāvuso, sīlavā sīlasampanno appamādādhikaraṇaṃ mahantaṃ bhogakkhandhaṃ adhigacchati,**Firstly, an ethical person gains substantial wealth on account of diligence.*";
P_HTM[4412]="*ayaṃ paṭhamo ānisaṃso sīlavato sīlasampadāya.**This is the first benefit.*";
P_HTM[4413]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, sīlavato sīlasampannassa kalyāṇo kittisaddo abbhuggacchati,**Furthermore, an ethical person gets a good reputation.*";
P_HTM[4414]="*ayaṃ dutiyo ānisaṃso sīlavato sīlasampadāya.**This is the second benefit.*";
P_HTM[4415]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, sīlavā sīlasampanno yaññadeva parisaṃ upasaṅkamati yadi khattiyaparisaṃ yadi brāhmaṇaparisaṃ yadi gahapatiparisaṃ yadi samaṇaparisaṃ, visārado upasaṅkamati amaṅkubhūto,**Furthermore, an ethical person enters any kind of assembly bold and self-assured, whether it’s an assembly of aristocrats, brahmins, householders, or ascetics.*";
P_HTM[4416]="*ayaṃ tatiyo ānisaṃso sīlavato sīlasampadāya.**This is the third benefit.*";
P_HTM[4417]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, sīlavā sīlasampanno asammūḷho kālaṃ karoti,**Furthermore, an ethical person dies not feeling lost.*";
P_HTM[4418]="*ayaṃ catuttho ānisaṃso sīlavato sīlasampadāya.**This is the fourth benefit.*";
P_HTM[4419]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, sīlavā sīlasampanno kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjati,**Furthermore, when an ethical person’s body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[4420]="*ayaṃ pañcamo ānisaṃso sīlavato sīlasampadāya. (14)**This is the fifth benefit.*";
P_HTM[4421]="*Codakena, āvuso, bhikkhunā paraṃ codetukāmena pañca dhamme ajjhattaṃ upaṭṭhapetvā paro codetabbo.**A mendicant who wants to accuse another should first establish five things in themselves.*";
P_HTM[4422]="*Kālena vakkhāmi no akālena,**I will speak at the right time, not at the wrong time.*";
P_HTM[4423]="*bhūtena vakkhāmi no abhūtena,**I will speak truthfully, not falsely.*";
P_HTM[4424]="*saṇhena vakkhāmi no pharusena,**I will speak gently, not harshly.*";
P_HTM[4425]="*atthasaṃhitena vakkhāmi no anatthasaṃhitena,**I will speak beneficially, not harmfully.*";
P_HTM[4426]="*mettacittena vakkhāmi no dosantarenāti.**I will speak lovingly, not from secret hate.*";
P_HTM[4427]="*Codakena, āvuso, bhikkhunā paraṃ codetukāmena ime pañca dhamme ajjhattaṃ upaṭṭhapetvā paro codetabbo. (15)**A mendicant who wants to accuse another should first establish these five things in themselves.*";
P_HTM[4428]="*Pañca padhāniyaṅgāni.**Five factors that support meditation.*";
P_HTM[4429]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu saddho hoti, saddahati tathāgatassa bodhiṃ:**A mendicant has faith in the Realized One’s awakening:*";
P_HTM[4430]="*‘itipi so bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato, lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā’ti.**‘That Blessed One is perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.’*";
P_HTM[4431]="*Appābādho hoti appātaṅko, samavepākiniyā gahaṇiyā samannāgato nātisītāya nāccuṇhāya majjhimāya padhānakkhamāya.**They are rarely ill or unwell. Their stomach digests well, being neither too hot nor too cold, but just right, and fit for meditation.*";
P_HTM[4432]="*Asaṭho hoti amāyāvī, yathābhūtaṃ attānaṃ āvikattā satthari vā viññūsu vā sabrahmacārīsu.**They’re not devious or deceitful. They reveal themselves honestly to the Teacher or sensible spiritual companions.*";
P_HTM[4433]="*Āraddhavīriyo viharati akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ pahānāya kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ upasampadāya thāmavā daḷhaparakkamo anikkhittadhuro kusalesu dhammesu.**They live with energy roused up for giving up unskillful qualities and embracing skillful qualities. They’re strong, staunchly vigorous, not slacking off when it comes to developing skillful qualities.*";
P_HTM[4434]="*Paññavā hoti udayatthagāminiyā paññāya samannāgato ariyāya nibbedhikāya sammādukkhakkhayagāminiyā. (16)**They’re wise. They have the wisdom of arising and passing away which is noble, penetrative, and leads to the complete ending of suffering.*";
P_HTM[4435]="*Pañca suddhāvāsā—**Five pure abodes:*";
P_HTM[4436]="*avihā, atappā, sudassā, sudassī, akaniṭṭhā. (17)**Aviha, Atappa, the Gods Fair to See, the Fair Seeing Gods, and Akaniṭṭha.*";
P_HTM[4437]="*Pañca anāgāmino—**Five non-returners:*";
P_HTM[4438]="*antarāparinibbāyī, upahaccaparinibbāyī, asaṅkhāraparinibbāyī, sasaṅkhāraparinibbāyī, uddhaṃsotoakaniṭṭhagāmī. (18)**one who is extinguished between one life and the next, one who is extinguished upon landing, one who is extinguished without extra effort, one who is extinguished with extra effort, and one who heads upstream, going to the Akaniṭṭha realm.*";
P_HTM[4439]="*Pañca cetokhilā.**Five kinds of emotional barrenness.*";
P_HTM[4440]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu satthari kaṅkhati vicikicchati nādhimuccati na sampasīdati.**Firstly, a mendicant has doubts about the Teacher. They’re uncertain, undecided, and lacking confidence.*";
P_HTM[4441]="*Yo so, āvuso, bhikkhu satthari kaṅkhati vicikicchati nādhimuccati na sampasīdati, tassa cittaṃ na namati ātappāya anuyogāya sātaccāya padhānāya, yassa cittaṃ na namati ātappāya anuyogāya sātaccāya padhānāya, ayaṃ paṭhamo cetokhilo.**This being so, their mind doesn’t incline toward keenness, commitment, persistence, and striving. This is the first kind of emotional barrenness.*";
P_HTM[4442]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu dhamme kaṅkhati vicikicchati … pe …**Furthermore, a mendicant has doubts about the teaching …*";
P_HTM[4443]="*saṃghe kaṅkhati vicikicchati …**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[4444]="*sikkhāya kaṅkhati vicikicchati …**the training …*";
P_HTM[4445]="*sabrahmacārīsu kupito hoti anattamano āhatacitto khilajāto.**A mendicant is angry and upset with their spiritual companions, resentful and closed off.*";
P_HTM[4446]="*Yo so, āvuso, bhikkhu sabrahmacārīsu kupito hoti anattamano āhatacitto khilajāto, tassa cittaṃ na namati ātappāya anuyogāya sātaccāya padhānāya, yassa cittaṃ na namati ātappāya anuyogāya sātaccāya padhānāya, ayaṃ pañcamo cetokhilo. (19)**This being so, their mind doesn’t incline toward keenness, commitment, persistence, and striving. This is the fifth kind of emotional barrenness.*";
P_HTM[4447]="*Pañca cetasovinibandhā.**Five emotional shackles.*";
P_HTM[4448]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu kāmesu avītarāgo hoti avigatacchando avigatapemo avigatapipāso avigatapariḷāho avigatataṇho.**Firstly, a mendicant isn’t free of greed, desire, fondness, thirst, passion, and craving for sensual pleasures.*";
P_HTM[4449]="*Yo so, āvuso, bhikkhu kāmesu avītarāgo hoti avigatacchando avigatapemo avigatapipāso avigatapariḷāho avigatataṇho, tassa cittaṃ na namati ātappāya anuyogāya sātaccāya padhānāya.* **";
P_HTM[4450]="*Yassa cittaṃ na namati ātappāya anuyogāya sātaccāya padhānāya.**This being so, their mind doesn’t incline toward keenness, commitment, persistence, and striving.*";
P_HTM[4451]="*Ayaṃ paṭhamo cetaso vinibandho.**This is the first emotional shackle.*";
P_HTM[4452]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu kāye avītarāgo hoti … pe …**Furthermore, a mendicant isn’t free of greed for the body …*";
P_HTM[4453]="*rūpe avītarāgo hoti … pe …**They’re not free of greed for form …*";
P_HTM[4454]="*puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu yāvadatthaṃ udarāvadehakaṃ bhuñjitvā seyyasukhaṃ passasukhaṃ middhasukhaṃ anuyutto viharati … pe …**They eat as much as they like until their bellies are full, then indulge in the pleasures of sleeping, lying, and drowsing …*";
P_HTM[4455]="*puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu aññataraṃ devanikāyaṃ paṇidhāya brahmacariyaṃ carati: ‘imināhaṃ sīlena vā vatena vā tapena vā brahmacariyena vā devo vā bhavissāmi devaññataro vā’ti.**They live the spiritual life hoping to be reborn in one of the orders of gods, thinking: ‘By this precept or observance or mortification or spiritual life, may I become one of the gods!’*";
P_HTM[4456]="*Yo so, āvuso, bhikkhu aññataraṃ devanikāyaṃ paṇidhāya brahmacariyaṃ carati: ‘imināhaṃ sīlena vā vatena vā tapena vā brahmacariyena vā devo vā bhavissāmi devaññataro vā’ti, tassa cittaṃ na namati ātappāya anuyogāya sātaccāya padhānāya. Yassa cittaṃ na namati ātappāya anuyogāya sātaccāya padhānāya.**This being so, their mind doesn’t incline toward keenness, commitment, persistence, and striving.*";
P_HTM[4457]="*Ayaṃ pañcamo cetaso vinibandho. (20)**This is the fifth emotional shackle.*";
P_HTM[4458]="*Pañcindriyāni—**Five faculties:*";
P_HTM[4459]="*cakkhundriyaṃ, sotindriyaṃ, ghānindriyaṃ, jivhindriyaṃ, kāyindriyaṃ. (21)**eye, ear, nose, tongue, and body.*";
P_HTM[4460]="*Aparānipi pañcindriyāni—**Another five faculties:*";
P_HTM[4461]="*sukhindriyaṃ, dukkhindriyaṃ, somanassindriyaṃ, domanassindriyaṃ, upekkhindriyaṃ. (22)**pleasure, pain, happiness, sadness, and equanimity.*";
P_HTM[4462]="*Aparānipi pañcindriyāni—**Another five faculties:*";
P_HTM[4463]="*saddhindriyaṃ, vīriyindriyaṃ, satindriyaṃ, samādhindriyaṃ, paññindriyaṃ. (23)**faith, energy, mindfulness, immersion, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[4464]="*Pañca nissaraṇiyā dhātuyo.**Five elements of escape.*";
P_HTM[4465]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhuno kāme manasikaroto kāmesu cittaṃ na pakkhandati na pasīdati na santiṭṭhati na vimuccati.**Take a case where a mendicant focuses on sensual pleasures, but their mind isn’t eager, confident, settled, and decided about them.*";
P_HTM[4466]="*Nekkhammaṃ kho panassa manasikaroto nekkhamme cittaṃ pakkhandati pasīdati santiṭṭhati vimuccati.**But when they focus on renunciation, their mind is eager, confident, settled, and decided about it.*";
P_HTM[4467]="*Tassa taṃ cittaṃ sugataṃ subhāvitaṃ suvuṭṭhitaṃ suvimuttaṃ visaṃyuttaṃ kāmehi.**Their mind is in a good state, well developed, well risen, well freed, and well detached from sensual pleasures.*";
P_HTM[4468]="*Ye ca kāmapaccayā uppajjanti āsavā vighātā pariḷāhā, mutto so tehi, na so taṃ vedanaṃ vedeti.**They’re freed from the distressing and feverish defilements that arise because of sensual pleasures, so they don’t experience that kind of feeling.*";
P_HTM[4469]="*Idamakkhātaṃ kāmānaṃ nissaraṇaṃ. (24.1)**This is how the escape from sensual pleasures is explained.*";
P_HTM[4470]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhuno byāpādaṃ manasikaroto byāpāde cittaṃ na pakkhandati na pasīdati na santiṭṭhati na vimuccati.**Take another case where a mendicant focuses on ill will, but their mind isn’t eager …*";
P_HTM[4471]="*Abyāpādaṃ kho panassa manasikaroto abyāpāde cittaṃ pakkhandati pasīdati santiṭṭhati vimuccati.**But when they focus on good will, their mind is eager …*";
P_HTM[4472]="*Tassa taṃ cittaṃ sugataṃ subhāvitaṃ suvuṭṭhitaṃ suvimuttaṃ visaṃyuttaṃ byāpādena.**Their mind is in a good state … well detached from ill will.*";
P_HTM[4473]="*Ye ca byāpādapaccayā uppajjanti āsavā vighātā pariḷāhā, mutto so tehi, na so taṃ vedanaṃ vedeti.**They’re freed from the distressing and feverish defilements that arise because of ill will, so they don’t experience that kind of feeling.*";
P_HTM[4474]="*Idamakkhātaṃ byāpādassa nissaraṇaṃ. (24.2)**This is how the escape from ill will is explained.*";
P_HTM[4475]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhuno vihesaṃ manasikaroto vihesāya cittaṃ na pakkhandati na pasīdati na santiṭṭhati na vimuccati.**Take another case where a mendicant focuses on harming, but their mind isn’t eager …*";
P_HTM[4476]="*Avihesaṃ kho panassa manasikaroto avihesāya cittaṃ pakkhandati pasīdati santiṭṭhati vimuccati.**But when they focus on compassion, their mind is eager …*";
P_HTM[4477]="*Tassa taṃ cittaṃ sugataṃ subhāvitaṃ suvuṭṭhitaṃ suvimuttaṃ visaṃyuttaṃ vihesāya.**Their mind is in a good state … well detached from harming.*";
P_HTM[4478]="*Ye ca vihesāpaccayā uppajjanti āsavā vighātā pariḷāhā, mutto so tehi, na so taṃ vedanaṃ vedeti.**They’re freed from the distressing and feverish defilements that arise because of harming, so they don’t experience that kind of feeling.*";
P_HTM[4479]="*Idamakkhātaṃ vihesāya nissaraṇaṃ. (24.3)**This is how the escape from harming is explained.*";
P_HTM[4480]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhuno rūpe manasikaroto rūpesu cittaṃ na pakkhandati na pasīdati na santiṭṭhati na vimuccati.**Take another case where a mendicant focuses on form, but their mind isn’t eager …*";
P_HTM[4481]="*Arūpaṃ kho panassa manasikaroto arūpe cittaṃ pakkhandati pasīdati santiṭṭhati vimuccati.**But when they focus on the formless, their mind is eager …*";
P_HTM[4482]="*Tassa taṃ cittaṃ sugataṃ subhāvitaṃ suvuṭṭhitaṃ suvimuttaṃ visaṃyuttaṃ rūpehi.**Their mind is in a good state … well detached from forms.*";
P_HTM[4483]="*Ye ca rūpapaccayā uppajjanti āsavā vighātā pariḷāhā, mutto so tehi, na so taṃ vedanaṃ vedeti.**They’re freed from the distressing and feverish defilements that arise because of form, so they don’t experience that kind of feeling.*";
P_HTM[4484]="*Idamakkhātaṃ rūpānaṃ nissaraṇaṃ. (24.4)**This is how the escape from forms is explained.*";
P_HTM[4485]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhuno sakkāyaṃ manasikaroto sakkāye cittaṃ na pakkhandati na pasīdati na santiṭṭhati na vimuccati.**Take a case where a mendicant focuses on identity, but their mind isn’t eager, confident, settled, and decided about it.*";
P_HTM[4486]="*Sakkāyanirodhaṃ kho panassa manasikaroto sakkāyanirodhe cittaṃ pakkhandati pasīdati santiṭṭhati vimuccati.**But when they focus on the ending of identity, their mind is eager, confident, settled, and decided about it.*";
P_HTM[4487]="*Tassa taṃ cittaṃ sugataṃ subhāvitaṃ suvuṭṭhitaṃ suvimuttaṃ visaṃyuttaṃ sakkāyena.**Their mind is in a good state, well developed, well risen, well freed, and well detached from identity.*";
P_HTM[4488]="*Ye ca sakkāyapaccayā uppajjanti āsavā vighātā pariḷāhā, mutto so tehi, na so taṃ vedanaṃ vedeti.**They’re freed from the distressing and feverish defilements that arise because of identity, so they don’t experience that kind of feeling.*";
P_HTM[4489]="*Idamakkhātaṃ sakkāyassa nissaraṇaṃ. (24.5)**This is how the escape from identity is explained.*";
P_HTM[4490]="*Pañca vimuttāyatanāni.**Five opportunities for freedom.*";
P_HTM[4491]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhuno satthā dhammaṃ deseti aññataro vā garuṭṭhāniyo sabrahmacārī.**Firstly, the Teacher or a respected spiritual companion teaches Dhamma to a mendicant.*";
P_HTM[4492]="*Yathā yathā, āvuso, bhikkhuno satthā dhammaṃ deseti aññataro vā garuṭṭhāniyo sabrahmacārī tathā tathā so tasmiṃ dhamme atthapaṭisaṃvedī ca hoti dhammapaṭisaṃvedī ca.**That mendicant feels inspired by the meaning and the teaching in that Dhamma, no matter how the Teacher or a respected spiritual companion teaches it.*";
P_HTM[4493]="*Tassa atthapaṭisaṃvedino dhammapaṭisaṃvedino pāmojjaṃ jāyati, pamuditassa pīti jāyati, pītimanassa kāyo passambhati, passaddhakāyo sukhaṃ vedeti, sukhino cittaṃ samādhiyati.**Feeling inspired, joy springs up. Being joyful, rapture springs up. When the mind is full of rapture, the body becomes tranquil. When the body is tranquil, one feels bliss. And when blissful, the mind becomes immersed.*";
P_HTM[4494]="*Idaṃ paṭhamaṃ vimuttāyatanaṃ. (25.1)**This is the first opportunity for freedom.*";
P_HTM[4495]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhuno na heva kho satthā dhammaṃ deseti aññataro vā garuṭṭhāniyo sabrahmacārī, api ca kho yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ vitthārena paresaṃ deseti … pe …**Furthermore, it may be that neither the Teacher nor a respected spiritual companion teaches Dhamma to a mendicant. But the mendicant teaches Dhamma in detail to others as they learned and memorized it. …*";
P_HTM[4496]="*api ca kho yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ vitthārena sajjhāyaṃ karoti … pe …**Or the mendicant recites the teaching in detail as they learned and memorized it. …*";
P_HTM[4497]="*api ca kho yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ cetasā anuvitakketi anuvicāreti manasānupekkhati … pe …**Or the mendicant thinks about and considers the teaching in their heart, examining it with the mind as they learned and memorized it. …*";
P_HTM[4498]="*api ca khvassa aññataraṃ samādhinimittaṃ suggahitaṃ hoti sumanasikataṃ sūpadhāritaṃ suppaṭividdhaṃ paññāya.**Or a meditation subject as a foundation of immersion is properly grasped, attended, borne in mind, and comprehended with wisdom.*";
P_HTM[4499]="*Yathā yathā, āvuso, bhikkhuno aññataraṃ samādhinimittaṃ suggahitaṃ hoti sumanasikataṃ sūpadhāritaṃ suppaṭividdhaṃ paññāya tathā tathā so tasmiṃ dhamme atthapaṭisaṃvedī ca hoti dhammapaṭisaṃvedī ca.**That mendicant feels inspired by the meaning and the teaching in that Dhamma, no matter how a meditation subject as a foundation of immersion is properly grasped, attended, borne in mind, and comprehended with wisdom.*";
P_HTM[4500]="*Tassa atthapaṭisaṃvedino dhammapaṭisaṃvedino pāmojjaṃ jāyati, pamuditassa pīti jāyati, pītimanassa kāyo passambhati, passaddhakāyo sukhaṃ vedeti, sukhino cittaṃ samādhiyati.**Feeling inspired, joy springs up. Being joyful, rapture springs up. When the mind is full of rapture, the body becomes tranquil. When the body is tranquil, one feels bliss. And when blissful, the mind becomes immersed.*";
P_HTM[4501]="*Idaṃ pañcamaṃ vimuttāyatanaṃ. (25.2–5.)**This is the fifth opportunity for freedom.*";
P_HTM[4502]="*Pañca vimuttiparipācanīyā saññā—**Five perceptions that ripen in freedom:*";
P_HTM[4503]="*aniccasaññā, anicce dukkhasaññā, dukkhe anattasaññā, pahānasaññā, virāgasaññā. (26)**the perception of impermanence, the perception of suffering in impermanence, the perception of not-self in suffering, the perception of giving up, and the perception of fading away.*";
P_HTM[4504]="*Ime kho, āvuso, tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena pañca dhammā sammadakkhātā;**These are the teachings grouped by five that have been rightly explained by the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[4505]="*tattha sabbeheva saṅgāyitabbaṃ … pe … atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānaṃ.**You should all recite these in concert.*";
P_HTM[4506]="*6. Chakka**6. Sixes*";
P_HTM[4507]="*Atthi kho, āvuso, tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena cha dhammā sammadakkhātā;**There are teachings grouped by six that have been rightly explained by the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[4508]="*tattha sabbeheva saṅgāyitabbaṃ … pe … atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānaṃ.**You should all recite these in concert.*";
P_HTM[4509]="*Katame cha?**What are the teachings grouped by six?*";
P_HTM[4510]="*Cha ajjhattikāni āyatanāni—**Six interior sense fields:*";
P_HTM[4511]="*cakkhāyatanaṃ, sotāyatanaṃ, ghānāyatanaṃ, jivhāyatanaṃ, kāyāyatanaṃ, manāyatanaṃ. (1)**eye, ear, nose, tongue, body, and mind.*";
P_HTM[4512]="*Cha bāhirāni āyatanāni—**Six exterior sense fields:*";
P_HTM[4513]="*rūpāyatanaṃ, saddāyatanaṃ, gandhāyatanaṃ, rasāyatanaṃ, phoṭṭhabbāyatanaṃ, dhammāyatanaṃ. (2)**sights, sounds, smells, tastes, touches, and thoughts.*";
P_HTM[4514]="*Cha viññāṇakāyā—**Six classes of consciousness:*";
P_HTM[4515]="*cakkhuviññāṇaṃ, sotaviññāṇaṃ, ghānaviññāṇaṃ, jivhāviññāṇaṃ, kāyaviññāṇaṃ, manoviññāṇaṃ. (3)**eye, ear, nose, tongue, body, and mind consciousness.*";
P_HTM[4516]="*Cha phassakāyā—**Six classes of contact:*";
P_HTM[4517]="*cakkhusamphasso, sotasamphasso, ghānasamphasso, jivhāsamphasso, kāyasamphasso, manosamphasso. (4)**contact through the eye, ear, nose, tongue, body, and mind.*";
P_HTM[4518]="*Cha vedanākāyā—**Six classes of feeling:*";
P_HTM[4519]="*cakkhusamphassajā vedanā, sotasamphassajā vedanā, ghānasamphassajā vedanā, jivhāsamphassajā vedanā, kāyasamphassajā vedanā, manosamphassajā vedanā. (5)**feeling born of contact through the eye, ear, nose, tongue, body, and mind.*";
P_HTM[4520]="*Cha saññākāyā—**Six classes of perception:*";
P_HTM[4521]="*rūpasaññā, saddasaññā, gandhasaññā, rasasaññā, phoṭṭhabbasaññā, dhammasaññā. (6)**perceptions of sights, sounds, smells, tastes, touches, and thoughts.*";
P_HTM[4522]="*Cha sañcetanākāyā—**Six bodies of intention:*";
P_HTM[4523]="*rūpasañcetanā, saddasañcetanā, gandhasañcetanā, rasasañcetanā, phoṭṭhabbasañcetanā, dhammasañcetanā. (7)**intention regarding sights, sounds, smells, tastes, touches, and thoughts.*";
P_HTM[4524]="*Cha taṇhākāyā—**Six classes of craving:*";
P_HTM[4525]="*rūpataṇhā, saddataṇhā, gandhataṇhā, rasataṇhā, phoṭṭhabbataṇhā, dhammataṇhā. (8)**craving for sights, sounds, smells, tastes, touches, and thoughts.*";
P_HTM[4526]="*Cha agāravā.**Six kinds of disrespect.*";
P_HTM[4527]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu satthari agāravo viharati appatisso; dhamme agāravo viharati appatisso; saṃghe agāravo viharati appatisso; sikkhāya agāravo viharati appatisso; appamāde agāravo viharati appatisso; paṭisanthāre agāravo viharati appatisso. (9)**A mendicant lacks respect and reverence for the Teacher, the teaching, and the Saṅgha, the training, diligence, and hospitality.*";
P_HTM[4528]="*Cha gāravā.**Six kinds of respect.*";
P_HTM[4529]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu satthari sagāravo viharati sappatisso; dhamme sagāravo viharati sappatisso; saṅghe sagāravo viharati sappatisso; sikkhāya sagāravo viharati sappatisso; appamāde sagāravo viharati sappatisso; paṭisanthāre sagāravo viharati sappatisso. (10)**A mendicant has respect and reverence for the Teacher, the teaching, and the Saṅgha, the training, diligence, and hospitality.*";
P_HTM[4530]="*Cha somanassūpavicārā.**Six preoccupations with happiness.*";
P_HTM[4531]="*Cakkhunā rūpaṃ disvā somanassaṭṭhāniyaṃ rūpaṃ upavicarati;**Seeing a sight with the eye, one is preoccupied with a sight that’s a basis for happiness.*";
P_HTM[4532]="*sotena saddaṃ sutvā …**Hearing a sound with the ear …*";
P_HTM[4533]="*ghānena gandhaṃ ghāyitvā …**Smelling an odor with the nose …*";
P_HTM[4534]="*jivhāya rasaṃ sāyitvā …**Tasting a flavor with the tongue …*";
P_HTM[4535]="*kāyena phoṭṭhabbaṃ phusitvā.**Feeling a touch with the body …*";
P_HTM[4536]="*Manasā dhammaṃ viññāya somanassaṭṭhāniyaṃ dhammaṃ upavicarati. (11)**Knowing a thought with the mind, one is preoccupied with a thought that’s a basis for happiness.*";
P_HTM[4537]="*Cha domanassūpavicārā.**Six preoccupations with sadness.*";
P_HTM[4538]="*Cakkhunā rūpaṃ disvā domanassaṭṭhāniyaṃ rūpaṃ upavicarati … pe …**Seeing a sight with the eye, one is preoccupied with a sight that’s a basis for sadness. …*";
P_HTM[4539]="*manasā dhammaṃ viññāya domanassaṭṭhāniyaṃ dhammaṃ upavicarati. (12)**Knowing a thought with the mind, one is preoccupied with a thought that’s a basis for sadness.*";
P_HTM[4540]="*Cha upekkhūpavicārā.**Six preoccupations with equanimity.*";
P_HTM[4541]="*Cakkhunā rūpaṃ disvā upekkhāṭṭhāniyaṃ rūpaṃ upavicarati … pe …**Seeing a sight with the eye, one is preoccupied with a sight that’s a basis for equanimity. …*";
P_HTM[4542]="*manasā dhammaṃ viññāya upekkhāṭṭhāniyaṃ dhammaṃ upavicarati. (13)**Knowing a thought with the mind, one is preoccupied with a thought that’s a basis for equanimity.*";
P_HTM[4543]="*Cha sāraṇīyā dhammā.**Six warm-hearted qualities.*";
P_HTM[4544]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhuno mettaṃ kāyakammaṃ paccupaṭṭhitaṃ hoti sabrahmacārīsu āvi ceva raho ca.**Firstly, a mendicant consistently treats their spiritual companions with bodily kindness, both in public and in private.*";
P_HTM[4545]="*Ayampi dhammo sāraṇīyo piyakaraṇo garukaraṇo saṅgahāya avivādāya sāmaggiyā ekībhāvāya saṃvattati. (14.1)**This warm-hearted quality makes for fondness and respect, conducing to inclusion, harmony, and unity, without quarreling.*";
P_HTM[4546]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhuno mettaṃ vacīkammaṃ paccupaṭṭhitaṃ hoti sabrahmacārīsu āvi ceva raho ca.**Furthermore, a mendicant consistently treats their spiritual companions with verbal kindness, both in public and in private.*";
P_HTM[4547]="*Ayampi dhammo sāraṇīyo … pe … ekībhāvāya saṃvattati. (14.2)**This too is a warm-hearted quality.*";
P_HTM[4548]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhuno mettaṃ manokammaṃ paccupaṭṭhitaṃ hoti sabrahmacārīsu āvi ceva raho ca.**Furthermore, a mendicant consistently treats their spiritual companions with mental kindness, both in public and in private.*";
P_HTM[4549]="*Ayampi dhammo sāraṇīyo … pe … ekībhāvāya saṃvattati. (14.3)**This too is a warm-hearted quality.*";
P_HTM[4550]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu ye te lābhā dhammikā dhammaladdhā antamaso pattapariyāpannamattampi, tathārūpehi lābhehi appaṭivibhattabhogī hoti sīlavantehi sabrahmacārīhi sādhāraṇabhogī.**Furthermore, a mendicant shares without reservation any material possessions they have gained by legitimate means, even the food placed in the alms-bowl, using them in common with their ethical spiritual companions.*";
P_HTM[4551]="*Ayampi dhammo sāraṇīyo … pe … ekībhāvāya saṃvattati. (14.4)**This too is a warm-hearted quality.*";
P_HTM[4552]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu yāni tāni sīlāni akhaṇḍāni acchiddāni asabalāni akammāsāni bhujissāni viññuppasatthāni aparāmaṭṭhāni samādhisaṃvattanikāni, tathārūpesu sīlesu sīlasāmaññagato viharati sabrahmacārīhi āvi ceva raho ca.**Furthermore, a mendicant lives according to the precepts shared with their spiritual companions, both in public and in private. Those precepts are unbroken, impeccable, spotless, and unmarred, liberating, praised by sensible people, not mistaken, and leading to immersion.*";
P_HTM[4553]="*Ayampi dhammo sāraṇīyo … pe … ekībhāvāya saṃvattati. (14.5)**This too is a warm-hearted quality.*";
P_HTM[4554]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu yāyaṃ diṭṭhi ariyā niyyānikā niyyāti takkarassa sammā dukkhakkhayāya, tathārūpāya diṭṭhiyā diṭṭhisāmaññagato viharati sabrahmacārīhi āvi ceva raho ca.**They live according to the view shared with their spiritual companions, both in public and in private. That view is noble and emancipating, and brings one who practices it to the complete ending of suffering.*";
P_HTM[4555]="*Ayampi dhammo sāraṇīyo piyakaraṇo garukaraṇo saṅgahāya avivādāya sāmaggiyā ekībhāvāya saṃvattati. (14.6)**This warm-hearted quality too makes for fondness and respect, conducing to inclusion, harmony, and unity, without quarreling.*";
P_HTM[4556]="*Cha vivādamūlāni.**Six roots of quarrels.*";
P_HTM[4557]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu kodhano hoti upanāhī.**Firstly, a mendicant is irritable and hostile.*";
P_HTM[4558]="*Yo so, āvuso, bhikkhu kodhano hoti upanāhī, so sattharipi agāravo viharati appatisso, dhammepi agāravo viharati appatisso, saṃghepi agāravo viharati appatisso, sikkhāyapi na paripūrakārī hoti.**Such a mendicant lacks respect and reverence for the Teacher, the teaching, and the Saṅgha, and they don’t fulfill the training.*";
P_HTM[4559]="*Yo so, āvuso, bhikkhu satthari agāravo viharati appatisso, dhamme agāravo viharati appatisso, saṃghe agāravo viharati appatisso, sikkhāya na paripūrakārī, so saṃghe vivādaṃ janeti. Yo hoti vivādo bahujanāhitāya bahujanāsukhāya anatthāya ahitāya dukkhāya devamanussānaṃ.**They create a dispute in the Saṅgha, which is for the hurt and unhappiness of the people, for the harm, hurt, and suffering of gods and humans.*";
P_HTM[4560]="*Evarūpañce tumhe, āvuso, vivādamūlaṃ ajjhattaṃ vā bahiddhā vā samanupasseyyātha. Tatra tumhe, āvuso, tasseva pāpakassa vivādamūlassa pahānāya vāyameyyātha.**If you see such a root of quarrels in yourselves or others, you should try to give up this bad thing.*";
P_HTM[4561]="*Evarūpañce tumhe, āvuso, vivādamūlaṃ ajjhattaṃ vā bahiddhā vā na samanupasseyyātha. Tatra tumhe, āvuso, tasseva pāpakassa vivādamūlassa āyatiṃ anavassavāya paṭipajjeyyātha.**If you don’t see it, you should practice so that it doesn’t come up in the future.*";
P_HTM[4562]="*Evametassa pāpakassa vivādamūlassa pahānaṃ hoti. Evametassa pāpakassa vivādamūlassa āyatiṃ anavassavo hoti.**That’s how to give up this bad root of quarrels, so it doesn’t come up in the future.*";
P_HTM[4563]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu makkhī hoti paḷāsī … pe …**Furthermore, a mendicant is offensive and contemptuous …*";
P_HTM[4564]="*issukī hoti maccharī … pe …**They’re jealous and stingy …*";
P_HTM[4565]="*saṭho hoti māyāvī …**They’re devious and deceitful …*";
P_HTM[4566]="*pāpiccho hoti micchādiṭṭhī …**They have wicked desires and wrong view …*";
P_HTM[4567]="*sandiṭṭhiparāmāsī hoti ādhānaggāhī duppaṭinissaggī … pe …**They’re attached to their own views, holding them tight, and refusing to let go.*";
P_HTM[4568]="*yo so, āvuso, bhikkhu sandiṭṭhiparāmāsī hoti ādhānaggāhī duppaṭinissaggī, so sattharipi agāravo viharati appatisso, dhammepi agāravo viharati appatisso, saṅghepi agāravo viharati appatisso, sikkhāyapi na paripūrakārī hoti.* **";
P_HTM[4569]="*Yo so, āvuso, bhikkhu satthari agāravo viharati appatisso, dhamme agāravo viharati appatisso, saṅghe agāravo viharati appatisso, sikkhāya na paripūrakārī, so saṅghe vivādaṃ janeti. Yo hoti vivādo bahujanāhitāya bahujanāsukhāya anatthāya ahitāya dukkhāya devamanussānaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4570]="*Evarūpañce tumhe, āvuso, vivādamūlaṃ ajjhattaṃ vā bahiddhā vā samanupasseyyātha. Tatra tumhe, āvuso, tasseva pāpakassa vivādamūlassa pahānāya vāyameyyātha.**If you see such a root of quarrels in yourselves or others, you should try to give up this bad thing.*";
P_HTM[4571]="*Evarūpañce tumhe, āvuso, vivādamūlaṃ ajjhattaṃ vā bahiddhā vā na samanupasseyyātha. Tatra tumhe, āvuso, tasseva pāpakassa vivādamūlassa āyatiṃ anavassavāya paṭipajjeyyātha.**If you don’t see it, you should practice so that it doesn’t come up in the future.*";
P_HTM[4572]="*Evametassa pāpakassa vivādamūlassa pahānaṃ hoti. Evametassa pāpakassa vivādamūlassa āyatiṃ anavassavo hoti. (15)**That’s how to give up this bad root of quarrels, so it doesn’t come up in the future.*";
P_HTM[4573]="*Cha dhātuyo—**Six elements:*";
P_HTM[4574]="*pathavīdhātu, āpodhātu, tejodhātu, vāyodhātu, ākāsadhātu, viññāṇadhātu. (16)**earth, water, fire, air, space, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[4575]="*Cha nissaraṇiyā dhātuyo.**Six elements of escape.*";
P_HTM[4576]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu evaṃ vadeyya:**Take a mendicant who says:*";
P_HTM[4577]="*‘mettā hi kho me cetovimutti bhāvitā bahulīkatā yānīkatā vatthukatā anuṭṭhitā paricitā susamāraddhā,**‘I’ve developed the heart’s release by love. I’ve cultivated it, made it my vehicle and my basis, kept it up, consolidated it, and properly implemented it.*";
P_HTM[4578]="*atha ca pana me byāpādo cittaṃ pariyādāya tiṭṭhatī’ti.**Yet somehow ill will still occupies my mind.’*";
P_HTM[4579]="*So ‘mā hevan’tissa vacanīyo, ‘māyasmā evaṃ avaca, mā bhagavantaṃ abbhācikkhi, na hi sādhu bhagavato abbhakkhānaṃ, na hi bhagavā evaṃ vadeyya.**They should be told, ‘Not so, venerable! Don’t say that. Don’t misrepresent the Buddha, for misrepresentation of the Buddha is not good. And the Buddha would not say that.*";
P_HTM[4580]="*Aṭṭhānametaṃ, āvuso, anavakāso, yaṃ mettāya cetovimuttiyā bhāvitāya bahulīkatāya yānīkatāya vatthukatāya anuṭṭhitāya paricitāya susamāraddhāya.**It’s impossible, reverend, it cannot happen that the heart’s release by love has been developed and properly implemented,*";
P_HTM[4581]="*Atha ca panassa byāpādo cittaṃ pariyādāya ṭhassati, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**yet somehow ill will still occupies the mind.*";
P_HTM[4582]="*Nissaraṇaṃ hetaṃ, āvuso, byāpādassa, yadidaṃ mettā cetovimuttī’ti. (17.1)**For it is the heart’s release by love that is the escape from ill will.’*";
P_HTM[4583]="*Idha panāvuso, bhikkhu evaṃ vadeyya:**Take another mendicant who says:*";
P_HTM[4584]="*‘karuṇā hi kho me cetovimutti bhāvitā bahulīkatā yānīkatā vatthukatā anuṭṭhitā paricitā susamāraddhā.**‘I’ve developed the heart’s release by compassion. I’ve cultivated it, made it my vehicle and my basis, kept it up, consolidated it, and properly implemented it.*";
P_HTM[4585]="*Atha ca pana me vihesā cittaṃ pariyādāya tiṭṭhatī’ti,**Yet somehow the thought of harming still occupies my mind.’*";
P_HTM[4586]="*so ‘mā hevan’tissa vacanīyo ‘māyasmā evaṃ avaca, mā bhagavantaṃ abbhācikkhi, na hi sādhu bhagavato abbhakkhānaṃ, na hi bhagavā evaṃ vadeyya.**They should be told, ‘Not so, venerable! …*";
P_HTM[4587]="*Aṭṭhānametaṃ, āvuso, anavakāso, yaṃ karuṇāya cetovimuttiyā bhāvitāya bahulīkatāya yānīkatāya vatthukatāya anuṭṭhitāya paricitāya susamāraddhāya,* **";
P_HTM[4588]="*atha ca panassa vihesā cittaṃ pariyādāya ṭhassati, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.* **";
P_HTM[4589]="*Nissaraṇaṃ hetaṃ, āvuso, vihesāya, yadidaṃ karuṇā cetovimuttī’ti. (17.2)**For it is the heart’s release by compassion that is the escape from thoughts of harming.’*";
P_HTM[4590]="*Idha panāvuso, bhikkhu evaṃ vadeyya:**Take another mendicant who says:*";
P_HTM[4591]="*‘muditā hi kho me cetovimutti bhāvitā bahulīkatā yānīkatā vatthukatā anuṭṭhitā paricitā susamāraddhā.**‘I’ve developed the heart’s release by rejoicing. I’ve cultivated it, made it my vehicle and my basis, kept it up, consolidated it, and properly implemented it.*";
P_HTM[4592]="*Atha ca pana me arati cittaṃ pariyādāya tiṭṭhatī’ti,**Yet somehow negativity still occupies my mind.’*";
P_HTM[4593]="*so ‘mā hevan’tissa vacanīyo ‘māyasmā evaṃ avaca, mā bhagavantaṃ abbhācikkhi, na hi sādhu bhagavato abbhakkhānaṃ, na hi bhagavā evaṃ vadeyya.**They should be told, ‘Not so, venerable! …*";
P_HTM[4594]="*Aṭṭhānametaṃ, āvuso, anavakāso, yaṃ muditāya cetovimuttiyā bhāvitāya bahulīkatāya yānīkatāya vatthukatāya anuṭṭhitāya paricitāya susamāraddhāya,* **";
P_HTM[4595]="*atha ca panassa arati cittaṃ pariyādāya ṭhassati, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.* **";
P_HTM[4596]="*Nissaraṇaṃ hetaṃ, āvuso, aratiyā, yadidaṃ muditā cetovimuttī’ti. (17.3)**For it is the heart’s release by rejoicing that is the escape from negativity.’*";
P_HTM[4597]="*Idha panāvuso, bhikkhu evaṃ vadeyya:**Take another mendicant who says:*";
P_HTM[4598]="*‘upekkhā hi kho me cetovimutti bhāvitā bahulīkatā yānīkatā vatthukatā anuṭṭhitā paricitā susamāraddhā.**‘I’ve developed the heart’s release by equanimity. I’ve cultivated it, made it my vehicle and my basis, kept it up, consolidated it, and properly implemented it.*";
P_HTM[4599]="*Atha ca pana me rāgo cittaṃ pariyādāya tiṭṭhatī’ti.**Yet somehow desire still occupies my mind.’*";
P_HTM[4600]="*So ‘mā hevan’tissa vacanīyo ‘māyasmā evaṃ avaca, mā bhagavantaṃ abbhācikkhi, na hi sādhu bhagavato abbhakkhānaṃ, na hi bhagavā evaṃ vadeyya.**They should be told, ‘Not so, venerable! …*";
P_HTM[4601]="*Aṭṭhānametaṃ, āvuso, anavakāso, yaṃ upekkhāya cetovimuttiyā bhāvitāya bahulīkatāya yānīkatāya vatthukatāya anuṭṭhitāya paricitāya susamāraddhāya,* **";
P_HTM[4602]="*atha ca panassa rāgo cittaṃ pariyādāya ṭhassati netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.* **";
P_HTM[4603]="*Nissaraṇaṃ hetaṃ, āvuso, rāgassa, yadidaṃ upekkhā cetovimuttī’ti. (17.4)**For it is the heart’s release by equanimity that is the escape from desire.’*";
P_HTM[4604]="*Idha panāvuso, bhikkhu evaṃ vadeyya:**Take another mendicant who says:*";
P_HTM[4605]="*‘animittā hi kho me cetovimutti bhāvitā bahulīkatā yānīkatā vatthukatā anuṭṭhitā paricitā susamāraddhā.**‘I’ve developed the signless release of the heart. I’ve cultivated it, made it my vehicle and my basis, kept it up, consolidated it, and properly implemented it.*";
P_HTM[4606]="*Atha ca pana me nimittānusāri viññāṇaṃ hotī’ti.**Yet somehow my consciousness still follows after signs.’*";
P_HTM[4607]="*So ‘mā hevan’tissa vacanīyo ‘māyasmā evaṃ avaca, mā bhagavantaṃ abbhācikkhi, na hi sādhu bhagavato abbhakkhānaṃ, na hi bhagavā evaṃ vadeyya.**They should be told, ‘Not so, venerable! …*";
P_HTM[4608]="*Aṭṭhānametaṃ, āvuso, anavakāso, yaṃ animittāya cetovimuttiyā bhāvitāya bahulīkatāya yānīkatāya vatthukatāya anuṭṭhitāya paricitāya susamāraddhāya,* **";
P_HTM[4609]="*atha ca panassa nimittānusāri viññāṇaṃ bhavissati, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.* **";
P_HTM[4610]="*Nissaraṇaṃ hetaṃ, āvuso, sabbanimittānaṃ, yadidaṃ animittā cetovimuttī’ti. (17.5)**For it is the signless release of the heart that is the escape from all signs.’*";
P_HTM[4611]="*Idha panāvuso, bhikkhu evaṃ vadeyya:**Take another mendicant who says:*";
P_HTM[4612]="*‘asmīti kho me vigataṃ, ayamahamasmīti na samanupassāmi,**‘I’m rid of the conceit “I am”. And I don’t regard anything as “I am this”.*";
P_HTM[4613]="*atha ca pana me vicikicchākathaṃkathāsallaṃ cittaṃ pariyādāya tiṭṭhatī’ti.**Yet somehow the dart of doubt and indecision still occupies my mind.’*";
P_HTM[4614]="*So ‘mā hevan’tissa vacanīyo ‘māyasmā evaṃ avaca, mā bhagavantaṃ abbhācikkhi, na hi sādhu bhagavato abbhakkhānaṃ, na hi bhagavā evaṃ vadeyya.**They should be told, ‘Not so, venerable! Don’t say that. Don’t misrepresent the Buddha, for misrepresentation of the Buddha is not good. And the Buddha would not say that.*";
P_HTM[4615]="*Aṭṭhānametaṃ, āvuso, anavakāso, yaṃ asmīti vigate ayamahamasmīti asamanupassato,**It’s impossible, reverend, it cannot happen that the conceit “I am” has been done away with, and nothing is regarded as “I am this”,*";
P_HTM[4616]="*atha ca panassa vicikicchākathaṃkathāsallaṃ cittaṃ pariyādāya ṭhassati, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**yet somehow the dart of doubt and indecision still occupy the mind.*";
P_HTM[4617]="*Nissaraṇaṃ hetaṃ, āvuso, vicikicchākathaṃkathāsallassa, yadidaṃ asmimānasamugghāto’ti. (17.6)**For it is the uprooting of the conceit “I am” that is the escape from the dart of doubt and indecision.’*";
P_HTM[4618]="*Cha anuttariyāni—**Six unsurpassable things:*";
P_HTM[4619]="*dassanānuttariyaṃ, savanānuttariyaṃ, lābhānuttariyaṃ, sikkhānuttariyaṃ, pāricariyānuttariyaṃ, anussatānuttariyaṃ. (18)**the unsurpassable seeing, listening, acquisition, training, service, and recollection.*";
P_HTM[4620]="*Cha anussatiṭṭhānāni—**Six recollections:*";
P_HTM[4621]="*buddhānussati, dhammānussati, saṃghānussati, sīlānussati, cāgānussati, devatānussati. (19)**the recollection of the Buddha, the teaching, the Saṅgha, ethics, generosity, and the deities.*";
P_HTM[4622]="*Cha satatavihārā.**Six consistent responses.*";
P_HTM[4623]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu cakkhunā rūpaṃ disvā neva sumano hoti na dummano, upekkhako viharati sato sampajāno.**A mendicant, seeing a sight with their eyes, is neither happy nor sad. They remain equanimous, mindful and aware.*";
P_HTM[4624]="*Sotena saddaṃ sutvā … pe …**Hearing a sound with their ears … Smelling an odor with their nose … Tasting a flavor with their tongue … Feeling a touch with their body …*";
P_HTM[4625]="*manasā dhammaṃ viññāya neva sumano hoti na dummano, upekkhako viharati sato sampajāno. (20)**Knowing a thought with their mind, they’re neither happy nor sad. They remain equanimous, mindful and aware.*";
P_HTM[4626]="*Chaḷābhijātiyo.**Six classes of rebirth.*";
P_HTM[4627]="*Idhāvuso, ekacco kaṇhābhijātiko samāno kaṇhaṃ dhammaṃ abhijāyati.**Someone born into a dark class gives rise to a dark result.*";
P_HTM[4628]="*Idha panāvuso, ekacco kaṇhābhijātiko samāno sukkaṃ dhammaṃ abhijāyati.**Someone born into a dark class gives rise to a bright result.*";
P_HTM[4629]="*Idha panāvuso, ekacco kaṇhābhijātiko samāno akaṇhaṃ asukkaṃ nibbānaṃ abhijāyati.**Someone born into a dark class gives rise to extinguishment, which is neither dark nor bright.*";
P_HTM[4630]="*Idha panāvuso, ekacco sukkābhijātiko samāno sukkaṃ dhammaṃ abhijāyati.**Someone born into a bright class gives rise to a bright result.*";
P_HTM[4631]="*Idha panāvuso, ekacco sukkābhijātiko samāno kaṇhaṃ dhammaṃ abhijāyati.**Someone born into a bright class gives rise to a dark result.*";
P_HTM[4632]="*Idha panāvuso, ekacco sukkābhijātiko samāno akaṇhaṃ asukkaṃ nibbānaṃ abhijāyati. (21)**Someone born into a bright class gives rise to extinguishment, which is neither dark nor bright.*";
P_HTM[4633]="*Cha nibbedhabhāgiyā saññā—**Six perceptions that help penetration:*";
P_HTM[4634]="*aniccasaññā anicce, dukkhasaññā dukkhe, anattasaññā, pahānasaññā, virāgasaññā, nirodhasaññā. (22)**the perception of impermanence, the perception of suffering in impermanence, the perception of not-self in suffering, the perception of giving up, the perception of fading away, and the perception of cessation.*";
P_HTM[4635]="*Ime kho, āvuso, tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena cha dhammā sammadakkhātā;**These are the teachings grouped by six that have been rightly explained by the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[4636]="*tattha sabbeheva saṅgāyitabbaṃ … pe … atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānaṃ.**You should all recite these in concert.*";
P_HTM[4637]="*7. Sattaka**7. Sevens*";
P_HTM[4638]="*Atthi kho, āvuso, tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena satta dhammā sammadakkhātā;**There are teachings grouped by seven that have been rightly explained by the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[4639]="*tattha sabbeheva saṅgāyitabbaṃ … pe … atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānaṃ.**You should all recite these in concert.*";
P_HTM[4640]="*Katame satta?**What are the teachings grouped by seven?*";
P_HTM[4641]="*Satta ariyadhanāni—**Seven kinds of noble wealth:*";
P_HTM[4642]="*saddhādhanaṃ, sīladhanaṃ, hiridhanaṃ, ottappadhanaṃ, sutadhanaṃ, cāgadhanaṃ, paññādhanaṃ. (1)**the wealth of faith, ethical conduct, conscience, prudence, learning, generosity, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[4643]="*Satta bojjhaṅgā—**Seven awakening factors:*";
P_HTM[4644]="*satisambojjhaṅgo, dhammavicayasambojjhaṅgo, vīriyasambojjhaṅgo, pītisambojjhaṅgo, passaddhisambojjhaṅgo, samādhisambojjhaṅgo, upekkhāsambojjhaṅgo. (2)**mindfulness, investigation of principles, energy, rapture, tranquility, immersion, and equanimity.*";
P_HTM[4645]="*Satta samādhiparikkhārā—**Seven prerequisites for immersion:*";
P_HTM[4646]="*sammādiṭṭhi, sammāsaṅkappo, sammāvācā, sammākammanto, sammāājīvo, sammāvāyāmo, sammāsati. (3)**right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, and right mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[4647]="*Satta asaddhammā—**Seven bad qualities:*";
P_HTM[4648]="*idhāvuso, bhikkhu assaddho hoti, ahiriko hoti, anottappī hoti, appassuto hoti, kusīto hoti, muṭṭhassati hoti, duppañño hoti. (4)**a mendicant is faithless, shameless, imprudent, uneducated, lazy, unmindful, and witless.*";
P_HTM[4649]="*Satta saddhammā—**Seven good qualities:*";
P_HTM[4650]="*idhāvuso, bhikkhu saddho hoti, hirimā hoti, ottappī hoti, bahussuto hoti, āraddhavīriyo hoti, upaṭṭhitassati hoti, paññavā hoti. (5)**a mendicant is faithful, conscientious, prudent, learned, energetic, mindful, and wise.*";
P_HTM[4651]="*Satta sappurisadhammā—**Seven aspects of the teachings of the good persons:*";
P_HTM[4652]="*idhāvuso, bhikkhu dhammaññū ca hoti atthaññū ca attaññū ca mattaññū ca kālaññū ca parisaññū ca puggalaññū ca. (6)**a mendicant knows the teachings, knows the meaning, knows themselves, knows moderation, knows the right time, knows assemblies, and knows people.*";
P_HTM[4653]="*Satta niddasavatthūni.**Seven qualifications for graduation.*";
P_HTM[4654]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu sikkhāsamādāne tibbacchando hoti, āyatiñca sikkhāsamādāne avigatapemo.**A mendicant has a keen enthusiasm to undertake the training …*";
P_HTM[4655]="*Dhammanisantiyā tibbacchando hoti, āyatiñca dhammanisantiyā avigatapemo.**to examine the teachings …*";
P_HTM[4656]="*Icchāvinaye tibbacchando hoti, āyatiñca icchāvinaye avigatapemo.**to get rid of desires …*";
P_HTM[4657]="*Paṭisallāne tibbacchando hoti, āyatiñca paṭisallāne avigatapemo.**for retreat …*";
P_HTM[4658]="*Vīriyārambhe tibbacchando hoti, āyatiñca vīriyārambhe avigatapemo.**to rouse up energy …*";
P_HTM[4659]="*Satinepakke tibbacchando hoti, āyatiñca satinepakke avigatapemo.**for mindfulness and alertness …*";
P_HTM[4660]="*Diṭṭhipaṭivedhe tibbacchando hoti, āyatiñca diṭṭhipaṭivedhe avigatapemo. (7)**to penetrate theoretically. And they don’t lose these desires in the future.*";
P_HTM[4661]="*Satta saññā—**Seven perceptions:*";
P_HTM[4662]="*aniccasaññā, anattasaññā, asubhasaññā, ādīnavasaññā, pahānasaññā, virāgasaññā, nirodhasaññā. (8)**the perception of impermanence, the perception of not-self, the perception of ugliness, the perception of drawbacks, the perception of giving up, the perception of fading away, and the perception of cessation.*";
P_HTM[4663]="*Satta balāni—**Seven powers:*";
P_HTM[4664]="*saddhābalaṃ, vīriyabalaṃ, hiribalaṃ, ottappabalaṃ, satibalaṃ, samādhibalaṃ, paññābalaṃ. (9)**faith, energy, conscience, prudence, mindfulness, immersion, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[4665]="*Satta viññāṇaṭṭhitiyo.**Seven planes of consciousness.*";
P_HTM[4666]="*Santāvuso, sattā nānattakāyā nānattasaññino, seyyathāpi manussā ekacce ca devā ekacce ca vinipātikā.**There are sentient beings that are diverse in body and diverse in perception, such as human beings, some gods, and some beings in the underworld.*";
P_HTM[4667]="*Ayaṃ paṭhamā viññāṇaṭṭhiti.**This is the first plane of consciousness.*";
P_HTM[4668]="*Santāvuso, sattā nānattakāyā ekattasaññino seyyathāpi devā brahmakāyikā paṭhamābhinibbattā.**There are sentient beings that are diverse in body and unified in perception, such as the gods reborn in Brahmā’s Host through the first absorption.*";
P_HTM[4669]="*Ayaṃ dutiyā viññāṇaṭṭhiti.**This is the second plane of consciousness.*";
P_HTM[4670]="*Santāvuso, sattā ekattakāyā nānattasaññino seyyathāpi devā ābhassarā.**There are sentient beings that are unified in body and diverse in perception, such as the gods of streaming radiance.*";
P_HTM[4671]="*Ayaṃ tatiyā viññāṇaṭṭhiti.**This is the third plane of consciousness.*";
P_HTM[4672]="*Santāvuso, sattā ekattakāyā ekattasaññino seyyathāpi devā subhakiṇhā.**There are sentient beings that are unified in body and unified in perception, such as the gods replete with glory.*";
P_HTM[4673]="*Ayaṃ catutthī viññāṇaṭṭhiti.**This is the fourth plane of consciousness.*";
P_HTM[4674]="*Santāvuso, sattā sabbaso rūpasaññānaṃ samatikkamā paṭighasaññānaṃ atthaṅgamā nānattasaññānaṃ amanasikārā ‘ananto ākāso’ti ākāsānañcāyatanūpagā.**There are sentient beings that have gone totally beyond perceptions of form. With the ending of perceptions of impingement, not focusing on perceptions of diversity, aware that ‘space is infinite’, they have been reborn in the dimension of infinite space.*";
P_HTM[4675]="*Ayaṃ pañcamī viññāṇaṭṭhiti.**This is the fifth plane of consciousness.*";
P_HTM[4676]="*Santāvuso, sattā sabbaso ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma ‘anantaṃ viññāṇan’ti viññāṇañcāyatanūpagā.**There are sentient beings that have gone totally beyond the dimension of infinite space. Aware that ‘consciousness is infinite’, they have been reborn in the dimension of infinite consciousness.*";
P_HTM[4677]="*Ayaṃ chaṭṭhī viññāṇaṭṭhiti.**This is the sixth plane of consciousness.*";
P_HTM[4678]="*Santāvuso, sattā sabbaso viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma ‘natthi kiñcī’ti ākiñcaññāyatanūpagā.**There are sentient beings that have gone totally beyond the dimension of infinite consciousness. Aware that ‘there is nothing at all’, they have been reborn in the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[4679]="*Ayaṃ sattamī viññāṇaṭṭhiti. (10)**This is the seventh plane of consciousness.*";
P_HTM[4680]="*Satta puggalā dakkhiṇeyyā—**Seven persons worthy of a religious donation:*";
P_HTM[4681]="*ubhatobhāgavimutto, paññāvimutto, kāyasakkhi, diṭṭhippatto, saddhāvimutto, dhammānusārī, saddhānusārī. (11)**one freed both ways, one freed by wisdom, a personal witness, one attained to view, one freed by faith, a follower of the teachings, and a follower by faith.*";
P_HTM[4682]="*Satta anusayā—**Seven underlying tendencies:*";
P_HTM[4683]="*kāmarāgānusayo, paṭighānusayo, diṭṭhānusayo, vicikicchānusayo, mānānusayo, bhavarāgānusayo, avijjānusayo. (12)**sensual desire, repulsion, views, doubt, conceit, desire to be reborn, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[4684]="*Satta saṃyojanāni—**Seven fetters:*";
P_HTM[4685]="*anunayasaṃyojanaṃ, paṭighasaṃyojanaṃ, diṭṭhisaṃyojanaṃ, vicikicchāsaṃyojanaṃ, mānasaṃyojanaṃ, bhavarāgasaṃyojanaṃ, avijjāsaṃyojanaṃ. (13)**attraction, repulsion, views, doubt, conceit, desire to be reborn, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[4686]="*Satta adhikaraṇasamathā—**Seven principles for the settlement of any disciplinary issues that might arise.*";
P_HTM[4687]="*uppannuppannānaṃ adhikaraṇānaṃ samathāya vūpasamāya sammukhāvinayo dātabbo, sativinayo dātabbo, amūḷhavinayo dātabbo, paṭiññāya kāretabbaṃ, yebhuyyasikā, tassapāpiyasikā, tiṇavatthārako. (14)**Removal in the presence of those concerned is applicable. Removal by accurate recollection is applicable. Removal due to recovery from madness is applicable. The acknowledgement of the offense is applicable. The decision of a majority is applicable. A verdict of aggravated misconduct is applicable. Covering over with grass is applicable.*";
P_HTM[4688]="*Ime kho, āvuso, tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena satta dhammā sammadakkhātā;**These are the teachings grouped by seven that have been rightly explained by the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[4689]="*tattha sabbeheva saṅgāyitabbaṃ … pe … atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānaṃ.**You should all recite these in concert.*";
P_HTM[4690]="*Dutiyabhāṇavāro niṭṭhito.**The second recitation section is finished.*";
P_HTM[4691]="*8. Aṭṭhaka**8. Eights*";
P_HTM[4692]="*Atthi kho, āvuso, tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena aṭṭha dhammā sammadakkhātā;**There are teachings grouped by eight that have been rightly explained by the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[4693]="*tattha sabbeheva saṅgāyitabbaṃ … pe … atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānaṃ.**You should all recite these in concert.*";
P_HTM[4694]="*Katame aṭṭha?**What are the teachings grouped by eight?*";
P_HTM[4695]="*Aṭṭha micchattā—**Eight wrong ways:*";
P_HTM[4696]="*micchādiṭṭhi, micchāsaṅkappo, micchāvācā, micchākammanto, micchāājīvo, micchāvāyāmo micchāsati, micchāsamādhi. (1)**wrong view, wrong thought, wrong speech, wrong action, wrong livelihood, wrong effort, wrong mindfulness, and wrong immersion.*";
P_HTM[4697]="*Aṭṭha sammattā—**Eight right ways:*";
P_HTM[4698]="*sammādiṭṭhi, sammāsaṅkappo, sammāvācā, sammākammanto, sammāājīvo, sammāvāyāmo, sammāsati, sammāsamādhi. (2)**right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion.*";
P_HTM[4699]="*Aṭṭha puggalā dakkhiṇeyyā—**Eight persons worthy of a religious donation.*";
P_HTM[4700]="*sotāpanno, sotāpattiphalasacchikiriyāya paṭipanno; sakadāgāmī, sakadāgāmiphalasacchikiriyāya paṭipanno; anāgāmī, anāgāmiphalasacchikiriyāya paṭipanno; arahā, arahattaphalasacchikiriyāya paṭipanno. (3)**The stream-enterer and the one practicing to realize the fruit of stream-entry. The once-returner and the one practicing to realize the fruit of once-return. The non-returner and the one practicing to realize the fruit of non-return. The perfected one, and the one practicing for perfection.*";
P_HTM[4701]="*Aṭṭha kusītavatthūni.**Eight grounds for laziness.*";
P_HTM[4702]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhunā kammaṃ kātabbaṃ hoti.**Firstly, a mendicant has some work to do.*";
P_HTM[4703]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[4704]="*‘kammaṃ kho me kātabbaṃ bhavissati, kammaṃ kho pana me karontassa kāyo kilamissati, handāhaṃ nipajjāmī’ti.**‘I have some work to do. But while doing it my body will get tired. I’d better have a lie down.’*";
P_HTM[4705]="*So nipajjati na vīriyaṃ ārabhati appattassa pattiyā anadhigatassa adhigamāya asacchikatassa sacchikiriyāya.**They lie down, and don’t rouse energy for attaining the unattained, achieving the unachieved, and realizing the unrealized.*";
P_HTM[4706]="*Idaṃ paṭhamaṃ kusītavatthu.**This is the first ground for laziness.*";
P_HTM[4707]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhunā kammaṃ kataṃ hoti.**Furthermore, a mendicant has done some work.*";
P_HTM[4708]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[4709]="*‘ahaṃ kho kammaṃ akāsiṃ, kammaṃ kho pana me karontassa kāyo kilanto, handāhaṃ nipajjāmī’ti.**‘I’ve done some work. But while working my body got tired. I’d better have a lie down.’*";
P_HTM[4710]="*So nipajjati na vīriyaṃ ārabhati … pe …**They lie down, and don’t rouse energy...*";
P_HTM[4711]="*idaṃ dutiyaṃ kusītavatthu.**This is the second ground for laziness.*";
P_HTM[4712]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhunā maggo gantabbo hoti.**Furthermore, a mendicant has to go on a journey.*";
P_HTM[4713]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[4714]="*‘maggo kho me gantabbo bhavissati, maggaṃ kho pana me gacchantassa kāyo kilamissati, handāhaṃ nipajjāmī’ti.**‘I have to go on a journey. But while walking my body will get tired. I’d better have a lie down.’*";
P_HTM[4715]="*So nipajjati na vīriyaṃ ārabhati …**They lie down, and don’t rouse energy...*";
P_HTM[4716]="*idaṃ tatiyaṃ kusītavatthu.**This is the third ground for laziness.*";
P_HTM[4717]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhunā maggo gato hoti.**Furthermore, a mendicant has gone on a journey.*";
P_HTM[4718]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[4719]="*‘ahaṃ kho maggaṃ agamāsiṃ, maggaṃ kho pana me gacchantassa kāyo kilanto, handāhaṃ nipajjāmī’ti.**‘I’ve gone on a journey. But while walking my body got tired. I’d better have a lie down.’*";
P_HTM[4720]="*So nipajjati na vīriyaṃ ārabhati …**They lie down, and don’t rouse energy...*";
P_HTM[4721]="*idaṃ catutthaṃ kusītavatthu.**This is the fourth ground for laziness.*";
P_HTM[4722]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu gāmaṃ vā nigamaṃ vā piṇḍāya caranto na labhati lūkhassa vā paṇītassa vā bhojanassa yāvadatthaṃ pāripūriṃ.**Furthermore, a mendicant has wandered for alms, but they didn’t get to fill up on as much food as they like, coarse or fine.*";
P_HTM[4723]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[4724]="*‘ahaṃ kho gāmaṃ vā nigamaṃ vā piṇḍāya caranto nālatthaṃ lūkhassa vā paṇītassa vā bhojanassa yāvadatthaṃ pāripūriṃ, tassa me kāyo kilanto akammañño, handāhaṃ nipajjāmī’ti.**‘I’ve wandered for alms, but I didn’t get to fill up on as much food as I like, coarse or fine. My body is tired and unfit for work. I’d better have a lie down.’*";
P_HTM[4725]="*So nipajjati na vīriyaṃ ārabhati …**They lie down, and don’t rouse energy...*";
P_HTM[4726]="*idaṃ pañcamaṃ kusītavatthu.**This is the fifth ground for laziness.*";
P_HTM[4727]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu gāmaṃ vā nigamaṃ vā piṇḍāya caranto labhati lūkhassa vā paṇītassa vā bhojanassa yāvadatthaṃ pāripūriṃ.**Furthermore, a mendicant has wandered for alms, and they got to fill up on as much food as they like, coarse or fine.*";
P_HTM[4728]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[4729]="*‘ahaṃ kho gāmaṃ vā nigamaṃ vā piṇḍāya caranto alatthaṃ lūkhassa vā paṇītassa vā bhojanassa yāvadatthaṃ pāripūriṃ, tassa me kāyo garuko akammañño, māsācitaṃ maññe, handāhaṃ nipajjāmī’ti.**‘I’ve wandered for alms, and I got to fill up on as much food as I like, coarse or fine. My body is heavy and unfit for work, like I’ve just eaten a load of beans. I’d better have a lie down.’*";
P_HTM[4730]="*So nipajjati na vīriyaṃ ārabhati …**They lie down, and don’t rouse energy...*";
P_HTM[4731]="*idaṃ chaṭṭhaṃ kusītavatthu.**This is the sixth ground for laziness.*";
P_HTM[4732]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhuno uppanno hoti appamattako ābādho.**Furthermore, a mendicant feels a little sick.*";
P_HTM[4733]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[4734]="*‘uppanno kho me ayaṃ appamattako ābādho;**‘I feel a little sick. Lying down would be good for me. I’d better have a lie down.’*";
P_HTM[4735]="*atthi kappo nipajjituṃ, handāhaṃ nipajjāmī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[4736]="*So nipajjati na vīriyaṃ ārabhati …**They lie down, and don’t rouse energy...*";
P_HTM[4737]="*idaṃ sattamaṃ kusītavatthu.**This is the seventh ground for laziness.*";
P_HTM[4738]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu gilānā vuṭṭhito hoti aciravuṭṭhito gelaññā.**Furthermore, a mendicant has recently recovered from illness.*";
P_HTM[4739]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[4740]="*‘ahaṃ kho gilānā vuṭṭhito aciravuṭṭhito gelaññā, tassa me kāyo dubbalo akammañño, handāhaṃ nipajjāmī’ti.**‘I’ve recently recovered from illness. My body is weak and unfit for work. I’d better have a lie down.’*";
P_HTM[4741]="*So nipajjati na vīriyaṃ ārabhati appattassa pattiyā anadhigatassa adhigamāya asacchikatassa sacchikiriyāya.**They lie down, and don’t rouse energy for attaining the unattained, achieving the unachieved, and realizing the unrealized.*";
P_HTM[4742]="*Idaṃ aṭṭhamaṃ kusītavatthu. (4)**This is the eighth ground for laziness.*";
P_HTM[4743]="*Aṭṭha ārambhavatthūni.**Eight grounds for arousing energy.*";
P_HTM[4744]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhunā kammaṃ kātabbaṃ hoti.**Firstly, a mendicant has some work to do.*";
P_HTM[4745]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[4746]="*‘kammaṃ kho me kātabbaṃ bhavissati, kammaṃ kho pana me karontena na sukaraṃ buddhānaṃ sāsanaṃ manasi kātuṃ, handāhaṃ vīriyaṃ ārabhāmi appattassa pattiyā anadhigatassa adhigamāya, asacchikatassa sacchikiriyāyā’ti.**‘I have some work to do. While working it’s not easy to focus on the instructions of the Buddhas. I’d better preemptively rouse up energy for attaining the unattained, achieving the unachieved, and realizing the unrealized.’*";
P_HTM[4747]="*So vīriyaṃ ārabhati appattassa pattiyā, anadhigatassa adhigamāya asacchikatassa sacchikiriyāya.**They rouse energy for attaining the unattained, achieving the unachieved, and realizing the unrealized.*";
P_HTM[4748]="*Idaṃ paṭhamaṃ ārambhavatthu.**This is the first ground for arousing energy.*";
P_HTM[4749]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhunā kammaṃ kataṃ hoti.**Furthermore, a mendicant has done some work.*";
P_HTM[4750]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[4751]="*‘ahaṃ kho kammaṃ akāsiṃ, kammaṃ kho panāhaṃ karonto nāsakkhiṃ buddhānaṃ sāsanaṃ manasi kātuṃ, handāhaṃ vīriyaṃ ārabhāmi … pe …**‘I’ve done some work. While I was working I wasn’t able to focus on the instructions of the Buddhas. I’d better preemptively rouse up energy.’*";
P_HTM[4752]="*so vīriyaṃ ārabhati …**They rouse up energy...*";
P_HTM[4753]="*idaṃ dutiyaṃ ārambhavatthu.**This is the second ground for arousing energy.*";
P_HTM[4754]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhunā maggo gantabbo hoti.**Furthermore, a mendicant has to go on a journey.*";
P_HTM[4755]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[4756]="*‘maggo kho me gantabbo bhavissati, maggaṃ kho pana me gacchantena na sukaraṃ buddhānaṃ sāsanaṃ manasi kātuṃ.**‘I have to go on a journey. While walking it’s not easy to focus on the instructions of the Buddhas. I’d better preemptively rouse up energy.’*";
P_HTM[4757]="*Handāhaṃ vīriyaṃ ārabhāmi … pe …* **";
P_HTM[4758]="*so vīriyaṃ ārabhati …**They rouse up energy...*";
P_HTM[4759]="*idaṃ tatiyaṃ ārambhavatthu.**This is the third ground for arousing energy.*";
P_HTM[4760]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhunā maggo gato hoti.**Furthermore, a mendicant has gone on a journey.*";
P_HTM[4761]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[4762]="*‘ahaṃ kho maggaṃ agamāsiṃ, maggaṃ kho panāhaṃ gacchanto nāsakkhiṃ buddhānaṃ sāsanaṃ manasi kātuṃ, handāhaṃ vīriyaṃ ārabhāmi … pe …**‘I’ve gone on a journey. While I was walking I wasn’t able to focus on the instructions of the Buddhas. I’d better preemptively rouse up energy.’*";
P_HTM[4763]="*so vīriyaṃ ārabhati …**They rouse up energy...*";
P_HTM[4764]="*idaṃ catutthaṃ ārambhavatthu.**This is the fourth ground for arousing energy.*";
P_HTM[4765]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu gāmaṃ vā nigamaṃ vā piṇḍāya caranto na labhati lūkhassa vā paṇītassa vā bhojanassa yāvadatthaṃ pāripūriṃ.**Furthermore, a mendicant has wandered for alms, but they didn’t get to fill up on as much food as they like, coarse or fine.*";
P_HTM[4766]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[4767]="*‘ahaṃ kho gāmaṃ vā nigamaṃ vā piṇḍāya caranto nālatthaṃ lūkhassa vā paṇītassa vā bhojanassa yāvadatthaṃ pāripūriṃ, tassa me kāyo lahuko kammañño, handāhaṃ vīriyaṃ ārabhāmi … pe …**‘I’ve wandered for alms, but I didn’t get to fill up on as much food as I like, coarse or fine. My body is light and fit for work. I’d better preemptively rouse up energy.’*";
P_HTM[4768]="*so vīriyaṃ ārabhati …**They rouse up energy...*";
P_HTM[4769]="*idaṃ pañcamaṃ ārambhavatthu.**This is the fifth ground for arousing energy.*";
P_HTM[4770]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu gāmaṃ vā nigamaṃ vā piṇḍāya caranto labhati lūkhassa vā paṇītassa vā bhojanassa yāvadatthaṃ pāripūriṃ.**Furthermore, a mendicant has wandered for alms, and they got to fill up on as much food as they like, coarse or fine.*";
P_HTM[4771]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[4772]="*‘ahaṃ kho gāmaṃ vā nigamaṃ vā piṇḍāya caranto alatthaṃ lūkhassa vā paṇītassa vā bhojanassa yāvadatthaṃ pāripūriṃ, tassa me kāyo balavā kammañño, handāhaṃ vīriyaṃ ārabhāmi … pe …**‘I’ve wandered for alms, and I got to fill up on as much food as I like, coarse or fine. My body is strong and fit for work. I’d better preemptively rouse up energy.’*";
P_HTM[4773]="*so vīriyaṃ ārabhati …**They rouse up energy...*";
P_HTM[4774]="*idaṃ chaṭṭhaṃ ārambhavatthu.**This is the sixth ground for arousing energy.*";
P_HTM[4775]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhuno uppanno hoti appamattako ābādho.**Furthermore, a mendicant feels a little sick.*";
P_HTM[4776]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[4777]="*‘uppanno kho me ayaṃ appamattako ābādho, ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ vijjati yaṃ me ābādho pavaḍḍheyya, handāhaṃ vīriyaṃ ārabhāmi … pe …**‘I feel a little sick. It’s possible this illness will worsen. I’d better preemptively rouse up energy.’*";
P_HTM[4778]="*so vīriyaṃ ārabhati …**They rouse up energy...*";
P_HTM[4779]="*idaṃ sattamaṃ ārambhavatthu.**This is the seventh ground for arousing energy.*";
P_HTM[4780]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu gilānā vuṭṭhito hoti aciravuṭṭhito gelaññā.**Furthermore, a mendicant has recently recovered from illness.*";
P_HTM[4781]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[4782]="*‘ahaṃ kho gilānā vuṭṭhito aciravuṭṭhito gelaññā, ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ vijjati yaṃ me ābādho paccudāvatteyya, handāhaṃ vīriyaṃ ārabhāmi appattassa pattiyā anadhigatassa adhigamāya asacchikatassa sacchikiriyāyā’ti.**‘I’ve recently recovered from illness. It’s possible the illness will come back. I’d better preemptively rouse up energy for attaining the unattained, achieving the unachieved, and realizing the unrealized.’*";
P_HTM[4783]="*So vīriyaṃ ārabhati appattassa pattiyā anadhigatassa adhigamāya asacchikatassa sacchikiriyāya.**They rouse energy for attaining the unattained, achieving the unachieved, and realizing the unrealized.*";
P_HTM[4784]="*Idaṃ aṭṭhamaṃ ārambhavatthu. (5)**This is the eighth ground for arousing energy.*";
P_HTM[4785]="*Aṭṭha dānavatthūni.**Eight reasons to give.*";
P_HTM[4786]="*Āsajja dānaṃ deti, bhayā dānaṃ deti, ‘adāsi me’ti dānaṃ deti, ‘dassati me’ti dānaṃ deti, ‘sāhu dānan’ti dānaṃ deti, ‘ahaṃ pacāmi, ime na pacanti, nārahāmi pacanto apacantānaṃ dānaṃ na dātun’ti dānaṃ deti, ‘idaṃ me dānaṃ dadato kalyāṇo kittisaddo abbhuggacchatī’ti dānaṃ deti.**A person might give a gift after insulting the recipient. Or they give out of fear. Or they give thinking, ‘They gave to me.’ Or they give thinking, ‘They’ll give to me.’ Or they give thinking, ‘It’s good to give.’ Or they give thinking, ‘I cook, they don’t. It wouldn’t be right for me to not give to them.’ Or they give thinking, ‘By giving this gift I’ll get a good reputation.’ Or they give thinking, ‘This is an adornment and requisite for the mind.’*";
P_HTM[4787]="*Cittālaṅkāracittaparikkhāratthaṃ dānaṃ deti. (6)* **";
P_HTM[4788]="*Aṭṭha dānūpapattiyo.**Eight rebirths by giving.*";
P_HTM[4789]="*Idhāvuso, ekacco dānaṃ deti samaṇassa vā brāhmaṇassa vā annaṃ pānaṃ vatthaṃ yānaṃ mālāgandhavilepanaṃ seyyāvasathapadīpeyyaṃ.**First, someone gives to ascetics or brahmins such things as food, drink, clothing, vehicles; garlands, fragrance, and makeup; and bed, house, and lighting.*";
P_HTM[4790]="*So yaṃ deti taṃ paccāsīsati.**Whatever they give, they expect something back.*";
P_HTM[4791]="*So passati khattiyamahāsālaṃ vā brāhmaṇamahāsālaṃ vā gahapatimahāsālaṃ vā pañcahi kāmaguṇehi samappitaṃ samaṅgībhūtaṃ paricārayamānaṃ.**They see an affluent aristocrat or brahmin or householder amusing themselves, supplied and provided with the five kinds of sensual stimulation.*";
P_HTM[4792]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[4793]="*‘aho vatāhaṃ kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā khattiyamahāsālānaṃ vā brāhmaṇamahāsālānaṃ vā gahapatimahāsālānaṃ vā sahabyataṃ upapajjeyyan’ti.**‘If only, when my body breaks up, after death, I would be reborn in the company of well-to-do aristocrats or brahmins or householders!’*";
P_HTM[4794]="*So taṃ cittaṃ dahati, taṃ cittaṃ adhiṭṭhāti, taṃ cittaṃ bhāveti, tassa taṃ cittaṃ hīne vimuttaṃ uttari abhāvitaṃ tatrūpapattiyā saṃvattati.**They settle on that thought, concentrate on it and develop it. As they’ve settled for less and not developed further, their thought leads to rebirth there.*";
P_HTM[4795]="*Tañca kho sīlavato vadāmi no dussīlassa.**But I say that this is only for those of ethical conduct, not for the unethical.*";
P_HTM[4796]="*Ijjhatāvuso, sīlavato cetopaṇidhi visuddhattā. (7.1)**The heart’s wish of an ethical person succeeds because of their purity.*";
P_HTM[4797]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, idhekacco dānaṃ deti samaṇassa vā brāhmaṇassa vā annaṃ pānaṃ … pe … seyyāvasathapadīpeyyaṃ.**Next, someone gives to ascetics or brahmins.*";
P_HTM[4798]="*So yaṃ deti taṃ paccāsīsati.**Whatever they give, they expect something back.*";
P_HTM[4799]="*Tassa sutaṃ hoti:**And they’ve heard:*";
P_HTM[4800]="*‘cātumahārājikā devā dīghāyukā vaṇṇavanto sukhabahulā’ti.**‘The Gods of the Four Great Kings are long-lived, beautiful, and very happy.’*";
P_HTM[4801]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[4802]="*‘aho vatāhaṃ kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā cātumahārājikānaṃ devānaṃ sahabyataṃ upapajjeyyan’ti.**‘If only, when my body breaks up, after death, I would be reborn in the company of the Gods of the Four Great Kings!’*";
P_HTM[4803]="*So taṃ cittaṃ dahati, taṃ cittaṃ adhiṭṭhāti, taṃ cittaṃ bhāveti, tassa taṃ cittaṃ hīne vimuttaṃ uttari abhāvitaṃ tatrūpapattiyā saṃvattati.**They settle on that thought, concentrate on it and develop it. As they’ve settled for less and not developed further, their thought leads to rebirth there.*";
P_HTM[4804]="*Tañca kho sīlavato vadāmi no dussīlassa.**But I say that this is only for those of ethical conduct, not for the unethical.*";
P_HTM[4805]="*Ijjhatāvuso, sīlavato cetopaṇidhi visuddhattā. (7.2)**The heart’s wish of an ethical person succeeds because of their purity.*";
P_HTM[4806]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, idhekacco dānaṃ deti samaṇassa vā brāhmaṇassa vā annaṃ pānaṃ … pe … seyyāvasathapadīpeyyaṃ.**Next, someone gives to ascetics or brahmins.*";
P_HTM[4807]="*So yaṃ deti taṃ paccāsīsati.**Whatever they give, they expect something back.*";
P_HTM[4808]="*Tassa sutaṃ hoti:**And they’ve heard:*";
P_HTM[4809]="*‘tāvatiṃsā devā … pe …**‘The Gods of the Thirty-Three …*";
P_HTM[4810]="*yāmā devā … pe …**the Gods of Yama …*";
P_HTM[4811]="*tusitā devā … pe …**the Joyful Gods …*";
P_HTM[4812]="*nimmānaratī devā … pe …**the Gods Who Love to Create …*";
P_HTM[4813]="*paranimmitavasavattī devā dīghāyukā vaṇṇavanto sukhabahulā’ti.**the Gods Who Control the Creations of Others are long-lived, beautiful, and very happy.’*";
P_HTM[4814]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[4815]="*‘aho vatāhaṃ kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā paranimmitavasavattīnaṃ devānaṃ sahabyataṃ upapajjeyyan’ti.**‘If only, when my body breaks up, after death, I would be reborn in the company of the Gods Who Control the Creations of Others!’*";
P_HTM[4816]="*So taṃ cittaṃ dahati, taṃ cittaṃ adhiṭṭhāti, taṃ cittaṃ bhāveti, tassa taṃ cittaṃ hīne vimuttaṃ uttari abhāvitaṃ tatrūpapattiyā saṃvattati.**They settle on that thought, concentrate on it and develop it. As they’ve settled for less and not developed further, their thought leads to rebirth there.*";
P_HTM[4817]="*Tañca kho sīlavato vadāmi no dussīlassa.**But I say that this is only for those of ethical conduct, not for the unethical.*";
P_HTM[4818]="*Ijjhatāvuso, sīlavato cetopaṇidhi visuddhattā. (7.3–7.)**The heart’s wish of an ethical person succeeds because of their purity.*";
P_HTM[4819]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, idhekacco dānaṃ deti samaṇassa vā brāhmaṇassa vā annaṃ pānaṃ vatthaṃ yānaṃ mālāgandhavilepanaṃ seyyāvasathapadīpeyyaṃ.**Next, someone gives to ascetics or brahmins such things as food, drink, clothing, vehicles; garlands, fragrance, and makeup; and bed, house, and lighting.*";
P_HTM[4820]="*So yaṃ deti taṃ paccāsīsati.**Whatever they give, they expect something back.*";
P_HTM[4821]="*Tassa sutaṃ hoti:**And they’ve heard:*";
P_HTM[4822]="*‘brahmakāyikā devā dīghāyukā vaṇṇavanto sukhabahulā’ti.**‘The Gods of Brahmā’s Host are long-lived, beautiful, and very happy.’*";
P_HTM[4823]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[4824]="*‘aho vatāhaṃ kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā brahmakāyikānaṃ devānaṃ sahabyataṃ upapajjeyyan’ti.**‘If only, when my body breaks up, after death, I would be reborn in the company of the Gods of Brahmā’s Host!’*";
P_HTM[4825]="*So taṃ cittaṃ dahati, taṃ cittaṃ adhiṭṭhāti, taṃ cittaṃ bhāveti, tassa taṃ cittaṃ hīne vimuttaṃ uttari abhāvitaṃ tatrūpapattiyā saṃvattati.**They settle on that thought, concentrate on it and develop it. As they’ve settled for less and not developed further, their thought leads to rebirth there.*";
P_HTM[4826]="*Tañca kho sīlavato vadāmi no dussīlassa;**But I say that this is only for those of ethical conduct, not for the unethical.*";
P_HTM[4827]="*vītarāgassa no sarāgassa.**And for those free of desire, not those with desire.*";
P_HTM[4828]="*Ijjhatāvuso, sīlavato cetopaṇidhi vītarāgattā. (7.8)**The heart’s wish of an ethical person succeeds because of their freedom from desire.*";
P_HTM[4829]="*Aṭṭha parisā—**Eight assemblies:*";
P_HTM[4830]="*khattiyaparisā, brāhmaṇaparisā, gahapatiparisā, samaṇaparisā, cātumahārājikaparisā, tāvatiṃsaparisā, māraparisā, brahmaparisā. (8)**the assemblies of aristocrats, brahmins, householders, and ascetics. An assembly of the gods under the Four Great Kings. An assembly of the gods under the Thirty-Three. An assembly of Māras. An assembly of Brahmās.*";
P_HTM[4831]="*Aṭṭha lokadhammā—**Eight worldly conditions:*";
P_HTM[4832]="*lābho ca, alābho ca, yaso ca, ayaso ca, nindā ca, pasaṃsā ca, sukhañca, dukkhañca. (9)**gain and loss, fame and disgrace, praise and blame, pleasure and pain.*";
P_HTM[4833]="*Aṭṭha abhibhāyatanāni.**Eight dimensions of mastery.*";
P_HTM[4834]="*Ajjhattaṃ rūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati parittāni suvaṇṇadubbaṇṇāni, ‘tāni abhibhuyya jānāmi passāmī’ti evaṃsaññī hoti.**Perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally, limited, both pretty and ugly. Mastering them, they perceive: ‘I know and see.’*";
P_HTM[4835]="*Idaṃ paṭhamaṃ abhibhāyatanaṃ.**This is the first dimension of mastery.*";
P_HTM[4836]="*Ajjhattaṃ rūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati appamāṇāni suvaṇṇadubbaṇṇāni, ‘tāni abhibhuyya jānāmi passāmī’ti—**Perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally, limitless, both pretty and ugly. Mastering them, they perceive: ‘I know and see.’*";
P_HTM[4837]="*evaṃsaññī hoti.* **";
P_HTM[4838]="*Idaṃ dutiyaṃ abhibhāyatanaṃ.**This is the second dimension of mastery.*";
P_HTM[4839]="*Ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati parittāni suvaṇṇadubbaṇṇāni, ‘tāni abhibhuyya jānāmi passāmī’ti evaṃsaññī hoti.**Not perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally, limited, both pretty and ugly. Mastering them, they perceive: ‘I know and see.’*";
P_HTM[4840]="*Idaṃ tatiyaṃ abhibhāyatanaṃ.**This is the third dimension of mastery.*";
P_HTM[4841]="*Ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati appamāṇāni suvaṇṇadubbaṇṇāni, ‘tāni abhibhuyya jānāmi passāmī’ti evaṃsaññī hoti.**Not perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally, limitless, both pretty and ugly. Mastering them, they perceive: ‘I know and see.’*";
P_HTM[4842]="*Idaṃ catutthaṃ abhibhāyatanaṃ.**This is the fourth dimension of mastery.*";
P_HTM[4843]="*Ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati nīlāni nīlavaṇṇāni nīlanidassanāni nīlanibhāsāni.**Not perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally that are blue, with blue color, blue hue, and blue tint.*";
P_HTM[4844]="*Seyyathāpi nāma umāpupphaṃ nīlaṃ nīlavaṇṇaṃ nīlanidassanaṃ nīlanibhāsaṃ, seyyathā vā pana taṃ vatthaṃ bārāṇaseyyakaṃ ubhatobhāgavimaṭṭhaṃ nīlaṃ nīlavaṇṇaṃ nīlanidassanaṃ nīlanibhāsaṃ;**They’re like a flax flower that’s blue, with blue color, blue hue, and blue tint. Or a cloth from Bāraṇasī that’s smoothed on both sides, blue, with blue color, blue hue, and blue tint.*";
P_HTM[4845]="*evameva ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati nīlāni nīlavaṇṇāni nīlanidassanāni nīlanibhāsāni, ‘tāni abhibhuyya jānāmi passāmī’ti evaṃsaññī hoti.**Mastering them, they perceive: ‘I know and see.’*";
P_HTM[4846]="*Idaṃ pañcamaṃ abhibhāyatanaṃ.**This is the fifth dimension of mastery.*";
P_HTM[4847]="*Ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati pītāni pītavaṇṇāni pītanidassanāni pītanibhāsāni.**Not perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally that are yellow, with yellow color, yellow hue, and yellow tint.*";
P_HTM[4848]="*Seyyathāpi nāma kaṇikārapupphaṃ pītaṃ pītavaṇṇaṃ pītanidassanaṃ pītanibhāsaṃ, seyyathā vā pana taṃ vatthaṃ bārāṇaseyyakaṃ ubhatobhāgavimaṭṭhaṃ pītaṃ pītavaṇṇaṃ pītanidassanaṃ pītanibhāsaṃ;**They’re like a champak flower that’s yellow, with yellow color, yellow hue, and yellow tint. Or a cloth from Bāraṇasī that’s smoothed on both sides, yellow, with yellow color, yellow hue, and yellow tint.*";
P_HTM[4849]="*evameva ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati pītāni pītavaṇṇāni pītanidassanāni pītanibhāsāni, ‘tāni abhibhuyya jānāmi passāmī’ti evaṃsaññī hoti.**Mastering them, they perceive: ‘I know and see.’*";
P_HTM[4850]="*Idaṃ chaṭṭhaṃ abhibhāyatanaṃ.**This is the sixth dimension of mastery.*";
P_HTM[4851]="*Ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati lohitakāni lohitakavaṇṇāni lohitakanidassanāni lohitakanibhāsāni.**Not perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally that are red, with red color, red hue, and red tint.*";
P_HTM[4852]="*Seyyathāpi nāma bandhujīvakapupphaṃ lohitakaṃ lohitakavaṇṇaṃ lohitakanidassanaṃ lohitakanibhāsaṃ, seyyathā vā pana taṃ vatthaṃ bārāṇaseyyakaṃ ubhatobhāgavimaṭṭhaṃ lohitakaṃ lohitakavaṇṇaṃ lohitakanidassanaṃ lohitakanibhāsaṃ;**They’re like a scarlet mallow flower that’s red, with red color, red hue, and red tint. Or a cloth from Bāraṇasī that’s smoothed on both sides, red, with red color, red hue, and red tint.*";
P_HTM[4853]="*evameva ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati lohitakāni lohitakavaṇṇāni lohitakanidassanāni lohitakanibhāsāni, ‘tāni abhibhuyya jānāmi passāmī’ti evaṃsaññī hoti.**Mastering them, they perceive: ‘I know and see.’*";
P_HTM[4854]="*Idaṃ sattamaṃ abhibhāyatanaṃ.**This is the seventh dimension of mastery.*";
P_HTM[4855]="*Ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati odātāni odātavaṇṇāni odātanidassanāni odātanibhāsāni.**Not perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally that are white, with white color, white hue, and white tint.*";
P_HTM[4856]="*Seyyathāpi nāma osadhitārakā odātā odātavaṇṇā odātanidassanā odātanibhāsā, seyyathā vā pana taṃ vatthaṃ bārāṇaseyyakaṃ ubhatobhāgavimaṭṭhaṃ odātaṃ odātavaṇṇaṃ odātanidassanaṃ odātanibhāsaṃ;**They’re like the morning star that’s white, with white color, white hue, and white tint. Or a cloth from Bāraṇasī that’s smoothed on both sides, white, with white color, white hue, and white tint.*";
P_HTM[4857]="*evameva ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati odātāni odātavaṇṇāni odātanidassanāni odātanibhāsāni, ‘tāni abhibhuyya jānāmi passāmī’ti evaṃsaññī hoti.**Mastering them, they perceive: ‘I know and see.’*";
P_HTM[4858]="*Idaṃ aṭṭhamaṃ abhibhāyatanaṃ. (10)**This is the eighth dimension of mastery.*";
P_HTM[4859]="*Aṭṭha vimokkhā.**Eight liberations.*";
P_HTM[4860]="*Rūpī rūpāni passati.**Having physical form, they see visions.*";
P_HTM[4861]="*Ayaṃ paṭhamo vimokkho.**This is the first liberation.*";
P_HTM[4862]="*Ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī bahiddhā rūpāni passati.**Not perceiving physical form internally, they see visions externally.*";
P_HTM[4863]="*Ayaṃ dutiyo vimokkho.**This is the second liberation.*";
P_HTM[4864]="*Subhanteva adhimutto hoti.**They’re focused only on beauty.*";
P_HTM[4865]="*Ayaṃ tatiyo vimokkho.**This is the third liberation.*";
P_HTM[4866]="*Sabbaso rūpasaññānaṃ samatikkamā paṭighasaññānaṃ atthaṅgamā nānattasaññānaṃ amanasikārā ‘ananto ākāso’ti ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Going totally beyond perceptions of form, with the ending of perceptions of impingement, not focusing on perceptions of diversity, aware that ‘space is infinite’, they enter and remain in the dimension of infinite space.*";
P_HTM[4867]="*Ayaṃ catuttho vimokkho.**This is the fourth liberation.*";
P_HTM[4868]="*Sabbaso ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma ‘anantaṃ viññāṇan’ti viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Going totally beyond the dimension of infinite space, aware that ‘consciousness is infinite’, they enter and remain in the dimension of infinite consciousness.*";
P_HTM[4869]="*Ayaṃ pañcamo vimokkho.**This is the fifth liberation.*";
P_HTM[4870]="*Sabbaso viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma ‘natthi kiñcī’ti ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Going totally beyond the dimension of infinite consciousness, aware that ‘there is nothing at all’, they enter and remain in the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[4871]="*Ayaṃ chaṭṭho vimokkho.**This is the sixth liberation.*";
P_HTM[4872]="*Sabbaso ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Going totally beyond the dimension of nothingness, they enter and remain in the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.*";
P_HTM[4873]="*Ayaṃ sattamo vimokkho.**This is the seventh liberation.*";
P_HTM[4874]="*Sabbaso nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Going totally beyond the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, they enter and remain in the cessation of perception and feeling.*";
P_HTM[4875]="*Ayaṃ aṭṭhamo vimokkho. (11)**This is the eighth liberation.*";
P_HTM[4876]="*Ime kho, āvuso, tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena aṭṭha dhammā sammadakkhātā;**These are the teachings grouped by eight that have been rightly explained by the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[4877]="*tattha sabbeheva saṅgāyitabbaṃ … pe … atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānaṃ.**You should all recite these in concert.*";
P_HTM[4878]="*9. Navaka**9. Nines*";
P_HTM[4879]="*Atthi kho, āvuso, tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena nava dhammā sammadakkhātā;**There are teachings grouped by nine that have been rightly explained by the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[4880]="*tattha sabbeheva saṅgāyitabbaṃ … pe … atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānaṃ.**You should all recite these in concert.*";
P_HTM[4881]="*Katame nava?**What are the teachings grouped by nine?*";
P_HTM[4882]="*Nava āghātavatthūni.**Nine grounds for resentment.*";
P_HTM[4883]="*‘Anatthaṃ me acarī’ti āghātaṃ bandhati;**Thinking: ‘They did wrong to me,’ you harbor resentment.*";
P_HTM[4884]="*‘anatthaṃ me caratī’ti āghātaṃ bandhati;**Thinking: ‘They are doing wrong to me’ …*";
P_HTM[4885]="*‘anatthaṃ me carissatī’ti āghātaṃ bandhati;**‘They will do wrong to me’ …*";
P_HTM[4886]="*‘piyassa me manāpassa anatthaṃ acarī’ti āghātaṃ bandhati … pe …**‘They did wrong by someone I love’ …*";
P_HTM[4887]="*anatthaṃ caratīti āghātaṃ bandhati … pe …**‘They are doing wrong by someone I love’ …*";
P_HTM[4888]="*anatthaṃ carissatīti āghātaṃ bandhati;**‘They will do wrong by someone I love’ …*";
P_HTM[4889]="*‘appiyassa me amanāpassa atthaṃ acarī’ti āghātaṃ bandhati … pe …**‘They helped someone I dislike’ …*";
P_HTM[4890]="*atthaṃ caratīti āghātaṃ bandhati … pe …**‘They are helping someone I dislike’ …*";
P_HTM[4891]="*atthaṃ carissatīti āghātaṃ bandhati. (1)**Thinking: ‘They will help someone I dislike,’ you harbor resentment.*";
P_HTM[4892]="*Nava āghātapaṭivinayā.**Nine methods to get rid of resentment.*";
P_HTM[4893]="*‘Anatthaṃ me acari, taṃ kutettha labbhā’ti āghātaṃ paṭivineti;**Thinking: ‘They did wrong to me, but what can I possibly do?’ you get rid of resentment.*";
P_HTM[4894]="*‘anatthaṃ me carati, taṃ kutettha labbhā’ti āghātaṃ paṭivineti;**Thinking: ‘They are doing wrong to me …’ …*";
P_HTM[4895]="*‘anatthaṃ me carissati, taṃ kutettha labbhā’ti āghātaṃ paṭivineti;**‘They will do wrong to me …’ …*";
P_HTM[4896]="*‘piyassa me manāpassa anatthaṃ acari … pe …**‘They did wrong by someone I love …’ …*";
P_HTM[4897]="*anatthaṃ carati … pe …**‘They are doing wrong by someone I love …’ …*";
P_HTM[4898]="*anatthaṃ carissati, taṃ kutettha labbhā’ti āghātaṃ paṭivineti;**‘They will do wrong by someone I love …’ …*";
P_HTM[4899]="*‘appiyassa me amanāpassa atthaṃ acari … pe …**‘They helped someone I dislike …’ …*";
P_HTM[4900]="*atthaṃ carati … pe …**‘They are helping someone I dislike …’ …*";
P_HTM[4901]="*atthaṃ carissati, taṃ kutettha labbhā’ti āghātaṃ paṭivineti. (2)**Thinking: ‘They will help someone I dislike, but what can I possibly do?’ you get rid of resentment.*";
P_HTM[4902]="*Nava sattāvāsā.**Nine abodes of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[4903]="*Santāvuso, sattā nānattakāyā nānattasaññino, seyyathāpi manussā ekacce ca devā ekacce ca vinipātikā.**There are sentient beings that are diverse in body and diverse in perception, such as human beings, some gods, and some beings in the underworld.*";
P_HTM[4904]="*Ayaṃ paṭhamo sattāvāso.**This is the first abode of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[4905]="*Santāvuso, sattā nānattakāyā ekattasaññino, seyyathāpi devā brahmakāyikā paṭhamābhinibbattā.**There are sentient beings that are diverse in body and unified in perception, such as the gods reborn in Brahmā’s Host through the first absorption.*";
P_HTM[4906]="*Ayaṃ dutiyo sattāvāso.**This is the second abode of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[4907]="*Santāvuso, sattā ekattakāyā nānattasaññino, seyyathāpi devā ābhassarā.**There are sentient beings that are unified in body and diverse in perception, such as the gods of streaming radiance.*";
P_HTM[4908]="*Ayaṃ tatiyo sattāvāso.**This is the third abode of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[4909]="*Santāvuso, sattā ekattakāyā ekattasaññino, seyyathāpi devā subhakiṇhā.**There are sentient beings that are unified in body and unified in perception, such as the gods replete with glory.*";
P_HTM[4910]="*Ayaṃ catuttho sattāvāso.**This is the fourth abode of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[4911]="*Santāvuso, sattā asaññino appaṭisaṃvedino, seyyathāpi devā asaññasattā.**There are sentient beings that are non-percipient and do not experience anything, such as the gods who are non-percipient beings.*";
P_HTM[4912]="*Ayaṃ pañcamo sattāvāso.**This is the fifth abode of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[4913]="*Santāvuso, sattā sabbaso rūpasaññānaṃ samatikkamā paṭighasaññānaṃ atthaṅgamā nānattasaññānaṃ amanasikārā ‘ananto ākāso’ti ākāsānañcāyatanūpagā.**There are sentient beings that have gone totally beyond perceptions of form. With the ending of perceptions of impingement, not focusing on perceptions of diversity, aware that ‘space is infinite’, they have been reborn in the dimension of infinite space.*";
P_HTM[4914]="*Ayaṃ chaṭṭho sattāvāso.**This is the sixth abode of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[4915]="*Santāvuso, sattā sabbaso ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma ‘anantaṃ viññāṇan’ti viññāṇañcāyatanūpagā.**There are sentient beings that have gone totally beyond the dimension of infinite space. Aware that ‘consciousness is infinite’, they have been reborn in the dimension of infinite consciousness.*";
P_HTM[4916]="*Ayaṃ sattamo sattāvāso.**This is the seventh abode of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[4917]="*Santāvuso, sattā sabbaso viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma ‘natthi kiñcī’ti ākiñcaññāyatanūpagā.**There are sentient beings that have gone totally beyond the dimension of infinite consciousness. Aware that ‘there is nothing at all’, they have been reborn in the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[4918]="*Ayaṃ aṭṭhamo sattāvāso.**This is the eighth abode of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[4919]="*Santāvuso, sattā sabbaso ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma nevasaññānāsaññāyatanūpagā.**There are sentient beings that have gone totally beyond the dimension of nothingness. They have been reborn in the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.*";
P_HTM[4920]="*Ayaṃ navamo sattāvāso. (3)**This is the ninth abode of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[4921]="*Nava akkhaṇā asamayā brahmacariyavāsāya.**Nine lost opportunities for spiritual practice.*";
P_HTM[4922]="*Idhāvuso, tathāgato ca loke uppanno hoti arahaṃ sammāsambuddho, dhammo ca desiyati opasamiko parinibbāniko sambodhagāmī sugatappavedito.**Firstly, a Realized One has arisen in the world. He teaches the Dhamma leading to peace, extinguishment, awakening, as proclaimed by the Holy One.*";
P_HTM[4923]="*Ayañca puggalo nirayaṃ upapanno hoti.**But a person has been reborn in hell.*";
P_HTM[4924]="*Ayaṃ paṭhamo akkhaṇo asamayo brahmacariyavāsāya.**This is the first lost opportunity for spiritual practice.*";
P_HTM[4925]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, tathāgato ca loke uppanno hoti arahaṃ sammāsambuddho, dhammo ca desiyati opasamiko parinibbāniko sambodhagāmī sugatappavedito.**Furthermore, a Realized One has arisen in the world.*";
P_HTM[4926]="*Ayañca puggalo tiracchānayoniṃ upapanno hoti.**But a person has been reborn in the animal realm.*";
P_HTM[4927]="*Ayaṃ dutiyo akkhaṇo asamayo brahmacariyavāsāya.**This is the second lost opportunity for spiritual practice.*";
P_HTM[4928]="*Puna caparaṃ … pe …**Furthermore, a Realized One has arisen in the world.*";
P_HTM[4929]="*pettivisayaṃ upapanno hoti.**But a person has been reborn in the ghost realm.*";
P_HTM[4930]="*Ayaṃ tatiyo akkhaṇo asamayo brahmacariyavāsāya.**This is the third lost opportunity for spiritual practice.*";
P_HTM[4931]="*Puna caparaṃ … pe …**Furthermore, a Realized One has arisen in the world.*";
P_HTM[4932]="*asurakāyaṃ upapanno hoti.**But a person has been reborn among the demons.*";
P_HTM[4933]="*Ayaṃ catuttho akkhaṇo asamayo brahmacariyavāsāya.**This is the fourth lost opportunity for spiritual practice.*";
P_HTM[4934]="*Puna caparaṃ … pe …**Furthermore, a Realized One has arisen in the world.*";
P_HTM[4935]="*aññataraṃ dīghāyukaṃ devanikāyaṃ upapanno hoti.**But a person has been reborn in one of the long-lived orders of gods.*";
P_HTM[4936]="*Ayaṃ pañcamo akkhaṇo asamayo brahmacariyavāsāya.**This is the fifth lost opportunity for spiritual practice.*";
P_HTM[4937]="*Puna caparaṃ … pe …**Furthermore, a Realized One has arisen in the world.*";
P_HTM[4938]="*paccantimesu janapadesu paccājāto hoti milakkhesu aviññātāresu, yattha natthi gati bhikkhūnaṃ bhikkhunīnaṃ upāsakānaṃ upāsikānaṃ.**But a person has been reborn in the borderlands, among barbarian tribes, where monks, nuns, laymen, and laywomen do not go.*";
P_HTM[4939]="*Ayaṃ chaṭṭho akkhaṇo asamayo brahmacariyavāsāya.**This is the sixth lost opportunity for spiritual practice.*";
P_HTM[4940]="*Puna caparaṃ … pe …**Furthermore, a Realized One has arisen in the world.*";
P_HTM[4941]="*majjhimesu janapadesu paccājāto hoti. So ca hoti micchādiṭṭhiko viparītadassano:**And a person is reborn in a central country. But they have wrong view and distorted perspective:*";
P_HTM[4942]="*‘natthi dinnaṃ, natthi yiṭṭhaṃ, natthi hutaṃ, natthi sukatadukkaṭānaṃ kammānaṃ phalaṃ vipāko, natthi ayaṃ loko, natthi paro loko, natthi mātā, natthi pitā, natthi sattā opapātikā, natthi loke samaṇabrāhmaṇā sammaggatā sammāpaṭipannā ye imañca lokaṃ parañca lokaṃ sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā pavedentī’ti.**‘There’s no meaning in giving, sacrifice, or offerings. There’s no fruit or result of good and bad deeds. There’s no afterlife. There are no duties to mother and father. No beings are reborn spontaneously. And there’s no ascetic or brahmin who is well attained and practiced, and who describes the afterlife after realizing it with their own insight.’*";
P_HTM[4943]="*Ayaṃ sattamo akkhaṇo asamayo brahmacariyavāsāya.**This is the seventh lost opportunity for spiritual practice.*";
P_HTM[4944]="*Puna caparaṃ … pe …**Furthermore, a Realized One has arisen in the world.*";
P_HTM[4945]="*majjhimesu janapadesu paccājāto hoti. So ca hoti duppañño jaḷo eḷamūgo, nappaṭibalo subhāsitadubbhāsitānamatthamaññātuṃ.**And a person is reborn in a central country. But they’re witless, dull, stupid, and unable to distinguish what is well said from what is poorly said.*";
P_HTM[4946]="*Ayaṃ aṭṭhamo akkhaṇo asamayo brahmacariyavāsāya.**This is the eighth lost opportunity for spiritual practice.*";
P_HTM[4947]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, tathāgato ca loke na uppanno hoti arahaṃ sammāsambuddho,**Furthermore, a Realized One has arisen in the world.*";
P_HTM[4948]="*dhammo ca na desiyati opasamiko parinibbāniko sambodhagāmī sugatappavedito. Ayañca puggalo majjhimesu janapadesu paccājāto hoti, so ca hoti paññavā ajaḷo aneḷamūgo, paṭibalo subhāsitadubbhāsitānamatthamaññātuṃ.**But he doesn’t teach the Dhamma leading to peace, extinguishment, awakening, as proclaimed by the Holy One. And a person is reborn in a central country. And they’re wise, bright, clever, and able to distinguish what is well said from what is poorly said.*";
P_HTM[4949]="*Ayaṃ navamo akkhaṇo asamayo brahmacariyavāsāya. (4)**This is the ninth lost opportunity for spiritual practice.*";
P_HTM[4950]="*Nava anupubbavihārā.**Nine progressive meditations.*";
P_HTM[4951]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu vivicceva kāmehi vivicca akusalehi dhammehi savitakkaṃ savicāraṃ vivekajaṃ pītisukhaṃ paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**A mendicant, quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, enters and remains in the first absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of seclusion, while placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[4952]="*Vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā … pe … dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**As the placing of the mind and keeping it connected are stilled, they enter and remain in the second absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of immersion, with internal clarity and confidence, and unified mind, without placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[4953]="*Pītiyā ca virāgā … pe … tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**And with the fading away of rapture, they enter and remain in the third absorption, where they meditate with equanimity, mindful and aware, personally experiencing the bliss of which the noble ones declare, ‘Equanimous and mindful, one meditates in bliss.’*";
P_HTM[4954]="*Sukhassa ca pahānā … pe … catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Giving up pleasure and pain, and ending former happiness and sadness, they enter and remain in the fourth absorption, without pleasure or pain, with pure equanimity and mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[4955]="*Sabbaso rūpasaññānaṃ samatikkamā … pe … ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Going totally beyond perceptions of form, with the ending of perceptions of impingement, not focusing on perceptions of diversity, aware that ‘space is infinite’, they enter and remain in the dimension of infinite space.*";
P_HTM[4956]="*Sabbaso ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma ‘anantaṃ viññāṇan’ti viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Going totally beyond the dimension of infinite space, aware that ‘consciousness is infinite’, they enter and remain in the dimension of infinite consciousness.*";
P_HTM[4957]="*Sabbaso viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma ‘natthi kiñcī’ti ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Going totally beyond the dimension of infinite consciousness, aware that ‘there is nothing at all’, they enter and remain in the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[4958]="*Sabbaso ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Going totally beyond the dimension of nothingness, they enter and remain in the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.*";
P_HTM[4959]="*Sabbaso nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ upasampajja viharati. (5)**Going totally beyond the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, they enter and remain in the cessation of perception and feeling.*";
P_HTM[4960]="*Nava anupubbanirodhā.**Nine progressive cessations.*";
P_HTM[4961]="*Paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ samāpannassa kāmasaññā niruddhā hoti.**For someone who has attained the first absorption, sensual perceptions have ceased.*";
P_HTM[4962]="*Dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ samāpannassa vitakkavicārā niruddhā honti.**For someone who has attained the second absorption, the placing of the mind and keeping it connected have ceased.*";
P_HTM[4963]="*Tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ samāpannassa pīti niruddhā hoti.**For someone who has attained the third absorption, rapture has ceased.*";
P_HTM[4964]="*Catutthaṃ jhānaṃ samāpannassa assāsapassāssā niruddhā honti.**For someone who has attained the fourth absorption, breathing has ceased.*";
P_HTM[4965]="*Ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ samāpannassa rūpasaññā niruddhā hoti.**For someone who has attained the dimension of infinite space, the perception of form has ceased.*";
P_HTM[4966]="*Viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ samāpannassa ākāsānañcāyatanasaññā niruddhā hoti.**For someone who has attained the dimension of infinite consciousness, the perception of the dimension of infinite space has ceased.*";
P_HTM[4967]="*Ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ samāpannassa viññāṇañcāyatanasaññā niruddhā hoti.**For someone who has attained the dimension of nothingness, the perception of the dimension of infinite consciousness has ceased.*";
P_HTM[4968]="*Nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ samāpannassa ākiñcaññāyatanasaññā niruddhā hoti.**For someone who has attained the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, the perception of the dimension of nothingness has ceased.*";
P_HTM[4969]="*Saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ samāpannassa saññā ca vedanā ca niruddhā honti. (6)**For someone who has attained the cessation of perception and feeling, perception and feeling have ceased.*";
P_HTM[4970]="*Ime kho, āvuso, tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena nava dhammā sammadakkhātā.**These are the teachings grouped by nine that have been rightly explained by the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[4971]="*Tattha sabbeheva saṅgāyitabbaṃ … pe … atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānaṃ.**You should all recite these in concert.*";
P_HTM[4972]="*10. Dasaka**10. Tens*";
P_HTM[4973]="*Atthi kho, āvuso, tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena dasa dhammā sammadakkhātā.**There are teachings grouped by ten that have been rightly explained by the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[4974]="*Tattha sabbeheva saṅgāyitabbaṃ … pe … atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānaṃ.**You should all recite these in concert.*";
P_HTM[4975]="*Katame dasa?**What are the teachings grouped by ten?*";
P_HTM[4976]="*Dasa nāthakaraṇā dhammā.**Ten qualities that serve as protector.*";
P_HTM[4977]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu sīlavā hoti. Pātimokkhasaṃvarasaṃvuto viharati ācāragocarasampanno, aṇumattesu vajjesu bhayadassāvī samādāya sikkhati sikkhāpadesu.**Firstly, a mendicant is ethical, restrained in the monastic code, conducting themselves well and seeking alms in suitable places. Seeing danger in the slightest fault, they keep the rules they’ve undertaken.*";
P_HTM[4978]="*Yaṃpāvuso, bhikkhu sīlavā hoti, pātimokkhasaṃvarasaṃvuto viharati, ācāragocarasampanno, aṇumattesu vajjesu bhayadassāvī samādāya sikkhati sikkhāpadesu.* **";
P_HTM[4979]="*Ayampi dhammo nāthakaraṇo. (1.1)**This is a quality that serves as protector.*";
P_HTM[4980]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu bahussuto hoti sutadharo sutasannicayo. Ye te dhammā ādikalyāṇā majjhekalyāṇā pariyosānakalyāṇā sātthā sabyañjanā kevalaparipuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ abhivadanti, tathārūpāssa dhammā bahussutā honti dhātā vacasā paricitā manasānupekkhitā diṭṭhiyā suppaṭividdhā.**Furthermore, a mendicant is very learned, remembering and keeping what they’ve learned. These teachings are good in the beginning, good in the middle, and good in the end, meaningful and well-phrased, describing a spiritual practice that’s entirely full and pure. They are very learned in such teachings, remembering them, reinforcing them by recitation, mentally scrutinizing them, and comprehending them theoretically.*";
P_HTM[4981]="*Yaṃpāvuso, bhikkhu bahussuto hoti … pe … diṭṭhiyā suppaṭividdhā.* **";
P_HTM[4982]="*Ayampi dhammo nāthakaraṇo. (1.2)**This too is a quality that serves as protector.*";
P_HTM[4983]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu kalyāṇamitto hoti kalyāṇasahāyo kalyāṇasampavaṅko.**Furthermore, a mendicant has good friends, companions, and associates.*";
P_HTM[4984]="*Yaṃpāvuso, bhikkhu kalyāṇamitto hoti kalyāṇasahāyo kalyāṇasampavaṅko.* **";
P_HTM[4985]="*Ayampi dhammo nāthakaraṇo. (1.3)**This too is a quality that serves as protector.*";
P_HTM[4986]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu suvaco hoti sovacassakaraṇehi dhammehi samannāgato khamo padakkhiṇaggāhī anusāsaniṃ.**Furthermore, a mendicant is easy to admonish, having qualities that make them easy to admonish. They’re patient, and take instruction respectfully.*";
P_HTM[4987]="*Yaṃpāvuso, bhikkhu suvaco hoti … pe … padakkhiṇaggāhī anusāsaniṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4988]="*Ayampi dhammo nāthakaraṇo. (1.4)**This too is a quality that serves as protector.*";
P_HTM[4989]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu yāni tāni sabrahmacārīnaṃ uccāvacāni kiṅkaraṇīyāni, tattha dakkho hoti analaso tatrupāyāya vīmaṃsāya samannāgato, alaṃ kātuṃ alaṃ saṃvidhātuṃ.**Furthermore, a mendicant is deft and tireless in a diverse spectrum of duties for their spiritual companions, understanding how to go about things in order to complete and organize the work.*";
P_HTM[4990]="*Yaṃpāvuso, bhikkhu yāni tāni sabrahmacārīnaṃ … pe … alaṃ saṃvidhātuṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4991]="*Ayampi dhammo nāthakaraṇo. (1.5)**This too is a quality that serves as protector.*";
P_HTM[4992]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu dhammakāmo hoti piyasamudāhāro, abhidhamme abhivinaye uḷārapāmojjo.**Furthermore, a mendicant loves the teachings and is a delight to converse with, being full of joy in the teaching and training.*";
P_HTM[4993]="*Yaṃpāvuso, bhikkhu dhammakāmo hoti … pe … uḷārapāmojjo.* **";
P_HTM[4994]="*Ayampi dhammo nāthakaraṇo. (1.6)**This too is a quality that serves as protector.*";
P_HTM[4995]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu santuṭṭho hoti itarītarehi cīvarapiṇḍapātasenāsanagilānappaccayabhesajjaparikkhārehi.**Furthermore, a mendicant is content with any kind of robes, alms-food, lodgings, and medicines and supplies for the sick.*";
P_HTM[4996]="*Yaṃpāvuso, bhikkhu santuṭṭho hoti … pe … parikkhārehi.* **";
P_HTM[4997]="*Ayampi dhammo nāthakaraṇo. (1.7)**This too is a quality that serves as protector.*";
P_HTM[4998]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu āraddhavīriyo viharati akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ pahānāya kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ upasampadāya, thāmavā daḷhaparakkamo anikkhittadhuro kusalesu dhammesu.**Furthermore, a mendicant lives with energy roused up for giving up unskillful qualities and embracing skillful qualities. They are strong, staunchly vigorous, not slacking off when it comes to developing skillful qualities.*";
P_HTM[4999]="*Yaṃpāvuso, bhikkhu āraddhavīriyo viharati … pe … anikkhittadhuro kusalesu dhammesu.* **";
P_HTM[5000]="*Ayampi dhammo nāthakaraṇo. (1.8)**This too is a quality that serves as protector.*";
P_HTM[5001]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu satimā hoti paramena satinepakkena samannāgato cirakatampi cirabhāsitampi saritā anussaritā.**Furthermore, a mendicant is mindful. They have utmost mindfulness and alertness, and can remember and recall what was said and done long ago.*";
P_HTM[5002]="*Yaṃpāvuso, bhikkhu satimā hoti … pe … saritā anussaritā.* **";
P_HTM[5003]="*Ayampi dhammo nāthakaraṇo. (1.9)**This too is a quality that serves as protector.*";
P_HTM[5004]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu paññavā hoti, udayatthagāminiyā paññāya samannāgato ariyāya nibbedhikāya sammādukkhakkhayagāminiyā.**Furthermore, a mendicant is wise. They have the wisdom of arising and passing away which is noble, penetrative, and leads to the complete ending of suffering.*";
P_HTM[5005]="*Yaṃpāvuso, bhikkhu paññavā hoti … pe … sammādukkhakkhayagāminiyā.* **";
P_HTM[5006]="*Ayampi dhammo nāthakaraṇo. (1.10)**This too is a quality that serves as protector.*";
P_HTM[5007]="*Dasa kasiṇāyatanāni.**Ten universal dimensions of meditation.*";
P_HTM[5008]="*Pathavīkasiṇameko sañjānāti, uddhaṃ adho tiriyaṃ advayaṃ appamāṇaṃ.**Someone perceives the meditation on universal earth above, below, across, non-dual and limitless.*";
P_HTM[5009]="*Āpokasiṇameko sañjānāti … pe …**They perceive the meditation on universal water …*";
P_HTM[5010]="*tejokasiṇameko sañjānāti …**the meditation on universal fire …*";
P_HTM[5011]="*vāyokasiṇameko sañjānāti …**the meditation on universal air …*";
P_HTM[5012]="*nīlakasiṇameko sañjānāti …**the meditation on universal blue …*";
P_HTM[5013]="*pītakasiṇameko sañjānāti …**the meditation on universal yellow …*";
P_HTM[5014]="*lohitakasiṇameko sañjānāti …**the meditation on universal red …*";
P_HTM[5015]="*odātakasiṇameko sañjānāti …**the meditation on universal white …*";
P_HTM[5016]="*ākāsakasiṇameko sañjānāti …**the meditation on universal space …*";
P_HTM[5017]="*viññāṇakasiṇameko sañjānāti, uddhaṃ adho tiriyaṃ advayaṃ appamāṇaṃ. (2)**They perceive the meditation on universal consciousness above, below, across, non-dual and limitless.*";
P_HTM[5018]="*Dasa akusalakammapathā—**Ten ways of doing unskillful deeds:*";
P_HTM[5019]="*pāṇātipāto, adinnādānaṃ, kāmesumicchācāro, musāvādo, pisuṇā vācā, pharusā vācā, samphappalāpo, abhijjhā, byāpādo, micchādiṭṭhi. (3)**killing living creatures, stealing, and sexual misconduct; speech that’s false, divisive, harsh, or nonsensical; covetousness, ill will, and wrong view.*";
P_HTM[5020]="*Dasa kusalakammapathā—**Ten ways of doing skillful deeds:*";
P_HTM[5021]="*pāṇātipātā veramaṇī, adinnādānā veramaṇī, kāmesumicchācārā veramaṇī, musāvādā veramaṇī, pisuṇāya vācāya veramaṇī, pharusāya vācāya veramaṇī, samphappalāpā veramaṇī, anabhijjhā, abyāpādo, sammādiṭṭhi. (4)**refraining from killing living creatures, stealing, and sexual misconduct; refraining from speech that’s false, divisive, harsh, or nonsensical; contentment, good will, and right view.*";
P_HTM[5022]="*Dasa ariyavāsā.**Ten noble abodes.*";
P_HTM[5023]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu pañcaṅgavippahīno hoti, chaḷaṅgasamannāgato, ekārakkho, caturāpasseno, paṇunnapaccekasacco, samavayasaṭṭhesano, anāvilasaṅkappo, passaddhakāyasaṅkhāro, suvimuttacitto, suvimuttapañño.**A mendicant has given up five factors, possesses six factors, has a single guard, has four supports, has eliminated idiosyncratic interpretations of the truth, has totally given up searching, has unsullied intentions, has stilled the physical process, and is well freed in mind and well freed by wisdom.*";
P_HTM[5024]="*Kathañcāvuso, bhikkhu pañcaṅgavippahīno hoti?**And how has a mendicant given up five factors?*";
P_HTM[5025]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhuno kāmacchando pahīno hoti, byāpādo pahīno hoti, thinamiddhaṃ pahīnaṃ hoti, uddhaccakukkuccaṃ pahīnaṃ hoti, vicikicchā pahīnā hoti.**It’s when a mendicant has given up sensual desire, ill will, dullness and drowsiness, restlessness and remorse, and doubt.*";
P_HTM[5026]="*Evaṃ kho, āvuso, bhikkhu pañcaṅgavippahīno hoti. (5.1)**That’s how a mendicant has given up five factors.*";
P_HTM[5027]="*Kathañcāvuso, bhikkhu chaḷaṅgasamannāgato hoti?**And how does a mendicant possess six factors?*";
P_HTM[5028]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu cakkhunā rūpaṃ disvā neva sumano hoti na dummano, upekkhako viharati sato sampajāno.**A mendicant, seeing a sight with their eyes, is neither happy nor sad. They remain equanimous, mindful and aware.*";
P_HTM[5029]="*Sotena saddaṃ sutvā … pe …**Hearing a sound with their ears … Smelling an odor with their nose … Tasting a flavor with their tongue … Feeling a touch with their body …*";
P_HTM[5030]="*manasā dhammaṃ viññāya neva sumano hoti na dummano, upekkhako viharati sato sampajāno.**Knowing a thought with their mind, they’re neither happy nor sad. They remain equanimous, mindful and aware.*";
P_HTM[5031]="*Evaṃ kho, āvuso, bhikkhu chaḷaṅgasamannāgato hoti. (5.2)**That’s how a mendicant possesses six factors.*";
P_HTM[5032]="*Kathañcāvuso, bhikkhu ekārakkho hoti?**And how does a mendicant have a single guard?*";
P_HTM[5033]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu satārakkhena cetasā samannāgato hoti.**It’s when a mendicant’s heart is guarded by mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[5034]="*Evaṃ kho, āvuso, bhikkhu ekārakkho hoti. (5.3)**That’s how a mendicant has a single guard.*";
P_HTM[5035]="*Kathañcāvuso, bhikkhu caturāpasseno hoti?**And how does a mendicant have four supports?*";
P_HTM[5036]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu saṅkhāyekaṃ paṭisevati, saṅkhāyekaṃ adhivāseti, saṅkhāyekaṃ parivajjeti, saṅkhāyekaṃ vinodeti.**After reflection, a mendicant uses some things, endures some things, avoids some things, and gets rid of some things.*";
P_HTM[5037]="*Evaṃ kho, āvuso, bhikkhu caturāpasseno hoti. (5.4)**That’s how a mendicant has four supports.*";
P_HTM[5038]="*Kathañcāvuso, bhikkhu paṇunnapaccekasacco hoti?**And how has a mendicant eliminated idiosyncratic interpretations of the truth?*";
P_HTM[5039]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhuno yāni tāni puthusamaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ puthupaccekasaccāni, sabbāni tāni nunnāni honti paṇunnāni cattāni vantāni muttāni pahīnāni paṭinissaṭṭhāni.**Different ascetics and brahmins have different idiosyncratic interpretations of the truth. A mendicant has dispelled, eliminated, thrown out, rejected, let go of, given up, and relinquished all these.*";
P_HTM[5040]="*Evaṃ kho, āvuso, bhikkhu paṇunnapaccekasacco hoti. (5.5)**That’s how a mendicant has eliminated idiosyncratic interpretations of the truth.*";
P_HTM[5041]="*Kathañcāvuso, bhikkhu samavayasaṭṭhesano hoti?**And how has a mendicant totally given up searching?*";
P_HTM[5042]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhuno kāmesanā pahīnā hoti, bhavesanā pahīnā hoti, brahmacariyesanā paṭippassaddhā.**It’s when they’ve given up searching for sensual pleasures, for continued existence, and for a spiritual path.*";
P_HTM[5043]="*Evaṃ kho, āvuso, bhikkhu samavayasaṭṭhesano hoti. (5.6)**That’s how a mendicant has totally given up searching.*";
P_HTM[5044]="*Kathañcāvuso, bhikkhu anāvilasaṅkappo hoti?**And how does a mendicant have unsullied intentions?*";
P_HTM[5045]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhuno kāmasaṅkappo pahīno hoti, byāpādasaṅkappo pahīno hoti, vihiṃsāsaṅkappo pahīno hoti.**It’s when they’ve given up sensual, malicious, and cruel intentions.*";
P_HTM[5046]="*Evaṃ kho, āvuso, bhikkhu anāvilasaṅkappo hoti. (5.7)**That’s how a mendicant has unsullied intentions.*";
P_HTM[5047]="*Kathañcāvuso, bhikkhu passaddhakāyasaṅkhāro hoti?**And how has a mendicant stilled the physical process?*";
P_HTM[5048]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu sukhassa ca pahānā dukkhassa ca pahānā pubbeva somanassadomanassānaṃ atthaṅgamā adukkhamasukhaṃ upekkhāsatipārisuddhiṃ catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**It’s when, giving up pleasure and pain, and ending former happiness and sadness, they enter and remain in the fourth absorption, without pleasure or pain, with pure equanimity and mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[5049]="*Evaṃ kho, āvuso, bhikkhu passaddhakāyasaṅkhāro hoti. (5.8)**That’s how a mendicant has stilled the physical process.*";
P_HTM[5050]="*Kathañcāvuso, bhikkhu suvimuttacitto hoti?**And how is a mendicant well freed in mind?*";
P_HTM[5051]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhuno rāgā cittaṃ vimuttaṃ hoti, dosā cittaṃ vimuttaṃ hoti, mohā cittaṃ vimuttaṃ hoti.**It’s when a mendicant’s mind is freed from greed, hate, and delusion.*";
P_HTM[5052]="*Evaṃ kho, āvuso, bhikkhu suvimuttacitto hoti. (5.9)**That’s how a mendicant is well freed in mind.*";
P_HTM[5053]="*Kathañcāvuso, bhikkhu suvimuttapañño hoti?**And how is a mendicant well freed by wisdom?*";
P_HTM[5054]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu ‘rāgo me pahīno ucchinnamūlo tālāvatthukato anabhāvaṅkato āyatiṃ anuppādadhammo’ti pajānāti.**It’s when a mendicant understands: ‘I’ve given up greed, hate, and delusion, cut them off at the root, made them like a palm stump, obliterated them, so they’re unable to arise in the future.’*";
P_HTM[5055]="*‘Doso me pahīno ucchinnamūlo tālāvatthukato anabhāvaṅkato āyatiṃ anuppādadhammo’ti pajānāti.* **";
P_HTM[5056]="*‘Moho me pahīno ucchinnamūlo tālāvatthukato anabhāvaṅkato āyatiṃ anuppādadhammo’ti pajānāti.* **";
P_HTM[5057]="*Evaṃ kho, āvuso, bhikkhu suvimuttapañño hoti. (5.10)**That’s how a mendicant’s mind is well freed by wisdom.*";
P_HTM[5058]="*Dasa asekkhā dhammā—**Ten qualities of an adept:*";
P_HTM[5059]="*asekkhā sammādiṭṭhi, asekkho sammāsaṅkappo, asekkhā sammāvācā, asekkho sammākammanto, asekkho sammāājīvo, asekkho sammāvāyāmo, asekkhā sammāsati, asekkho sammāsamādhi, asekkhaṃ sammāñāṇaṃ, asekkhā sammāvimutti. (6)**an adept’s right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, right immersion, right knowledge, and right freedom.*";
P_HTM[5060]="*Ime kho, āvuso, tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena dasa dhammā sammadakkhātā.**Reverends, these are the teachings grouped by ten that have been rightly explained by the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[5061]="*Tattha sabbeheva saṅgāyitabbaṃ na vivaditabbaṃ, yathayidaṃ brahmacariyaṃ addhaniyaṃ assa ciraṭṭhitikaṃ, tadassa bahujanahitāya bahujanasukhāya lokānukampāya atthāya hitāya sukhāya devamanussānan”ti.**You should all recite these in concert, without disputing, so that this spiritual path may last for a long time. That would be for the welfare and happiness of the people, for the benefit, welfare, and happiness of gods and humans.”*";
P_HTM[5062]="*Atha kho bhagavā uṭṭhahitvā āyasmantaṃ sāriputtaṃ āmantesi:**Then the Buddha got up and said to Venerable Sāriputta,*";
P_HTM[5063]="*“sādhu sādhu, sāriputta,**“Good, good, Sāriputta!*";
P_HTM[5064]="*sādhu kho tvaṃ, sāriputta, bhikkhūnaṃ saṅgītipariyāyaṃ abhāsī”ti.**It’s good that you’ve taught this exposition of the reciting in concert.”*";
P_HTM[5065]="*Idamavocāyasmā sāriputto, samanuñño satthā ahosi.**That is what Venerable Sāriputta said, and the teacher approved.*";
P_HTM[5066]="*Attamanā te bhikkhū āyasmato sāriputtassa bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, the mendicants were happy with what Sāriputta said.*";
P_HTM[5067]="*Saṅgītisuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5068]="*34. Dasuttarasutta  - Up to Ten * **";
P_HTM[5069]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[5070]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā campāyaṃ viharati gaggarāya pokkharaṇiyā tīre mahatā bhikkhusaṅghena saddhiṃ pañcamattehi bhikkhusatehi.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Campā on the banks of the Gaggarā Lotus Pond together with a large Saṅgha of five hundred mendicants.*";
P_HTM[5071]="*Tatra kho āyasmā sāriputto bhikkhū āmantesi:**There Sāriputta addressed the mendicants:*";
P_HTM[5072]="*“āvuso bhikkhave”ti.**“Reverends, mendicants!”*";
P_HTM[5073]="*“Āvuso”ti kho te bhikkhū āyasmato sāriputtassa paccassosuṃ.**“Reverend,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[5074]="*Āyasmā sāriputto etadavoca:**Sāriputta said this:*";
P_HTM[5075]="*“Dasuttaraṃ pavakkhāmi,**“I will relate the teachings*";
P_HTM[5076]="*dhammaṃ nibbānapattiyā;**up to ten for attaining extinguishment,*";
P_HTM[5077]="*Dukkhassantakiriyāya,**for making an end of suffering,*";
P_HTM[5078]="*sabbaganthappamocanaṃ.**the release from all ties.*";
P_HTM[5079]="*1. Eko dhammo**1. Groups of One*";
P_HTM[5080]="*Eko, āvuso, dhammo bahukāro, eko dhammo bhāvetabbo, eko dhammo pariññeyyo, eko dhammo pahātabbo, eko dhammo hānabhāgiyo, eko dhammo visesabhāgiyo, eko dhammo duppaṭivijjho, eko dhammo uppādetabbo, eko dhammo abhiññeyyo, eko dhammo sacchikātabbo.**Reverends, one thing is helpful, one thing should be developed, one thing should be completely understood, one thing should be given up, one thing makes things worse, one thing leads to distinction, one thing is hard to comprehend, one thing should be produced, one thing should be directly known, one thing should be realized.*";
P_HTM[5081]="*Katamo eko dhammo bahukāro?**What one thing is helpful?*";
P_HTM[5082]="*Appamādo kusalesu dhammesu.**Diligence in skillful qualities.*";
P_HTM[5083]="*Ayaṃ eko dhammo bahukāro. (1)* **";
P_HTM[5084]="*Katamo eko dhammo bhāvetabbo?**What one thing should be developed?*";
P_HTM[5085]="*Kāyagatāsati sātasahagatā.**Mindfulness of the body that is full of pleasure.*";
P_HTM[5086]="*Ayaṃ eko dhammo bhāvetabbo. (2)* **";
P_HTM[5087]="*Katamo eko dhammo pariññeyyo?**What one thing should be completely understood?*";
P_HTM[5088]="*Phasso sāsavo upādāniyo.**Contact, which is accompanied by defilements and is prone to being grasped.*";
P_HTM[5089]="*Ayaṃ eko dhammo pariññeyyo. (3)* **";
P_HTM[5090]="*Katamo eko dhammo pahātabbo?**What one thing should be given up?*";
P_HTM[5091]="*Asmimāno.**The conceit ‘I am’.*";
P_HTM[5092]="*Ayaṃ eko dhammo pahātabbo. (4)* **";
P_HTM[5093]="*Katamo eko dhammo hānabhāgiyo?**What one thing makes things worse?*";
P_HTM[5094]="*Ayoniso manasikāro.**Improper attention.*";
P_HTM[5095]="*Ayaṃ eko dhammo hānabhāgiyo. (5)* **";
P_HTM[5096]="*Katamo eko dhammo visesabhāgiyo?**What one thing leads to distinction?*";
P_HTM[5097]="*Yoniso manasikāro.**Proper attention.*";
P_HTM[5098]="*Ayaṃ eko dhammo visesabhāgiyo. (6)* **";
P_HTM[5099]="*Katamo eko dhammo duppaṭivijjho?**What one thing is hard to comprehend?*";
P_HTM[5100]="*Ānantariko cetosamādhi.**The heart’s immersion of immediate result.*";
P_HTM[5101]="*Ayaṃ eko dhammo duppaṭivijjho. (7)* **";
P_HTM[5102]="*Katamo eko dhammo uppādetabbo?**What one thing should be produced?*";
P_HTM[5103]="*Akuppaṃ ñāṇaṃ.**Unshakable knowledge.*";
P_HTM[5104]="*Ayaṃ eko dhammo uppādetabbo. (8)* **";
P_HTM[5105]="*Katamo eko dhammo abhiññeyyo?**What one thing should be directly known?*";
P_HTM[5106]="*Sabbe sattā āhāraṭṭhitikā.**All sentient beings are sustained by food.*";
P_HTM[5107]="*Ayaṃ eko dhammo abhiññeyyo. (9)* **";
P_HTM[5108]="*Katamo eko dhammo sacchikātabbo?**What one thing should be realized?*";
P_HTM[5109]="*Akuppā cetovimutti.**The unshakable heart’s release.*";
P_HTM[5110]="*Ayaṃ eko dhammo sacchikātabbo. (10)* **";
P_HTM[5111]="*Iti ime dasa dhammā bhūtā tacchā tathā avitathā anaññathā sammā tathāgatena abhisambuddhā.**So these ten things that are true, real, and accurate, not unreal, not otherwise were rightly awakened to by the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[5112]="*2. Dve dhammā**2. Groups of Two*";
P_HTM[5113]="*Dve dhammā bahukārā, dve dhammā bhāvetabbā, dve dhammā pariññeyyā, dve dhammā pahātabbā, dve dhammā hānabhāgiyā, dve dhammā visesabhāgiyā, dve dhammā duppaṭivijjhā, dve dhammā uppādetabbā, dve dhammā abhiññeyyā, dve dhammā sacchikātabbā.**Two things are helpful, two things should be developed, two things should be completely understood, two things should be given up, two things make things worse, two things lead to distinction, two things are hard to comprehend, two things should be produced, two things should be directly known, two things should be realized.*";
P_HTM[5114]="*Katame dve dhammā bahukārā?**What two things are helpful?*";
P_HTM[5115]="*Sati ca sampajaññañca.**Mindfulness and situational awareness.*";
P_HTM[5116]="*Ime dve dhammā bahukārā. (1)* **";
P_HTM[5117]="*Katame dve dhammā bhāvetabbā?**What two things should be developed?*";
P_HTM[5118]="*Samatho ca vipassanā ca.**Serenity and discernment.*";
P_HTM[5119]="*Ime dve dhammā bhāvetabbā. (2)* **";
P_HTM[5120]="*Katame dve dhammā pariññeyyā?**What two things should be completely understood?*";
P_HTM[5121]="*Nāmañca rūpañca.**Name and form.*";
P_HTM[5122]="*Ime dve dhammā pariññeyyā. (3)* **";
P_HTM[5123]="*Katame dve dhammā pahātabbā?**What two things should be given up?*";
P_HTM[5124]="*Avijjā ca bhavataṇhā ca.**Ignorance and craving for continued existence.*";
P_HTM[5125]="*Ime dve dhammā pahātabbā. (4)* **";
P_HTM[5126]="*Katame dve dhammā hānabhāgiyā?**What two things make things worse?*";
P_HTM[5127]="*Dovacassatā ca pāpamittatā ca.**Being hard to admonish and having bad friends.*";
P_HTM[5128]="*Ime dve dhammā hānabhāgiyā. (5)* **";
P_HTM[5129]="*Katame dve dhammā visesabhāgiyā?**What two things lead to distinction?*";
P_HTM[5130]="*Sovacassatā ca kalyāṇamittatā ca.**Being easy to admonish and having good friends.*";
P_HTM[5131]="*Ime dve dhammā visesabhāgiyā. (6)* **";
P_HTM[5132]="*Katame dve dhammā duppaṭivijjhā?**What two things are hard to comprehend?*";
P_HTM[5133]="*Yo ca hetu yo ca paccayo sattānaṃ saṅkilesāya, yo ca hetu yo ca paccayo sattānaṃ visuddhiyā.**What are the causes and conditions for the corruption of sentient beings, and what are the causes and conditions for the purification of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[5134]="*Ime dve dhammā duppaṭivijjhā. (7)* **";
P_HTM[5135]="*Katame dve dhammā uppādetabbā?**What two things should be produced?*";
P_HTM[5136]="*Dve ñāṇāni—**Two knowledges:*";
P_HTM[5137]="*khaye ñāṇaṃ, anuppāde ñāṇaṃ.**knowledge of ending, and knowledge of non-arising.*";
P_HTM[5138]="*Ime dve dhammā uppādetabbā. (8)* **";
P_HTM[5139]="*Katame dve dhammā abhiññeyyā?**What two things should be directly known?*";
P_HTM[5140]="*Dve dhātuyo—**Two elements:*";
P_HTM[5141]="*saṅkhatā ca dhātu asaṅkhatā ca dhātu.**the conditioned element and the unconditioned element.*";
P_HTM[5142]="*Ime dve dhammā abhiññeyyā. (9)* **";
P_HTM[5143]="*Katame dve dhammā sacchikātabbā?**What two things should be realized?*";
P_HTM[5144]="*Vijjā ca vimutti ca.**Knowledge and freedom.*";
P_HTM[5145]="*Ime dve dhammā sacchikātabbā. (10)* **";
P_HTM[5146]="*Iti ime vīsati dhammā bhūtā tacchā tathā avitathā anaññathā sammā tathāgatena abhisambuddhā.**So these twenty things that are true, real, and accurate, not unreal, not otherwise were rightly awakened to by the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[5147]="*3. Tayo dhammā**3. Groups of Three*";
P_HTM[5148]="*Tayo dhammā bahukārā, tayo dhammā bhāvetabbā … pe … tayo dhammā sacchikātabbā.**Three things are helpful, etc.*";
P_HTM[5149]="*Katame tayo dhammā bahukārā?**What three things are helpful?*";
P_HTM[5150]="*Sappurisasaṃsevo, saddhammassavanaṃ, dhammānudhammappaṭipatti.**Associating with good people, listening to the true teaching, and practicing in line with the teaching.*";
P_HTM[5151]="*Ime tayo dhammā bahukārā. (1)* **";
P_HTM[5152]="*Katame tayo dhammā bhāvetabbā?**What three things should be developed?*";
P_HTM[5153]="*Tayo samādhī—**Three kinds of immersion.*";
P_HTM[5154]="*savitakko savicāro samādhi, avitakko vicāramatto samādhi, avitakko avicāro samādhi.**Immersion with placing the mind and keeping it connected. Immersion without placing the mind, but just keeping it connected. Immersion without placing the mind or keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[5155]="*Ime tayo dhammā bhāvetabbā. (2)* **";
P_HTM[5156]="*Katame tayo dhammā pariññeyyā?**What three things should be completely understood?*";
P_HTM[5157]="*Tisso vedanā—**Three feelings:*";
P_HTM[5158]="*sukhā vedanā, dukkhā vedanā, adukkhamasukhā vedanā.**pleasant, painful, and neutral.*";
P_HTM[5159]="*Ime tayo dhammā pariññeyyā. (3)* **";
P_HTM[5160]="*Katame tayo dhammā pahātabbā?**What three things should be given up?*";
P_HTM[5161]="*Tisso taṇhā—**Three cravings:*";
P_HTM[5162]="*kāmataṇhā, bhavataṇhā, vibhavataṇhā.**craving for sensual pleasures, craving for continued existence, and craving to end existence.*";
P_HTM[5163]="*Ime tayo dhammā pahātabbā. (4)* **";
P_HTM[5164]="*Katame tayo dhammā hānabhāgiyā?**What three things make things worse?*";
P_HTM[5165]="*Tīṇi akusalamūlāni—**Three unskillful roots:*";
P_HTM[5166]="*lobho akusalamūlaṃ, doso akusalamūlaṃ, moho akusalamūlaṃ.**greed, hate, and delusion.*";
P_HTM[5167]="*Ime tayo dhammā hānabhāgiyā. (5)* **";
P_HTM[5168]="*Katame tayo dhammā visesabhāgiyā?**What three things lead to distinction?*";
P_HTM[5169]="*Tīṇi kusalamūlāni—**Three skillful roots:*";
P_HTM[5170]="*alobho kusalamūlaṃ, adoso kusalamūlaṃ, amoho kusalamūlaṃ.**non-greed, non-hate, and non-delusion.*";
P_HTM[5171]="*Ime tayo dhammā visesabhāgiyā. (6)* **";
P_HTM[5172]="*Katame tayo dhammā duppaṭivijjhā?**What three things are hard to comprehend?*";
P_HTM[5173]="*Tisso nissaraṇiyā dhātuyo—**Three elements of escape.*";
P_HTM[5174]="*kāmānametaṃ nissaraṇaṃ yadidaṃ nekkhammaṃ, rūpānametaṃ nissaraṇaṃ yadidaṃ arūpaṃ, yaṃ kho pana kiñci bhūtaṃ saṅkhataṃ paṭiccasamuppannaṃ, nirodho tassa nissaraṇaṃ.**Renunciation is the escape from sensual pleasures. The formless is the escape from form. Cessation is the escape from whatever is created, conditioned, and dependently originated.*";
P_HTM[5175]="*Ime tayo dhammā duppaṭivijjhā. (7)* **";
P_HTM[5176]="*Katame tayo dhammā uppādetabbā?**What three things should be produced?*";
P_HTM[5177]="*Tīṇi ñāṇāni—**Three knowledges:*";
P_HTM[5178]="*atītaṃse ñāṇaṃ, anāgataṃse ñāṇaṃ, paccuppannaṃse ñāṇaṃ.**regarding the past, future, and present.*";
P_HTM[5179]="*Ime tayo dhammā uppādetabbā. (8)* **";
P_HTM[5180]="*Katame tayo dhammā abhiññeyyā?**What three things should be directly known?*";
P_HTM[5181]="*Tisso dhātuyo—**Three elements:*";
P_HTM[5182]="*kāmadhātu, rūpadhātu, arūpadhātu.**sensuality, form, and formlessness.*";
P_HTM[5183]="*Ime tayo dhammā abhiññeyyā. (9)* **";
P_HTM[5184]="*Katame tayo dhammā sacchikātabbā?**What three things should be realized?*";
P_HTM[5185]="*Tisso vijjā—**Three knowledges:*";
P_HTM[5186]="*pubbenivāsānussatiñāṇaṃ vijjā, sattānaṃ cutūpapāte ñāṇaṃ vijjā, āsavānaṃ khaye ñāṇaṃ vijjā.**recollection of past lives, knowledge of the death and rebirth of sentient beings, and knowledge of the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[5187]="*Ime tayo dhammā sacchikātabbā. (10)* **";
P_HTM[5188]="*Iti ime tiṃsa dhammā bhūtā tacchā tathā avitathā anaññathā sammā tathāgatena abhisambuddhā.**So these thirty things that are true, real, and accurate, not unreal, not otherwise were rightly awakened to by the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[5189]="*4. Cattāro dhammā**4. Groups of Four*";
P_HTM[5190]="*Cattāro dhammā bahukārā, cattāro dhammā bhāvetabbā … pe … cattāro dhammā sacchikātabbā.**Four things are helpful, etc.*";
P_HTM[5191]="*Katame cattāro dhammā bahukārā?**What four things are helpful?*";
P_HTM[5192]="*Cattāri cakkāni—**Four situations:*";
P_HTM[5193]="*patirūpadesavāso, sappurisūpanissayo, attasammāpaṇidhi, pubbe ca katapuññatā.**living in a suitable region, relying on good people, being rightly resolved in oneself, and past merit.*";
P_HTM[5194]="*Ime cattāro dhammā bahukārā. (1)* **";
P_HTM[5195]="*Katame cattāro dhammā bhāvetabbā?**What four things should be developed?*";
P_HTM[5196]="*Cattāro satipaṭṭhānā—**The four kinds of mindfulness meditation.*";
P_HTM[5197]="*idhāvuso, bhikkhu kāye kāyānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**A mendicant meditates by observing an aspect of the body—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[5198]="*Vedanāsu … pe …**They meditate observing an aspect of feelings …*";
P_HTM[5199]="*citte …**mind …*";
P_HTM[5200]="*dhammesu dhammānupassī viharati ātāpī sampajāno satimā vineyya loke abhijjhādomanassaṃ.**principles—keen, aware, and mindful, rid of desire and aversion for the world.*";
P_HTM[5201]="*Ime cattāro dhammā bhāvetabbā. (2)* **";
P_HTM[5202]="*Katame cattāro dhammā pariññeyyā?**What four things should be completely understood?*";
P_HTM[5203]="*Cattāro āhārā—**Four foods:*";
P_HTM[5204]="*kabaḷīkāro āhāro oḷāriko vā sukhumo vā, phasso dutiyo, manosañcetanā tatiyā, viññāṇaṃ catutthaṃ.**solid food, whether coarse or fine; contact is the second, mental intention the third, and consciousness the fourth.*";
P_HTM[5205]="*Ime cattāro dhammā pariññeyyā. (3)* **";
P_HTM[5206]="*Katame cattāro dhammā pahātabbā?**What four things should be given up?*";
P_HTM[5207]="*Cattāro oghā—**Four floods:*";
P_HTM[5208]="*kāmogho, bhavogho, diṭṭhogho, avijjogho.**sensuality, desire for rebirth, views, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[5209]="*Ime cattāro dhammā pahātabbā. (4)* **";
P_HTM[5210]="*Katame cattāro dhammā hānabhāgiyā?**What four things make things worse?*";
P_HTM[5211]="*Cattāro yogā—**Four bonds:*";
P_HTM[5212]="*kāmayogo, bhavayogo, diṭṭhiyogo, avijjāyogo.**sensuality, desire for rebirth, views, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[5213]="*Ime cattāro dhammā hānabhāgiyā. (5)* **";
P_HTM[5214]="*Katame cattāro dhammā visesabhāgiyā?**What four things lead to distinction?*";
P_HTM[5215]="*Cattāro visaṃyogā—**Four kinds of detachment:*";
P_HTM[5216]="*kāmayogavisaṃyogo, bhavayogavisaṃyogo, diṭṭhiyogavisaṃyogo, avijjāyogavisaṃyogo.**detachment from the bonds of sensuality, desire for rebirth, views, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[5217]="*Ime cattāro dhammā visesabhāgiyā. (6)* **";
P_HTM[5218]="*Katame cattāro dhammā duppaṭivijjhā?**What four things are hard to comprehend?*";
P_HTM[5219]="*Cattāro samādhī—**Four kinds of immersion:*";
P_HTM[5220]="*hānabhāgiyo samādhi, ṭhitibhāgiyo samādhi, visesabhāgiyo samādhi, nibbedhabhāgiyo samādhi.**immersion liable to decline, stable immersion, immersion that leads to distinction, and immersion that leads to penetration.*";
P_HTM[5221]="*Ime cattāro dhammā duppaṭivijjhā. (7)* **";
P_HTM[5222]="*Katame cattāro dhammā uppādetabbā?**What four things should be produced?*";
P_HTM[5223]="*Cattāri ñāṇāni—**Four knowledges:*";
P_HTM[5224]="*dhamme ñāṇaṃ, anvaye ñāṇaṃ, pariye ñāṇaṃ, sammutiyā ñāṇaṃ.**knowledge of the present phenomena, inferential knowledge, knowledge of others’ minds, and conventional knowledge.*";
P_HTM[5225]="*Ime cattāro dhammā uppādetabbā. (8)* **";
P_HTM[5226]="*Katame cattāro dhammā abhiññeyyā?**What four things should be directly known?*";
P_HTM[5227]="*Cattāri ariyasaccāni—**The four noble truths:*";
P_HTM[5228]="*dukkhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ, dukkhasamudayaṃ ariyasaccaṃ, dukkhanirodhaṃ ariyasaccaṃ, dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā ariyasaccaṃ.**suffering, the origin of suffering, the cessation of suffering, and the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering.*";
P_HTM[5229]="*Ime cattāro dhammā abhiññeyyā. (9)* **";
P_HTM[5230]="*Katame cattāro dhammā sacchikātabbā?**What four things should be realized?*";
P_HTM[5231]="*Cattāri sāmaññaphalāni—**Four fruits of the ascetic life:*";
P_HTM[5232]="*sotāpattiphalaṃ, sakadāgāmiphalaṃ, anāgāmiphalaṃ, arahattaphalaṃ.**stream-entry, once-return, non-return, and perfection.*";
P_HTM[5233]="*Ime cattāro dhammā sacchikātabbā. (10)* **";
P_HTM[5234]="*Iti ime cattārīsadhammā bhūtā tacchā tathā avitathā anaññathā sammā tathāgatena abhisambuddhā.**So these forty things that are true, real, and accurate, not unreal, not otherwise were rightly awakened to by the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[5235]="*5. Pañca dhammā**5. Groups of Five*";
P_HTM[5236]="*Pañca dhammā bahukārā … pe … pañca dhammā sacchikātabbā.**Five things are helpful, etc.*";
P_HTM[5237]="*Katame pañca dhammā bahukārā?**What five things are helpful?*";
P_HTM[5238]="*Pañca padhāniyaṅgāni—**Five factors that support meditation.*";
P_HTM[5239]="*idhāvuso, bhikkhu saddho hoti, saddahati tathāgatassa bodhiṃ:**A mendicant has faith in the Realized One’s awakening:*";
P_HTM[5240]="*‘itipi so bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā’ti.**‘That Blessed One is perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.’*";
P_HTM[5241]="*Appābādho hoti appātaṅko samavepākiniyā gahaṇiyā samannāgato nātisītāya nāccuṇhāya majjhimāya padhānakkhamāya.**They are rarely ill or unwell. Their stomach digests well, being neither too hot nor too cold, but just right, and fit for meditation.*";
P_HTM[5242]="*Asaṭho hoti amāyāvī yathābhūtamattānaṃ āvīkattā satthari vā viññūsu vā sabrahmacārīsu.**They’re not devious or deceitful. They reveal themselves honestly to the Teacher or sensible spiritual companions.*";
P_HTM[5243]="*Āraddhavīriyo viharati akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ pahānāya, kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ upasampadāya, thāmavā daḷhaparakkamo anikkhittadhuro kusalesu dhammesu.**They live with energy roused up for giving up unskillful qualities and embracing skillful qualities. They’re strong, staunchly vigorous, not slacking off when it comes to developing skillful qualities.*";
P_HTM[5244]="*Paññavā hoti udayatthagāminiyā paññāya samannāgato ariyāya nibbedhikāya sammā dukkhakkhayagāminiyā.**They’re wise. They have the wisdom of arising and passing away which is noble, penetrative, and leads to the complete ending of suffering.*";
P_HTM[5245]="*Ime pañca dhammā bahukārā. (1)* **";
P_HTM[5246]="*Katame pañca dhammā bhāvetabbā?**What five things should be developed?*";
P_HTM[5247]="*Pañcaṅgiko sammāsamādhi—**Right immersion with five factors:*";
P_HTM[5248]="*pītipharaṇatā, sukhapharaṇatā, cetopharaṇatā, ālokapharaṇatā, paccavekkhaṇanimittaṃ.**pervaded with rapture, pervaded with pleasure, pervaded with mind, pervaded with light, and the foundation for reviewing.*";
P_HTM[5249]="*Ime pañca dhammā bhāvetabbā. (2)* **";
P_HTM[5250]="*Katame pañca dhammā pariññeyyā?**What five things should be completely understood?*";
P_HTM[5251]="*Pañcupādānakkhandhā—**Five grasping aggregates:*";
P_HTM[5252]="*rūpupādānakkhandho, vedanupādānakkhandho, saññupādānakkhandho, saṅkhārupādānakkhandho viññāṇupādānakkhandho.**form, feeling, perception, choices, and consciousness.*";
P_HTM[5253]="*Ime pañca dhammā pariññeyyā. (3)* **";
P_HTM[5254]="*Katame pañca dhammā pahātabbā?**What five things should be given up?*";
P_HTM[5255]="*Pañca nīvaraṇāni—**Five hindrances:*";
P_HTM[5256]="*kāmacchandanīvaraṇaṃ, byāpādanīvaraṇaṃ, thinamiddhanīvaraṇaṃ, uddhaccakukkuccanīvaraṇaṃ, vicikicchānīvaraṇaṃ.**sensual desire, ill will, dullness and drowsiness, restlessness and remorse, and doubt.*";
P_HTM[5257]="*Ime pañca dhammā pahātabbā. (4)* **";
P_HTM[5258]="*Katame pañca dhammā hānabhāgiyā?**What five things make things worse?*";
P_HTM[5259]="*Pañca cetokhilā—**Five kinds of emotional barrenness.*";
P_HTM[5260]="*idhāvuso, bhikkhu satthari kaṅkhati vicikicchati nādhimuccati na sampasīdati.**Firstly, a mendicant has doubts about the Teacher. They’re uncertain, undecided, and lacking confidence.*";
P_HTM[5261]="*Yo so, āvuso, bhikkhu satthari kaṅkhati vicikicchati nādhimuccati na sampasīdati, tassa cittaṃ na namati ātappāya anuyogāya sātaccāya padhānāya.**This being so, their mind doesn’t incline toward keenness, commitment, persistence, and striving.*";
P_HTM[5262]="*Yassa cittaṃ na namati ātappāya anuyogāya sātaccāya padhānāya.* **";
P_HTM[5263]="*Ayaṃ paṭhamo cetokhilo.**This is the first kind of emotional barrenness.*";
P_HTM[5264]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu dhamme kaṅkhati vicikicchati … pe …**Furthermore, a mendicant has doubts about the teaching …*";
P_HTM[5265]="*saṅghe kaṅkhati vicikicchati … pe …**the Saṅgha …*";
P_HTM[5266]="*sikkhāya kaṅkhati vicikicchati … pe …**the training …*";
P_HTM[5267]="*sabrahmacārīsu kupito hoti anattamano āhatacitto khilajāto, yo so, āvuso, bhikkhu sabrahmacārīsu kupito hoti anattamano āhatacitto khilajāto, tassa cittaṃ na namati ātappāya anuyogāya sātaccāya padhānāya.**A mendicant is angry and upset with their spiritual companions, resentful and closed off.*";
P_HTM[5268]="*Yassa cittaṃ na namati ātappāya anuyogāya sātaccāya padhānāya.**This being so, their mind doesn’t incline toward keenness, commitment, persistence, and striving.*";
P_HTM[5269]="*Ayaṃ pañcamo cetokhilo.**This is the fifth kind of emotional barrenness.*";
P_HTM[5270]="*Ime pañca dhammā hānabhāgiyā. (5)* **";
P_HTM[5271]="*Katame pañca dhammā visesabhāgiyā?**What five things lead to distinction?*";
P_HTM[5272]="*Pañcindriyāni—**Five faculties:*";
P_HTM[5273]="*saddhindriyaṃ, vīriyindriyaṃ, satindriyaṃ, samādhindriyaṃ, paññindriyaṃ.**faith, energy, mindfulness, immersion, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[5274]="*Ime pañca dhammā visesabhāgiyā. (6)* **";
P_HTM[5275]="*Katame pañca dhammā duppaṭivijjhā?**What five things are hard to comprehend?*";
P_HTM[5276]="*Pañca nissaraṇiyā dhātuyo—**Five elements of escape.*";
P_HTM[5277]="*idhāvuso, bhikkhuno kāme manasikaroto kāmesu cittaṃ na pakkhandati na pasīdati na santiṭṭhati na vimuccati.**A mendicant focuses on sensual pleasures, but their mind isn’t eager, confident, settled, and decided about them.*";
P_HTM[5278]="*Nekkhammaṃ kho panassa manasikaroto nekkhamme cittaṃ pakkhandati pasīdati santiṭṭhati vimuccati.**But when they focus on renunciation, their mind is eager, confident, settled, and decided about it.*";
P_HTM[5279]="*Tassa taṃ cittaṃ sugataṃ subhāvitaṃ suvuṭṭhitaṃ suvimuttaṃ visaṃyuttaṃ kāmehi.**Their mind is in a good state, well developed, well risen, well freed, and well detached from sensual pleasures.*";
P_HTM[5280]="*Ye ca kāmapaccayā uppajjanti āsavā vighātā pariḷāhā, mutto so tehi. Na so taṃ vedanaṃ vedeti.**They’re freed from the distressing and feverish defilements that arise because of sensual pleasures, so they don’t experience that kind of feeling.*";
P_HTM[5281]="*Idamakkhātaṃ kāmānaṃ nissaraṇaṃ. (7.1)**This is how the escape from sensual pleasures is explained.*";
P_HTM[5282]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhuno byāpādaṃ manasikaroto byāpāde cittaṃ na pakkhandati na pasīdati na santiṭṭhati na vimuccati.**Take another case where a mendicant focuses on ill will, but their mind isn’t eager …*";
P_HTM[5283]="*Abyāpādaṃ kho panassa manasikaroto abyāpāde cittaṃ pakkhandati pasīdati santiṭṭhati vimuccati.**But when they focus on good will, their mind is eager …*";
P_HTM[5284]="*Tassa taṃ cittaṃ sugataṃ subhāvitaṃ suvuṭṭhitaṃ suvimuttaṃ visaṃyuttaṃ byāpādena.**Their mind is in a good state … well detached from ill will.*";
P_HTM[5285]="*Ye ca byāpādapaccayā uppajjanti āsavā vighātā pariḷāhā, mutto so tehi. Na so taṃ vedanaṃ vedeti.**They’re freed from the distressing and feverish defilements that arise because of ill will, so they don’t experience that kind of feeling.*";
P_HTM[5286]="*Idamakkhātaṃ byāpādassa nissaraṇaṃ. (7.2)**This is how the escape from ill will is explained.*";
P_HTM[5287]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhuno vihesaṃ manasikaroto vihesāya cittaṃ na pakkhandati na pasīdati na santiṭṭhati na vimuccati.**Take another case where a mendicant focuses on harming, but their mind isn’t eager …*";
P_HTM[5288]="*Avihesaṃ kho panassa manasikaroto avihesāya cittaṃ pakkhandati pasīdati santiṭṭhati vimuccati.**But when they focus on compassion, their mind is eager …*";
P_HTM[5289]="*Tassa taṃ cittaṃ sugataṃ subhāvitaṃ suvuṭṭhitaṃ suvimuttaṃ visaṃyuttaṃ vihesāya.**Their mind is in a good state … well detached from harming.*";
P_HTM[5290]="*Ye ca vihesāpaccayā uppajjanti āsavā vighātā pariḷāhā, mutto so tehi. Na so taṃ vedanaṃ vedeti.**They’re freed from the distressing and feverish defilements that arise because of harming, so they don’t experience that kind of feeling.*";
P_HTM[5291]="*Idamakkhātaṃ vihesāya nissaraṇaṃ. (7.3)**This is how the escape from harming is explained.*";
P_HTM[5292]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhuno rūpe manasikaroto rūpesu cittaṃ na pakkhandati na pasīdati na santiṭṭhati na vimuccati.**Take another case where a mendicant focuses on form, but their mind isn’t eager …*";
P_HTM[5293]="*Arūpaṃ kho panassa manasikaroto arūpe cittaṃ pakkhandati pasīdati santiṭṭhati vimuccati.**But when they focus on the formless, their mind is eager …*";
P_HTM[5294]="*Tassa taṃ cittaṃ sugataṃ subhāvitaṃ suvuṭṭhitaṃ suvimuttaṃ visaṃyuttaṃ rūpehi.**Their mind is in a good state … well detached from forms.*";
P_HTM[5295]="*Ye ca rūpapaccayā uppajjanti āsavā vighātā pariḷāhā, mutto so tehi. Na so taṃ vedanaṃ vedeti.**They’re freed from the distressing and feverish defilements that arise because of form, so they don’t experience that kind of feeling.*";
P_HTM[5296]="*Idamakkhātaṃ rūpānaṃ nissaraṇaṃ. (7.4)**This is how the escape from forms is explained.*";
P_HTM[5297]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhuno sakkāyaṃ manasikaroto sakkāye cittaṃ na pakkhandati na pasīdati na santiṭṭhati na vimuccati.**Take a case where a mendicant focuses on identity, but their mind isn’t eager, confident, settled, and decided about it.*";
P_HTM[5298]="*Sakkāyanirodhaṃ kho panassa manasikaroto sakkāyanirodhe cittaṃ pakkhandati pasīdati santiṭṭhati vimuccati.**But when they focus on the ending of identity, their mind is eager, confident, settled, and decided about it.*";
P_HTM[5299]="*Tassa taṃ cittaṃ sugataṃ subhāvitaṃ suvuṭṭhitaṃ suvimuttaṃ visaṃyuttaṃ sakkāyena.**Their mind is in a good state, well developed, well risen, well freed, and well detached from identity.*";
P_HTM[5300]="*Ye ca sakkāyapaccayā uppajjanti āsavā vighātā pariḷāhā, mutto so tehi. Na so taṃ vedanaṃ vedeti.**They’re freed from the distressing and feverish defilements that arise because of identity, so they don’t experience that kind of feeling.*";
P_HTM[5301]="*Idamakkhātaṃ sakkāyassa nissaraṇaṃ.**This is how the escape from identity is explained.*";
P_HTM[5302]="*Ime pañca dhammā duppaṭivijjhā. (7.5)* **";
P_HTM[5303]="*Katame pañca dhammā uppādetabbā?**What five things should be produced?*";
P_HTM[5304]="*Pañca ñāṇiko sammāsamādhi:**Right immersion with five knowledges.*";
P_HTM[5305]="*‘ayaṃ samādhi paccuppannasukho ceva āyatiñca sukhavipāko’ti paccattaṃyeva ñāṇaṃ uppajjati.**The following knowledges arise for you personally: ‘This immersion is blissful now, and results in bliss in the future.’*";
P_HTM[5306]="*‘Ayaṃ samādhi ariyo nirāmiso’ti paccattaññeva ñāṇaṃ uppajjati.**‘This immersion is noble and spiritual.’*";
P_HTM[5307]="*‘Ayaṃ samādhi akāpurisasevito’ti paccattaṃyeva ñāṇaṃ uppajjati.**‘This immersion is not cultivated by sinners.’*";
P_HTM[5308]="*‘Ayaṃ samādhi santo paṇīto paṭippassaddhaladdho ekodibhāvādhigato, na sasaṅkhāraniggayhavāritagato’ti paccattaṃyeva ñāṇaṃ uppajjati.**‘This immersion is peaceful and sublime and tranquil and unified, not held in place by forceful suppression.’*";
P_HTM[5309]="*‘So kho panāhaṃ imaṃ samādhiṃ satova samāpajjāmi sato vuṭṭhahāmī’ti paccattaṃyeva ñāṇaṃ uppajjati.**‘I mindfully enter into and emerge from this immersion.’*";
P_HTM[5310]="*Ime pañca dhammā uppādetabbā. (8)* **";
P_HTM[5311]="*Katame pañca dhammā abhiññeyyā?**What five things should be directly known?*";
P_HTM[5312]="*Pañca vimuttāyatanāni—**Five opportunities for freedom.*";
P_HTM[5313]="*idhāvuso, bhikkhuno satthā dhammaṃ deseti aññataro vā garuṭṭhāniyo sabrahmacārī.**Firstly, the Teacher or a respected spiritual companion teaches Dhamma to a mendicant.*";
P_HTM[5314]="*Yathā yathā, āvuso, bhikkhuno satthā dhammaṃ deseti, aññataro vā garuṭṭhāniyo sabrahmacārī tathā tathā so tasmiṃ dhamme atthappaṭisaṃvedī ca hoti dhammapaṭisaṃvedī ca.**That mendicant feels inspired by the meaning and the teaching in that Dhamma, no matter how the Teacher or a respected spiritual companion teaches it.*";
P_HTM[5315]="*Tassa atthappaṭisaṃvedino dhammapaṭisaṃvedino pāmojjaṃ jāyati, pamuditassa pīti jāyati, pītimanassa kāyo passambhati, passaddhakāyo sukhaṃ vedeti, sukhino cittaṃ samādhiyati.**Feeling inspired, joy springs up. Being joyful, rapture springs up. When the mind is full of rapture, the body becomes tranquil. When the body is tranquil, one feels bliss. And when blissful, the mind becomes immersed.*";
P_HTM[5316]="*Idaṃ paṭhamaṃ vimuttāyatanaṃ. (9.1)**This is the first opportunity for freedom.*";
P_HTM[5317]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhuno na heva kho satthā dhammaṃ deseti, aññataro vā garuṭṭhāniyo sabrahmacārī, api ca kho yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ vitthārena paresaṃ deseti**Furthermore, it may be that neither the Teacher nor a respected spiritual companion teaches Dhamma to a mendicant. But the mendicant teaches Dhamma in detail to others as they learned and memorized it.*";
P_HTM[5318]="*yathā yathā, āvuso, bhikkhu yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ vitthārena paresaṃ deseti tathā tathā so tasmiṃ dhamme atthappaṭisaṃvedī ca hoti dhammapaṭisaṃvedī ca.**That mendicant feels inspired by the meaning and the teaching in that Dhamma, no matter how they teach it in detail to others as they learned and memorized it.*";
P_HTM[5319]="*Tassa atthappaṭisaṃvedino dhammapaṭisaṃvedino pāmojjaṃ jāyati, pamuditassa pīti jāyati, pītimanassa kāyo passambhati, passaddhakāyo sukhaṃ vedeti, sukhino cittaṃ samādhiyati.**Feeling inspired, joy springs up. Being joyful, rapture springs up. When the mind is full of rapture, the body becomes tranquil. When the body is tranquil, one feels bliss. And when blissful, the mind becomes immersed.*";
P_HTM[5320]="*Idaṃ dutiyaṃ vimuttāyatanaṃ. (9.2)**This is the second opportunity for freedom.*";
P_HTM[5321]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhuno na heva kho satthā dhammaṃ deseti, aññataro vā garuṭṭhāniyo sabrahmacārī, nāpi yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ vitthārena paresaṃ deseti. Api ca kho yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ vitthārena sajjhāyaṃ karoti.**Furthermore, it may be that neither the Teacher nor … the mendicant teaches Dhamma. But the mendicant recites the teaching in detail as they learned and memorized it.*";
P_HTM[5322]="*Yathā yathā, āvuso, bhikkhu yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ vitthārena sajjhāyaṃ karoti tathā tathā so tasmiṃ dhamme atthappaṭisaṃvedī ca hoti dhammapaṭisaṃvedī ca.**That mendicant feels inspired by the meaning and the teaching in that Dhamma, no matter how they recite it in detail as they learned and memorized it.*";
P_HTM[5323]="*Tassa atthappaṭisaṃvedino dhammapaṭisaṃvedino pāmojjaṃ jāyati, pamuditassa pīti jāyati, pītimanassa kāyo passambhati, passaddhakāyo sukhaṃ vedeti, sukhino cittaṃ samādhiyati.**Feeling inspired, joy springs up. Being joyful, rapture springs up. When the mind is full of rapture, the body becomes tranquil. When the body is tranquil, one feels bliss. And when blissful, the mind becomes immersed.*";
P_HTM[5324]="*Idaṃ tatiyaṃ vimuttāyatanaṃ. (9.3)**This is the third opportunity for freedom.*";
P_HTM[5325]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhuno na heva kho satthā dhammaṃ deseti, aññataro vā garuṭṭhāniyo sabrahmacārī, nāpi yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ vitthārena paresaṃ deseti, nāpi yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ vitthārena sajjhāyaṃ karoti.**Furthermore, it may be that neither the Teacher nor … the mendicant teaches Dhamma … nor does the mendicant recite the teaching.*";
P_HTM[5326]="*Api ca kho yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ cetasā anuvitakketi anuvicāreti manasānupekkhati.**But the mendicant thinks about and considers the teaching in their heart, examining it with the mind as they learned and memorized it.*";
P_HTM[5327]="*Yathā yathā, āvuso, bhikkhu yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ cetasā anuvitakketi anuvicāreti manasānupekkhati tathā tathā so tasmiṃ dhamme atthappaṭisaṃvedī ca hoti dhammapaṭisaṃvedī ca.**That mendicant feels inspired by the meaning and the teaching in that Dhamma, no matter how they think about and consider it in their heart, examining it with the mind as they learned and memorized it.*";
P_HTM[5328]="*Tassa atthappaṭisaṃvedino dhammapaṭisaṃvedino pāmojjaṃ jāyati, pamuditassa pīti jāyati, pītimanassa kāyo passambhati, passaddhakāyo sukhaṃ vedeti, sukhino cittaṃ samādhiyati.**Feeling inspired, joy springs up. Being joyful, rapture springs up. When the mind is full of rapture, the body becomes tranquil. When the body is tranquil, one feels bliss. And when blissful, the mind becomes immersed.*";
P_HTM[5329]="*Idaṃ catutthaṃ vimuttāyatanaṃ. (9.4)**This is the fourth opportunity for freedom.*";
P_HTM[5330]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhuno na heva kho satthā dhammaṃ deseti, aññataro vā garuṭṭhāniyo sabrahmacārī, nāpi yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ vitthārena paresaṃ deseti, nāpi yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ vitthārena sajjhāyaṃ karoti, nāpi yathāsutaṃ yathāpariyattaṃ dhammaṃ cetasā anuvitakketi anuvicāreti manasānupekkhati;**Furthermore, it may be that neither the Teacher nor … the mendicant teaches Dhamma … nor does the mendicant recite the teaching … or think about it.*";
P_HTM[5331]="*api ca khvassa aññataraṃ samādhinimittaṃ suggahitaṃ hoti sumanasikataṃ sūpadhāritaṃ suppaṭividdhaṃ paññāya.**But a meditation subject as a foundation of immersion is properly grasped, attended, borne in mind, and comprehended with wisdom.*";
P_HTM[5332]="*Yathā yathā, āvuso, bhikkhuno aññataraṃ samādhinimittaṃ suggahitaṃ hoti sumanasikataṃ sūpadhāritaṃ suppaṭividdhaṃ paññāya tathā tathā so tasmiṃ dhamme atthappaṭisaṃvedī ca hoti dhammappaṭisaṃvedī ca.**That mendicant feels inspired by the meaning and the teaching in that Dhamma, no matter how a meditation subject as a foundation of immersion is properly grasped, attended, borne in mind, and comprehended with wisdom.*";
P_HTM[5333]="*Tassa atthappaṭisaṃvedino dhammappaṭisaṃvedino pāmojjaṃ jāyati, pamuditassa pīti jāyati, pītimanassa kāyo passambhati, passaddhakāyo sukhaṃ vedeti, sukhino cittaṃ samādhiyati.**Feeling inspired, joy springs up. Being joyful, rapture springs up. When the mind is full of rapture, the body becomes tranquil. When the body is tranquil, one feels bliss. And when blissful, the mind becomes immersed.*";
P_HTM[5334]="*Idaṃ pañcamaṃ vimuttāyatanaṃ.**This is the fifth opportunity for freedom.*";
P_HTM[5335]="*Ime pañca dhammā abhiññeyyā. (9.5)* **";
P_HTM[5336]="*Katame pañca dhammā sacchikātabbā?**What five things should be realized?*";
P_HTM[5337]="*Pañca dhammakkhandhā—**Five spectrums of the teaching:*";
P_HTM[5338]="*sīlakkhandho, samādhikkhandho, paññākkhandho, vimuttikkhandho, vimuttiñāṇadassanakkhandho.**ethics, immersion, wisdom, freedom, and knowledge and vision of freedom.*";
P_HTM[5339]="*Ime pañca dhammā sacchikātabbā. (10)* **";
P_HTM[5340]="*Iti ime paññāsa dhammā bhūtā tacchā tathā avitathā anaññathā sammā tathāgatena abhisambuddhā.**So these fifty things that are true, real, and accurate, not unreal, not otherwise were rightly awakened to by the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[5341]="*6. Cha dhammā**6. Groups of Six*";
P_HTM[5342]="*Cha dhammā bahukārā … pe … cha dhammā sacchikātabbā.**Six things are helpful, etc.*";
P_HTM[5343]="*Katame cha dhammā bahukārā?**What six things are helpful?*";
P_HTM[5344]="*Cha sāraṇīyā dhammā.**Six warm-hearted qualities.*";
P_HTM[5345]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhuno mettaṃ kāyakammaṃ paccupaṭṭhitaṃ hoti sabrahmacārīsu āvi ceva raho ca,**Firstly, a mendicant consistently treats their spiritual companions with bodily kindness, both in public and in private.*";
P_HTM[5346]="*ayampi dhammo sāraṇīyo piyakaraṇo garukaraṇo saṅgahāya avivādāya sāmaggiyā ekībhāvāya saṃvattati. (1.1)**This warm-hearted quality makes for fondness and respect, conducing to inclusion, harmony, and unity, without quarreling.*";
P_HTM[5347]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhuno mettaṃ vacīkammaṃ … pe … ekībhāvāya saṃvattati. (1.2)**Furthermore, a mendicant consistently treats their spiritual companions with verbal kindness.*";
P_HTM[5348]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhuno mettaṃ manokammaṃ … pe … ekībhāvāya saṃvattati. (1.3)**Furthermore, a mendicant consistently treats their spiritual companions with mental kindness.*";
P_HTM[5349]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu ye te lābhā dhammikā dhammaladdhā antamaso pattapariyāpannamattampi, tathārūpehi lābhehi appaṭivibhattabhogī hoti sīlavantehi sabrahmacārīhi sādhāraṇabhogī, ayampi dhammo sāraṇīyo … pe … ekībhāvāya saṃvattati. (1.4)**Furthermore, a mendicant shares without reservation any material possessions they have gained by legitimate means, even the food placed in the alms-bowl, using them in common with their ethical spiritual companions.*";
P_HTM[5350]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu, yāni tāni sīlāni akhaṇḍāni acchiddāni asabalāni akammāsāni bhujissāni viññuppasatthāni aparāmaṭṭhāni samādhisaṃvattanikāni, tathārūpesu sīlesu sīlasāmaññagato viharati sabrahmacārīhi āvi ceva raho ca, ayampi dhammo sāraṇīyo … pe … ekībhāvāya saṃvattati. (1.5)**Furthermore, a mendicant lives according to the precepts shared with their spiritual companions, both in public and in private. Those precepts are unbroken, impeccable, spotless, and unmarred, liberating, praised by sensible people, not mistaken, and leading to immersion.*";
P_HTM[5351]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu yāyaṃ diṭṭhi ariyā niyyānikā niyyāti takkarassa sammā dukkhakkhayāya, tathārūpāya diṭṭhiyā diṭṭhi sāmaññagato viharati sabrahmacārīhi āvi ceva raho ca,**Furthermore, a mendicant lives according to the view shared with their spiritual companions, both in public and in private. That view is noble and emancipating, and leads one who practices it to the complete ending of suffering.*";
P_HTM[5352]="*ayampi dhammo sāraṇīyo piyakaraṇo garukaraṇo, saṅgahāya avivādāya sāmaggiyā ekībhāvāya saṃvattati.**This warm-hearted quality makes for fondness and respect, conducing to inclusion, harmony, and unity, without quarreling.*";
P_HTM[5353]="*Ime cha dhammā bahukārā. (1.6)* **";
P_HTM[5354]="*Katame cha dhammā bhāvetabbā?**What six things should be developed?*";
P_HTM[5355]="*Cha anussatiṭṭhānāni—**Six recollections:*";
P_HTM[5356]="*buddhānussati, dhammānussati, saṅghānussati, sīlānussati, cāgānussati, devatānussati.**the recollection of the Buddha, the teaching, the Saṅgha, ethics, generosity, and the deities.*";
P_HTM[5357]="*Ime cha dhammā bhāvetabbā. (2)* **";
P_HTM[5358]="*Katame cha dhammā pariññeyyā?**What six things should be completely understood?*";
P_HTM[5359]="*Cha ajjhattikāni āyatanāni—**Six interior sense fields:*";
P_HTM[5360]="*cakkhāyatanaṃ, sotāyatanaṃ, ghānāyatanaṃ, jivhāyatanaṃ, kāyāyatanaṃ, manāyatanaṃ.**eye, ear, nose, tongue, body, and mind.*";
P_HTM[5361]="*Ime cha dhammā pariññeyyā. (3)* **";
P_HTM[5362]="*Katame cha dhammā pahātabbā?**What six things should be given up?*";
P_HTM[5363]="*Cha taṇhākāyā—**Six classes of craving:*";
P_HTM[5364]="*rūpataṇhā, saddataṇhā, gandhataṇhā, rasataṇhā, phoṭṭhabbataṇhā, dhammataṇhā.**craving for sights, sounds, smells, tastes, touches, and thoughts.*";
P_HTM[5365]="*Ime cha dhammā pahātabbā. (4)* **";
P_HTM[5366]="*Katame cha dhammā hānabhāgiyā?**What six things make things worse?*";
P_HTM[5367]="*Cha agāravā—**Six kinds of disrespect.*";
P_HTM[5368]="*idhāvuso, bhikkhu satthari agāravo viharati appatisso. Dhamme … pe … saṅghe … sikkhāya … appamāde … paṭisanthāre agāravo viharati appatisso.**A mendicant lacks respect and reverence for the Teacher, the teaching, and the Saṅgha, the training, diligence, and hospitality.*";
P_HTM[5369]="*Ime cha dhammā hānabhāgiyā. (5)* **";
P_HTM[5370]="*Katame cha dhammā visesabhāgiyā?**What six things lead to distinction?*";
P_HTM[5371]="*Cha gāravā—**Six kinds of respect.*";
P_HTM[5372]="*idhāvuso, bhikkhu satthari sagāravo viharati sappatisso. Dhamme … pe … saṅghe … sikkhāya … appamāde … paṭisanthāre sagāravo viharati sappatisso.**A mendicant has respect and reverence for the Teacher, the teaching, and the Saṅgha, the training, diligence, and hospitality.*";
P_HTM[5373]="*Ime cha dhammā visesabhāgiyā. (6)* **";
P_HTM[5374]="*Katame cha dhammā duppaṭivijjhā?**What six things are hard to comprehend?*";
P_HTM[5375]="*Cha nissaraṇiyā dhātuyo—**Six elements of escape.*";
P_HTM[5376]="*idhāvuso, bhikkhu evaṃ vadeyya:**Take a mendicant who says:*";
P_HTM[5377]="*‘mettā hi kho me, cetovimutti bhāvitā bahulīkatā yānīkatā vatthukatā anuṭṭhitā paricitā susamāraddhā,**‘I’ve developed the heart’s release by love. I’ve cultivated it, made it my vehicle and my basis, kept it up, consolidated it, and properly implemented it.*";
P_HTM[5378]="*atha ca pana me byāpādo cittaṃ pariyādāya tiṭṭhatī’ti.**Yet somehow ill will still occupies my mind.’*";
P_HTM[5379]="*So ‘mā hevan’tissa vacanīyo ‘māyasmā evaṃ avaca, mā bhagavantaṃ abbhācikkhi. Na hi sādhu bhagavato abbhakkhānaṃ, na hi bhagavā evaṃ vadeyya.**They should be told, ‘Not so, venerable! Don’t say that. Don’t misrepresent the Buddha, for misrepresentation of the Buddha is not good. And the Buddha would not say that.*";
P_HTM[5380]="*Aṭṭhānametaṃ āvuso anavakāso yaṃ mettāya cetovimuttiyā bhāvitāya bahulīkatāya yānīkatāya vatthukatāya anuṭṭhitāya paricitāya susamāraddhāya.**It’s impossible, reverend, it cannot happen that the heart’s release by love has been developed and properly implemented,*";
P_HTM[5381]="*Atha ca panassa byāpādo cittaṃ pariyādāya ṭhassatīti, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**yet somehow ill will still occupies the mind.*";
P_HTM[5382]="*Nissaraṇaṃ hetaṃ, āvuso, byāpādassa, yadidaṃ mettācetovimuttī’ti. (7.1)**For it is the heart’s release by love that is the escape from ill will.’*";
P_HTM[5383]="*Idha panāvuso, bhikkhu evaṃ vadeyya:**Take another mendicant who says:*";
P_HTM[5384]="*‘karuṇā hi kho me cetovimutti bhāvitā bahulīkatā yānīkatā vatthukatā anuṭṭhitā paricitā susamāraddhā.**‘I’ve developed the heart’s release by compassion. I’ve cultivated it, made it my vehicle and my basis, kept it up, consolidated it, and properly implemented it.*";
P_HTM[5385]="*Atha ca pana me vihesā cittaṃ pariyādāya tiṭṭhatī’ti.**Yet somehow the thought of harming still occupies my mind.’*";
P_HTM[5386]="*So: ‘mā hevan’tissa vacanīyo, ‘māyasmā evaṃ avaca, mā bhagavantaṃ abbhācikkhi … pe …**They should be told, ‘Not so, venerable! …*";
P_HTM[5387]="*nissaraṇaṃ hetaṃ, āvuso, vihesāya, yadidaṃ karuṇācetovimuttī’ti. (7.2)**For it is the heart’s release by compassion that is the escape from thoughts of harming.’*";
P_HTM[5388]="*Idha panāvuso, bhikkhu evaṃ vadeyya:**Take another mendicant who says:*";
P_HTM[5389]="*‘muditā hi kho me cetovimutti bhāvitā … pe …**‘I’ve developed the heart’s release by rejoicing. …*";
P_HTM[5390]="*atha ca pana me arati cittaṃ pariyādāya tiṭṭhatī’ti.**Yet somehow negativity still occupies my mind.’*";
P_HTM[5391]="*So: ‘mā hevan’tissa vacanīyo ‘māyasmā evaṃ avaca … pe …**They should be told, ‘Not so, venerable! …*";
P_HTM[5392]="*nissaraṇaṃ hetaṃ, āvuso, aratiyā, yadidaṃ muditācetovimuttī’ti. (7.3)**For it is the heart’s release by rejoicing that is the escape from negativity.’*";
P_HTM[5393]="*Idha panāvuso, bhikkhu evaṃ vadeyya:**Take another mendicant who says:*";
P_HTM[5394]="*‘upekkhā hi kho me cetovimutti bhāvitā … pe …**‘I’ve developed the heart’s release by equanimity. …*";
P_HTM[5395]="*atha ca pana me rāgo cittaṃ pariyādāya tiṭṭhatī’ti.**Yet somehow desire still occupies my mind.’*";
P_HTM[5396]="*So: ‘mā hevan’tissa vacanīyo ‘māyasmā evaṃ avaca … pe …**They should be told, ‘Not so, venerable! …*";
P_HTM[5397]="*nissaraṇaṃ hetaṃ, āvuso, rāgassa yadidaṃ upekkhācetovimuttī’ti. (7.4)**For it is the heart’s release by equanimity that is the escape from desire.’*";
P_HTM[5398]="*Idha panāvuso, bhikkhu evaṃ vadeyya:**Take another mendicant who says:*";
P_HTM[5399]="*‘animittā hi kho me cetovimutti bhāvitā … pe …**‘I’ve developed the signless heart’s release. …*";
P_HTM[5400]="*atha ca pana me nimittānusāri viññāṇaṃ hotī’ti.**Yet somehow my consciousness still follows after signs.’*";
P_HTM[5401]="*So: ‘mā hevan’tissa vacanīyo ‘māyasmā evaṃ avaca … pe …**They should be told, ‘Not so, venerable! …*";
P_HTM[5402]="*nissaraṇaṃ hetaṃ, āvuso, sabbanimittānaṃ yadidaṃ animittā cetovimuttī’ti. (7.5)**For it is the signless release of the heart that is the escape from all signs.’*";
P_HTM[5403]="*Idha panāvuso, bhikkhu evaṃ vadeyya:**Take another mendicant who says:*";
P_HTM[5404]="*‘asmīti kho me vigataṃ, ayamahamasmīti na samanupassāmi,**‘I’m rid of the conceit “I am”. And I don’t regard anything as “I am this”.*";
P_HTM[5405]="*atha ca pana me vicikicchākathaṅkathāsallaṃ cittaṃ pariyādāya tiṭṭhatī’ti.**Yet somehow the dart of doubt and indecision still occupies my mind.’*";
P_HTM[5406]="*So: ‘mā hevan’tissa vacanīyo ‘māyasmā evaṃ avaca, mā bhagavantaṃ abbhācikkhi, na hi sādhu bhagavato abbhakkhānaṃ, na hi bhagavā evaṃ vadeyya.**They should be told, ‘Not so, venerable! Don’t say that. Don’t misrepresent the Buddha, for misrepresentation of the Buddha is not good. And the Buddha would not say that.*";
P_HTM[5407]="*Aṭṭhānametaṃ, āvuso, anavakāso yaṃ asmīti vigate ayamahamasmīti asamanupassato.**It’s impossible, reverend, it cannot happen that the conceit “I am” has been done away with, and nothing is regarded as “I am this”,*";
P_HTM[5408]="*Atha ca panassa vicikicchākathaṅkathāsallaṃ cittaṃ pariyādāya ṭhassati, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**yet somehow the dart of doubt and indecision still occupy the mind.*";
P_HTM[5409]="*Nissaraṇaṃ hetaṃ, āvuso, vicikicchākathaṅkathāsallassa, yadidaṃ asmimānasamugghāto’ti.**For it is the uprooting of the conceit “I am” that is the escape from the dart of doubt and indecision.’*";
P_HTM[5410]="*Ime cha dhammā duppaṭivijjhā. (7.6)* **";
P_HTM[5411]="*Katame cha dhammā uppādetabbā?**What six things should be produced?*";
P_HTM[5412]="*Cha satatavihārā.**Six consistent responses.*";
P_HTM[5413]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu cakkhunā rūpaṃ disvā neva sumano hoti na dummano, upekkhako viharati sato sampajāno.**A mendicant, seeing a sight with their eyes, is neither happy nor sad. They remain equanimous, mindful and aware.*";
P_HTM[5414]="*Sotena saddaṃ sutvā … pe …**Hearing a sound with their ears …*";
P_HTM[5415]="*ghānena gandhaṃ ghāyitvā …**Smelling an odor with their nose …*";
P_HTM[5416]="*jivhāya rasaṃ sāyitvā …**Tasting a flavor with their tongue …*";
P_HTM[5417]="*kāyena phoṭṭhabbaṃ phusitvā …**Feeling a touch with their body …*";
P_HTM[5418]="*manasā dhammaṃ viññāya neva sumano hoti na dummano, upekkhako viharati sato sampajāno.**Knowing a thought with their mind, they’re neither happy nor sad. They remain equanimous, mindful and aware.*";
P_HTM[5419]="*Ime cha dhammā uppādetabbā. (8)* **";
P_HTM[5420]="*Katame cha dhammā abhiññeyyā?**What six things should be directly known?*";
P_HTM[5421]="*Cha anuttariyāni—**Six unsurpassable things:*";
P_HTM[5422]="*dassanānuttariyaṃ, savanānuttariyaṃ, lābhānuttariyaṃ, sikkhānuttariyaṃ, pāricariyānuttariyaṃ, anussatānuttariyaṃ.**the unsurpassable seeing, listening, acquisition, training, service, and recollection.*";
P_HTM[5423]="*Ime cha dhammā abhiññeyyā. (9)* **";
P_HTM[5424]="*Katame cha dhammā sacchikātabbā?**What six things should be realized?*";
P_HTM[5425]="*Cha abhiññā—**Six direct knowledges.*";
P_HTM[5426]="*idhāvuso, bhikkhu anekavihitaṃ iddhividhaṃ paccanubhoti—ekopi hutvā bahudhā hoti, bahudhāpi hutvā eko hoti; āvibhāvaṃ tirobhāvaṃ; tirokuṭṭaṃ tiropākāraṃ tiropabbataṃ asajjamāno gacchati seyyathāpi ākāse; pathaviyāpi ummujjanimujjaṃ karoti seyyathāpi udake; udakepi abhijjamāne gacchati seyyathāpi pathaviyaṃ; ākāsepi pallaṅkena kamati seyyathāpi pakkhī sakuṇo; imepi candimasūriye evaṃmahiddhike evaṃmahānubhāve pāṇinā parāmasati parimajjati; yāva brahmalokāpi kāyena vasaṃ vatteti. (10.1)**A mendicant wields the many kinds of psychic power: multiplying themselves and becoming one again; appearing and disappearing; going unimpeded through a wall, a rampart, or a mountain as if through space; diving in and out of the earth as if it were water; walking on water as if it were earth; flying cross-legged through the sky like a bird; touching and stroking with the hand the sun and moon, so mighty and powerful; controlling the body as far as the Brahmā realm.*";
P_HTM[5427]="*Dibbāya sotadhātuyā visuddhāya atikkantamānusikāya ubho sadde suṇāti dibbe ca mānuse ca, ye dūre santike ca. (10.2)**With clairaudience that is purified and superhuman, they hear both kinds of sounds, human and divine, whether near or far.*";
P_HTM[5428]="*Parasattānaṃ parapuggalānaṃ cetasā ceto paricca pajānāti, sarāgaṃ vā cittaṃ sarāgaṃ cittanti pajānāti … pe … avimuttaṃ vā cittaṃ avimuttaṃ cittanti pajānāti. (10.3)**They understand the minds of other beings and individuals, having comprehended them with their own mind.*";
P_HTM[5429]="*So anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati, seyyathidaṃ—ekampi jātiṃ … pe … iti sākāraṃ sauddesaṃ anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati. (10.4)**They recollect many kinds of past lives, with features and details.*";
P_HTM[5430]="*Dibbena cakkhunā visuddhena atikkantamānusakena satte passati cavamāne upapajjamāne hīne paṇīte suvaṇṇe dubbaṇṇe sugate duggate yathākammūpage satte pajānāti … pe … (10.5)**With clairvoyance that is purified and superhuman, they see sentient beings passing away and being reborn—inferior and superior, beautiful and ugly, in a good place or a bad place. They understand how sentient beings are reborn according to their deeds.*";
P_HTM[5431]="*Āsavānaṃ khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharati.**They realize the undefiled freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom in this very life. And they live having realized it with their own insight due to the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[5432]="*Ime cha dhammā sacchikātabbā. (10.6)* **";
P_HTM[5433]="*Iti ime saṭṭhi dhammā bhūtā tacchā tathā avitathā anaññathā sammā tathāgatena abhisambuddhā.**So these sixty things that are true, real, and accurate, not unreal, not otherwise were rightly awakened to by the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[5434]="*7. Satta dhammā**7. Groups of Seven*";
P_HTM[5435]="*Satta dhammā bahukārā … pe … satta dhammā sacchikātabbā.**Seven things are helpful, etc.*";
P_HTM[5436]="*Katame satta dhammā bahukārā?**What seven things are helpful?*";
P_HTM[5437]="*Satta ariyadhanāni—**Seven kinds of wealth of noble ones:*";
P_HTM[5438]="*saddhādhanaṃ, sīladhanaṃ, hiridhanaṃ, ottappadhanaṃ, sutadhanaṃ, cāgadhanaṃ, paññādhanaṃ.**the wealth of faith, ethical conduct, conscience, prudence, learning, generosity, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[5439]="*Ime satta dhammā bahukārā. (1)* **";
P_HTM[5440]="*Katame satta dhammā bhāvetabbā?**What seven things should be developed?*";
P_HTM[5441]="*Satta sambojjhaṅgā—**Seven awakening factors:*";
P_HTM[5442]="*satisambojjhaṅgo, dhammavicayasambojjhaṅgo, vīriyasambojjhaṅgo, pītisambojjhaṅgo, passaddhisambojjhaṅgo, samādhisambojjhaṅgo, upekkhāsambojjhaṅgo.**mindfulness, investigation of principles, energy, rapture, tranquility, immersion, and equanimity.*";
P_HTM[5443]="*Ime satta dhammā bhāvetabbā. (2)* **";
P_HTM[5444]="*Katame satta dhammā pariññeyyā?**What seven things should be completely understood?*";
P_HTM[5445]="*Satta viññāṇaṭṭhitiyo—**Seven planes of consciousness.*";
P_HTM[5446]="*santāvuso, sattā nānattakāyā nānattasaññino, seyyathāpi manussā ekacce ca devā ekacce ca vinipātikā.**There are sentient beings that are diverse in body and diverse in perception, such as human beings, some gods, and some beings in the underworld.*";
P_HTM[5447]="*Ayaṃ paṭhamā viññāṇaṭṭhiti. (3.1)**This is the first plane of consciousness.*";
P_HTM[5448]="*Santāvuso, sattā nānattakāyā ekattasaññino, seyyathāpi devā brahmakāyikā paṭhamābhinibbattā.**There are sentient beings that are diverse in body and unified in perception, such as the gods reborn in Brahmā’s Host through the first absorption.*";
P_HTM[5449]="*Ayaṃ dutiyā viññāṇaṭṭhiti. (3.2)**This is the second plane of consciousness.*";
P_HTM[5450]="*Santāvuso, sattā ekattakāyā nānattasaññino, seyyathāpi devā ābhassarā.**There are sentient beings that are unified in body and diverse in perception, such as the gods of streaming radiance.*";
P_HTM[5451]="*Ayaṃ tatiyā viññāṇaṭṭhiti. (3.3)**This is the third plane of consciousness.*";
P_HTM[5452]="*Santāvuso, sattā ekattakāyā ekattasaññino, seyyathāpi devā subhakiṇhā.**There are sentient beings that are unified in body and unified in perception, such as the gods replete with glory.*";
P_HTM[5453]="*Ayaṃ catutthī viññāṇaṭṭhiti. (3.4)**This is the fourth plane of consciousness.*";
P_HTM[5454]="*Santāvuso, sattā sabbaso rūpasaññānaṃ samatikkamā … pe … ‘ananto ākāso’ti ākāsānañcāyatanūpagā.**There are sentient beings that have gone totally beyond perceptions of form. With the ending of perceptions of impingement, not focusing on perceptions of diversity, aware that ‘space is infinite’, they have been reborn in the dimension of infinite space.*";
P_HTM[5455]="*Ayaṃ pañcamī viññāṇaṭṭhiti. (3.5)**This is the fifth plane of consciousness.*";
P_HTM[5456]="*Santāvuso, sattā sabbaso ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma ‘anantaṃ viññāṇan’ti viññāṇañcāyatanūpagā.**There are sentient beings that have gone totally beyond the dimension of infinite space. Aware that ‘consciousness is infinite’, they have been reborn in the dimension of infinite consciousness.*";
P_HTM[5457]="*Ayaṃ chaṭṭhī viññāṇaṭṭhiti. (3.6)**This is the sixth plane of consciousness.*";
P_HTM[5458]="*Santāvuso, sattā sabbaso viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma ‘natthi kiñcī’ti ākiñcaññāyatanūpagā.**There are sentient beings that have gone totally beyond the dimension of infinite consciousness. Aware that ‘there is nothing at all’, they have been reborn in the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[5459]="*Ayaṃ sattamī viññāṇaṭṭhiti.**This is the seventh plane of consciousness.*";
P_HTM[5460]="*Ime satta dhammā pariññeyyā. (3.7)* **";
P_HTM[5461]="*Katame satta dhammā pahātabbā?**What seven things should be given up?*";
P_HTM[5462]="*Sattānusayā—**Seven underlying tendencies:*";
P_HTM[5463]="*kāmarāgānusayo, paṭighānusayo, diṭṭhānusayo, vicikicchānusayo, mānānusayo, bhavarāgānusayo, avijjānusayo.**sensual desire, repulsion, views, doubt, conceit, desire to be reborn, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[5464]="*Ime satta dhammā pahātabbā. (4)* **";
P_HTM[5465]="*Katame satta dhammā hānabhāgiyā?**What seven things make things worse?*";
P_HTM[5466]="*Satta asaddhammā—**Seven bad qualities:*";
P_HTM[5467]="*idhāvuso, bhikkhu assaddho hoti, ahiriko hoti, anottappī hoti, appassuto hoti, kusīto hoti, muṭṭhassati hoti, duppañño hoti.**a mendicant is faithless, shameless, imprudent, uneducated, lazy, unmindful, and witless.*";
P_HTM[5468]="*Ime satta dhammā hānabhāgiyā. (5)* **";
P_HTM[5469]="*Katame satta dhammā visesabhāgiyā?**What seven things lead to distinction?*";
P_HTM[5470]="*Satta saddhammā—**Seven good qualities:*";
P_HTM[5471]="*idhāvuso, bhikkhu saddho hoti, hirimā hoti, ottappī hoti, bahussuto hoti, āraddhavīriyo hoti, upaṭṭhitassati hoti, paññavā hoti.**a mendicant is faithful, conscientious, prudent, learned, energetic, mindful, and wise.*";
P_HTM[5472]="*Ime satta dhammā visesabhāgiyā. (6)* **";
P_HTM[5473]="*Katame satta dhammā duppaṭivijjhā?**What seven things are hard to comprehend?*";
P_HTM[5474]="*Satta sappurisadhammā—**Seven aspects of the teachings of the good persons:*";
P_HTM[5475]="*idhāvuso, bhikkhu dhammaññū ca hoti atthaññū ca attaññū ca mattaññū ca kālaññū ca parisaññū ca puggalaññū ca.**a mendicant knows the teachings, knows the meaning, knows themselves, knows moderation, knows the right time, knows assemblies, and knows people.*";
P_HTM[5476]="*Ime satta dhammā duppaṭivijjhā. (7)* **";
P_HTM[5477]="*Katame satta dhammā uppādetabbā?**What seven things should be produced?*";
P_HTM[5478]="*Satta saññā—**Seven perceptions:*";
P_HTM[5479]="*aniccasaññā, anattasaññā, asubhasaññā, ādīnavasaññā, pahānasaññā, virāgasaññā, nirodhasaññā.**the perception of impermanence, the perception of not-self, the perception of ugliness, the perception of drawbacks, the perception of giving up, the perception of fading away, and the perception of cessation.*";
P_HTM[5480]="*Ime satta dhammā uppādetabbā. (8)* **";
P_HTM[5481]="*Katame satta dhammā abhiññeyyā?**What seven things should be directly known?*";
P_HTM[5482]="*Satta niddasavatthūni—**Seven qualifications for graduation.*";
P_HTM[5483]="*idhāvuso, bhikkhu sikkhāsamādāne tibbacchando hoti, āyatiñca sikkhāsamādāne avigatapemo.**A mendicant has a keen enthusiasm to undertake the training …*";
P_HTM[5484]="*Dhammanisantiyā tibbacchando hoti, āyatiñca dhammanisantiyā avigatapemo.**to examine the teachings …*";
P_HTM[5485]="*Icchāvinaye tibbacchando hoti, āyatiñca icchāvinaye avigatapemo.**to get rid of desires …*";
P_HTM[5486]="*Paṭisallāne tibbacchando hoti, āyatiñca paṭisallāne avigatapemo.**for retreat …*";
P_HTM[5487]="*Vīriyārambhe tibbacchando hoti, āyatiñca vīriyārambhe avigatapemo.**to rouse up energy …*";
P_HTM[5488]="*Satinepakke tibbacchando hoti, āyatiñca satinepakke avigatapemo.**for mindfulness and alertness …*";
P_HTM[5489]="*Diṭṭhipaṭivedhe tibbacchando hoti, āyatiñca diṭṭhipaṭivedhe avigatapemo.**to penetrate theoretically. And they don’t lose these desires in the future.*";
P_HTM[5490]="*Ime satta dhammā abhiññeyyā. (9)* **";
P_HTM[5491]="*Katame satta dhammā sacchikātabbā?**What seven things should be realized?*";
P_HTM[5492]="*Satta khīṇāsavabalāni—**Seven powers of one who has ended the defilements.*";
P_HTM[5493]="*idhāvuso, khīṇāsavassa bhikkhuno aniccato sabbe saṅkhārā yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya sudiṭṭhā honti.**Firstly, a mendicant with defilements ended has clearly seen with right wisdom all conditions as truly impermanent.*";
P_HTM[5494]="*Yaṃpāvuso, khīṇāsavassa bhikkhuno aniccato sabbe saṅkhārā yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya sudiṭṭhā honti, idampi khīṇāsavassa bhikkhuno balaṃ hoti, yaṃ balaṃ āgamma khīṇāsavo bhikkhu āsavānaṃ khayaṃ paṭijānāti: ‘khīṇā me āsavā’ti. (10.1)**This is a power that a mendicant who has ended the defilements relies on to claim: ‘My defilements have ended.’*";
P_HTM[5495]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, khīṇāsavassa bhikkhuno aṅgārakāsūpamā kāmā yathābhūtaṃ sammappaññāya sudiṭṭhā honti.**Furthermore, a mendicant with defilements ended has clearly seen with right wisdom that sensual pleasures are truly like a pit of glowing coals. …*";
P_HTM[5496]="*Yaṃpāvuso … pe … ‘khīṇā me āsavā’ti. (10.2)* **";
P_HTM[5497]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, khīṇāsavassa bhikkhuno vivekaninnaṃ cittaṃ hoti vivekapoṇaṃ vivekapabbhāraṃ vivekaṭṭhaṃ nekkhammābhirataṃ byantībhūtaṃ sabbaso āsavaṭṭhāniyehi dhammehi.**Furthermore, the mind of a mendicant with defilements ended slants, slopes, and inclines to seclusion. They’re withdrawn, loving renunciation, and they’ve totally done with defiling influences. …*";
P_HTM[5498]="*Yaṃpāvuso … pe … ‘khīṇā me āsavā’ti. (10.3)* **";
P_HTM[5499]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, khīṇāsavassa bhikkhuno cattāro satipaṭṭhānā bhāvitā honti subhāvitā.**Furthermore, a mendicant with defilements ended has well developed the four kinds of mindfulness meditation. …*";
P_HTM[5500]="*Yaṃpāvuso … pe … ‘khīṇā me āsavā’ti. (10.4)* **";
P_HTM[5501]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, khīṇāsavassa bhikkhuno pañcindriyāni bhāvitāni honti subhāvitāni.**Furthermore, a mendicant with defilements ended has well developed the five faculties. …*";
P_HTM[5502]="*Yaṃpāvuso … pe … ‘khīṇā me āsavā’ti. (10.5)* **";
P_HTM[5503]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, khīṇāsavassa bhikkhuno satta bojjhaṅgā bhāvitā honti subhāvitā.**Furthermore, a mendicant with defilements ended has well developed the seven awakening factors. …*";
P_HTM[5504]="*Yaṃpāvuso … pe … ‘khīṇā me āsavā’ti. (10.6)* **";
P_HTM[5505]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, khīṇāsavassa bhikkhuno ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvito hoti subhāvito.**Furthermore, a mendicant with defilements ended has well developed the noble eightfold path. …*";
P_HTM[5506]="*Yaṃpāvuso, khīṇāsavassa bhikkhuno ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo bhāvito hoti subhāvito, idampi khīṇāsavassa bhikkhuno balaṃ hoti, yaṃ balaṃ āgamma khīṇāsavo bhikkhu āsavānaṃ khayaṃ paṭijānāti:**This is a power that a mendicant who has ended the defilements relies on to claim:*";
P_HTM[5507]="*‘khīṇā me āsavā’ti.**‘My defilements have ended.’*";
P_HTM[5508]="*Ime satta dhammā sacchikātabbā. (10.7)* **";
P_HTM[5509]="*Itime sattati dhammā bhūtā tacchā tathā avitathā anaññathā sammā tathāgatena abhisambuddhā.**So these seventy things that are true, real, and accurate, not unreal, not otherwise were rightly awakened to by the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[5510]="*Paṭhamabhāṇavāro niṭṭhito.**The first recitation section is finished.*";
P_HTM[5511]="*8. Aṭṭha dhammā**8. Groups of Eight*";
P_HTM[5512]="*Aṭṭha dhammā bahukārā … pe … aṭṭha dhammā sacchikātabbā.**Eight things are helpful, etc.*";
P_HTM[5513]="*Katame aṭṭha dhammā bahukārā?**What eight things are helpful?*";
P_HTM[5514]="*Aṭṭha hetū aṭṭha paccayā ādibrahmacariyikāya paññāya appaṭiladdhāya paṭilābhāya paṭiladdhāya bhiyyobhāvāya vepullāya bhāvanāya pāripūriyā saṃvattanti.**There are eight causes and reasons that lead to acquiring the wisdom fundamental to the spiritual life, and to its increase, growth, development, and fulfillment once it has been acquired.*";
P_HTM[5515]="*Katame aṭṭha?**What eight?*";
P_HTM[5516]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu satthāraṃ upanissāya viharati aññataraṃ vā garuṭṭhāniyaṃ sabrahmacāriṃ, yatthassa tibbaṃ hirottappaṃ paccupaṭṭhitaṃ hoti pemañca gāravo ca.**It’s when a mendicant lives relying on the Teacher or a spiritual companion in a teacher’s role. And they set up a keen sense of conscience and prudence for them, with warmth and respect.*";
P_HTM[5517]="*Ayaṃ paṭhamo hetu paṭhamo paccayo ādibrahmacariyikāya paññāya appaṭiladdhāya paṭilābhāya, paṭiladdhāya bhiyyobhāvāya vepullāya bhāvanāya pāripūriyā saṃvattati. (1.1)**This is the first cause.*";
P_HTM[5518]="*Taṃ kho pana satthāraṃ upanissāya viharati aññataraṃ vā garuṭṭhāniyaṃ sabrahmacāriṃ, yatthassa tibbaṃ hirottappaṃ paccupaṭṭhitaṃ hoti pemañca gāravo ca. Te kālena kālaṃ upasaṅkamitvā paripucchati paripañhati:**When a mendicant lives relying on the Teacher or a spiritual companion in a teacher’s role—with a keen sense of conscience and prudence for them, with warmth and respect—from time to time they go and ask them questions:*";
P_HTM[5519]="*‘idaṃ, bhante, kathaṃ?**‘Why, sir, does it say this?*";
P_HTM[5520]="*Imassa ko attho’ti?**What does that mean?’*";
P_HTM[5521]="*Tassa te āyasmanto avivaṭañceva vivaranti, anuttānīkatañca uttānīkaronti, anekavihitesu ca kaṅkhāṭṭhāniyesu dhammesu kaṅkhaṃ paṭivinodenti.**Those venerables clarify what is unclear, reveal what is obscure, and dispel doubt regarding the many doubtful matters.*";
P_HTM[5522]="*Ayaṃ dutiyo hetu dutiyo paccayo ādibrahmacariyikāya paññāya appaṭiladdhāya paṭilābhāya, paṭiladdhāya bhiyyobhāvāya, vepullāya bhāvanāya pāripūriyā saṃvattati. (1.2)**This is the second cause.*";
P_HTM[5523]="*Taṃ kho pana dhammaṃ sutvā dvayena vūpakāsena sampādeti—kāyavūpakāsena ca cittavūpakāsena ca.**After hearing that teaching they perfect withdrawal of both body and mind.*";
P_HTM[5524]="*Ayaṃ tatiyo hetu tatiyo paccayo ādibrahmacariyikāya paññāya appaṭiladdhāya paṭilābhāya, paṭiladdhāya bhiyyobhāvāya vepullāya bhāvanāya pāripūriyā saṃvattati. (1.3)**This is the third cause.*";
P_HTM[5525]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu sīlavā hoti, pātimokkhasaṃvarasaṃvuto viharati ācāragocarasampanno, aṇumattesu vajjesu bhayadassāvī samādāya sikkhati sikkhāpadesu.**Furthermore, a mendicant is ethical, restrained in the monastic code, conducting themselves well and seeking alms in suitable places. Seeing danger in the slightest fault, they keep the rules they’ve undertaken.*";
P_HTM[5526]="*Ayaṃ catuttho hetu catuttho paccayo ādibrahmacariyikāya paññāya appaṭiladdhāya paṭilābhāya, paṭiladdhāya bhiyyobhāvāya vepullāya bhāvanāya pāripūriyā saṃvattati. (1.4)**This is the fourth cause.*";
P_HTM[5527]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu bahussuto hoti sutadharo sutasannicayo. Ye te dhammā ādikalyāṇā majjhekalyāṇā pariyosānakalyāṇā sātthā sabyañjanā kevalaparipuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ abhivadanti, tathārūpāssa dhammā bahussutā honti dhātā vacasā paricitā manasānupekkhitā diṭṭhiyā suppaṭividdhā.**Furthermore, a mendicant is very learned, remembering and keeping what they’ve learned. These teachings are good in the beginning, good in the middle, and good in the end, meaningful and well-phrased, describing a spiritual practice that’s entirely full and pure. They are very learned in such teachings, remembering them, reinforcing them by recitation, mentally scrutinizing them, and comprehending them theoretically.*";
P_HTM[5528]="*Ayaṃ pañcamo hetu pañcamo paccayo ādibrahmacariyikāya paññāya appaṭiladdhāya paṭilābhāya, paṭiladdhāya bhiyyobhāvāya vepullāya bhāvanāya pāripūriyā saṃvattati. (1.5)**This is the fifth cause.*";
P_HTM[5529]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu āraddhavīriyo viharati akusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ pahānāya, kusalānaṃ dhammānaṃ upasampadāya, thāmavā daḷhaparakkamo anikkhittadhuro kusalesu dhammesu.**Furthermore, a mendicant lives with energy roused up for giving up unskillful qualities and embracing skillful qualities. They are strong, staunchly vigorous, not slacking off when it comes to developing skillful qualities.*";
P_HTM[5530]="*Ayaṃ chaṭṭho hetu chaṭṭho paccayo ādibrahmacariyikāya paññāya appaṭiladdhāya paṭilābhāya, paṭiladdhāya bhiyyobhāvāya vepullāya bhāvanāya pāripūriyā saṃvattati. (1.6)**This is the sixth cause.*";
P_HTM[5531]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu satimā hoti paramena satinepakkena samannāgato. Cirakatampi cirabhāsitampi saritā anussaritā.**Furthermore, a mendicant is mindful. They have utmost mindfulness and alertness, and can remember and recall what was said and done long ago.*";
P_HTM[5532]="*Ayaṃ sattamo hetu sattamo paccayo ādibrahmacariyikāya paññāya appaṭiladdhāya paṭilābhāya, paṭiladdhāya bhiyyobhāvāya vepullāya bhāvanāya pāripūriyā saṃvattati. (1.7)**This is the seventh cause.*";
P_HTM[5533]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu pañcasu upādānakkhandhesu, udayabbayānupassī viharati:**Furthermore, a mendicant meditates observing rise and fall in the five grasping aggregates.*";
P_HTM[5534]="*‘iti rūpaṃ iti rūpassa samudayo iti rūpassa atthaṅgamo;**‘Such is form, such is the origin of form, such is the ending of form.*";
P_HTM[5535]="*iti vedanā iti vedanāya samudayo iti vedanāya atthaṅgamo;**Such is feeling, such is the origin of feeling, such is the ending of feeling.*";
P_HTM[5536]="*iti saññā iti saññāya samudayo iti saññāya atthaṅgamo;**Such is perception, such is the origin of perception, such is the ending of perception.*";
P_HTM[5537]="*iti saṅkhārā iti saṅkhārānaṃ samudayo iti saṅkhārānaṃ atthaṅgamo;**Such are choices, such is the origin of choices, such is the ending of choices.*";
P_HTM[5538]="*iti viññāṇaṃ iti viññāṇassa samudayo iti viññāṇassa atthaṅgamo’ti.**Such is consciousness, such is the origin of consciousness, such is the ending of consciousness.’*";
P_HTM[5539]="*Ayaṃ aṭṭhamo hetu aṭṭhamo paccayo ādibrahmacariyikāya paññāya appaṭiladdhāya paṭilābhāya, paṭiladdhāya bhiyyobhāvāya vepullāya bhāvanāya pāripūriyā saṃvattati.**This is the eighth cause.*";
P_HTM[5540]="*Ime aṭṭha dhammā bahukārā. (1.8)* **";
P_HTM[5541]="*Katame aṭṭha dhammā bhāvetabbā?**What eight things should be developed?*";
P_HTM[5542]="*Ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo seyyathidaṃ—**The noble eightfold path, that is:*";
P_HTM[5543]="*sammādiṭṭhi, sammāsaṅkappo, sammāvācā, sammākammanto, sammāājīvo, sammāvāyāmo, sammāsati, sammāsamādhi.**right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion.*";
P_HTM[5544]="*Ime aṭṭha dhammā bhāvetabbā. (2)* **";
P_HTM[5545]="*Katame aṭṭha dhammā pariññeyyā?**What eight things should be completely understood?*";
P_HTM[5546]="*Aṭṭha lokadhammā—**Eight worldly conditions:*";
P_HTM[5547]="*lābho ca, alābho ca, yaso ca, ayaso ca, nindā ca, pasaṃsā ca, sukhañca, dukkhañca.**gain and loss, fame and disgrace, praise and blame, pleasure and pain.*";
P_HTM[5548]="*Ime aṭṭha dhammā pariññeyyā. (3)* **";
P_HTM[5549]="*Katame aṭṭha dhammā pahātabbā?**What eight things should be given up?*";
P_HTM[5550]="*Aṭṭha micchattā—**Eight wrong ways:*";
P_HTM[5551]="*micchādiṭṭhi, micchāsaṅkappo, micchāvācā, micchākammanto, micchāājīvo, micchāvāyāmo, micchāsati, micchāsamādhi.**wrong view, wrong thought, wrong speech, wrong action, wrong livelihood, wrong effort, wrong mindfulness, and wrong immersion.*";
P_HTM[5552]="*Ime aṭṭha dhammā pahātabbā. (4)* **";
P_HTM[5553]="*Katame aṭṭha dhammā hānabhāgiyā?**What eight things make things worse?*";
P_HTM[5554]="*Aṭṭha kusītavatthūni.**Eight grounds for laziness.*";
P_HTM[5555]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhunā kammaṃ kātabbaṃ hoti,**Firstly, a mendicant has some work to do.*";
P_HTM[5556]="*tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[5557]="*‘kammaṃ kho me kātabbaṃ bhavissati, kammaṃ kho pana me karontassa kāyo kilamissati, handāhaṃ nipajjāmī’ti.**‘I have some work to do. But while doing it my body will get tired. I’d better have a lie down.’*";
P_HTM[5558]="*So nipajjati, na vīriyaṃ ārabhati appattassa pattiyā anadhigatassa adhigamāya asacchikatassa sacchikiriyāya.**They lie down, and don’t rouse energy for attaining the unattained, achieving the unachieved, and realizing the unrealized.*";
P_HTM[5559]="*Idaṃ paṭhamaṃ kusītavatthu. (5.1)**This is the first ground for laziness.*";
P_HTM[5560]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhunā kammaṃ kataṃ hoti.**Furthermore, a mendicant has done some work.*";
P_HTM[5561]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[5562]="*‘ahaṃ kho kammaṃ akāsiṃ, kammaṃ kho pana me karontassa kāyo kilanto, handāhaṃ nipajjāmī’ti.**‘I’ve done some work. But while working my body got tired. I’d better have a lie down.’*";
P_HTM[5563]="*So nipajjati, na vīriyaṃ ārabhati … pe …**They lie down, and don’t rouse energy...*";
P_HTM[5564]="*idaṃ dutiyaṃ kusītavatthu. (5.2)**This is the second ground for laziness.*";
P_HTM[5565]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhunā maggo gantabbo hoti.**Furthermore, a mendicant has to go on a journey.*";
P_HTM[5566]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[5567]="*‘maggo kho me gantabbo bhavissati, maggaṃ kho pana me gacchantassa kāyo kilamissati, handāhaṃ nipajjāmī’ti.**‘I have to go on a journey. But while walking my body will get tired. I’d better have a lie down.’*";
P_HTM[5568]="*So nipajjati, na vīriyaṃ ārabhati … pe …**They lie down, and don’t rouse energy...*";
P_HTM[5569]="*idaṃ tatiyaṃ kusītavatthu. (5.3)**This is the third ground for laziness.*";
P_HTM[5570]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhunā maggo gato hoti.**Furthermore, a mendicant has gone on a journey.*";
P_HTM[5571]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[5572]="*‘ahaṃ kho maggaṃ agamāsiṃ, maggaṃ kho pana me gacchantassa kāyo kilanto, handāhaṃ nipajjāmī’ti.**‘I’ve gone on a journey. But while walking my body got tired. I’d better have a lie down.’*";
P_HTM[5573]="*So nipajjati, na vīriyaṃ ārabhati … pe …**They lie down, and don’t rouse energy...*";
P_HTM[5574]="*idaṃ catutthaṃ kusītavatthu. (5.4)**This is the fourth ground for laziness.*";
P_HTM[5575]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu gāmaṃ vā nigamaṃ vā piṇḍāya caranto na labhati lūkhassa vā paṇītassa vā bhojanassa yāvadatthaṃ pāripūriṃ.**Furthermore, a mendicant has wandered for alms, but they didn’t get to fill up on as much food as they like, coarse or fine.*";
P_HTM[5576]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[5577]="*‘ahaṃ kho gāmaṃ vā nigamaṃ vā piṇḍāya caranto nālatthaṃ lūkhassa vā paṇītassa vā bhojanassa yāvadatthaṃ pāripūriṃ, tassa me kāyo kilanto akammañño, handāhaṃ nipajjāmī’ti … pe …**‘I’ve wandered for alms, but I didn’t get to fill up on as much food as I like, coarse or fine. My body is tired and unfit for work. I’d better have a lie down.’...*";
P_HTM[5578]="*idaṃ pañcamaṃ kusītavatthu. (5.5)**This is the fifth ground for laziness.*";
P_HTM[5579]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu gāmaṃ vā nigamaṃ vā piṇḍāya caranto labhati lūkhassa vā paṇītassa vā bhojanassa yāvadatthaṃ pāripūriṃ.**Furthermore, a mendicant has wandered for alms, and they got to fill up on as much food as they like, coarse or fine.*";
P_HTM[5580]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[5581]="*‘ahaṃ kho gāmaṃ vā nigamaṃ vā piṇḍāya caranto alatthaṃ lūkhassa vā paṇītassa vā bhojanassa yāvadatthaṃ pāripūriṃ, tassa me kāyo garuko akammañño, māsācitaṃ maññe, handāhaṃ nipajjāmī’ti.**‘I’ve wandered for alms, and I got to fill up on as much food as I like, coarse or fine. My body is heavy, unfit for work, like I’ve just eaten a load of beans. I’d better have a lie down.’...*";
P_HTM[5582]="*So nipajjati … pe …**They lie down, and don’t rouse energy...*";
P_HTM[5583]="*idaṃ chaṭṭhaṃ kusītavatthu. (5.6)**This is the sixth ground for laziness.*";
P_HTM[5584]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhuno uppanno hoti appamattako ābādho, tassa evaṃ hoti:**Furthermore, a mendicant feels a little sick. They think:*";
P_HTM[5585]="*‘uppanno kho me ayaṃ appamattako ābādho atthi kappo nipajjituṃ, handāhaṃ nipajjāmī’ti.**‘I feel a little sick. Lying down would be good for me. I’d better have a lie down.’*";
P_HTM[5586]="*So nipajjati … pe …**They lie down, and don’t rouse energy...*";
P_HTM[5587]="*idaṃ sattamaṃ kusītavatthu. (5.7)**This is the seventh ground for laziness.*";
P_HTM[5588]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu gilānāvuṭṭhito hoti aciravuṭṭhito gelaññā.**Furthermore, a mendicant has recently recovered from illness.*";
P_HTM[5589]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[5590]="*‘ahaṃ kho gilānāvuṭṭhito aciravuṭṭhito gelaññā.**‘I’ve recently recovered from illness. My body is weak and unfit for work. I’d better have a lie down.’*";
P_HTM[5591]="*Tassa me kāyo dubbalo akammañño, handāhaṃ nipajjāmī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[5592]="*So nipajjati … pe …**They lie down, and don’t rouse energy...*";
P_HTM[5593]="*idaṃ aṭṭhamaṃ kusītavatthu.**This is the eighth ground for laziness.*";
P_HTM[5594]="*Ime aṭṭha dhammā hānabhāgiyā. (5.8)* **";
P_HTM[5595]="*Katame aṭṭha dhammā visesabhāgiyā?**What eight things lead to distinction?*";
P_HTM[5596]="*Aṭṭha ārambhavatthūni.**Eight grounds for arousing energy.*";
P_HTM[5597]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhunā kammaṃ kātabbaṃ hoti, tassa evaṃ hoti:**Firstly, a mendicant has some work to do. They think:*";
P_HTM[5598]="*‘kammaṃ kho me kātabbaṃ bhavissati, kammaṃ kho pana me karontena na sukaraṃ buddhānaṃ sāsanaṃ manasikātuṃ, handāhaṃ vīriyaṃ ārabhāmi appattassa pattiyā anadhigatassa adhigamāya asacchikatassa sacchikiriyāyā’ti.**‘I have some work to do. While working it’s not easy to focus on the instructions of the Buddhas. I’d better preemptively rouse up energy for attaining the unattained, achieving the unachieved, and realizing the unrealized.’*";
P_HTM[5599]="*So vīriyaṃ ārabhati appattassa pattiyā anadhigatassa adhigamāya asacchikatassa sacchikiriyāya.**They rouse energy for attaining the unattained, achieving the unachieved, and realizing the unrealized.*";
P_HTM[5600]="*Idaṃ paṭhamaṃ ārambhavatthu. (6.1)**This is the first ground for arousing energy.*";
P_HTM[5601]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhunā kammaṃ kataṃ hoti.**Furthermore, a mendicant has done some work.*";
P_HTM[5602]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[5603]="*‘ahaṃ kho kammaṃ akāsiṃ, kammaṃ kho panāhaṃ karonto nāsakkhiṃ buddhānaṃ sāsanaṃ manasikātuṃ, handāhaṃ vīriyaṃ ārabhāmi … pe …**‘I’ve done some work. While I was working I wasn’t able to focus on the instructions of the Buddhas. I’d better preemptively rouse up energy.’...*";
P_HTM[5604]="*idaṃ dutiyaṃ ārambhavatthu. (6.2)**This is the second ground for arousing energy.*";
P_HTM[5605]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhunā maggo gantabbo hoti.**Furthermore, a mendicant has to go on a journey.*";
P_HTM[5606]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[5607]="*‘maggo kho me gantabbo bhavissati, maggaṃ kho pana me gacchantena na sukaraṃ buddhānaṃ sāsanaṃ manasikātuṃ, handāhaṃ vīriyaṃ ārabhāmi … pe …**‘I have to go on a journey. While walking it’s not easy to focus on the instructions of the Buddhas. I’d better preemptively rouse up energy.’...*";
P_HTM[5608]="*idaṃ tatiyaṃ ārambhavatthu. (6.3)**This is the third ground for arousing energy.*";
P_HTM[5609]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhunā maggo gato hoti.**Furthermore, a mendicant has gone on a journey.*";
P_HTM[5610]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[5611]="*‘ahaṃ kho maggaṃ agamāsiṃ, maggaṃ kho panāhaṃ gacchanto nāsakkhiṃ buddhānaṃ sāsanaṃ manasikātuṃ, handāhaṃ vīriyaṃ ārabhāmi … pe …**‘I’ve gone on a journey. While I was walking I wasn’t able to focus on the instructions of the Buddhas. I’d better preemptively rouse up energy.’...*";
P_HTM[5612]="*idaṃ catutthaṃ ārambhavatthu. (6.4)**This is the fourth ground for arousing energy.*";
P_HTM[5613]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu gāmaṃ vā nigamaṃ vā piṇḍāya caranto na labhati lūkhassa vā paṇītassa vā bhojanassa yāvadatthaṃ pāripūriṃ.**Furthermore, a mendicant has wandered for alms, but they didn’t get to fill up on as much food as they like, coarse or fine.*";
P_HTM[5614]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[5615]="*‘ahaṃ kho gāmaṃ vā nigamaṃ vā piṇḍāya caranto nālatthaṃ lūkhassa vā paṇītassa vā bhojanassa yāvadatthaṃ pāripūriṃ, tassa me kāyo lahuko kammañño, handāhaṃ vīriyaṃ ārabhāmi … pe …**‘I’ve wandered for alms, but I didn’t get to fill up on as much food as I like, coarse or fine. My body is light and fit for work. I’d better preemptively rouse up energy.’...*";
P_HTM[5616]="*idaṃ pañcamaṃ ārambhavatthu. (6.5)**This is the fifth ground for arousing energy.*";
P_HTM[5617]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu gāmaṃ vā nigamaṃ vā piṇḍāya caranto labhati lūkhassa vā paṇītassa vā bhojanassa yāvadatthaṃ pāripūriṃ.**Furthermore, a mendicant has wandered for alms, and they got to fill up on as much food as they like, coarse or fine.*";
P_HTM[5618]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[5619]="*‘ahaṃ kho gāmaṃ vā nigamaṃ vā piṇḍāya caranto alatthaṃ lūkhassa vā paṇītassa vā bhojanassa yāvadatthaṃ pāripūriṃ.**‘I’ve wandered for alms, and I got to fill up on as much food as I like, coarse or fine. My body is strong and fit for work. I’d better preemptively rouse up energy.’...*";
P_HTM[5620]="*Tassa me kāyo balavā kammañño, handāhaṃ vīriyaṃ ārabhāmi … pe …* **";
P_HTM[5621]="*idaṃ chaṭṭhaṃ ārambhavatthu. (6.6)**This is the sixth ground for arousing energy.*";
P_HTM[5622]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhuno uppanno hoti appamattako ābādho.**Furthermore, a mendicant feels a little sick.*";
P_HTM[5623]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[5624]="*‘uppanno kho me ayaṃ appamattako ābādho ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ vijjati, yaṃ me ābādho pavaḍḍheyya, handāhaṃ vīriyaṃ ārabhāmi … pe …**‘I feel a little sick. It’s possible this illness will worsen. I’d better preemptively rouse up energy.’...*";
P_HTM[5625]="*idaṃ sattamaṃ ārambhavatthu. (6.7)**This is the seventh ground for arousing energy.*";
P_HTM[5626]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu gilānā vuṭṭhito hoti aciravuṭṭhito gelaññā.**Furthermore, a mendicant has recently recovered from illness.*";
P_HTM[5627]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[5628]="*‘ahaṃ kho gilānā vuṭṭhito aciravuṭṭhito gelaññā, ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ vijjati, yaṃ me ābādho paccudāvatteyya, handāhaṃ vīriyaṃ ārabhāmi appattassa pattiyā anadhigatassa adhigamāya asacchikatassa sacchikiriyāyā’ti.**‘I’ve recently recovered from illness. It’s possible the illness will come back. I’d better preemptively rouse up energy for attaining the unattained, achieving the unachieved, and realizing the unrealized.’*";
P_HTM[5629]="*So vīriyaṃ ārabhati appattassa pattiyā anadhigatassa adhigamāya asacchikatassa sacchikiriyāya.**They rouse energy for attaining the unattained, achieving the unachieved, and realizing the unrealized.*";
P_HTM[5630]="*Idaṃ aṭṭhamaṃ ārambhavatthu.**This is the eighth ground for arousing energy.*";
P_HTM[5631]="*Ime aṭṭha dhammā visesabhāgiyā. (6.8)* **";
P_HTM[5632]="*Katame aṭṭha dhammā duppaṭivijjhā?**What eight things are hard to comprehend?*";
P_HTM[5633]="*Aṭṭha akkhaṇā asamayā brahmacariyavāsāya.**Eight lost opportunities for spiritual practice.*";
P_HTM[5634]="*Idhāvuso, tathāgato ca loke uppanno hoti arahaṃ sammāsambuddho, dhammo ca desiyati opasamiko parinibbāniko sambodhagāmī sugatappavedito.**Firstly, a Realized One has arisen in the world. He teaches the Dhamma leading to peace, extinguishment, awakening, as proclaimed by the Holy One.*";
P_HTM[5635]="*Ayañca puggalo nirayaṃ upapanno hoti.**But a person has been reborn in hell.*";
P_HTM[5636]="*Ayaṃ paṭhamo akkhaṇo asamayo brahmacariyavāsāya. (7.1)**This is the first lost opportunity for spiritual practice.*";
P_HTM[5637]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, tathāgato ca loke uppanno hoti arahaṃ sammāsambuddho, dhammo ca desiyati opasamiko parinibbāniko sambodhagāmī sugatappavedito.**Furthermore, a Realized One has arisen in the world.*";
P_HTM[5638]="*Ayañca puggalo tiracchānayoniṃ upapanno hoti.**But a person has been reborn in the animal realm.*";
P_HTM[5639]="*Ayaṃ dutiyo akkhaṇo asamayo brahmacariyavāsāya. (7.2)**This is the second lost opportunity for spiritual practice.*";
P_HTM[5640]="*Puna caparaṃ … pe …**Furthermore, a Realized One has arisen in the world.*";
P_HTM[5641]="*pettivisayaṃ upapanno hoti.**But a person has been reborn in the ghost realm.*";
P_HTM[5642]="*Ayaṃ tatiyo akkhaṇo asamayo brahmacariyavāsāya. (7.3)**This is the third lost opportunity for spiritual practice.*";
P_HTM[5643]="*Puna caparaṃ … pe …**Furthermore, a Realized One has arisen in the world.*";
P_HTM[5644]="*aññataraṃ dīghāyukaṃ devanikāyaṃ upapanno hoti.**But person has been reborn in one of the long-lived orders of gods.*";
P_HTM[5645]="*Ayaṃ catuttho akkhaṇo asamayo brahmacariyavāsāya. (7.4)**This is the fourth lost opportunity for spiritual practice.*";
P_HTM[5646]="*Puna caparaṃ … pe …**Furthermore, a Realized One has arisen in the world.*";
P_HTM[5647]="*paccantimesu janapadesu paccājāto hoti milakkhesu aviññātāresu, yattha natthi gati bhikkhūnaṃ bhikkhunīnaṃ upāsakānaṃ upāsikānaṃ.**But a person has been reborn in the borderlands, among barbarian tribes, where monks, nuns, laymen, and laywomen do not go.*";
P_HTM[5648]="*Ayaṃ pañcamo akkhaṇo asamayo brahmacariyavāsāya. (7.5)**This is the fifth lost opportunity for spiritual practice.*";
P_HTM[5649]="*Puna caparaṃ … pe …**Furthermore, a Realized One has arisen in the world.*";
P_HTM[5650]="*ayañca puggalo majjhimesu janapadesu paccājāto hoti, so ca hoti micchādiṭṭhiko viparītadassano:**And a person is reborn in a central country. But they have wrong view and distorted perspective:*";
P_HTM[5651]="*‘natthi dinnaṃ, natthi yiṭṭhaṃ, natthi hutaṃ, natthi sukatadukkaṭānaṃ kammānaṃ phalaṃ vipāko, natthi ayaṃ loko, natthi paro loko, natthi mātā, natthi pitā, natthi sattā opapātikā, natthi loke samaṇabrāhmaṇā sammaggatā sammāpaṭipannā ye imañca lokaṃ parañca lokaṃ sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā pavedentī’ti.**‘There’s no meaning in giving, sacrifice, or offerings. There’s no fruit or result of good and bad deeds. There’s no afterlife. There are no duties to mother and father. No beings are reborn spontaneously. And there’s no ascetic or brahmin who is well attained and practiced, and who describes the afterlife after realizing it with their own insight.’*";
P_HTM[5652]="*Ayaṃ chaṭṭho akkhaṇo asamayo brahmacariyavāsāya. (7.6)**This is the sixth lost opportunity for spiritual practice.*";
P_HTM[5653]="*Puna caparaṃ … pe …**Furthermore, a Realized One has arisen in the world.*";
P_HTM[5654]="*ayañca puggalo majjhimesu janapadesu paccājāto hoti, so ca hoti duppañño jaḷo eḷamūgo, nappaṭibalo subhāsitadubbhāsitānamatthamaññātuṃ.**And a person is reborn in a central country. But they’re witless, dull, stupid, and unable to distinguish what is well said from what is poorly said.*";
P_HTM[5655]="*Ayaṃ sattamo akkhaṇo asamayo brahmacariyavāsāya. (7.7)**This is the seventh lost opportunity for spiritual practice.*";
P_HTM[5656]="*Puna caparaṃ … pe …**Furthermore, a Realized One has arisen in the world.*";
P_HTM[5657]="*ayañca puggalo majjhimesu janapadesu paccājāto hoti, so ca hoti paññavā ajaḷo aneḷamūgo, paṭibalo subhāsitadubbhāsitānamatthamaññātuṃ.**But he doesn’t teach the Dhamma leading to peace, extinguishment, awakening, as announced by the Holy One. And a person is reborn in a central country. And they’re wise, bright, clever, and able to distinguish what is well said from what is poorly said.*";
P_HTM[5658]="*Ayaṃ aṭṭhamo akkhaṇo asamayo brahmacariyavāsāya.**This is the eighth lost opportunity for spiritual practice.*";
P_HTM[5659]="*Ime aṭṭha dhammā duppaṭivijjhā. (7.8)* **";
P_HTM[5660]="*Katame aṭṭha dhammā uppādetabbā?**What eight things should be produced?*";
P_HTM[5661]="*Aṭṭha mahāpurisavitakkā—**Eight thoughts of a great man.*";
P_HTM[5662]="*appicchassāyaṃ dhammo, nāyaṃ dhammo mahicchassa.**‘This teaching is for those of few wishes, not those of many wishes.*";
P_HTM[5663]="*Santuṭṭhassāyaṃ dhammo, nāyaṃ dhammo asantuṭṭhassa.**It’s for the contented, not those who lack contentment.*";
P_HTM[5664]="*Pavivittassāyaṃ dhammo, nāyaṃ dhammo saṅgaṇikārāmassa.**It’s for the secluded, not those who enjoy company.*";
P_HTM[5665]="*Āraddhavīriyassāyaṃ dhammo, nāyaṃ dhammo kusītassa.**It’s for the energetic, not the lazy.*";
P_HTM[5666]="*Upaṭṭhitasatissāyaṃ dhammo, nāyaṃ dhammo muṭṭhassatissa.**It’s for the mindful, not the unmindful.*";
P_HTM[5667]="*Samāhitassāyaṃ dhammo, nāyaṃ dhammo asamāhitassa.**It’s for those with immersion, not those without immersion.*";
P_HTM[5668]="*Paññavato ayaṃ dhammo, nāyaṃ dhammo duppaññassa.**It’s for the wise, not the witless.*";
P_HTM[5669]="*Nippapañcassāyaṃ dhammo, nāyaṃ dhammo papañcārāmassāti ime aṭṭha dhammā uppādetabbā. (8)**This teaching is for those who don’t enjoy proliferating, not for those who enjoy proliferating.’*";
P_HTM[5670]="*Katame aṭṭha dhammā abhiññeyyā?**What eight things should be directly known?*";
P_HTM[5671]="*Aṭṭha abhibhāyatanāni—**Eight dimensions of mastery.*";
P_HTM[5672]="*ajjhattaṃ rūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati parittāni suvaṇṇadubbaṇṇāni, ‘tāni abhibhuyya jānāmi passāmī’ti—**Perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally, limited, both pretty and ugly. Mastering them, they perceive: ‘I know and see.’*";
P_HTM[5673]="*evaṃsaññī hoti.* **";
P_HTM[5674]="*Idaṃ paṭhamaṃ abhibhāyatanaṃ. (9.1)**This is the first dimension of mastery.*";
P_HTM[5675]="*Ajjhattaṃ rūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati appamāṇāni suvaṇṇadubbaṇṇāni, ‘tāni abhibhuyya jānāmi passāmī’ti—**Perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally, limitless, both pretty and ugly. Mastering them, they perceive: ‘I know and see.’*";
P_HTM[5676]="*evaṃsaññī hoti.* **";
P_HTM[5677]="*Idaṃ dutiyaṃ abhibhāyatanaṃ. (9.2)**This is the second dimension of mastery.*";
P_HTM[5678]="*Ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati parittāni suvaṇṇadubbaṇṇāni, ‘tāni abhibhuyya jānāmi passāmī’ti—**Not perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally, limited, both pretty and ugly. Mastering them, they perceive: ‘I know and see.’*";
P_HTM[5679]="*evaṃsaññī hoti.* **";
P_HTM[5680]="*Idaṃ tatiyaṃ abhibhāyatanaṃ. (9.3)**This is the third dimension of mastery.*";
P_HTM[5681]="*Ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati appamāṇāni suvaṇṇadubbaṇṇāni, ‘tāni abhibhuyya jānāmi passāmī’ti—**Not perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally, limitless, both pretty and ugly. Mastering them, they perceive: ‘I know and see.’*";
P_HTM[5682]="*evaṃsaññī hoti.* **";
P_HTM[5683]="*Idaṃ catutthaṃ abhibhāyatanaṃ. (9.4)**This is the fourth dimension of mastery.*";
P_HTM[5684]="*Ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati nīlāni nīlavaṇṇāni nīlanidassanāni nīlanibhāsāni.**Not perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally that are blue, with blue color, blue hue, and blue tint.*";
P_HTM[5685]="*Seyyathāpi nāma umāpupphaṃ nīlaṃ nīlavaṇṇaṃ nīlanidassanaṃ nīlanibhāsaṃ, seyyathā vā pana taṃ vatthaṃ bārāṇaseyyakaṃ ubhatobhāgavimaṭṭhaṃ nīlaṃ nīlavaṇṇaṃ nīlanidassanaṃ nīlanibhāsaṃ;**They’re like a flax flower that’s blue, with blue color, blue hue, and blue tint. Or a cloth from Bāraṇasī that’s smoothed on both sides, blue, with blue color, blue hue, and blue tint.*";
P_HTM[5686]="*evameva ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati nīlāni nīlavaṇṇāni nīlanidassanāni nīlanibhāsāni, ‘tāni abhibhuyya jānāmi passāmī’ti evaṃsaññī hoti.**Mastering them, they perceive: ‘I know and see.’*";
P_HTM[5687]="*Idaṃ pañcamaṃ abhibhāyatanaṃ. (9.5)**This is the fifth dimension of mastery.*";
P_HTM[5688]="*Ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati pītāni pītavaṇṇāni pītanidassanāni pītanibhāsāni.**Not perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally that are yellow, with yellow color, yellow hue, and yellow tint.*";
P_HTM[5689]="*Seyyathāpi nāma kaṇikārapupphaṃ pītaṃ pītavaṇṇaṃ pītanidassanaṃ pītanibhāsaṃ, seyyathā vā pana taṃ vatthaṃ bārāṇaseyyakaṃ ubhatobhāgavimaṭṭhaṃ pītaṃ pītavaṇṇaṃ pītanidassanaṃ pītanibhāsaṃ;**They’re like a champak flower that’s yellow, with yellow color, yellow hue, and yellow tint. Or a cloth from Bāraṇasī that’s smoothed on both sides, yellow, with yellow color, yellow hue, and yellow tint.*";
P_HTM[5690]="*evameva ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati pītāni pītavaṇṇāni pītanidassanāni pītanibhāsāni, ‘tāni abhibhuyya jānāmi passāmī’ti evaṃsaññī hoti.**Mastering them, they perceive: ‘I know and see.’*";
P_HTM[5691]="*Idaṃ chaṭṭhaṃ abhibhāyatanaṃ. (9.6)**This is the sixth dimension of mastery.*";
P_HTM[5692]="*Ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati lohitakāni lohitakavaṇṇāni lohitakanidassanāni lohitakanibhāsāni.**Not perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally that are red, with red color, red hue, and red tint.*";
P_HTM[5693]="*Seyyathāpi nāma bandhujīvakapupphaṃ lohitakaṃ lohitakavaṇṇaṃ lohitakanidassanaṃ lohitakanibhāsaṃ, seyyathā vā pana taṃ vatthaṃ bārāṇaseyyakaṃ ubhatobhāgavimaṭṭhaṃ lohitakaṃ lohitakavaṇṇaṃ lohitakanidassanaṃ lohitakanibhāsaṃ;**They’re like a scarlet mallow flower that’s red, with red color, red hue, and red tint. Or a cloth from Bāraṇasī that’s smoothed on both sides, red, with red color, red hue, and red tint.*";
P_HTM[5694]="*evameva ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati lohitakāni lohitakavaṇṇāni lohitakanidassanāni lohitakanibhāsāni, ‘tāni abhibhuyya jānāmi passāmī’ti evaṃsaññī hoti.**Mastering them, they perceive: ‘I know and see.’*";
P_HTM[5695]="*Idaṃ sattamaṃ abhibhāyatanaṃ. (9.7)**This is the seventh dimension of mastery.*";
P_HTM[5696]="*Ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati odātāni odātavaṇṇāni odātanidassanāni odātanibhāsāni.**Not perceiving form internally, someone sees visions externally that are white, with white color, white hue, and white tint.*";
P_HTM[5697]="*Seyyathāpi nāma osadhitārakā odātā odātavaṇṇā odātanidassanā odātanibhāsā, seyyathā vā pana taṃ vatthaṃ bārāṇaseyyakaṃ ubhatobhāgavimaṭṭhaṃ odātaṃ odātavaṇṇaṃ odātanidassanaṃ odātanibhāsaṃ;**They’re like the morning star that’s white, with white color, white hue, and white tint. Or a cloth from Bāraṇasī that’s smoothed on both sides, white, with white color, white hue, and white tint.*";
P_HTM[5698]="*evameva ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati odātāni odātavaṇṇāni odātanidassanāni odātanibhāsāni, ‘tāni abhibhuyya jānāmi passāmī’ti evaṃsaññī hoti.* **";
P_HTM[5699]="*Idaṃ aṭṭhamaṃ abhibhāyatanaṃ.**This is the eighth dimension of mastery.*";
P_HTM[5700]="*Ime aṭṭha dhammā abhiññeyyā. (9.8)* **";
P_HTM[5701]="*Katame aṭṭha dhammā sacchikātabbā?**What eight things should be realized?*";
P_HTM[5702]="*Aṭṭha vimokkhā—**Eight liberations.*";
P_HTM[5703]="*rūpī rūpāni passati.**Having physical form, they see visions.*";
P_HTM[5704]="*Ayaṃ paṭhamo vimokkho. (10.1)**This is the first liberation.*";
P_HTM[5705]="*Ajjhattaṃ arūpasaññī eko bahiddhā rūpāni passati.**Not perceiving physical form internally, someone see visions externally.*";
P_HTM[5706]="*Ayaṃ dutiyo vimokkho. (10.2)**This is the second liberation.*";
P_HTM[5707]="*Subhanteva adhimutto hoti.**They’re focused only on beauty.*";
P_HTM[5708]="*Ayaṃ tatiyo vimokkho. (10.3)**This is the third liberation.*";
P_HTM[5709]="*Sabbaso rūpasaññānaṃ samatikkamā paṭighasaññānaṃ atthaṅgamā nānattasaññānaṃ amanasikārā ‘ananto ākāso’ti ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Going totally beyond perceptions of form, with the ending of perceptions of impingement, not focusing on perceptions of diversity, aware that ‘space is infinite’, they enter and remain in the dimension of infinite space.*";
P_HTM[5710]="*Ayaṃ catuttho vimokkho. (10.4)**This is the fourth liberation.*";
P_HTM[5711]="*Sabbaso ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma ‘anantaṃ viññāṇan’ti viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Going totally beyond the dimension of infinite space, aware that ‘consciousness is infinite’, they enter and remain in the dimension of infinite consciousness.*";
P_HTM[5712]="*Ayaṃ pañcamo vimokkho. (10.5)**This is the fifth liberation.*";
P_HTM[5713]="*Sabbaso viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma ‘natthi kiñcī’ti ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Going totally beyond the dimension of infinite consciousness, aware that ‘there is nothing at all’, they enter and remain in the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[5714]="*Ayaṃ chaṭṭho vimokkho. (10.6)**This is the sixth liberation.*";
P_HTM[5715]="*Sabbaso ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Going totally beyond the dimension of nothingness, they enter and remain in the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.*";
P_HTM[5716]="*Ayaṃ sattamo vimokkho. (10.7)**This is the seventh liberation.*";
P_HTM[5717]="*Sabbaso nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Going totally beyond the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, they enter and remain in the cessation of perception and feeling.*";
P_HTM[5718]="*Ayaṃ aṭṭhamo vimokkho.**This is the eighth liberation.*";
P_HTM[5719]="*Ime aṭṭha dhammā sacchikātabbā. (10.8)* **";
P_HTM[5720]="*Iti ime asīti dhammā bhūtā tacchā tathā avitathā anaññathā sammā tathāgatena abhisambuddhā.**So these eighty things that are true, real, and accurate, not unreal, not otherwise were rightly awakened to by the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[5721]="*9. Nava dhammā**9. Groups of Nine*";
P_HTM[5722]="*Nava dhammā bahukārā … pe … nava dhammā sacchikātabbā.**Nine things are helpful, etc.*";
P_HTM[5723]="*Katame nava dhammā bahukārā?**What nine things are helpful?*";
P_HTM[5724]="*Nava yonisomanasikāramūlakā dhammā, yonisomanasikaroto pāmojjaṃ jāyati, pamuditassa pīti jāyati, pītimanassa kāyo passambhati, passaddhakāyo sukhaṃ vedeti, sukhino cittaṃ samādhiyati, samāhite citte yathābhūtaṃ jānāti passati, yathābhūtaṃ jānaṃ passaṃ nibbindati, nibbindaṃ virajjati, virāgā vimuccati.**Nine things rooted in proper attention. When you attend properly, joy springs up. When you’re joyful, rapture springs up. When the mind is full of rapture, the body becomes tranquil. When the body is tranquil, you feel bliss. And when you’re blissful, the mind becomes immersed. When your mind is immersed, you truly know and see. When you truly know and see, you grow disillusioned. Being disillusioned, desire fades away. When desire fades away you’re freed.*";
P_HTM[5725]="*Ime nava dhammā bahukārā. (1)* **";
P_HTM[5726]="*Katame nava dhammā bhāvetabbā?**What nine things should be developed?*";
P_HTM[5727]="*Nava pārisuddhipadhāniyaṅgāni—**Nine factors of trying to be pure.*";
P_HTM[5728]="*sīlavisuddhi pārisuddhipadhāniyaṅgaṃ, cittavisuddhi pārisuddhipadhāniyaṅgaṃ, diṭṭhivisuddhi pārisuddhipadhāniyaṅgaṃ, kaṅkhāvitaraṇavisuddhi pārisuddhipadhāniyaṅgaṃ, maggāmaggañāṇadassanavisuddhi pārisuddhipadhāniyaṅgaṃ, paṭipadāñāṇadassanavisuddhi pārisuddhipadhāniyaṅgaṃ, ñāṇadassanavisuddhi pārisuddhipadhāniyaṅgaṃ, paññāvisuddhi pārisuddhipadhāniyaṅgaṃ, vimuttivisuddhi pārisuddhipadhāniyaṅgaṃ.**The factors of trying to be pure in ethics, mind, view, overcoming doubt, knowledge and vision of the variety of paths, knowledge and vision of the practice, knowledge and vision, wisdom, and freedom.*";
P_HTM[5729]="*Ime nava dhammā bhāvetabbā. (2)* **";
P_HTM[5730]="*Katame nava dhammā pariññeyyā?**What nine things should be completely understood?*";
P_HTM[5731]="*Nava sattāvāsā—**Nine abodes of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[5732]="*santāvuso, sattā nānattakāyā nānattasaññino, seyyathāpi manussā ekacce ca devā ekacce ca vinipātikā.**There are sentient beings that are diverse in body and diverse in perception, such as human beings, some gods, and some beings in the underworld.*";
P_HTM[5733]="*Ayaṃ paṭhamo sattāvāso. (3.1)**This is the first abode of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[5734]="*Santāvuso, sattā nānattakāyā ekattasaññino, seyyathāpi devā brahmakāyikā paṭhamābhinibbattā.**There are sentient beings that are diverse in body and unified in perception, such as the gods reborn in Brahmā’s Host through the first absorption.*";
P_HTM[5735]="*Ayaṃ dutiyo sattāvāso. (3.2)**This is the second abode of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[5736]="*Santāvuso, sattā ekattakāyā nānattasaññino, seyyathāpi devā ābhassarā.**There are sentient beings that are unified in body and diverse in perception, such as the gods of streaming radiance.*";
P_HTM[5737]="*Ayaṃ tatiyo sattāvāso. (3.3)**This is the third abode of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[5738]="*Santāvuso, sattā ekattakāyā ekattasaññino, seyyathāpi devā subhakiṇhā.**There are sentient beings that are unified in body and unified in perception, such as the gods replete with glory.*";
P_HTM[5739]="*Ayaṃ catuttho sattāvāso. (3.4)**This is the fourth abode of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[5740]="*Santāvuso, sattā asaññino appaṭisaṃvedino, seyyathāpi devā asaññasattā.**There are sentient beings that are non-percipient and do not experience anything, such as the gods who are non-percipient beings.*";
P_HTM[5741]="*Ayaṃ pañcamo sattāvāso. (3.5)**This is the fifth abode of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[5742]="*Santāvuso, sattā sabbaso rūpasaññānaṃ samatikkamā paṭighasaññānaṃ atthaṅgamā nānattasaññānaṃ amanasikārā ‘ananto ākāso’ti ākāsānañcāyatanūpagā.**There are sentient beings that have gone totally beyond perceptions of form. With the ending of perceptions of impingement, not focusing on perceptions of diversity, aware that ‘space is infinite’, they have been reborn in the dimension of infinite space.*";
P_HTM[5743]="*Ayaṃ chaṭṭho sattāvāso. (3.6)**This is the sixth abode of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[5744]="*Santāvuso, sattā sabbaso ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma ‘anantaṃ viññāṇan’ti viññāṇañcāyatanūpagā.**There are sentient beings that have gone totally beyond the dimension of infinite space. Aware that ‘consciousness is infinite’, they have been reborn in the dimension of infinite consciousness.*";
P_HTM[5745]="*Ayaṃ sattamo sattāvāso. (3.7)**This is the seventh abode of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[5746]="*Santāvuso, sattā sabbaso viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma ‘natthi kiñcī’ti ākiñcaññāyatanūpagā.**There are sentient beings that have gone totally beyond the dimension of infinite consciousness. Aware that ‘there is nothing at all’, they have been reborn in the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[5747]="*Ayaṃ aṭṭhamo sattāvāso. (3.8)**This is the eighth abode of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[5748]="*Santāvuso, sattā sabbaso ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma nevasaññānāsaññāyatanūpagā.**There are sentient beings that have gone totally beyond the dimension of nothingness. They have been reborn in the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.*";
P_HTM[5749]="*Ayaṃ navamo sattāvāso.**This is the ninth abode of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[5750]="*(3.9) Ime nava dhammā pariññeyyā.* **";
P_HTM[5751]="*Katame nava dhammā pahātabbā?**What nine things should be given up?*";
P_HTM[5752]="*Nava taṇhāmūlakā dhammā—**Nine things rooted in craving.*";
P_HTM[5753]="*taṇhaṃ paṭicca pariyesanā, pariyesanaṃ paṭicca lābho, lābhaṃ paṭicca vinicchayo, vinicchayaṃ paṭicca chandarāgo, chandarāgaṃ paṭicca ajjhosānaṃ, ajjhosānaṃ paṭicca pariggaho, pariggahaṃ paṭicca macchariyaṃ, macchariyaṃ paṭicca ārakkho, ārakkhādhikaraṇaṃ daṇḍādānasatthādānakalahaviggahavivādatuvaṃtuvaṃpesuññamusāvādā aneke pāpakā akusalā dhammā sambhavanti.**Craving is a cause for seeking. Seeking is a cause for gaining material possessions. Gaining material possessions is a cause for assessing. Assessing is a cause for desire and lust. Desire and lust is a cause for attachment. Attachment is a cause for possessiveness. Possessiveness is a cause for stinginess. Stinginess is a cause for safeguarding. Owing to safeguarding, many bad, unskillful things come to be: taking up the rod and the sword, quarrels, arguments, fights, accusations, divisive speech, and lies.*";
P_HTM[5754]="*Ime nava dhammā pahātabbā. (4)* **";
P_HTM[5755]="*Katame nava dhammā hānabhāgiyā?**What nine things make things worse?*";
P_HTM[5756]="*Nava āghātavatthūni:**Nine grounds for resentment.*";
P_HTM[5757]="*‘anatthaṃ me acarī’ti āghātaṃ bandhati,**Thinking: ‘They did wrong to me,’ you harbor resentment.*";
P_HTM[5758]="*‘anatthaṃ me caratī’ti āghātaṃ bandhati,**Thinking: ‘They are doing wrong to me’ …*";
P_HTM[5759]="*‘anatthaṃ me carissatī’ti āghātaṃ bandhati;**‘They will do wrong to me’ …*";
P_HTM[5760]="*‘piyassa me manāpassa anatthaṃ acarī’ti āghātaṃ bandhati … pe …**‘They did wrong by someone I love’ …*";
P_HTM[5761]="*‘anatthaṃ caratī’ti āghātaṃ bandhati … pe …**‘They are doing wrong by someone I love’ …*";
P_HTM[5762]="*‘anatthaṃ carissatī’ti āghātaṃ bandhati;**‘They will do wrong by someone I love’ …*";
P_HTM[5763]="*‘appiyassa me amanāpassa atthaṃ acarī’ti āghātaṃ bandhati … pe …**‘They helped someone I dislike’ …*";
P_HTM[5764]="*‘atthaṃ caratī’ti āghātaṃ bandhati … pe …**‘They are helping someone I dislike’ …*";
P_HTM[5765]="*‘atthaṃ carissatī’ti āghātaṃ bandhati.**Thinking: ‘They will help someone I dislike,’ you harbor resentment.*";
P_HTM[5766]="*Ime nava dhammā hānabhāgiyā. (5)* **";
P_HTM[5767]="*Katame nava dhammā visesabhāgiyā?**What nine things lead to distinction?*";
P_HTM[5768]="*Nava āghātapaṭivinayā:**Nine methods to get rid of resentment.*";
P_HTM[5769]="*‘anatthaṃ me acari, taṃ kutettha labbhā’ti āghātaṃ paṭivineti;**Thinking: ‘They did wrong to me, but what can I possibly do?’ you get rid of resentment.*";
P_HTM[5770]="*‘anatthaṃ me carati, taṃ kutettha labbhā’ti āghātaṃ paṭivineti;**Thinking: ‘They are doing wrong to me …’ …*";
P_HTM[5771]="*‘anatthaṃ me carissati, taṃ kutettha labbhā’ti āghātaṃ paṭivineti;**‘They will do wrong to me …’ …*";
P_HTM[5772]="*‘piyassa me manāpassa anatthaṃ acari … pe …**‘They did wrong by someone I love …’ …*";
P_HTM[5773]="*anatthaṃ carati … pe …**‘They are doing wrong by someone I love …’ …*";
P_HTM[5774]="*anatthaṃ carissati, taṃ kutettha labbhā’ti āghātaṃ paṭivineti;**‘They will do wrong by someone I love …’ …*";
P_HTM[5775]="*‘appiyassa me amanāpassa atthaṃ acari … pe …**‘They helped someone I dislike …’ …*";
P_HTM[5776]="*atthaṃ carati … pe …**‘They are helping someone I dislike …’ …*";
P_HTM[5777]="*atthaṃ carissati, taṃ kutettha labbhā’ti āghātaṃ paṭivineti.**Thinking: ‘They will help someone I dislike, but what can I possibly do?’ you get rid of resentment.*";
P_HTM[5778]="*Ime nava dhammā visesabhāgiyā. (6)* **";
P_HTM[5779]="*Katame nava dhammā duppaṭivijjhā?**What nine things are hard to comprehend?*";
P_HTM[5780]="*Nava nānattā—**Nine kinds of diversity.*";
P_HTM[5781]="*dhātunānattaṃ paṭicca uppajjati phassanānattaṃ, phassanānattaṃ paṭicca uppajjati vedanānānattaṃ, vedanānānattaṃ paṭicca uppajjati saññānānattaṃ, saññānānattaṃ paṭicca uppajjati saṅkappanānattaṃ, saṅkappanānattaṃ paṭicca uppajjati chandanānattaṃ, chandanānattaṃ paṭicca uppajjati pariḷāhanānattaṃ, pariḷāhanānattaṃ paṭicca uppajjati pariyesanānānattaṃ, pariyesanānānattaṃ paṭicca uppajjati lābhanānattaṃ ().**Diversity of elements gives rise to diversity of contacts. Diversity of contacts gives rise to diversity of feelings. Diversity of feelings gives rise to diversity of perceptions. Diversity of perceptions gives rise to diversity of intentions. Diversity of intentions gives rise to diversity of desires. Diversity of desires gives rise to diversity of passions. Diversity of passions gives rise to diversity of searches. Diversity of searches gives rise to diversity of gains.*";
P_HTM[5782]="*Ime nava dhammā duppaṭivijjhā. (7)* **";
P_HTM[5783]="*Katame nava dhammā uppādetabbā?**What nine things should be produced?*";
P_HTM[5784]="*Nava saññā—**Nine perceptions:*";
P_HTM[5785]="*asubhasaññā, maraṇasaññā, āhārepaṭikūlasaññā, sabbalokeanabhiratisaññā, aniccasaññā, anicce dukkhasaññā, dukkhe anattasaññā, pahānasaññā, virāgasaññā.**the perceptions of ugliness, death, repulsiveness in food, dissatisfaction with the whole world, impermanence, suffering in impermanence, not-self in suffering, giving up, and fading away.*";
P_HTM[5786]="*Ime nava dhammā uppādetabbā. (8)* **";
P_HTM[5787]="*Katame nava dhammā abhiññeyyā?**What nine things should be directly known?*";
P_HTM[5788]="*Nava anupubbavihārā—**Nine progressive meditations.*";
P_HTM[5789]="*idhāvuso, bhikkhu vivicceva kāmehi vivicca akusalehi dhammehi savitakkaṃ savicāraṃ vivekajaṃ pītisukhaṃ paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**A mendicant, quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, enters and remains in the first absorption …*";
P_HTM[5790]="*Vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā … pe … dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**second absorption …*";
P_HTM[5791]="*Pītiyā ca virāgā … pe … tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**third absorption …*";
P_HTM[5792]="*Sukhassa ca pahānā … pe … catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**fourth absorption.*";
P_HTM[5793]="*Sabbaso rūpasaññānaṃ samatikkamā … pe … ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Going totally beyond perceptions of form, with the ending of perceptions of impingement, not focusing on perceptions of diversity, aware that ‘space is infinite’, they enter and remain in the dimension of infinite space.*";
P_HTM[5794]="*Sabbaso ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma ‘anantaṃ viññāṇan’ti viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Going totally beyond the dimension of infinite space, aware that ‘consciousness is infinite’, they enter and remain in the dimension of infinite consciousness.*";
P_HTM[5795]="*Sabbaso viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma ‘natthi kiñcī’ti ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Going totally beyond the dimension of infinite consciousness, aware that ‘there is nothing at all’, they enter and remain in the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[5796]="*Sabbaso ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Going totally beyond the dimension of nothingness, they enter and remain in the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.*";
P_HTM[5797]="*Sabbaso nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Going totally beyond the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, they enter and remain in the cessation of perception and feeling.*";
P_HTM[5798]="*Ime nava dhammā abhiññeyyā. (9)* **";
P_HTM[5799]="*Katame nava dhammā sacchikātabbā?**What nine things should be realized?*";
P_HTM[5800]="*Nava anupubbanirodhā—**Nine progressive cessations.*";
P_HTM[5801]="*paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ samāpannassa kāmasaññā niruddhā hoti,**For someone who has attained the first absorption, sensual perceptions have ceased.*";
P_HTM[5802]="*dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ samāpannassa vitakkavicārā niruddhā honti,**For someone who has attained the second absorption, the placing of the mind and keeping it connected have ceased.*";
P_HTM[5803]="*tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ samāpannassa pīti niruddhā hoti,**For someone who has attained the third absorption, rapture has ceased.*";
P_HTM[5804]="*catutthaṃ jhānaṃ samāpannassa assāsapassāssā niruddhā honti,**For someone who has attained the fourth absorption, breathing has ceased.*";
P_HTM[5805]="*ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ samāpannassa rūpasaññā niruddhā hoti,**For someone who has attained the dimension of infinite space, the perception of form has ceased.*";
P_HTM[5806]="*viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ samāpannassa ākāsānañcāyatanasaññā niruddhā hoti,**For someone who has attained the dimension of infinite consciousness, the perception of the dimension of infinite space has ceased.*";
P_HTM[5807]="*ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ samāpannassa viññāṇañcāyatanasaññā niruddhā hoti,**For someone who has attained the dimension of nothingness, the perception of the dimension of infinite consciousness has ceased.*";
P_HTM[5808]="*nevasaññānāsaññāyatanaṃ samāpannassa ākiñcaññāyatanasaññā niruddhā hoti,**For someone who has attained the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception, the perception of the dimension of nothingness has ceased.*";
P_HTM[5809]="*saññāvedayitanirodhaṃ samāpannassa saññā ca vedanā ca niruddhā honti.**For someone who has attained the cessation of perception and feeling, perception and feeling have ceased.*";
P_HTM[5810]="*Ime nava dhammā sacchikātabbā. (10)* **";
P_HTM[5811]="*Iti ime navuti dhammā bhūtā tacchā tathā avitathā anaññathā sammā tathāgatena abhisambuddhā.**So these ninety things that are true, real, and accurate, not unreal, not otherwise were rightly awakened to by the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[5812]="*10. Dasa dhammā**10. Groups of Ten*";
P_HTM[5813]="*Dasa dhammā bahukārā … pe … dasa dhammā sacchikātabbā.**Ten things are helpful, ten things should be developed, ten things should be completely understood, ten things should be given up, ten things make things worse, ten things lead to distinction, ten things are hard to comprehend, ten things should be produced, ten things should be directly known, ten things should be realized.*";
P_HTM[5814]="*Katame dasa dhammā bahukārā?**What ten things are helpful?*";
P_HTM[5815]="*Dasa nāthakaraṇā dhammā—**Ten qualities that serve as protector.*";
P_HTM[5816]="*idhāvuso, bhikkhu sīlavā hoti, pātimokkhasaṃvarasaṃvuto viharati ācāragocarasampanno, aṇumattesu vajjesu bhayadassāvī samādāya sikkhati sikkhāpadesu.**First, a mendicant is ethical, restrained in the monastic code, conducting themselves well and seeking alms in suitable places. Seeing danger in the slightest fault, they keep the rules they’ve undertaken.*";
P_HTM[5817]="*Yaṃpāvuso, bhikkhu sīlavā hoti … pe … sikkhati sikkhāpadesu.* **";
P_HTM[5818]="*Ayampi dhammo nāthakaraṇo. (1.1)**This is a quality that serves as protector.*";
P_HTM[5819]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu bahussuto … pe … diṭṭhiyā suppaṭividdhā.**Furthermore, a mendicant is learned.*";
P_HTM[5820]="*Yaṃpāvuso, bhikkhu bahussuto … pe …* **";
P_HTM[5821]="*ayampi dhammo nāthakaraṇo. (1.2)**This too is a quality that serves as protector.*";
P_HTM[5822]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu kalyāṇamitto hoti kalyāṇasahāyo kalyāṇasampavaṅko.**Furthermore, a mendicant has good friends, companions, and associates.*";
P_HTM[5823]="*Yaṃpāvuso, bhikkhu … pe … kalyāṇasampavaṅko.* **";
P_HTM[5824]="*Ayampi dhammo nāthakaraṇo. (1.3)**This too is a quality that serves as protector.*";
P_HTM[5825]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu suvaco hoti sovacassakaraṇehi dhammehi samannāgato, khamo padakkhiṇaggāhī anusāsaniṃ.**Furthermore, a mendicant is easy to admonish, having qualities that make them easy to admonish. They’re patient, and take instruction respectfully.*";
P_HTM[5826]="*Yaṃpāvuso, bhikkhu … pe … anusāsaniṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5827]="*Ayampi dhammo nāthakaraṇo. (1.4)**This too is a quality that serves as protector.*";
P_HTM[5828]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu yāni tāni sabrahmacārīnaṃ uccāvacāni kiṅkaraṇīyāni tattha dakkho hoti analaso tatrupāyāya vīmaṃsāya samannāgato, alaṃ kātuṃ, alaṃ saṃvidhātuṃ.**Furthermore, a mendicant is deft and tireless in a diverse spectrum of duties for their spiritual companions, understanding how to go about things in order to complete and organize the work.*";
P_HTM[5829]="*Yaṃpāvuso, bhikkhu … pe … alaṃ saṃvidhātuṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5830]="*Ayampi dhammo nāthakaraṇo. (1.5)**This too is a quality that serves as protector.*";
P_HTM[5831]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu dhammakāmo hoti piyasamudāhāro abhidhamme abhivinaye uḷārapāmojjo.**Furthermore, a mendicant loves the teachings and is a delight to converse with, being full of joy in the teaching and training.*";
P_HTM[5832]="*Yaṃpāvuso, bhikkhu … pe … uḷārapāmojjo.* **";
P_HTM[5833]="*Ayampi dhammo nāthakaraṇo. (1.6)**This too is a quality that serves as protector.*";
P_HTM[5834]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu santuṭṭho hoti itarītarehi cīvarapiṇḍapātasenāsanagilānappaccayabhesajjaparikkhārehi.**Furthermore, a mendicant is content with any kind of robes, alms-food, lodgings, and medicines and supplies for the sick.*";
P_HTM[5835]="*Yaṃpāvuso, bhikkhu … pe …* **";
P_HTM[5836]="*ayampi dhammo nāthakaraṇo. (1.7)**This too is a quality that serves as protector.*";
P_HTM[5837]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu āraddhavīriyo viharati … pe … kusalesu dhammesu.**Furthermore, a mendicant is energetic.*";
P_HTM[5838]="*Yaṃpāvuso, bhikkhu … pe …* **";
P_HTM[5839]="*ayampi dhammo nāthakaraṇo. (1.8)**This too is a quality that serves as protector.*";
P_HTM[5840]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu satimā hoti, paramena satinepakkena samannāgato, cirakatampi cirabhāsitampi saritā anussaritā.**Furthermore, a mendicant is mindful. They have utmost mindfulness and alertness, and can remember and recall what was said and done long ago.*";
P_HTM[5841]="*Yaṃpāvuso, bhikkhu … pe …* **";
P_HTM[5842]="*ayampi dhammo nāthakaraṇo. (1.9)**This too is a quality that serves as protector.*";
P_HTM[5843]="*Puna caparaṃ, āvuso, bhikkhu paññavā hoti udayatthagāminiyā paññāya samannāgato, ariyāya nibbedhikāya sammā dukkhakkhayagāminiyā.**Furthermore, a mendicant is wise. They have the wisdom of arising and passing away which is noble, penetrative, and leads to the complete ending of suffering.*";
P_HTM[5844]="*Yaṃpāvuso, bhikkhu … pe …* **";
P_HTM[5845]="*ayampi dhammo nāthakaraṇo.**This too is a quality that serves as protector.*";
P_HTM[5846]="*Ime dasa dhammā bahukārā. (1.10)* **";
P_HTM[5847]="*Katame dasa dhammā bhāvetabbā?**What ten things should be developed?*";
P_HTM[5848]="*Dasa kasiṇāyatanāni—**Ten universal dimensions of meditation.*";
P_HTM[5849]="*pathavīkasiṇameko sañjānāti uddhaṃ adho tiriyaṃ advayaṃ appamāṇaṃ.**Someone perceives the meditation on universal earth above, below, across, non-dual and limitless.*";
P_HTM[5850]="*Āpokasiṇameko sañjānāti … pe …**They perceive the meditation on universal water …*";
P_HTM[5851]="*tejokasiṇameko sañjānāti …**the meditation on universal fire …*";
P_HTM[5852]="*vāyokasiṇameko sañjānāti …**the meditation on universal air …*";
P_HTM[5853]="*nīlakasiṇameko sañjānāti …**the meditation on universal blue …*";
P_HTM[5854]="*pītakasiṇameko sañjānāti …**the meditation on universal yellow …*";
P_HTM[5855]="*lohitakasiṇameko sañjānāti …**the meditation on universal red …*";
P_HTM[5856]="*odātakasiṇameko sañjānāti …**the meditation on universal white …*";
P_HTM[5857]="*ākāsakasiṇameko sañjānāti …**the meditation on universal space …*";
P_HTM[5858]="*viññāṇakasiṇameko sañjānāti uddhaṃ adho tiriyaṃ advayaṃ appamāṇaṃ.**They perceive the meditation on universal consciousness above, below, across, non-dual and limitless.*";
P_HTM[5859]="*Ime dasa dhammā bhāvetabbā. (2)* **";
P_HTM[5860]="*Katame dasa dhammā pariññeyyā?**What ten things should be completely understood?*";
P_HTM[5861]="*Dasāyatanāni—**Ten sense fields:*";
P_HTM[5862]="*cakkhāyatanaṃ, rūpāyatanaṃ, sotāyatanaṃ, saddāyatanaṃ, ghānāyatanaṃ, gandhāyatanaṃ, jivhāyatanaṃ, rasāyatanaṃ, kāyāyatanaṃ, phoṭṭhabbāyatanaṃ.**eye and sights, ear and sounds, nose and smells, tongue and tastes, body and touches.*";
P_HTM[5863]="*Ime dasa dhammā pariññeyyā. (3)* **";
P_HTM[5864]="*Katame dasa dhammā pahātabbā?**What ten things should be given up?*";
P_HTM[5865]="*Dasa micchattā—**Ten wrong ways:*";
P_HTM[5866]="*micchādiṭṭhi, micchāsaṅkappo, micchāvācā, micchākammanto, micchāājīvo, micchāvāyāmo, micchāsati, micchāsamādhi, micchāñāṇaṃ, micchāvimutti.**wrong view, wrong thought, wrong speech, wrong action, wrong livelihood, wrong effort, wrong mindfulness, wrong immersion, wrong knowledge, and wrong freedom.*";
P_HTM[5867]="*Ime dasa dhammā pahātabbā. (4)* **";
P_HTM[5868]="*Katame dasa dhammā hānabhāgiyā?**What ten things make things worse?*";
P_HTM[5869]="*Dasa akusalakammapathā—**Ten ways of doing unskillful deeds:*";
P_HTM[5870]="*pāṇātipāto, adinnādānaṃ, kāmesumicchācāro, musāvādo, pisuṇā vācā, pharusā vācā, samphappalāpo, abhijjhā, byāpādo, micchādiṭṭhi.**killing living creatures, stealing, and sexual misconduct; speech that’s false, divisive, harsh, or nonsensical; covetousness, ill will, and wrong view.*";
P_HTM[5871]="*Ime dasa dhammā hānabhāgiyā. (5)* **";
P_HTM[5872]="*Katame dasa dhammā visesabhāgiyā?**What ten things lead to distinction?*";
P_HTM[5873]="*Dasa kusalakammapathā—**Ten ways of doing skillful deeds:*";
P_HTM[5874]="*pāṇātipātā veramaṇī, adinnādānā veramaṇī, kāmesumicchācārā veramaṇī, musāvādā veramaṇī, pisuṇāya vācāya veramaṇī, pharusāya vācāya veramaṇī, samphappalāpā veramaṇī, anabhijjhā, abyāpādo, sammādiṭṭhi.**refraining from killing living creatures, stealing, and sexual misconduct; avoiding speech that’s false, divisive, harsh, or nonsensical; contentment, good will, and right view.*";
P_HTM[5875]="*Ime dasa dhammā visesabhāgiyā. (6)* **";
P_HTM[5876]="*Katame dasa dhammā duppaṭivijjhā?**What ten things are hard to comprehend?*";
P_HTM[5877]="*Dasa ariyavāsā—**Ten noble abodes.*";
P_HTM[5878]="*idhāvuso, bhikkhu pañcaṅgavippahīno hoti, chaḷaṅgasamannāgato, ekārakkho, caturāpasseno, paṇunnapaccekasacco, samavayasaṭṭhesano, anāvilasaṅkappo, passaddhakāyasaṅkhāro, suvimuttacitto, suvimuttapañño.**A mendicant has given up five factors, possesses six factors, has a single guard, has four supports, has eliminated idiosyncratic interpretations of the truth, has totally given up searching, has unsullied intentions, has stilled the physical process, and is well freed in mind and well freed by wisdom.*";
P_HTM[5879]="*Kathañcāvuso, bhikkhu pañcaṅgavippahīno hoti?**And how has a mendicant given up five factors?*";
P_HTM[5880]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhuno kāmacchando pahīno hoti, byāpādo pahīno hoti, thinamiddhaṃ pahīnaṃ hoti, uddhaccakukkuccaṃ pahīnaṃ hoti, vicikicchā pahīnā hoti.**It’s when a mendicant has given up sensual desire, ill will, dullness and drowsiness, restlessness and remorse, and doubt.*";
P_HTM[5881]="*Evaṃ kho, āvuso, bhikkhu pañcaṅgavippahīno hoti. (7.1)**That’s how a mendicant has given up five factors.*";
P_HTM[5882]="*Kathañcāvuso, bhikkhu chaḷaṅgasamannāgato hoti?**And how does a mendicant possess six factors?*";
P_HTM[5883]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu cakkhunā rūpaṃ disvā neva sumano hoti na dummano, upekkhako viharati sato sampajāno.**A mendicant, seeing a sight with their eyes, is neither happy nor sad. They remain equanimous, mindful and aware.*";
P_HTM[5884]="*Sotena saddaṃ sutvā … pe …**Hearing a sound with their ears …*";
P_HTM[5885]="*ghānena gandhaṃ ghāyitvā …**Smelling an odor with their nose …*";
P_HTM[5886]="*jivhāya rasaṃ sāyitvā …**Tasting a flavor with their tongue …*";
P_HTM[5887]="*kāyena phoṭṭhabbaṃ phusitvā …**Feeling a touch with their body …*";
P_HTM[5888]="*manasā dhammaṃ viññāya neva sumano hoti na dummano, upekkhako viharati sato sampajāno.**Knowing a thought with their mind, they’re neither happy nor sad. They remain equanimous, mindful and aware.*";
P_HTM[5889]="*Evaṃ kho, āvuso, bhikkhu chaḷaṅgasamannāgato hoti. (7.2)**That’s how a mendicant possesses six factors.*";
P_HTM[5890]="*Kathañcāvuso, bhikkhu ekārakkho hoti?**And how does a mendicant have a single guard?*";
P_HTM[5891]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu satārakkhena cetasā samannāgato hoti.**It’s when a mendicant’s heart is guarded by mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[5892]="*Evaṃ kho, āvuso, bhikkhu ekārakkho hoti. (7.3)**That’s how a mendicant has a single guard.*";
P_HTM[5893]="*Kathañcāvuso, bhikkhu caturāpasseno hoti?**And how does a mendicant have four supports?*";
P_HTM[5894]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu saṅkhāyekaṃ paṭisevati, saṅkhāyekaṃ adhivāseti, saṅkhāyekaṃ parivajjeti, saṅkhāyekaṃ vinodeti.**After reflection, a mendicant uses some things, endures some things, avoids some things, and gets rid of some things.*";
P_HTM[5895]="*Evaṃ kho, āvuso, bhikkhu caturāpasseno hoti. (7.4)**That’s how a mendicant has four supports.*";
P_HTM[5896]="*Kathañcāvuso, bhikkhu paṇunnapaccekasacco hoti?**And how has a mendicant eliminated idiosyncratic interpretations of the truth?*";
P_HTM[5897]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhuno yāni tāni puthusamaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ puthupaccekasaccāni, sabbāni tāni nunnāni honti paṇunnāni cattāni vantāni muttāni pahīnāni paṭinissaṭṭhāni.**Different ascetics and brahmins have different idiosyncratic interpretations of the truth. A mendicant has dispelled, eliminated, thrown out, rejected, let go of, given up, and relinquished all these.*";
P_HTM[5898]="*Evaṃ kho, āvuso, bhikkhu paṇunnapaccekasacco hoti. (7.5)**That’s how a mendicant has eliminated idiosyncratic interpretations of the truth.*";
P_HTM[5899]="*Kathañcāvuso, bhikkhu samavayasaṭṭhesano hoti?**And how has a mendicant totally given up searching?*";
P_HTM[5900]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhuno kāmesanā pahīnā hoti, bhavesanā pahīnā hoti, brahmacariyesanā paṭippassaddhā.**It’s when they’ve given up searching for sensual pleasures, for continued existence, and for a spiritual path.*";
P_HTM[5901]="*Evaṃ kho, āvuso, bhikkhu samavayasaṭṭhesano hoti. (7.6)**That’s how a mendicant has totally given up searching.*";
P_HTM[5902]="*Kathañcāvuso, bhikkhu anāvilasaṅkappā hoti?**And how does a mendicant have unsullied intentions?*";
P_HTM[5903]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhuno kāmasaṅkappo pahīno hoti, byāpādasaṅkappo pahīno hoti, vihiṃsāsaṅkappo pahīno hoti.**It’s when they’ve given up sensual, malicious, and cruel intentions.*";
P_HTM[5904]="*Evaṃ kho, āvuso, bhikkhu anāvilasaṅkappo hoti. (7.7)**That’s how a mendicant has unsullied intentions.*";
P_HTM[5905]="*Kathañcāvuso, bhikkhu passaddhakāyasaṅkhāro hoti?**And how has a mendicant stilled the physical process?*";
P_HTM[5906]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu sukhassa ca pahānā dukkhassa ca pahānā pubbeva somanassadomanassānaṃ atthaṅgamā adukkhamasukhaṃ upekkhāsatipārisuddhiṃ catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Giving up pleasure and pain, and ending former happiness and sadness, they enter and remain in the fourth absorption, without pleasure or pain, with pure equanimity and mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[5907]="*Evaṃ kho, āvuso, bhikkhu passaddhakāyasaṅkhāro hoti. (7.8)**That’s how a mendicant has stilled the physical process.*";
P_HTM[5908]="*Kathañcāvuso, bhikkhu suvimuttacitto hoti?**And how is a mendicant well freed in mind?*";
P_HTM[5909]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhuno rāgā cittaṃ vimuttaṃ hoti, dosā cittaṃ vimuttaṃ hoti, mohā cittaṃ vimuttaṃ hoti.**It’s when a mendicant’s mind is freed from greed, hate, and delusion.*";
P_HTM[5910]="*Evaṃ kho, āvuso, bhikkhu suvimuttacitto hoti. (7.9)**That’s how a mendicant is well freed in mind.*";
P_HTM[5911]="*Kathañcāvuso, bhikkhu suvimuttapañño hoti?**And how is a mendicant well freed by wisdom?*";
P_HTM[5912]="*Idhāvuso, bhikkhu ‘rāgo me pahīno ucchinnamūlo tālāvatthukato anabhāvaṅkato āyatiṃ anuppādadhammo’ti pajānāti.**It’s when a mendicant understands: ‘I’ve given up greed, hate, and delusion, cut them off at the root, made them like a palm stump, obliterated them, so they’re unable to arise in the future.’*";
P_HTM[5913]="*‘Doso me pahīno … pe …* **";
P_HTM[5914]="*āyatiṃ anuppādadhammo’ti pajānāti.* **";
P_HTM[5915]="*‘Moho me pahīno … pe …* **";
P_HTM[5916]="*āyatiṃ anuppādadhammo’ti pajānāti.* **";
P_HTM[5917]="*Evaṃ kho, āvuso, bhikkhu suvimuttapañño hoti.**That’s how a mendicant’s mind is well freed by wisdom.*";
P_HTM[5918]="*Ime dasa dhammā duppaṭivijjhā. (7.10)* **";
P_HTM[5919]="*Katame dasa dhammā uppādetabbā?**What ten things should be produced?*";
P_HTM[5920]="*Dasa saññā—**Ten perceptions:*";
P_HTM[5921]="*asubhasaññā, maraṇasaññā, āhārepaṭikūlasaññā, sabbalokeanabhiratisaññā, aniccasaññā, anicce dukkhasaññā, dukkhe anattasaññā, pahānasaññā, virāgasaññā, nirodhasaññā.**the perceptions of ugliness, death, repulsiveness in food, dissatisfaction with the whole world, impermanence, suffering in impermanence, not-self in suffering, giving up, fading away, and cessation.*";
P_HTM[5922]="*Ime dasa dhammā uppādetabbā. (8)* **";
P_HTM[5923]="*Katame dasa dhammā abhiññeyyā?**What ten things should be directly known?*";
P_HTM[5924]="*Dasa nijjaravatthūni—**Ten grounds for wearing away.*";
P_HTM[5925]="*sammādiṭṭhissa micchādiṭṭhi nijjiṇṇā hoti.**For one of right view, wrong view is worn away.*";
P_HTM[5926]="*Ye ca micchādiṭṭhipaccayā aneke pāpakā akusalā dhammā sambhavanti, te cassa nijjiṇṇā honti.**And the many bad, unskillful qualities that arise because of wrong view are worn away.*";
P_HTM[5927]="*Sammāsaṅkappassa micchāsaṅkappo … pe …**For one of right intention, wrong intention is worn away. …*";
P_HTM[5928]="*sammāvācassa micchāvācā …**For one of right speech, wrong speech is worn away. …*";
P_HTM[5929]="*sammākammantassa micchākammanto …**For one of right action, wrong action is worn away. …*";
P_HTM[5930]="*sammāājīvassa micchāājīvo …**For one of right livelihood, wrong livelihood is worn away. …*";
P_HTM[5931]="*sammāvāyāmassa micchāvāyāmo …**For one of right effort, wrong effort is worn away. …*";
P_HTM[5932]="*sammāsatissa micchāsati …**For one of right mindfulness, wrong mindfulness is worn away. …*";
P_HTM[5933]="*sammāsamādhissa micchāsamādhi …**For one of right immersion, wrong immersion is worn away. …*";
P_HTM[5934]="*sammāñāṇassa micchāñāṇaṃ nijjiṇṇaṃ hoti.**For one of right knowledge, wrong knowledge is worn away. …*";
P_HTM[5935]="*Sammāvimuttissa micchāvimutti nijjiṇṇā hoti.**For one of right freedom, wrong freedom is worn away.*";
P_HTM[5936]="*Ye ca micchāvimuttipaccayā aneke pāpakā akusalā dhammā sambhavanti, te cassa nijjiṇṇā honti.**And the many bad, unskillful qualities that arise because of wrong freedom are worn away.*";
P_HTM[5937]="*Ime dasa dhammā abhiññeyyā. (9)* **";
P_HTM[5938]="*Katame dasa dhammā sacchikātabbā?**What ten things should be realized?*";
P_HTM[5939]="*Dasa asekkhā dhammā—**Ten qualities of an adept:*";
P_HTM[5940]="*asekkhā sammādiṭṭhi, asekkho sammāsaṅkappo, asekkhā sammāvācā, asekkho sammākammanto, asekkho sammāājīvo, asekkho sammāvāyāmo, asekkhā sammāsati, asekkho sammāsamādhi, asekkhaṃ sammāñāṇaṃ, asekkhā sammāvimutti.**an adept’s right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, right immersion, right knowledge, and right freedom.*";
P_HTM[5941]="*Ime dasa dhammā sacchikātabbā. (10)* **";
P_HTM[5942]="*Iti ime satadhammā bhūtā tacchā tathā avitathā anaññathā sammā tathāgatena abhisambuddhā”ti.**So these hundred things that are true, real, and accurate, not unreal, not otherwise were rightly awakened to by the Realized One.”*";
P_HTM[5943]="*Idamavocāyasmā sāriputto.**This is what Venerable Sāriputta said.*";
P_HTM[5944]="*Attamanā te bhikkhū āyasmato sāriputtassa bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, the mendicants were happy with what Sāriputta said.*";
P_HTM[5945]="*Dasuttarasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ ekādasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5946]="*Pāthikavaggo niṭṭhito.* **";
P_HTM[5947]="*Pāthiko ca udumbaraṃ,* **";
P_HTM[5948]="*cakkavatti aggaññakaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[5949]="*Sampasādanapāsādaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[5950]="*mahāpurisalakkhaṇaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[5951]="*Siṅgālāṭānāṭiyakaṃ,* **";
P_HTM[5952]="*saṅgīti ca dasuttaraṃ;* **";
P_HTM[5953]="*Ekādasahi suttehi,* **";
P_HTM[5954]="*pāthikavaggoti vuccati.* **";
P_HTM[5955]="*Pāthikavaggapāḷi niṭṭhitā.* **";
P_HTM[5956]="*Tīhi vaggehi paṭimaṇḍito sakalo* **";
P_HTM[5957]="*dīghanikāyo samatto.**The Long Discourses are completed.*";
